<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA TO RETURN TO DODGER STADIUM
</HEADLINE>
 (or use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK GIRARDOT  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ow that the Montreal Expos have left town, the
Los Angeles Dodgers are ready to take on the New York Mets and
their former catcher, Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a big series for us,'' Dodgers manager Glenn
Hoffman said. ``There's going to be some electricity; there was a
lot when we went to New York. You know we need a big series.''
</P>
<P>
   Told that Piazza hit a home run Thursday against the San
Francisco Giants, Hoffman rolled his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means he's swinging the bat better now,'' Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   Then turning toward the visitor dugout at Dodger Stadium,
Hoffman remarked, ``Coming in from the other side might cool him
off a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The return of Piazza has bolstered ticket sales at Dodger
Stadium. As many as 150,000 fans are expected to attend the
four-game weekend series, officials said. Going into Thursday, the
Dodgers were seven games behind the Mets in the race for the
National League wild-card berth. So will this be the highlight of
the Dodgers homestand?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that they are all big. We got the Giants coming up at
the end, the Phillies are right there. We're fighting to try to get
back into it. They are all important,'' Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Been there: Dodgers second baseman Eric Young's game-winning
solo homer with two outs in the ninth Wednesday shouldn't have been
too surprising.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was just his fifth home run of the season, it was
the third time in 1998 that Young slugged the game-winner. In all,
four of Young's five home runs have either tied games or given the
Dodgers the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Three of Young's homers have come in the last 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been hot,'' Hoffman said. ``That one (Wednesday) was a
slider out and away he carried to right. For momentum-wise it was
perfect. He's really swinging the bat well.''
</P>
<P>
   __ On the mend: Right-hander Ismael Valdes made his second rehab
start in San Bernardino on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Infielder Tripp Cromer, coming back from surgery on his right
elbow, will also play at least five innings at second base, Hoffman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how he comes out of that and whether or not to bump
up the playing time,'' Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's game was the final meeting between the Dodgers
and Expos. Going into the game the Dodgers were 4-1 against the
Expos at home; 4-4 overall.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Grudzielanek, who went hitless Wednesday night, did not
start Thursday's game. Juan Castro was inserted into the lineup by
Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're giving Juan the start,'' Hoffman said.
``(Grudzielanek's) feet are a little sore and we're going to get
him ready for the (next) series.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
