<HEADLINE>
FILES FLY AS INTERIOR DEPARTMENT ANSWERS BABBITT SUBPOENAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIANNE FLYNN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Interior Department and at least one Indian
tribe are busy gathering documents to comply with a flurry of grand
jury subpoenas issued in the independent counsel investigation of
Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, sources have told ``The Arizona
Republic''.``''
</P>
<P>
   The House Government Reform and Oversight Committee also has
turned over all the documents it collected for two weeks of
hearings on the Babbitt matter early this year. Its staff met with
some of the half-dozen lawyers that independent counsel Carol Elder
Bruce has hired to conduct the probe, even though it has questions
about Bruce's choice of two attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   And Bruce has circulated a list of witnesses that she might want
to talk to before the probe is completed, sources familiar with the
investigation have told ``The Republic''.
</P>
<P>
   As the nation's attention has been focused on the work of
Kenneth Starr, the independent prosecutor investigating President
Clinton's relationship with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky, the Babbitt investigating team has quietly gone about its
business. The word is that the independent counsel wants to reach a
conclusion about the case by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Interior is sagging under demands to comb four years of
electronic mail messages for those concerning the decision at the
heart of the Babbitt investigation: the July 14, 1995, denial of a
casino license for a Wisconsin tribe, according to department
employees who declined to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail messages among Interior staff on changing the rationale
behind the decision were seized upon by House investigators as
evidence of political influence on the denial.
</P>
<P>
   Interior also has been ordered to provide voluminous information
on taking land into trust for tribes, something a favorable casino
decision would have required, and to come forth with reams of
documents on Indian gaming.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Department declined to talk about the investigation
or any subpoenas.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt, a former Arizona governor, is accused of lying in a
Senate hearing about the casino decision. Attorney General Janet
Reno asked that an independent counsel be appointed to investigate
the perjury allegations, and whether the underlying decision was
``criminally corrupted.'' Bruce was appointed in March.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate investigators have said the denial was
influenced by political contributions to Democrats from opposing
tribes trying to protect their own gambling interests from
competition.
</P>
<P>
   At least one, and perhaps two of the opposing tribes have been
subpoenaed for documents relevant to the inquiry, sources in
contact with tribal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Three bands of Chippewa Indians were asking Interior to allow
them to build a casino at a failing Hudson, Wis., dog track owned
by a Florida gaming company. Oneida, Sioux and another band of
Chippewas, which operated their own gaming facilities nearby,
opposed the application. These opposing tribes contributed more
than $300,000 to Democrats in the 1996 election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Republicans on the House committee that investigated
Babbitt are concerned about Bruce's hiring of two attorneys, Barry
Coburn and David Schertler, who were partners in a Washington firm.
Coburn's hiring in particular irks the committee. It was he who
advised leaders of the Cheyenne-Arapaho tribe to claim Fifth
Amendment protections from self-incrimination in Senate testimony
about Clinton administration solicitation of contributions from
Indian country.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is a bit too close to the one he's currently charged
with investigating, although the committee members, who declined to
be identified, stop short of calling it a conflict. &QL; 
 &UR; Adrianne Flynn can be reached at (202) 662-7262 or at
adrianne.flynn &LR; pni.com
 &UR; via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
