<HEADLINE>
SOPHOMORE POLAK RISES TO OCCASION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ UCLA's biggest player has the biggest
responsibility _ protecting quarterback Cade McNown's blind side _
and right tackle Brian Polak is not taking it lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Polak, a 325-pound sophomore, prepared for his role by rising at
5 a.m. daily this summer and commuting to Westwood from his home in
Hacienda Heights. His workouts began at 6 a.m., with 90 minutes of
conditioning followed by two hours of weight training. He was one
of 40 players who had perfect attendance in the summer program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian did a lot of maturing this summer,'' strength coach
Kevin Yoxall said.
</P>
<P>
   To help secure the job _ and McNown's back _ Polak got stronger,
quicker and tougher. He played in 10 games last year as a true
freshman, relieving All-American Chad Overhauser and was the best
of an inexperienced bunch during spring drills. But UCLA signed a
junior college transfer, James Ghezzi, from Glendale College, in
case Polak wasn't ready.
</P>
<P>
   The summer commutes allayed their fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got here (a few weeks ago), all the coaches took one
look at me and said, `Wow, you look a lot better,''' Polak said.
``I just rededicated myself. I had a great opportunity ahead of me,
and I knew if I worked hard I could contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   Polak, a Bishop Amat graduate, entered training camp as the
starter. He's smart and possesses remarkably quick feet for a
325-pounder. Although he added five pounds this summer, his body
fat decreased. With more muscle and less fat, his agility improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he continues to improve through the rest of fall camp, then
we'll be very good at right tackle,'' line coach Mark Weber said.
</P>
<P>
   __ How they stand: Health allowing, Weber wants to rotate 10
players for the five line spots. The starting five is established,
from left to right: Kris Farris, Oscar Cabrera, Shawn Stuart, Andy
Meyers and Polak.
</P>
<P>
   The top reserves are Matt Phelan, who can play either guard
position, and Ghezzi, who can play either tackle. Beyond those
seven, the competition is fierce.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Blake Worley has scaled the depth chart and is
entrenched as the fourth tackle ahead of David Wilford. ``He's big
and strong and very far along, physically,'' Weber said of Worley.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, freshman Mike Saffer is challenging Ed Anderson for
the fourth guard spot.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Danoff is the backup center, but Stuart is expected to take
at least 90 percent of the snaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy had a good spring and is legitimately in the two deep,
but it's hard to rotate the center,'' Weber said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Movin' up: Freshman cornerback Julius Williams, who played
with DeShaun Foster at Tustin, is a pleasant surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a guy we thought would probably redshirt, but he has
impressed us enough that he might not,'' coach Bob Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is third on the depth chart at right cornerback, behind
Jason Bell and Ryan Roques.
</P>
<P>
   __ Walendy update: Starting fullback Craig Walendy continues to
recover from an allergic reaction to insect bites and has not
practiced. But he is expected to play against Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing it safe,'' he said. ``At this point, I could
play. But if something went wrong, it would jeopardize quite a bit
of the season. If we give them time to heal, then it's just a
matter of a week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
