<HEADLINE>
AUTO TECHNOLOGY: SHINING INFRARED LIGHT ON OBJECTS IN SHADOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (duplication warning: also sent with `f' code)  
 (bl)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARMEL, Calif. _ It wasn't a dark and stormy night, but it was a
dark and winding road. There were no street lights along the
mountain highway outside Carmel; there were only a few houses,
widely spaced. Suddenly, a person in a black coat darted in front
of the Cadillac DeVille prototype I was driving.
</P>
<P>
   I could see him with my naked eye only when I was within several
feet of him. By then, he was already across the road.
</P>
<P>
   I breathed a sigh of relief that I had been aware of his
presence. For I had actually spotted him sooner, while the car was
several yards back down the road, thanks to the Cadillac's Night
Vision display.
</P>
<P>
   The fleeting figure who interrupted my test drive proved the
point that General Motors' Cadillac Division was trying to make:
that its Night Vision system allows a driver to see three to five
times farther down the road than he or she would with only the low
headlight beams. That extra distance gives the driver more time to
react to an impending, dangerous situation.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac, which demonstrated the system recently in California
and Washington, plans to be the world's first automaker to offer a
night vision system on a production vehicle. The system will be an
option on the next-generation DeVille, which is scheduled to go on
sale in about a year as a 2000 model.
</P>
<P>
   The DeVille will be the only GM vehicle to have the system
initially, though Cadillac executives acknowledged that the
technology could be expanded to other models. Cadillac has
historically led other GM divisions in the introduction of features
like air bags, anti-lock brakes and stability controls.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Zellner, chief engineer of the 2000 DeVille, noted that
although nighttime driving represented only about a quarter of all
driving, it accounted for more than half of all traffic deaths and
62 percent of pedestrian fatalities, according to the National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration. In addition, vehicles often
strike deer and other animals at night _ more than 300,000
collisions with deer are reported annually, and many others go
unreported.
</P>
<P>
   ``Visibility is a major factor,'' Zellner said. Improving
visibility by three to five times, as Cadillac says its night
vision system does, means more time to react to a deer. At 60 miles
an hour, reaction time increases from 3.5 seconds without night
vision to nearly 15 seconds with it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nighttime is like drawing the curtain around a car,'' Zellner
said. ``But Night Vision draws back the curtains.''
</P>
<P>
   Night-vision technology was developed in the 1960s for the
military. The earliest systems were very expensive _ about $1
million each _ and could not cope with the heat of an automobile
engine. The technology has since been refined and the cost has
dropped sharply; night-vision goggles are now on the shelves of
discount stores.
</P>
<P>
   During the Persian Gulf war, fighter pilots used the technology
to home in on targets in the dark, a scene made familiar in
newscasts. Since then, night vision has been adapted for use in law
enforcement, like border patrols, as well as by fire departments
and marine rescue missions.
</P>
<P>
   In the DeVille prototype, a sensor that looks like a camera lens
peeks out of the grille. The unit, developed by Raytheon Systems
Co., uses infrared technology to detect the heat emitted by objects
_ like people, animals or moving vehicles _ that may be invisible
to the eye. Indeed, the amount of background light is irrelevant,
since the device ``sees'' only heat.
</P>
<P>
   The heat-sensitive image is projected onto the lower portion of
the DeVille's windshield, much like the heads-up display that gives
a speedometer reading in cars like the Pontiac Grand Prix GTP. The
image is in black and white, but in reverse. ``Hot'' objects, like
animals and people, appear white; ``cool'' objects, like the trees
lining the road, appear dark. The man in the dark coat who darted
in front of me appeared as a bright white image on the display.
</P>
<P>
   Because the system recognizes heat but not light, it ignores the
approaching headlights that can produce a blinding glare. In the
demonstration of the Cadillac system, a car came toward me with its
high beams on, but Night Vision did not show the headlights at all.
I could see the car, though, and because the image was glare-free,
I could tell there was no other vehicle behind it. In rain and fog,
engineers said, the picture may be more fuzzy, but the system still
works, essentially seeing through the elements.
</P>
<P>
   Night Vision powers up automatically. The headlights must be on,
and the Twilight Sentinel feature, which turns the lights on when
it detects darkness, must sense that it is nighttime. The
projection on the windshield can be adjusted up or down to suit the
height of the driver. Or it can be turned off if it is distracting
or unneeded _ as it would be on well-lighted city streets.
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration has not
studied Cadillac's night vision system, a spokesman, Phil Frame,
said. But a recent study done for the safety administration by
Scientex, an Alexandria, Va., consulting firm that conducts studies
on highway safety issues, indicated that a night vision system
might indeed benefit drivers. Ken Gish, Scientex's senior human
factors psychologist, said the studies showed that a driver using
such a system could see 1,200 feet beyond the range of the naked
eye.
</P>
<P>
   In the tests, conducted with a video monitor instead of a
heads-up display like Cadillac's, older drivers were less willing
to use the system. Younger drivers were more likely to use it and
realized the most benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, Cadillac engineers said, the Night Vision system should
be used as a backup. The driver should primarily rely on his or her
own vision, and glance at the night display on occasion, as he or
she would look at the rear view mirror. But I found myself focusing
on the night vision screen, only occasionally looking up at the
real world.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac did not disclose a price for its system, though it is
likely to cost from $1,500 to $2,000. Executives said they expected
about 5 percent of DeVilles to be ordered with it.
</P>
</TEXT>
