<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORS-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR REDUCING TO TWO MEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL SCHLOTTER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Figures.
</P>
<P>
   If anybody was going to stop Jeff Gordon's four-race win streak,
it had to be Mark Martin, who did just that with his victory in
last Saturday's Goody's 500 at Bristol, Tenn. After all, one or the
other of the Winston Cup Tour's top two drivers has won six of the
past seven races.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, Martin narrowed the gap between himself and
points leader Gordon to 67 points. And he extended a couple of
streaks of his own.
</P>
<P>
   It was Martin's 13th straight top-10 finish. And he is the only
driver among the top 14 to not have suffered a DNF (Did Not Finish)
so far in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon finished fifth in the race after battling an
ill-performing car all day long. But Martin was the only driver to
make a significant gain on him. The season points race has thus
become essentially a two-man battle with 11 races remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett, running third, 223 points behind Gordon, said it's
time to step up the pressure on the leaders or start thinking about
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to catch those two before it's too late,'' Jarrett
said. ``What we need is some wins and for them to have some
trouble. If not, we might as well forget about this championship.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Giving back: Like many racers, Valencia product Bryan Herta
got his start racing go-karts.
</P>
<P>
   Herta, who drives on the FedEx CART circuit for Team Rahal,
announced this week that he has purchased an interest in the Las
Vegas Karting Center in Sloan, Nev., with the intent of helping
young drivers get started.
</P>
<P>
   ``The center will host a number of national karting events as
well as establishing a first-class karting school,'' said Herta,
who began racing go-karts at 12. ``We want to help develop more
young racing talent at our center.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Musical chairs: Max Papis became the third driver to depart
the Arciero-Wells CART race team this year when he announced this
week he won't return in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Papis, who replaced La Canada's Jeff Krosnoff with the team
following Krosnoff's fatal crash in 1996, is rumored to be a
leading candidate to take over driving duties for Bobby Rahal, who
is retiring at the end of this season.
</P>
<P>
   Papis' departure follows those of Hiro Matsushima, who has
retired, and Robby Gordon, who will pursue other driving
opportunities next year. Scott Pruett recently signed with
Arciero-Wells to fill one of the vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   __ Starting over: His once-intimidating lead gone, Granada
Hills' M.K. Kanke heads to Saturday's NASCAR Southwest Featherlite
Tour NAPA 125in Colorado in second place.
</P>
<P>
   Kanke, the victim of three straight DNFs, now trails Steve
Portenga by 43 points (1,458-1,415) with six races remaining.
Despite his recent run of ill fortune, he remains optimistic about
winning this season's Southwest title.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of the season, we'll be back up there,'' Kanke
said. ``The reason we did so well at the beginning is all the other
guys had problems. We all have our ups and downs.''
</P>
<P>
   Kanke is also encouraged by returning to Colorado National
Speedway (Erie, Colo.). The track is home to his team, Bonicelli
Racing of Colorado Springs, and is the site of previous Kanke
victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won last year's race there,'' Kanke said. ``I think we can
win again.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Father vs. son: With Dale Earnhardt Jr. leading the NASCAR
Busch Grand National tour, there is a pretty good chance he and his
racing icon father, Dale Sr., could face off against each other as
members of next year's International Race of Champions tour.
</P>
<P>
   If that comes to pass, their first IROC event will likely not be
the first time they have raced against each other. That day is
supposed to come Nov. 22 in Japan, when the two Earnhardt's run in
the NASCAR Thunder Special Coca-Cola 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be really weird the first time I try to pass him on
the track _ if I get a chance to pass him,'' the younger Earnhardt
said. ``But it is something that will be exciting for both of us,
I'm sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Sr. said he has fond memories of his only time racing
his father, Ralph Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got one exciting time racing with my dad and it was pretty
neat,'' he said. ``It is exciting to see Dale Jr. grow into the
sport and it will be a great experience to race him in Japan.
However, it wouldn't look very good for him to beat his old dad
now, would it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Nuts and bolts: After running as high as fourth at the Indy
Racing League Radisson 200 at Pikes Peak on Aug. 16, Roberto
Guerrero has been signed to finish the season for the CBR team....
Road racer Ron Fellows will be in the Winston Cup No. 96
Caterpillar Chevy at the CMT 300 Sunday in place of Hut Stricklin,
who is recuperating from torn cartilage in his chest.... La
Canada's Tommy Kendall was part of a three-man team that claimed
fifth place last weekend at the First Union Six Hours at the Glen
road race at Watkins Glen, N.Y. Kendall's team started 10th....
Canyon Country's Jay Drake won the 50-lap USAC sprint car EMGE Joe
James/Pat O'Connor Classic at Salem, Ind., Sunday.... Tony Stewart
practiced at the Atlanta Motor Speedway on Thursday, ending rumors
his team might skip the event to protest a 15-point penalty
assessed them by IRL officials this week. The IRL docked Stewart
and teammate Robbie Buhl for using illegal rear wings in the Aug.
16 Radisson 200. The loss of points moved Stewart from first to
third in season points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 0018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
