<SLUG> BC-BBO-LITTLE-LEAGUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOMS RIVER EAST WINS U.S. LITTLE LEAGUE TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ED GUZMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. _ They all made the pilgrimage here from Toms
River, N.J. Several hundred came by the busload and the carload,
having clearly caught the fever over their Little League team. One
devoted fan even came dressed in a monkey suit, holding up a sign
that read ``Unleash the Beast from the East.''
</P>
<P>
   These fans were not disappointed. Going through the pregame
tradition of tapping their lucky 2-foot tall gorilla, won in an
amusement park in Bristol, Conn., the Toms River East players
continued their charmed run with a 5-2 victory over Greenville,
N.C., in Thursday night's U.S. championship game in front of 28,300
at Howard J. Lamade Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Toms River had a three-run outburst in the first inning and then
held on for the second time in three days to win the U.S.
championship to stay undefeated in the series. Toms River will try
to continue its romp through Williamsport on Saturday afternoon
when it plays in the Little League World Series championship game
against Kashima, Japan, which won the international championship
earlier Thursday by 3-2 over Langley, Canada, in eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   For Toms River, shortstop Todd Frazier capped another brilliant
performance with a two-run home run over the center-field fence _
his third home run of the Series _ to give Toms River some
breathing room entering the sixth and final inning. Starting
pitcher Scott Fisher went the distance, allowing only four hits and
striking out 10. When first baseman Shelton Nelson's fly ball to
center field landed firmly in R.J. Johansen's glove for the final
out, the dream of a Little League World Series title was one step
closer to reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome,'' Frazier said of the victory. ``It's like
we're the No. 1 team in the whole United States and it's a great
feeling to be that.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier, who had scored seven of Toms River's 17 runs in this
World Series entering Thursday night, once again set the table for
his team's attack, drawing a walk on a full count to lead off the
game. Fisher followed with a towering fly ball to left that
Greenville left fielder J.D. Morgan was unable to handle, driving
in Frazier. Third baseman Gabe Gardner followed with his second
World Series home run, a majestic fly ball that landed well into
the grassy knoll beyond center field.
</P>
<P>
   Three batters into the game, and Toms River had a 3-0 lead. It
set the tone for the evening, much to the delight of the Toms River
crowd, which filled the night with chants of ``Let's go, East!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed after the first three games,'' said Toms River
manager Mike Gaynor. ``But after a week of competition, I felt
pretty confident heading into tonight's game. When we got up 3-0
early, it kind of took the wind out of the other team's sails.''
</P>
<P>
   Having won its first three games without starting its best
pitcher, Toms River finally started Fisher, a left-hander, Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, whose no-hitter in the East region championship game in
Bristol last week sent Toms River to the Little League World
Series, overcame some first-inning jitters and was masterful
against a power-hitting Greenville lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Greenville got a run back in the bottom of the first inning when
Brack Massey reached on a throwing error by Gardner.
</P>
<P>
   Massey made his way around the bases on a passed ball and two
wild pitches.
</P>
<P>
   After the first-inning, Greenville starting pitcher Alex White
let only one Toms River runner reach third base. White got some
great defensive help in the second inning, as right fielder Mike
Lilley made a diving grab of a Frazier line drive that was slicing
toward the line. The following inning, Fisher was denied a base hit
when third baseman Brandon Brown made a difficult over-the-shoulder
catch of Fisher's pop-up.
</P>
<P>
   Greenville again cut into the lead when shortstop Justin Hardee
crushed a pitch over the right-field fence for a solo home run. But
Toms River put on some nifty defense of its own, as second baseman
Joey Franceschini went up the middle to rob Massey of a hit.
</P>
<P>
   A scary moment occurred in the top of the fourth inning when
right fielder Eric Campesi led off the inning with a dribbler back
to the mound. White threw the ball away, but Campesi ran right into
first baseman Shelton Nelson's outstretched forearm.
</P>
<P>
   Campesi was down for several minutes, but eventually walked off
the field.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher brought the same determination to the mound, striking out
nine through the first five innings and retiring 13 of the next 16
batters he faced after allowing the first run to score.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher brought the delirious Toms River crowd to its feet when
he struck out the side in the fifth inning, capping off the inning
by getting Hardee swinging.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just one of the greatest pitchers,'' Frazier said. ``He's
awesome. I feel really confident when he's on the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier then commented on Saturday's game: ``I just want to go
out and have fun. Even if we lose, we're still the No. 1 team in
the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor added, jokingly, ``We're not going to lose, Todd.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, with Toms River on such a roll, he may only have
been half-joking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
