<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6745 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-RDP-ART-1STLD-     08-28 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-RDP-ART-1STLD-WRITHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MOSCOW: President Clinton.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an unusual move that spoke volumes about Yeltsin's diminished
authority, it was Yastrzhembsky who went to the parliament on
Thursday and spent three hours in conference with the chief of
Russia's Communist Party, Gennadi Zyuganov. The focus of their
discussions was a draft document which demands that the president
cede his considerable powers to appoint and fire governments and
sign economic decrees, and yield them to the parliament, or Duma,
now dominated by the Communist Party-led opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the document would commit the Duma to support
Chernomyrdin as prime minister, stop impeachment proceedings
against Yeltsin, impose a moratorium on no confidence votes against
the government and pass a law on ``social guarantees'' for the
president.
</P>
<P>
   The political document _ devised as an informal treaty between
the Kremlin, the Duma and the Russian government _ would circumvent
the Russian constitution, forcing Yeltsin to become little more
than a ceremonial head of state, with powers similar to Britain's
Queen Elizabeth.
</P>
<P>
   According to a well-informed Russian journalist, Yastrzhembsky
told Zyuganov on Thursday that the president will refuse to sign
the document. Zyuganov, in turn, said that without the president's
signature, the parliament will not confirm Chernomyrdin as prime
minister at a session now scheduled for next week.
</P>
<P>
   In public comments after the meeting, Yastrzhembsky said only
that the political document, and the separate draft program for a
radical change in the country's economic course, ``constitute a
basis for compromise.'' Zyuganov hinted that negotiations are not
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presidential camp is now aware of what is happening in the
country and now that they understand reality, consultations may
become more productive,'' he said, noting in other comments that
the president's future ``social welfare'' was also discussed.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sergei Markov, director of the Institute of
Political Studies, Yeltsin's resignation before his term expires in
2000 is `'definitely under discussion, but the issue is when, and
with what mechanism.'' Markov said Yeltsin's primary concern will
be a guarantee that he and his family will be immune from any
future prosecution, which could arise on a list of charges,
including treason, included in articles of impeachment now being
discussed in the Duma.
</P>
<P>
   `'But,'' said Markov,''Boris Yeltsin can only resign if he sees
that Mr. Chernomyrdin controls the situation.'' Markov and other
political analysts say pressure on Yeltsin to resign is probably
coming from advisers who want to see Chernomyrdin _ whom Yeltsin
has already anointed as his successor _ run for president in early
elections, before he is too badly tarnished by the economic crisis.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But other analysts cautioned that most resignation scenarios now
spinning wildly on Moscow's rumor mill lack any hard information
about Yeltsin's own intentions. `'We don't know what the president
thinks about it,'' said Vyacheslav Nikonov, director of the
Politica Foundation. `'There is alot of talk about this
resignation, but no one is sure if he is well informed about it.''
</P>
<P>
   `'Everything is up to Yeltsin,''said Pavel Voshchanov, a
journalist who was the Russian president's press spokesman during
the 1991 coup. `'The situation in the Kremlin is in complete
disarray, almost everyone has left him. He is in a dead end.''
</P>
<P>
   Grigory Yavlinsky, who heads a party that has opposed Yeltsin's
policies but supports economic reform, said in a radio interview
that Yeltsin has to come forward with an explanation for his
decision to rename Chernomyrdin as prime minister, five months
after he fired him. `'If the Chernomyrdin appointment implies early
elections, let us hear this,'' said Yavlinsky in an Echo Moskvy
broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers agree that Chernomyrdin, faced with a fast
deteriorating economic situation, is ready to compromise with the
parliament, and its Communist-dominated majority, and even accept
its draft economic program. He is also expected to agree on naming
several Communists to his cabinet, although both sides may agree
that their ministerial portfolios should be limited to second-tier
positions, such as agriculture or culture.
</P>
<P>
   `'What Mr. Chernomyrdin needs most is early approval by the
Duma,'' said Nikonov, `'which is why he will sacrifice many things.
He also wants to spread responsibility as widely as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The draft document, now headed for discussion, would reverse a
seven-year- long economic reform program which has been based on
mass privatization and tight monetary policies. Instead, it calls
for increased government management of the economy, protection of
the banking system and support for Russian industry _ policies that
would necessarily require a mass infusion of rubles.
</P>
<P>
   In presenting the program on Thursday, the parliament's deputy
speaker, Vladimir Ryzhkov, parliamentary leader of Chernomyrdin's
party, Our Home is Russia, agreed that the program would require
money, ``but not a Niagara Falls of worthless rubles that will
inundate the economy and spur hyper-inflation.'' He described the
program as a compromise document, with proposals advanced by the
leftist opposition that is `'quite civilized and reasonable, not
extremist at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
