<HEADLINE>
RAFTER CONTINUES TO BLAZE THROUGH U.S. OPEN TUNEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMACK, N.Y. _ For Patrick Rafter, it was women's day at the
Hamlet Cup. Rafter, the dashing Australian who is seeded second,
gave his fans something to swoon over Thursday afternoon when he
signed autographs, kissed a woman celebrating her 40th birthday and
charmed his way through a question-and-answer session with more
than 400 women. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday ight, he gave them something to cheer. Rafter made
quick work of Martin Damm of the Czech Republic, 6-4, 6-3, to reach
the quarterfinals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very relaxed and serving well,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rafter, the defending U.S. Open champion, has won 23 of his last
25 matches. He will take on Nicolas Escude of France on Friday.
Escude disposed of Hicham Arazi of Morocco, 6-3, 3-6, 6-3. Arazi
will be Rafter's first-round opponent in the United States Open
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it was crucial to play well in the Open tuneup, Rafter
said: ``It's important to feel good and to hit the ball well. The
results here are not quite as significant. I don't need to win here
to repeat.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gustavo Kuerten of Brazil fought off stifling afternoon humidity
and four match points in the tie breaker to defeat Francisco Clavet
of Spain, 2-6, 6-3, 7-6 (10-8). In the quarterfinals, Kuerten will
face eighth-seeded Felix Mantilla of Spain, a 7-6 (7-4), 6-3 winner
over Bohdan Ulihrach of the Czech Republic, in another
quarterfinal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be too difficult to come back,'' Kuerten
said, ``but when I got to within a point I just thought I would
make him play my ball.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kuerten fell behind, 6-3, in the tie breaker before he went into
one of the shot-making flurries that characterize his play as much
as his inconsistency. He slammed a service winner, ripped a topspin
forehand winner and then evened the tie breaker with a drop shot
that died on contact with the asphalt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 8-8, Kuerten tapped another drop shot that Clavet returned,
but Kuerten's reflex volley landed for a winner to make it 9-8. He
then served an ace to finish the 1-hour-50-minute match. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I could play a little more intelligently,'' said Kuerten, who
won the 1997 French Open but has just one tour victory since. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because of his recent lack of success, the No. 27-ranked Kuerten
enters next week's Open without the fanfare of 1997. ``Maybe when I
go up in the rankings, I push myself too hard,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's other Hamlet quarterfinals, David Prinosil of
Germany will meet Marat Safin of Russia and Daniel Vacek of the
Czech Republic will play fourth-seeded Greg Rusedski of England.
</P>
</TEXT>
