<SLUG> BC-IRAN-SUIT-AWARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAN ORDERED TO PAY DAMAGES TO HOSTAGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge has awarded $65 million in damages
to three Americans who sued the Iranian government for its part in
kidnapping the three men in Lebanon in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson of U.S. District Court reportedly
found that the former hostages _ Joseph Cicippio, Frank Reed and
David Jacobsen _ were the victims of terrorism under a federal law
passed two years ago that allows such victims to pursue civil suits
in American courts against some foreign governments.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Iran will ever pay any of the damages is doubtful. It
did not take part in the legal proceedings, according to The
Washington Post, which first reported the judge's ruling in its
Friday editions.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson awarded $20 million to Cicippio, $16 million to Reed and
$9 million to Jacobsen, The Post reported. He awarded $10 million
each to the wives of Cicippio and Reed.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs had argued that the Iranian government controlled
the Hezbollah extremists who carried out the kidnappings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
