u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     08-28 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PHOENIX _ It wasn't pretty, but it sure was fun.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a couple of minor details.
</P>
<P>
   The team coached by the lady with the big mouth won. And the
player once coached by the Houston coach hit the shot that beat her
old coach _ 54-51 _ in the opening game of the best-of-three WNBA
finals.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, some kind of gratitude
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I hadn't coached her so well,'' Van Chancellor said of
one-time Ole Miss and current Phoenix star Jennifer Gillom, whose
post-up bucket with nine seconds left Thursday gave the
high-and-mighty Comets their first truly gagging dose of adversity
all season long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Jennifer,'' Chancellor said. ``But I love us more.''
</P>
<P>
   At Comets practice today, however, it's going to be tough love.
Chancellor didn't care for much of what he saw this night. While he
loathes the format that put the Comets in their predicament _ how
do you go 27-3 and wind up starting the WNBA Championship Series on
the road in a nut house like America West Arena? _ he decided not
to make excuses.
</P>
<P>
   He leveled the blame where it belonged _ on his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have liked to have seen us show a lot more patience
with the basketball,'' Chancellor said. ``We're going to talk about
it a bunch, you can bet on that.''
</P>
<P>
   And he would have preferred that, patience or no patience, they
shoot with a modicum of accuracy and rebound with a tad more
tenacity.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets proved they are a great team because they shouldn't
have been anywhere close to winning at the end, yet they weren't
flat-out beaten until a pull-up 12-footer by Sheryl Swoopes decided
to literally jump back out of the basket after it was down inside.
</P>
<P>
   Not much help for Cooper
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes nearly threw the ball away on the inbounds pass, but
Tina Thompson made a gutsy save and Swoopes, suffering through a
dreadful offensive performance, wound up with a clean look at the
hoop.
</P>
<P>
   Her redemption was at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Clank.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Cynthia Cooper's 40-foot hook shot off the right
side of rim in the last second was the miss that put the Comets
into their sudden sudden-death mode, but I'm not going to pick on
Madam Coop, believe me.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper tried to win it by herself, scoring 29 of Houston's 51
points while hitting 11 of the Comets' paltry 21 field goals. Her
11-for-24 compared rather favorably to the 8-for-38 the other
starters managed. That included a 3-for-14 effort by Swoopes and
poor Kim Perrot's 1-for-12.
</P>
<P>
   Factor in the Mercury's plus-nine rebounding bulge, and
Chancellor was exactly right: The Comets had no business hanging
around until the end. They put up 25 fewer points than their
regular-season norm.
</P>
<P>
   Especially galling for the frustrated visitors was the memory of
Miller, after an earlier loss to the Comets here, going before the
crowd and basically promising the Mercury would have the last
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   And way back in the preseason, Miller had told the locals the
Mercury was going to ``bring this bad boy home.'' How ``bad boy''
came to mean ``championship'' escapes me, but I suppose, whatever
the vernacular, it ain't bragging if you do it.
</P>
<P>
   If. I wouldn't count the Comets out just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to win two home games,'' Chancellor said. ``It's as
simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   And one loss would double their season total at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   Turbo's time has come
</P>
<P>
   By the way, memo to you Comets crazies: You owe the Mercury the
same kind of roof-raising racket Saturday that your heroines were
subjected to here in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix pulled out all the stops. Even the Gorilla, the Suns'
eternal, infernal mascot, dropped by for a visit. After one
trampoline dunk, he pulled himself up onto the rim and stood there,
waving a giant Mercury flag while the 13,634 customers went utterly
berserk.
</P>
<P>
   And the referees actually let him do it, although during the
same timeout Miller was assessed a technical foul.
</P>
<P>
   This is war, Les. Turbo had better be on the premises Saturday.
And Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the Comets had better bring a bench. Miller got
66 minutes from five Phoenix reserves whereas Chancellor played
only Janeth Arcain and Yolanda Moore for a combined 27. The Comets'
dismal shooting and poor boxing out were no doubt fatigue-related.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes and Cooper, who missed five of her last seven shots,
each played 39 minutes on ouchy knees, and Perrot was on the court
for 38 with her aching ankle. No Phoenix player went more than 34
minutes. And the Mercury, with far fresher legs, still shot only 35
percent. Gillom was 4-for-19 herself until The Bucket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have done a better job of telling my team, `Don't let
Jennifer beat us,''' Chancellor said. ``We should have forced her
to kick the ball out.''
</P>
<P>
   At least another opportunity beckons. It's
put-up-to-shut-up-Miller time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
