<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS MIGHT BE RECEPTIVE TO JAGS' WILLIE JACKSON
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. AND KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ If the Dallas Cowboys are in the market for
a receiver, Willie Jackson of the Jaguars might be available on
Sunday's final cutdown day.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who was cut by the Cowboys as a rookie before
resurrecting his career in Jacksonville, is on the bubble. Rookie
Alvis Whitted has passed him as the No. 3 receiver with the
Jaguars, and receiver Reggie Barlow is expected to be their kick
returner. The Jaguars must decide how prudent it is to keep Jackson
and his veteran salary as a No. 4 or No. 5 receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of Michael Irvin and Ernie Mills, Jackson offers the
Cowboys more experience than any of their receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking quality receivers, the Cowboys used tight end Eric
Bjornson in the four-receiver set at times Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clarence E. Hill Jr. ZEBBIE IN NICKEL
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys gave former Texas Tech quarterback Zebbie Lethridge,
who is trying to make the transition to cornerback, a long look
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Lethridge played in the first-team nickel defense against the
Jaguars and replaced starter Kevin Smith at left cornerback in the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Jaguars quarterback Mark Brunell showed no mercy on the former
signal caller, burning him deep for a 31-yard touchdown pass to
Jimmy Smith. The Cowboys are trying to decide if Lethridge is worth
a roster spot or if he is a practice-squad candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Brunell and Smith weren't picking on Lethridge, they gave the
same treatment to cornerback Kevin Mathis, burning him deep for a
45-yard touchdown pass in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clarence E. Hill Jr. DAVIS STARTS AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   After starting ahead of Mills for the third consecutive game,
Billy Davis looks like he has won the battle at No. 2 receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Davis did not catch a pass Thursday night, but finished the
preseason with seven catches for 57 yards and a touchdown. Mills
caught one pass for 14 yards Thursday night, giving him three
catches for 27 yards in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clarence E. Hill Jr. CUTDOWN FODDER
</P>
<P>
   The hardest decision the Cowboys might have to make concerning
cutdowns will be at wide receiver. Because of the receiving ability
of backup tight end Bjornson, coach Chan Gailey has indicated he
could conceivably keep five wide receivers on his roster.
</P>
<P>
   With that, the axe could fall on either Macey Brooks or Jeff
Ogden.
</P>
<P>
   Both had two receptions Thursday night. But Ogden had 61 yards
receiving to Brooks' 18. And Ogden turned in one of the night's
highlights with a one-handed, 39-yard reception from Jason Garrett
that set up a third quarter touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kevin Lyons TEAGUE MAKES CASE
</P>
<P>
   Omar Stoutmire got the start again at free safety for the fourth
time in the five preseason games. However, veteran George Teague
made a strong case for the position with a first-quarter pass
deflection that linebacker Dexter Coakley intercepted and returned
22 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The play was indicative of what Teague, who has been known as a
gambler throughout his six-year career and has a knack for making
big plays, can offer the Cowboys. Stoutmire, however, was solid in
run support. He recorded three tackles in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clarence E. Hill Jr. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Team owner Jerry Jones said the club is checking into whether
to sign linebacker Jim Schwantz, whom the 49ers released several
days ago.
</P>
<P>
   _ Linebacker James Bates (sprained left ankle), running back
Chris Warren (strained left groin), and cornerback Lethridge (left
hand contusion) were listed on the Cowboys' postgame injury report.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kevin Lyons
</P>
</TEXT>
