<HEADLINE>
VALDES PLEASED WITH SEVEN-INNING OUTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. _ The blisters on his right hand that
stalled Ismael Valdes' road back to Dodger Stadium resurfaced in
perhaps his final rehabilitation start.
</P>
<P>
   The wounds opened up again, but unlike Saturday in Vero Beach,
Fla., when Los Angelesdodgers pitcher Valdes was limited to 31/3
innings, he wasn't about to pack it in Thursday at San Bernardino
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to go,'' Valdes said. ``(The Stampede coaching staff)
wanted me to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   His second rehab start since landing on the disabled list in
late July with a strained abdominal muscle, this one coming for the
Single-A San Bernardino Stampede against the JetHawks Thursday
night, wasn't anything spectacular when analyzing the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The JetHawks managed seven hits and scratched out two runs off
the 25-year-old right-hander in 61/3 innings. But he achieved his
goals, throwing 92 pitches, 68 for strikes. He finished with four
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an excellent experience for me. It's what I needed,''
Valdes said. ``The best thing for me was I went into the seventh
inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes came out throwing strikes _ seven in a row to begin the
game. He jumped ahead in the count to the first six hitters he
faced, retiring all of them on just 21 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, when his blister acted up again, Valdes yielded a
bloop single to Karl Thompson when the ball was misjudged in right
field. Anton French followed with a clean base hit to right and
Joel Ramirez's blooper that dropped just inside of the right-field
line produced a run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't snap the slider and breaking ball. But the fastball
and changeup was pretty good,'' said Valdes, who hopes to return to
the big club by Tuesday and pitch again late next week.
</P>
<P>
   He experieneced no discomfort in his abdominal area, the reason
he was put on the disabled list. He even tested it, making a diving
stab of Joel Ramirez's would-be base hit back up the middle. On his
belly, Valdes flipped the ball over to first for the out.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably not something Dodgers manager Glenn Hoffman,
pitching coach Charlie Hough and company would want to see, but
Valdes wasn't concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel it and I was never even thinking about it,'' he
said. ``There was no pain on my side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 0052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
