<HEADER>
A6797 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-COMETS-MERCURY-HN     08-28 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-MERCURY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Half of Phoenix coach Cheryl Miller's guarantee is in
the bag.
</P>
<P>
   With the Comets shooting terribly all game, Miller's Mercury
rode a strong first-half performance from center Jennifer Gillom to
deck the defending champions 54-51 in the first game of the 1998
WNBA Championship Series on Thursday night at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like they said in The Wizard of Oz, there's no place like
home,'' Miller told the crowd once the Mercury had taken a 1-0 lead
in the best-of-three series, which resumes at Compaq Center at 3
p.m. Saturday for Game 2. ``We've been getting a little bit of heat
lately because of some brash statements made by the head coach. If
you don't believe in this team, in this city, in this franchise, I
tell you, it's on.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a similar postgame speech to one she delivered in July
when the Comets had beaten the Mercury 65-62 at America West,
sending Phoenix on a skid that resulted in seven losses in nine
games. Then, the Basketball Hall of Famer promised the teams would
meet in the WNBA finals and that the Mercury would ``win that bad
boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix now has the upper hand largely because of Gillom's
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jennifer is a great player just like Cooper (the Comets'
Cynthia Cooper) is a great player, and they make plays down the
stretch,'' Miller said. ``She was able to do that, and we made sure
on our last play that we would get the ball to Jennifer.''
</P>
<P>
   After a timeout and with the score tied at 51, Gillom took a
pass from Michele Timms, dribbled and, with Tina Thompson
defending, turned and dropped in a layup that gave the Mercury a
53-51 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt great,'' Gillom said. ``I had been struggling all
night. But I didn't care if I didn't make another shot, as long as
I made that one.''
</P>
<P>
   It completed a game during which the runner-up in this year's
voting for Most Valuable Player, Gillom, got the best of it despite
a championship-record 29 points by Cooper, the two-time MVP.
</P>
<P>
   Missed shots told the tale for the Comets, who were well under
40 percent most of the game and finished at 32.3 percent
(21-for-65). And the final seconds epitomized their plight. Sheryl
Swoopes (3-for-14) had an open look but missed from 12 feet with
less than three seconds left. Michelle Griffiths grabbed the
rebound, was fouled by Yolanda Moore and made one of two free
throws for a 54-51 lead with 1.5 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Van Chancellor called a timeout and, Swoopes said, ``told
us not to give up, that we still had time.''
</P>
<P>
   Time and opportunity. But a 3-point try by Cooper from near
midcourt missed. And the Mercury had a win that put its coach
within a victory of making good on her vow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shot that I took with 2.3 seconds left,'' Swoopes said,
``did the same thing all of my shots did tonight. It went in and
came back out.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was 11-for-24 and was the only Comet to score in double
figures. Swoopes had eight points, but no one else had more than
four.
</P>
<P>
   Of her final shot, Cooper said: ``You don't win or lose in the
last second of a ballgame. You hope and pray in the last 10
seconds. But you win a game in the first 39 minutes. And for the
first 39 minutes tonight, we didn't play our game. As a result, we
found ourselves in a very difficult situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither team will want to brag about its shooting. Phoenix,
which outrebounded the Comets 41-32, was 22-for-63 from the floor
for 34.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Comets came out strong and went ahead 18-10 following
five straight points by Cooper, they cooled off rapidly from that
point on. Phoenix caught fire and, with Gillom and Timms each
scoring nine points in the period, mounted a 33-29 lead at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Two free throws by Gillom with 15:34 to go in the game gave the
Mercury a 41-33 lead, its biggest. But then, the Mercury couldn't
find the basket. Nine straight misses and a turnover cleared a path
for the Comets to gain steam behind six points from Cooper. And
when Monica Lamb connected with 7:44 left, the Comets led 46-45.
</P>
<P>
   But a 3-pointer from Kristi Harrower ended the Mercury's drought
and overhauled the Comets 48-47.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dodged some bullets,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Harrower had a layup two minutes later to tie the score at 51
with 2:38 left. The rest of the game was a frenetic show of
basketball that ended with Gillom delivering the dagger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew if Jennifer got a shot that she'd make it,'' said
Chancellor, who coached Gillom at Mississippi. ``It was special for
her. I wish it had been a little short. I love her, but I love us
more.''
</P>
<P>
   What remains now, Cooper said, is for the Comets to return home,
go back to the drawing board and adjust the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely nothing the Phoenix Mercury did tonight was the
reason we played the way we did,'' she said. ``They should be
worried about their offense, why they scored only 54 points. We're
worried about why we only scored 51 points. The bottom line is we
didn't play the style of basketball that we're capable of playing.
We've got to go back and make adjustments so that we do play that
way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
