<SLUG> BC-TELLABS-CIENA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELLABS RENEGOTIATES CIENA DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tellabs Inc. is expected to announce Friday that it has
renegotiated its agreement to acquire Ciena Corp., executives close
to the talks said late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new terms, which were still being worked out Thursday
night after the board of Tellabs met all day Tuesday to discuss a
renegotiated settlement, Ciena shareholders are expected to receive
eight-tenths of a share of Tellabs for each Ciena share they own.
</P>
<P>
   That would value the deal _ based on Tellabs' closing stock
price of $57.8125 Thursday _ at more than $4.8 billion. The
previous value of the deal, which was based on a one-for-one swap,
was estimated at $7.1 billion. Shares of Ciena closed Thursday at
$30.8125, down $3.4375.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts had expected the merger to be renegotiated
because of two setbacks earler this month.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 14, Ciena announced that its third-quarter profit would
be less than half of expectations _ between 13 cents and 15 cents a
share. Analysts, according to a survey by First Call Corp., an
investment research company, had expected Ciena to earn 32 cents a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Ciena fell $17.625, or 23.9 percent, to $54.125, on
the news earlier this month, while Tellabs' shares dropped
$13.6875, or 19 percent, to $58.125. When the deal was announced in
June, a mere 62.5 cents separated the value of the two stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had long considered Ciena's operations, which make
equipment that can increase the capacity of long-distance networks,
to be high risk. The company has only 11 customers, led by Sprint
and Worldcom, which together made up 95 percent of its sales last
year. But few expected the company to post such a setback.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Nettles, Ciena's chief executive, attributed his
company's troubles to a delay in a $25 million order and a large
discount that was given to an important customer in exchange for
future volume sales.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the two companies then began discussing a
renegotiation by phone, talks that lasted for two weeks, an
executive close to the negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on the heels of the earnings news, came a disclosure from
AT&AMP;T Corp. that it had decided not to buy Ciena's technology for
expanding the capacity of fiber optic networks.
</P>
<P>
   For Ciena, the timing could not have been worse. AT&AMP;T delivered
the news to Nettles less than an hour before Ciena and Tellabs were
to convene separate shareholder meetings in Baltimore and Lisle,
Ill., to vote on their merger.
</P>
<P>
   Because most analysts on Wall Street assumed that AT&AMP;T would buy
$100 million worth of equipment from Ciena next year _ accounting
for more than 11 percent of its expected revenue _ Tellabs and
Ciena then decided to postpone the votes until Sept. 9.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Michael Birck, the chief executive of Tellabs, said
that he thought that the deal would move forward.
</P>
<P>
   But he declined to say whether the terms would remain the same.
Several analysts said then that they thought that the deal would
still go ahead but that the terms would have to be renegotiated in
Tellabs' favor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
