</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-BONNIE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE TOLL: MAINLY INCONVENIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Updates storm's status as of 11 pm eastern time.)  (With sidebar, HURRICANE-MEDIA) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jw/js) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WRIGHTSVILLE BEACH, N.C. _ Two years ago, residents of this
surfside resort just east of Wilmington returned to their island
after the passing of Hurricane Fran and found utter devastation.
Sand dunes were flattened. Beachfront houses were swamped. Boats
were tossed ashore.
</P>
<P>
   They found none of that Thursday as they streamed back to survey
the damage from Hurricane Bonnie, which blew through this area on
Wednesday afternoon. A few shingles were missing, a few dwellings
and businesses had water damage.
</P>
<P>
   The dunes, artificially replenished earlier this year, had lost
a bit of sand. A single small boat, the Bahama Gem, had been lifted
out of the marsh and deposited on a muddy bank. Even the Shell
Island Resort, a beachfront condominium that is close to falling
into the sea, suffered little noticeable damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very fortunate,'' said Ed Taylor, an assistant to the
town manager.
</P>
<P>
   In Brunswick County, just south of Wilmington, officials
expressed amazement at the dearth of significant destruction.
``It's totally unreal, especially as big as this hurricane was and
as long as it hung around,'' said Cecil Logan, a spokesman for the
county's disaster services. That was the sentiment up and down the
North Carolina coast Thursday as coastal residents, waterlogged but
relieved, awoke to the realization that Hurricane Bonnie had not
lived up to her advance notices.
</P>
<P>
   Although the National Hurricane Center reported that the
category 3 storm carried maximum sustained winds of 115 mph, there
were few physical signs that its power had been that intense. Some
longtime residents said they had developed an ear for hurricanes,
and could tell from the sound of the hurricane that it would not be
as destructive as Fran, which caused nearly $6 billion in property
damage.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said it was too early to make a dollar
assessment of the damage from the latest hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   Grover Gore, a 66-year-old lawyer who has lived for 33 years on
the Cape Fear River in Southport, said that really bad storms would
progress from whistling to howling to roaring to screeching to
screaming. ``We had screeching but we didn't have as much of it as
with Fran,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As the hurricane was downgraded to a tropical storm Thursday,
with winds of 70 mph slowly churning northward through eastern
North Carolina, there were still no reports of deaths or serious
injuries from it. Many of the injuries that were reported by area
hospitals, including electric shocks and carbon monoxide poisoning,
resulted from the improper use of generators.
</P>
<P>
   There were, of course, plenty of ecological consequences,
particularly for sand dunes and rain-sodden rivers. The Pamlico
River washed over its banks in places near Washington, N.C., as did
the Neuse River in New Bern, where major highways were closed. Many
cities in the region received between nine and 11 inches of
rainfall in the last two days.
</P>
<P>
   Residents in Carolina Beach, just south of here, close to where
the eye of the storm made landfall, reported that several feet of
sand had washed ashore on the north end of their island.
</P>
<P>
   At North Topsail Beach, early assessments indicated that 60
percent of the dunes had washed away, some in half-mile long
chunks. On one end of the island, a truck was buried in sand to the
tops of its tires. Boardwalks were twisted and torn away and some
houses were perched precariously near the edge of the water,
because of beach and dune erosion.
</P>
<P>
   North Topsail Beach, with the help of the Federal Emergency
Management Agency, had spent $2 million replenishing the dunes
blown away by Hurricanes Fran and Bertha in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to have to start over again,'' said Tony
Hammond, the town manager. ``The ones that had the vegetation
seemed to have held up better. The ones with limited vegetation
didn't do as well.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, President Clinton declared North Carolina a
disaster area, making it eligible for federal assistance like loans
to farmers and emergency assistance for food and clothing. The aid
was announced in a telephone call between Gov. James Hunt Jr. and
White House Chief of Staff Erskine Bowles, who has said he is
considering a campaign for governor of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Another hurricane, Danielle, was ``following behind on the heels
of Bonnie'' in the Atlantic with winds approaching 90 mph., said
Jorge Aguirre, a meterologist with the National Hurricane Center in
Miami. He said it was too soon to predict the path of Hurricane
Danielle.
</P>
<P>
   As Tropical Storm Bonnie slogged back toward the Atlantic
Thursday night, winds picked up when the center of the storm
reached Kitty Hawk on the Outer Banks, reaching hurricane status
again at 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone here suffered some inconvenience from the
hurricane, but little more. As of 4 p.m. Thursday, some 248,000
households and businesses remained without electricity in eastern
North Carolina, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities on many barrier islands kept bridges closed,
preventing evacuated residents from returning to their homes,
because they were still checking for downed power lines and for
damage to water and sewage systems. As they waited for hours at a
checkpoint at the foot of the bridge to Carolina Beach, many
residents could not hide their frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't leave again,'' said J. Nicole Haywood. ``I may die in
the next one, but I won't leave. This just irks me to death.''
</P>
<P>
   After more than a day without power, many residents were
desperate for hot showers and hot meals. At Johnny's Deli and New
York Style Pizzeria, one of the first restaurants in Wilmington to
open Thursday morning, a line of eager customers stretched out the
door at 11 a.m. Pizza for brunch? Why not, said Wendy R. Kulp, a
22-year-old Wilmington woman who survived the hurricane on a diet
of potato chips and apples.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard on the radio that it was open,'' she said. ``We looked
it up in the yellow pages and rushed over here as fast as we could.
The thought of hot food and cooked cheese sounds really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Others waiting for pizza said they were happy to get outside
after spending Wednesday trapped indoors. ``I'm really sick of
talking to them,'' said Tracey Hopkins, gesturing toward her two
roommates. ``And we've done all the crossword puzzles in People
magazine for the last three months.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 0112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
