<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDMONDS IN SWING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He was coming off a two-homer game at Yankee Stadium
the night before and is batting .303 with 20 homers and 71 RBI this
season, but Jim Edmonds says 1998 has been a struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I've had a mediocre year,'' he said. ``I've tried to do
too much. I changed my stance a little bit and it didn't work. I
changed back and have been trying to catch up. You can't do that.
It's definitely a learning process every year you go out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Since sitting out three games last weekend because of a bruised
back, Edmonds has come out swinging, hitting .471 in four games.
There's no doubting Edmonds' importance to the team, Angels manager
Terry Collins says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Jim Edmonds plays the next 30 games the way Jim Edmonds can
play, we'll win,'' Collins said matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the two homers in the second game of Wednesday's
doubleheader, Edmonds says yes, it was special.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty exciting to hit one here, because I'd never hit
one here before,'' he said. ``It was the only American League park
I'd never homered. But it would have been better if we could have
won the game.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Unusual glare: The Angels normally don't get a lot of
national attention, but playing well against the Yankees has
changed things a little for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to be in the spotlight, this will help,''
Collins said. ``People start to know your players and it helps
players get exposure. Our guys have got a lot of attention here and
they've responded positively to it.''
</P>
<P>
   However, they haven't reached the status of the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a household name,'' Collins said. ``We even
 &UR; !ital! &LR; changed &UR; !off! &LR;  our name (from California to Anaheim).''
</P>
<P>
   __ Playoff musings: If the Angels win the AL West, they'll play
either the Yankees or the Red Sox in the first round. They say it
doesn't matter who they play, as long as they get there.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the Yankees? They would play either the Angels or
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either team could be difficult in a short series,'' Yankees
pitcher David Cone told a New York newspaper. ``Anaheim's got
quality hitters and the outfielders are as good as they come. And
Cleveland, we know what they did to us last year. It's pick your
poison.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Erstad battles: Darin Erstad drew praise for his at-bat in
the top of the ninth inning in Wednesday's second game. The Angels
trailed 6-5 and had Paco Martin on first with two out. Erstad fell
behind in the count 0-2.
</P>
<P>
   But he fouled off five pitches with two strikes, worked the
count full, then drilled the ball into the right-field corner to
score Martin and tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Erstad's at-bat (Wednesday) night should be taped and sent out
to every baseball organization,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Celebrity clubhouse: The Angels' clubhouse before Thursday's
game was a who's who of former players, all of whom are
broadcasters now.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy John, Bobby Murcer and Jeff Torborg roamed the clubhouse,
but none got more attention than Torborg's son, Gale, who is a
professional wrestler with the WCW.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 0117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
