<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES TOP ANGELS IN EXTRA INNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Their usually precise starter failed miserably, their
usually reliable middle reliever stumbled as a closer, but their
unreliable setup man and a rookie making his major league debut
finally pitched sharply enough for the Yankees to erase some of
their concerns and give them life last night. Just when the Angels
were poised to smack the Yankees one last time before they boarded
an airplane, the Yankees smacked back.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams snapped an 0-for-12 slump in stylish fashion by
blasting a double off the center-field fence against Mike Fetters
to score Derek Jeter from second base and lift the Yankees to a
thrilling 6-5 victory in 11 innings. Jay Tessmer, who had never
even been in Yankee Stadium until Wednesday, pitched a scoreless
inning to win his first major league game on a memorable night.
</P>
<P>
   So the Yankees snatched the last two games of what could have
been a much more frustrating five-game series against a team they
might meet in the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the loss, the Angels gave the Yankees something to
ponder if the clubs do play in October by winning 6 of their 11
games this season and finishing as the only team with a winning
mark against the Yankees and the only team to win a series at the
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Or, did the Yankees give the Angels something to ponder by
beating them in their final at-bat the final two nights?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a pride factor involved in this,'' said Manager Joe
Torre. ``Someone asked me if we needed to win this game. We didn't
need it for the standings. But we needed this game for our psyche
and for our pride. You don't want anyone coming in your house and
rearranging your furniture. We held our own.''
</P>
<P>
   They did it because Jeter reached on a walk to open the 11th
and, one out later, the Angels pitched to Williams instead of
walking him and pitching to Paul O'Neill. It was a delicate
decision for Terry Collins, but walking Williams would have set up
a double play. Besides, Chad Curtis was on deck after O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a choice, O'Neill or Williams,'' said Torre, whose team
is 96-36 and has already matched its victory total for all of 1997.
``I like our chances with either one of those guys trying to knock
in the run.''
</P>
<P>
   So after David Cone's control deserted him, after Ramiro Mendoza
failed to do an imitation of Mariano Rivera and after Mike Stanton
may have proved that he is back with one and two-thirds shutout
innings, the game belonged to Tessmer. All the rookie did was
retire the Angels 1-2-3 with two strikeouts and explode in
excitement as center fielder Jim Edmonds collided with the fence
and failed to corral Williams's shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to say I'm the happiest guy in the Stadium,'' said
Tessmer. ``When he hit the ball, I was praying he didn't catch it.
I can't explain how it felt. It was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch's sacrifice fly in the eighth, a ball he hit in
the air that Torre was actually happy about, gave the Yankees a 5-4
lead. But Mendoza permitted a run-scoring single to Orlando
Palmeiro that tied it at 5-5, and the game remained that way until
the 11th.
</P>
<P>
   Cone was nicked for a run in the third on Randy Velarde's
two-out single, but he fashioned 1-2-3 innings in the first,
second, fourth and fifth and looked smooth as he took a 3-1 edge
into the sixth. All Cone needed to do was maintain the lead or hope
the bullpen held it and he would be one triumph away from his
second 20-victory season.
</P>
<P>
   But Cone turned into Mark Wohlers into the sixth by walking
three straight. Cone fell behind 2-0 on Tim Salmon and staggered
off the mound like someone who had been tossed out of a moving cab
on Fifth Avenue. But help was not summoned and Salmon's fly to
center chopped New York's lead to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had left-handed hitters Edmonds and Garret Anderson
due up and the Yankees had left-hander Graeme Lloyd warming up.
Edmonds was 4 for 23 off Cone and 2 for 8 off Lloyd, but Torre said
he did not consider removing Cone. It was a mistake as Edmonds
pounded a double to right-center field that scored two and gave the
Angels a 4-3 lead. Lloyd replaced Cone and got Anderson to ground
out. But the lead was gone, Cone was done and Torre had been wrong.
O'Neill's sacrifice fly tied the game, 4-4, in the seventh. Still,
Cone was miffed by his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this game was very important,'' said Cone. ``I was
fired up for it. For the first five innings, I was on track. Then I
got out of sync.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Finley, the 6-foot-6-inch left-hander with the nasty
split-finger fastball, had held the Yankees to one run in 15
innings this season and had won his last five decisions against
them. Torre offered a possible strategy of staying even with the
Angels until Finley departed, which the Yankees did in stopping
Anaheim, 3-0, in 10 innings on July 30.
</P>
<P>
   But Finley was not as dominant last night. With two outs in the
fourth and the Angels ahead by 1-0, Chili Davis drilled a 2-1
fastball into the right-field bleachers and gave the Yanks a 2-1
lead with his first homer in pinstripes. It was Davis's most
important hit as a Yankee, but it was not the most pivotal hit of
the night. That came from Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any team that comes in here, they're going to have to beat
us,'' said Davis. ``It's been that way all year. I haven't been
here for all of it, but this team doesn't lie down or relax. That's
just the way it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
