<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6824 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     08-28 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' STRATEGY BACKFIRES IN N.Y.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By now, anything less than a thrilling game between
the Angels and New York Yankees would be a drastic deviation from
the norm.
</P>
<P>
   Said Angels manager Terry Collins: ``It's been a great series,
but I'll be glad to get out of here. These games have been tough.''
</P>
<P>
   And he said that !ital!before!off! Bernie Williams doubled home
Derek Jeter with the winning run in the bottom of the 11th inning
for a 6-5 Yankees victory in front of 29,213 at Yankee Stadium on
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real tough one,'' Collins said afterward. ``It's one of
those games where ... you can't walk eight (actually nine) guys and
not do the fundamental things against the New York Yankees and win
ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it was the walk the Angels didn't give up that cost
them.
</P>
<P>
   Williams came to the plate with Jeter on second and first base
open with one out. Williams went into the game leading the league
in hitting with a .341 average.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels decided to have Mike Fetters pitch to Williams,
who hit a drive off the fence in left-center field that Jim Edmonds
nearly caught. Instead, Edmonds re-injured his bruised upper back
crashing into the fence and Jeter scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figured with Fetters' forkball, we had a decent chance go
get him,'' Collins said. ``But we didn't. (On-deck hitter Paul)
O'Neill has killed us. We thought if we could get Williams, we
could walk O'Neill and pitch to (Chad) Curtis.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Angels finished the five-game series with two
losses but headed to Boston with a sense of accomplishment, having
won three of five from baseball's best team.
</P>
<P>
   ``On any given night, we can compete with anybody,'' Collins
said. ``On a given night, we'll compete with the Yankees, Braves,
Astros, anybody. We have a good team. These games the emotions were
high, the adrenaline was flowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest part about winning the first three is when you
have a chance to win the next two and don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Fetters (2-8), one of five relievers to follow starter Chuck
Finley, got the loss. Jay Tessmer (1-0) pitched the 11th and got
the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever been involved in a tougher four
days,'' Collins said. ``The games are so grueling, so hard. We gave
absolute-maximum effort, gave everything we had. It's the longest
four days I've ever spent.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's game was billed as a matchup between two of the best
starters in the league but became a battle of bullpens.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Finley nor Yankees starter David Cone made it out of the
sixth inning, leaving the game to the relievers.
</P>
<P>
   Finley left the game in the sixth inning leading 4-3, but the
Yankees had runners on first and second with nobody out. Pep Harris
came in and got out of the inning in only 11 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees scored one run in both the seventh and eighth
innings, aided by throwing errors by the Angels each inning.
</P>
<P>
   But true to recent form, the Angels, trailing 5-4, rallied in
the ninth against Yankees reliever Ramiro Mendoza.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Walbeck singled, went to second on a sacrifice and scored
the tying run on Orlando Palmeiro's one-out single.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, it only delayed the loss by a couple innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an exhausting situation,'' a weary Edmonds said. ``To see
the level of intensity on the bench for five games and to finish
with an 11-inning game, I'm almost relieved it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   But will they meet again?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're an outstanding team with a great manager and good
coaches,'' Collins said. ``But we want a chance to play them in
October. I want that opportunity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
