<SLUG> BC-LA-RUSSIANS-REACT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMIGRES SHARE RUSSIA WORRIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHARLINE CHIANG AND JIN WHANG  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the economic and political chaos escalated in
Russia on Thursday, many area emigres watched and worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, it was a big-power country. Now when I think about it
I just want to cry,'' said Boris Kramskoy, 66, of North Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Kramskoy, speaking through a translator, said he worries about
his friends in Russia, particularly the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current crisis in Russia is very bad. They're having a
hard time. They're not getting their salary on time,'' said Mike
Ray, a West Hollywood resident who owns the European Meat Market in
North Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, 52, returned two weeks ago from a visit to his
mother-in-law in a suburb outside Moscow, during which he
distributed money and food.
</P>
<P>
   Lana Vosicher, an accounts manager at Adat Ari El, a synagogue
in North Hollywood, was not as concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been here so long, why should I care? I've been here
18 years,'' she said. ``That country is out of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kira, publisher of the national Russian-language
newspaper Contact and president of the Cable Russian Network Inc.,
said events in Russia could impact the United States. If, for
instance, Russia reverts to a military regime, Kira believes more
Russian Jews will be motivated to emigrate.
</P>
<P>
   One business that is keeping a close eye on Russia is J.T.
Granatelli Lubricants. The Camarillo, Calif.-based company struck a
deal in January to supply Russian petroleum companies and
refineries with motor oil additives and similar products.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Hibler, the company's president, said after spending two
years to develop ties with Russians, clients there had warned of
the crisis three months ago so he was prepared to slow shipments.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the biggest things any company that deals with
that area can do is to have a relationship with someone who they
trust to let them know what's really going on there,'' Hibler said.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans, for now, have little to worry about, one expert
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any major disaster. ... It creates uncertainty,
and I suppose people may be more cautious about spending,'' said
Robert Krol, an economics professor at California State University,
Northridge. ``The greater concern is how will the U.S. government
change in terms of policy. ... My hunch is that they won't have
much reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
