<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6834 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BREWERS_DIAMONDBA     08-28 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BREWERS_DIAMONDBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILENT BATS STILL PLAGUE D-BACKS  
 2-HITTER GIVES BREWERS 1ST SHUTOUT OF SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After two straight victories over the New York Mets ended their
road trip on an uplifting note, the Diamondbacks hoped to build on
that with a strong effort in a six-game homestand this week against
Pittsburgh and Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   But they dropped the first two to the Pirates, and on Thursday
night watched the Brewers put on a Roque horror pitcher show.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Rafael Roque, making only his fourth start of the
season, quieted the Diamondbacks on two hits through seven innings,
and veteran right-hander Eric Plunk did the rest as Milwaukee
recorded its first shutout of the season with a 4-0 victory at Bank
One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers, who were the only team in the major leagues without
a shutout, raised their record to 64-70. Arizona fell to 50-85.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee's last shutout was Aug. 24, 1997, when right-hander
Jose Mercedes beat Detroit, 6-0. The losing pitcher for the Tigers
was right-hander Willie Blair, who went on to sign a free-agent
deal with the Diamondbacks during the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks had only one runner go beyond first base
against Roque.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Jay Bell connected on the first pitch of the seventh
inning for a single to right-center field. He advanced to second on
a wild pitch and moved to third on a fly ball to deep center by
Travis Lee for the second out, but was stranded there when Bernard
Gilkey grounded out for the final out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The only other hit off Roque (2-1) was a broken-bat single to
shallow center by Lee to lead off the second, but Lee was erased on
an inning-ending double-play grounder by Yamil Benitez.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had trouble scoring runs all year,'' said Diamondbacks
Manager Buck Showalter, whose team was shut out for the 12th time
in its first season.
</P>
<P>
   Roque made his first major league start against the Diamondbacks
in Milwaukee on Aug. 1. He pitched four innings and gave up three
runs on five hits and was not involved in the decision.
</P>
<P>
   He was sent down to Triple-A Louisville, recalled Aug. 16 and
made starts against the San Diego Padres that day and Aug. 22,
winning the second.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to compare Thursday night's outing with his first against
Arizona, Roque said, ``Today, I threw more fastballs. Right now,
I'm just trying to stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Bobby Hughes said that once he saw Roque's fastball was
consistent, he suggested that the pitcher mix it up, working both
the inner and outer halves of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I knew he would be effective,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Brewers Manager Phil Garner was glad to get the shutout,
although he said that if the team didn't, it wouldn't have been
embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it would mean, other than we obviously are
not getting it done,'' Garner said. ``Frustrating, strange, maybe .
. .''
</P>
<P>
   Roque and Diamondbacks right-hander Andy Benes were locked in a
scoreless duel until first baseman David Nilsson hit a rope out of
the park to right field with one out in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   It was the only run given up by Benes (11-13), who lost his
second straight. Benes did have trouble with Jeff Cirillo, who
collected three hits off him. Cirillo also hit a two-run double off
right-hander Felix Rodriguez in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I gave up a lot of hits (nine in eight innings), I
thought I pitched fairly well,'' Benes said. ``But am I satisfied?
No. You're never satisfied when you lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the other guys are pitching well like they were tonight,
you've got to go out and put zeroes up on the board, because one
run is too many to give up.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
