<SLUG> BC-MARKETS-ASIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN STOCKS FALL 2 PERCENT, BUT REBOUND FROM A 12-YEAR LOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Stock markets around Asia nose-dived in early trading on
Friday, as investors feared that the deep Russian economic crisis
would hinder economic growth in the West and slow a recovery in
this region.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark Nikkei index of 225 issues at one point plunged
during morning trading to its lowest level since March 1986, down
621 points, or 4.3 percent, to 13,792.76. It then recouped much of
those losses, to stand at 14,128.97 at the midday recess _ down
284.82 points, or nearly 2 percent, from Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the key index in Singapore was off 0.3 percent, to
908.24; down 2.87 percent, to 305.55, in South Korea, and down 2.86
percent, to 2,487.40 in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most basic thing is not to panic,'' the Japanese finance
minister, Kiichi Miyazawa, said at a regular news conference on
Friday morning. Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said he hoped that
Russia's problems would not have a major impact on the world
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese yen strengthened against the dollar, trading here
at 140.6, as currency traders sold dollars in reaction to the sharp
fall in New York stocks on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning's early panic in Asian markets subsided a little
in later trading. Funds linked to the government in Taiwan helped
lift stocks there from lows, and institutional investors in
Singapore began buying after an early selloff by retail investors.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong, monetary authorities again intervened to buy
stocks. Still, at midmorning, the benchmark Hang Seng index was
down 66.37 points, or 0.8 percent, at 7,856.60.
</P>
<P>
   Asian countries have been highly sensitive to troubles elsewhere
because of the impact that outside economic shocks could have on
fragile economic recoveries here. South Korea announced on Thursday
that its economic growth for the second quarter ended on June 30
contracted by 6.6 percent on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
   Japan, too, is struggling to deal with an overwhelming banking
crisis that has engulfed the nation, and Hong Kong is battling an
economic contraction and a spike in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sitting here watching the world falling to pieces,'' said
Richard Jerram, an economist at ING Baring Securities Japan.
Referring to governments in the region, he added, ``The question
is, what can they do?''
</P>
<P>
   Investors in Asia are worried that exports, the bright prospect
for the struggling economies here, may subside if markets in Europe
and the United States suffer from a fallout from Russia. Western
economies are sensitive to the Russian debt crisis through their
commercial debt exposure and through investments in the capital
markets, with Germany, Moscow's biggest trading partner, most
directly exposed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a weakening in Western stock markets could mean
that Western buyers of goods would have less ability to absorb
exports from Asia.
</P>
<P>
   So in Tokyo, the shares of export manufacturers were hard hit,
with even the favorite stocks like the Toyota Motor Co. and the
Sony Corp. tumbling. Some banking stocks had no buyers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
