<HEADER>
A6837 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINAL-S-WADSWO     08-28 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINAL-S-WADSWORTH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWANN: SIGN TOP DRAFT PICK  
 PLUMMER, OTHERS WANT WADSWORTH IN CARDS' FOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Enough is enough, several Cardinals players said Thursday. Get
Andre Wadsworth signed, sealed and delivered, for the good of the
team and a community that finally is showing interest in the
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The most outspoken about the club's refusal to budge from its
negotiating position with the holdout first-round draft pick is the
man who has squeezed the biggest paycheck from ownership, Pro Bowl
tackle Eric Swann. In February, Swann received a club record $7.5
million signing bonus in a five-year, $25 million package.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a ton of people finally excited about the Arizona
Cardinals,'' Swann said. ``The organization has to be aware that in
this business, if you disappoint your fans time in and time out,
soon you'll have no fans. I've had enough of playing in a stadium
where three-fourths of the fans are for the opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we have a chance to turn it around. You have to do it
right and get it done. On one hand, the organization is saying,
`Trust me, believe in me,' but they have to do what is right to
earn that. The worst thing in the world is to violate the trust of
a fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're finally to the point where most of our players have the
attitude that they really want to win. It's important to me to win,
to know what that feels like because we never have here. That takes
bringing our good players in. We need to get this done. ''
</P>
<P>
   Recent indications are that Wadsworth is willing to sit out the
season and go back into the 1999 draft and that the club is willing
to let him. In fact, while Phoenix radio station KGME maintains
that Wadsworth has decided to sit out the season, Cardinals
officials said they spent Thursday afternoon exchanging proposals
with his agent, Eugene Parker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I defintely feel this isn't over,'' said Cardinals Vice
President Bob Ferguson, ``we hope to get this done.''
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth began graduate school classes at Florida State on
Thursday and plans to serve as a graduate assistant coach for the
Seminoles.
</P>
<P>
   The sticking point is Wadsworth's demand for voidable years at
the midpoint of a long contract. Club owner Bill Bidwill has
authorized an offer to Wadsworth that includes a $10.4 million
signing bonus, the third-highest ever to a rookie. But Bidwill
steadfastly refuses to include voidables.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for both sides to come off their hard-line stances and
make a deal, in Swann's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was counting on whoever is in charge to do the right things
to get a deal done,'' Swann said. ``He's a valuable asset who was
penciled in as a starter at left defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing, knowing we have such a valuable asset on
the shelf. For the last 3{ weeks, Eric Swann has been grieving.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Jake Plummer stopped short of saying that he, too,
is grieving. But Plummer made it clear that the time has come for a
resolution to the impasse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we all want to play with our best players around
us,'' Plummer said. ``I'd like to see both sides work to get it
done. But if we don't get him in, we'll still win and still have a
good team.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with a quick resolution, Wadsworth would be hard-pressed to
get ready to play at Dallas in the Sept. 6 season opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it does is shift all the plans around,'' said offensive
tackle Lomas Brown, a seven-time Pro Bowler. ``We're asking some
guys to play left defensive end who we otherwise wouldn't have
asked, and that disrupts the whole chemistry of the defense. There
are some guys real frustrated about it on the defensive side.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer said the club has not suffered a public relations black
eye yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``From reading the paper, it seems a lot of people think Andre
is just a young guy who is greedy,'' Plummer said. ``But the
organization also should be willing to give a little extra, too, to
help get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer might soon be back at the negotiating table himself. He
has one more year after this one remaining on a contract far below
the market value of a starting NFL quarterback, $595,000. In any
renegotiation, his agent, Leigh Steinberg, may ask for voidable
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even thinking about that yet,'' Plummer said. ``I've
just got to go play. If I play well and we win, I'll have no
worries.''
</P>
<P>
   Long snapper Trey Junkin has been in the league longer than
anyone on the roster, 16 years. He's seen plenty, but one thing
hasn't changed: an owner's right to do what he wants with his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the last time I checked, Bill Bidwill is the owner of the
team,'' Junkin said. ``Nobody can tell him what to do.'' &QL; 
Staff writer Steve Schoenfeld contributed to this report. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 0216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
