<HEADLINE>
BRYMER, SEAHAWKS GEAR UP FOR 49ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Dennis Erickson and Steve Mariucci agree on
two things entering their teams' preseason finale at the Kingdome
on Friday night:
</P>
<P>
   -- The last thing either wants to see is an injury to one of his
starting players when Erickson's Seahawks host Mariucci's San
Francisco 49ers;
</P>
<P>
   -- And, five preseason games are at least one too many.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five times in the preseason, three hours a day, my heart is in
my mouth, and I'm praying nobody gets hurt,'' Mariucci said after
the 49ers' three-point victory over the Seahawks two weeks ago in
Vancouver, B.C.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't try convincing Chris Brymer the preseason should be
shortened. The Seahawks' rookie free-agent guard will be the one
basking in every moment of the game.
</P>
<P>
   This probably will be Brymer's final game with the Seahawks.
When the roster is trimmed to 53 players on Sunday, Andrew Greene
will be the No. 4 guard behind starters Pete Kendall and Brian
Habib and guard-turned-center Chris Gray. When the five-man
practice squad is compiled Monday, look for the return of
guard-deep snapper Jason McEndoo, the seventh-round draft choice
from Washington State who was released on this week's cut to 60.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no control over that,'' Brymer said. ``The thing I can
do is go out and play my hardest and hopefully things will fall
into place for me. All I can do is play my heart out.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Brymer's final game should have been last week.
</P>
<P>
   Brymer was not invited to play in any of the all-star games
after his senior season at USC, or to the NFL scouting combine in
February. One pre-draft scouting report gave him less than a 25
percent chance of making an NFL roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad it happened like that because it made it more of a
challenge,'' Brymer said.
</P>
<P>
   Brymer's first challenge was just getting over the awe-factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much talent at the position, it was just
unbelievable for me that I was a part of it,'' he said. ``There's
Habib, a Super Bowl champion (with Denver last year). There's
(Kevin) Glover, a Pro Bowler. There's `House' Ballard, another Pro
Bowler. Heck, Kendall is well on his way to being a Pro Bowler. So
is Walter (Jones). He's got to be one of the best athletes I've
ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   And right in the middle of the mix, mixing it up, has been
Brymer, who has more than made up for what he might lack in talent
with determination and desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had good days, then I have a bad day now and then,''
Brymer said. ``You've just got to forget about that day and move on
to the next. You can't sit there and enjoy the glory or the next
thing you know you're getting put on your butt.''
</P>
<P>
   Brymer had one glorious moment in last week's game against
Arizona when he delivered what is called a pancake block on the
Cardinals' Eric Swann, a 313-pound Pro Bowl defensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   After being turned and flattened to the ground by Brymer, Swann
was so incensed that he kicked at the rookie and was ejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really mad that some guy came in and took care of
him,'' Brymer said. ``I'm going to remember that all my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Brymer, the memories of this summer have been
long distance for his wife, who remained in Los Angeles where she
works for an insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been working through the whole time, too, knowing I was
a rookie free agent,'' Brymer said. ``She's seen me play, but only
on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, she'll see him play a lot. Erickson plans to use
his No. 1 offense for only three series, so Brymer and his mates on
the No. 2 line can expect to play almost three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Not ideal, but better than the alternative, which is getting a
starter injured in a meaningless game.
</P>
<P>
   That's why this night, this game, will belong to players like
Chris Brymer.
</P>
<P>
   HAWK TALK: QB Steve Young was not expected to play for the
49ers. But after Young practiced Thursday, Mariucci said Young
might play one series. Young bruised his passing hand by smacking
it on a helmet in the 49ers' game against the Miami Dolphins on
Sunday . . . Injuries will prevent DT Cortez Kennedy (sprained
ankle), WR James McKnight (sprained knee) and LB Darrin Smith
(cracked ribs) from playing for the Seahawks. . . . Rookie K Wade
Richey, released by the Seahawks on Monday, has been claimed off
waivers by the 49ers and will kick for them. ``There's no question
Wade can kick in this league. He has great potential,'' Erickson
said . . . Rookie LB Anthony Simmons, the Seahawks' first-round
draft choice, ran through some agility drills with trainer Jim
Whitesel during Friday's 30-minute walk-through. Simmons has been
sidelined since spraining his right knee in the July 31 preseason
opener at Dallas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
