r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-BICKLEY_MERCURY-M     08-28 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-BICKLEY_MERCURY-MILLER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER'S MOUTH CONTINUES TO MAKE LOUD PRESENCE FELT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cheryl Miller just can't help it.
</P>
<P>
   She opens her mouth. She makes enemies.
</P>
<P>
   She refuses to talk. She makes enemies.
</P>
<P>
   She grabs a microphone after the Mercury claw to within 40
minutes of the WNBA Championship, conducts a pep rally in the glow
of victory, and she has a dynasty seething.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, my mama has taught me to be humble all my life,''
said Houston's Cynthia Cooper, two-time MVP and pretty much the
Michael Jordan of her league. ``The Bible says to be humble. It
gets to a point . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper shakes her head.
</P>
<P>
   She remembers the last time Miller picked up a microphone. It
was following a Houston victory at America West Arena earlier in
the season, a game when she predicted the two teams would be back
again in August. And then, when it really mattered, the results
would be different.
</P>
<P>
   Say what you want about Miller. But she was right.
</P>
<P>
   So, of course, after a 54-51 victory over the defending
champions, a team that hadn't lost a playoff game in their brief
history, a little gloating was in order.
</P>
<P>
   Whipping a near sellout crowd into delirium, Miller acknowledged
that she had taken some heat for her ``brash statements.'' She
thanked the fans for their support. Then she claimed the series was
``on.'' Except the pronunciation was ``Awwwwwwn,'' the taunting,
salt-in-the-wound version.
</P>
<P>
   And the opponent heard every word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheryl said something earlier, that it's the Houston Comets
that are blowing things out of proportion from the previous game
that we played here,'' Cooper said. ``She came back and said some
things tonight. The bottom line is Cheryl doesn't go out on the
court, so I'm not worried about what she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can pump up her fans. She can go out in the middle of
downtown and yell and scream. It's great for women's basketball.
It's probably great for the Phoenix Mercury fans. It doesn't matter
to Cynthia Cooper. For me, it doesn't weigh a hill of beans. It
doesn't matter what she says. They didn't beat us. We beat
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   What all of this means is simple: Like her or not, Miller is a
presence. She has a brother who is one of the top 10 players in the
NBA, a brother who did color commentary for Thursday's game, a
brother who says some of the most cocky things you'll ever hear.
And her personality still smothers his.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the Houston coach passes out candy to the
scorer's table before the game begins.
</P>
<P>
   The man is slightly overmatched.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Miller came out bobbing and weaving, clapping
her hands, telling the crowd to pump up the volume. When she
disliked a particular call Thursday, she threw her hands up to her
audience, which broke into a derisive chant targeting the
officials.
</P>
<P>
   All of which built into the crescendo of another post-game
soliloquy, ramifications be damned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a genuine love affair with us and our fans,'' Miller
said. ``If you're here, if you've been here all season, it's a
genuine love affair between the fans, this team and this staff.
It's just a way of acknowledging them. It's one of the main reasons
we want to bring a championship home to Phoenix.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also the reason that the Comets want to beat her more than
they do anyone in a Mercury uniform. This is either coaching genius
or simply part of an overgrown personality. Either way, she's
always the lightning rod, and hey, some things just run in the
family.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to like women's basketball. It will never be the
caliber of the NBA. It will never appeal to the masses. But you
can't argue with 13,600 people. You can't debate an attendance base
that continued to grow this season despite scheduling conflicts
with the Diamondbacks. In Phoenix, it's working.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to like Cheryl Miller, either. A lot of people
don't. But she's good copy. She's a big name in a league short on
headlines. And with another mouthful of bravado, she's added some
competitive drama to a series _ and a league _ that needs all it
can get. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
