<HEADLINE>
PINIELLA DRIVEN BY FATE TO SET RECORD HAT TRICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Not since 1981, when Maury Wills secretly changed the
dimensions of the batter's box to help his pitchers, has a Mariner
manager visited the frontiers of personal goofiness as Lou Piniella
did Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It was later revealed that Wills had a severe cocaine problem.
Piniella has a drug problem too: He's been drug through a wretched
season.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella certainly can't be faulted for wanting to join Wills in
an altered state. But since Wills' personal effects have long ago
been cleared out of the Kingdome, Piniella, for emotional release,
must rely on more traditional methods.
</P>
<P>
   His first couple of leg swings in the ninth inning at Jacobs
Field were worthy of last year's Seahawk special teams. But as the
tirade wore on into the fourth quarter, he was in sync with his
snapper and holder, getting excellent height and distance.
</P>
<P>
   The kicks may prove to be the longest in sports history: From
Cleveland to Cooperstown, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Since baseball has statistics, categories and awards for
everything, it has to find a place for Piniella's bonnet de boot.
</P>
<P>
   We have seen Piniella kick dirt, throw bases, tackle his own
pitchers, tell off George Steinbrenner and Marge Schott and
threaten to bungee jump off Randy Johnson. But for sheer
entertainment, Wednesday's loopiness deserves a place in the Hall
of Fame, if not its own cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   That hat belongs next to Aaron's 715th, Maris' 61st, McGwire's
pills, Ruth's keg and Jim Bouton's hotel-room keyhole.
</P>
<P>
   There was some fear in Seattle sports that once George Karl was
gone, there would be no one to take us to the edge, where we could
peer into the startling, smarmy abyss. But Piniella has rescued us
from the vanilla middle.
</P>
<P>
   As Robert Duvall put might have put it in ``Apocalypse Now,'' I
love the smell of dysfunction in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   As every armchair psychologist deduced instantly via TV,
Piniella's fury of leg-whipping was not merely about Russ Davis
being erroneously called out on the basepath. The blown call was
just the fuse for unloading a season's worth of managerial
ordnance.
</P>
<P>
   While the TV cameras caught Ken Griffey Jr. and David Segui
snickering in the dugout as Piniella did a one-man impression of
the Radio City Rockettes, it occurred that they were two among a
very few in Mariner blue who were not a part of Lose Crew.
</P>
<P>
   Most Mariners have been significant contributors to Piniella's
trip around the bend. While we don't know for sure, we can take a
guess at the identity of the cats in the hat:
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Ayala: Piniella has been like a father to Ayala, and Ayala
has been like a sun _ look at him and your eyes hurt. Perhaps
Piniella has heard for the 300th time the canard persisting in
Seattle that the relief pitcher married into Piniella's family. If
so, Piniella is talking to the Addams Family about a trade for
Pugsley.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson: He said in spring training he wouldn't talk about
his contract in the media, nor let it bother him. The next day he
was whining in the Los Angeles Times. The rest of his Mariner
career he gave up home runs to every Elmer Fudd in baseball. ``I
baby him, I talk to him, I listen to his crappy music and I say I
like his lousy photographs. He can kiss my Astro roster.''
</P>
<P>
   Russ Davis: ``Son, how many times Igottatellya: See the ball,
catch the ball. That fella across the infield? He's the first
baseman. He's our friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariner owners: ``They were rich when they bought the team. Now
they're walking around with their pants pockets turned out, and
they think they know baseball. At least Marge had a nice dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Heathcliff Slocumb: ``Three million bucks for four balls in a
row to the first batter. Fergawdsake, I can pay a buck to a stiff
from a bowling alley for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Woody Woodward: ``No, no, no, Woody! I said, `I want to kill
Randy, not deal Randy!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Himself: Why can't I talk to a young pitcher without scaring the
hell out of him? Why can't I keep a pitching coach? Why can't I
order somebody to bunt a runner along? What was I thinking when I
said in spring I was happy with the bullpen? Doesn't anybody
remember how smart I was in 1995? How did Lee Elia know when to get
out, and why didn't he tell me? Who the hell is Jose Paniagua? Why
can't I ever find my electric shaver? Where's my dignity?
</P>
<P>
   There's more, but you get the idea. Given the burdens under
which he's been operating, it's amazing Piniella didn't blow up
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   He's really not the sort of guy to keep such things under his
hat.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
