<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOYER REACHES 1,000 WHIFFS, 100 WINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Each of the two numbers ending in zero had special
meaning for Mariner left-hander Jamie Moyer. He said the smallest
one was the most satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   On a night in which the veteran pitcher captured his 100th
major-league victory, he also struck out his 1,000th big-league
batter as the Mariners battered the Cleveland Indians for a change,
pounding out a 10-4 win before 43,142 fans at Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the 100 wins,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners scored four runs in the first inning Thursday
night, watched the lead dwindle to one in the fifth, and then
resumed their offensive assault behind home runs from Alex
Rodriguez, a solo shot in the seventh and Joey Cora, a three-run
blast into the right-field seats in the eighth. It was Rodriguez's
career-high 37th home run.
</P>
<P>
   Relievers Jose Paniagua and Mike Timlin surrendered one hit in
three innings of superb mop-up work, giving Seattle its second win
in 11 games this season against the defending American League
champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleveland has beaten us up pretty much all season and it's
nice to walk away with a win,'' Moyer said. ``We're still not out
of this (AL West) race yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but the oxygen in their pennant-hope tank is near
empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to win a lot of games,'' Moyer added, ``but stranger
things have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows all about long odds.
</P>
<P>
   As a youngster in high school and college, coaches told Moyer he
never would make it as a pro baseball player. He didn't throw hard
enough. He was advised that small, skinny guys don't have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   But guile and determination have been Moyer's version of
muscle-building supplements. He reached the 1,000-strikeout plateau
when he struck out David Bell in the sixth inning, his fourth and
final strikeout of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone had told me three years ago that I would win 100
games, I probably would have said it would take me 30 years to get
there,'' he said. ``But it's a case of being in the right place at
the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer said he wondered if he ever would climb above the .500
mark.
</P>
<P>
   A 13-3 record with Boston and Seattle in 1996 and 17-5 record
with the M's last season put him over the .500 hump. And he's still
climbing, improving to 11-8 this season.
</P>
<P>
   The latest one wasn't as easy as the score indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer's pursuit of the milestone win came in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   After David Justice sliced a two-run deficit in half with a
one-out home run to left-center, Cleveland put runners on second
and third with two outs.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Lofton stepped in, already having hit a homer.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Moyer fed the speedy Indians center fielder an
outside pitch that was hit to Rodriguez, and the inning was over.
So was Moyer's 29th start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting Lofton was the big out of the game,'' manager Lou
Piniella said. ``The bullpen did the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua, who has been brilliant since being promoted from Class
AAA Tacoma two weeks ago, shut down the Indians in the seventh and
eighth innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a young kid with only four or five months in the
big-leagues who has come in here and thrown strikes,'' Timlin said
of Paniagua. ``He's throwing good strikes. I had heard that
Montreal thought he had a control problem.''
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't been a problem with Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua has worked 61/3 innings and walked two batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He goes right after the hitters,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners went right after Indians starter Jaret Wright.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs and Rodriguez on second base in the first inning,
Edgar Martinez walked, David Segui singled home the game's first
run, Russ Davis doubled home another, and Rob Ducey's infield
single and Wright's throwing error produced two more.
</P>
<P>
   Segui's single was the first of his three hits in the series
finale. He also doubled in the third and ninth innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to see David swinging the bat well again,'' said
Piniella of his first baseman who has been struggling since missing
four games earlier this month because of a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Cora's sixth homer of the season extended his hitting streak to
13 games and he also contributed one of the best defensive plays in
the game _ robbing Bell of an RBI single after Justice led off with
a double.
</P>
<P>
   Although Justice advanced to third on the play, Moyer escaped
with a 4-2 lead when he snagged Sandy Alomar's line drive and
doubled Alomar off the base.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also made a dandy defensive play. He lunged two rows into
the seats to catch Justice's popup in the eighth inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
