<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA NEEDS A REALITY CHECK ABOUT `ANDRO' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Contractors have been hired, scaffolding is going up
and hammers are flying on the greatest rebuilding project since the
Marshall Plan: Rationalizations for Mark McGwire's drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Much the same rehab is going on for Bill Clinton's image. But
more Americans care about the home run record than the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In one way, Clinton and McGwire are twins joined at the
headline. They are the two most talked-about icons in America at
the moment, for all the obvious reasons plus one more:
</P>
<P>
   Both were caught cheating on the job, and most people don't want
to hear about it.
</P>
<P>
   America doesn't want to know where Clinton puts parts of his
body or what McGwire puts in his body.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us are so eager to believe the best in those who have
done well by us that we don't want to hear they cheated.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has labored nobly on the edge of sports' most glamorous
record for more than a decade. He donates his time to children's
causes, can cry a big man's tears and is as close to Superman as we
get without finding a spaceship from Krypton.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you like or despise Clinton, the president is always the
personalized reflection of the nation's good times and bad times,
and we are in the midst of relative prosperity and peace.
</P>
<P>
   For the president and the slugger, most people just want
everything to be OK. We don't want the truth, we want reassurance.
This obsessive craving is why Disneyland works: We're perpetually
on a hunt for a world made false by eliminating reality.
</P>
<P>
   A distaste for truth is understandable, but that doesn't mean it
can't be dealt with in a way that doesn't destroy or condemn
everything attached to it.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of McGwire, his use of a testosterone-generating
substance called androstenedione does not reduce him and his
achievements to a mere freak of pharmacy. No drug is available that
will give a hitter the reflexes, timing and guts to hit a Randy
Johnson fastball 500 feet.
</P>
<P>
   But according to anecdotal evidence of some trainers and
athletes, andro may give him the strength to turn a 340-foot fly
out into a 350-foot home run.
</P>
<P>
   It's curious that McGwire claims to have begun using andro about
a year ago, about the time he fell three homers short of the
record. Apparently, McGwire decided the record was worth the
potential jeopardy to his health, because the 1998 season and its
expansion-diluted pitching might be his last good shot.
</P>
<P>
   His long history of injury, coupled with the fact that he is the
oldest player to challenge Roger Maris' mark, has made the
temptation irresistible to indulge andro, a legal, over-the-counter
substance, because the medical evidence does not yet scream in neon
letters about side effects or long-term consequences.
</P>
<P>
   He can find a number of athletes, trainers and doctors who will
support his conclusion that his regulated consumption is safe. Just
as a similar number of medical professionals can be found who will
say that conclusion isn't possible yet, as well as those who will
testify that andro's two primary uses are to mask detection of
steroids, as East German athletes did for years, and serve as a
sexual stimulant.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the facts, McGwire's tacit endorsement of andro will
cause instant over-consumption by those least able to draw
distinctions and make judgments.
</P>
<P>
   ``This entire episode has been one great big advertisement for
the drugs,'' Charles Yesalis, professor of human and performance
development at Penn State and author of ``The Steroids Game,'' told
The New York Times. ``You're going to have all kinds of kids
running out to the malls to buy it. Regardless of what the
Cardinals may say, andro is one honest-to-God sex steroid. This is
not vitamin C.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that baseball hasn't banned it is no surprise, given
the time warp in which the game exists. The sport has no rules on
performance enhancers. Can't wait to see the expression on
commissioner Bud Selig's face when he finds out teams no longer
travel to games by train.
</P>
<P>
   To limit the potential damage, what McGwire needs is full
disclosure, however difficult it may be.
</P>
<P>
   Use of performance enhancers is a huge international sports
issue, but largely ignored in the U.S. because we don't much care
about the sports where drugs are rife, such as track, swimming and
cycling.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's acknowledgment opens the door for a national
discussion on what constitutes acceptable and unacceptable drugs;
which substances are therapeutic and which enhance performance.
</P>
<P>
   As was written here about EPO, another naturally produced
hormone whose abuse scandalized the Tour de France, it's time to
consider separate classes of competition, open and pure, because
crooks are so far ahead of cops.
</P>
<P>
   As disappointing and disillusioning as it was to see McGwire's
lack of trust in his own natural abilities, he has a chance to
regain the trust of those who still think honesty is a worthwhile
thing.
</P>
<P>
   He, the Cardinals and baseball can take the lead in being open
about use of andro and any other history of performance enhancing
substances, knowing McGwire's previous goodwill will create a fair
response from the sports public.
</P>
<P>
   Or, they can continue the national trend of running away from
the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
