<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON, WE HAVE LIFTOFF  
 MERCURY SENDS A MESSAGE TO DEFENDING CHAMPIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one raced to Andrea Kuklova's locker after the Mercury put
the WNBA defending champion Houston Comets on the brink of
elimination Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   There were too many second-half heroes to mob, especially
Jennifer Gillom, who transformed her block with 33.4 seconds left
at one end into a determined layup at the other at 8.9 to beat the
Comets, 54-51, in the only Phoenix home game of the best-of-three
finals.
</P>
<P>
   But the 13,634 X-factors at America West Arena would have had
little to cheer down the stretch if it hadn't been for Kuklova, the
nearly forgotten Slovakian guard whose first-half poise kept
Houston from pushing the cold-shooting Mercury into the ropes for
the rest of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 16-8, with two fouls apiece on defensive keys Umeki
Webb and Michelle Griffiths and shooting just 26.7 percent from the
field, Phoenix (22-12) was at risk of handing the opener to the
Comets' Big Three.
</P>
<P>
   But like two days earlier in Cleveland, when Cheryl Miller
snagged 6-foot-8 Maria Stepanova off the bench for nine critical
minutes that put away the semifinal tiebreaker, the 6-foot Kuklova
came up just as big.
</P>
<P>
   Her line _ two points, three assists and a block in 11:42 _
cannot adequately explain the difference she made in sending the
Mercury into the locker room with an uplifting 33-29 lead. The
Mercury was the first team to beat Houston (29-4) twice this
season.
</P>
<P>
   The scene shifts to the Compaq Center for Game 2 at 1 p.m.
Saturday and, if necessary, Game 3 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a firm believer there are horses for courses,'' said
Mercury point guard Michele Timms. ``It's been a real experiment
for the coaching staff, finding the right games to play Maria, Dre
(Kuklova) and Kristi (Harrower). There have been games where they
haven't had much court time, but there have been games where they
have and have come on and done really well.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you know what, she's an international player and a great
player. She's been in finals before. Looking at our team, I
wouldn't have worried if I was the coaching staff because we have a
heck of a lot of experience. And Dre's been in big games before
with her national team, her French team and her Slovakian team. She
played with a lot of poise and a lot of confidence, which is tough
when you've been sitting out.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuklova has only reached double-figure minutes in one of the 10
previous games. But she kept Sheryl Swoopes in check when defensive
assignments were shuffled because of the fouls, and Swoopes never
found her range. She went 3-for-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very important game and I played well,'' Kuklova said
through her French interpreter. ``It's hard not to play for a few
games then to come out and do well against a big team like Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played good defense and on offense I didn't force anything
and took my time. It was good for the team because it was kind of
so-so then we started looking for the best shot.''
</P>
<P>
   As is typical of championship basketball, defense prevailed and
neither team achieved 35 percent shooting from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Two-time WNBA most valuable player Cynthia Cooper was seven
above her league-leading average with 29 points, but the other
parts of the all-league trio (Swoopes and Tina Thompson) combined
for 12. Gillom was the only other player to reach double-figure
scoring and her 15 points were five below her average in what for
the MVP runner-up rates as an off night.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-3 center got a hand on the forced shot by 5-5 Kim Perrot
as the shot clock ran down on Houston inside the final minute with
the game tied at 51. The rejection went to Timms, who called a
20-second timeout as the Mercury shifted into a now well-polished
routine of intelligent execution in critical situations.
</P>
<P>
   Stalling until 17 seconds (14 on the shot clock) remained, Timms
started a play that was not intended for Gillom, the queen of
buzzer beaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was supposed to be used as a decoy,'' she said, the idea
being to work the ball side to side and catch the Comets
overguarding Gillom. ``The ball ended up in my hands, and I saw
Michele (Timms) on the wing open.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 34-year-old also knew she was one-on-one down low and
beat the 23-year-old Thompson to the basket before Cooper could
help.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's one-handed three-point heave at the buzzer came
respectably close but could not avert the prediction of her former
USC college teammate, Miller _ who foresaw a Mercury win _ from
coming true.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix did play Houston here again, as Miller promised after a
three-point loss JulyT21 to the Comets, and did reverse the
outcome. But unlike the winner-take-all, one-game format of 1997,
that doesn't win a title. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
