<HEADLINE>
FOX PLAYS HIS 6TH POSITION  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Andy Fox, it's six down and three to go.
</P>
<P>
   Fox started in center field against Milwaukee on Thursday night,
the sixth different position he has played this season. Devon White
was a late scratch because of back spasms.
</P>
<P>
   Fox logged a few innings in center during spring training, but
had not played there in a real game since last year, in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another place that Andy gives us an option,'' Manager
Buck Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said it wasn't a big change from the corner outfield
positions. One good thing is that the ball doesn't slice as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's that much of a difference,'' he said.
``You've got more room to cover, but a fly ball is a fly ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox has mainly been the Diamondbacks' second baseman, but he
also has played left field, right field, first base and third base.
That leaves pitcher and catcher _ which he never has played _ and
shortstop, where Fox has seen considerable action in the past.
Would he like to play all nine positions before the season ends?
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be kind of neat, but I don't think it's gonna
happen,'' he said, citing the ``horror story'' of Jose Canseco
pitching (he hurt his arm) and the possibility of injury as a
catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice, but it wouldn't ruin the season if I didn't
do it,'' said Fox, who has pushed his batting average to near the
.300 mark. ``I don't want to make a mockery of the game.'' &QL;  &QL; 
High marks &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks Class-A affiliate in the California League,
High Desert, reaped some major awards Thursday. Right-hander Brad
Penny was named Most Valuable Player and Pitcher of the Year. It's
the first time since 1980 and the second time since 1960 a pitcher
was named MVP. And Don Wakamatsu, a former Arizona State catcher,
was named Manager of the Year. &QL;  &QL; 
Bean counting &QL;  &QL; 
After three straight home crowds of fewer than 40,000, Thursday's
attendance was announced as 40,856 even though a lot of green seats
were showing. Perhaps one reason was that some people reportedly
bought multiple tickets to stock up on Beanie Babies being given
away (Sly, the fox, with a card of authenticity autographed by
Andy). &QL;  &QL; 
Pretty cheesy &QL;  &QL; 
Is there any doubt who rules the Land of the Cheeseheads? The
Brewers' game against the Diamondbacks tonight was bumped from the
club's regular radio station to another station for a Green Bay
Packers preseason game.
</P>
<P>
   Also, with the tying run on third base for the Diamondbacks in
Thursday's game, the Fox Network cut away to catch up with Sammy
Sosa's home run chase. Batting in the eighth inning at Colorado's
Coors Field, the Chicago Cubs' slugger flied out. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
