u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-FOOLS-REVIEW-HNS     08-28 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FOOLS-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
FEUDING WIDOWS OF '50s STAR KEEP THE BEAT GOING IN `FOOLS' 
 
By JEFF MILLAR 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some ideas for movies are just so rip-roaring,
makes-perfect-sense good that the inertia of the conception runs
all through the execution, spackling over bigger errors than it
should. ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love'' is based upon something just
irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-'80s, three women in their late 40s presented
themselves in a New York City courtroom in the matter of Frankie
Lymon.
</P>
<P>
   If you are of a certain age, you will surely remember doo-wop,
that subgenus of rhythm and blues; you might remember the
Teenagers, the group Lymon fronted; you will probably remember
their big hit _ ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love'' _ which Lymon
co-wrote, because it's a great song.
</P>
<P>
   But if you ever heard Lymon sing ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love''
there is no chance of forgetting that. His voice hadn't changed
when he recorded it, in 1955. If you could tear a half-inch-thick
pane of glass, that's what Lymon's voice sounded like on ``Why Do
Fools Fall in Love.`` It made Michael Jackson sound like James Earl
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   He was in the first wave of R&AMP;B artists who got suburban
teen-agers sprinting across the color line to the Alan Freed stage
shows. For a while, it was very good. But the Teenagers dissolved,
he went solo, his voice broke, he took to heroin, the gigs stopped
coming. By age 25, he was a nostalgia act, when he worked at all.
In 1968, an overdose sent him to rock 'n' roll heaven.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, Diana Ross covered ``Fools'' beginning a process that
led to the courtroom. Each of the women claimed Frankie's cut of
the royalties, because each believed herself to be his widow _
widows Nos. 1, 2 and 3, as the bemused judge calls them in order of
(alleged) nuptials. This matter could have been cleared up more
simply if Frankie had divorced any of them, but he didn't. Frankie
wasn't a details guy.
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 is Elizabeth Waters (Vivica A. Fox), recently released
from a Pennsylvania prison after one of several convictions for
theft. She says she was married to Frankie in 1964, when he was
living in New York, then tumbling down the professional ladder and
deep into dope. She said she turned tricks to support them.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 is Zola Taylor (Halle Berry), who was the female of the
doo-wop heavyweights The Platters (``Only You,'' ``My Prayer'').
She says she was married to Frankie when she lived in Los Angeles
in 1965. She helped get him a few gigs; and when she was off on a
four-month tour, Frankie spent every dime Zola had saved and
trashed her house.
</P>
<P>
   No. 3 is Emira Engle (Lela Rochon), a demure Georgia
schoolteacher, who said she was married to Frankie in 1967, met him
when he was stationed there in the Army. They had a big church
wedding. And although Frankie had moved out, ostensibly to restart
his career, she was still married to him when he died.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers find a good deal of the amusement in flashing
back from the witness stand to show each widow's version of
Frankie, ``Rashomon'' style. The homebody, gardening and
handy-with-a-hammer husband Emira describes is as plausible to
Widows Nos. 1 and 2 as one of those bugs from ``Starship
Troopers.''
</P>
<P>
   Still more amusing is the character work for show-biz-tough Zola
and the street-tough Elizabeth. They had their turf war over
Frankie while he was alive and don't like each other a bit. Berry
and Fox really light into this material. They're wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   Rochon is stalwart as the drabbie. As Frankie, Larenz Tate has
been dealt the worst hand at the table. As the direct object of the
``Roshamon'' gimmick, he's a big piece of wet clay being molded by
somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   Frankie's sketched almost entirely in the glyphs of
show-biz-movie cliches and the character given most of screenwriter
Tina Andrews' weakest dialogue. When an entertainer character looks
into the middle distance and begins a line with, ``When I'm out
there on that stage. ...'' I've learned to clap my hands over my
ears before the rest of the line can be delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Understand that this feints being a bio-pic of Frankie Lymon,
but it simply is not. It's about the three widows. Because the film
is not conceptualized to tell a linear nor even coherent story
about Lymon _ although you might find yourself wishing it were _
Tate just isn't allowed to work toward his own sense of what
Frankie is really like. Tate is an adequate actor, but this
assignment would have scared off an all-star team. He does a
first-rate job, though, of becoming Frankie onstage. He lip-synchs
the original Lymon recordings and is agile in the synchronized
group moves, as vital to doo-wop as the bass who goes, ``Oom Bopa
Doom Bopa Doom Bopa Doo Dut.''
</P>
<P>
   But I'll tell you, when director Gregory Nava, who also did
``Selena,'' is really getting into the doo-wop life, up there with
Little Richard (as himself, and a stitch) on the Alan Freed stage
show tours, lots more than I was actually prepared to forgive was
suddenly forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   Fun movie. Watch that R rating. Did I say Elizabeth and Zola
were tough? They're tough, baby.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
