 NEWS &AMP; FEATURES SUMMARY No 2476 - August 28, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To publish any of the special ``separate buy'' articles listed
below, it must be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from
one of these New York Times sales representatives:
</P>
<P>
   _ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 33-1-47-42-17-11;
fax, 33-1-47-42-80-44 or 33-1-47-42-18-81. e-mail: nyt &LR; calva.net
NEWS AND FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2476 -- August 28, 1998 We are
offering the following articles for sale. Please contact us for
availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. PRINCESS DIANA A. DIANA'S PICTURE WAS WORTH 1,000 OF HER
WORDS. By Kate Kellaway. B. THE CELEBRITY MONARCHY. By Ian Buruma.
C. HOW PEOPLE MOURNED IN BRITAIN. By Michael Ignatieff.
</P>
<P>
   (The above three articles are from Prospect magazine. Not
available U.K.) D. PRINCESS DIANA : A LOOK BACK. By Dorothy
Rompalske. Biography magazine.
_________________________________________________________________
2. TO COMBAT TERRORISTS, U.S. RAIDS REQUIRE COMMANDO UNITS,
</P>
<P>
   NOT CRUISE MISSILES, RANAN LURIE SAYS Ranan Lurie, who is known
internationally as a political cartoonist and analyst, was a
celebrated Israeli army combat major in the Six Day War. He
addresses the strategy chosen by the United States to enter into
what President Clinton is now calling ``a long, ongoing struggle
between freedom and fanaticism, between the rule of law and
terrorism.'' To Lurie, it takes hand-to-hand, gutsy commando action
to bring down terrorists, and the idea of firing Tomahawk missiles
at a training camp buried in the mountains is an expensive way of
``saying something you don't really mean.'' Interview by Carolee
Morrison. 1,500 words.
_________________________________________________________________
3. STUDIES LIKELY TO FUEL DEBATE OVER ANIMAL ORGAN TRANSPLANTS
Researchers are trying to find ways to transplant animal organs
into humans (xenotransplantation,) but there is a danger that
animal tissues are infected with pathogens which, though harmless
to animals, could cause serious diseases in humans. By Michael
McCarthy. Lancet News Service. 1,000 words.
_________________________________________________________________
4. ``WAR ON TERRORISM'' CAN DRIVE YOU BONKERS In what has become
the manner of the times, the newly proclaimed ``war on terrorism''
is taking on a shrill, hyper-menacing tone that cannot help the
U.S. deal with the problem. Some commentators seem almost gleeful
at finding a dangerous new enemy to take the place of the Cold War
threat. It is as though nothing else is going on in the world
except Monica Lewinsky and terrorism. By Flora Lewis. 800 words.
_________________________________________________________________
5. KIDS WHO CAN'T SAY GOODBYE Some children have difficulty with
transitions because they think that all their fun is being removed
- and that they'll never have a good time again. Margaret D. Rosin
gives sound advice on what to say and do to help children move
along. From Child magazine. 1,200 words.
_________________________________________________________________
6. WHAT'S DOING IN CASABLANCA Casablanca, the biggest city and main
port of Morocco, is intensely romantic - faded, languid and vaguely
decadent. Tips on events, sightseeing, hotels and restaurants. By
Joseph B. Treaster. NYT Way To Go! 1,800 words + photos + map.
_________________________________________________________________
7. MEDICAL BREAKTHROUGHS YOU CAN TOUCH The health-and-fitness world
of the future is now on display in Disneyland's new
``Innoventions'' exhibit, which provides hands-on fun for adults
and children. The exhibit combines Disney's storytelling abilities
with the expertise of other companies to demonstrate the hottest
developments in technology (e.g. a 10-foot-high interactive human
heart: when you put your hand on the heart, you can hear your own
heartbeat.) By Kathy Sena. From California Health magazine. 700
words + photos.
_________________________________________________________________
8. MAKE YOUR SHOPPING 'ROBOT' SEARCH THE NET So far, shopping
robots have been fairly primitive. The category's ancestor,
Andersen Consultant's Bargain Finder, searches 10 on-line stores
for the price of a compact disk and displays the results on a
single page. Now two young Germans have gone a step further toward
a ``smarter'' shopping agent. By Bruno Giussani. From New York
Times CyberTimes. 1,100 words.
_________________________________________________________________
9. ``SUFFERING CAMPS'' FOR OBESE CHINESE CHILDREN One effect of the
general rise in the standard of living in China and, above all, of
the government's ``single child'' policy, which encourages parents
to give in to their child's slightest whim, has resulted in martial
establishments known as ``suffering camps'' for overweight
children. By Frederic Bobin. From Le Monde. 600 words. (English
translation available.)
________________________________________________________________
10. JET-AGE BEDOUINS Home isn't what it used to be. These days we
may live on planes, in fast-food shops and hotel lobbies. Many
people don't actually have a place of their own but simply shuttle
back and forth. More and more of us are going tribal - living in
the crevices between cultures like jet-age Bedouins, in homes as
mobile as our spirits ..... By Pico Iyer. Wired magazine. 1,000
words.
</P>
</TEXT>
