<HEADER>
A7165 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-DYER29-COX     08-28 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-DYER29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REVIEW: Uproarious 'Rage' mocks the writer's life
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OUT OF SHEER RAGE: Wrestling with D.H. Lawrence, By Geoff Dyer,
North Point; 241 pages; $22
</P>
<P>
   For most of its length, Out of Sheer Rage is a book about how
Geoff Dyer cannot bring himself to write a book, specifically a
book about D.H. Lawrence, the writer who made him want to become a
writer. That's a terrible thing to do to anyone, and Out of Sheer
Rage is Dyer's revenge.
</P>
<P>
   It's a hilarious, viciously ill-tempered screed, reeking of more
or less justified self-loathing, reading as if it was written on
the razored edge between a speed trip and utter despair, as if the
author was the result of some unholy one-night stand between Hunter
Thompson and Dorothy Parker.
</P>
<P>
   The initial idea is that if Dyer can focus on writing a sober
study of Lawrence, it might enable him to pull his life together.
Instead, his failure to write the book only accelerates the chaos,
which in turn forces him to slaughter his own literary child before
it can achieve maturity.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, as Dyer notes, the book on Lawrence is a way of
evading the book he really wants to write, a novel. ``I went from
not working on my book about Lawrence to not working on the novel
because all of this to-ing and fro-ing and note-taking actually
meant that I never did any work on either book.''
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere Dyer looks, something happens to stimulate the fury
he thought was exhausted. Dyer and his girlfriend, a long-suffering
creature named Laura - her motto for their relationship is
``Together Forever''; his is ``Together Whenever'' - go for a moped
ride. The cycle crashes, whereupon Dyer develops a pain in his neck
that forces him to keep a hand under his chin for support.
</P>
<P>
   ``To everyone else ... it looked like I was deep in thought,
wrestling with philosophical problems, when all I was doing was
trying to bear the awful weight of my head - which, on reflection,
is what all philosophical thought comes down to anyway: how to bear
the awful weight of your head.''
</P>
<P>
   He tries reading recent criticism of Lawrence, and the turgid
post-structuralist prose only increases his roiling frustration:
``How could these people with no feeling for literature have ended
up teaching it, writing about it? ... Writing like that kills
everything it touches. Walk around a university campus and there is
an almost palpable smell of death about the place because hundreds
of academics are busy killing everything they touch.''
</P>
<P>
   He concludes this outburst, which would have fit splendidly in
the mouth of Network's Howard Beale, with, ``How can you know
anything about literature if all you've done is read books?''
</P>
<P>
   In a desperate attempt to jump-start his book, Dyer and his
girlfriend go on a disastrous odyssey that retraces Lawrence's
footsteps from Eastwood, England, his hometown (which now features
a blue line that leads you on a self-guided tour of Lawrence
sites), to Mexico, to Taos, New Mexico. In all these places, Dyer
encounters bad food, vile inhabitants and spontaneous explosions of
eczema.
</P>
<P>
   At first, I thought Geoff Dyer had written a hilarious novel in
the form of nonfiction, a successor to A Fan's Notes or My Search
for Warren Harding. But, hidden in the thickets of misanthropy is
some serious critical writing about Lawrence. It's perfectly
intelligent criticism, but it pales in originality next to Dyer's
take on his own life. Besides, at this late date, I'd rather
countenance root canal than read about The Plumed Serpent.
</P>
<P>
   Between the lines of Dyer's neurasthenia is a trenchant
self-portrait of the writer as doomed misfit. Musing on the subject
of children, whom he regards largely as virulent carriers of
influenza, Dyer writes that ``children are so convenient: you have
children because you're struggling to get by as an artist ... or
failing to get by with your career. Then you can persuade yourself
that your children prevented you from having this career that had
never looked like working out. So it goes on: Things are always
forsaken in the name of an obligation to someone else, never as a
failing, a falling short of yourself. Before you know it, desire
has atrophied to the degree that it can only make itself apparent
by passing itself off as an obligation.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of Sheer Rage is as perfect a picture of the Writer as Jerk
as the Coen brothers' Barton Fink or Woody Allen's Deconstructing
Harry - exposure to which is mandatory, cautionary viewing for
anyone foolish enough to want to be a writer, or self-destructive
enough to want to live with a writer, but more or less
incomprehensible to those unfamiliar with the dismal trade.
</P>
<P>
   There may be better books published in 1998, and there assuredly
will be more serious books published in 1998, but the utter
originality of Out of Sheer Rage makes it unlikely to be exceeded
for sheer pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
