<HEADER>
A7168 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOUND-METEORITES29-C0     08-28 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOUND-METEORITES29-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: You may have a valuable meteorite and not know it
 &HT;    By Frank Cerabino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I don't want you to think I'm a nut,'' the man said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he told me about the grapefruit-size meteorite that left a
crater in the back yard of his Acreage home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out to feed the ducks when I saw it,'' Rick Daddea
said.
</P>
<P>
   So I went to see Daddea, the rock and the alleged crater at the
edge of his backyard duck pond.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I got to Daddea's secluded Acreage home, his
thinking on the rock had evolved from talking about ``donating it
to the Smithsonian'' to ``selling it to the highest bidder.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one of the reasons scientists are squeamish when talking
about meteorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been burned before with meteorites,'' said Dr. Jack
Horkheimer, director of the Miami Space Transit Planetarium.
``There are so many things that can mimic a meteorite. And there
are people who do it for hoaxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Daddea says he thinks he has the real thing. That's why he took
the dense, dark rock on Wednesday to the South Florida Science
Museum in West Palm Beach, where planetarium director Erich
Landstrom chipped off a piece of it to send to the Smithsonian for
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Landstrom doesn't have anything to say about the alleged
meteorite until the results come back in about a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get people every day telling me they've found a meteorite,''
said Eric Twelker, a lawyer in Juneau, Alaska, who owns an on-line
meteorite sales business called The Meteorite Market. ``One guy's
been pushing a piece of limestone on me for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Twelker buys and sells meteorites around the world. He has an
inventory of about 500 meteorite chunks for sale and thousands of
what he describes as ``little bitty things.''
</P>
<P>
   Meteorites are priced by the gram, and a 5-pound rock, something
about the size of Daddea's find, could fetch thousands of dollars
from a collector, Twelker said.
</P>
<P>
   Some meteorites are more significant than others. Most of them
come from the asteroid belt between Jupiter and Mars. When these
asteroid chunks collide during their orbits, they break apart and
Jupiter's gravitational power flings them into elliptical
trajectories that cross Earth's path.
</P>
<P>
   But others are actually wayward pieces of our moon or other
planets. A meteorite from Mars, a rarity, goes for about $2,000 per
gram, Twelker said. (There are about 457 grams per pound.)
</P>
<P>
   One piece, weighing about a hundredth of an ounce, sold at
auction this year for $4,600.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Earth receives at least 10 tons of meteoric dust every
day,'' Horkheimer said.
</P>
<P>
   Entry into the Earth's atmosphere burns up most of the
meteorites, turning them into flashes in the night sky but nothing
big enough to make an impact on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   But a small number of meteorite chunks do manage to survive the
scorching trip through our planet's atmosphere. The biggest of all
is a 60-ton meteorite that landed in Namibia. America's biggest
meteorite struck in Willamette, Ore., and weighed 14 tons.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, a 27-pound meteorite demolished a car parked in
a driveway in Peekskill, N.Y. And this year, seven boys playing
basketball in Monahans, Texas, were surprised when a meteorite ball
landed near their court.
</P>
<P>
   That meteorite, which weighed less than three pounds, was sold
at auction last month to a collector for $23,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are real meteorites,'' Twelker said, ``and they do
fall.''
</P>
<P>
   But he sees a lot of so-called meteorites that don't end up
being out of this world.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think that unusual rocks are meteorites, and that's
generally not the case,'' he said. ``I recently had a guy who
brought a musket ball to my attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Daddea took an astronomy course in college, has a telescope at
his house and was recently in his back yard looking for meteorite
trails in the night sky.
</P>
<P>
   A meteorite the size of his rock might have created a sonic boom
and would have definitely landed in a ground-pounding fireball,
Twelker said.
</P>
<P>
   But Daddea didn't see or hear it land, he said. He said he
discovered it while walking to the edge of his duck pond one
morning and seeing the edge of the rock sticking out in the middle
of a circular, pothole-size indentation in the soft, sandy soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a meteorite,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The rock does display some of the characteristics of a
meteorite.
</P>
<P>
   It attracts a magnet _ a vast majority of meteorites contain
iron.
</P>
<P>
   It has a dark rind on the outer surface, which appears to be
what's known as a fusion crust, a burned appearance created by the
entry into Earth's atmosphere. And it also has an irregular shape
marked by ``thumb prints,'' which the heat generated from entry
causes in meteorites.
</P>
<P>
   But scientists perform specialized tests on possible meteorites,
examining their crystal structure and pinpointing their composition
to rule out earthly copycats.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things that are very difficult to fake,'' Twelker
said.
</P>
<P>
   So Daddea's waiting for the test results to come back and
starting to collect preliminary offers from collectors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been getting offers of several thousands of dollars for
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about keeping it for yourself?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   Daddea said he'd have no use for a meteorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a rock,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 1032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 10:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7169 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PREACHER-SWAP29-COX     08-28 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREACHER-SWAP29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clergy exchange creates bonds that span an ocean
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The preacher spoke with a delightful
English accent, but some of the words he used needed translation.
Most of us understand fridge, but calling a sports utility vehicle
a lorry is a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the English pastor, the Rev. David Farey, was warm and
genuine as he prayed with the American congregation at the Church
of the Advent in Palm City, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The Advent's real pastor, the Rev. Dexter Kessler, was at All
Saint's Church in Laughton, in the south of England.
</P>
<P>
   He led worship in a church built in 1229, more than 700 years
before anyone thought of building the Church of the Advent.
</P>
<P>
   The clergymen swapped churches, homes and cars for August. Each
took his family and went abroad to the other's parish.
</P>
<P>
   That offered one the opportunity to visit the colonies, the
other to discover his roots. It is the first trip for each to the
other's country. Each had an unusual and inexpensive vacation, met
new friends and overcame some culture shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is very big,'' said Farey, 42, reflecting on the
size of American cars, homes, roads, stores, stoves and
refrigerators. ``And it's very hot. But it's great to be here. The
wonderful thing that sets this apart is that we are living in
someone's home. We get to meet people in a way that you wouldn't if
you simply went as a tourist.''
</P>
<P>
   Farey is a priest of the Church of England and pastor of three
small churches in villages about an hour south of London. It is
common for English parsons to have responsibility for more than one
small congregation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Farey is here with his wife, Pat, and their three children,
Christina, 9, Jonathan, 6, and Luke, 3.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler, 54, is pastor of Advent and a priest of the Episcopal
Church in America. The exchange is possible because the two
churches are historically and spiritually linked.
</P>
<P>
   The Episcopal church is the independent American expression of
the Church of England that began after the American Revolution. The
denominations have a kind of spiritual mother-daughter
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The two clergy traded places for the month. Each pastor led
services on one Sunday (substitute clergy looked after the churches
for the remainder of the month). The rest of the pastors' time is
for holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Advent have taken the Fareys into their hearts and
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a wonderful thing,'' said Heidi McNabb, a vestry
member. ``We've adopted them. Now, they are part of our family.''
</P>
<P>
   Kessler and his wife, Cindy, have become part of another church
family. They are in a little village of several hundred people
where the roads are narrow, the pubs popular and there are more
sheep than people.
</P>
<P>
   In the village pubs _ Roebucks or The Green Man _ they are
welcomed ``not as tourists or Americans but as part of the local
community,'' Kessler said in a telephone interview from his August
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fantastic,'' he said. ``I get up in the morning and
look out. I can't see a car. I can't hear an airplane. I hear
birds. Roses are everywhere. The people in the town have welcomed
us like members of the family.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the swap began through a little-known,
not-for-profit, one-man organization in Ontario, Canada, called the
Episcopal Clergy Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Christopher Davis, a priest of the Anglican Church of
Canada, is the third person to run the exchange since it began in
Pennsylvania in 1981, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He places a notice in church magazines, advertising the service.
English, Canadian and American Episcopal clergy interested in an
exchange submit information about their homes and churches and send
a $10 fee to Davis.
</P>
<P>
   He publishes a newsletter in February and April each year,
listing the interested clergy. The rest of the arrangements are up
to them, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler and Farey were among 51 clergy in this year's
newsletter. They contacted each other to make the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I seldom hear about how many exchanges actually take place,''
Davis said. ``The only indication that the system is working is
that people keep applying.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every exchange includes the use of a car, Davis said. This
one did.
</P>
<P>
   The Kesslers traveled more than 1,200 miles in the first two
weeks in search of history, Dexter Kessler said. They crisscrossed
the country from Shakespeare's Stratford-on-Avon to Bath, Dover and
Canterbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like walking back into all the books you've read, the
English literature, English history, church history,'' Kessler
said. ``It's very moving to walk in the same footsteps that people
have walked for hundreds of years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fareys have been traveling as well, discovering things
ancient and modern. A trip to Lake Okeechobee brought them, to
their wonder, face to face with an alligator. Disney World and the
Kennedy Space Center are on their agenda.
</P>
<P>
   They are delighted to be in America _ even if that means being
among an English-speaking people who do not understand their
language.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really God-smacked that we're here,'' said Pat Farey.
``It's a big adventure for us. God-smacked? You don't use that
expression? It means amazed.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
