</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDIO54-MEMORIES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Memories of Studio 54
 &HT;    By Thom Smith
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   `If you were really into it, you won't remember'
</P>
<P>
   Society photographer Lucien Capehart:
</P>
<P>
   I used to have hourlong phone conversations with Steve Rubell
all the time and never met him. Why? I don't know why. He just
liked to talk to people.
</P>
<P>
   It was a lot of fun. Like a big movie theater. It still had a
lot of the theater seats in it. It was all black inside, a lot of
narrow passageways.
</P>
<P>
   One waiter I know in Palm Beach says if you were really into it,
you won't remember.
</P>
<P>
   `It seemed like it was never gonna stop'
</P>
<P>
   Artist Bruce Helander:
</P>
<P>
   The first time I went there, it was a juice bar, and it was
packed. They were serving fruit juice and nobody knew why. It
turned out Rubell had taken out a caterer's license, which is a
one-night deal, and was nabbed. He finally did get his liquor
license later on.
</P>
<P>
   It was the height of disco, and everybody was just happy to get
in the door. The B&AMP;T _ bridge and tunnel _ crowd, was so eager to
get in that they didn't complain. I had no problem because I was an
artist and Rubell wanted people who looked like we did. If you
looked right and strutted the right strut, that's what he was
looking for.
</P>
<P>
   Later on in the evenings, they couldn't close the cash registers
because they were overflowing with cash. Very few people left until
the wee hours of the morning. The great shocker was that the doors
would open and it was like a nuclear blast because it was complete
daylight. We had been dancing all night and didn't realize it.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Warhol would always be there. There was always a circle of
people around him. He had a big magic marker and Interview
magazines, and he would sign them across the top. His real purpose
was finding portrait candidates for the magazine. He definitely was
the king of the place. He was almost always there.
</P>
<P>
   The whole thing was lighting. The decor didn't matter because it
was kept dark and romantic and secretive. If you wanted to be seen,
you'd go to the bathroom _ that's where the lights were. It didn't
matter which, men and women were in both.
</P>
<P>
   It just seemed like it was never gonna stop.
</P>
<P>
   Roxanne Pulitzer: It was another world
</P>
<P>
   It was the place to go at the time. Herbert (husband Peter's
first name) and I pulled up in our limo, and we both looked at each
other because there was such a crowd. ...
</P>
<P>
   One big heavyset man pointed at us _ I don't know why _ and we
walked right in.
</P>
<P>
   It was the time of disco _ we stayed late, the people-watching
was great. ... Even back then they had the transvestites, men
together on the dance floor. ... You felt like you were in another
world.
</P>
<P>
   We had just been married a couple of years. I was a baby going
there. It was exciting that you could see so many celebrities _
Halston and Liza, Bianca Jagger, David Bowie, Warhol _ oddly
enough, he was with C.Z. Guest.
</P>
<P>
   It was dark, with lights on the dance floor. I couldn't even
describe the colors. It was red and black, I think, almost
bordello-ish in my mind. You could see every extreme _ lots of
beautiful people.
</P>
<P>
   Thom Smith writes for The Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
