<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7171 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STUDIO54-OWNER29-COX     08-28 1809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDIO54-OWNER29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-Studio 54 co-owner Ian Schrager still selling excitement
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The boyish grin and the chiseled good looks from the
days when he was co-owner of Studio 54 are still there.
</P>
<P>
   And the energy.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Schrager goes from 0 to 60 in 4 seconds _ his plans for a
new ``boutique'' line of hotels and his enthusiasm for his newly
acquired European hotels accelerating at a speed that would leave
button-down CEOs with their button-down market surveys smelling
rubber.
</P>
<P>
   Schrager looks hipper than a Gap ad in his collarless white
shirt rolled up above the elbows and wrinkled khaki pants. His new
offices overlooking the Hudson River are all monastic white,
serene, ultra-chic.
</P>
<P>
   A perfect contrast to his frenetic pace and colorful ideas.
</P>
<P>
   He is the largest hotel owner in New York, the mastermind behind
some of the world's most fashionable, and profitable, hotels
including Manhattan's trendiest trio, the Royalton, Morgans and the
Paramount, and Miami Beach's hottest ticket, the Delano.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, he will renovate the St. Moritz on Central Park South,
turning it into his luxurious flagship.
</P>
<P>
   Schrager's genius is his combination of business savvy and
creativity _ and his nose for cutting-edge trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like this reconciliation of art and commerce,'' he said.
``You can do both. You can do something that's very financially
successful and something special.''
</P>
<P>
   But few do, especially in the hotel industry, where a room is a
room is a room, and the most you can hope for is a plaid sofa and
HBO.
</P>
<P>
   At Schrager's hotels, though, the rooms are, well, different.
</P>
<P>
   There are the Alice-in-Wonderland chairs with high backs that
would easily accommodate Shaquille O'Neal, beds jutting out of
6-foot-high silk-screened Jan Vermeer paintings with gilted frames,
and bathroom sinks that look like stainless steel ice cream cones.
</P>
<P>
   Guests are shocked, and delighted. And they keep coming.
</P>
<P>
   He gives them what they crave _ excitement, drama and art for a
price that the hip, but not necessarily the wealthy, can afford.
(Paramount rates start at $135.)
</P>
<P>
   Schrager does have his detractors. Hotelier Donald Trump told
The New York Times that Schrager ``puts linoleum in the bathrooms
and gets people to pay a high price.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he was making a compliment to me,'' said
Schrager, laughing. ``I sent Donald a roll of linoleum because we
don't have any linoleum in the bathrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   What he does have is a psychic ability to predict what people
want.
</P>
<P>
   How does a person go about creating a Paramount or a Royalton?
</P>
<P>
   ``Vision,'' he said, without hesitation, ``a certain idea, a
passion, enthusiasm, a certain desire to do something different.''
</P>
<P>
   And hard work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It evolves through attrition,'' he said. ``You leave no stone
unturned. You give everything you have to it, no detail goes
unnoticed. Then at the end of the day it all miraculously comes
together and the sum of the parts is more than the individuals.
It's like a painting.''
</P>
<P>
   The hotel industry, he said, has been organized around either
great service _ the Ritz Carlton is an example _ or great
execution, such as the Marriott, but not innovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my opportunity and my niche,'' he said. ``Sameness
and predictability used to be considered a virtue. I don't think it
is a virtue. Holiday Inn used to say the best surprise is no
surprise. But I think there's nothing better than a good
surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   The hallways in his hotels are a little dark with dramatic neon
lighting. ``It's to prepare the person for the next act,'' he said,
with all seriousness.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels should be theater, high drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should a hotel be just a place to sleep? Why can't it be
fun?'' he asked. ``It was the same thing when I was in the
nightclub business. Why does a bathroom have to be just to relieve
the kidneys? Why can't there be some entertainment to bring a smile
to your face?''
</P>
<P>
   In the ladies' rest room at the Royalton, it's impossible to
find the entrances to the cubicles, which have mirrored doors.
There are no handles and no clues. You have to push the mirrors to
find out where the doors are.
</P>
<P>
   And people do smile, unless they're in a big hurry.
</P>
<P>
   He describes hotels not in terms of rooms and beds but ``the
whole package, the whole vibration, the whole visceral
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   As he expands his company, and he plans to buy five hotels each
year, will it be difficult to sustain the excitement? ``It really
doesn't worry me because it's the strength of the idea,'' he said
simply.
</P>
<P>
   Schrager knows ideas. Back in the '70s, he and college friend
Steve Rubell had an infamous one _ Studio 54, the hottest disco
ever, where a typical night would see Rubell schmoozing Mick
Jagger, Elizabeth Taylor, Liza Minnelli and Halston.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, as a new generation catches disco fever with the
movie ``54'' and new books on the nightclub, Schrager feels no
nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have bittersweet memories about it,'' he said. ``This
tremendous amount of attention focused on that right now I find
very amusing. I didn't participate or cooperate with anybody having
anything to do with it because it doesn't bring anything good to me
and my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The disco days of the 1970s are in the distant past.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was like high school. I'm onto something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Hotels were the logical next step from nightclubs, he said,
because at both you're taking care of guests and keeping them
entertained. The transition turned out to be easy.
</P>
<P>
   No one is more amazed by his hotel success than he is. ``What
makes me so insecure is that I never lose the marvel that other
people also like it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody has to admire, or even understand it, only
those with an appreciation for high style, or at least those who
like to watch celebrities. Schrager doesn't care about the
convention crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because what we're doing is not institutional, 500 million
people don't have to like it. It allows me to try things that
haven't been done before.''
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics who said his hip hotels would have the shelf life of
his infamous nightclub (three years) are now asking him to create
hotels for them. He is talking to Starwood Hotels, owner of
Sheraton and other brands, about creating a line of special hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Many of his competitors are still trying to figure out how he
stays on top of the trends, a skill that an MBA can't give.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not intellectual, it's purely instinctive,'' he said,
without hesitation. ``What Steve and I did in nightclubs, that was
the kind of nightclub I wanted to go to. It was just a very
personal thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Schrager does stay in other people's hotels
occasionally, and he especially likes the Ritz in Paris and
Claridges in London, those are not the kind of places that capture
his imagination. He's not interested in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want something that is modern and of the future, not
something retro, not something my parents would have liked. It's
not something I reject because they would have liked it, but, hey,
I'm my own person. It's my discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Schrager is certain that other creative people work the same
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that Donna Karan and Calvin Klein and all the other
fashion designers design clothes that they like, that they
themselves would like to wear or would like to see on their
partners.''
</P>
<P>
   Ian Schrager did not set out to be a hotelier. He was a Jewish
kid from Brooklyn who played stickball in the streets and
eventually went to law school.
</P>
<P>
   The trip from Brooklyn to a sleek Manhattan office with the
white sofas and the white orchids on the coffee table, was a ride
in the fast lane, and it wasn't smooth.
</P>
<P>
   The bumps along the way included the closing of Studio 54 in
1979, a 13-month stay in a federal prison with Rubell for tax
evasion in 1980, and bankruptcy court in the early 1990s when his
prize assets, the Paramount and Royalton, were over-leveraged.
</P>
<P>
   The worst was going to jail. ``Steve said jail will humble
anybody,'' he recalled. ``The first day going in and having that
door slam on you _ that I still remember, the clanging of that
door.''
</P>
<P>
   And he missed more than a year of his life.
</P>
<P>
   But Schrager said he remembered something his father had taught
him: ``There's never any harm in falling down. What the harm is is
not dusting yourself off and picking yourself up and starting
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Schrager bought a modest hotel with Rubell after their prison
release and turned it into the sleek Morgans, an immediate
celebrity hangout.
</P>
<P>
   Rubell died in 1989 from hepatitis, and he didn't get to see the
Paramount.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss my friend,'' Schrager said a year after it opened.
``It's not quite as much fun without Steve. We were like Spanky and
Our Gang. If he were here, he would be the one on the front line,
and I would be saying, `Steve, do the people like it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Schrager was the one on the front line, and he restructured
the Paramount and Royalton and proceeded to build an empire of 16
haute hotels in New York, California, Miami and soon-to-open hotels
in Paris and London.
</P>
<P>
   And the celebrities flock to them like they did to Studio 54.
The Delano Hotel is home to Madonna's restaurant, The Blue Door.
Gloria Estefan shot an album cover in the 150-foot-long swimming
pool.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Schrager, 52, married Rita Narona, a
Cuban-American from Miami and former dancer with the New York City
Ballet, and has two daughters ages 4 and 8 months. The hotel
magnate is now changing diapers.
</P>
<P>
   So why is he still so driven when he has such extraordinary
financial and personal success?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the fear of failure that pushes you. It's not the
race for the brass ring. If you're swimming, you have no choice but
to swim to the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   He has three goals for his hotel empire: to do five
one-of-a-kind hotels a year; to take one of his existing hotels,
such as the Royalton, and roll out a line of them (``They would all
be defined by the setting and the place, but still have the same
spirit''); and to create a ``boutique'' brand for a large hotel
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't do the Delano in every city in the country, but I
could do something that's more sophisticated, that has some
originality, that's out there on the edge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He's also planning a merchandising business, primarily the
furniture, sheets and other items associated with Schrager Hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Will there be an Ian Schrager cologne?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not within my circle of competence,'' he said,
grinning. ``I won't go there. But sheets _ I probably know more
about sheets than anybody. Why not sell them?''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Blackerby writes for The Palm Beach Post.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
