<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7172 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STUDIO54-REVIEW29-COX     08-28 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDIO54-REVIEW29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plot of '54,' where are you?
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're after a metaphor for the dizzy, druggy, discoing 1970s
_ and is anyone really on that search? _ surely, New York's
infamous Studio 54 will do. The frenetic inner sanctum of the
Beautiful People and would-be celebrities was so lacking in
significance that it virtually defines the decade.
</P>
<P>
   The film industry's current fascination with the '70s (``Boogie
Nights,'' ``The Last Days of Disco'') gains another belt notch in
``54,'' which takes us behind those legendary, well-guarded doors
to find out what we missed. If it makes you feel any better, the
answer is ``Not much.''
</P>
<P>
   Give first-time feature director Mark Christopher (and
production designer Kevin Thompson) credit for visually evoking the
bacchanalian excess of former steakhouse magnate Steve Rubell's
playhouse. If it really was as depicted, Studio 54 was the ultimate
toga party, an Egyptian spectacle, a Felliniesque frolic and a
major consumer of confetti and glitter dust. Summing up the scene
is a suspended crescent man-in-the-moon, with a gilded spoon of
cocaine swinging towards his nose.
</P>
<P>
   Say what you will about disco music, but the movie's soundtrack
also captures the era well. If only Christopher's screenplay
weren't so painfully wooden and hokey, he might have something
here.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Boogie Nights,'' it takes the viewpoint of a wide-eyed
innocent. He's Shane O'Shea, a 19-year-old, curly-haired New Jersey
hunk, staring across the river at Manhattan's skyline and yearning
to party at Studio 54. Picked out of the clamoring horde of
hopefuls on the sidewalk outside the club, Shane's looks gain him
entry to the pharmaceutical fantasyland, then gets him hired as a
beefcake busboy. Having caught the heavy-lidded eye of Rubell, he
soon rises to the coveted level of bartender.
</P>
<P>
   Shane's pals are club lackey Greg and his coat-checking wife
Anita (Salma Hayek), who yearns to be the next disco queen. Greg
eventually gets sticky fingers around the cash he hauls out to
bagmen, and Anita gets her shot at fame but is upstaged by an
overdose victim on the dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   After popping pills like dinner mints and playing sex toy to
such customers as a Bianca Jagger-ish Sela Ward, Shane connects
briefly with soap opera actress Julie Black (Neve Campbell). In one
of the movie's sillier scenes, these two Jersey transplants pause
from the glitter of Studio 54 and go on a bowling date like
comic-book teens Archie and Veronica.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher's script is remarkably free of irony or attitude
about the club scene. It does, however, take a dim view of Rubell,
seen almost exclusively through his drug habits, male employee
pawing and creative accounting methods. Yet ``Saturday Night Live''
alum Mike Myers knits these into a surprisingly effective and
affecting performance, even if he does look more and more like Jon
Lovitz as the movie progresses.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Phillippe has the vacant good looks and sweet naivete
required to play Shane. Director Christopher turns us into
celebrity voyeurs by salting the movie with cameo appearances from
the likes of Michael York and Lauren Hutton. The end credits
indicate whole scenes of other cameos that didn't make the final
cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``54'' does capture the sights and sounds of the '70s, at least
one specific, grimy corner of it. What it lacks is a story worth
caring about.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
