<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7173 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN29-COX     08-28 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    I'm older than all the pro ballplayers
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I celebrated a birthday recently. Send no
presents, please. It's no big deal, though I am now older than
Elvis was when he died. Further, I do not believe there are any
active major-league baseball players older than me.
</P>
<P>
   The closest in age I could find in a cursory Internet search was
Paul Molitor with the Twins, who's 364 days younger than me.
</P>
<P>
   Same with football. Warren Moon, former Oilers quarterback now
with Seattle, is nearly 42, which means I have a 15-month head
start on him. I could find no other NFL players even in their 40s.
</P>
<P>
   Feel free to correct me. It would make me feel better. Since I
turned 30, my personal definition of officially entering middle age
would be when I was older than anybody playing major league
baseball or professional football.
</P>
<P>
   That time apparently has come, unless some sports trivia
know-it-all dredges up a third-string utility infielder resting on
the bench somewhere whose birthday precedes mine. I'm hopeful but
not terribly so.
</P>
<P>
   My birthday and the few days around it seem to be common dates.
A reporter here has the same birthday. A few years ago, I was
exactly twice as old as she _ an unpleasant realization on my part.
My daughter's birthday is the day after mine. My late grandfather's
birthday was yesterday. Apparently there were some very busy people
around Thanksgiving, including me, I suppose.
</P>
<P>
   I dislike not being an age that's divisible by five. I can't
remember how old I am when asked. When I was 30, 35, or 40, I
always knew my age. In between is tougher. I have to subtract the
year of my birth from the current year. I get in trouble when I
forget what the current year is. I'm told this is a common problem,
but I believe I am just being humored.
</P>
<P>
   I remember exactly where I was 20 years ago today, though. I was
in The Daily Sentinel building in downtown Nacogdoches. It was a
Thursday afternoon, and I had finished processing film when I got
the call. It's time, my then-wife, a few weeks overdue, said. We
headed to the hospital. I was excited. My first child would be born
on my birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Kasey did not cooperate. Some 20 hours later, 11 hours too
late for my birthday, she arrived in Nacogdoches. For two decades
now, Kasey and I have celebrated our birthdays together. She's
grown now, in her third year of college. I spent my birthday eve
moving her into an apartment after two years in the dorm. She is
slowly learning about the real world. I'm paying the rent, of
course, and the college tuition, but she's paying utilities and car
insurance. There is light at the end of the parental tunnel. But
not much, with a trio of children to follow.
</P>
<P>
   My second daughter timed it better. She arrived dead in the
middle of the day on my father's birthday. Now she's 17 and
entering her last year of high school. In nine months, she too will
be at the University of Texas. How did all this happen so quickly?
</P>
<P>
   There are still children in the house, by marriage and not
blood, but mine full-time nonetheless. Most of the time they make
me feel younger, when I'm carrying the 9-year-old piggyback around
the yard, praying my back doesn't go out, or discussing the musical
merits of Jimi Hendrix and Janis Joplin with the 14-year-old punk
rocker.
</P>
<P>
   I don't feel middle-aged, though I'm told by all four children
that I look it. I'm blessed with an iron constitution to match my
skull. The few aches and pains are minor nuisances. I've had an
interesting life to this point, sometimes too interesting, what
with marriages, job changes, and such, but it's all worked out
somehow. As that great American Joe Walsh sang, ``Life's been good
to me so far.''
</P>
<P>
   I come from a long line of long-lived folks on both sides of the
family tree, so I plan on being around awhile, though I'm finally
old enough to understand I'm not invincible. And as humorist Bob
Murphey says: In the great scheme of things, if you want to know
how much you'll be missed once you're gone, stick your hand in a
bucket of water, then pull it out _ and see how much difference
you've made in the bucket. Now that's keeping it all in
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Someone once told me that what really matters is who you loved
and who loved you. So I feel blessed to this point.
</P>
<P>
   I just wish I could find a 43-year-old major league ballplayer
on some team's roster.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Daily Sentinel in
Nacogdoches, Texas. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
