</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEEKEND FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release on the weekend of Saturday,
August 29, 1998, are moving today to clients of the New York Times
News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   BLIND _ Lori Hardy gave birth to her first child hoping, like
any other mother, for just a normal, healthy baby. She had no
reason to expect complications. But when Tyler Hardy was born three
years ago, doctors told her matter of factly that he had no eyes.
The Hardys were changed by the realization that their child would
not have a normal life, and that theirs would never be completely
normal again either. Through the Center for the Visually Impaired,
the couple, who live in Canton, are learning that blindness and
visual impairment are challenges to be met squarely, not shrunk
from. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 56. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   SCRAPBOOKS -- Family photo albums take on a new look when
creative people put their mind to it. (Ricardo, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   FOUND-METEORITES _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``I don't want you to
think I'm a nut,'' the man said. Then he told me about the
grapefruit-size meteorite that left a crater in the back yard of
his Acreage home. ``I went out to feed the ducks when I saw it,''
Rick Daddea said. (Cerabino, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   STUDIO54-OWNER _ NEW YORK _ The boyish grin and the chiseled
good looks from the days when he was co-owner of Studio 54 are
still there. Ian Schrager goes from 0 to 60 in 4 seconds in
describing his plans for a new ``boutique'' line of hotels. And
about the old days at Studio 54. (Blackerby, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   STUDIO54-MEMORIES _ Old-timers reminisce. (Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   STUDIO54-REVIEW _ Film review. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-DYER _ Review of ``Out of Sheer Rage: Wrestling with D.H.
Lawrence,'' By Geoff Dyer, North Point; 241 pages; $22. (Eyman,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOME&AMP;GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   GARDENMUSEUM _ LONDON _ It's a gardener's treasure chest _ a
17th-century watering can, shovels more than 100 years old, an
1800s wheelbarrow, even a Victorian cucumber straightener _ and the
goods aren't even outdoors. They're in church. Avid gardeners would
agree that's the perfect sanctuary for worshipping 300 years of
tools that have made their work easier. But the 17th-century church
east of London's embankment is an even more appropriate home for
the Museum of Garden History _ the only collection of its kind in
the world _ because of its own legacy. Its churchyard contains the
tomb of two famed plantsmen, a bit of history that prompted
Rosemary Nicholson and her late husband, John, to open the museum
in the first place. ``People thought we were absolutely mad,'' she
says of their struggle 20 years ago to convert the dilapidated
church and graveyard into an exhibition space and repository for
rare plants. ``They would ask, 'Garden history? What's that? What
do we need to know about it?' `` Apparently lots, as Americans'
passion for gardening reaches levels rivaling that of the British.
``Look at how many people are doing it. It's become such a pasttime
with everyone,'' Nicholson says. (Flanders, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   RELIGON-LABYRINTH _ DECATUR, Ga. There is a sense of suspension
in time and space as soft sock feet fall in rhythm on canvas. With
soothing music playing in the background, worshipers at Holy
Trinity Episcopal Church in Decatur are walking the labyrinth. One
evening and one Sunday each month, a carpeted room in the church
becomes a pilgrimage site. The ancient tradition of the labyrinth
has been revived, giving a pattern to meditation. (GWhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   VOLUNTEER _ B'Nai B'rith, the country's oldest (and world's
largest) service organization, is in the process of collecting
stuffed animals, part of a massive and innovative program to
provide toys for youngsters in area hospitals. (Henry, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   PREACHER-SWAP _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The preacher spoke with
a delightful English accent, but some of the words he used needed
translation. Most of us understand fridge, but calling a sports
utility vehicle a lorry is a stretch. He was preaching in Florida
while his counterpart performed has duties in England. (Gushee,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
