<HEADER>
A7177 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARMON-COLUMN29-COX     08-28 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARMON-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In light of new `facts,' old transgressions are subject to
review
 &HT;    By Gary Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ We've been so turned upside down for so
long that it's going to take us a while to get our bearings in the
brave new world of Clintonian sexual mores.
</P>
<P>
   We're going to need new handbooks on office conduct and
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But before we look forward, we ought to look backward a bit and
see how grievously and unjustly we've treated folks who've done
what all the president's mouthpieces assure us ``Everybody Does.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of them have even been naive enough to speak truthfully
when questioned about their escapades, showing that they don't
understand the first thing about genuine moral leadership.
</P>
<P>
   First on that list of folks we now know were held to an
unreasonable standard and who deserve better now that we know
better has to be our former alcohol-tinged local police chief,
Darold Sloan.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a guy who got taken down either by a vast right-wing
conspiracy or a frequently hinging left elbow, it's hard to tell
which.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, though, if Clinton's OK, then Sloan's OK.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's sex life is his private business. Sloan's drinking
life ought to have been his own business. To suggest that either
couldn't enforce the laws in public while flouting them in private
is narrow-minded and bigoted.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, we have Bill Clinton to help us come to grips with
the peculiar, primitive and destructive notion that presidents and
chiefs of police ought not be above the law.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan was considerate enough to do his drinking in Ridgway, well
outside his own jurisdiction, but hey, Monica Lewinsky has taken
pains to point out that she and the president generally adjourned
for private bouts of Twister to a room off the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't want to spoil the work environment, would we?
</P>
<P>
   Sloan had the misfortune to get caught, then get caught up in a
series of events that undid him. None of that could be foreseen by
a trained police professional. Oh no.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had the misfortune to have selected as sex partner a
thoroughly modern Monica whose notion of discretion was to limit
her chit-chat to a few dozen close friends. No way a seasoned pro
such as himself could have foreseen that. Oh no.
</P>
<P>
   True leaders sometimes have to show the way and Bill Clinton
hasn't failed in that regard. True leaders also have a sense of
timing and we have time yet to evaluate in the cases of Ronald Pond
and Rod Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Pond is a former Grand Junction firefighter who faces
prescription-fraud charges in a case investigated by a Grand
Junction police officer, Rod Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Things looked pretty bad for Pond, what with allegations of drug
use on the job and questions about how he obtained the stuff, until
some things started to come out about the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the small matter that Baker and the
soon-to-be-former Mrs. Pond were involved in a relationship. No
wagging finger of denial here for prosecutors, who wrote that the
relationship ``at some point ... became sexual.''
</P>
<P>
   And a good thing, too. Had it been financial, there might be a
clear conflict, because it is the economy, stupid, but as the
president has made clear, sex doesn't matter. We can rest easy when
it comes to the interrogation techniques of the GJPD.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation cleared both Grand Junction police and Mesa
County District Attorney's Office scrutiny, but some defense
attorney with a misplaced sense of propriety might try to make
something of it before a jury. But The People can point out with
the moral authority of the presidency that ``Everybody Does It.''
</P>
<P>
   Heck, that avenue might even be open to Pond, who could admit
the charges and dismiss them as unimportant because, as everyone
knows, ``Everybody Does It.''
</P>
<P>
   Just change the ``It'' and demand they acquit.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton might have derided Ronald Reagan's ``trickle-down''
economic theory, but he's proven Reagan's case.
</P>
<P>
   The shame is that what's trickled down is enough to make one
throw up.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Harmon writes a column for The Daily Sentinel of Grand
Junction, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
