<HEADER>
A7178 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN29-COX     08-28 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mammoths?
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DINOSAUR VALLEY STATE PARK, Texas _ Texas' 1,523-acre state park
that straddles the Paluxy River is appropriately named Dinosaur
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Dinosaurs spent a lot of time tromping through here. Their
footprints are all over the place.
</P>
<P>
   Now tourists and dinosaur lovers tromp all over the place.
</P>
<P>
   Watching tourists track dinosaur tracks in the riverbed and
along the banks reminded me of the time my nephew and I came across
fresh bear tracks one summer high up in the Rocky Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   We followed the large tracks for about an hour before it dawned
on us that catching up with the bear would be harmful to relatives
who would fall down laughing at our funeral.
</P>
<P>
   It's good that the tromping of dinosaurs and tourists is
separated by 110 million years or so because tourists can sit
inside some of the dinosaur tracks here.
</P>
<P>
   Literature given to visitors entering Dinosaur Valley State Park
near Glen Rose says the first dinosaur tracks were discovered in
1909. But the tracks weren't widely acclaimed until an American
Museum of Natural History official visited the site in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   It's absurd to say the tracks weren't discovered until 1909.
There is archaeological evidence of Indian campsites next to many
of the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Indians who visited this area were surely experts in
animal tracks, it's interesting to speculate what they must have
thought about the huge tracks imbedded in the limestone.
</P>
<P>
   The three-toed carnosaur tracks look like the tracks of a bird
of unimaginable size. These tracks are between 12 to 24 inches long
and 9 to 17 inches wide. The animals that left these tracks had a
stride that ranged between 45 to 65 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Even more amazing to the ancient Indians would be the footprints
of sauropods that left saucer-like depressions ranging over three
feet long and two feet wide. Besides the four stubby toes of the
back feet, these animals also left smaller horseshoe-shaped tracks
where the front feet depressed the mud that turned to rock. These
animals had a stride from seven to 10 feet.
</P>
<P>
   A third category of dinosaur tracks along the Paluxy River
remains somewhat of a mystery. These tracks, like the carnosaur
tracks, are of a two-legged, three-toed animal. The toes, however,
are not nearly as elongated as those of the carnosaur. The current
best guess is that they are the tracks of an ornithopod, perhaps
the iguanodon.
</P>
<P>
   Generations of native tribes also must have read the remarkable
story left by a double set of tracks.
</P>
<P>
   These renowned tracks were left by a giant brontosaurus-like
sauropod followed by the bird-like tracks of a large carnivorous
dinosaur. This is a record of an ancient hunt. That might have
caused sleepless nights for the Indians who later camped nearby.
</P>
<P>
   What were these fearsome animals? Where did they go? Will they
return?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this partially answers why dinosaurs are so compelling
to people today.
</P>
<P>
   Americans aren't nearly as interested in other extinct species.
Woolly mammoths, for instance, were enormous animals that also
disappeared. They had huge tusks that curved upwards. That's
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   But no one cranks out toys, movies and books about woolly
mammoths, saber-toothed tigers or any of thousands of other extinct
species.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of scientists believe they have solved one of
the dinosaur mysteries. They believe dinosaurs did not become
extinct. Today's birds not only are descendants of dinosaurs, they
are dinosaurs, according to an emerging body of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   If so, that answers another dinosaur mystery. What did dinosaurs
taste like? Like chicken, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNethaol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
