<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7179 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FSU-WARREN29-COX     08-28 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FSU-WARREN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Warren hopes to shine at Florida
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Despite spending a few relaxing days in Austin
early this summer visiting friends, David Warren is perfectly happy
to be residing in Tallahassee, Fla. Actually, he's happy to be
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Warren, a defensive end from John Tyler High in Tyler who as the
state's top football recruit two years ago selected Florida State
over the University of Texas, saw his summer vacation take a
bizarre and potentially tragic twist on Aug. 5. Awakening from a
customary afternoon nap in his dorm room, he was stricken by a
seizure that rendered him unconscious and threw the Seminoles into
extreme panic mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``That thing scared us all to death,'' said Jim Gladden, who
coaches Florida State's defensive ends. ``Nobody had a clue what it
was all about.``
</P>
<P>
   The only one not panicking was Warren. For good reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out. I don't remember anything about it,'' he said. ``So
it was kind of hard to be scared.``
</P>
<P>
   After a battery of hospital tests revealed nothing abnormal,
doctors cleared Warren to practice. So it's opposing teams Warren
hopes to scare in his sophomore season, beginning Monday when the
second-ranked Seminoles play No. 14 Texas A&AMP;M in the Kickoff
Classic at East Rutherford, N.J. Warren seems none the worse for
his scare _ in Florida State's first scrimmage he logged three
sacks, made a tackle behind the line, forced a fumble and broke up
a pass in 43 plays against the first-team offense.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-4-inch, 250-pound Warren is penciled in as a backup
at left end to fellow sophomore Roland Seymour, but in the Florida
State rotation scheme Gladden estimated he'll get at least 40
percent of the plays. Last year, Warren saw spot duty in 10 games
behind All-American Andre Wadsworth, who went on to become the
third overall pick of the NFL draft by the Arizona Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Seminoles' reputation for producing ends like
Wadsworth and Peter Boulware, whom the Baltimore Ravens chose with
the fourth overall pick in 1997 after coming out following his
junior year, that lured Warren toFlorida State. Warren, the USA
Today high school defensive player of the year as a senior at John
Tyler, was leaning toward signing with the Longhorns until he took
his last recruiting visit, to Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe I made a bad decision at all,'' said Warren.
``Everyone said this is best school for defensive ends to attend,
and I feel that way, too. I believe it's the scheme and style. I
don't know why, exactly, but it seems like the defensive ends here
are always wide open for the sacks.``
</P>
<P>
   Gladden, a 24-year coaching veteran at Florida State who is the
senior member of Bobby Bowden's staff, recruited Warren, luring him
away from Texas despite Warren's kinship to Longhorns legend Earl
Campbell, a cousin. Gladden said the Seminoles expected Warren to
sign with Texas until Boulware announced he was leaving Florida
State early.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Pete announced he was going, his (Warren's) tune
changed,'' said Gladden, who compared Warren to a young Boulware.
``I think he's got a chance to be a lot like him. He's got the same
kind of speed, but he's going to be bigger. David needed to work on
his upper-body strength and he's done that. He's got a 'swole' _
he's 'swolled' up.``
</P>
<P>
   Warren, who also took a recruiting trip to A&AMP;M, says he hasn't
been disowned by his home state for having the traitorous audacity
to leave its borders for school, not that that makes him
particularly unique. In fact, he spent several days in Austin early
in the summer visiting with former Longhorns Joey Ellis and Patrick
Hayes, who also attended John Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do much except just visit and go rafting in San
Marcos, but it was a lot of fun,'' Warren reported. ``They were
telling me that if I'd signed with Texas, I could be enjoying
myself like that every day. I just laughed.``
</P>
<P>
   Warren returned to Tallahassee later to attend the second
session of summer school and prepare for the season. Besides his
seizure episode _ ``Just a freak thing, nothing major'' _ he has
been slowed by back spasms. The spasms have bothered him off and on
but hit him hard midway through the traditional 1 1/2-mile run the
Seminoles run on the first day of practice.
</P>
<P>
   Gladden noted that, ``The biggest thing he struggles with right
now is he washes out. The intense humidity and heat cause him to
run out of gas and get drained. But he'll get better at that.``
</P>
<P>
   Despite the painful back spasms, Warren didn't drop out of the 1
1/2-mile run, even though he slowed to a walk and took 17 minutes
to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get maddest at not pushing myself when I get tired. I don't
want to quit,'' he said. ``It could have been easy to quit that
day, but I never saw Wadsworth quit at doing anything. I just told
myself that it wasn't going to kill me to push myself.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
