<SLUG> BC-GRAZIANO-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Think things are bad now, Marlins fans?
 &HT;    By Dan Graziano
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ If you thought the trading away of the World Series
roster was tough to watch, wait until you see what may be coming
next.
</P>
<P>
   Marlins General Manager Dave Dombrowski, whose contract expires
at the end of October, interviewed this week for the GM job with
the Los Angeles Dodgers. There's a pretty good chance they'll offer
him the job and a pretty good chance he'll take it.
</P>
<P>
   And that, baseball fans, would truly mean the end.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, kids cried when Moises Alou and Charles Johnson were
traded. And no, you don't see people walking around at games with
``DOMBROWSKI'' stitched across the back of their Marlins jerseys.
But there's no more important person in the organization, and
letting Dombrowski go would be worse than any of the player trades
he was forced to make.
</P>
<P>
   It would signal no hope of recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Given the choice, the Marlins' first and only GM would like to
stay. Dombrowski has presided over the growing pains of the early
years, the elation of the World Series, and the pain of the payroll
purge. He has a wife and a newborn daughter, makes about $700,000
per year and is one of the most respected men in his profession.
And Wayne Huizenga (who, it appears, will still own the team next
year), Don Smiley (whose attempt to buy the team is fading badly)
and John Henry (to whom Huizenga would sell the team if his motives
for doing so were as pure as he originally stated) all have said
they'd want Dombrowski to stay.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers are prepared to offer him $1 million per year.
Hmm ... let's see ... Work for a tradition-rich franchise and an
aggressive new owner who can promise unlimited financial backing
year in and year out? Or stay behind in Florida and wonder what the
future of your team is?
</P>
<P>
   Huizenga may be willing to hang onto the team, but he's showing
no interest in making sure he has a team to hang onto. Dombrowski
isn't the only one without a 1999 contract. Assistant GM Frank
Wren, VP of Player Personnel Gary Hughes (who, incidentally, will
interview for that Dodgers' GM job on Tuesday), VP of Player
Development John Boles _ all are without contracts. The only
baseball operations personnel with 1999 contracts are manager Jim
Leyland (who's probably leaving anyway) and Dominican Operations
Director Jesus Alou.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, people this qualified can all find other jobs. And if
Dombrowski leaves, someone such as Wren or Boles or Hughes could be
in line to take over as Marlins GM. That's not the real worry.
</P>
<P>
   The worry is, how decimated does this team become? Plans already
call for the trading of arbitration-eligible shortstop Edgar
Renteria and left fielder Cliff Floyd after this season. This team
could turn into Montreal South, where the players play until they
improve enough to make big salaries and then are traded to teams
that can afford to pay them.
</P>
<P>
   No matter who buys the team, a stadium would be four or five
years away. So it wouldn't make any sense to start building back up
for about two more years. But even some light, some hope, would be
enough for the core and the braintrust to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``How wonderful would it be,'' one prominent member of the
organization said last week, ``after all this, to build it back up
again? And win again? That would be one of the greatest
achievements ever. And with what we have here, we could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But time is running out. If there's no new owner and no new plan
within the next couple of weeks, Dombrowski could be out the door
to Hollywood and take everyone with him. And then what is South
Florida left with?
</P>
<P>
   A team that's not worth watching, most likely.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, a team that's not worth buying.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
