<SLUG> BC-HOUSING-ANNEXATION29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Housing project residents sue over non-annexation
 &HT;    By Jennifer Peltz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Residents of a Belle Glade housing project have asked a
federal court to right what they see as nearly 40 years of
injustice.
</P>
<P>
   They say the city has discriminated against them and violated
their voting rights by refusing to annex the project.
</P>
<P>
   The case is an echo of America's legal and political past,
scholars say. While courts saw similar cases at the height of the
civil rights movement, they are ``incredibly rare these days,''
University of Florida law professor Fletcher Baldwin said.
</P>
<P>
   The residents' chance of winning hinges on showing a long
history of racial inequality _ the history a lower court refused to
consider last year, saying it simply happened too long ago. That
court ruled for the city, saying there was no present-day proof of
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one of the appeals judges wondered this week about
the importance of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is not all this prior history'' worth considering? Judge
Stanley Marcus asked. ``Isn't all this stuff relevant?''
</P>
<P>
   From 1973 until as recently as 1995, Belle Glade officials
turned down requests to annex the historically black Okeechobee
Center housing complex. They did annex the companion white complex,
Osceola Center, in 1961. The city-appointed Belle Glade Housing
Authority owns and runs both.
</P>
<P>
   Official policy segregated the complexes until 1977. Their
racial makeups remain different: 92 percent of Okeechobee Center
residents are black, compared to 46 percent of Osceola Center
residents, according to the most recent figures available.
</P>
<P>
   To the residents who sued, there's only one explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did something for the white tenants: They gave them
citizenship, the right to vote, various benefits of being in a
city,'' residents' lawyer Neil Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   As city residents, Osceola Center tenants can vote for the city
commissioners who appoint the housing authority board. And they pay
50 percent less than outsiders, including Okeechobee Center
residents, for city water service, court documents say.
</P>
<P>
   ``When asked to do the same for the black tenants, they said
no,'' Bradley said. ``They could not conceivably have had a
non-racial motive for saying no.''
</P>
<P>
   But city officials offer a different rationale.
</P>
<P>
   The Osceola manager clamored for city police protection while
the Okeechobee manager didn't, they say in court papers. The city
can't afford to take in another big public housing project, since
it won't pay taxes. And the Okeechobee Center was too far away to
meet state requirements for annexation, though the requirements
came after residents started asking.
</P>
<P>
   The city also notes that a study committee, which included an
Okeechobee Center resident and other black people, recommended
against annexing the complexation in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court decision isn't expected for at least a month.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
