A7183 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UT-DORMS-COOP29-COX     08-28 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UT-DORMS-COOP29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    University may close co-ops
 &HT;    By Angela Shah
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ University of Texas administrators could decide
in two weeks whether to shut down the university's Women's
Cooperative _ eliminating a campus fixture since the Great
Depression _ to make room for next year's freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   James Vick, UT vice president for student affairs, said that
administrators are reviewing the future of 12 buildings that house
about 220 students on the northwest side of campus near Kinsolving
dormitory. The students, most of whom are women, have leases with
UT that expire in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``The university is in the midst of a lot of change in housing.
We feel it's very important to have about 75 percent of freshmen in
dorms,'' Vick said. ``The co-ops have the smallest percentage, at
about 25 percent. We're trying to decide whether to have co-ops.''
</P>
<P>
   UT's housing view is shared by other large, public universities
like rival Texas A&AMP;M. Students who begin academic careers living on
campus thrive because of the proximity to student services and the
extended family dorm life provides, Vick said.
</P>
<P>
   UT is seeking a greater voice in the day-to-day management of
the usually semi-autonomous co-ops. The co-ops have traditionally
maintained a 21-member council of residents that decides who may
live in co-op housing and how each house spends its money.
</P>
<P>
   Co-op residents buy and cook their own food, divide chores among
residents and maintain a budget for their ``household.'' Until
recently, the co-ops residents were all female.
</P>
<P>
   But a recent threat of a lawsuit by two male UT students seeking
access to the co-ops spurred UT administrators to order co-op
leaders to admit men and take a closer look at operations of the
co-ops. Sixteen spaces in one co-op have been set aside for male
residents. Only 11 of those spaces are filled, said Jay Neiverth,
office manager for the co-ops.
</P>
<P>
   If administrators decide to shut down the co-ops, Neiverth said
UT will be eliminating a vital source of affordable housing for
many students. Created in the 1930s to provide economical housing
for women students, the co-ops today continue to be good bargains.
Students pay about $3,000 each year _ about $1,000 less than in any
other campus dormitory _ to live in a co-op, he said. As landlord,
UT collects rent and provides security and overall maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are allowed to stay here, we could make it 75 percent
freshmen,'' Neiverth said. ``If that's what it takes to remain on
campus, that's what we'll do.''
</P>
<P>
   Vick said administrators are considering requiring that 75
percent of co-op spaces go to freshmen. ``It certainly has been
mentioned,'' he said. ``But there is some question how effective
the co-ops would be. The co-op leadership has usually come from
more advanced students.''
</P>
<P>
   UT administrators and co-op officials also are deciding what to
do about $700,000 that UT Women's Cooperative, an unincorporated
nonprofit, has in an investment portfolio. The money was left over
from residents who lived in co-ops before1989 and whose expenses
were lower than their housing fees. In 1989, the co-ops began
giving refunds to residents if their housing fees were not used by
the end of the year. Vick said administrators want to make sure
they are not left with a tax liability if the money is turned over
to the UT Women's Cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Neiverth said the co-op council is trying to incorporate as a
nonprofit, which is tax exempt.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Shah writes for the Austin American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
