<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WACHOVIA-SOFLA29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wachovia moves in to South Florida, touting more products
 &HT;    By Danielle Herubin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Signs and computer equipment at more
than 30 former offices of 1st United Bancorp are being replaced
this week as Wachovia Bank makes its official entry into South
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Wachovia, based in Winston-Salem, N.C., bought Boca Raton-based
1st United late last year for about $222 million.
</P>
<P>
   1st United had offices in Palm Beach, Martin, Broward and
Brevard counties.
</P>
<P>
   Warren S. Orlando, former head of 1st United and now chief
executive of Wachovia's Florida Banking, said customers won't
notice much change because the personalities of the two banks are
similar.
</P>
<P>
   But they will have access to more products, Orlando said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Wachovia (NYSE: WB, $79.25) will provide free
financial planning, from saving for a child's college education to
investing in stocks for retirement, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wachovia also offers Internet banking. Customers can log on at
any time, move money between accounts and make investments.
</P>
<P>
   Wachovia Chief Executive L.M. Baker Jr., who was in Palm Beach
County Thursday to meet with former 1st United employees, said he
expects 200,000 of Wachovia's customers, or 5 percent, to use
Internet banking by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Customers already using it are having a much easier time than
anyone predicted, Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   ''You tell me your grandmother won't do it,'' he said. ``Well,
you better check with your grandmother.''
</P>
<P>
   Wachovia, which offers business and consumer banking, has more
than 750 offices in the Southeast, including 39 in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   It has $48.5 billion in assets and 21,800 employees, including
470 in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Wachovia will begin an advertising campaign in September,
Orlando said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
