<HEADLINE>
MATT DAMON ZOOMS FROM FROM ZERO TO SEXY 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
feature.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly column with color art.) 
 World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 Color slides and black and white photos of Matt Damon with Gretchen
Mol in a scene from ``Rounders'' and with Robin Williams in a scene
from ``Good Will Hunting.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Not long ago Matt Damon was down and out in Hollywood.
 &HT;    The boyish actor was counting pennies, living on beans and
wondering if he'd ever get work for bit parts in TV sitcoms.
 &HT;    What a difference a couple of years make.
 &HT;    Today at 28 Damon is the hottest actor in Hollywood. He's been
on the cover of just about every major magazine since he and his
writing partner Ben Affleck sold their ``Good Will Hunting'' script
to Hollywood for half a million dollars and as a bonus took home
the Oscar for screenwriting. Now Damon finds himself working
virtually around the clock.
 &HT;    Currently he's appearing in the title role in Steven Spielberg's
blockbuster ``Saving Private Ryan.'' On Sept. 11 he shows up in a
leading role in ``Rounders,'' a film about professional poker
players, costarring Edward Norton, Martin Laundau, John Turturo and
John Malkovich. Damon plays a cardsharp who uses his winnings to
put himself through law school.
 &HT;    He's about to spend five months in Italy shooting ``The Talented
Mr. Ripley'' opposite Jude Law, with ``English Patient'' director
Anthony Minghella. Billy Bob Thornton will direct him in ``All The
Pretty Horses'' early next year.
 &HT;    Damon was hired for ``Saving Private Ryan'' while on the set of
``Good Will Hunting,'' when Robin Williams introduced him to
Spielberg. Damon compared working on ``Ryan'' to ``having a
scholarship into the best film school in the world.''
 &HT;    On the personal front he ended his high-profile romance with his
``Good Will'' costar Minnie Driver shortly after going on TV to
announce his love for her. Since the Oscars he has been dating
Winona Ryder so persistently that USA Today ran a story that said,
``Winona and Matt are not engaged.''
 &HT;    Sitting in a swank hotel in Marina Del Rey, Calif., he smiles at
the story: ``Well, I don't want to talk about it. There was a time
when I was very open about my personal life but I've made mistakes
before. This engagement stuff is kind of silly.''
 &HT;    Apart from the occasional wince, however, he handles his
newfound status with aplomb and tries to keep a sense of
proportion.
 &HT;    ``It's gotten a little crazy,'' he sighs. ``But I think it's all
due to the power of the media. Look, in the mid-'80s there were
stories that said Michael Jackson and Bruce Springsteen were the
biggest stars in the world. Michael couldn't leave the house
without 25 bodyguards and Springsteen you could bump into in a
local bar. I think it's all what you make of it. I'm not gonna do
the whole bodyguard nonsense _ or anything like that. I'm trying to
keep things in perspective.''
 &HT;    Family and friends in hometown Boston help keep his feet on the
ground. ``I'm really lucky that it didn't happen until now,'' he
says. ``I have a whole bunch of people I grew up with who aren't
that impressed but are happy for us.''
 &HT;    One of them is Ben Affleck, his longtime writing and acting pal
who is now dating Gwyneth Paltrow. ``I haven't seen him in a while,
'' says Damon, ``but I like to kid him about Gwyneth _ I'd
telephone and say, 'Hey, your girlfriend is doing real good. How
are those love scenes going?'''
 &HT;    He says Affleck plans to join him in Italy to finish a script.
``It might be a story about a halfway house in Boston,'' says
Damon. ``We've done 150 pages ... but only five of them were
usable. We're dying to get to work. ``Good Will Hunting'' is a hard
act to follow.'
 &HT;    Also they both have concerns about overusing their friendship
and the cute story of their collaboration. ``We're getting to the
point,'' Damon explains, ``where we don't want to feel we pimped
out our friendship _ especially with the flood of stories about how
we grew up together. And sometimes you can't help feeling that
you're whoring out your personal life for professional gain.''
 &HT;    If he seems overly cautious about, ``the success thing'', it's
because he sees the danger signs everywhere he goes. ``People laugh
at your jokes too hard now and you know the joke wasn't that funny.
But then maybe after a while you think it is. ''
 &HT;    Still he wants to make it clear he's not one of those stars who
no sooner get a whiff of success than they start whining about a
loss of privacy. ``I went from needing money and really needing a
job to being able to sit back and pick select jobs really
carefully. It's an incredible feeling. Things have turned into an
embarrassment of riches _ it's every dream I've ever dared dream
come true.
 &HT;    ``And it's tough to have a bad day when you're in the dairy
section of the supermarket and people keep coming up and saying,
'Good job.''''
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;     c.1998 Ivor Davis  (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based
