<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, Aug. 28, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Saturday and Sunday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-BAN (Sacramento) _ California Gov. Pete Wilson has vowed to
veto a bill approved by the state Assembly that would be the
toughest assault weapons ban in the country. Wilson says it goes
too far and invites lawsuits. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   BILINGUAL-EDUCATION (Oakland) _ Supporters of bilingual
education win a victory when a judge ordered the state Board of
Education to consider allowing school districts to keep bilingual
programs despite voter approval of anti-bilingual Proposition 227.
By ROBERT SELNA.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-SCAM (San Francisco) _ A Sacramento AIDS activist says he
mailed 4,000 bogus letters billing Northern Californians $76 each
as an attention-getting device to persuade California Gov. Pete
Wilson to declare a state of medical emergency for AIDS. By ERIC
BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-PARK (Albany, N.Y.) _ A confederacy of Indian tribes is
divided over a proposed state park along the Hudson River, with one
representative of the group calling it insensitive and offensive,
while members of a Wisconsin-based tribe that helped develop the
plan say they support it. By JAMES M. ODATO.
</P>
<P>
   SHARK-BITE (San Francisco) _ When razor-sharp teeth attached to
a 2,000-pound eating machine known as a great white shark rip
through your skin, it's a good idea to fight back. And, hopefully,
you'll have a friend handy to help you out. A 16-year-old San
Rafael boy learned that lesson firsthand this week and is on the
road to recovery. By RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-JUDGE (Sacramento) _ Gov. Pete Wilson is considering a
parting gift to termed-out state Sen. Quentin L. Kopp of San
Francisco _ a judgeship on the Sonoma County Superior Court. But
Wilson has asked the Democratic-controlled legislature to fund 40
new judgeships throughout the state, and Democrats are wary of
giving him any new appointments. By ROBERT SALLADAY and RACHEL
GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CRISIS (San Francisco) _ The real culprit for the latest
market troubles is Japan. Although most analysts blamed Thursday's
global market slide on the Russian economy, the downturn can be
traced to the 3 percent decline in Tokyo's Nikkei average the day
before. Japan's inability to resolve its own crisis is keeping
global markets from recovering. By LARRY AMERNICK.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-INVESTORS (San Francisco) _ The Russian currency crisis
has sent global markets spinning, but the average American investor
shouldn't fret. A Q&AMP;A. By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Yes, Apple Computer's iMAC is the
coolest-looking computer around. And, yes, it's both functional and
aesthetically pleasing. And, yes, at $1,299, it's relatively cheap.
So, what's wrong with it? Well, hardly anything. In fact, it's a
hit. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A reader wants to know about the
various software packages designed to ``automatically'' update the
software and drivers on a PC. A Q&AMP;A. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Undated) _ Real-time video interviewing, with
its promise a few years ago of allowing companies to interview
prospective employees thousands of miles away, never really caught
on in the workplace. But there are areas where it's taking off,
such as schools and government agencies. By L.M. SIXEL. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RADIO-LEYKIS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Tom Leykis has no clue what he is
doing. It's minutes before he goes on the air, where Leykis will
impart his usual mix of core beliefs and insights and whatever else
he can think of to a coast-to-coast radio audience. This is
national, baby, high-tech, high-minded entertainment. And Leykis is
a professional. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-FOOLS-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love,'' the
story of three women who show up in a New York courtroom claiming
to be the widows of 1950s star Frankie Lymon, is a fun movie with a
good beat. By JEFF MILLAR (Already filed) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-54 (Undated) _ Even a dim bulb can have a few bright
flashes, and ``54'' has two of them. One is Mike Meyers' spooky,
tragicomic turn as Studio 54 owner-guru Steve Rubell. The other is
Ryan Phillippe's pants. That's where the fun begins and ends in
this dull movie. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-SLUMS (San Francisco) _ ``Slums of Beverly Hills''
is a nice coming-of-age comedy helped by a cast of old pros. By
BARBARA SHULGASSER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING (Undated) _ A Los Angeles company offers to compose
music and lyrics to fit any occasion or person, and deliver that
song permanently preserved on a compact disc. By STEVE BARNES.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-WOMEN'S-HOCKEY (Lake Placid, N.Y.) _ The ever-growing
diversity of the talent pool in the U.S. women's ice hockey circle
shows how the sport is growing in popularity. Seventy-two young
women gathered this week at Lake Placid's Olympic Center to share
their abilities _ and prepare for the next Olympic event. By TIM
REYNOLDS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Going to Russia is just the
ticket to improve Bill Clinton's morale. The best healing process
for low self-esteem is to look good in comparison with someone
else. Why not go see Boris Yeltsin next week, do the twist with
some Kremlin interns, and enjoy the company of a world leader who
has more trouble than you do? By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-WELFARE (San Francisco) _ OK, let's talk about moral
responsibility as the growing chorus of bipartisan voices is making
it clear that President Clinton has lost the moral authority to
lead. The upcoming two-year anniversary of welfare reform should
make this fact crystal clear. That's right, welfare reform. By STAR
PARKER.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONFESS (San Francisco) _ In Protestant, puritan and
prudish America, President William J. Clinton is slowly becoming a
Catholic. He seems to be developing a deeper sense of sin, the
fallen state of humankind, and the need to confess. By ALBERTO
HUERTA.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GAYS (San Francisco) _ As an American watching President
Clinton pretend to apologize to the nation for having an
inappropriate relationship with former intern Monica Lewinsky, I
felt embarrassed, sad and angry. But as a gay American, I felt
despair. To the extent that the scandal will hamper Clinton's
effectiveness, I felt I was losing a quiet warrior for the rights
of my community. By DAVE FORD.
</P>
</TEXT>
