<HEADLINE>
CREATE A SONG FOR THAT SPECIAL OCCASION 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Foners, Web sites CQ)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE BARNES  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUST FOR YOU: Song For You, a Los Angeles company, offers to
compose music and lyrics to fit any occasion or person, and deliver
that song permanently preserved on a compact disc. You provide the
information _ name, event, likes or dislikes, habits or hobbies _
and Song For You writes words, adapts music, records its singers
performing the tune and prints the recipient's name on a CD. The
company has joshed a birthday boy about his fondness for McDonald's
food, for example, and found rhymes for an anniversary tune about a
man who enjoys hunting. Although Song For You has operated for a
decade in Israel, the Netherlands and Britain, where it claims a
half-million sales, the company's U.S. operations are but a few
months old. The service costs $59 per song. For information or to
order, call 800-789-SONG (7664).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMBO CARRIER: Those folks at Levenger, a catalog of ``tools for
serious readers,'' have found a device that's halfway between a
wallet and a moneyclip. Face it: billfolds can get bulky, causing
pocket bulges and lopsided sitting, and moneyclips are
ostentatious, sending the message that you carry so many bills that
they threaten to burst from your trousers unless you keep them
firmly fastened. Levenger's idea pairs a moneyclip on one side (it
can manage up to 30 bills) with a slot on the other that holds one
to five cards _ credit, debit, charge, work ID and driver's
license, let's say. The solid brass Smart Money Clip, available in
matte-black or 24k-gold-plated finishes, costs $25. To order one or
request a catalog, full of fountain pens, desk accessories, comfy
chairs and whatnots, call 800-544-0880 or visit the catalog's site
on the World Wide Web, http://www.levenger.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PIANO LESSONS BY PHONE: By dialing 541-664-6751 will get you a
three-minute mini piano lesson for only the price of a
long-distance telephone call. A recent recording succintly
explained and demonstrated a chord technique called ``straddling''
_ leaving out the middle note of a chord _ and how it can be used
to embellish a standard arrangement of a song. Coincidentally,
``How To Dress Up Naked Music'' is one of the several hundred
courses available from Keyboard Workshop, the Oregon business that
operates the piano-lesson hot line. Another is ``How To Make Cool
Sounds on Any Keyboard _ Without Knowing a Thing About Music.''
Courses typically include sheet music, a cassette tape and a video,
and range from $40 to $200. For a free catalog, call the above
number and leave your name and address after the lessons ends,
visit the company's Web site, http://www.playpiano.com, or write
P.O. Box 700, Medford, OR 97501.
</P>
</TEXT>
