<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WOMEN'S-HOCKEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FESTIVAL SHOWS GROWING POPULARITY OF WOMEN'S HOCKEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Connecticut, Minnesota)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM REYNOLDS  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. _ In stature, there is no comparison between
A.J. Mleczko and Natalie Darwitz.
</P>
<P>
   Mleczko, a Harvard senior, is 23, is 5-feet-11-inches tall,
shoots from the left, has played on three national teams and is the
owner of an Olympic gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   Darwitz is an eighth-grader at Eagan Junior/Senior High School
in Eagan, Minn. She is 14, and is nine inches and 40 pounds shy of
matching Mleczko's frame. She shoots from the right side and has
never before been at a full-fledged national team camp of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few days, however, they have been teammates at the
USA Hockey Women's Festival at the Olympic Center in Lake Placid.
Mleczko is the oldest player of the 72 invitees at the camp;
Darwitz is the youngest.
</P>
<P>
   The differences between the two players illustrate the
ever-growing diversity of the talent pool in the U.S. women's ice
hockey circle, with Mleczko representing the corps of current
stalwarts that skated to Olympic gold last February in Nagano,
Japan, and Darwitz one of the heir apparents who will be asked to
carry the program to even loftier heights in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can look at anybody here and say that they can
play in the next Olympics. I really do,'' Mleczko said. ``The fact
that they're here means they have the potential and capacity to
improve and get there. Whether they do or not, it depends on the
coaching they get and the desire and drive they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though it's been barely six months since the Americans beat
Canada for the first-ever Olympic women's hockey gold, the
celebration is pretty much complete for U.S. women's coach Ben
Smith. Instead of trying to stay within the basking glow of the
gold, Smith already is focusing on this December's Three Nations
Cup in Finland, the world championships March, also in Finland, and
all the while steering toward the 2002 Olympic Winter Games in Salt
Lake City, which is the primary destination of this camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Phase 1 of the process,'' Smith said while watching
one of the four 18-player groups practice Tuesday morning. ``The
thing that catches my eye is that we've got a group here where no
one seems like they're out of place. Now, it's just a question of
what kind of growth physically they have. They've got a three-year
tunnel and we'll see who comes out of that tunnel ready to help the
next program.''
</P>
<P>
   The talent pool is more populous now than ever, mainly because
of the emergence of young women players. USA Hockey, the national
governing body, had only 153 registered girls teams nationwide nine
years ago, and less than 500 five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there are well more than 1,000 registered teams, and more
than 27,000 girls players, compared to 5,533 in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   What that means is from the smallest grassroots level to the
national team, there are more, and better, players to choose from,
and the bar is being raised considerably each year, it seems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked at these USA camps since they started in 1991,''
said Laura Halldorson, the women's hockey coach at the University
of Minnesota. ``It really has been incredible, not only the
increase in talent but the increase in depth. Any of these young
teams could beat probably any of the national teams from back
then.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a bunch of players here that could be there in 2002,''
said goaltender Sara DeCosta, one of four players at the festival
who played for Team USA in Nagano, along with Angela Ruggerio,
Jenny Schmidgall and Mleczko. ``We're climbing the mountain at a
fast pace now. There's so many girls getting involved at such a
young age. Four years ago, there wasn't any way to have a camp with
72 players like this. No way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 72 players, all of whom are still college-eligible, were
chosen by a group of various coaches Smith contacted. Once the
invitees arrived in Lake Placid, they were broken down into four
teams of fairly equal ability, each consisting of two goaltenders,
six defensemen and 10 forwards. The age makeup of each team is
nearly exactly the same, as the four teams all have players ranging
from 18.8 to 19.5 years old on average.
</P>
<P>
   The format for the week-long player identification/development
event is a round-robin tournament, concluding with bronze- and
gold-medal matches on Saturday. Coaches from some of the top men's
and women's college programs are running the teams, while Smith
sits high atop the Olympic Center ice, watching and evaluating each
player.
</P>
<P>
   Yale men's hockey coach Tim Taylor coached one of the four
teams, and raved about the players all sharing one common bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have one agenda and one agenda only, and that's to be
better players,'' Taylor said. ``They are terrific to work with.''
</P>
<P>
   The first-timers appear to make the most of their opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's a good player and it makes you play off of everyone
else,'' said Julie Chu, a 16-year-old sophomore at Choate Rosemary
Hall in Connecticut. ``You just have to play the moment. If you
don't play the moment, you're never going to get ahead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
