<HEADLINE>
`54' WHERE ARE YOU? LATEST DISCO FILM SKIPS FUN, INSIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even a dim bulb can have a few bright flashes, and ``54'' has
two of them. One is Mike Meyers' spooky, tragicomic turn as Studio
54 owner-guru Steve Rubell. The other is Ryan Phillippe's pants.
</P>
<P>
   Let us explain. Phillippe plays a kid from Jersey who Talks Like
Dis but gets a job at the famed Manhattan discotheque by virtue of
his resemblance to Renaissance artworks (``You have the body of
David and the face of a Botticelli,'' purrs one admirer). After
spending nine-tenths of the action in satin jogging shorts, he
appears near the film's close in a pair of denim jeans ringed, at
bottom, by extraordinary furry white pant cuffs. The cuffs are
ravishing _ they seem to borrow DNA from Kris Kringle and a large
angora and they give the movie a welcome dose of unadorned
seventies nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   It's a moment of pure pop charm in a film that boasts, by and
large, all the thrill of polyester.
</P>
<P>
   Weird, isn't it? You'd think, wouldn't you, that the iconic '70s
nightclub, replete with glamour and glitter and sundry sordid
goings-on, would be a rich subject for a film. At the very least it
ought to be entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   The genius of Paul Thomas Anderson's ``Boogie Nights'' wasn't
just the intensity of the drama or the giddiness of its late-1970s
soundtrack it was the width of the bell-bottoms, the dorkiness of
the haircuts and the repulsive puce of Mark Wahlberg's velvet suit.
</P>
<P>
   Disco-era films are fashionable right now (``The Ice Storm,''
``The Last Days of Disco,'' the upcoming ``Slums of Beverly
Hills''), and for good reason: The Me Decade was plump with
pop-cultural tidbits.
</P>
<P>
   While ``54'' dances to a thudding disco soundtrack, it misses
the point of all that gyrating; there's little humor, no irony, no
gaze at the era through a shiny cinematic snow-dome. And there's no
fun.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Mark Christopher makes several fatal errors with
his feature-film debut. One is his shift of emphasis away from
Rubell, a drug-addicted, Svengali-like figure with dreams of an
endless party. Meyers is terrific; he's a control freak desperate
for love, a man consumed by his own insatiable needs. When he's on
screen, the film's worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Christopher focuses the film on Phillippe's character, an
adorable but bloodless innocent named Shane O'Shea. It's an old
trick, sending a fresh young thing into a den of iniquity, but here
it backfires. As he bumps and grinds among the nude, the near-nude,
the painted, the famous (Truman! Andy!) and the guys dressed like
Roman gladiators, the viewer yearns to spend more time with them
and less with the dull boy preening on the dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   Furry-cuffed jeans or no furry-cuffed jeans, Shane is just way
too dull for Studio 54.
</P>
<P>
   His friends aren't much better. Salma Hayek throws off sparks as
a fiery singer and 54 employee, and Breckin Meyer brings surprising
moral weight to his performance as her virtuous husband but the
other supporting players gasp in airless roles. Michael York and
Lauren Hutton appear in pointless wee parts as high-class snobs.
Neve Campbell, as a soap star and disco habitue, is flat as a
cracker. Sherry Stringfield, nearly unrecognizable behind a Farrah
Fawcett flip, has a minuscule role as the night club's accountant.
And Ellen Albertini Dow, last seen as the rapping granny in ``The
Wedding Singer,'' is reduced to snorting coke in ``54.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the film suffers from Shane's dullsville voice-over
(``bartending was the best job in the world''), which opens the
film, closes it and pops up periodically like a large zit. If
nothing else, may ``54'' mark an end to droning narrators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
