<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-PARK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIVE AMERICANS DIVIDED OVER STATE PARK PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES M. ODATO  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A confederacy of Native American tribes is
divided over a proposed state park along the Hudson River, with one
representative of the group calling it insensitive and offensive,
while members of a Wisconsin-based tribe that helped develop the
plan say they support it.
</P>
<P>
   John Sam Sapiel, acting director of the Muhheconnew National
Confederacy Bureau of Political Affairs, said Thursday the proposal
for the new 1,358-acre Schodack Island State Park needs agreement
from eight tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Sapiel disclosed letters of opposition he and other tribal
leaders sent to New York Gov. George Pataki this summer. Chiefs of
at least two of the eight tribes of the confederacy wrote similar
letters to Pataki, one as recently as last week.
</P>
<P>
   However, disagreement among the tribes is evident.
</P>
<P>
   A key band of Indians who descended from the Mohicans who lived
on Schodack Island during Colonial times supports the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tribe has not ever adopted a resolution in opposition to
the development of that island,'' said Gary Ehman, a spokesman for
the Stockbridge-Munsee Band of Mohican Tribe, in Bowler, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   The Stockbridge band, which is one of the eight tribes of the
Muhheconnew confederacy, has been involved in developing the master
plan. The other tribes appear to have been left out.
</P>
<P>
   The master plan, dated Aug. 5, responds to a number of the
concerns Sapiel raised in his June 25 letter to Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Sapiel complained that the state plans a parking
lot, toilets and camp sites in the center of the island capital of
an Indian confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   The master plan says the facilities will be developed on areas
that were once underwater or areas with ``limited cultural
sensitivity.'' However, Sapiel, who says he has not read the master
plan, still insists that the project not go ahead as scheduled, as
he opposes any development on or near the capital of the Mohican
tribe.
</P>
<P>
   He said the eight tribes have a stake in the island because it
once was the seat of the confederacy's council fire, a gathering of
the various bands.
</P>
<P>
   Sapiel also notes that the confederacy helped repel French and
English attempts at colonization until illness cut the population
at the turn of the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 13, Pataki announced completion of the master plan. He
said it would create ``a spectacular new state park.''
</P>
<P>
   The park, with seven miles of shoreline, is the site where Henry
Hudson moored the Half Moon in 1609 and went ashore to visit an
Indian chief, according to state records.
</P>
<P>
   Schodack Island, technically a peninsula, is scheduled to become
accessible to the general public with the creation of a bridge over
railroad tracks bordering the river near Schodack Landing.
</P>
<P>
   The park is to have a camping loop with toilets, canoe and kayak
access onto Schodack Creek and a Native American interpretive area,
the state says.
</P>
<P>
   New York Parks Commissioner Bernadette Castro responded
incredulously to Sapiel's point of view because of the substantial
work she said her office conducted to make sure the island's
development respected the wishes of Mohicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We carefully selected land which was felt to be not
significant,'' Castro said.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the office's archaeologist, Robert Kuhn, said he had
reviewed Sapiel's letter and said each point was addressed in the
final master plan. ``I'm not sure we agree with them,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are proceeding with the project,'' he said. ``We do feel
the project's worthwhile and has tremendous public benefit and
we've taken into consideration issues raised by Native Americans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
