<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7347 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RADIO-LEYKIS-HNS &LR;      08-28 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-LEYKIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN WITH NO PLAN FILLS THE NATION'S AIRWAVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Tom Leykis has no clue what he is doing.
</P>
<P>
   It's minutes before he goes on the air, where Leykis will impart
his usual mix of core beliefs and insights and whatever else he can
think of to a coast-to-coast radio audience. This is national,
baby, high-tech, high-minded entertainment. The man is a
professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep in mind that at this moment I have no idea what I'm going
to talk about,'' Leykis says while walking casually toward the
studio of Albany station WGY-AM, from where the Los Angeles-based
host did his show one recent night.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow he knows he'll make it work. It usually does.
</P>
<P>
   Literally seconds before air time Leykis _ in a baseball cap,
shorts, patterned shirt and shades _ hits upon a topic for the
first hour of his four-hour show: a man suing his ex-fiance for not
returning a $31,940 engagement ring. So it will go for the second
hour, and the third and fourth. Need a topic in five seconds ...
hmmm, let's try this.
</P>
<P>
   He said his prep work comes from living and a life in radio,
providing him all the background he needs. He is pragmatic rather
than dogmatic, making him tough to pigeonhole but easy to enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, his nighttime live talk show begins with the song
``Enter Sandman'' by the heavy metal band Metallica, and the
42-year-old does bring a rock edge to his daily rants/observations.
But the show itself is more like jazz, free-form and unpredictable.
The audience doesn't know where it is going to go because Leykis
doesn't know where it is going to go. He calls it keeping it fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tom Leykis Show'' is a misnomer. A show _ his goes out to
about 175 radio stations over Westwood One Radio network _ usually
has a script, some order, a rough sketch of a plan. But those are
rules, and Leykis hates rules. He takes the show where the
conversation takes him. For four hours a big microphone eavesdrops
on his conversations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a slice of me,'' Leykis explained before going on the
air. ``It is the part of me people find the most interesting.
Fortunately for me, very few people are themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   So who is Tom Leykis? He is smart. And infantile. And insightful
and uncouth. A small ``l'' liberal who leans toward the libertarian
side, he can be in his depth talking about national policy issues.
It's just that sex is so much more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   On air, off air, it's the same person. There is no character
named Tom Leykis, just the person. Listeners, mostly young, like
him because he takes on topics as varying as relationships and
baseball and politics and, or course, sex, without any academic
artifice. He is the guy next you at a bar who happens to have a
radio show _ and an opinion on everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always saying exactly what I think,'' Leykis said. And it
can be mean. He has gone after fellow talk-show host Dr. Laura
Schlessinger with a vengeance. And arguing with Leykis is a bad
idea; a skilled debater at home on the air, he will probably carve
you up.
</P>
<P>
   Leykis also knows when to shut up, a rare talent in radio. He
hooks up Lisa and Bob, two callers from California, and let them
argue on whether live-in girlfriends should give their partner an
ultimatum to get married. Leykis _ who for the past seven years has
been on wife No. 4 _ stands back and occasionally giggles as the
callers take over the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like that when they forget they are on the radio,'' he
says off-air.
</P>
<P>
   Leykis has made many stops in his 19-year career, and one of the
most important may have been at the old WQBK-AM in Albany for a
couple of years back in the early 1980s. It was here where Leykis
began formulating the idea for a radio show. He was told to be
himself. He liked the idea. He went national in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Leykis has no plans to be an old man working at a local station
when his fame wanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there is no demand for what I'm doing, I will leave with
dignity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a plan. Which doesn't sound like Leykis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
