<SLUG> BC-SUNDANCE-REDFORD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASSES VS. THE KID: `SUNDANCE' SQUARE-OFF ENDS AMICABLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LAURA VOZZELLA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A showdown between the Sundance Kid and the
Bass gang has ended in a bloodless draw.
</P>
<P>
   Since last year, Robert Redford and Fort Worth's Bass family
have been wrangling over use of the name ``Sundance'' for movie
theaters. The end came this week, when the Kid agreed to ride off
into the sunset.
</P>
<P>
   Redford, who portrayed the Wild West outlaw in the 1969 film
``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid,'' uses the name on his
Utah-based Sundance Enterprises, Sundance Film Festival and
Sundance Institute. With plans to add a chain of art-house cinemas
to the Sundance stable, Redford learned last year that the Basses
had already plastered the name on movie houses in Fort Worth's
Sundance Square.
</P>
<P>
   The Kid was up in arms. His posse of lawyers fired off letters
telling AMC's Sundance 11 and Sundance Palace 9 theaters to drop
the Sundance name.
</P>
<P>
   The Basses dragged the shootout into U.S. District Court in Fort
Worth in December. They asked a judge to declare them rightful
owners of the name.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides claimed first dibs.
</P>
<P>
   Redford, linked to the name by movie fans for nearly three
decades, started his Sundance Institute in 1980 after buying up
thousands of acres in Park City, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   But Fort Worth had the real Sundance Kid, Harry Longabaugh, who
whooped it up in Cowtown brothels and saloons with a gang of
outlaws called the Wild Bunch in the 1880s. The Basses claimed they
had used the terms Sundance Square and Sundance continuously in
Texas at least since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow _ neither side would explain Thursday _ the parties came
to an agreement, finalized Wednesday by U.S. District Judge John
McBryde.
</P>
<P>
   The Basses retain the right to use the name Sundance on movie
theaters in Tarrant and 10 surrounding Texas counties, along with
Love and Carter counties in Oklahoma. Redford's Sundance
Enterprises may use the name on movie theaters anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really what we wanted,'' said Wesley Harris, an
attorney for the Basses' Sundance Square. ``And I guess they
decided it would work for them, too.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 1313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
