<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7410 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRATERNITY-CASE-BOS &LR;      08-28 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRATERNITY-CASE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER BU STUDENT SUES OVER 1995 ASSAULT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ZACHARY R. DOWDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was Rush Week in October of 1995 when Jessica
Smithers, a Boston University freshman, and her friends set out to
a party at BU's fraternity mecca near West Campus.
</P>
<P>
   At 17, Smithers was intrigued by the bottomless kegs of beer,
loud music, and dirty dancing in dark, steamy rooms.
</P>
<P>
   She also was drawn to a burly senior who beckoned her to an
after-hours bash at a Gardner Street fraternity and dutifully
freshened her spiked punch drink.
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, he later turned violent, raping her in a frat
house as she, intoxicated , weakly put up a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Smithers has begun the process of suing BU for $3 million,
hoping to hold the college responsible for the actions of its
students and unruly fraternities. At issue _ for BU and,
potentially, other universities _ is whether a college can
advertise the benefits of Greek life and also legally distance
itself from wanton frat behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Smithers's lawyer, Timothy Corcoran, wrote President Jon
Westling letter in November, claiming BU failed to warn and protect
her _ by policing parties, for example, from fraternity life's
seamy underside: binge drinking and sexual assaults.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want the asset without the liability,'' Corcoran said.
</P>
<P>
   While BU officials do not contest Smithers's account of her
alleged rape, they claim they are not liable because the rape
occurred off campus and because the fraternity was not even
recognized by BU.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert A. Ross, BU's dean of students, said BU does not own or
lease fraternity houses and is not responsible for lax security in
buildings housing students off campus, such as the one where
Smithers allegedly was raped.
</P>
<P>
   Corcoran, however, compared the case to that of a party host or
a tavern owner being held liable for tragedies if they are linked
to alcohol consumed on the host's premises. And he said BU's
responsibility doesn't end at its geographical boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``BU has an affirmative duty to look out for the safety and
security of its students and to protect them from all forseeable
risks,'' said Stephen Hennessy, another Smithers attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, the BU dean, said that the university swiftly investigated
and suspended the student who was accused of rape after he was
found responsible in campus court.
</P>
<P>
   He said that had the rape taken place in a BU building, the
school might bear financial responsibility, as in the case of a
Pine Manor College student who was raped in December of 1977 by an
intruder who slipped through campus security.
</P>
<P>
   But Smithers' attorneys said, also, that BU knew the assailant
had a history of sexual assault from a prior incident when he
allegedly restrained an intoxicated woman and told BU police she
lived at the building to prevent her from leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, however, insisted that ``We had no prior knowledge of a
sexual assault attempt by the student.''
</P>
<P>
   He said students learn the dangers of alcohol and sexual assault
at orientation, and via reading materials, workshops, and Rape
Awareness Week programs in the first weeks of school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tragedy that this happened,'' Ross added. ``But the
majority of our fraternities are not problematic.''
</P>
<P>
   Smithers's alleged ordeal is not uncommon on campus. The
Chronicle of Higher Education reported in May that between 1995 and
1996 reported rapes on 487 campuses with 5,000 or more students
jumped 14.8 percent, from 1,013 to 1,161.
</P>
<P>
   But Smithers, a 20-year-old environmental studies major and
honor student at George Washington University, is not a typical
victim if only because she is speaking out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had a clear understanding of sexual assault until it
happened to me,'' said Smithers, who transfered to GW after her
allegedly traumatic experience at BU. ``I had no idea how
life-changing it is. If I can prevent one woman from having to go
through it I'd feel so much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Smithers said the assailant met her and her friends when they
stopped by Sigma Phi Epsilon's Linden Street house at about 11 p.m.
on Oct. 7, 1995 to ask for directions to a party being held by
another fraternity. The assailant invited them to an after-hours
party later on.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, Smithers and her group stopped by the after-hours
bash. She said the alleged assailant kept her by his side, leaving
her only for more punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taken in by the scene,'' she said. ``I felt impressed
and good. I didn't think anything bad was going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   By 3 a.m., Smithers got sick, and the group hailed taxis on
Commonwealth Avenue. In the confusion, Smithers was left behind
with the student, who had scribbled his phone number on a bank
statement. That paper was used at the campus court when he claimed
he never met Smithers.
</P>
<P>
   Smithers said he urged her to go back to Sigma Phi Epsilon. She
had no taxi money to get to her room in Kenmore Square, and the T
had stopped running, as did BU's escort service.
</P>
<P>
   She said she went back to the fraternity and locked herself in
the bathroom. But he barged in and told her to sleep on his futon.
She fell asleep but remembers half-waking and performing oral sex.
Dazed, she tried to fight but her body felt weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt really incapacitated,'' she said. ``It was almost like
seeing what was happening to me but not being able to do anything
about it. I couldn't stop it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
