<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANGER FOR US AS WORLD ECONOMIC CRISIS WORSENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Maine they tell the story of four hunters who every deer
season hire the same float plane to fly them into the north country
camp where everyone always gets their buck.
</P>
<P>
   Last season was no different: four hunters, four deer. But when
the pilot returned, he shook his head: I can't ferry you all out in
one trip, with those heavy deer carcasses too. They complained, he
resisted; they cajoled, he wavered; they threatened, he caved.
</P>
<P>
   Load 'em all up, he shrugged, we'll give it a go. They taxied
across the lake, he gunned it, up they went, weaving and wobbling.
After five minutes of flight, down they came. After the smoke
cleared, and they crawled from the wreckage, one hunter asked:
``Where are we?'' The pilot, still groggy, took his bearings, and
proclaimed: ``Looks like we're only about 100 yards from where we
all crashed last year.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a story about not making the same mistake over and over
again. Which is a tendency of all mankind. And what brings it to
mind is the sound of the ruble collapsing as Russia's currency,
banking, and political systems crash.
</P>
<P>
   Pile Russia's paralysis atop Japan's nosedive, the wider Asian
``depression,'' as financial writers have begun to label it, and
the persistent inability of the bulk of African countries to grow
their economies, and the ``globalization'' that fired US economic
growth turns into a two-way trip.
</P>
<P>
   That escalator that Americans rode up is suddenly thrown into
reverse. It goes down as well as up. And down is not good for Mr.
Dow, Mr. Jones, or Mr. and Mrs. North America. The intricate
network of arteries and veins that carried US goods abroad and
brought foreign goods here was like the human body's circulatory
system. Our economy grew strong and healthy and developed a vast
appetite for more.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, people in Thailand stopped buying pickup trucks.
Indonesia's corrupt political system cracked and fell apart.
Japan's banking structure turned out to be rotten with
uncollectible loans. The equally rotten Japanese political system
is still unable to put meaningful reforms in place.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese economy's eight percent growth rate target is
receding amid floods and anticipated layoffs of ``tens of
millions'' of workers from inefficient government-owned
enterprises, National Public Radio warned yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   All the kinds of stuff we sold to the Pacific rim piles up on US
docks or sits in cartons in US warehouses. Our
96-percent-of-capacity employment picture is punctured by layoffs
in industry after industry. Deflation stares us in the face _
factories can't sell stuff for the price they used to get, so
manufacturers have to cut prices or eat what they produce.
</P>
<P>
   You can't sell what people won't buy. And consumers in Japan,
Asia, and now Russia, are not buying as they used to. Globalization
can take our economy down as well as up. It appears today that the
broad economic expansion that began in the early '90s is not going
to last the decade.
</P>
<P>
   This changes a lot of things for everybody. Millions of
Americans will be in danger of being laid off, fired, forced into
early retirement, downsized, or otherwise diminished in their
earning capacity. The vast middle class who have stuffed payroll
deductions into mutual funds and 401(k) plans will have to swallow
investment losses after the fat years of double-digit increases.
</P>
<P>
   The anticipated economic slowdown has yet to impact the
political system here. The US throttle is still wide open. Housing
starts, hiring plans, and discretionary income show Americans are
still spending. But that could slow dramatically by November. Our
off-year elections could be held in an atmosphere of chaotic
foreign economic news, sharply declining consumer confidence, and
the disappearance of the comfort zone that has bathed incumbent
politicians of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   What happens to Clinton when the public gets antsy, then ornery?
What happens to Newt Gingrich's 11-seat majority in the US House?
What about the media weather, the context in which election choices
will be framed? We can only guess. The next 10 weeks can serve up a
lot of lousy economic news. Will voters react? Some will. Enough to
change results? Who knows?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the media musings about Monica, her dress, her
twitterings to Kenneth Starr, and the let's-impeach-Clinton mob
will perforce diminish. Recession is not a pleasant topic for
anyone, but if Clinton has shown anything in six years, he's proven
he can convince the majority of folks he is on their side on
economic issues.
</P>
<P>
   I still think it will take a sharp economic downturn before the
US House returns to Democratic control. Not this time, I'm
thinking. Voters have been too fat for too long to turn on a dime.
Clinton's hairsplitting on just what constitutes ``sexual relations
with that woman, Ms. Lewinsky,'' will not help.
</P>
<P>
   But then you can usually count on enough Republicans to go
berserk, by shutting down the government, or demanding Clinton's
impeachment, to turn people off. The GOP's Krazy Konservatives
remind me of that bush pilot who keeps overloading the float plane:
``Hey, maybe this time it'll work.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist who for the life of him can't
recall where he first heard that bush pilot yarn.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
