<SLUG> BC-FBC-TV-JACKSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON HAS HAD BEST SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC's Keith Jackson has set the standard for college football
announcers over the last three decades, his voice unable to hide
his Southern roots. He still calls linemen ``Big Ugly,'' fast
receivers ``burners,'' and passes ``hummers.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Whoa Nellie'' is his trademark, an expression he uses to
convey excitement, a sudden turn in the action, or a spectacular
play. Jackson doesn't remember when he started using those words.
He does, however, recall being told by one of his mentors not to be
afraid to turn a phrase ``if it was explanatory, had some flavor
and color, and helped people understand and enjoy the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson plans to retire after this season, but not before he
calls the Rose Bowl _ his favorite postseason game _ on Jan. 1 and
the Fiesta Bowl Jan. 4, where the top-ranked team will play No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has been outspoken about what he views as the
commercialization of college football, and he concedes television
has played a major role.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started it,'' he said. ``Newspapers didn't bring that money
to the table, television did. And that has always been my problem.
I'm not a journalist. It's a simple thing. When ABC spends half a
billion dollars on something, I'm not going to rip and tear it
apart. We got ourselves in this particular fix.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson still has a passion for the game, the pageantry, the
marching bands and tailgating, and in some cases entire states
rooting and cheering, lives linked with their team's fortunes on
the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not my stage,'' he said. ``The stage belongs to the
athletes and coaches who play the game. People don't throw down
1,000 bucks for a TV to hear me talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson boasts he has seen some of the greatest games in college
football history. He rattled off a couple: the 1967 USC-UCLA games
when O.J. Simpson had two great touchdown runs and UCLA quarterback
Gary Beban went on to earn the Heisman Trophy; the 1979 Sugar Bowl
game between Penn State and Alabama when most believed the Crimson
Tide's goal-line stand in the fourth quarter was the deciding
factor. It wasn't, however, because on the next series Alabama was
forced to punt and its punter shanked a 27-yarder. But Penn State
had 12 men on the field and the punter got another kick, this time
booming it for 53 yards _ Whoa Nellie _ preventing the Nittany
Lions from getting close to the end zone again.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, 71, is a storyteller, able to bring viewers back in
time. He called his first college game at Washington State in 1958
for the college radio station and has collected stories ever since.
He is a Southern boy at heart, born near the Georgia-Alabama line.
He left home when he was 16 and lied about his age to join the
Marines for four years in 1946. He then enrolled at Washington
State.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson originally wanted to become a police officer but the
broadcasting bug hit him hard. He has had a ball, and still
believes in the purity of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think we've got a grand old game,'' he told the New
Orleans Times-Picayune last year. ``I don't think we've got to bury
it for the sake of a dollar. Oh yes, the dollar. The old buck is
what's pulling the wagon everywhere. But I'm sure they will work
that out.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has met all of the greats along the way. Joe Paterno.
Bear Bryant. Johnny Rodgers.
</P>
<P>
   One of his favorite stories involves Frank Howard, the former
athletic director at Clemson. Jackson was working the Clemson game
against Duke in 1966, and Clemson's campus is near a lake where
students wanted to start a crew team.
</P>
<P>
   Now Jackson knew a little about crew, having made the first live
radio broadcast (1958) of a sporting event (crew) from the Soviet
Union to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   So Jackson was talking with Howard and asked why he didn't want
to start a crew team at Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ain't nobody going to spend my money sitting on their ass
going backwards.''
</P>
<P>
   (AT)8football collegiate television
</P>
</TEXT>
