<HEADLINE>
A SUMMER OF DISCONTENT IN JOURNALISM. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A specter is haunting American journalism. The specter of
fairness.
</P>
<P>
   The standard-bearer for the new Miss Prissyfingers school of
reporting is Steven Brill's Content, the new journalism ``review''
that has already succeeded in its primary mission: getting itself
written about by other journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Let me tell you about two interesting items I read in the
September issue before I threw it across the room. There's a funny
parody of the entire Brill endeavor by Calvin Trillin, and, much as
it pains me to admit it, egomaniacal windbag James Cramer's article
on the death of the Wall Street Journal's ``Heard on the Street''
column was excellent. I'm sure Brillyfingers would want me to
disclose that the magazine also has an unflattering (if incoherent)
article on the recent travails at the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   I just couldn't stand the cover story on Bill Gates. Reason A:
Content has dug up a December 1977 New Mexico police mug shot of
Bill G. under arrest. The magazine convinced me that Gates has not
told the truth about the incident, and mentions that the arrest
file ``is nowhere to be found'' in Albuquerque Police Department
records. Huh?
</P>
<P>
   But for some reason Content insists that Gates was hauled in on
``a probably minor but still unknown charge.'' Huh? Yes, Gates has
copped to some speeding tickets, and was arrested in 1989 on
suspicion of DWI. But how do we know that the New Mexico arrest
wasn't, say, a drug-related misdemeanor, or a weapons charge? We
don't. Yet Content undermines its own writer's excellent reporting
with speculation that Gates was taken in on a ``probably minor
charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Reason B: Content writer Elizabeth Stevens carefully describes
Microsoft's notorious ``Astroturf'' plan to use regional public
relations firms to generate ``objective,'' third-party media
coverage favorable to M/s. She quotes an anonymous P.R. executive
(Anonymous source! Big no-no in Prissyville!) involved in the
scheme to the effect that M/s's P.R. firm, Edelman Worldwide, would
pay the local companies so they could truthfully say they weren't
working for Microsoft. Fine. But then we have to read this
duplicitous statement from Microsoft's in-house flack, Mich
Mathews: ``It's plainly inaccurate to suggest any firm retained by
Microsoft would not identify itself as working for Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   My point? Read carefully, Mathews' statement is a Clintonian
masterpiece of non-denial. (``He was never alone in a hotel with
Paula Jones.'') So why quote her? Answer: to be fair.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
FOOTNOTE TO HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is one aspect of the now-tiresome ``Wag the
Dog''-is-really-about-Bill-Clinton scenario that has not been fully
appreciated. ``Wag the Dog'' is based on a superb novel by Larry
Beinhart called ``American Hero.'' Beinhart's book is a
``non-fiction'' novel. His phony war is the Persian Gulf War, and
the men behind the curtain are George Bush and his aide James
Baker.
</P>
<P>
   So how did ``Dog's'' anti-Bush pedigree become a by-the-numbers
blueprint for Clinton-bashing? (In the movie, the president
provokes a war with Albania to distract attention from a sexual
dalliance with a Girl Scout.) The plot sprang whole, it seems, from
the fertile mind of Newton's Own David Mamet.
</P>
<P>
   Following a furious fur fight with the Screen Writers Guild,
Mamet received only second credit for ``Wag,'' after Hilary Henkin,
who adapted the Beinhart novel for the screen. But given that Mamet
never read Beinhart's book nor Henkin's script, it seems that
column hacks and editorial jockeys across the country have the
mercurial playwright to thank for the endless stream of
life-imitates-fiction bleatings of recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SHOVED ASIDE
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One casualty of this week's Boston Herald redesign seems to be
the jumpy Herald newsboy, who used to be seen sprinting across the
top of the tabloid's front page, necktie flopped back over his
shoulder, eagerly hawking our crosstown rival.
</P>
<P>
   The image was a needlepoint contribution from the mother of
Robert Choate, who ran the Herald in the 1940s. The original
newsboy carried the original Herald, a broad sheet (wide-format)
like the Globe. When the Herald became a tabloid, the little runner
started brandishing the smaller paper, and since Monday's redesign,
he's selling the nouveau Herald. That's right. Unlike his
flesh-and-blood counterparts, the Herald newsboy hasn't vanished.
He's now scrunched in above the second-page index, and above the
editorial page, far from prying eyes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
