<HEADER>
A7424 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-28 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL EYE OF THE STORM ISN'T BONNIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hurricane Bonnie shows how fortunate Americans are. No other
nation has the media and meteorological resources to produce a
storm before the storm, raining down infrared, color-enhanced
satellite photographs of Bonnie, graphics of its path, and map
after map of the landfall zone.
</P>
<P>
   No other nation has the army of talking heads to babble in
higher and higher pitches as Bonnie's winds went from 50 to 70 to
115 miles per hour. By the time Bonnie came ashore on Wednesday,
the proclamation by a CNN reporter that ``She's big and bad'' was
an anticlimax. Anyone with any sense had left the most threatened
areas of the North Carolina coast. By landfall, camera shots made
it seem that reporters outnumbered residents.
</P>
<P>
   One way of looking at it, and a totally legitimate one, is that
the media coverage did its job. Lives were surely saved by
evacuations and property damage surely was lessened by people who
battened down the hatches and brought their boats to safe harbor.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a self-absorption about the hype that makes us
forget that it is our wealth that permits us to treat a hurricane
almost as entertainment. Between our satellite tracking, our
well-paved evacuation routes and sturdy housing stock, Americans
have dramatically reduced the chances of dying in hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Gone, probably, are the days of 1900 when an unannounced
hurricane killed between 6,000 and 12,000 people in Galveston,
Texas. Or even 1928 when a hurricane in central Florida killed
1,836 people. It would probably be considered a national disaster
if fatalities reached the 259 of Hurricane Camille in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Americans now have the luxury of thinking about storms more in
terms of material property. Hurricane Andrew killed only 26 people
even thought it was America's most costly hurricane, causing $30
billion of damage in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   That is a luxury still unknown to much of the world's
population. As Americans sat by the Weather Channel, Bangladesh,
with almost no coverage from the American press, is screaming for
international help. Between 20 million and 30 million people, or
between the equivalent of the populations of Texas and California
are homeless and over 400 have died as a result of floods triggered
by monsoons.
</P>
<P>
   In China, at least 3,000 people have been killed, 5 million
houses have been destroyed and at least 223 million people, the
equivalent of 85 percent of the population of the United States,
have been affected by the worst floods in 44 years. The Chinese
government has dispatched 178,000 troops to guard dikes that
protect millions of people from further disaster.
</P>
<P>
   China, it could be argued to some degree, has itself to blame
for some of the flood damage, by allowing heavy deforestation in
pursuit of development and not investing in strong dikes. But
Bangladesh, too poor to afford housing to withstand water and wind,
and unable to afford reliable roads, is always ripe for disaster.
Besides the 400 who have died, more than 100,000 people are
suffering from intestinal illnesses from contaminated water.
</P>
<P>
   Bangladesh has asked for $681.5 million in emergency aid. As
Boston television stations sent their reporters to North Carolina
to stand in the wind _ with Channel 7 calling it a ``striptease''
that slowly revealed its power, Bangladesh's finance minister, Shah
Kibria, was saying halfway around the world, ``The current flood is
an economic disaster for Bangladesh.''
</P>
<P>
   While Boston's army of talking heads zeroed in on preparations
for Bonnie by the relatively relaxed rich on Nantucket _ which is
not likely to be hit with hurricane force winds _ President Jiang
Zemin of China issued an order that state media said was a
``do-or-die order for the troops to safeguard the dikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Bonnie was, of course, serious business. But it seems
almost arrogant that Americans can watch hour after hour of Bonnie
coverage while relief teams in northeastern China are preparing to
dig semi-subterranean shelters for the homeless before the cold
nights of fall. It feels like two planets to see the rich debate
riding out the storm on their yachts while Bangladesh is in
desperate need of baby food and water purification tablets.
</P>
<P>
   As America watches Bonnie rotate on TV maps to the point of
hypnosis, it should consider the far greater suffering in
Bangladesh and China _ countries which we exploit for sneakers and
baseball caps. If we did, we might do ourselves two favors. One is,
we might be reminded of our privilege of national wealth. The other
is we might be more moved to share our weather, housing, and road
technology so hurricanes and monsoons do not cost hundreds of lives
abroad. Bangladesh and China couldn't care less about the Weather
Channel. They need someone to tune in, period.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
