<HEADLINE>
WEST VIRGINIA, SYRACUSE ARE TWO FOR THE SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; When the curtain goes up on Sept. 5, West Virginia and
Syracuse will carry the Big East's tattered banner in the opening
week of the football season. The No. 12 Mountaineers host
top-ranked Ohio State and the No. 14 Orangemen host 10th-ranked
Tennessee in a pair of nationally televised marquee matchups.
</P>
<P>
   By season's end, many expect West Virginia and Syracuse to be
fighting for the conference title and the right to represent the
Big East in the new Bowl Championship Series. The Mountaineers were
picked to win the crown in a media poll, with Syracuse a very close
second in the balloting, 174 points to 172.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get off to a good start last year and we won the
conference championship,'' said Syracuse coach Paul Pasqualoni,
responding to a question about his team's notorious habit of
stumbling out of the blocks. ``We didn't get off to a good start
the year before and we ended well, so to me it's a heck of a lot
more important how you end the season than how you start.''
</P>
<P>
   It is imperative, though, that running back Amos Zereoue of West
Virginia and quarterback Donovan McNabb of Syracuse not stub their
toes at the start, lest their hopes for the Heisman Trophy suffer.
</P>
<P>
   But Zereoue, a 5-foot-10-inch, 200-pound junior who was third in
the nation last year with 150.5 rushing yards per game, said,
``This season is not about me winning the Heisman Trophy. It's
about my team winning the Big East championship and going to a
bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   That is McNabb's mission as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not playing for the Heisman,'' said McNabb, who passed for
2,488 yards and 20 touchdowns last season in leading Syracuse from
the depths of a 1-3 start to an 8-0 finish and the Big East title.
``I'm going to be playing for my team.''
</P>
<P>
   When McNabb and Zereoue meet on the field Nov. 7 in Morgantown,
W.Va., it'll be a head-on collision with the conference title
likely to be at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a two-horse race,'' insisted West Virginia coach Don
Nehlen, whose team returns not only Zereoue but seven other
starters on offense and seven on defense from a squad that went 7-5
overall, 4-3 conference. ``How many teams are in our league? Eight
of us? It's an eight-team race. The bottom team can beat the top,
in my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   While it remains to be seen whether Temple, which welcomes new
coach Bobby Wallace from Division 2 North Alabama, and Rutgers,
which hopes to rebound from an 0-11 season, will be up to the task,
the Big East on the whole does project to be stronger, even though
its teams went 0 for 4 in postseason play.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College, predicted to finish sixth after going 4-7, 3-4,
in Tom O'Brien's inaugural season as head coach, will be jockeying
with the likes of Miami, Virginia Tech, and possibly Pittsburgh for
postseason consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Miami, picked to finish third, is looking to get back to the
postseason after sitting home for only the second time in 15 years.
Coach Butch Davis will likely restore the 'Canes to full strength
with the return of 16 starters from a young squad.Senior QB Scott
Covington, who takes over for Ryan Clement, and junior Edgerrin
James, who rushed for 1,098 yards and set a conference record with
a 271-yard effort vs. BC, will pace Miami's offense, while seven
returning starters will solidify the defense.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech will field a younger squad, replacing 11 starters,
but has proven commodities in senior QB Al Clark and two of the
best kickers in the conference _ junior placekicker Shayne Graham
and junior punter Jimmy Kibble.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh undergos a serious overhaul after Walt Harris led the
Panthers to a stunning turnaround and their first bowl appearance
since 1989 in his first year at the helm. A new quarterback,
offensive line, and running back must be found.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the conference is going to be extremely tough this
year,'' said Pasqualoni, whose team might have the toughest
nonconference schedule in the country, with games against
Tennessee, at Michigan, at North Carolina State, and vs.
Cincinnati. ``West Virginia has a lot of good players coming back,
so they're going to be tough. Miami has got just excellent,
excellent speed, talent, and young players. Virginia Tech has an
excellent core of players coming back and Coach (Frank) Beamer has
maintained a high level of play at Virginia Tech. Walt (Harris) at
Pittsburgh and Tom O'Brien at BC have both elevated their programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got Bobby Wallace at Temple, who's going to drive people
crazy with (quarterback) Kevin Harvey running that (option) offense
they're going to run; it's going to be tough on everybody. And
(Rutgers coach) Terry (Shea) finally has a quarterback (Mike
McMahon) who's been in the system a couple of years, so they're
going to be a better team.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I think the conference is going be a very, very tough
conference every single week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
