<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENING DAY HAS ARRIVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   August. Time for predictions about a season that will unfold
over the next 16 weeks:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE WHO'S NO. 1 ISSUE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Take your pick. It looks like a wide-open race among Florida
State, Ohio State, Florida, Nebraska, and a handful of other teams.
Our best guess is a Florida State-Arizona State title game in the
Fiesta Bowl. But a sleeper such as Louisiana State or Kansas State
could emerge as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE BCS QUESTION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's Bowl Championship Series, which used to be the Bowl
Alliance. What's new is that the Rose Bowl is part of the BCS, as
are the Pacific-10 and Big Ten, which means we should have a true
national championship game. The BCS will include eight teams
(champions of the Big East, Southeastern, Atlantic Coast, Big 12,
Pac-10, and Big Ten conferences, plus two at-large slots), in the
Fiesta Bowl (Jan. 4, championship game), Rose Bowl, Orange Bowl,
and Sugar Bowl. No more of this business of polls as the only
criteria. Now we'll have the two polls, plus three computers
spitting out rankings based on wins, losses, strength of schedule,
and other data. It's an improvement, but we still have plenty of
room for controversy _ say, if we have three unbeaten teams or one
unbeaten team and five or six teams with one loss all trying to get
to the national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
GAMES TO WATCH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 5: Ohio State at West Virginia, Tennessee at Syracuse,
Michigan at Notre Dame, Washington at Arizona State. One of the
biggest first weeks ever.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 19: Florida at Tennessee. It's a new era for Tennessee,
with QB Tee Martin attempting to do what Peyton Manning couldn't in
four tries: beat the Gators.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 10: LSU at Florida. This could replace Florida-Tennessee as
the most important SEC rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 14: Nebraska at Kansas State. The Wildcats haven't beaten
Nebraska since the '60s. If they want to be contenders instead of
pretenders, this is the year the streak (now at 29) must end.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 21: Michigan at Ohio State. The Buckeyes are No. 1 in both
the AP and coaches' preseason polls. But unless they can find a way
to beat the Wolverines, they won't even be No. 1 in the Big Ten.
Also, Florida at Florida State. The winner has a good chance of
playing for the national title. Loser gets to say, ``Wait until
next year.'' Edge: FSU, because the game is in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 27: Arizona State at Arizona. A meaningful Pac-10 game in
November? It doesn't happen very often, but the conference is
strong this year, with UCLA and Arizona State both national title
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE HEISMAN WATCH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Texas running back Ricky Williams is the front-runner, but will
the Longhorns be good enough to support his candidacy? No Heisman
winner has come from a team with two or more regular-season losses
since Brigham Young's Ty Detmer in 1990. Other contenders: UCLA QB
Cade McNown, West Virginia RB Amos Zereoue, Central Florida QB
Daunte Culpepper, Florida State QB Chris Weinke.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
UPSETS, UPSETS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They'll come early and often. Here's a couple to watch for right
out of the box: Louisiana Tech over Nebraska tomorrow and West
Virginia over Ohio State Sept. 5. If it goes 48-0 the other way in
both games, please disregard this.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SLEEPERS, SLEEPERS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin, Notre Dame, and Miami all could have very good
records very late in the season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE BOSTON COLLEGE QUESTION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How about 7-4 with a bowl bid? Too optimistic? Maybe. But if the
Eagles can win at Georgia Tech Sept. 5, they could be on their way
to a winning season. Tom O'Brien has the Eagles pointed in the
right direction, and it's going to be 5-6, 6-5, or 7-4, depending
on luck as much as anything else.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOT SEATS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State coach John Cooper is on one _ not in terms of job
security, but simply to beat Michigan. Alabama coach Doug DuBose,
too, simply because it's Alabama coming off a losing season. And
Rutgers coach Terry Shea, simply because the Knights look like the
worst team in the Big East again and unless there is a dramatic
turnaround, another change will have to be made.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE BIG EAST &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's improving. Syracuse is good, Miami should be back, and West
Virginia has to be great. We'll know a lot more after Sept. 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
