<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7442 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-PROGRAM-BOS &LR;      08-28 1637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PROGRAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO BUILD A PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Neb. _ Sheldon Jackson remembers the meeting. He
recalls the words, the feeling in the locker room. He was just a
redshirt freshman, a Southern California kid who had wound up here
among the children-of-the-corn fanatics known as Nebraska football
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, a tight end who has worked his way into a starting role
after four years in the system, says it was Christian Peter,
Nebraska's former All-America defensive lineman, who put it in
perspective for him at that team meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got up and just started talking,'' Jackson was saying with
a smile. ``He made it clear to all of us. He said, `We're here to
win the national championship.' And that was in the first meeting
of the season. My eyes kind of opened wide when I heard those
words. I just said, `Man, this is serious stuff.' And then I
thought about it. Around here, in any two of four years, you have a
real chance to win a national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Nebraska has shown the past five years, you have a chance
to win a national title in any season.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Jackson why he came halfway across the country, far from his
family and friends, and he answers without hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Program,'' he says. ``I came here because of The
Program.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
______ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There aren't any written instructions or guidelines that tell
you when it will happen. Nor is there an official announcement or
press release.
</P>
<P>
   It just happens. Suddenly, it's not simply a school. Not merely
the University of Nebraska or Florida State University or Penn
State or the University of Michigan. It's The Program.
</P>
<P>
   As another college football season is about to begin _ this one
with a new bowl system that seems closer than ever to crowning a
national champion on the field rather than in the polls _ there
still is only a handful of elite programs that seem to be
legitimate contenders for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Which raises a simple question: What does it take to go from
being a football-playing school to a Program?
</P>
<P>
   Is it simply winning games? Or is it something else, something
intangible, a feeling you get when you walk into a stadium that
tells you this is more than a sport, more than a group of
student-athletes going out on a Saturday afternoon and playing for
school spirit? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Start by winning
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Winning seems to be almost a given as one of the necessary
elements. In the '90s, Nebraska, Florida State, and Florida are a
close 1-2-3 in winning percentage. Not surprisingly, those schools
have won or shared the last five national championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning helps build tradition,'' says Big East commissioner
Mike Tranghese, who has a school in Miami that from the mid '80s to
the early '90s epitomized a Program. ``And if you have that, then
you have a constituency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Penn State, Nebraska, and Michigan. Even when those
schools struggle, they continute to have sellouts, and that helps
programs to be legitimate. The common element is a huge attendance
base.''
</P>
<P>
   A move to the highest level seldom happens in a year or even
two. It takes a series of successful _ and highly publicized _
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Take Florida. Until Steve Spurrier arrived back at his alma
mater in 1990, Florida was just another school that played football
_ not all that well _ and cheated _ not all that well _ in a
conference dominated by Alabama, Auburn, and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't happen right away,'' said Spurrier, whose work with
the Gators culminated with their first national championship in
1996. ``It took a while. But we had all the resources here. When I
got here in 1990, there was a black cloud hovering over the
program. Slowly, we got more and more good players to come here.
Now it's our challenge to win it all each year.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Nebraska, Florida is a threat to win it all any season. Not
only are the Gators in a high-profile league (the Southeastern
Conference), playing before sellout crowds of almost 90,000 each
Saturday, but they also are in arguably the richest recruiting area
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, Florida, and then Florida State, picks the best
talent in the state. Then everyone else gets their turn. The
advantage is so huge that even Notre Dame doesn't bother to recruit
heavily in Florida any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've pretty much conceded the best players in the state each
year to Florida and Florida State,'' said Notre Dame coach Bob
Davie.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bowden has been at Florida State since 1976 and can cite
for you, chapter and verse, the times when an in-state recruit
wouldn't even consider the Seminoles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came here, I really didn't come with the idea of
staying,'' said Bowden, who has built the Seminoles into the most
consistent program in college football, with 11 straight final
rankings of No. 4 or better. ``I was going to stay maybe four or
five years and go back home to Auburn or Alabama.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden built up Florida State football the way John Calipari
built up the University of Massachusetts basketball program: by
playing anyone, anywhere, at any time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't take any shortcuts,'' said Bowden. ``We tried to
build it right. We struggled some at the start, but now we got it
to where it's going pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think kids want to play in a highly visible program. They
want to play in a bowl game. They want to play at a place where
they have a chance to win the national championship. All that stuff
we have, plus we have location. Places like Florida and Southern
California are natural drawing powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got here, we couldn't get a kid to take a visit.
Just couldn't do it. Now we can.''
</P>
<P>
   As Nebraska has proven, however, location is not the only
drawing card for athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Athletes look at us and they look at the wins,'' says Nebraska
coach Frank Solich, who has the tough task of following Tom Osborne
as the Huskers' new mentor. ``Its pretty obvious that's important
to players. I think they respect Nebraska for what we've
accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska has accomplished quite a bit, including 2 1/2 national
championships in the last four seasons, no losing seasons for the
last two decades, and an almost guaranteed spot in the Top 10 every
year.
</P>
<P>
   Solich, who is replacing a legend in Osborne, says he will use a
basic premise in coaching: If it ain't broke, don't fix it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be ridiculous to set aside those things that helped
this program get to where it was,'' said Solich, sitting in an
office that seemed strangely empty without the overwhelming
presence of Osborne. ``I'm not looking forward to doing a lot of
things differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Nebraska lure is a tradition that turns the football
stadium in Lincoln into the third-largest gathering place in the
state, with more than 76,000 worshipers of Cornhusker football.
</P>
<P>
   ``History and tradition are part of the success of this place,''
said Nebraska athletic director Bill Byrne. ``Nebraska has that.
But there was a time in the '40s and '50s when the administration
here wanted to de-emphasize football and it showed. Then in 1962
they brought in Bob Devaney.''
</P>
<P>
   Devaney restored a commitment to Nebraska football that remains
today. He upgraded facilities, brought in better athletes,
recruited on a wider scale. He turned a football-playing school
into a Program. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Success can have a price
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If there are other key elements to building a Program besides
winning, facilities and coaching continuity seem to be prominent
among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at us,'' said Bowden. ``I've been here 23 years. Most of
my assistants have been around 15, 16, 17 years. Look over at Penn
State, where Joe Paterno has had a staff that's been around
forever. Those things are important.''
</P>
<P>
   A downside of schools becoming Programs is that sometimes
shortcuts are taken or a recruiting class comes in more noteworthy
for what it does off the field than on it. That happened at Miami,
which is only now recovering from the excesses of the Jimmy Johnson
and Dennis Erickson eras.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska, too, has had to deal with some unpleasantness in
recent years. Incidents involving Lawrence Phillips and Christian
Peter are still prominent in the consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   But Byrne says Nebraska has learned from the past and is going
into a new century with a more complete program. He ticks off a
dozen things the ``new'' Nebraska athletic program is doing _
things ranging from nutritional to psychological evaluation and
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stress wellness here,'' said Byrne. ``We have counseling
and seminars on everything from date rape and anger abuse to
problem-solving skills. We're dealing with a new set of issues. The
Ozzie and Harriet family background of the '50s and '60s just
doesn't exist anymore. Less than 40 percent of our athletes have
any kind of health insurance at all. We're getting kids who come
here from living with grandma, or from a single-parent household,
or no parents at all. We treat our athletes like family.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaches say they try to control what they can, but they can't
control everything and everyone. The NCAA doesn't allow them to,
and they don't really want to, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the way it is,'' said Bowden. ``Now you find
things out on the evening news or in your newspaper. You just hold
your breath and hope you are doing things right. But you never
know, you never know what can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the rewards seem worth the risk for a Program.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was 30 years old,'' said Bowden with a smile and a shake
of his head, ``I might be able to tolerate losing some. But at 69,
I ain't got much time anyway. I like this side better than the
other side. I like the way it is now. I like our Program.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
