r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-INVESTORS-HNS &LR;      08-28 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-INVESTORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS SAY RUSSIAN WOES WON'T SWAMP UNITED STATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ American investors shouldn't fret about the
Russian currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
   So say Michael Bernstam, a Hoover Institution fellow and
co-author of the recently published ``Fixing Russia's Banks: A
Proposal for Growth,'' and Hartmut Fischer, an economics professor
at the University of San Francisco. The Hoover Institution on War,
Revolution and Peace is a public policy research center at Stanford
University in Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   We asked the two to explain why the Russian economy is
collapsing and what impact it will have in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Question: Is Russia's economy really collapsing; if so why?
</P>
<P>
   BERNSTAM: Yes, but it had collapsed quite a while ago. It was
seven years in the making. That's when Russia started its economic
reforms and began privatizing its industries. Now, Russia is in a
very deep depression. Their depression is much greater than our
Great Depression. Our depression was 30 percent of our gross
domestic product; theirs is 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Before the reforms, Russian annual income _ per capita, in
world-market comparable prices _ was about $7,500. Now, it's
$4,000. It's poorer than Botswana, which has an average annual per
capita income of about $5,600. Mexico is about $8,000. The average
Mexican is twice as rich as the average Russian, and Mexico is a
very poor country.
</P>
<P>
   FISCHER: Privatization didn't work because it fell into the
hands of an oligarchy, which hasn't made major changes in Russia's
companies in terms of modernizing them. Russia still has lots of
companies producing old stuff that's not competitive in the world
market.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why is this happening now?
</P>
<P>
   BERNSTAM: It is happening now because Russia has accumulated so
much debt that it cannot pay. It's been borrowing heavily from the
West since 1995 for its privatization efforts. It's a policy
failure. They created an economy of looters and pirates.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has advised the Russian government to ignore
all their debt problems and the liabilities of their companies, and
go ahead with privatization. And secondly, to stop inflation, we
advised them to issue debt. Now that debt is the noose around their
necks that's strangling them. We did not understand what was going
on.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is Russia's crisis a result of the Asian crisis?
</P>
<P>
   BERNSTAM: It's coincidental. The Asian crisis contributed to it,
but the Russian crisis has had its own momentum. How the Asian
crisis impacted Russia was that it scared off foreign investors
from emerging markets. So people started to sell Russian stocks.
The Asian flu worsened Russia's general sickness.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why does what is happening in Russia affect the U.S. stock
market?
</P>
<P>
   FISCHER: It will lead people to reassess the presently high
stock valuations. Any crisis will have a negative effect on the
market. It adds to a certain amount of pessimism.
</P>
<P>
   Now, investors are even more afraid to put their money in other
emerging markets like Latin America and Asia. They're pulling money
out and investing in U.S. bonds, so bond prices have been going up.
It's a safe haven.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will this affect my mutual fund or 401(k)? Why?
</P>
<P>
   BERNSTAM: Not directly and not much, unless your mutual fund was
exposed to Russia and unless it was badly exposed to some other
shaky countries.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. has trillions invested in mutual funds around the
world. Of that, Russian stocks and bonds accounted for a fraction.
So, it's not a big deal at all for the U.S. But if we lose more
elsewhere, and depending on how much, it may become a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street is feeling uneasy about it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Should small investors be worried?
</P>
<P>
   BERNSTAM: No, for the same reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will this crisis affect anything in the U.S. beyond the value
of stocks, such as inflation or unemployment?
</P>
<P>
   BERNSTAM: No.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do we depend on Russia for any goods and services?
</P>
<P>
   FISCHER: Except for some gasoline, no. Russia is a substantial
exporter of oil, so it will probably try to sell more oil. But this
shouldn't lower prices since they've already been declining.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which U.S. industries _ and companies _ are most heavily
involved in Russia? What will happen to them and how will it affect
consumers?
</P>
<P>
   FISCHER: There will be some impact, but the Russian market
usually isn't a big part of their business. Many of these companies
in Russia, like Coca-Cola and McDonald's, knew it would be
difficult, that there might be disasters. But they wanted to have a
presence in the market because they believed it had a great future.
Now, that future is postponed.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure they're not going to pull out. They'll weather the
storm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
