<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FSU-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEMINOLES HAVE STAYED IN TOP FORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Some coaches will flinch, not wanting to
hear the words or accept the pressure that comes with them. Other
coaches are almost blase about it, as if it isn't a big deal at
all.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Bobby Bowden. Tell the veteran Florida State
coach that you think his team is No. 1 in the country and Bowden
will smile, laugh, look you in the eye, and say, ``So do we. So do
we.''
</P>
<P>
   So here we are at the start of another season, and the annual
question is posed: Who's No. 1?
</P>
<P>
   Why Florida State? Why not?
</P>
<P>
   Consider that, since 1987, Florida State:
</P>
<P>
   _has finished no worse than fourth in the final Associated Press
poll, an NCAA record;
</P>
<P>
   _has become the only program in NCAA history to win 10 or more
games for 11 straight years;
</P>
<P>
   _has a combined record of 118-15-1;
</P>
<P>
   _has been ranked No. 1 by the AP 41 times and been in the Top 10
160 of 170 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't hide our ambitions,'' said Bowden. ``Our goal is to
be No. 1 when the season is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden has reached that goal only once _ in 1993. But were it
not for a couple of what Bowden calls ``wide right'' games _ in
which missed field goals cost the Seminoles victories against Miami
_ or a play or two against another arch rival, Florida, FSU might
have a handful of national titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're ranked No. 1, it brings a lot of notoriety to your
program,'' said Bowden. ``But it leaves you no room for error. And
every year, we've had one of them. You may have a chance for one,
but not two. If you go errorless, you've got a chance to win that
darn thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to this season, which will open for FSU Monday
in the Meadowlands against Texas A&AMP;M in the Kickoff Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got as good a chance as anybody,'' said Bowden, who has
14 starters back from last year's 11-1 team, which finished a
strong runner-up to Michigan and Nebraska in the polls and in the
opinion of many people may have been better than either of those
teams.
</P>
<P>
   This year's team has some holes, most notably at quarterback,
where 26-year-old sophomore Chris Weinke moves into a leadership
role with almost no college football experience, and along the
offensive line, where experience, not talent, is the only missing
ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, FSU is as tough as ever, which means tougher than
almost every other team in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the players,'' said Bowden. ``Now it's just a matter
of getting it done.''
</P>
<P>
   FSU probably will get it done, although a schedule that includes
Texas A&AMP;M, Southern Cal, Miami, Florida, and rising Atlantic Coast
Conference powers North Carolina and Virginia offers no guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got all we can handle,'' acknowledged Bowden. ``We play
as tough a schedule as you'll find, and it seems like everybody
else is playing Georgia Southern.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Bowden is complaining. He wants it this way. He wants
to play the best, because by doing so he feels he can be the best.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, FSU comes close. Only in 1993 did everything work
out the way Bowden planned.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of Jan. 4, 1999, in the Fiesta Bowl, Bowden and the
Seminoles should get championship No. 2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
