</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MTUNION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DO-IT-YOURSELF DYNASTY IN DIVISION 3 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALLIANCE, Ohio _ The day is hot and sticky, normal for Northeast
Ohio in August. Larry Kehres doesn't mind. Not a bit. Kehres is
already in fall mode, putting on his game face, so to speak, as he
prepares for another football season.
</P>
<P>
   Kehres has reason to be enthusiastic. He is the coach of
back-to-back national champions and has an astounding 94-6-1 record
in the '90s, which includes a 77-2-1 mark during the regular
season, three national titles in the past five years, and a winning
streak that has reached 28 games.
</P>
<P>
   So on a steamy Thursday afternoon, only a few days before the
start of practice, Kehres is hard at work _ putting together a new
blocking sled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' he says. ``Down here, we don't have equipment
managers or big-timers like that. So we have to do it ourselves.
Took us a while to figure it out. We had to do it three times. We
were laughing among ourselves, saying, `Are we that dumb?' We
should have videotaped how we did it so we can do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Division 3 football, where the game may be the same,
where the athletes are just as enthusiastic and intense on
Saturdays, where the desire to win is equal to what you will find
at such hallowed college football places as South Bend, Ind.,
Lincoln, Neb., and Tallahassee, Fla. _ but where the fringe
benefits are almost nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Kehres, with more national championships than
Florida State's Bobby Bowden and Florida's Steve Spurrier combined,
with a higher winning percentage than anyone in history except
Notre Dame's Knute Rockne, is putting together a blocking sled on a
hot summer day. And it is why he will be shoveling the snow off the
field in November and December when winter arrives at Mount Union
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
______ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even at its busiest, when nearly 2,000 students are roaming the
campus, Mount Union has a cozy, comfortable feel to it. Alliance is
Middle America, a place where people don't necessarily latch their
doors at night, where the sound of lawnmowers and weed whackers is
more prevalent than traffic and police sirens.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say it is without a pulse. Sitting in a corner of
Northeast Ohio, an hour southeast of Cleveland, an hour and a half
northwest of Pittsburgh, and just east of Akron, Mount Union is in
the heart of a territory rich in football tradition and deep in
talent. The arrival of fall gets the juices flowing here.
</P>
<P>
   Canton, Ohio, the home of the Pro Football Hall of Fame, and
Massillon, Ohio, a hotbed of high school talent, are only minutes
away. The nation's Division 1 powers come here to sweep away the
super blue-chip athletes. But what they leave is not bad, and in
Division 3, this gives Kehres a huge advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great state for high school football,'' says Kehres, an
Ohio native who is in his 28th season at Mount Union (he has been a
player, an assistant coach, and for 12 years the head coach). ``All
around Northeast Ohio, and into Western Pennsylvania, you'll find a
lot of talent and you'll find that most of the players are
fundamentally sound. When it comes to things like blocking and
tackling, we don't have to start on Page 1.''
</P>
<P>
   But with no athletic scholarships, an Ohio Athletic Conference
rule that prohibits home visits, and a no-cut policy that allows
every student who shows up to compete, the recruiting of talent can
be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   For much of its history, which dates back to 1893, Mount Union
football has been a middle-of-the-road program. That changed in
1986, when Kehres, a former quarterback who still holds the school
record for longest completion (95 yards), was elevated from
assistant to head coach. Since then, the Purple Raiders have not
had a losing season. Since 1990, they have not lost more than two
games in any season. And they have turned themselves into the
winningest college football program in the nation _ with a better
record than Florida State, Nebraska, and everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Kehres, who has had opportunities to move to a higher level
(most recently at Kent State), brings a Division 1-A mentality to
his Division 3 program, especially as a season is about to begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty intense,'' says senior running back Ryan Gorius, a
three-year letter-winner. ``I don't think he's any different than
coaches you would find at a lot of big schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not in game preparation or desire to win. The Purple
Raiders still have to compete with freshman high school teams for
stadium time, and the media attention comes only during the
playoffs, but listen to Kehres or Gorius or linebacker Jason Hall,
the leading tackler on a team that led the country in scoring
defense last season, and what you hear does not reflect a casual
attitude toward football.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' said Kehres, sitting in an office filled with trophies
and cluttered with a shipment of new shoes, ``is my favorite time
of year. I like going to practice. Liked it as a player. Like it as
a coach. You get a sense of accomplishment. It still comes down to
a core ingredient of hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
______ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Purple Raiders have indeed worked hard the past few years,
their efforts last year producing a 14-0 season and second
consecutive national championship.
</P>
<P>
   And while the framework for success remains in a solid group of
returning seniors, there are enough question marks _ especially at
the skill positions _ to lead some people to think Mount Union
might lose a game this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest challenge we have is to get players and coaches to
be patient and be realistic in the rate of improvement we have,''
says Kehres. ``We had a quarterback here who started 53 consecutive
games. He started every game from the time he walked onto this
campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell our players this won't be a continuation of the past
two years, but something we will have to build ourselves as they
get more experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mount Union experience of the past two years was remarkable,
a 28-0 run.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what happens this year, we're going to have those
last two seasons,'' said Gorius. ``We're going to have it next
year, 10 years from now, and as long as we live.''
</P>
<P>
   But this group of seniors does not want to be the class that
breaks the string, whether that means losing a regular-season game
or not winning the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already got together as a group and talked about it,'' says
Hall. ``We're not living in the past. We know we've got a lot of
work ahead of us, but we have a lot of leadership and a good
nucleus of people coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Kehres cautions that the expectations may be too high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are telling me that they'll come see us in a
playoff game,'' said Kehres. ``I tell them they're taking a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a hard year and we know it. We're not going to go
out and score 21 points in the first quarter every time we turn
around. Mentally, we're ready; I hope our fans are.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
______ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Winning as much as this team wins can change people. Kehres says
that hasn't happened to him. At least he hopes it hasn't. Part of
the reason is the built-in humbling experience of coaching at the
Division 3 level.
</P>
<P>
   All coaches at this level are members of the college faculty and
required to teach 24 hours a year in credits. Coaching counts for
some of that, and as athletic director as well as football coach,
Kehres does no classroom work. But reminders that football is only
a sport here _ and not a multimillion-dollar business _ are never
far away.
</P>
<P>
   The changes Kehres has made are found in his approach to
players. As he nears 50, he says, he is more patient, more
tolerant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a much better listener than I was 7 or 8 years ago,'' he
says. ``I'm more adaptable at taking what the players say and
incorporating their ideas into what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, he has also become more comfortable with his
status and how he teaches the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not Alabama, we're not Southern California,'' he says.
``We don't take other teams' offenses. We're our own.''
</P>
<P>
   The transition from good to great came in small steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we had a master plan and it worked out
perfectly,'' Kehres says. ``It's more like we took some side steps,
maybe a step backward, before we finally got it right. All the time
we constantly asked ourselves what can go wrong. We spent a lot of
time being a problem solver.''
</P>
<P>
   Kehres sometimes has wandering thoughts on Saturdays, when
big-time college football floods the television screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just once it would be nice to run out on the field with
105,000 people cheering you,'' he says. ``But that's before the
game. Once the game starts and you put your headsets on, football
is football.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
