<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSCOLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSTRUCTION SITE AT THE HEIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When the USA Today/ESPN preseason poll was released
this month, the usual programs were represented at the top. The
Ohio States. The Florida States. The Nebraskas. The Floridas. The
Michigans. All are past national champions.
</P>
<P>
   Further down the poll, there was UCLA, LSU, Tennessee, Penn
State, Georgia, Virginia, Auburn, and, at No. 24, Notre Dame. Among
the nouveau riche programs that cracked the rankings were Kansas
State (at No. 6), Colorado State (16), and Southern Mississippi
(21).
</P>
<P>
   As for Boston College?
</P>
<P>
   After going 4-7 last season and finishing in a fifth-place tie
in the Big East in Tom O'Brien's first year as head coach, the
Eagles were nowhere to be seen. BC was not even among ``others
receiving votes.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was a time not long ago when BC was indeed counted
among the Top 25 teams in the country. After a 4-7 season in 1991,
his first year at the helm, former coach Tom Coughlin restored the
foundering program to national prominence. In 1992, Coughlin
steered the Eagles to an 8-3 season and a Hall of Fame Bowl berth,
and in '93, they went 9-3, making a second consecutive New Year's
Day bowl appearance, in the Carquest.
</P>
<P>
   Each of those seasons was highlighted by a ``program-making''
game: in 1992, BC won at Penn State, 35-32, and the following year,
it upset top-ranked Notre Dame, 41-39, at South Bend, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   While BC managed to recapture some of the national limelight it
basked in after Doug Flutie's 1994 Miracle in Miami, the program
was still lacking in certain amenities _ namely, a refurbished
stadium and practice facilities _ enjoyed by other major programs.
</P>
<P>
   Until BC found a way to put more facilities on its cramped
campus, rival schools were certain to point out this drawback to
prospective recruits.
</P>
<P>
   Despite strong opposition from neighbors in Brookline, Newton,
and Allston-Brighton, BC finally upgraded its facilities in 1994,
expanding Alumni Stadium to 44,500 seats. But the man who lobbied
strongest for a new stadium, Coughlin, was not there to see it; he
left in February 1994 to become head coach of the Jacksonville
Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   It was a stunning departure that shook BC's program to its
foundation. Coughlin's successor, Dan Henning, enjoyed a modicum of
success in his first season _ a 7-4 campaign punctuated by a 30-11
rout of Notre Dame and a trip to the Aloha Bowl _ but two years
later, BC was rocked by a gambling scandal that smeared the
school's reputation and eventually cost Henning his job.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it has fallen upon O'Brien, a 49-year-old former Marine and
Naval Academy graduate, to build things back up again.
</P>
<P>
   So where do you begin when you're building anew?
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the top programs across the country,'' said
O'Brien, ``the No. 1 thing that strikes me is continuity _ not only
with the head coach, but with the assistant coaches and the people
who've been there for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, winning has a lot to do with it. Maybe some guys
could have continuity in a program but haven't been afforded the
opportunity with patience within the administration and/or the
alumni to put all their ducks in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``A classic example is if you look at the University of North
Carolina. Mack Brown, I think he won one game in his first two
years, and he didn't have a winning season until his fourth year
and he was lucky to be 6-5. They showed great patience and
determination with him _ that he was going to do it. He kept his
staff mostly intact and made one or two coaching changes along the
way.''
</P>
<P>
   When O'Brien took his first head job in December 1996, after
serving as a longtime assistant to Virginia coach George Welsh, his
first order of business was to assemble a staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a formula, but there are couple of different
things,'' O'Brien said. ``First thing is, when you take a job, you
have to understand the parameters of the job _ what is expected of
you and what they want out of the program. When you understand what
those qualifications are, then you go about as a coach making sure
you hire the right people that will fit into the system or the
program you want to build.
</P>
<P>
   ``With that said, the most important thing is _ and I always use
the phrase `in the boat' _ they have to be pulling their oars, and
they have to be rowing in the same direction, and they all have to
be on board, because it only takes one or two going in the opposite
direction to pull a program down.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everybody works towards the same goal _ not only on the
staff, but the support staff in the training room, the equipment
room, in the weight room _ and we're all on the same page, then
nobody cares who gets credit. The bottom line is to win football
games and to do it the right way. I think we have started with that
in place here at Boston College, so we can build a foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   BC athletic director Gene DeFilippo thinks it begins with a
commitment from the very top of the administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is essential that you have a president who is committed,
because then you've got a real chance to build a successful
program,'' said DeFilippo, who came to BC from Villanova last
September as the successor to Chet Gladchuk, now the University of
Houston AD. ``The next thing is that you need an athletic director
who understands what it takes to help the coaches build a program.
For example, an athletic director has to do his part in the way of
facilities, and we're totally committed to our facilities here.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the recent improvements is a fenced and lighted practice
area on Shea Field, which in the past doubled as a parking lot for
the more generous boosters of BC football. In addition, BC will
finally have an indoor practice facility this winter when a 55-foot
bubble is erected over the stadium field.
</P>
<P>
   Given BC's strong academic reputation and its attractive setting
in Boston, O'Brien knows that the upgrades will make his program
even more attractive to local and national recruits.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that relates to the long-term effects of the program, and
it has to do with recruiting, which is as important a part of this
program as anything,'' said O'Brien, whose class of 18 recruits
this year included eight local athletes, including former St.
John's Prep quarterback Brian St. Pierre, who will likely redshirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The better players I have, the better coach I'll become,'' he
said. ``In order to get the good players, there's something you can
promise right now _ the chance to play early, those kind of things.
But when you get this program off the ground and running and now
you're recruiting with top programs in the country year in and year
out, then facilities will become very important.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where I think the athletic director comes into play and
does a great job. We seem to be on the same page with the vision of
where we want to go with this program and facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   If the rebuilding of BC's football program is analogous to the
construction of a house (``If you build a strong foundation, you're
going to have a strong home,'' said O'Brien), where does the
project stand?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still fighting some personnel things as a football team
because of what we inherited. It would be important for us to have
a good year to help us sign a good class.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be better in recruiting and we have to be better on
the football field. Every day we want to try and improve this
program in some way or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when you get good.''
</P>
<P>
   And get back into the Top 25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
