u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      08-28 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES' ROLE CAST IN DOUBT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ When Ferric Collons got wind that a reporter
asked Mike Jones about being ``on the bubble'' Collons said, ``He's
not on the bubble. He's on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the kind of respect Jones has earned from his teammates.
They are protective of him because he is so fiercely loyal to them.
</P>
<P>
   Just two seasons ago, Jones was one of the defensive captains, a
true leader and inspiration, as well as one of the players who
keeps the team loose with his kidding and practical jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are some real issues involving the veteran, numbers
being the biggest one.
</P>
<P>
   When coach Pete Carroll talks about his defensive tackle
rotation, he mentions Chad Eaton, Mark Wheeler, Henry Thomas, and
Brandon Mitchell. When he speaks about his ends, he mentions
Collons, Chris Sullivan, Willie McGinest, and Greg Spires. That's
eight players.
</P>
<P>
   Jones plays both positions. Last year, he started seven games in
place of McGinest at the elephant spot and four games for the
injured Collons.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean Jones is the ninth defensive lineman? If he is,
what do the Patriots do with fourth-round draft pick Leonta Rheams?
The Patriots are not apt to cut such a high pick. If Rheams is
waived and then put on the practice squad, Jones is in. Would they
keep Jones over Rheams? Or Mitchell, their second-round pick of a
year ago?
</P>
<P>
   There's always the possibility the Patriots could swing a deal
for a defensive lineman. They are one of the few teams with depth
at a position that's fairly thin around the league.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is clearly a bit uncomfortable about the subject, but he
doesn't duck it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really can't tell what an organization is thinking,'' said
Jones. ``Look at Pittsburgh and Greg Lloyd. That man is the
backbone of that organization. He represented the organization like
no player in the last decade, so you just don't know in this
game.''
</P>
<P>
   After two injury-filled seasons, the Steelers released Lloyd
this summer to save money under the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Jones says he thinks about his spot on the team only when
reporters confront him with the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I feel is when I get in a game I need to make
some plays,'' he said. ``Everything else will handle itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just need to concentrate on my game. There's no need to talk
about it. You can't control what they say one way or the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think about it, and you hear you guys come to me that I'm
on the bubble again. You try and forget about it but you keep
throwing it up in my face. I deal with it like I can. I put the
negativity away and go about doing the things I need to do to get
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll finally mentioned Jones a couple of days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike has been in the mix all along,'' said Carroll. ``He plays
all of the spots for us. He has become a utility guy. Last week he
played the elephant position and tackle and did all the stuff. He's
also been competing for an inside spot on the nickel team.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones turned 29 this week, so he's not yet thinking about life
after football. Most defensive linemen are just hitting their prime
at his age. If he doesn't hit his stride for the Patriots, there
are a number of teams that would be interested in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a blessing,'' said Jones. ``I'm fortunate to be playing
a position where there's a need. It's just like cornerbacks;
there's a need for corners in the NFL. I'm blessed that it is that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones has been hampered with a knee injury throughout training
camp, but he considers himself to be at full speed. He will get
plenty of opportunities in the Philadelphia game Saturday night.
Unlike other veterans who just try to get through exhibition games
unscathed, Jones knows he has to do better than that.
</P>
<P>
   The other issue weighing heavily on his situation is money.
Jones's salary is in the high six-figures. The Patriots have some
cap room left, but they would have much more if they could drop a
veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's reality,'' said Jones. ``That's just the way it is. I
don't let stuff like that frustrate me because I have no control
over it. I won't let that linger in my mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
