</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN29 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home care injustices
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Believe it or not, the best thing that's happened to Ray and
Frances lately has been for him to be declared terminally ill.
</P>
<P>
   They are counting this among their blessings due to new,
ruthless Medicare rules.
</P>
<P>
   Recently they were notified that Medicare was going to yank
funds for the home care that was keeping him out of a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   Now, because he's been declared terminally ill, he is getting
Medicare-funded services through a hospice. Do we call this good
luck?
</P>
<P>
   Ray and Frances (not their real names) live in a Central Florida
retirement community. She called me after reading a column I wrote
about the plight of a man dying of Lou Gehrig's disease who got
similar ``good news'' after having the home-care coverage revoked
that was paying for home-care aides to visit him. Now, because he
could be classified as terminally ill, he would still get extended
Medicare coverage through a hospice.
</P>
<P>
   That shouldn't be necessary. In either case, the Medicare
recipient is sick enough not to have anyone splitting hairs.
Terminal? Not terminal?
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, Ray was virtually paralyzed by a severe stroke 14
years ago. He's been beset by complications of diabetes. His most
serious condition is gastro paresis, a near-paralysis of his
intestinal tract. Bowels are a life-or-death matter for everyone,
but for him it's an ordeal that calls for home-care aides. They
often act invasively and manually to clear an intestinal blockage.
</P>
<P>
   But in the eyes of Medicare under new cost-cutting rules, Ray
was just in a holding pattern, not ``sick'' enough _ no fever, for
instance _ to need a physician or nurse.
</P>
<P>
   The rules were included in Medicare reforms in the 1997 Balanced
Budget Act. Aimed at waste and fraud, the rules effectively drew a
line and capped projected home-care costs nationwide based on 1994
figures.
</P>
<P>
   What Congress didn't realize when it made its cuts was that
fraud wasn't driving up the amount of home care for which Medicare
was paying. Choice was doing that. People were turning to home care
over nursing homes, saving the federal government money in the long
run. It's as common as sundown for the costs of nursing home care
to sap someone of resources, effectively spending him or herself
into poverty and onto Medicaid rolls.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what would have happened in the case of Ray and
Frances. He would have gone into a nursing home. She has some
savings for that, but ultimately, depending on how long he lived,
it would be at a sum cost increase to the taxpayer.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening right now across the country is that because of
Medicare cuts, home care, an industry based on economy and choice,
is being decimated, driving many into nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas alone, more than 1,000 home-care agencies have shut
down this year, with thousands more teetering on the brink.
</P>
<P>
   This has gotten Congress' attention. Indications are that
emergency measures may be taken in September.
</P>
<P>
   When I started to write this column I was prepared to use Ray's
and Frances's real names. Later she asked me to refrain. Though
things had worked out all right with hospice stepping in, she still
was worried about losing benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows when somebody is going to die,'' she said,
pointing out that the ``terminally ill'' classification for hospice
care is based on a six-month life expectancy.
</P>
<P>
   A wife worries she'll be penalized because her husband didn't
die on time. Imagine.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald. E-mail:
jyoungmail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
