<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV30-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERRIBLE FUND WORTH DUMPING, EVEN AT A LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 30, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. On March 15 of 1996 I invested $5,000 in Van Wagoner Emerging
Growth fund, and I maintained a dollar cost averaging program in
the fund until July of that year. My total investment came to
$9,100, and it is now worth $6,700. I don't know what to do at this
point. Should I get out with such a loss, or stay in? I am
desperate at this time; I don't want to lose any more of my money.
What do you advise?
</P>
<P>
   M.C., Dedham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I suggest you chalk this one up to experience. The record of
Van Wagoner Emerging Growth is simply awful. Founded at the end of
1995, it got off to a bold start, showing 30.30 percent gains in
the first quarter of 1996, and following that with a 14.89 percent
gain in the second. From there on, it's been mostly downhill.
Entering this week, the fund's record showed a loss of 31.5 percent
over the past year, and a year-to-date loss of 11.6 percent. This
compares to a peer-group average gain of 3.7 percent over the past
52 weeks, and a 3.2 percent gain year-to-date.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the fund's woes can be tied to a portfolio very heavily
concentrated in two sectors -- technology and utilities. But since
both the technology and utility sectors have done a great deal
better than this fund, in the end the blame must be tied simply to
lousy stock-picking. Morningstar Mutual Funds reports that the fund
is moving to a more diversified portfolio, raising the fund's
portfolio from 79 to 112 issues during the first quarter. But since
the losses have continued since that point, there seems to have
been no positive effect. Because of its relative youth, Morningstar
doesn't rate the fund, but it seems likely that when the ratings
come, it will start out in the cellar.
</P>
<P>
   So I suggest you join the herd: money has been flowing out of
this fund steadily since 1996, and I suggest you follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   One word about your abandoned dollar-cost-averaging plan: When I
discuss dollar cost averaging I like to describe it as a
'discipline.' I use this word because when there is a downturn,
investors must grit their teeth and contemplate the prospect that
they might be throwing good money after bad. As it turned out, in
your case it was all to the better to quit. But as a general rule,
it's a bad practice to abandon a dollar-cost-averaging plan once
the investment begins heading south. After all, the entire logic
behind the plan is that you bring your average cost per share down
by adding additional shares at lower prices during a downturn. If
you lose faith in a fund that's the target of a dollar-cost
averaging program, the thing to do it quit the fund, but not the
program; you simply move to a better fund and resume the
discipline. I write this not so much to admonish you, but to
encourage other readers who are engaged in these programs not to
lose heart during the current choppy markets -- remember, the key
word is discipline.
</P>
<P>
   If you're still willing to stick with the mid-cap growth
objective, I suggest you take a look at T. Rowe Price Mid-Cap
Growth fund, one of the strongest funds in the category.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like your thoughts on selling four Fidelity funds
that are in a taxable account and have been held six years -- in
favor of switching to an index fund. I have $14,500 in Fidelity
Blue Chip Growth, $57,000 in Fidelity Equity Income II, $14,300 in
Fidelity Growth and Income, and $14,300 in Fidelity Puritan.
</P>
<P>
   J.A., Lunenburg, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think the IRS would be very happy to hear of your proposal.
What you're considering is selling four very solid funds in which
you have achieved handsome gains over the last four years -- thus
generating a sizable tax bill. And while your current portfolio
isn't particularly well diversified -- the stock portfolios of all
four funds you hold are dominated by large-cap stocks -- the
chances are that if you buy a single index fund you will end up
with pretty much the same thing. Even if you went with Vanguard's
Total Stock Market Index fund, which tracks the nation's 5,000
largest stocks, you would still have a holding dominated by the
large caps. The only way you could get a diversified index
portfolio would be to buy a number of different Vanguard Index
funds -- you might use Index 500, the Mid-Cap Index, the Small-Cap
Index, and Balanced Index to achieve a good measure of
diversification.
</P>
<P>
   But I don't think that added diversification would outweigh the
negative effect of the big tax bill you would doubtless pay if you
sold, so my instinct would be to stand pat. I have long been a fan
of index funds, but I am also aware that their current popularity
is largely a function of the fact that for the last few years most
of them have simply been in the right place at the right time --
heavily invested in large-cap stocks during one of the most
enduring bull markets for large-cap stocks. I think at some point
the worm will turn, and then the highly rated managers of the funds
you hold will be able to show their stuff, adjusting their
portfolios to changing markets, rather than simply riding the
formulas as index fund managers must do.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's the best investment course I can take to increase my
income? I am 74 years old and I have $11,200 a year coming in from
Social Security. The rest of my income comes from IRA investments,
which are very conservatively invested in Treasury Notes and CDs.
The total comes to $316,000, with yields ranging from a low of 5.27
percent on a CD to 6.75 percent on a Treasury Note.
</P>
<P>
   S.M., San Diego
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I tally a portfolio average yield of 5.53 percent, bringing
you a total annual income stream of $17,488. I think you could
reasonably bump the income stream up by a little more than $3,000
-- but as always seems to be the case, when you get a better deal
there will be a price to pay. In this case, the price is risk. With
the Treasury Notes and the CD , you have substantially no risk; the
federal government stands behind both investments.
</P>
<P>
   Once you get into investments with higher yields, you will face
a whole spectrum of risks -- risk that the market value of your
investments will fall, risk that the yields will decline, and even
in some cases, risk that the issuers of bonds you own will default.
</P>
<P>
   A conservative and well-managed bond fund can mitigate and
reduce some of these risk levels, but you can never escape it
entirely. So right from the outset you will have to decide whether
an additional $3,000 a year is worth the risk that your investment
might perform poorly. You should decide further whether you are the
kind of person who can watch an investment with an ever-changing
market value calmly; for some people, the worries that come with a
market investment completely outweigh the slightly higher yields.
</P>
<P>
   If you're still with me, I suggest a portfolio of no-load mutual
funds in the following categories -- a Ginnie Mae fund, invested in
federally-guaranteed mortgage securities, a short-term bond fund,
and a high-yield bond fund. If half the portfolio were in the GNMA
fund and the balance split between the short-term and high-yield
bond funds, you could expect an average portfolio yield of about
6.5 percent, bringing you an income stream of $20,540 a year. You
can also expect the value of your holdings to be in more or less
constant flux -- rising in value when interest rates fall or are
expected to fall, and falling in value when interest rates rise. In
addition, you could expect the high-yield bond fund to fall in
value if the economy goes into a tailspin. But if you look at such
a portfolio over the course of many years -- say a decade or more
-- what you'll likely see is little or no change in principal
value, and a steady stream of interest checks.
</P>
<P>
   So three warnings apply to such a portfolio. First, you must
understand and accept the risk factors that are inherent in bonds.
Second, you should invest only for the long term, committing only
money you expect to leave there for a decade or more.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, if there's a chance that you'll need money to face
an emergency, you'd be best off leaving a reasonable amount in a
more cautious investment such as a money market fund -- so you
won't have to face the prospect of selling bond fund shares at a
bad time in the event you need money on short notice.
</P>
<P>
   Most large fund families sell mutual funds in these categories.
My favorite is Vanguard, especially when it comes to bond funds,
because Vanguard adopts a straightforward plain vanilla approach to
managing such funds, and second because Vanguard's typically low
expense levels tend to give them an extra edge in performance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
