<HEADER>
A7464 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BONNIE-ELIZABETHCITY2     08-28 1847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIE-ELIZABETHCITY28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High winds blamed for death, leave over 8,000 without power
 &HT;    By Ginger Livingston, Tom Langhorne, Emilio Sahurie and Angela
Forest
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELIZABETH CITY, N.C. _ For a hurricane that supposedly was down
for the count, Bonnie sure packed a heck of a nasty second punch.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane-turned tropical storm-turned hurricane ravaged
communities across the Albemarle with high winds late Thursday
night, causing at least one death and leaving hundreds battling
floodwaters and thousands more without electricity.
</P>
<P>
   James ''Pee-Wee'' Edwards, Pasquotank-Camden Central
Communications director, said tornadic activity was reported
throughout both counties around 11:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had several people call who said they saw tornadoes but it
is still unconfirmed,'' said Christy Saunders, Pasquotank-Camden
Emergency Management director.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't tornadoes, it was probably straight-line winds.''
</P>
<P>
   Saunders said this morning that wind gusts of approximately 83
mph were reported in Elizabeth City. And the National Weather
Service has an unofficial report of 93-mph winds in Currituck
County.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the Currituck community of Barco that a 12-year-old
girl was killed when a tree fell on her home as she was sleeping.
Law enforcement authorities had not released the victim's name --
believed to be North Carolina's only fatality from Bonnie -- as of
presstime this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the rest of the damage from Bonnie's fierce winds seemed
confined to cosmetic damage to houses, downed power lines and
fallen trees.
</P>
<P>
   In South Mills, Joyce Medlin said she was awakened early Friday
by the cries of neighbors after a large oak tree crushed their
garage. Medlin's car was parked in the garage for protection
against the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bonnie didn't pass through this area like people were
saying,'' Medlin said. ``It stayed around a lot longer than
expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Barco resident Rosemary Gilbert said the storm shattered three
windows and ripped shingles at her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through a hurricane before but this one scared the
heck out of me,'' Gilbert said. ``It was just nasty.''
</P>
<P>
   The strong winds also flipped over a 17,000-pound
tractor-trailer on Kelsey Road in the Newland township of
Pasquotank County.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the damage came during Bonnie's second pass through
the region, however. Around 4 p.m., a large pine tree,
three-to-four feet in diameter, snapped and blocked Body Road for
approximately four hours.
</P>
<P>
   When the tree fell it brought down several hundred yards of
electric lines. No homes or vehicles were damaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a crash and when I looked outside there was a lot of
electricity, a lot of fire,'' said Lorraine Payne, who lived
nearby. ``It tore down my transformer, dropped it in my driveway. I
was worried because wires were hanging on my car but luckily it
wasn't raining and (the electric crews) came right away.''
</P>
<P>
   The tree was removed and electric power restored around 9 p.m.,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pasquotank-Camden emergency management officials could offer no
concrete estimates this morning for damages and flooding, though
that will surely change as the day progresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've received no reports of flooding, and there's been no
major, major damage reported to us -- but I'm sure there will be
some later this morning as people wake up and get stirring and
looking around,'' Edwards said before 7 a.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, emergency communications director for
Pasquotank-Camden-Elizabeth City, said most of the structural
damage to houses, and power outages, are believed to have occurred
between 11 p.m. Thursday and 2 a.m. today, when winds were
heaviest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We received several unconfirmed reports of tornadic winds for
that period,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many streets and yards in Elizabeth City's rivershore
communities were littered this morning with downed trees or parts
of trees. Roads on Rivershore Drive and Riverside Avenue, and
surrounding neighborhoods, were covered with tree branches of
various sizes and other debris from trees.
</P>
<P>
   Everything was soaked.
</P>
<P>
   At 1000 Riverside, a large portion of tree lay suspended across
a power line. On the 1100 block of Parkview Drive, a large tree lay
across the road, making it impassable by vehicles. At 1207 Fairfax
Avenue, a tree was split almost evenly down the middle, a portion
of it still standing and the other portion lying in the yard.
</P>
<P>
   Flooding in rivershore communities appeared this morning to have
receded since mid-Thursday afternoon's storms, when some
intersections were so congested with water that vehicles could not
pass. At one such intersection, Flora Street and Riverside Avenue,
water appeared to be several feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   Like it was in other areas, much of the damage in Currituck
seems to have occurred after 11 p.m. Much of it centered around
central and northern Currituck County, said Sheriff Glenn Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   Brinkley said winds in Corolla and Grandy were only clocked at
around 20 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Strong winds also downed trees in Knotts Island preventing a
sheriff's deputy from driving through the main causeway.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much has happened last night,'' Brinkley said. ``People
don't realize the damage until they see it for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   More than 8,000 North Carolina Power customers in Pasquotank,
Perquimans and Currituck counties had lost power as of 7:15 a.m.
today.
</P>
<P>
   The figure represents the vast majority of the company's
approximately 10,160 customers in 19 northeastern North Carolina
counties who lost power as a result of Hurricane Bonnie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't have an estimate of when we hope to get
everyone restored,'' North Carolina Power spokesman Bryant Brooks
said shortly after 7:30 a.m. today. ``I can say that we are working
on it around-the-clock, with some help from contract crews and
(employees of) Virginia Power.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said outages in Camden totaled only about 150.
</P>
<P>
   Some 5,000 of the City of Elizabeth City's power customers --
about half of the total -- were knocked out, City Manager Steven
Harrell said this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost only about 1,000 customers during Hurricane Bertha,
and they were back up by the end of the day,'' Harrell said at
about 8:20 a.m. ``But anytime you've got half your customers out,
like we do now, that's a pretty severe outage.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrell said most of the power outages are concentrated in the
northern and western parts of town. The rest of the city suffered
only ``sporadic'' outages, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked when power might be restored, the city manager had no
estimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crews are working right now,'' he said. ``We have a mutual aid
contract with other members of ElectriCities, and crews from (some
of those municipalities) are on their way here now. I expect it
will take a couple of hours for them to get here and get working.''
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the storm, 9,000 customers were without power,
said Jim Stone, a supervisor with the North Carolina Power office
in Elizabeth City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have six contract crews and three tree trimming crews plus
our normal crews but I don't think we'll get everyone until
probably mid-morning Saturday,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's storm activity shocked many North Carolina
Power workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I left at lunch yesterday I didn't think the trouble was
going to be that bad, but coming back in last night, the winds
starting picking up and it got very bad,'' said Skip Mason, a
lineman.
</P>
<P>
   Mason's crew was sent to Camden County to restore power in the
area of Anytown Road.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was snapped poles, cross arms broken, everywhere,'' he
said. ``Acouple of times we had to take our chainsaws out and cut
our way through so we could go down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Beside dozens of downed trees, one utility pole blocked N.C.
Highway 343, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stone said it wasn't easy restoring electricity Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the wind and the rain you're fight and then you have
to go down right-of-way lugging things in and out. It's not just
working along side the road,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stone's counterparts with the Albemarle Electric Membership
Cooperative faced similar problems.
</P>
<P>
   A large part of Perquimans County, including Hertford and
Winfall, lost power at 11:30 p.m. As of 6:45 this morning, both
Hertford and Winfall remained without power, said Perquimans
Sheriff Ralph Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   In Chowan County, there were no injuries or structural damage
reported during the storm's second day, said Emergency Management
Official Patty Madry.
</P>
<P>
   Like other areas, Chowan reported widespread power outages
Thursday. None were widespread, however, and as of Friday morning
power in those areas had been restored, Madry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some temporary flooding at Pembroke Circle, West Queen
Street, Wildcat Road, King Street, Water Street last night. But
that is all clear today,'' she said this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also said that high winds and water surges forced the
closing of the S-Bridge across the Perquimans River on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The storm added at least two feet of water to the Perquimans
River, causing 3-foot surges along the waterway. The bridge was
reopened to traffic early
</P>
<P>
   today.
</P>
<P>
   Perquimans Sheriff Robinson said strong winds forced down power
lines on Snug Harbor Road near U.S. Highway 17 and Bagley Swamp
Road off State Highway 37 late Thursday. Sheriff and police
officials, along with the State Highway Patrol monitored the lines
and checked major roads throughout the county to ensure they
remained open to traffic, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Flooding in the area appeared to be minor, Robinson said this
morning, with most of it reported near Harvey Point Road and at the
intersection of State Highway 37 and U.S. Highway 17 Business
heading toward the S-Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had a chance to assess how some of the (minor) roads
are doing,'' he said. ``We have a lot of trees down on Holiday
Island and in Winfall (the winds) hit hard and there are trees down
toward Bagley Swamp. We have a lot
</P>
<P>
   of debris down naturally, but I think we should be in pretty
good shape,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of debris-filled highways, N.C. Highway Patrol and
Currituck County Sheriff deputies were ordered to block roads
leading into Currituck County.
</P>
<P>
   Around 9 a.m. this morning, road blocks were lifted to the
relief of a multitude of cars lined up at the major county
intersections such as U.S. Highway 158 and N.C. Highway 34.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina Power crews were also out restoring power to
parts of Currituck County which were hard hit by resurgent winds
from Bonnie.
</P>
<P>
   N.C. Department of Transportation trucks also scoured the county
cutting large limbs and removing them from major roads.
</P>
<P>
   Pasquotank-Camden Emergency Management's Saunders said
assessment crews will be patrolling both Pasquotank and Camden
today to see exactly how much damage occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger Livingston, Tom Langhorne, Emilio Sahurie and Angela
Forest write for The Daily Advance of Elizabeth City.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
