<HEADER>
A7466 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BONNIE-STAYBEHINDS28-     08-28 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNIE-STAYBEHINDS28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some Outer Banks residents toughed it out
 &HT;    Eds: ''Today'' is Friday.
 &HT;    By Emilio Sahurie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELIZABETH CITY, N.C. _ For Outer Banks residents who stayed
behind when everyone else fled, Hurricane Bonnie had packed more
hype than punch by the time it crawled through the area Thursday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, was before Bonnie regained hurricane strength
early this morning just east of the Outer Banks. The rejuvenated
storm pounded the area with heavy winds, rain and flood waters
before moving farther out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   While thousands of vacationers and residents were ordered to
evacuate the resort area on Tuesday, some across the Outer Banks
preferred to brace themselves for the worst in the comfort of
familiar surroundings - their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon, as Bonnie's wrath weakened crossing the
Albemarle region, Charlotte Draper's only concern was lifting
furniture and belongings off the floor. Although Bonnie's strength
was downgraded as it moved northeast toward the coast, rising water
levels associated with the system were a priority to many in the
barrier islands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you raise the level of water, you know what happens,''
said Draper, who along with her husband, Bill, decided to stay at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Draper, who lives near the Currituck Sound in Kitty Hawk, said
an elderly mother and her husband's work with the Coast Guard
auxiliary were the main reasons why her family stayed behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people heeded the warning,'' Draper said. ``But a lot of
the people who stayed behind have gone through this kind of weather
before.''
</P>
<P>
   A day after Bonnie landed in the Wilmington area, the Outer
Banks looked more like a ghost town than a thriving resort
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very quiet,'' realtor Doug Brindley from his Corolla
office said Thursday. ``Even more so than winter.''
</P>
<P>
   The local Post Office in Corolla closed on Tuesday after
evacuations orders were issued. But there were signs of life on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Wink's of Corolla, a local grocery store, remained opened this
week to the delight of those who stayed behind. Across the county
line, in Dare, storm stragglers made several convenient stores the
hot spot for fresh cups of coffee and other vital supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Brindley said he stayed because the overnight forecast from
Wednesday night did not predict any major impact on Currituck's
Outer Banks. As a volunteer fire fighter and the developer of 459
resort homes, Brindley also felt an obligation to help those who
lingered in the Outer Banks.
</P>
<P>
   Similar civic reasons made Mary Bichner keep the grocery store
she runs, one of the oldest businesses in Corolla open this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have lived here 27 years and I care about the needs of the
community,'' said Bichner, who has worked at Wink's for 16 years.
``I felt people should be able to come here for whatever they
needed.''
</P>
<P>
   From talking to Currituck County Sheriff's Deputies, Bichner
said she estimates about 600-700 people remained in the paved areas
of Corolla - not counting the Carova Beach area. That's a far cry
from the population explosion of more than 20,000 visitors that
pack into Currituck's Outer Banks on a weekly basis during the
tourist season.
</P>
<P>
   About the only major inconvenience in Corolla on Thursday was
the lack of water in one subdivision, Corolla Light. A local
utility company shut off the water supply from a water tower to
stabilize the structure from heavy winds. Lighter water towers are
considered more of a risk for toppling over.
</P>
<P>
   However, since the order to evacuate had not been rescinded by
Thursday afternoon, the water shortage in this particular community
wasn't a problem, said Brindley.
</P>
<P>
   The only preoccupation, Brindley and other real estate agents in
the Outer Banks had on Thursday was answering questions from
tourists eager to return. Because new tourists typically arrive on
a weekly basis, the earliest a new batch of tourists is likely to
return is this Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be nice to get them back,'' Bichner said. ``It will be
nice for business too.''
</P>
<P>
   Emilio Sahurie writes for The Daily Advance of Elizabeth City.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
