<HEADLINE>
AN UPGRADE TO COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walter Zenga salvaged the Revolution's 1997 season with a
spectacular comeback from knee surgery as the team qualified for
the Major League Soccer playoffs. Now, he can provide only a
spiritual and strategic role as the Revolution face a must-win
situation against Miami in Fort Lauderdale Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The saviors of the team are the players,'' said Zenga,
Thursdaywho was named to replace Thomas Rongen as coach three days
ago. ``They have to believe in themselves. They can't believe it's
over, because in soccer the game is not over until the final
whistle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to have what it takes within themselves, they have
to have respect for themselves, pride, and the will to do something
positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like last year, maybe, I can pass on to the other players what
I know of the game. The difference is I will have to do it while
sitting on the bench instead of standing in the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga returned from Italy Thursday, and his initial greetings
were from Logan Airport workers while he awaited Revolution general
manager Brian O'Donovan and assistant coach Sid Mazzola.
</P>
<P>
   ``This feels like a second home,'' Zenga said. ``It's destiny. I
played my last game for Italy here, and we won, 2-0 (against the
Republic of Ireland June 4, 1992). Last year I played so well, and
it was a little bit crazy. But I really like living here.''
</P>
<P>
   The negotiated resignation of Rongen and the hiring of Zenga
occurred quickly after the Revolution fell, 5-1, to Los Angeles
last Saturday. Even Zenga at his most impulsive could not have
anticipated the speed of the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done some strange things,'' said Zenga, ``and, yes, this
seems strange because six months ago I was told I couldn't come
back. And now, it's yes I can come back. But this is life. I can't
explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga said he considered renouncing his December retirement, but
by then, the Revolution had signed goalkeeper Ian Feuer. The
Revolution seemed to be moving in the right direction as they
earned 10 points in the first seven games of this season. After 26
matches, though, they have only 20 points and are in last place in
the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga, 38, inspired the Revolution last year even when he was
limited by injuries, bringing the experience of nearly 20 years of
playing in European. The Revolution have greatly missed the
intangible qualities Zenga added. He compared MLS teams to the US
national team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the US in the World Cup,'' he said. ``They didn't play
badly. They were just missing a pizzico di furbizia (i.e. a little
cleverness, or smarts).
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it is the mentality, part of it is because of the
rules. For example, this is the only place in the world where ties
do not exist, so it's not in the mentality. In Europe, when we are
playing badly, we know how to play not to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga has continued to view the MLS from afar.
</P>
<P>
   ``D.C. United, as usual, is the best team, and Los Angeles is
playing very well,'' Zenga said. ``It looks like they could be the
best two teams, but Columbus is also playing very well and Kansas
City has the same players and is always difficult to play against.
Chicago is a new team that is playing well. Miami, I will see them
between now and Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga will meet the team for the first time this morning at
Babson College.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't talk about what the team needs,'' Zenga said. ``We
hope to do what we did last year, which was a miracle, winning in
the last minute of the last game.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Rongen's parting comments, he accused unnamed players of
sabotaging him, with speculation centering on the Revolution's
foreign players. ``I have nothing to say about Thomas because he is
no longer coach and it would be irrelevant to comment,'' midfielder
David Nakhid said. ``But if he does try to criticize me or hinder
my career in any way, I will take action. Otherwise, I have nothing
to say.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
