<SLUG> BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING ON THE DOG NOW IS ARNOLD'S JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hush Puppies have been worn by Tom Hanks and Susan Sarandon.
They've been photographed by Richard Avedon. And now the perfect
footwear complement to horned-rim glasses and polyester pants will
be promoted by Arnold Communications of Boston, New England's
largest ad agency.
</P>
<P>
   Hush Puppies, a division of Michigan-based Wolverine World Wide
Inc., said Thursday it picked Arnold to be its new ad agency partly
because of Arnold's work in helping to launch the updated version
of the Volkswagen Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Beetle, Hush Puppies is a brand with ``a tremendous
past,'' but one that needs to ``freshen up the franchise,'' said
Jeff Lewis, Hush Puppies vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   It will be up to Arnold, a subsidiary of Maryland-based Snyder
Communications Inc., to create ``breakthrough'' global
repositioning for a brand whose mascot is a famous basset hound.
</P>
<P>
   When new Hush Puppies ads from Arnold start breaking early next
year, will they use the dog?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' said Francis J. Kelly III, Arnold's chief
marketing officer and a managing partner.
</P>
<P>
   Doing for Hush Puppies what Arnold has done for the VW Beetle
could be a challenge. VW spends more than $100 million a year on
marketing in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Hush Puppies, in contrast, has a global advertising budget
estimated between $5 million and $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing Arnold after an informal ad agency review, Hush
Puppies ended its six-year relationship with its previous ad
agency, Bozell Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Asked the reason for switching agencies, Lewis said: ``It's a
difficult climate for the entire shoe industry.''
</P>
<P>
   To thrive in that climate Hush Puppies needs ads that are as
distinctive as Arnold's work for VW, and Bozell was not delivering,
Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   In creating a Hush Puppies campaign, the trick will be to come
up with ads that are ``respectful of the past, but also plug the
brand into how people live today,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   With its limited budget, the Hush Puppies account will only
partly compensate Arnold for the $40 million Century 21 ad account
the agency lost last week.
</P>
<P>
   But if Hush Puppies won't bulk up Arnold's bottom line, it will
give the agency a brand name with global recognition nearly as
great as the Nike swoosh or McDonald's golden arches.
</P>
<P>
   Hush Puppies has indeed enjoyed a storied career. When it
arrived on the scene in 1958, many men owned only two types of
shoes _ sneakers and wing-tips. Hush Puppies filled the gap in
between and, at one point, the brand boasted: ``We invented
casual.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people remember Hush Puppies as a single shoe model made of
pigskin suede. In truth, the Hush Puppies family includes several
lines and styles of shoes for men, women, and children.
</P>
<P>
   Some early models were named after employees' dogs. As a result,
a footwear aficionado could choose among the Duchess, the Bowzer,
or the Bozo as he or she decided which Hush Puppies style best
complemented the outfit du jour.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Hush Puppies Bozo was the preferred loafer of the
1950s hepcat and the '60s swinger, the fashion cachet of a once
proud shoe slowly began to erode.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1980s, Hush Puppies were viewed as more lame than tony.
In an unsuccessful attempt to convince sophisticates that they
should pad about pieds-a-terre and salons in pigskin suede, ads
from the era had the brand's canine mascot lapping Perrier from its
water dish.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '90s, Hush Puppies appeared to hit bottom.
</P>
<P>
   That's when ``a little company called Nike came in and rewrote
the rules for the shoe industry,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid 1990s, however, Hush Puppies enjoyed a sensational
comeback. Actor Hanks wore a pair for much of his acclaimed
performance in the movie ``Forrest Gump.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a New York couturier dyed Hush Puppies in Day-Glo colors to
accent his latest collection of designer duds, and suddenly purple
Hush Puppies were hotter than Hootie &AMP; the Blowfish.
</P>
<P>
   Wolverine, which had 1997 revenues of $665 million, does not
disclose sales for its Hush Puppies brand, but Lewis claims they
have taken a quantum leap from the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Now, said Kelly, it's up to Arnold to help sustain that growth
and create a ``brand buzz'' around Hush Puppies that's comparable
to the one made by VW's Beetle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
