<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7477 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-BLAIR-HNS &LR;      08-28 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BLAIR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND BLAIR PROFIT FROM EACH OTHER'S COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspaper   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ After President Clinton ordered cruise missile strikes
against alleged terrorist installations in Sudan and Afghanistan,
Britain's Prime Minister Tony Blair, as usual, was the first
foreign leader to back him.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister has forged such a close relationship with
Clinton in the 16 months since he won office that any hesitation on
his part in supporting the attacks might have led other European
chiefs to hold back too, with serious diplomatic repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Blair are firmly established as the No. 1 chums of
global politics. They are to the late 1990s what former President
Ronald Reagan and former British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
were to the 1980s: political partners who have given a special
personal ingredient to the so-called Anglo-American special
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The comparison stops there, of course. Thatcher and Reagan were
conviction politicians who genuinely shared a set of economic and
social principles they sought to translate into reality. If their
current successors in the White House and No. 10 Downing Street
have any real convictions, they've managed to keep them well out of
sight.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in an effort to give their partnership greater intellectual
substance, they are promoting what they call a ``third way'' as an
alternative to traditional leftist and conservative policies. Next
month in New York, they are holding a one-day conference with such
leaders as Italy's left-of-center prime minister, Romano Prodi. to
discuss the concept.
</P>
<P>
   Yet fundamentally, what Blair and Clinton have in common is an
opportunistic approach to politics and a single-minded
determination to keep the voters content, even if that means
switching their positions every couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from that, each keenly appreciates what he has to gain
from close association with the other.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's private life is as blameless as Clinton's is marred. So
from the president's viewpoint, it's good to have a personally
upright character like the British leader in his corner, standing
by his side at news conferences and praising his statesmanship in
glowing terms.
</P>
<P>
   If someone like Blair, after all, can so readily set Clinton's
sexual adventures to one side, how important can they be? Blair's
presence is a kind of character reference _ or so Clinton would
like the public to believe.
</P>
<P>
   However, the profit from the friendship isn't all on one side.
Blair's revamped Labor Party _ known as New Labor _ has tied its
banner to the notion that it is a transatlantic version of
Clinton's Democrats, with as much appeal to the middle class as to
its longtime labor union supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's close identification with Clinton, a leader who has won
two national elections, has helped to silence critics within his
own party. They hope that through the association with the man in
the White House, Blair also has discovered the formula for a string
of election triumphs.
</P>
<P>
   As long as each draws benefit from it, the Clinton-Blair idyll
will go on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 1349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
