<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASHVILLE CABLE OUTLET FINDS NEW ENGLAND AUDIENCE AT NHIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As president of The Nashville Network, the cable service known
mostly for auto racing and country music, David Hall has seen
viewership grow from 7 million homes in 1983 to 75 million last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Based on those Neilson numbers, TNN was higher-rated than CNBC,
E! Entertainment Television, ESPN2, and MTV, except on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Hall received anecdotal proof of that recently when TNN sent a
truck filled with T-shirts, baseball caps, and other paraphernalia
emblazoned with the TNN logo to New Hampshire International
Speedway in Loudon.
</P>
<P>
   As Hall tells the story, the merchandise trailor sold out of
goods in one afternoon. TNN sent another load, and that sold out
the next day. ``The guy called us and said that people were really
hungry for the TNN stuff, so we sent another load,'' Hall said.
``After he sold all of that stuff, he closed up the trailor and
drove off.''
</P>
<P>
   TNN has become a household name, largely because of its auto
racing broadcasts. The network will carry about 90 live events this
year, including tomorrow's NASCAR CMT Twin 100's from NHIS and
Sunday's Farm Aid on CMT 300 Winston Cup race, also from the Loudon
track. Both start at 1 p.m. Veteran Eli Gold will call the action,
with Buddy Baker and Dick Berggren.
</P>
<P>
   Hall knows that auto racing has become ``must-carry
programming'' for TNN, which last year was acquired by CBS. ``Those
races produce our highest ratings and ad sales,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for TNN's steady growth is that Hall saw his
niche and captured it. In a day when cable and over-the-air
networks are willing to spend billions of dollars on sports
properties such as professional football games, TNN focuses on auto
racing, fishing, and family entertianment. ``We are very proud
about that,'' Hall said. ``We don't put on programs with a lot of
violence or bad language.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall understands TNN's place in the television universe. ``When
the US invaded Iraq several years ago, some of out producers wanted
to know what we should have on for our viewers,'' he said. ``I told
them to tell our viewers to turn to CNN.''
</P>
<P>
   That attitude has helped TNN grow by about 15 percent each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly think we have to be cautious,'' Hall said. ``There
is only a certain amount of sports advertising dollars out there.
We can't slice and dice too much of that pie.''
</P>
<P>
   As it is now, however, motor sports is making money.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Clemens comeback?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, Roger Clemens told ESPN's Chris Meyers on
Wednesday that he would not rule out playing in Boston again.
Clemens didn't provide any details during his ``Up Close''
appearance, and Meyers didn't ask ... Ivan Robinson's 10-round
slugfest with Arturo Gotti last Saturday night earned HBO an 8.1
rating, the highest ``After Dark'' has earned this year. The rating
means Robinson's split-decision victory was seen in about 1.8
million homes ... Fox Sports this week unveiled a nightly update on
the home-run chase. ``Countdown to 62'' consists of 15-second
updates airing every night between 9:30 and 10, detailing the
latest developments in Mark McGwire's and Sammy Sosa's attempts to
break the Roger Maris's season record of 61 home runs. Each update
comes during a commercial break and provides video highlights ...
ESPN2 signed a deal to televise three Harlem Globetrotters games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
