<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-GORDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON, EVERNHAM MAKE FOR FAST FRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever since they met, some seven years ago at a Busch Grand
National test session at Charlotte Motor Speedway, it seems theirs
has been a beautiful friendship. Or rather, a fast friendship, with
emphasis on the ``fast.'' Jeff Gordon, the 27-year-old NASCAR
Winston Cup driver of the No. 24 Dupont-sponsored Chevrolet Monte
Carlo, and crew chief Ray Evernham, the point man for Rick
Hendrick's three-car stable, would not want it any other way.
</P>
<P>
   The reason this Dynamic Duo has come to be regarded as the most
successful collaboration of the '90s on the Winston Cup circuit is
a simple matter of chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing, because we clicked right from the start,'' said
Gordon, the two-time defending NASCAR Winston Cup champion who will
be at New Hampshire International Speedway this weekend to defend
his title in Sunday's Country Music Television 300. ``First time I
ever met him, he saw I could drive a race car and I saw he really
knew a lot about a race car, especially what I wanted in a race
car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray's never tried to tell me how to drive a car. He's not the
type of coach who says, `OK, you've got to do this or you've got to
do that.' He just recognizes maybe when I need a little boost or
when I need to be calmed down and lets me drive the car from there
on out.''
</P>
<P>
   Evernham, 41, has been the stabilizing force of Gordon's wildly
successful ride in the 24 car. He was the steward for Gordon's
first two Winston Cup titles in 1995, and in 1997, when Gordon won
a staggering $6,375,658, bolstered by the Winston Million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it means everything _ chemistry,'' Gordon said.
``There are steps along the way that builds that. It just doesn't
come automatic. It comes from good race cars, it comes from good
engines, it comes from good pit stops, and it just builds on each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, that confidence turns into great chemistry.
But once you have it, it seems like it stays with you for a while.
When you're down, that chemistry holds you together like glue and
never lets you give up. We work really well off each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon will enter Sunday's race with a 67-point lead over Mark
Martin in the Winston Cup standings. He has socked away $3,868,357
in a season that has included eight victories, including four in a
row to tie the modern record. Feeling ill and driving a backup that
admittedly was not one of the best cars in his stable, Gordon went
to Bristol, Tenn., last week trying to win his fifth in a row, but
he finished fifth behind winner Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel confident we're going to run good at a lot of tracks,''
said Gordon, who has won twice at NHIS _ in 1994 and in last year's
second Winston Cup whistlestop at the 1-mile oval. ``Right now, our
momentum really hasn't been broken or anything. We're still the
same team.''
</P>
<P>
   While their success on the track has forged a trust and a mutual
respect for each other's enormous talents, it's not as though
Gordon and Evernham are as inseperable as, say, Batman and Robin.
They are more like Felix Unger and Oscar Madison: complete
opposites.
</P>
<P>
   Evernham, a native of Keyport, N.J., is East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, a native Hoosier from Pittsboro, Ind., is Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   A motorhead through and through, Evernham is a lover of
motorcycles, cars, street rods, anything on wheels that's capable
of going fast.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, said Evernham, ``is a big stick and ball guy, and I'm
not,'' referring to the driver's passion for basketball and golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're friends, definitely,'' said Evernham. ``But we're not
friends like everybody thinks. We don't do things socially
together. We don't talk on the phone really much during the week.
We spend our time at the racetrack. It's like having a younger
brother, even though we're basically from two generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Evernham hailing from My Generation.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon from Generation Next.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good way to describe it,'' Gordon said. ``We just
have a lot of respect for each other. It's hard to describe the
relationship that we have, because we're definitely opposite types
of people. He's very organized and methodical about the way he does
things, and he's very intense about that race car and about that
race team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, I'm very intense when I get behind the wheel, but when I'm
not behind the wheel I'm very laidback and relaxed and just let
things kind of roll off my back. But I think his intensity really
makes me work harder and gets the most out of me and I think my
relaxed, laidback attitude kind allows him to get a little more
relaxed and enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Evernham, ``We get along real good and we respect one
another. I respect him and how he lives his life, and I think he
respects the way I live my life and how I do my job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a mutual respect more than anything. We're friends
because of that, not because we have a good time together or
anything. We don't. We're really opposites. If it weren't for the
race car, we probably wouldn't have ever hung out with one another.
The racing brought us together and it's the respect that keeps us
together.''
</P>
<P>
   What does the future for the Dynamic Duo? It seems the next
logical step would be to become partners in their own Winston Cup
team.
</P>
<P>
   But Evernham cuationed, ``I just don't want to be a car owner.
If I wanted to do that, I could do it right now. The ideal
situation would be if I could grow into ownership or part-ownership
here at Hendrick Motorsports. I want to be part of a multicar
operation that has the capablity to dominate the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be the owner of a Winston Cup car that ran 10th to 15th
every week, that doesn't interest me. But to be involved with Rick
and Jeff and other people _ I'd rather have a small percentage of
something big that can win races than be 100 percent owner of
something that really doesn't have a shot at winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that would hinge on Gordon's involvement in the
venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we are partners right now,'' said Gordon. ``If
that were to continue to go to another level and it'd involve
Hendrick Motorsports, then I'd definitely be for it. For us to go
off on our own and try to own and build a team the caliber of
Hendrick Motorsports would be like taking a step backwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as long as we're happy and are able to win races and
championships and get what we want, like we do at Hendrick
Motorsports, then I don't see us going anywhere or wanting to do
anything else. But I can definitely tell you we'd like to be more
involved with Hendrick Motorsports if that opportunity ever came
up. But I just feel like any time I'm in a race car, I want it to
be involved with Ray.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we definitely recognize that we do amazing things
together, and we can continue to do that as long as we stick
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Which was the plan from the very start.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
