<HEADLINE>
ALLEGORY OF A KANSAS TOWN PAINTS NO PLACE LIKE HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
NOW IT'S TIME TO SAY GOOD-BYE 
By Dale Peck 
Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, 458 pp., $25 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dale Peck's ``Now It's Time To Say Good-bye'' is a strong stew
of a novel, and its ingredients are unlikely companions _ baroque
inventiveness, Jacobean tragedy, gothic grotesquerie, American
regional realism, &UR;  &LR; the postmodern European novel, &UR;  &LR; ``Dr.
Strangelove,'' ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil,'' and
Stephen King, more literate but hardly kinder, gentler.
</P>
<P>
   Peck, the author of two previous, highly praised novels, ``The
Law of Enclosures'' and ``Martin and John,'' has set this one in
Kansas, where he grew up. The town is Galatia (it's on the map,
although Cadavera County is not), an African-American town that has
now been taken over by Galatea, a white community that moved in
when nearby Kenosha burned down.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the town and of its people is told in a polyphony
of many voices, some of them speaking out of turn, and at least one
from beyond the grave. Justin Time and his lover Colin Nieman have
fled to Kansas; they are burnt out by the AIDS epidemic in New York
_ 500 of their friends have died. Their Kansas connection is a
painter named Wade Painter, who keeps company with a black hustler
who works the local truckstop and calls himself Divine. The
formidable Rosemary Krebs likes to think she runs the town; the
minister Abraham Greeving is the custodian of its history.
Greeving's daughter Webbie has come home to take care of him, but
yearns for escape.
</P>
<P>
   The town is full of hostile divisions of sexual identity and
race, and everyone seems to have a past and a secret. ``What every
prostitute learns sooner or later,'' Justin, who has been a
prostitute himself observes, ``is that most people have only one
secret, and that secret is whom they truly love.'' There has been a
lynching; before the townspeople have finished telling their
stories there has been rape, other couplings violent and tender,
arson, severed thumbs and fingertips, and several murders. The pigs
have feasted on a man, been shot, and served in a barbecue on
Founder's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Law and order are represented by the mayor, Rosemary Krebs's
ineffectual husband, by the overweight mailman who eats a dozen
eggs for breakfast (cooked in a quarter-inch of bacon fat), and by
the literal minded Sheriff Eustace (Lawman) Brown. Art imposes
different forms of order. Colin writes a novel about the town, and
Wade has drawn and painted the town and its residents most of his
life. Justin, it turns out, wrote Colin's most famous book, and
begins to paint by reproducing some of Wade's drawings. There are
also magical forces at work in the land.
</P>
<P>
   Justin appears to be the presiding consciousness; at least he
introduces the story and survives its end. But after he witnesses a
brutal rape and survives an attack, he falls silent for most of the
rest of the book _ but not before delivering a Joycean vision to
the baffled Lawman Brown. ``He finished with Lucy, finished her,
ruined her, ended her, he lifted her to the sky and he showed her
to me and he showed himself to me and showed me to me, he showed us
all ourselves and then he fell on me, he did and Lucy did, Lucy who
was in his arms and I who was on the ground and then I was gone,
and when I opened my eyes he was gone, and Lucy was gone, and I was
gone again, and gone forever.''
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to know what to make of ``Now It's Time To Say
Good-bye.'' It is horrifing and funny and then too funny to be
horrifying, or too horrifying to amuse. It is fiercely compelling
and profoundly unpleasant. It is a virtuoso technical exercise that
is also soul-music.. Kansas is as real as a town on a map and far
more fantastic than Oz _ we're not in Kansas any more, but in the
farthest reaches of the human psyche. The author's dedication
prefigures the tone of the novel: ``I wouldn't wish this book on
anyone, except maybe (a couple of friends).'' There is no place
that Dale Peck is afraid to go, but what he takes for granted about
human nature is just as astonishing. He does show us all of
ourselves, even if we don't want to believe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 1356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
