<HEADER>
A7500 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-CHAMBERMAID-BOS     08-28 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CHAMBERMAID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHAMBERMAID' IGNITES IMAGINATION WITH FANTASY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE CHAMBERMAID 
Directed by: Bigas Luna 
Screenplay by: Luna, Cuca Canals, Jean-Louis Benoit (novel: Didier
Decoin) 
Starring: Romane Bohringer, Olivier Martinez, Aitana Sanchez-Gijon,
Didier Bezace, Aldo Maccione 
Running time: 96 minutes 
Rating: Unrated 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bigas Luna's ``The Chambermaid'' won't be seen by more than a
small fraction of the worldwide audience for James Cameron's
``Titanic.'' But of the two films with a Titanic motif, it's the
one to see. Where Cameron's film was pulp fiction, Luna's far more
imaginative work expands as it toys with the notion of what art is
and how it comes about. Its two lovers only spend a night together,
and may or may not have had sex. And they never board the doomed
liner. They only join the dockside crowd seeing it off from
Southampton. But those tendrils of circumstance are all Luna and
his cast need to spin a beguiling tale about imagination ignited by
fantasy and longing.
</P>
<P>
   It begins in a grimy French factory town in 1912, with Olivier
Martinez's foundry worker named Horty winning a race and receiving
as first prize a ticket to Southampton and a hotel room there so he
can see the Titanic depart. The catch is that there's only one
ticket, and the boss has his eye on Martinez's pretty wife, Zoe
(Romane Bohringer). With misgivings, Horty leaves. No sooner has he
settled into his hotel room than there's a knock on the door. When
he opens it, a beautiful woman asks him to come to her rescue.
</P>
<P>
   She's a chambermaid on the Titanic (the film's original title),
she tells him. But before she can report for duty the next morning,
the woman named Marie (Aitana Sanchez-Gijon) needs a place to sleep
and all the hotels are full. Horty gives her his bed, which she
offers to share. Is the love scene that follows the real thing or a
dream? We're not quite sure. All we see is the two of them leave
the next morning and make their way toward the great ocean liner.
En route, Horty has Marie photographed.
</P>
<P>
   When he returns home, Zoe, who also works at the foundry, tells
him she has been promoted. Suspicious and angry, he storms off and
takes to drinking with his cronies. When he hears that the Titanic
has sunk, he produces the photograph of Marie, and begins
embellishing the story of their night together. By the time he's
through, he has everyone believing they enjoyed a night of mad
passion on the liner itself. The story plays well _ except to Zoe.
It attracts crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Horty finds himself attached to a traveling troupe as its
romantic troubadour. He tells Zoe the story of grand doomed passion
is fiction, but the more he reassures her, the less she believes
him. Now it's her turn to be jealous. Deftly, Bigas Luna works his
way around to an unpredictable and satisfying climax, but while the
external events of ``The Chambermaid'' are engrossing, the thing
that gives it resonance is its meditation on the ways of
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Does Horty's story represent the prostitution of experience? Or
do his distortions add up to an artist's fusing of desire and
inspiration? Is artistic creation a lie that tells deeper truths
than facts alone can tell? The film is too securely rooted in its
characters and Bigas Luna's hand is too sophisticated to ever allow
his film to evaporate into an arid philosophical debate. We always
feel there's a lot riding on the way events transpire here. But the
playfulness with which the larger issues dance alongside them is
what makes ``The Chambermaid'' the elegant and altogether
stimulating delight it is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 1356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7501 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-WHYDO-BOS &LR;      08-28 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WHYDO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SKIN-DEEP LOOK AT DOO-WOP STAR LYMON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
WHY DO FOOLS FALL IN LOVE 
Directed by: Gregory Nava 
Screenplay by: Tina Andrews 
Starring: Halle Berry, Viveca Vivica A. Fox, Lela Rochon, Larenz
Tate, Little Richard, Paul Mazursky 
Running time: 115 minutes 
Rated: R (language and some sexuality) 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love,'' pushing off from the short,
chaotic life of doo-wop single-hit-sensation Frankie Lymon, plays
like a posthumous ``Waiting to Exhale.'' It's filled with color and
energy. The musical stagings, including the title song, are on the
money, especially when the real-life Little Richard does his thing.
The leads deliver performances of size and pop icon dimension. But
the film, like Lymon's life, can't conceal the fact that it's a bit
of a hodge-podge that never really illuminates its subject,
settling instead for lively iconography.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gregory Nava's film is more ambitious than the usual
Hollywood biopic. It begins where most other biopics end, years
after Lymon's death from a heroin overdose at 25, when Diana Ross
cuts a version of Lymon's big hit that gives the film its name, and
it's realized that there's still a lot of money to be made in
royalties. The fun begins when one widow surfaces, then a second,
then a third.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, they're fighting it out in court to see who gets
the money _ assuming they can pry it away from Paul Mazursky's
record label owner who stole most of it with the ball point pen he
used to persuade the naive Lymon to sign his rights away. If
nothing else, the film makes abundantly clear that Lymon got the
girls while Mazursky's sleazeball got the money. And not only did
Lymon get the girls. He married them, heedless of the legalities
involved.
</P>
<P>
   The question of who his legal widow might be is complicated by
the fact that two of the women left a few legal strings untied
themselves. As the two more flamboyant ones, Halle Berry and Vivica
J. Fox have the most fun and are the most fun to watch. Berry
enjoys a stretch as Zola Taylor, the singer who as a member of The
Platters was just as prominent as Lymon, lasted longer, and
survived Frankie leaving her broke. Fox strikes off into new
territory, too, as the second wife, who loved Frankie enough after
his career fell apart to turn to prostitution when his drug habit
took over.
</P>
<P>
   Lela Rochon's third wife, a Georgia schoolteacher Frankie met
and charmed while in the service after being drafted, could have
fallen into the goody-two-shoes trap. But she projects enough
strength of her own to make the other two realize she's a
formidable opponent, too. Larenz Tate's Frankie, who broke through
in 1955 at the age of 13, is persuasive as the charismatic little
guy who charmed all three on his way to trigamy and worse.
</P>
<P>
   But Tina Andrews's script never really gets under Frankie's skin
to convince us we're seeing him portrayed from the inside. We never
feel the rush of Frankie's instant stardom, followed by his pain
and bewilderment as he slides downhill, unable to know what to do
to stop it, or how to find in his offstage life the kind of high he
feels onstage. The women are much better at portraying survival
skills than pain, and the film is juiciest when it finally lets
them interact. Certainly, it's dynamic and colorful and winningly
performed.
</P>
<P>
   It's also candid about the way record biz execs ripped off their
singers (Mazursky's larcenous exploiter wisely is played in low-key
style) and wryly ironic about the way the court case plays out. But
in the end it never gives us a more than emblematic look at Lymon.
Nava's skill at image-making is richly and, when it has to be,
garishly apparent. But ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love'' plays like a
series of postcards from the heady rise and fall of teen singing
sensation Lymon _ and from the exhilaration and suffering caused by
his sad rudderlessness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 1358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
