<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7502 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV30-BO     08-28 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV30-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NISSAN FRONTIER A YEAR OLD AND ALREADY CHANGED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, August 30, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R.WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frontier, introduced as a 1998 model, is a simple truck from
Nissan _ actually a line of simple little pickups, starting with
the standard cab equipped with basic 5-speed manual transmission,
rear-drive, and a four-cylinder engine with a sticker price under
$12,000. With the $470 delivery charge, it works out to $12,460 to
put a bottom-feeder Nissan Frontier in your driveway _ and there
isn't much dicker in that sticker. The dealer markup reflected in
that price is hardly enough to make it worthwhile taking it off the
delivery truck and mounting the hubcaps.
</P>
<P>
   The line spirals upward from there, ascending a series of steps
reflecting increased equipment, power, size, price _ and dealer
profit potential; you can have 4WD, king cab, automatic
transmission, V-6 engine, lots of bells and whistles, yet the top
sticker is still under $21K. This now; stand by for changes.
</P>
<P>
   With the '99 model year, that Standard model disappears in favor
of a new base XE grade, presumably priced somewhat more than the
old Standard but less than the '98 XE $13,190 bottom model.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, I met and liked the 1998 4-cylinder version
of Frontier; lately I have had more time in a top-of-the-line SE
4WD King Cab _ a '99 with the 170-horsepower V-6, four-speed
automatic gearbox, air conditioning, and all the ... well, this SE
didn't have all the bells and whistles. In '98, the SE came with
power mirrors, power locks, and power windows; the '99 SE came with
armstrong power _ manual window cranks and manual locks. The
mirrors appeared to be the power option, but, if so, somebody had
neglected to install the power control. One had to resort to
``digital'' control _ pushing with the fingers.
</P>
<P>
   The '99 sample is a prototype, not a production model.
Prototypes come through with the latest in what's new, but
sometimes the carryover stuff, the equipment that remains
unchanged, suffers in the rush to build the prototype _ whatever's
handy gets installed. That was my theory, anyway, but the fact is
that the SE for '99 comes standard with all that manual stuff.
Power windows, locks, mirrors and remote entry are offered as an
optional ``Power Package'' in '99.
</P>
<P>
   The prototype, by the way, isn't certified, can't be registered,
and so can't be sold; this nifty little truck will likely end its
brief career in a crusher, although some prototype vehicles wind up
in schools as teaching aids.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of offering this prototype for evaluation was to
give the writer a sense of the powertrain, that new V-6 engine in
particular. My sense is that this sparsely trimmed little truck,
after driving a long string of luxury-oriented vehicles and a
couple of heavy hauler trucks, was akin to a refreshing glass of
seltzer after too much rich food _ oh what a relief it was.
</P>
<P>
   Incipient arthritis does make a manual window crank a bit more
than a nuisance, and I recommend remote locking devices for
safety's sake, but the whole of the truck just set right, felt
good. The engine is powerful in this modest-sized vehicle, offers
good acceleration, decent torque to start a load moving, and
certainly wasn't overwhelmed by the juice drive.
</P>
<P>
   The handling was good for a light truck, improves somewhat with
a load. The light rear of an empty pickup naturally wants to come
around to meet the grille in very hard braking, and a high center
of gravity sets the Frontier to leaning on sharp turns. But the
Frontier behaved rather well; the rear end never did swing out, and
although the feeling of security became a little tentative as
centrifugal force tried to push it over in the hard corners, no
wheels lifted from the pavement, and the track was true to the
steering desired.
</P>
<P>
   Air conditioning is standard on the SE, and the air conditioner
in this baby, prototype or not, was Chill City, a most welcome bit
of comfort on a hot, sticky day. The glove box is minuscule. Two
key-shaped cupholders lie between the armrest _ which conceals a
square, covered bin _ and the shifter; the holders have removable
rubber inserts. Another pair sits behind the bin for the rear
passengers _ as if they will have room to drink.
</P>
<P>
   The King Cab, in this writer's opinion, is overstating the case
for room. If this be royal room, it might rank as earl or baron,
but king it is not. Jump seats fold out from the sides of the
truck; you sit with your knees facing the other passenger, and
you'd best be small passengers on a short trip. But, with the seats
folded up out of the way, there is room to put a lot of stuff
behind the front seats _ the seats slide forward to provide fairly
easy access to that rear room. Bring the tuba, the tools, the gun
rack, and fishing tackle _ I'd estimate six cases of wine fit back
there, or a couple of trunks.
</P>
<P>
   The cargo box was fitted with the optional $299 bedliner, and
tiedown loops were easily accessible through cutouts _ they are in
the corners near the top of the box. Towing capacity with the V-6,
by the way, is 5,000 pounds _ nice truck for hauling a small boat.
Fuel mileage worked out to a hair better than 19 miles per gallon
over about 560 miles measured.
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of pickup trucks out there in a variety of sizes.
I can't tell you this is the best of the lot _ it isn't _ but I can
tell you that it's a very good light truck, and this particular
rendition hit me right. I really, really liked it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For the on-line browsers, I'll be available to chat on line
about cars Tuesdays, 2 p.m. to 3 p.m. Just point your Internet
browser to http://www.boston.com and enter the keyword chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
