<SLUG> BC-COMEDY-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLINS CRAFTS HIS COMEDY INSIDE AND OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bobby Collins grew up eating baloney sandwiches and powdered
milk in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was brought up on baloney and liverwurst _ I actually
thought liverwurst was real meat,'' he says from his home on Long
Island where he's putting the finishing touches on some new
material. ``It's the kind of food that gives you a heart attack
before you even finish the sandwich.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins, who was named Bobby after Bob Hope, is a throwback
comedian defined, in some way, by what he doesn't do. He doesn't
string jokes together or deliver them like he was shooting the
enemy with a submachine gun. He's not a shock guy, using vulgarity
to hammer home a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, his material is adult without being offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a kid we used to watch Red Skelton and I looked
over at my father on the couch laughing at Skelton and I thought,
even then, how much I'd like to make people laugh,'' says Collins,
who understood early on that no matter what the economic
circumstances, a good laugh is a good laugh. ``I thought if I could
do that I could be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Is he?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yea, I'm about as happy as you can get in this crazy
business,'' says the comic commentator whose CD, ``On the Inside,''
was nominated for an Emmy last year. He lost out to his good
friend, Jeff Foxworthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot opening for people,'' he says. ``I opened for
Sinatra, Julio Iglesias, and Cher,'' he says. ``The best. Not
because of the way they entertained _ although that was great, too
_ but because of the way they acted. The way they got rid of their
own egos. Some entertainers love to berate musicians at rehearsals.
I don't want to mention any names, but I also opened for Dolly
Parton. Anyway, when Julio or Cher or Frank wanted to make a point,
they always waited until an appropriate time and took the person
aside. It was a sign that they didn't need to berate others to make
themselves seem big.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Collins's angles is to describe the inside and outside of
a particular situation. For example, his wife wants to go shopping
to Sam's Club. Outside, Collins is saying something like, ``Yes,
dear.'' Inside, he's saying, ``Shopping? Shopping sucks.''
</P>
<P>
   While Collins has been under contract for situation comedies on
the major networks, he's not as interested in making it on
television as he used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, riding around on the corporate jet and making the
big money is appealing,'' he says. ``But they make you do things
you don't want to do. I'm working on one now, but I won't do it
unless I have the ability to change material and cast the show and
have my hand in it. I'm perfectly happy coming in for a weekend and
making 15 grand. What's wrong with that?''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly beats baloney and liverwurst.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly does,'' says Collins. ``And it's my own material.
It's a great job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
