<HEADER>
A7519 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-54-BOS &LR;      08-28 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-54-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MECCA OF COOL TURNS OUT LUKEWARM IN `54' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
54 
Directed and written by: Mark Christopher 
Starring: Ryan Phillippe, Mike Myers, Salma Hayek, Breckin Meyer,
Neve Campbell, Sela Ward, Ellen Dow, Sherry Stringfield, Heather
Matarazzo 
Rated: R (sexuality, drug use and language) 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``54'' isn't the film it should have been, but it's easy enough
to watch _ which is one of the reasons it isn't the film it should
have been. Essentially, it's a pared-down piece of soft-centered
nostalgia for a glittery era that went into overdrive, then
self-destructed. The story of the social forces swirling around
Studio 54, Manhattan's foremost anything-goes disco of the '70s,
calls for nothing less than the multi-skeined bite of a
``Nashville.'' What we get is more like ``Noshville.'' The cursory,
perfunctory ``54'' doesn't bite off nearly enough. The smallish
morsel it does settle for too readily accepts at face value Steve
Rubell's smiling declaration that he just wanted to ``throw the
best damned party the world has ever seen and make it last
forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Myers's portrayal of Rubell, who parlayed a steakhouse in
Brooklyn into the '70s mecca of cool, is the best thing in the
film. Like most good comics, his mimetic skills and timing are on
the money, especially when he's stoned and blissfully invites the
attentions of the IRS and other government agencies by not
bothering to conceal money-skimming and on-site drug dealing. When
one patron ODs and dies on the dance floor, Rubell mutters
something about having lost a friend, rationalizes her death away
by declaring that she couldn't handle her drugs, then switches his
attention to what really mattered most to him at the moment, namely
that Princess Grace, spotted on the premises, shouldn't be kept
waiting for drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Myers's Rubell floats druggily in and out of sexual confusion,
making a pass at a waiter as his bodyguard hauls him, all but
passed out, home to his bed. When the young working class waiter
awkwardly tries to fend off the pass by declaring that he isn't
gay, Myers's Rubell, replies, just before literally vomiting on his
money, ``Oh! Labels.'' But Rubell could not have been as
consistently oblivious as the film makes him out to be in,
presumably, its desire to stay away from darker areas so the
central character would appear more viewer-friendly. Leaving the
central theme largely unexplored in its rush to boil things down to
a personalized temptation story, it's left to a voiceover to
explain that Rubell was the first to notice the switch to a
celebrity culture. He made access to the club raise Manhattan's
collective anxiety level, by granting entry only to those deemed
cool enough to hurdle the velvet rope.
</P>
<P>
   We're told Rubell enjoyed power-tripping on the right side of
the rope, reminding the doorman who really was boss. Here, he's
mostly a pussycat, spacy, cuddly, smiling his toothy, lopsided
smile mostly to himself, guilty only of carelessness. This softens
the conflict, simplistically corny as it is, between bright lights
and the sentimentalized solid moral values of the working class, as
personified by Ryan Phillippe's refugee from Jersey City, Shane
O'Shea. Shane can't believe his good fortune when he's admitted to
the club after his friends are excluded, then gets a job as a
waiter, then a bartender. Celeb status rubs off on him, and it goes
to his head. The film plays like a cleaned-up version of ``The
Rake's Progress,'' taking place over 10 different nights during
which, presumably, the fate of Shane's tarnished but essentially
pure soul will be decided.
</P>
<P>
   He's flanked by another salt-of-the-earth working-class couple,
Breckin Meyer's waiter and Salma Hayek's coat check girl hoping to
use the job as a launch pad to a singing career. Meanwhile, the
parade of jaded decadents weaves through the place, occasionally
nibbling at the newcomer with the curly hair and the highly defined
and visible abs. Phillippe does little to indicate a quantum leap
beyond hunk du jour status. True, Shane mostly just stands around
with his face hanging out, wondering first what to make of it all,
then wondering how to exploit it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he doesn't leap off the screen the way Mark Wahlberg's
very similar character did in ``Boogie Nights,'' which bathed the
porn industry in the same rosy glow that this film bathes the disco
sniffery. He's handsome, but so expressionless that it's not yet
possible to tell what he can do. But he's hot enough to have been
cast in at least three upcoming films, so we'll soon know more.
Considering that he last was seen hanging on the wrong end of a
steel hook in ``I Know What You Did Last Summer,'' this role
represents, one supposes, advancement.
</P>
<P>
   The woman of Shane's dreams, partly because she made it out of
New Jersey to become a soap opera regular, is played by Neve
Campbell, who raises the film's wholesomeness quotient. But it's
Myers's face, smiling a zonked-out smile that presumably takes its
cue from the club's hanging sculpture of the man in the moon and
the big cocaine spoon suspended beside him, that you remember from
the hazy, glossed-over ``54.'' Writer-director Mark Christopher is
much better at making images than he is at writing, or filling
those images with emotional impact or a sardonic point of view. No
edge or danger comes off the screen. The whole of ``54'' hasn't a
fraction of the wit in any five minutes of Whit Stillman's less
lurid but more poignant ``The Last Days of Disco.'' In short,
there's more fizzle than fizz in this slick-looking but superficial
excursion. If the atmosphere was as benign as it is here, what was
all the fuss about?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
