<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7521 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-28 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEO INTERVIEWS MAY HAVE BEEN JUST A FAD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three years ago, college recruiters were abuzz over new
technology that would allow them to conduct closed-circuit job
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   With the technology, companies could interview prospective
employees thousands of miles away without having to incur the
expense of traveling to a campus, staying in a hotel and buying
meals.
</P>
<P>
   But the trend never caught on. Only a few companies invested in
the technology. And many employers still want to shake an
applicant's hand.
</P>
<P>
   It's surprising, said David Small, who expected real-time video
interviewing would be the wave of the future. Small, director of
career services at the University of Houston, invested $5,000 in
equipment that made the University of Houston a virtual pioneer
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Today, only about four or five students each semester use the
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   It's a similar story at the University of Texas at El Paso.
Students use the video equipment about 10 times a year, said Briane
Carter, director of career services.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said universities were quick to jump on the trend because
they tend to embrace technology. Private companies, on the other
hand, aren't quite so fast to adopt, especially human resource
departments that drive much of the initial recruiting efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Human resources officials also are not the final employment
decision makers, Carter said, and line managers don't take kindly
to the idea that they can't meet prospective employees
face-to-face.
</P>
<P>
   That said, there are areas in which video interviewing is taking
off. Organizations that already have sophisticated technology in
place and are used to communicating electronically with other
offices have adapted their technology for video interviewing,
Carter said. School districts, for example, have adapted equipment
they own to communicate with schools.
</P>
<P>
   And government agencies accustomed to technology, such as the
Defense Department and intelligence-related agencies, use their
equipment to interview candidates for short-term internships and to
initially screen job applicants, she said.
</P>
<P>
   John Hannabach thinks it's too early to write the obituary for
video interviewing. Hannabach, director of career services at
Georgia Tech in Atlanta, estimates that 50 to 60 companies across
the nation are using their computer equipment for video
interviewing but many more could easily adapt the technology they
are already using to conduct on-camera meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Hannabach speculates that video interviewing really will take
off when the economy turns down. Video interviews are cheap, he
said. With some systems, the cost is nothing more than a
long-distance phone call.
</P>
<P>
   But some recruiters who have used video interviewing in the past
aren't too sure it's anything more than a passing fancy.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Howze, managing director of the Alexander Group in Houston,
has interviewed job candidates by video when she's been under a
tight time deadline. But it's not very satisfying, she said.
</P>
<P>
   A recruiter's job is to entice a job candidate to consider the
recruiter's client as a good place to work, Howze said. ``It's hard
to sell people over a TV set,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And it was expensive, said Howze, who went to a copy shop in her
neighborhood that had the technology and paid about $350 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Howze said her company will be installing equipment next year so
all four offices can communicate with one another. That will make
it easier and cheaper to do video interviewing, but Howze still
prefers a personal visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I don't get a good handle on a candidate,'' she
said, adding that there is a little delay between words and
movement on the screen, which makes the experience disconcerting.
``You can tell a lot about somebody from a handshake.''
</P>
<P>
   While video interviewing hasn't exactly taken off, it's a good
recruiting tool for the university, Small said. Parents and
students like the fact that the university has the capability for
video interviewing.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said that having the technology lets employers interview
at El Paso who wouldn't normally come to the university to
interview. It opens up new career opportunities for students, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   So if some of the experts are right and video interviewing
really catches on later, here are a few tips from Carter to make
the best presentation:
</P>
<P>
   _ Try the system out ahead of time to get used to any delay in
sound transmission. That way, you'll be more relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   _ If the walls behind you are pale, wear something bright to
stand out.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't wear anything distracting such as wiggly earrings. And
keep yourself from waving your arms around as you talk.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't forget to smile.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR; XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
