<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BAUHAUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK FROM THE GRAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The band committed euthanasia 15 years ago, and the first wave
of black-clad goths wept and wailed. The band's first single,
released back in 1979, was ``Bela Lugosi's Dead'' and four years
later Bauhaus had followed Lugosi to the grave.
</P>
<P>
   Except ... well, you know how it is with the undead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The former members of the London-based Bauhaus moved on. For
guitarist Daniel Ash, bassist David J, and drummer Kevin Haskins,
this initially meant Tones on Tail, later Love &AMP; Rockets; for
singer Peter Murphy, this meant a solo career. There were successes
and failures for each, Love &AMP; Rockets actually hitting the Top 5
with the song ``So Alive'' and Murphy scoring most effectively with
his ``Deep'' album.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the years, says J, reunion offers were dangled in
front of Bauhaus, but the band members resisted. ``We hadn't felt
the artistic compulsion to get on and do it,'' he says. ``It never
seemed thrilling, and we had other commitments.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, they finally opened the tomb, dusted themselves off,
and climbed out. A best-of CD, ``Crackle,'' was being released.
They reunited for an unannounced club gig in Los Angeles at the
Hollywood Athletic Club. They announced two more reunion dates and
both sold out in 15 minutes. A third date was added and sold out
that same day. More than 11,000 tickets gone in a flash. The guys
went ``Hmmmm ...''
</P>
<P>
   Now it's a tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing shows we never imagined we could,'' says Murphy.
``It's not like a revue, it's a resurrection. It's a band that
feels like we split a couple of weeks ago, in terms of musicality
and how it feels. It's really theater, this show. We're refining
it. I think sometimes it gets out of control, but that's OK. That's
part of what's unexpected about the Bauhaus experience. Pure
theater is really about being in the moment. Rehearsal and the
shape of the script is one thing, but the actual acting is the
art.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauhaus emerged as English punk rock was going down in flames
for the first time. The post-punk movement Bauhaus was part of
offered something more brooding and despairing. Murphy was, and
remains, the high-cheekboned, Bowie-esque singer, the frontman who
makes the gestures. The others are relatively inert. Bauhaus's key
songs include ``She's in Parties,'' ``Kick in the Eye,'' ``Silent
Hedges,'' and ``Burning From the Inside.'' The music has an aura of
dark celebration about it. There's a certain, if submerged pop
sensibility, and a steely electronic-cum-industrial feeling. Angst
and melodrama factor in substantially. It has roots in
glam/art-rock, as seen in band covers of Bowie's ``Ziggy
Stardust,'' T.Rex's ``Telegram Sam,'' and Brian Eno's ``Third
Uncle.''
</P>
<P>
   Why is the time right now to reform?
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we collectively feel,'' says J, ``is that the cultural
climate is just right. It's primed for it. Stylistically, there is
an atmosphere that runs through music, through fashion, through
films, that is very influenced by a kind of awareness (of Bauhaus).
It's a kind of dark romanticism that's also, in our case, a
connection with German expressionism, art and film. That was really
a big influence on Bauhaus as a group. We just felt very
enthusiastic about the prospect of getting together. It was
suddenly exciting, intoxicating, the idea of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Resurrection tour only plays six cities. Is it fun?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Dan is calling it a lot of fun,'' says Murphy, of Ash.
``That seems to be his description.'' Fun is a somewhat ironic word
in Bauhaus's dark world.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's always a very weighty thing to go on tour,''
Murphy continues. ``Not only physically but in terms of putting on
a show. That's the way I am. There's a lot of heart and warmth and
giving in it, but it's also very very serious in a way, too. It's
actually very Bauhaus, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bauhaus is always highly volatile,'' says J, who has made his
home in Pepperill, Mass. for the last three years. (He is soon
moving to LA.) ``It had a highly combustible chemistry. And that
was necessary to make it spark, make it happen. But it was also
part of why it actually came apart. We were still on good terms,
but in 1983, the idea of us continuing to work together was
impossible because it had become so fracturous.''
</P>
<P>
   Ego clash?
</P>
<P>
   ``The ego was not absent,'' says J.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't, personally, a bitter split,'' maintains Murphy.
``It was a split based on having burnt ourselves out. We were very
young in the sense that we didn't know how to deal with the power
we were conjuring up. And, also, there were a lot of creative ideas
in the band that weren't being expressed at the individual level.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ash, back in 1984, on tour in Boston with Tones on Tail, said,
``We got fed up with each other ... we're not the best of
friends.'')
</P>
<P>
   The band released four studio albums during its first life. As
it was dissolving, the band's manager inquired if any of the
parties wished to continue under the Bauhaus name. Both camps found
that idea abhorrent, says Murphy. They would risk new bands and new
sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all extremely strong individuals with strong ideas,'' he
says, ``and our chemistry was about the pushing and pulling of
those ideas. It's not democratic in that sense. I mean I'm very
much a leader and I know what doesn't work. I have a strong sense
of aesthetics and theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Nostalgia is anathema to any self-respecting modern rocker _
artist or fan. Murphy is no exception. ``It's not a desperate
return to the past,'' he maintains. ``It isn't nostalgic in that
we're only living in the moment. It's very vital now. For many of
those in the audience, they've attached themselves to Bauhaus in
such a powerful way, in successive generations, and that's been
another phenomenon about us.''
</P>
<P>
   Love &AMP; Rockets releases a moody, brilliant album ``Lift'' next
month, a striking comeback from their turgid last effort ``Sweet
F.A.'' Murphy is in the midst of recording and will release a solo
album early next year. Is there a future for Bauhaus in all this?
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I'm feeling now, I just really want a long sleep,''
says Murphy, with a laugh. ``I couldn't imagine doing an album. But
I'm not really sure. I mean, when Bauhaus is on _ and this is one
of the things I'm certain about _ Bauhaus is a very unique band ...
and I think we've got albums in us.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the playing, says J, the dynamics of old are still there,
but ``we're playing the songs so much better, 'cause we've had 15
years of playing solidly. Our heads are a lot more clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking forward to this open-air event,'' says J of the
Harborlights show. ``Bauhaus is not, obviously, an outdoorsy kind
of group. I was hoping it was going to be a full moon, but the it's
the night before the full moon so I think we're going to make it
into something of a pagan rite.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy resents it when Bauhaus is portrayed in a cliched goth
manner, but he can still relate to the old ethic. ``The goths are
beautiful,'' he says, ``a vast depth of subcultural, aesthetic, and
poetic ideas, and we would identify with that as we did back in
1979. But not the post-modern distortion ... the costume without
the brain.''
</P>
<P>
   For the goths, young and old, says J, the reunion tour ``is an
opportunity for them to hold their hand over the source of the fire
and feel the heat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
