<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-FRIENDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR `FRIENDS &AMP; NEIGHBORS,' LIAISONS WITH CYNICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
YOUR FRIENDS &AMP; NEIGHBORS 
Directed and written by: Neil La Bute 
Starring: Amy Brenneman, Aaron Eckhardt, Catherine Keener,
Nastassja Kinski, Jason Patric, Ben Stiller 
Running time: 100 minutes 
Rated: R (graphic sexual dialogue, strong sexuality and language) 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although his filmmaking career has barely begun, Neil LaBute is
already the undisputed master of the feel-bad movie. ``Your Friends
&AMP; Neighbors'' doesn't generate as much withering misyogny as his
jolting debut film, ``In the Company of Men.'' Artifice keeps
breaking into its roundelay of savage sexual game-playing. Still,
as the dying Mercurtio said of the sword shoved between his ribs,
'twill do. In LaBute's first film, two rage-driven corporate execs
joined forces to sexually humiliate a deaf woman office worker.
``Your Friends &AMP; Neighbors'' expands the list of players to six in
a comedy of contemporary urban sexual self-immolation.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say what the six are making as they lurch from bed
to bed, but it isn't love, unless you regard self-regard as a
branch of it. The bleak lovelessness, and the humor that LaBute
amazingly is able to wrench from the joyless couplings, is perhaps
best expressed in an exchange between Ben Stiller's Jerry and
Catherine Keener's Terri. When Jerry insists on providing a
play-by-play description of their lovemaking, the exasperated Terri
says, ``Look, let's just do it, OK? I don't need the narration.''
Terri has a point and the excellent Keener deserves to enjoy an
overdue breakout. Each time the characters are technically
together, each is really making love to himself or herself.
</P>
<P>
   This of course is LaBute's point. Beneath the joylessness of the
unsatisfying sex we see a therapeutic intent. Couples who copulate
without intimacy aren't going to enjoy it much, and couples who
copulate in anger aren't going to enjoy it at all, except insofar
as sex represents an outlet for aggression. Certainly this is the
case with Jason Patric's narcissistic doctor, who at one point
nostalgically recalls the locker room gang rape of a boy in high
school and once wrote a woman who rejected him to tell her one of
her previous partners tested HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
   Stiller's drama teacher and actor is at one point seen
rehearsing Wycherly's Restoration comedy, ``The Country Wife,'' a
detail that reinforces LaBute's skewering of the emptiness of
desperate promiscuity. In Restoration London, though, the
characters had colorful, if sometimes too frankly allegorical
names. Here, the names are modular _ Jerry, Terri, Cherry, Barry,
Cary and Mary _ bolstering the sense that it makes little
difference who sleeps with whom, considering how little each is
bringing to the bed.
</P>
<P>
   The alienation, in short, is what makes the sex so cutthroat.
And so blackly funny in what must stand as one of the year's
superior ensemble efforts as the bedroom scenes and locker room
scenes (reinforcing sex as a lethal contact sport in the eyes of
the men and the scarcely less dysfunctional women) succeed one
another in LaBute's emotional gulag. Stiller's actor takes on the
quality of a human drill bit, boring ever onward, never aware.
Aaron Eckhardt, the heartless barracuda of ``In the Company of
Men,'' goes the opposite route here, playing a going-soft cuckold,
upended by his impotence.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Brenneman is fascinating, too, and the most complex,
possibly because the repose on her face (a quality that attracts
Stiller's restless mess) belies the confusion she's feeling.
Keener's brittle woman betrayed by her live-in lover, the actor,
touchingly blends anger and pain as she turns to a lesbian
relationship, hoping she'll be less hurt by Natassja Kinski's art
gallery assistant. The gallery scenes, when each of the characters
in succession hits on Kinski by pretending to comment on the same
painting, falls flat. But most of LaBute's probes are on target in
this simultaneously sad and funny aerial photograph of an emotional
tundra. ``Your Friends &AMP; Neighbors'' will restore your faith in
cynicism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
