<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SLUMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTYFING THE `SLUMS OF BEVERLY HILLS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
SLUMS OF BEVERLY HILLS 
Directed and written by: Tamara Jenkins 
Starring: Natasha Lyonne, Alan Arkin, Marisa Tomei, Carl Reiner,
David Krumholtz, Eli Marienthal, Kevin Corrigan 
Running time: 91 minutes 
Rated: R (strong sexual situations, nudity, language and drug
content) 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coming-of-age films don't get any warmer, funnier, raunchier, or
more endearing than Tamara Jenkins's brightly feisty memoir,
``Slums of Beverly Hills.'' Among other things, the film is a
corrective, making up for ``Pretty Woman'' and all those other
films that reinforce the image of Beverly Hills as Rodeo Drive and
movie stars' mansions nestled in the hills above. There are slums
in Beverly Hills, jerry-built stucco-membraned boxes sitting on
wrought-iron stilts, bearing self-mocking names like Bella Capri or
Camelot.
</P>
<P>
   As a girl scampering around the fringes of the wrong side of
Beverly Hills, moving at night each time her father would suddenly
announce, ``C'mon, we're going,'' and pile the family's belongings
into the back of his Cadillac, Jenkins says she came to think of
her family as the Jewish Joads. In this semiautobiographical
evocation of the slippery slope of status-seeking, she's brought to
sweetly quirky life by Natasha Lyonne, the only level-headed member
of the family she regards as irredeemably weird. But then, it has
always been her job to put on the brakes and introduce some healthy
skepticism into the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Her social and navigational skills are brought to a screeching
halt when, to her horror, she begins to sprout breasts that appear
as alarmingly as a suddenly inflated life jacket. This means a
struggle to maintain her equilibrium in close quarters with her
father and two younger brothers, all of whom feel free to comment
upon her changing body. If Lyonne represents the future, as soon as
she can negotiate this awkward growth spurt, Alan Arkin's patriarch
stands as another of the superb characterizations he has been
crafting these past few years.
</P>
<P>
   The thing that makes Lyonne's Vivian so unforgettable is that
part of her sees that her life is as howlingly ridiculous as it's
mortifying. Jenkins wasn't interested in going back and taking
potshots at her family. The tenderness with which she embraces them
gives Arkin all he needs to make Murray, the single father in
social and financial disarray, more than a poor schlep who can't
get the American dream right. He hangs in there, Murray does,
clinging to the underside of Beverly Hills for the school system
and the status, giving his kids advantage if he can't give them
money.
</P>
<P>
   If Arkin's Murray is a study in wistful exhaustion and Lyonne's
Vivian is uneasily poised on the brink of adulthood, Marisa Tomei's
loose cannon from the well-to-do side of the family is never just a
caricature of wantonness. The film plays her instability for
poignance, never cheap laughs, even when the two women bond during
an improvised dance with a vibrator as she ushers Vivian into the
lusty side of life. Vivian has a wisdom in her eyes and a largeness
of personality that enable her to hold the screen against her
earthy, but ultimately lost cousin.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Tomei, despite the extravagance of her character, has
an uphill battle to stake out some turf for herself amid the
lovingly tolerant father-daughter duet between Lyonne and Arkin.
It's never discussed, but Vivian is pushed into the absent mother
role, holding the family together, flaky as it is, and not minding.
David Krumholtz's brother with dreams of his own, and Kevin
Corrigan, as the first suitor to whom Vivian's instincts correctly
lead her, add to the appeal. Jenkins' blend of eccentricity and
emotional expansiveness make ``Slums of Beverly Hills'' the
filmgoer's address of choice in the weeks ahead. It's got riches
you'll never see in ``90210.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
