<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, WARRIOR FOR GAY RIGHTS, MAY BE MORTALLY WOUNDED 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE FORD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As an American watching President Clinton
pretend to apologize to the nation for having an ``inappropriate
relationship'' with former intern Monica Lewinsky, I felt
embarrassed, sad and angry.
</P>
<P>
   But as a gay American, I felt deep despair. To the extent that
the scandal would hamper the president's legislative effectiveness,
I felt I was losing a quiet warrior for the rights of my community.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton is no policy peach; I don't agree, for instance,
with his idea of ``welfare reform.'' But he has done more for the
lesbian and gay community than any president in history. Granted,
the ``don't ask, don't tell'' gays-in-the-military debacle rankled,
as did his support of the Defense of Marriage Act, which allowed
states to deny the legality of gay marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Anomalies aside, however, Clinton's presidency is rife with
historical lesbian and gay firsts. He is the first president to
sign an executive order protecting federal workers from job
discrimination based on sexual orientation. He is the first to
invite lesbian and gay leaders to the White House for policy
discussions. He is the first to support hate-crimes legislation. He
is the first to say ``lesbian and gay'' in a speech to his party's
presidential nominating convention (in 1996). And, in another
first, he has appointed more open lesbians and gays to
administration posts than any president before him.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when symbols carry the weight of truth, Clinton's
symbolic relationship with the lesbian and gay community also
speaks volumes. He hobnobs with David Geffen, an openly gay mogul.
He is the first president to speak before a national lesbian and
gay group (the Human Rights Campaign). At that function, he was
photographed sharing a joke with actors _ and lovers _ Ellen
DeGeneres and Anne Heche, who casually draped their arms around
each others' shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt independent counsel Kenneth Starr is just doing his
job. But only an ignoramus would argue he's not allied with
conservative forces. His four-year investigation _ starting with an
Arkansas land deal, and spinning through the death of lawyer Vince
Foster and alleged White House travel office improprieties _ has
skidded to a halt, horribly, on the hope of pinning a perjury
charge on a president based on the man's sexual misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of politicized persecution lesbians and gays
understand. I don't mean to compare healthy homosexual behavior to
aberrant heterosexual behavior (in this case, adultery and what
some would consider on-the-job sexual harassment). Nonetheless,
lesbians and gays are accustomed to having our sexual behavior held
up to public and political scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   True, our fight for civil rights is based on our sexual
orientation _ or, more prosaically, on whom and how we love. Yet a
host of Americans consider our sexual orientation a ``sin'' (just
as they consider adultery a sin, I suppose). This putative moral
high ground allows some of them license to take the low road in
waging political war against the lesbian and gay community: Our
private behavior becomes a matter of public debate, and often is
twisted into unrecognizable forms.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., recently
likened homosexuality to kleptomania and alcoholism, and called it
``curable.'' Calculating its timing, a coalition of right-wing
groups ran ads in major U.S. newspapers exhorting lesbians and gays
to ``convert'' to heterosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   This is part of a new _ and misguided _ attempt to whip up
support for the Republican Party. And it has consequences. The
Republican-controlled House recently passed an amendment that, if
signed into law, would prevent San Francisco from using federal
housing money to implement the city's domestic partner's ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   Another recent Republican-sponsored amendment _ narrowly
defeated _ would have voided Clinton's executive order sparing
lesbian and gay federal workers from sexual orientation-based job
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   A weakened President Clinton may embolden Republicans in their
gloves-off rhetorical and legislative assault on the lesbian and
gay community. That is a disturbing thought. Like most Americans,
I'm not thrilled with the man's private behavior, but I support his
presidency. As a gay man, I remain troubled that, through
thoughtless private conduct, he has endangered the kind of work
he's done on behalf of my community.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ford is a San Francisco-based free-lance writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
