<HEADER>
A7551 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAZING-INITIATION-SPI     08-28 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAZING-INITIATION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAZING: INITIATION RITUALS LOSE FAVOR WHEN FUN GOES TOO FAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seattle Mariner Alex Rodriguez stood outside Kansas City's
Kauffman Stadium, signing autographs and explaining himself. The
shortstop usually causes a stir wherever he goes, but nothing could
top this. He wore a dress.
</P>
<P>
   Then an impressionable rookie, Rodriguez was only doing what his
veteran teammates had ordered. This was hazing, Mariner-style.
</P>
<P>
   Today, former University of Washington tight end Cam Cleeland
continues to suffer headaches and blurred vision, the victim of a
violent rite of initiation inflicted upon him at the New Orleans
Saints training camp in Wisconsin. Wearing a pillow case over his
head and forced to run a gauntlet of teammates, Cleeland was socked
in the head by someone swinging a bag of rolled quarters.
</P>
<P>
   As Cleeland considers a pro career hanging in the balance and
possible legal action, the curious ritual of hazing remains
ingrained in our military, schools and athletic teams.
</P>
<P>
   In some states, laws have been passed rejecting it. Soldiers,
students and athletes abusing peers in this roguish manner
routinely have been punished or banished. Still it persists.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``I considered it part of coming up in baseball, part of your
development,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Frank Smoll, a UW sports psychologist, finds this logic
troublesome. He wonders how embarrassing, insulting or hurting
anyone could be beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to think, what is the purpose of hazing, and it might be
that misery loves company and that might pull a group closer,''
Smoll said. ``But I have strong doubts that this creates elements
of cohesion. It more likely creates barriers between the hazees and
the hazers.''
</P>
<P>
   The first evidence of hazing appeared in the mid-1800s on ships.
To build discipline or simply to bully, some crewmen were subjected
to unnecessary, humiliating or often painful tasks.
</P>
<P>
   From there, hazing evolved to the military, fraternal
organizations, schools and athletic teams. The armed forces, in
particular, made this part of their culture and have come to regret
it in the more politically correct 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy has had to live down ``Tailhook,'' an annual hotel
gathering in which drunken airmen subject women to a gauntlet of
groping and other degradation. The Marines have had to answer for
``pinnings,'' an equally crude display requiring men and women to
have spiked military decorations driven into their chests by
superiors as reward for passing parachute training.
</P>
<P>
   The need to pass inspection in an unsettling manner is not
solely male-oriented. In recent years, Seattle-area high school
cheerleaders were disciplined after forcing newcomers to imitate
sex acts, wear condoms in their hair or get down on all fours and
bark like dogs, all at school.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariner veterans still insist that their rookies go through
annual hazing, usually on the final road trip in September. By
their reasoning, it's fairly tame stuff. A couple of veterans seek
out a thrift shop and buy the most outlandish outfits they can
find, then return to the clubhouse and substitute rookies' regular
clothes for the new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, pitchers Jeff Fassero and Jamie Moyer did the
shopping. They picked out ballerina dresses for Andy Sheets and
Giomar Guevara.
</P>
<P>
   In previous years, the late-season Mariner rookie wardrobe has
included striped pants, plaid shirts, goofy hats and bizarre shoes.
Once dressed, players are instructed to stand outside the stadium
and sign autographs for a designated period.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Raul Ibanez was forced to wear a green shirt,
checkered pants and maroon sports coat. That wasn't the hard part.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to give 20 autographs and it was a little bit
embarrassing,'' he said. ``Can you imagine how difficult it is to
give 20 autographs when no one even wants your autograph? I'll
probably have to do it again this year, because I'm still
technically a rookie.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks have toned down their antics considerably. Rookies
now mostly carry teammates' helmets and shoulder pads from the
field and fetch soft drinks and bus food trays in the cafeteria.
The occasional school song is demanded. Rookies used to have their
clothes burned, get taped naked to goal posts or trees and find
snakes or frogs in their beds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here it's very tame; we hardly do anything,'' quarterback
Warren Moon said. ``I've been places where they cut all your hair
off or cut weird designs in your hair, and you have to keep it for
at least 24 hours before they can cut the rest of it off. ... What
happened in New Orleans is totally uncalled for.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon spent his rookie season as a pro player in the Canadian
Football League with Edmonton. He escaped the worst of the
indoctrination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most they ever made me do was chug a beer against
somebody,'' he said. ``If you lose, you've got to keep doing it.
Fortunately, I won the first time and I was out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems everyone has a hazing story to tell. Even Cleeland's
father, Gene, was not spared. As a high school football player in
Arizona, he was forced to wear makeshift underwear made out of
burlap sack. He remembers how hot he felt.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Cleeland, however, is not laughing now. His son's pro
football future is uncertain, though Cam's blurred vision has
improved.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the injury, Gene Cleeland suggested the
incident was racist, making statements he now regrets. With his son
hurt in a foolish manner, Cleeland says he spoke without thinking.
His son admonished him for it. Admittedly, Gene Cleeland was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   But the player's father has not changed his stance on hazing.
The practice still has too much acceptance, with too little
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere, sometime, someone must stand up to the bullies,''
Gene Cleeland said. ``It's important that someone does, so no
mother's son has to go through this kind of thing again.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporters Jim Street and Clare Farnsworth contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
