<P>
   &UR; FOR SATURDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of SATURDAY, Aug. 29:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUSSIA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-RDP (Moscow) _ Developments in Moscow, efforts to calm
the political and economic frenzy. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-YELTSIN (Moscow) _ Boris Yeltsin, in TV interview, says
he will not resign. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S. (Washington) _ The view of the Russian turmoil from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S.-SUMMIT (Washington) _ How next week's plans for a
Clinton-Yeltsin summit meeting are affected by the current
developments. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-GERMANY (Frankfurt) _ The effect of Russian crisis on the
coming German elections. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   NY-RUSSIANS (New York) _ The mood among Russian immigrants in
Brooklyn as their former homeland is engulfed by crisis. By Jim
Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-U.S. (Washington) _ Developments, legal and otherwise, in
the investigation of the terrorist attacks on U.S. embassies in
East Africa.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   ATTACK-CAPETOWN (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ Developments in
the Capetown Planet Hollywood bombing investigation. By Donald G.
McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N.-ASSESS (United Nations) _ A news analysis on the U.N.
arms inspection regime in Iraq following the protest resignation of
Scott Ritter. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-GINGRICH (Washington) _ House Speaker Newt Gingrich, in
Alaska, sounds off in support of Ritter. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-REBELLION (Kinshasa) _ Developments: Government parades
its rebel prisoners before the press. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MARKETS &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks open higher, flatten out, then move
into negative territory. At 1:15 p.m., the industrial average was
off 52 points and the Nasdaq index was off 395 points. At midday,
the long bond was off 2/32 point, with the yield at 5.35 percent.
By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ One statistic stands out to explain the
importance of Japan, along with its misery: When trading ended
Friday in Tokyo, Japanese stocks this week alone had dropped in
value by $241 billion _ a sum that exceeds the size of the entire
Russian economy at present exchange rates. In other words, in one
glum week's work, Japan managed the financial equivalent of wiping
Russia off the world map. Japan is so monumental as to be central
to the health of the global economy, but for now it remains a mess,
albeit an impressively large one. A month after Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi took office, vowing ``to deal with each issue in a
dramatic, speedy way,'' Japan remains firmly in recession and
largely paralyzed politically and economically. By Nicholas D.
Kristof and Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-ECON (Hong Kong) _ Hong Kong's financial crisis is
gathering steam. The government on Friday went on the largest
buying spree yet in its two-week-old battle to hurt those betting
against stocks and the local currency. Still, the Hang Seng Index
fell 1.2 percent because the government stood virtually alone in
buying shares during the stock exchange's busiest day ever. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-FED (Jackson Hole, Wyo.) _ From the Fed's annual
conference, what the policy makers think. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-ECON (Mexico City) _ The problems are mounting in Latin
America, and the region's finance ministers will meet with the IMF
in Washington next week. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BANKAMERICA (Undated) _ BankAmerica says it has recorded
$220 million of trading losses this year, mostly in Russia. By
Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-SMALL-INVESTORS (New York) _ What the little investors
think of the markets. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-MARKETS (Rome) _ How European bourses fared. By John
Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER FINANCIAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NORTHWEST-PILOTS (Minneapolis) _ Developments at Northwest as
pilots prepare to strike at midnight tonight. By Laurence
Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   OXFORD (Undated) _ Developments in Oxford Healthcare's annual
meeting. By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   TELLABS-CIENA (Undated) _ As expected, Tellabs and Ciena agreed
to new merger terms. Tellabs will now exchange 0.8 share for each
Ciena share. rather than the one-for-one swap originally agreed
upon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Developments in Kenneth Starr's
investigation of the president: Bruce Lindsey returns to the grand
jury; reports leak out of the conflicts between Lewinsky and Currie
accounts on the return of gifts. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RIGHTS (Oak Bluffs, Mass.) _ President Clinton
commemorates the 35th anniversary of the historic civil rights
march, along with John Lewis, one of the original participants. By
Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENREAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-BONNIE (Virginia Beach, Va.) _ Rejuvenated by warm
ocean waters, the storm that struck the Carolinas regained
hurricane strength during the night and battered Virginia's coast.
Winds as high as 75 mph snapped ship mooring ropes and left
hundreds of thousands of people without electricity on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFING (Undated) _ The weekly column of news and
notes on politics. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-PORN-SHOP (New York) _ A court ruling is due today in New
York City's effort to close down Show World, a notorious porn
emporium in the Times Square area. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-MILLIONAIRE (New York) _ Developments in the
investigation of the disappearance of a wealthy woman in Manhattan.
By Robert D. McFadden.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
