   HURRICANE BONNIE
</P>
<P>
   STORMS _ Rejuvenated by warm ocean waters, Bonnie regained
hurricane strength during the night and battered Virginia's coast.
Winds as high as 75 mph snapped ship mooring ropes and left
hundreds of thousands of people without electricity today. Watching
Danielle. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH MAP
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE-FATALITY _ BARCO, N.C. _ A 12-year-old girl, apparently
the only North Carolina victim of Hurricane Bonnie, died in her
Barco home after a tree crashed through her bedroom shortly after
midnight Thursday night. (Sahurie, Elizabeth City Daily Advance).
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE-ELZABETHCITY _ ELIZABETH CITY, N.C. _ For a hurricane
that supposedly was down for the count, Bonnie sure packed a heck
of a nasty second punch. The hurricane-turned tropical storm-turned
hurricane ravaged communities across the Albemarle with high winds
late Thursday night, causing at least one death and leaving
hundreds battling floodwaters and thousands more without
electricity. (Elizabeth City Daily Advance) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BONNIE-STAYBEHINDS _ ELIZABETH CITY, N.C. _ For Outer Banks
residents who stayed behind when everyone else fled, Hurricane
Bonnie had packed more hype than punch by the time it crawled
through the area Thursday evening. That, of course, was before
Bonnie regained hurricane strength early this morning just east of
the Outer Banks. The rejuvenated storm pounded the area with heavy
winds, rain and flood waters before moving farther out to sea.
(Sahurie, Elizabeth City Daily Advance).
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS FLOODING
