</P>
<P>
   MILLION _ First there was the Million Man March, then the
Million Woman March. Now youth plan to get into the act Labor Day
weekend with competing marches in Atlanta and New York City. The
gatherings have been the works for months, attracting little media
attention but sparking conflicts between organizing groups. The
controversial and militant Khallid Muhammad, a former top-ranking
Nation of Islam minister, is putting together the New York meeting
while a more mainstream, religious group is planning the Atlanta
march. Each march has attracted its own set of endorsees, but the
Atlanta gathering appears to have the largest base of mainstream
support. (Reid,n Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   NOTEBOOK -- Security was tighter and access to the media
purposefully controlled during Newt Gingrich's swing through Iowa
and the West. More items to come. (Sherman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   HOMELESS-VENUS _ Venus Rodriguez's life has begun a new chapter
with the start of classes at Clark Atlanta University. With her
white T-shirt and baggy jeans, she looks the part of any
18-year-old at Clark Atlanta University freshman. But beneath the
pleasant smile is a hardened, woman-child, who refuses to mince
words about her life in a homeless shelter or with a drug-addicted
mother. ``At the age of 15, I had been through things that
30-year-olds couldn't dream of,'' Venus said. ``I was homeless,
went to 11 different schools, was in foster care. I want people to
be inspired by my story.'' (Suggs, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   POLTALK_ Telling tales to win over voters is a lost art in this
sound-bite age. But Jake Pickle, Jim Wright, Bob Armstrong and
Molly Ivins know how it's done. They tell 'em at a Political Talk
free show tonight at UT. we advance with story. (McCarthy, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   UT-DORMS-COOP _ AUSTIN, Texas _ University of Texas
administrators could decide in two weeks whether to shut down the
university's Women's Cooperative _ eliminating a campus fixture
since the Great Depression _ to make room for next year's freshmen.
(Shah, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSING-ANNEXATION _ MIAMI _ Residents of a Belle Glade housing
project have asked a federal court to right what they see as nearly
40 years of injustice. They say the city has discriminated against
them and violated their voting rights by refusing to annex the
project. The case is an echo of America's legal and political past,
scholars say. (Peltz, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MILLIONTH-MAURO-DOOR _ As he heads toward knocking on his
symbolic millionth door Sunday, Garry Mauro does not hesitate when
asked to recount the most memorable moment from his door-to-door
tour of Texas. The man who came to the door naked in Paris and
carried on a conversation. So it goes as Mauro sweats toward the
end of what he thinks has been an incredibly good couple of months
of block walking and door knocking. Down in polls and payroll,
Mauro believes he scored political points this summer while
Republican Gov. George W. Bush spent some time at the family digs
in Maine. Pounding the pavement, in one form or another, is a
time-honored method of attracting attention and this political
season is no different. For Mauro's underfinanced campaign, it also
proved to be a sustainable gimmick that _ especially in small- and
mid-sized cities _ got him some valuable free time on the evening
TV news. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   POLMONEY-SENATE _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate returns Monday from
its summer vacation with most Republican members holding firm
against a bipartisan campaign finance bill. However, Sens. John
McCain, R-Ariz., and Russell Feingold, D-Wis., insist that the five
legislative weeks left before the Congress's scheduled adjournment
on Oct. 9 might give them enough time to overcome that. (Mollison,
Cox News Service).
</P>
