<HEADER>
A7578 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONFESS-HNS &LR;      08-28 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONFESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON HAS LITTLE ROOM FOR ABSOLUTION IN WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALBERTO HUERTA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At a recent luncheon with essayist and
television commentator Richard Rodriguez and a small group of very
bright Harvard and University of San Francisco graduates, I
suggested that in Protestant, puritan and prudish America,
President Clinton was slowly becoming a Catholic. He seemed to be
developing a deeper sense of sin, the fallen state of humankind,
and the need to confess.
</P>
<P>
   In the president's address to the nation, he admitted to an
inappropriate relationship with a White House intern, which he said
was wrong. He said he would do whatever it took to make this right
with his wife, his daughter and his God.
</P>
<P>
   If the president were a Catholic, which he is not, would his
words hold up under the rigor of a Catholic confession? Would he
receive absolution? Catholic confession is understood as the
Sacrament of Reconciliation, bringing the penitent back to some
original state of grace that has been lost by sin.
</P>
<P>
   In confession, a priest ascertains: the gravity of the sin;
contrition; and a firm purpose of amendment. To some degree, the
last two conditions must be present for the priest to administer
absolution, and then give a penance.
</P>
<P>
   When a person confesses, he or she acknowledges guilt and the
need for forgiveness. For example, if the penitent says he is
having a relationship with someone, the priest asks if he is single
or married. If single, whether they plan at some later date to
marry? If married, whether the penitent can separate himself from
the occasion that is harming the Sacrament of Marriage.
</P>
<P>
   By having an affair outside of marriage, Clinton has committed
adultery. However, the New Testament reminds us that Jesus tells
those accusing the adulterous woman, ``Let he who is without sin
cast the first stone'' _ that we are all in a fallen state.
Adultery can be forgiven. Clinton confessed that by his actions, he
harmed his family and many others. We also know that his affair
with the intern is over. He is concerned with making things right
again.
</P>
<P>
   When a priest hears a penitent admit he or she has harmed
others, and expresses a willingness to make this right again, the
priest is satisfied that contrition has been articulated. And if
the penitent is able and willing to separate himself from whatever
is endangering his spiritual side of grace, the priest knows he has
expressed a firm purpose of amendment.
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton's speech to the nation, he admitted wrongdoing and a
desire to repair the damage he had inflicted on those close to him.
In a Catholic confession, he would receive absolution and penance.
Both his confession and penance would be confidential under the
Seal of Confession.
</P>
<P>
   In politically charged Washington, however, punishment is often
sought for a public confession _ one having little to do with
forgiveness, and less with reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The Rev. Alberto Huerta is an associate professor in the
Department of Modern and Classical Languages at the University of
San Francisco.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 1419EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
