<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7598 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-WELFARE-HNS &LR;      08-28 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WELFARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S PERSONAL DISGRACE UNDERMINES `WELFARE REFORM' 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STAR PARKER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As the growing chorus of bipartisan voices is
making clear, President Clinton has lost the moral authority to
lead. The upcoming two-year anniversary of welfare reform should
make this fact crystal clear. That's right, welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual promiscuity is the unaddressed underbelly of welfare that
could minimize the effectiveness of the historic 1996 reform bill.
Government legislation can only go so far in cleaning up the
horrible mess created by 30 years of the welfare state. We need a
moral leader to navigate the difficult terrain that encompasses
moral and spiritual repair of the social fabric in urban America.
</P>
<P>
   If President Clinton wants to say that the whole Lewinsky matter
is all about sex, fine. Let's talk about sex. While it is true that
the government played a large role in the illegitimacy rates that
began soaring in 1965 _ the year Lyndon Johnson changed the welfare
laws to financially encourage young mothers to stay single, jobless
and without any savings _ there's one fact to keep in mind. Babies
aren't made outside of marriage without sexual promiscuity.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1960s, the sexual revolution sent the message to
women over the nation's loudspeaker that one could have sex without
consequences. Rather than use the time-honored practice of social
scolding for such irresponsibility, the nation, including black
churches in our cities, turned a blind eye toward destructive
personal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bill Clinton has decided that lewd acts with a government
intern, only slightly older than his own daughter, in the Oval
Office _ the people's office _ are none of the public's business.
If we allow that attitude to take hold, we're setting a dangerous
precedent for the nation as a whole, not just the office of the
presidency. The very man who signed into law a welfare reform bill
designed to increase personal responsibility is now claiming that
his sexual irresponsibility is his own private business.
</P>
<P>
   We've gotten to the sad point where more than seven of every 10
black babies born today are fatherless, precisely because we've
permitted sexual promiscuity to become socially acceptable.
Forgiveness is one thing, acceptance is quite another.
</P>
<P>
   Even if we personally forgive Clinton, we can neither accept nor
condone his actions. How can he stand before a group of women
seeking to leave welfare and tell them to take responsibility for
their actions when as the leader of the Free World he couldn't keep
his pants zipped in the Oval Office with a 21-year-old intern?
</P>
<P>
   He can't. His efforts to 'fess up amounted to, ``I take
responsibility, but it's Ken Starr's fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Excuse me? That's like a welfare mom saying, ``It was my
responsibility, but society made me do it.''
</P>
<P>
   That simply doesn't cut it. As humans, when we screw up, we need
to repent and try to make right what we made wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than take the respectable path of remorse and
restitution, Clinton hides behind the cloak of religion in a
pathetic search for sympathy. He asks forgiveness. He brings Jesse
Jackson, a minister with no church besides CNN, for counseling on
this ``private matter.'' Clinton doesn't pray, he preys _ on young
women working beneath him, something he has done with impunity.
</P>
<P>
   Only the wicked and the weak would ``spin'' religion. Clinton
has shown, in reprehensible fashion, that he is all too willing to
let others take the fall for him and that responsibility is a last
ditch resort.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star Parker is a former welfare mother. She runs the Coalition
on Urban Renewal and Education, based in Los Angeles, and is the
author of ``Pimps, Whores, and Welfare Brats.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
