<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7616 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORBACHEV-RUSSIAN-CRI     08-28 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORBACHEV-RUSSIAN-CRISIS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE IS A WAY OUT OF THE RUSSIAN CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV  
 c.1998 La Stampa  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Once again Russia is having a change of government. This is
symptomatic of a dangerous problem. The highly touted ``energetic
technocrat'' whose approval by the legislature was obtained after
much arm-twisting is out. The acting prime minister is Viktor
Chernomyrdin, sourly dismissed a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The pundits are at a loss wondering how to interpret these
developments. The answer, however, is simple. Another attempt to
force a set of impossible economic programs on the country has
failed. Now our failed leaders are casting about for a straw to
grasp.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the policy course pursued since 1992 is so
obvious that it has now been recognized officially.
</P>
<P>
   The country is being swept by a new devastating wave of the
financial crisis. The stock market hits new lows every day. Despite
having obtained multibillion dollar loans abroad, the Russian
government has been forced to take emergency measures to halt the
free-fall or at least to ease the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The devaluation of the ruble and the real threat of bankruptcy
have demonstrated that the system born of the reckless, selfishly
conceived reforms of the 1990s is unsustainable. A speculative
economy, a corrupt government, a criminalized environment, tens of
millions of forgotten and abandoned people: Such is the outcome of
the Yeltsin era.
</P>
<P>
   The defining fact today is the credibility gap dividing the
authorities and Russian society. The crisis is not so much economic
as political.
</P>
<P>
   Until very recently, the president and his entourage tried to
ignore this fact. Today they seem to be waking up to what's
happening. Continuing to cling to power while closing their eyes
and plugging their ears could be self-defeating. The appointment of
Chernomyrdin as acting prime minister is therefore likely to signal
the beginning of the process of transferring power to an heir
apparent. We are witnessing Yeltsin's political sunset.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is a hidden agenda here. By all indications, the
president wants to use Chernomyrdin to try to prolong his political
existence, to somehow make it to the constitutionally mandated
election time. The new premier has thus been assigned the role of
the chief firefighter called in to save the regime.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Chernomyrdin too needs time to raise his
extremely low popularity rating in preparation for presidential
elections. The prime minister's office gives him leverage to do
that, but it is unlikely that he will succeed, given the depth of
the crisis and the current lineup of political forces.
</P>
<P>
   But is there perhaps some hope that the ``heavyweight''
Chernomyrdin has been called in for a different purpose _ that at
long last he will form a government capable of changing the course.
</P>
<P>
   Much as one might wish to believe it, it is unlikely. The
extraordinary difficulties Russia is experiencing today began, as
everyone knows, on Chernomyrdin's watch and with his involvement.
Thus the reemergence of Chernomyrdin does nothing to address the
federal authority's credibility problem. It does not create the
trust needed to solve any major issue.
</P>
<P>
   The call for early elections, therefore, continues to be timely
and urgent. Indeed, early elections of the president and of the
Duma, which bears its share of responsibility for what has happened
to Russia, are indispensable, as is a referendum to amend the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   I am convinced that the role of the legislature should be
increased. It is very important to normalize the presidency. Russia
needs a balanced system of institutions of government. Only a
strong, functional parliament and an effective cabinet and
president can implement policies of economic growth and Russia's
revival.
</P>
<P>
   The state has to play an essential regulating role to help
realize the country's enormous potential.
</P>
<P>
   Today conditions are still in place to conduct early elections
in an orderly way, taking advantage of the fact that the widespread
popular discontent has not yet burst out in extreme forms. But the
legendary patience of the Russian people should not be tested too
long. It has its limits.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Translated from the Russian by Pavel Palazchenko.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.1998 LaStampa &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Mikhail Gorbachev, the last leader of the Soviet Union before
its collapse in 1991 and Nobel Peace Prize winner, now heads the
Gorbachev Foundation, a political think tank in Moscow, with a new
office at Northeastern University, in Boston.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 1437EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
