<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7630 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     08-28 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESSFUL SOFT-CORE SHOWS PAY THE BILLS FOR CABLE'S QUALITY FARE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's a pool hustler who dresses to the nines and lives in a
gloriously spacious loft. So the suave swagger he exhibits in
luring her to his bachelor pad is hardly surprising. What is? Only
one bed. But, hey, it's a pretty ``wide'' bed, as he assures her.
``And if you move over there a little,'' he suggests, pointing to
the other side of the bed, ``we could sort of share it.''
</P>
<P>
   Most women I know would sprint for the door after digesting a
loaded line like that. But on Showtime's ``Red Shoe Diaries,'' the
Penthouse Forum of television, fantasy is reality and reality is
fantasy. Sure enough, as a saxophone purrs in the background, her
shirt, then bra, then undies disappear, and so does she, behind his
bare shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as the two go at it on a pool table, she says in
breathless narration: ``We couldn't get enough of one another.''
</P>
<P>
   I suppose the same could be said for cable and its lust for
late-night erotica. ``Red Shoe Diaries'' has shut down production
after six seasons on the pay cable channel, but it leaves a strange
but true legacy: It was both creator of ``art house'' soft porn and
savior of the kind of quality programming for which pay cable has
also become known.
</P>
<P>
   HBO's exhausting space odyssey ``From the Earth to the Moon''
was a quality miniseries. But its best ratings barely matched the
worst ratings of the channel's ``Real Sex'' series, that occasional
special that could best be described as sexually freaky
infotainment for the swingers set.
</P>
<P>
   Performing just as well for HBO is ``Taxicab Confessions,''
documentaries produced from cameras hidden in Las Vegas taxis
providing viewers with titillating situations such as, for
instance, a woman describing masturbation in frank detail and a
couple having sex in the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   Back on ``Showtime,'' a tamer erotic pleasure, ``Sex in the
City,'' has, in its first season, eclipsed the celebrated ``The
Larry Sanders Show'' in terms of ratings, drawing nearly 2 million
more viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Speak with cable executives in private, and they'll say that
late-night erotic series attract viewers, and the profits help them
pay for the more socially redeeming programs.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the arrival of ``Red Shoe Diaries'' in 1992 that
programmers began producing their own erotic dramas in place of NR
(no rating) films. Many ran for only a season, but others, like the
French-produced series ``Emmanuelle'' on Cinemax, have stuck around
and become after-hours favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red Shoe Diaries'' was innovative for its time, soft porn that
stayed true to its basic, lusty principles while adding music-video
artiness, jumpy, nervy video cuts and dim mood lighting for a
veneer of upscale, almost snooty, erotica. Lifetime with nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like the exquisitely executed ``The Hunger,'' also on
Showtime, are a cross between the daring of a low-budget
independent film and the cleverness of ``Twilight Zone.'' With
``The Hunger,'' you're reminded of its aims only when the clothes
drop and the camera hangs around to record bare bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, ``Red Shoe Diaries'' gained a measure of
respectability from its narrator, ``X-Files'' star David Duchovny,
who also starred in its two-hour movie launch. The series'
credibility seemed to rise with his growing fame, even though he's
around only to open and close each episode by reading the letters
from conflicted women searching for independence, usually from
boneheaded guys.
</P>
<P>
   HBO declines to break down its viewing demographic, but says
that an equal number of women and men tune in to erotic series such
as ``Red Shoe Diaries;'' Showtime says the same for ``The Hunger.''
</P>
<P>
   And they expect more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish there was a bigger audience for things that were either
that smart or that subtle,'' Jeff Bewkes, HBO's chairman and CEO,
said of ``Larry Sanders,'' which recently ended its run. ``But what
can you do? I mean, we keep trying. `From the Earth to the Moon'
did not have a lot of scantily clad people in it. Mostly, they were
dressed up in these moon suits.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that was the problem.
</P>
<P>
