<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7641 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-DIANA-TEX     08-28 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DIANA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLEMNITY AND SLEAZE MINGLE AS TV REMEMBERS PRINCESS DIANA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Returning this week is the Princess Diana media derby, as
network, all-news and cable outlets plan tributes, culminating on
or near the Aug. 31 anniversary of her death in that Paris car
crash.
</P>
<P>
   Call it morbid, but from an economic perspective, it's a little
like Christmas in the retail biz. Di was big business in life; in
death we upgraded her to pseudo-sainthood, eclipsing the real saint
who died days later, Mother Teresa. But then Mother Teresa didn't
represent glamour, beauty, royalty and wealth _ or grace the cover
of People magazine 43 times before her death.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2 billion people worldwide viewed Diana's televised
funeral, even though we in the States had to set alarm clocks to do
it.
</P>
<P>
   Warning: The Di tributes and remembrances range from highbrow to
lowlife; they are alternately somber, sappy, saccharine and sleazy.
What do you expect from E! Entertainment?
</P>
<P>
   The Learning Channel jumped the gun last week with ``Memories of
Diana'' and ``Diana: Secrets Behind the Crash.'' ``Secrets'' made
intriguing assertions (such as that the flashes rumored to have
blinded the driver didn't come from pursuing ``paparazzi'' but from
an anti-personnel stun flash to stop them), but it covered little
new ground for anyone who has stayed on top of the ongoing
developments. (''Secrets'' will air again Nov. 7.)
</P>
<P>
   Expect each network's evening newscast and morning infotainment
show to devote in-depth reports to Diana, and local stations to add
to the clutter, figuring they ought to do ``something.''
</P>
<P>
   Some offerings:
</P>
<P>
   7 p.m. CDT Sunday, MSNBC. Anchor Jodi Applegate hosts a live,
one-hour special from London, the first of scattered reports
throughout the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   7 p.m. Sunday, E! Entertainment. This installment of ``The E!
True Hollywood Story'' examines Diana's life and death with the
usual Diana and Prince Charles footage and interviews, but with
that E! flair.
</P>
<P>
   7 a.m. CDT Monday. ``This Morning'' reports from London with
Jane Robelot co-anchoring and CBS correspondents reporting from
Paris and elsewhere. No word yet whether ``Today'' and ``Good
Morning America'' will follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   7 p.m. CDT Monday, NBC. Richard Attenborough, filmmaker and
friend of Diana, narrates a more personal ``Diana.'' Covering two
hours, it includes interviews with friends, associates,
photographers, magazine editors, columnists, authors and social
commentators who give their views on the impact of Diana's life.
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Monday, History Channel. One of the better offerings,
``As It Happened: When Diana Died'' looks back at Diana's death and
examines her legacy and effect on Britain's monarchy. ``It's a more
removed view,'' promises a History Channel spokeswoman. ``It's not
like NBC, which is a reminiscence of Diana as a person. Here we ask
the question: What has she left us?''
</P>
<P>
   And because it's the History Channel, the program also looks at
``parallels in history'' to explain the Diana phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. CDT Friday through Monday, MSNBC. ``Time &AMP; Again's'' Jane
Pauley presents ``The Life &AMP; Death of Princess Diana'' as four
nightly one-hour reports.
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. CDT Monday, CBS. ``48 Hours'' with Dan Rather updates its
June story about the investigation of Diana's death, including the
potential obstruction of justice by the Ritz Hotel; also, Dodi al
Fayed's butler, Rene Delorm, takes viewers on a tour of the places
Dodi and Diana visited together.
</P>
<P>
   9:30 p.m. CDT Tuesday, MTV. Diana will be the focus of the music
channel's new weekly series, ``BIOrhythm,'' which offers an
intriguing take on the biography genre by telling stories using
only music and footage. ``BIOrhythm: Princess Di'' covers
everything from Diana's 1981 wedding to her funeral. There are
songs from the Smashing Pumpkins, Ella Fitzgerald, Nirvana _ and
Verdi's ``Requiem.'' Hey, at least it's original.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
