<SLUG> BC-HOT-TIPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPECTANT MODEL DESIGNS MATERINTY FASHIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Some of us are a tad tired of celebs exposing
everything, including their pregnant bellies, on the covers of
magazines. So Miz Hot Tips was impressed that when sexy swimsuit
model Kathy Ireland became visibly pregnant, she not only covered
up but designed a clothing line for herself and other expectant
moms.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ireland, ``Being pregnant is such a jubilant time
in a woman's life ... and when I was pregnant with my first child,
it was difficult to find enough selections that offered comfort and
style at a reasonable price.''
</P>
<P>
   So with budget and boredom on her mind, she launched the Kathy
Ireland Maternity Collection this month at Kmart stores. The
collection includes necessities like jeans and khaki pants, a lot
of stylin' black, and also velour holiday dresses. And take note
that there's not one dumb bow in the entire selection. And, best of
all, Ireland will have new collections arriving each month as your
size (and hers) changes. Most items are priced between $16.99 and
$24.99.
</P>
<P>
   PEEL-PERFECT: Now, for those women who aren't pregnant and have
a figure worthy of a sleek catsuit, read on. The House of Elegance
will make you a leather catsuit similar to the one Uma Thurman wore
as Emma Peel in that new and notably dull film ``The Avengers,''
for $825. It's a custom design, based on the measurements you send
them, and it takes about four weeks for delivery. For information,
write to House of Elegance, P.O. Box 342, Ithaca, N.Y. 14851. Or
call (607) 275-0839.
</P>
<P>
   MALL PATROL: It's another ho-hummer of a weekend, and you're
torn between watching women's wrestling on the tube or going
shopping. Hmmm. Miz Hot Tips knows it's a tough call, but she
suggests getting out in the real world, like Northridge Fashion
Center, which is holding a teen fashion show presented by YM
magazine at 1 p.m. today in the center court.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the Sunset Plaza mall in West Hollywood, where the Anna
Sui boutique opens today. And at most Macy's stores today and
Sunday, you can get a free ``First Course'' style guide for men
just for trying on a pair of the new Slates pants.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 3, you can get a makeup make-over from artist Mary
Greenwell, who has done the faces of Brooke Shields and even
Princess Diana. She'll be at the Elizabeth Arden counter of
Robinsons-May at the Glendale Galleria between 11 a.m. and 4 p.m.
Call (818) 247-2600, Ext. 2132.
</P>
<P>
   Or get a make-over with an expert from Bobbi Brown Essentials on
the same day at Bloomingdale's in Century City.
</P>
<P>
   Other new stores to look for are Pottery Barn, which opens Sept.
5 at The Oaks mall in Thousand Oaks, and the Monah Li boutique,
which will open Oct. 15 at 1765 Vermont Ave., Los Angeles. Li is an
edgy new designer who's a current nominee for the CaliforniaMart's
Rising Star Award.
</P>
<P>
   GET SMART: Always wish you knew how to talk opera? The Los
Angeles Opera League will have you knowing one aria from another in
no time with its new opera seminar series that kicks off at 9 a.m.
Sept. 5 with a discussion of Bizet's ``Carmen'' and Massenet's
tragic romance, ``Werther.'' Admission is $15, and the location is
Hotel Inter-Continental Los Angeles, 251 S. Olive St., Los Angeles.
For more information, call (213) 972-7220.
</P>
<P>
   MYSTERY MASH: If you just can't take all those people singing at
the top of their lungs to each other, maybe you'd prefer a quiet
little murder. To introduce you to some of the best contemporary
mystery writers, UCLA Extension is offering ``Murder They Write:
Six Evenings with Premier Mystery Writers.'' The authors who will
help you explore the fine art of murder through conversations and
short readings include Jan Burke, author of ``Goodnight, Irene,''
and Michael Connelly of ``Blood Work.'' The class fee is $210, and
the first class is 7 p.m. Oct. 15. To register, call (818)
784-7006.
</P>
<P>
   A CHICHI NEIGHBORHOOD: Finally, you can make yourself at home in
Hancock Park. You know, that ritzy neighborhood where celebs like
Mr. Blackwell live? Anyway, at 1 p.m. Sunday the Hancock Park
Historical Society will take you on a walking tour of Windsor
Square to visit seven homes and gardens built in the '20s by
leading architects.
</P>
<P>
   Miz Hot Tips hopes you'll remember your party manners and not
touch anything. And also wear flat, soft-soled shoes that won't
scratch wooden floors. Reservations are $25, and the number to call
is (213) 243-8182.
</P>
