<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7667 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIANA-INVESTIGATIONS-     08-28 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANA-INVESTIGATIONS-$ADV30-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS OFFICIAL PROBE INTO DIANA'S DEATH NEARS END, QUESTIONS JUST
BEGINNING
 &HT;    With DIANA-ANNIVERSARY-$ADV30.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Aug. 30 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Despite a year of deliberations by a jury of talk
shows, newspapers and authors, the real trial has yet to begin.
</P>
<P>
   And at the rate this investigation is proceeding, it may well
become known as the ``Trial of the Next Century.''
</P>
<P>
   In stark contrast to high-profile cases in the United States,
the French inquiry into who caused the death of Princess Diana of
Wales has been conducted with nearly absolute stealth.
</P>
<P>
   Magistrate Herve Stephan, who under French law has the powers of
judge, investigator and prosecutor, has succeeded in shrouding the
probe in the strict secrecy that French law requires.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare statement last week, Stephan said the investigation
would end in October, when several ongoing tests are concluded. It
was the first statement prosecutors had issued since the early days
of the case. It was released to respond to the crush of media
queries surrounding the anniversary of Diana's death.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are still trying to determine the meaning of
abnormally high levels of carbon monoxide in the blood of driver
Henri Paul, who was killed in the crash, the prosecutors said.
Blood tests also found that he was heavily drunk.
</P>
<P>
   The origin of the carbon monoxide isn't clear, but the gas can
cause dizziness, headaches, nausea and disorientation -- even
leaving a person in a coma.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also are reviewing the efforts to treat Diana at
the crash site. It is common in France to treat even seriously
injured people at crash sites, a practice that differs from
thinking in the United States that patients should be taken
immediately to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   A third probe involves lab tests on the body of the wrecked
black Mercedes. Forensic tests are being conducted on the crashed
car to determine if it had been brushed by a mysterious Fiat before
the accident. Investigators said they had interviewed nearly 3,000
owners of Fiat Unos and reportedly have come up empty.
</P>
<P>
   Police also have interviewed 153 people as potential witnesses
to the crash, but the investigators did not reveal any of their
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Only when the report by Stephan and his colleague, magistrate
Marie-Christine Devidal, is issued will it be determined who, if
anyone, will be criminally charged. A criminal trial would be open
to the press and public, even though no television cameras will be
allowed, said a spokesman for the court in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, the only people in clear legal jeopardy are the
paparazzi who were trailing -- some say, chasing -- the Mercedes
that night, and who have been widely condemned for their part in
the world's most famous car crash.
</P>
<P>
   Ten men -- nine photographers and the driver of one of the
motorcycles giving chase -- have been in legal limbo since the
early days following the accident. At that point, they were placed
under formal investigation on charges of both manslaughter and
failure to assist people in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses have not agreed on the behavior of the photographers,
however, with some saying they were following too closely and
others saying they kept a safe distance before the crash.
</P>
<P>
   None of the paparazzi -- some of whom still work Diana-related
events -- has been formally charged.
</P>
<P>
   In early June, Stephan summoned the paparazzi to give secret
testimony. Also present were Mohamed Al Fayed, the father of Dodi
Al Fayed, who also perished in the crash. Frances Shand Kydd,
Diana's mother, was also there to hear the testimony.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no reliable leaks of the testimony, but some
news reports have said that those close to the case believe all 10
will be cleared of the manslaughter charges. However, some may go
to trial on the non-assistance charge, facing minor penalties,
perhaps a fine.
</P>
<P>
   But questions remain about other aspects of the case. It is
unclear how much management at the Paris Ritz Hotel, which Diana
and Al Fayed were leaving, knew about Henri Paul's condition. That
factor could come into play in determining the prestigious hotel's
liability in the case.
</P>
<P>
   And what about bodyguard Trevor Rees-Jones, the sole survivor of
the crash? Six months ago, his story was that Paul appeared fine
that night -- that he wasn't visibly drunk. But that was before he
resigned from the employ Mohamed Al Fayed, owner of the Ritz.
</P>
<P>
   The latest clue comes in the form of new charges about the
mechanical condition of the car itself. It has been widely reported
here that a person familiar with the Mercedes has told
investigators that the car's brakes were faulty, making it
especially difficult to brake suddenly.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known whether Etoile Limousines, which rented the car
to the Ritz, warned the hotel about the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps seeking to learn more about these matters, Stephan
Tuesday questioned two key witnesses: the president of the Ritz
Hotel, Frank Klein, and its director, Claude Roulet.
</P>
<P>
   With prospects of civil litigation and even more criminal
investigations, Stephan's report is likely to signal only the end
of the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
