<HEADER>
A7670 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIANA-REVIEW-LADN     08-28 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANA-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASE OF `DIANA' DEJA VU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Hey, how's this for a novel idea? NBC is going to
air a loving tribute to Princess Diana on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, you've seen one before?
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, that was Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diana,'' a two-hour documentary, will air at 8 p.m. to
commemorate the first anniversary of Diana's death.
</P>
<P>
   The network went to the big guns to put this together. Emmy
Award-winner Robert Halmi Sr. is the executive producer, and
Academy Award-winning filmmaker Lord Richard Attenborough narrates.
</P>
<P>
   Attenborough, who was a close friend of Diana's, makes it clear
at the outset that this is not a tawdry tale that dredges up the
sensational events of her very public adult life.
</P>
<P>
   Attenborough was brought into the fold by the royal family to
help a shy princess with her public speaking. So his part was done
from a place of respect, admiration and love. His insight is
apparent, and his style of narration is conversational, making the
two hours a comfortable ride.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people talking are friends, including Lucia Flecha
de Lima, Mary Robertson (Diana was her child's nanny), plus Diana's
nanny and Diana's friend Lana Marks. We also hear from her
hairstylist, makeup artist (who tries all too hard to sound like a
confidante), her acupuncturist and her astrologer.
</P>
<P>
   Sure these people had some interesting access, but it shows how
documenting ``Diana'' has been overdone. How far down the line can
they go?
</P>
<P>
   Who will be interviewed for the next documentary, someone who
watched this documentary?
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of the show is the most interesting, where we get
to learn about Diana as a child and what influenced and motivated
her to be the person she became. We hear from teachers and school
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   The story, told in chronological order, bogs down as it goes on.
This is mainly because Diana's charitable work in foreign countries
and with AIDs patients already is so well-known.
</P>
<P>
   People she has helped speak up, but it's too redundant and
seemed too packaged.
</P>
<P>
   This is a classy piece of work about a woman who nearly always
conducted herself with dignity and compassion. It's crisply edited
and nice to look at. But it is a clearly exhausted subject.
Television was jammed with coverage at the time of her tragic
death, and now, one year later, Round 2 continues with repeats and
new stories, but no new information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 1505EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7673 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIANA-TV-LADN     08-28 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANA-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIALS REMEMBER DIANA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Monday will mark a year since Princess Diana
died, and if you missed Friday's television lineup of anniversary
shows, there's plenty more to come this weekend and early next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the many Diana retrospectives scheduled: &QL; 
TODAY &QC; 
MSNBC: ``Diana: The First Anniversary,'' the all-news network will
air continuous reports filed by NBC correspondents until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   E!: ``E! News Weekend'' will air reports from London at noon and
5 p.m. today and 10 a.m. and 2 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   FOX NEWS CHANNEL: ``A Diana Special: Movietone Presents the
Royals'' at 11 a.m., repeating at 3 p.m. Sunday, with vintage
family footage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farewell to a Princess'' at noon and repeating at 1 p.m.
Sunday, an abridged version of the funeral, hosted by Catherine
Crier and Brit Hume.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diana Remembered'' at 4 p.m. and repeating at noon Sunday, a
look at the life of Diana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles &AMP; Diana: The Royal Wedding'' at 5 p.m., with repeats
Sunday at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. &QL; 
SUNDAY &QC;
</P>
<P>
   FOX NEWS CHANNEL: ``The Real Diana'' at 5 p.m. The show includes
home movies of Diana's childhood, a tour of the Diana museum, an
update on the investigation of the fatal crash and a previously
aired interview with Earl Charles Spencer.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;E: ``Diana: True Story,'' a two-hour biography, 5, 7, 9 and 11
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   E!: ``E! True Hollywood Story'' will use news footage and
photographs in its spin on a documentary, 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC: Jodi Applegate will anchor a live, one-hour tribute, 5
p.m. &QL; 
MONDAY &QC;
</P>
<P>
   NBC, CHANNEL 4: ``Diana,'' an intimate two-hour documentary
narrated by Richard Attenborough, 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   KCBS, CHANNEL 2: ``This Morning,'' 7 a.m., Jane Robelot
co-anchors from London with reports from Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``48 Hours,'' beginning at 10 p.m., will air an update of its
June investigation into the deaths of Diana and Dodi al Fayed.
Fayed's butler will also take viewers on a tour of some of the
places the couple went.
</P>
