<HEADER>
A7679 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS-BAN-HNS &LR;      08-28 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-BAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSAULT RIFLE BAN FACES VETO IN CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ California Gov. Pete Wilson has vowed to veto a
bill approved this week by the state Assembly that would be the
toughest assault weapons ban in the country.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the governor said the measure goes too far and
invites lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   If Wilson rejects the bill, California will be left without an
effective assault weapons ban, because a state law passed in 1989
in the wake of a schoolyard massacre in Stockton has been
emasculated by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   On its third attempt in the lower house, a measure by Democratic
Assemblyman Don Perata of Oakland passed Thursday by a 41-31 vote.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would expand the list of banned weapons, put
first-ever restrictions on large magazine clips and increase the
penalties for using high-powered weapons when committing a felony.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, the legislature approved a measure that would put
consumer protections on junk guns, or ``Saturday night specials.''
Under the bill, all handguns manufactured in California must meet
drop-safety and firing-safety tests. Wilson is expected to veto
that measure as well.
</P>
<P>
   Despite word from Wilson spokesman Ron Low that the Perata bill
was unacceptable, the assemblyman said he hoped the public would
call or write Wilson and encourage him to sign his bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican governor, who is considering a run for president
in 2000, has 30 days to decide. Since the legislature ends its
two-year session at midnight Monday, Perata said that if Wilson
``doesn't sign it, California basically has no assault weapon
ban.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I think what happens is some wacko walks out there
on Oct. 5 and opens up on some schoolyard or factory, and that's
going to be Pete's legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Low said the Wilson administration had tried over several
months to reduce the number of banned guns. Specifically, Wilson
wanted to allow weapons with up to a 20-round capacity, instead of
the 19 rounds Perata wrote into the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The distinction is important because many high-powered weapons,
such at the M-16 made mostly during the Vietnam War, use 20-round
magazines. Perata said those weapons were for military use and had
no business on the street.
</P>
<P>
   Low said Perata had changed the definition of an assault weapon
14 times and ended up with a measure that would prompt a flood of
lawsuits in order to determine the law's meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it comes down in current form, the administration cannot
support this bill,'' Low said. ``There were a number of definitions
to expand the guns covered under the assault weapons ban, and the
more definitions that were added, the more confusing it got, and
the more chances there would be challenges to the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the veto threat, Luis Tolley, the western director for
Handgun Control Inc., called Thursday's vote a ``tremendous victory
for public safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Tolley said Perata's measure addressed a number of the
governor's concerns: It would postpone enactment until 2000 to give
owners time to comply, boost penalties to add as much as 10 more
years in prison for using high-powered weapons to commit a felony,
and would expand rather than replace the 1959 law.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association and most Assembly Republicans
called Perata's measure vague and said it would lead to more
confusion about what constitutes an assault weapon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
