<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7682 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAMAICA-BROTHELS-$ADV     08-28 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAMAICA-BROTHELS-$ADV29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANSWER TO TOURIST HARASSMENT IN JAMAICA ... RED-LIGHT DISTRICTS?
 &HT;    With photos placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Aug. 29 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSTON, Jamaica _ For years, hawkers, panhandlers, drug
dealers, and prostitutes have been as much a part of the landscape
of this Caribbean island as coconut groves and jerk chicken.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, a chorus of complaints from visitors has become so
deafening it's threatened to destroy the foundation on which
Jamaica's economy is built: tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Jamaica Chamber of Commerce has come up with a
controversial solution to alleviate at least part of the problem:
legalize brothels so that red-light districts can be created.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least we'd get the prostitutes off the streets,'' reasoned
Howard Hamilton, chamber president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a problem here and I don't think we should hide our
heads in the sand,'' he said. ``I'm not advocating prostitution,
but it's out there and we should regulate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourism is by far Jamaica's most valuable industry, accounting
for 45 percent of its foreign exchange, for 13.7 percent of its
$6.2 billion gross domestic product (GDP), and for one in every
four jobs.
</P>
<P>
   This island of 2.5 million people welcomed 1.9 million visitors
last year, including 700,000 cruise ship passengers. About 60
percent came from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But harassment by overzealous prostitutes, drug dealers, taxi
drivers, hair braiders and curio vendors has taken its toll in a
country that has been hit hard over the last few years by the North
American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) -- losing dozens of foreign
businesses to lowered trade barriers between Canada, Mexico, and
the United States. After shrinking in both 1996 and 1997, Jamaica's
GDP is expected to do the same this year.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why the stakes are so high for this country so bent
on protecting the new mainstay of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   While the number of tourists who visit other Caribbean countries
is expected to jump by a whopping 7 percent this year, the number
who visit Jamaica is expected to climb by a mere 1-to-2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we had three cruise ships come in here a week, but
this year we only have one a week,'' said Rijhu Jagwani, owner of
the Glad Rags store in Montego Bay. ``There's no question that
harassment has driven some tourists away, and this is hurting
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, persistent heckling threatens to ``kill the goose that
lays the golden egg,'' warned Prime Minister P.J. Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to refuse to come to Jamaica because of
harassment, resulting in a virtual collapse of the tourism industry
so that there'll be no jobs for anyone at all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Holland America and Celebrity cruise lines have pulled
out of Montego Bay, partly because travelers were reporting
discomfort during their stops there.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey by the Jamaica Tourist Board, 56 percent
of visitors to Jamaica last year said they'd been harassed at some
point during their stays. Of that number, 60 percent had been asked
to buy drugs and 13 percent said the incidents had spoiled their
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson has so far not commented on Hamilton's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   But Patterson has initiated a government crackdown on
harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Signs have gone up alongside many highways directed at Jamaicans
that say: ``Tourism Is Everyone's Business.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, the penalties for first-time offenders who bother
tourists to buy or barter for drugs, sex and souvenirs were raised
100-fold, from $27 to $2,700. The penalties for repeat offenders
were increased from $41 to $4,100.
</P>
<P>
   Night courts were established so that law-enforcement officers
can appear in court without having to abandon their beats.
</P>
<P>
   But while big fines might deter those with a legitimate business
who have a lot to lose, it's not clear how they will affect the
marginal players, the unemployed people trying to eke out a living
with few options to choose from.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel McCook, a spokesman for the Jamaica Tourist Board,
concedes that it's not easy to haul violators before the courts on
charges of harassment or solicitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a sensitive issue because on one hand you want to
encourage visitors to interact with average Jamaicans so that they
learn about the culture, but on the other hand you don't want
visitors to feel uncomfortable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At least with red-light districts, Hamilton contends,
streetwalking prostitutes wouldn't be a bother.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's proposed that the government require medical
certification for the brothels and regular testing of the
prostitutes for sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
   He said the districts could be modeled after the aptly named
Campo Alegre, or Camp of Happiness -- the government-operated
red-light district in Curacao.
</P>
<P>
   As a Dutch possession, prostitution is legal on that island and
is regulated by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Located on a hill near the airport, Campo Alegre resembles a
prison camp, and is guarded by policemen.
</P>
<P>
   The Jamaica Council of Churches has blasted Hamilton's proposal,
issuing a statement that instructs chamber members to ask
themselves whether they would recommend prostitution for their own
sons and daughters.
</P>
<P>
   But Hamilton argues that with unemployment already nearing 20
percent, drastic action is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got an economic situation in this country where people
are desperate to find jobs so of course they flock to the tourist
areas because it's the only place they can make money, but they're
scaring away the tourists,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Making people even more desperate is the rising popularity of
all-inclusive resorts. Tourists tend to tether themselves there and
not make themselves available to the hawkers and small business
owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``People offering things are more assertive now,'' McCook said.
``The manner of selling has gotten more offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
