<HEADER>
A7686 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELARUS-PUPPET-$ADV29     08-28 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELARUS-PUPPET-$ADV29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN OLD-STYLE COMMUNIST BELARUS, CENSORS PUSH 'PINOCCHIO' OFF
MINSK STAGE
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Aug. 29 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CEZARY GOLINSKI 
 &HT;    c.1998 Special to the Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINSK, Belarus _ The Soviet Union has collapsed and the Moscow
nights swing nowadays, but back here in Minsk old communist-style
think is still the norm.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of ``Pinocchio.'' The Belorussian version of the
traditional puppet show for children was yanked off the Minsk stage
not long ago when critics saw too many allusions to the current
nasty political scene in the play.
</P>
<P>
   How could a mere children's show cause so much offense in this
dictator-run land? That's easy. To begin with, Ales Surau, the set
designer, dressed the wooden ``actors'' in contemporary quilted
jackets, Russian workers' caps and workers' rubber boots.
</P>
<P>
   That act alone aroused the ire of the nation's critics. ``The
peasants look like criminals. I was at a collective farm not long
ago and I saw people there who were very well-dressed,'' one them
complained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pinocchio,'' or ``Lipawiczki,'' as the Belorussian version is
known, had been a big hit when it played earlier this year at the
Puppet Theater in Grodno, a provincial center that's a lot less
uptight than this rigid capital -- which is under the all-watchful
eye of Belarus President Alexander Lukashenko.
</P>
<P>
   But when the play was shifted from Grodno to the Creative
Laboratory in the Puppet Theater here, located across from the
residence of the president, nothing apparently went right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole circle of critics came to see it,'' Surau, the
designer, recalled. ``But when they gathered there, they went into
shock. What had made people laugh in Grodno caused fear in the
capital.''
</P>
<P>
   As a backdrop for the puppets, Surau designed a three-foot
garland that bore a striking resemblance to the new Belorussian
national emblem -- a Lukashenko creation that the president had
made to replace the historical version.
</P>
<P>
   Surau added what he called ``a creative modification'' to the
new post-Soviet emblem. His garland consisted of fake bananas,
coconuts, pineapples and green tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to stress the idyllic character and agricultural
significance of the performance,'' Surau said with a straight face.
</P>
<P>
   To further his rather mild anti-government parody, in the center
of the garland he placed a globe. And in the center of the globe he
painted a tractor, built by the state tractor factory and known as
``The Belorussia.''
</P>
<P>
   The tractor occupied the exact spot on the map where Minsk
should have been. And on the left side of the map was another
perceived slight: a small Catholic Church in the place of his home
town of Grodno.
</P>
<P>
   To add to the insults against the official line, the walls of
the stage were covered with the presidential newspaper ``Sovietska
Belarus,'' instead of ordinary wallpaper. And in the ``windows''
there were border posts, painted in red and green stripes, where
the actual action of the play took place.
</P>
<P>
   The performance consisted of two plots -- a play within a play.
</P>
<P>
   One plot line followed the traditional battle between good and
evil, as the wooden boy brought joy to the hearts of his father and
fought off evil in the form devilish cats. The other plot focused
on the life of a present-day Belorussian family who had lived for
70 years on a collective farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the wall of the peasant hut hung a very simple radio,''
Surau said, one which could tune in only one station.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the basic object of equipment in every village home,''
he pointedly noted. ``A few times during the play the national
anthem resounded from the radio. This same one which awakens people
every day at six in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The critics were indignant that we had insulted the national
anthem. But it was really they who actually insulted it because
when they watched the performance, they never once stood up. When I
reminded them of this, they began to shout: 'You can't order us
when to stand up.'''
</P>
<P>
   The loyal critics also went ballistic over another scene that
they thought insulted Lukashenko. It depicted a peasant on the
collective farm reading the ``Sovietska Belarus'' newspaper and
thinking out loud, ``Who is the most beautiful person in our
country?'' and answering ``It's well known who.''
</P>
<P>
   After the critics complained, officials ordered the play off the
stage, supposedly to be ``polished up.'' Although the Minsk
audiences, minus the critics, loved it, the play has yet to be
revived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to say whether we were dealing with critics or
censors, the outspoken Surau said. ``I guess they were critics who,
out of fear, took on the role of censors.''
</P>
<P>
   (Cezary Golinski, is the Belarus correspondent of ``Gazeta
Wyborcza,'' a leading Polish newspaper published in Warsaw and
other Polish cities.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
