</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CANDIDATE FEELS A DOWNWARD PULL FROM CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLYMPIA, Wash. -- Perhaps because he is a clinical psychologist
or perhaps because he is the type of enthusiastic congressional
aspirant either party would like to recruit, the candidate is
compellingly candid. ``Three weeks ago,'' Brian Baird says,
``people were saying about the president, `Get off his back.' Now
there's a profound sense of disappointment. If you try to defend
the president, you run into questions like `Isn't character
important?' Character is tremendously important, and that's where
the president let us down. It's sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Baird, a Democrat, is on a bus, zooming along I-5, pointing out
Mount Rainier and Mount St. Helens to Dick Gephardt, telling the
House minority leader that the Columbia River needs dredging. In
1996, Baird lost to Republican Representative Linda Smith by 887
votes. She opted to seek a US Senate seat and Baird, running
nonstop for three years, seems stronger than any of the four
Republicans in the Sept. 15 primary for the 3d Congressional
District in southwestern Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a specter from what folks here call ``the other Washington''
clouds his optimism. ``You try to organize, get every voter out,
and something happens,'' he says. In 1996, Bill Clinton carried
this district with 49 percent, the same as his nationwide total.
Baird wants to discuss Social Security, education, and health care,
but confronts voter discontent with Clinton, which mushroomed after
the president's televised address Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``As frustrated as people are, they do want to put it behind
us,'' Baird says. In his psychology classes at Pacific Lutheran
University, ``I teach responsibility,'' he says. He fingers
Clinton, not Kenneth Starr, as the distraction to his campaign:
``It's his fault that people are talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   For Gephardt, distractions usually are speed bumps on his
disciplined, on-message salesman's mission. He has spent a Willy
Loman week, out there with a shoeshine and a smile among places
like Scranton, Bloomington, Dubuque, Janesville, and Olympia,
trying to win back the House for the Democrats. But he, too, faces
the reality of impeachment and doesn't shy from the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't jump to conclusions,'' he says at every stop.
``We don't know what the report from Ken Starr will say or even if
there will be a report. I hope there's nothing in it. But whatever
happens, we will deal with it in an objective, fair, and just
manner. This must not be a partisan street brawl.''
</P>
<P>
   This wait-and-see attitude is shared by the man Gephardt wants
to replace, Speaker Gingrich. In the deepest recesses of their wish
list, neither Gephardt nor Gingrich wants a premature inauguration
of President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt's reputation for rectitude is such that he sounds
risque when he says, ``You might say I have gavel envy.'' He calls
Clinton's conduct ``reprehensible,'' enunciating each syllable.
This does not please the White House, but does serve as an
etiquette tip to House candidates in close contests on how to
distance themselves discreetly from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding ``a partisan street brawl'' is both statesmanlike and
practical. Such a squabble could depress turnout, a grim prospect
for Gephardt and for candidates like Brian Baird. Asked if he has
met any voters who say they're so disgusted they just won't vote,
he candidly says ``Yes, about one percent, I'd say.'' Baird also
notes that in 1996, he lost by three-eighths of one percent. The
numbers for Gephardt are sobering. Republicans hold an edge of 11
seats in today's House. ``We expect to pick up five or six seats,''
he says. But with some expected losses of current Democratic seats,
he really needs about 16 victories.
</P>
<P>
   Like another notable redhead from St. Louis, Mark McGwire,
Gephardt is battling history. Hitting 62 home runs may be easier
than winning an off-year victory for a party headed by a president
with a muted message and tattered coattails.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
