<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISITING THE HIGH-TECH WORLD OF AUTO DESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your next car is being designed by mathematicians _ number
crunchers who spend long hours bending things, inventing computer
models, and wade gleefully through miles of printouts to perfect
the widgets and whatsits that go into a modern car. To me, at
least, there is some fun in this boring work; the lab has moved
onto the track.
</P>
<P>
   I spent a fruitful afternoon at Ford's Technical Center in
Dearborn, Mich., last week watching the crunchers crunch and
participating in some on-the-track testing exercises. The
demonstration pitted a new Mercury Cougar against a Mitsubishi
Eclipse in the Lommel Lane Change, an exercise named for Ford's
test center in Belgium. Both cars are wired, instrumented, and
equipped with a high-tech addition to the steering wheel to measure
driver input precisely.
</P>
<P>
   Lasers mounted on the car establish a reference plane parallel
with the driving surface, and computers record every deviation,
every twitch of the chassis. At 40 miles per hour through the
course, my seat-of-the-pants sense was that the Cougar was flatter
through the hard turns, exhibited less body roll, and, therefore,
could make it through the course somewhat faster than the Eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   The generous array of computer printouts and graphs depicting my
runs through the course verified that my seat-of-the-pants sense
was on target that day _ measurements don't lie.
</P>
<P>
   And then it occurred to me _ just who or what is being tested
here? Were the media reps participating being evaluated to to
establish a baseline against which to judge their car reviews?
Instead of merely saying that so-and-so doesn't know what he is
talking about, will Ford have a data base to prove it?
</P>
<P>
   The engineers I dumped this on looked at first shocked, then
amused _ apparently they hadn't thought of that yet. But then,
journalists naturally seem to have a conspiratorial bent in their
thinking. And now that we've brought it up ....
</P>
<P>
   Your columnist will delve deeper into the complexity of car
design in future episodes of Automobilia; knowing what the
engineers can achieve should give the consumer some insight into
what he/she should be looking to find in a car.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are giants among us whose labors go largely unnoticed in
the clamor of everyday life _ until suddenly they are no longer
there. Such was Carl S. Amsley, 77, of St. Thomas, Pa., who died in
his sleep a week ago today.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Amsley? Not exactly a household word in the automotive
world but something of a legend in the steam automobile fraternity,
a virtual deity among owners of Stanley Steamers _ Amsley bought,
sold, owned, repaired, or rebuilt more Stanleys than any other man
perhaps since the Stanley twins packed in the business in the
1920s, but at least since Fred Marriott closed his shop in the
'50s.
</P>
<P>
   Amsley was one of the few keepers of the steam automotive flame
in a world focused on V-8s. In the words of Susan S. Davis,
director of the Stanley Museum, ``When steam technology and
Stanleys were falling through the cracks, Amsley was guarding those
cracks.''
</P>
<P>
   I first met Amsley in 1984 on a trip to Kingfield, Maine, to
find out what was up with a fledgling Stanley Museum and see what
steam cars were all about. Amsley was standing in the doorway of a
barn on Stanley Avenue, taking shelter from a shower, beer in hand,
a broad smile on his face as he whipped out a business card
proclaiming ``Stanley Sales &AMP; Service.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the only Stanley dealer still in business,'' he announced.
And he never did stop selling Stanleys _ the car, the idea, the
legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ever ridden in a Stanley?'' he finally asked me, and, upon
getting a negative reply, led me to a car sitting in the museum
parking lot, an early ``coffin nose'' with a mother-in-law seat
behind the driver and passenger seats. The car smelled of burning
oil, diffusing heat, hissing oh so slightly as it stood ready, its
pilot light maintaining steam pressure in the boiler. We climbed
aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hold this,'' he said as he thrust the still full bottle into
my hand, opened the throttle, and sent the car chuffing through the
streets of Kingfield. As Amsley warmed to his task, the steamer
picked up real speed, a somewhat scary experience for the
uninitiated clinging to a seat sans seatbelt, perched high off the
street in this open antique.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch this,'' said Amsley, beaming, as he missed a station
wagon by about a coat of paint and sent the Stanley sliding across
the museum parking lot up on two wheels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, what do you think about Stanleys now?'' he asked. I
countered with a question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you always drive your car like that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell no,'' he roared back. ``This ain't my car.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it wasn't, not that day, anyway. But if he hadn't owned it
at some time, you can bet he had worked on it. A contractor by
trade, Amsley began an affair with steam in the 1950s when steamers
were a drag on the market, mostly junkers for sale cheap. Amsley
traded, bought, sold, learned, built, proselytized, taught steam
and steamers. He invented a new class of car, the ``sweepings,'' a
car assembled from random collections of Stanley parts with a few
new pieces thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   Amsley became the source, the resident expert, and butt of many
a joke _ he was frequently credited with keeping 500 of the 400 or
so remaining Stanleys running, a reference to his building cars
from odd parts.
</P>
<P>
   But, that's exactly why he was important; he kept Stanleys
running. Amsley was a force for the automotive hobby. If some of
his cars can be criticized in the light of current-day restoration
and provenance standards, there is still ample cause to praise him
for keeping them in existence and plenty of reason to praise his
craftsmanship. When few people cared about steam, Amsley was the
person to whom those few turned for parts, cars, service, help, and
enthusiastic encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanley Museum has become the center of focus for the steam
hobby, a clearinghouse for those seeking expertise, cars, parts, or
just information. Interest in steam and Stanleys has grown
exponentially in the last 10 years. Amsley was a charter member and
enthusiastic supporter of the museum. Several who knew him have
established a memorial fund in his name at the museum _ you can
write to the Stanley Museum, Box 280, Kingfield, ME 04947 or
telephone 207-265-2729 for details.
</P>
<P>
   Amsley's middle name wasn't Stanley, but it might as well have
been. He left quite a legacy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Industry bible Automotive News reports that General Motors is
now pressuring its suppliers for discounts _ in cash. Up front. Is
this the action of a company serious about cutting costs _ or is
this the symptom of a cash-strapped company in dire straits?
</P>
<P>
   The General has also terminated any effort to acquire Kia, the
ailing Korean car company. GM has been courting Korean firms for a
long time, once had a partnership with Daewoo _ remember the
subcompact Tracer? But the talk continues of closing old factories
and building new ones.
</P>
<P>
   So, how much did GM lose in the strike? And just how cash-short
is the General?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For the on-line browsers, I'll be available to chat on line
about cars Tuesdays, 2 p.m. to 3 p.m. Just point your Internet
browser to http://www.boston.com and enter the keyword chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 1530EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7714 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STYLES-WEDDINGS-$ADV3     08-28 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLES-WEDDINGS-$ADV30-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEDDING DRESS THAT ATE HOLLYWOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday Aug. 30)  
(js) 
 By AMY M. SPINDLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the only formal party some people are ever invited to. It's
the only couture dress many women will ever own. It's the only
catered event many people ever attend. There's no mystery to why
people love weddings and are thrilled to sit through them again and
again. And in today's popular culture, geared to pander and give
the people what they want and only what they want, audiences are
getting plenty of opportunity to sit through weddings. Again and
again.
</P>
<P>
   From all the wedding movies, weddings in sitcoms, issues of
magazines devoted to weddings and from the sheer size of the
traditional ``grand finale'' wedding dresses on the runways right
now, it might be reasonable to guess that there are more weddings
than ever. There aren't. Bride's magazine's statistics show that
the number of weddings per year in the United States has hovered
steadily around 2.4 million since the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   What's changed is that now there are ways to measure exactly how
much the country loves weddings, whether it's circulation of
magazines, Nielsen ratings, or box-office receipts. It's been
proven that weddings sell. That's why, after the success of ``Four
Weddings and a Funeral,'' ``My Best Friend's Wedding'' and ``The
Wedding Singer,'' there are dozens of movies with ``wedding'' or
``bride'' in the title in development.
</P>
<P>
   Even fashion seems to be surrendering its former snobbism about
weddings; Vogue came out with its first-ever bridal issue in June.
And instead of the subdued bridal gowns that once closed the runway
shows, designers are sending out enormous made-for-television
bridal dresses. There are weddings during the soap-opera sweeps,
and weddings, or almost weddings, in pilot episodes of every
television show from the new ``Will and Grace'' to ``Friends'' to
``Suddenly Susan'' to ``ER'' And weddings, or weddings canceled by
cold feet, in the last television shows of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the tradition in TV,'' said Garry Marshall, the
former television producer, who directed the movie ``Pretty
Woman.'' ``When your ratings went down, you turned it into a
wedding. We got Fonzie married, we got Richie married, we got Mork
married. We almost got Laverne married. We got Shirley married.
Brides and sweeps weeks go together in TV. When you leave it out,
they ask you about it. I know when I did `Pretty Woman,' a lot of
the comments were: `Why didn't you go one more scene? Why didn't
you have the wedding?' ''
</P>
<P>
   When Marshall reunites Julia Roberts and Richard Gere for
``Runaway Bride,'' to be released next summer, there's not one
wedding, he said, but ``four or five weddings, depending on the
rewrite.'' Ms. Roberts plays a serial jilter, always leaving the
man at the altar; Gere plays a journalist hired to write about her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Other Sister,'' Marshall's film to be released in March,
starring Diane Keaton and Juliette Lewis, has two weddings in it.
He's also producing a documentary for Showtime, tied in to the
millennium, for May 1999. Directors were asked to expound on a
theme. Barry Levinson (``Wag the Dog'') got the future; Marshall
got weddings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the Wedding Master,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There's competition for that title. ``Polish Wedding,''
``Wedding Band'' and ``My Best Friend's Wedding'' were released
this year. In ``The Wedding Singer,'' Drew Barrymore falls for a
wedding singer. And in ``Picture Perfect,'' Jennifer Aniston falls
for a man who videotapes weddings. Next, there will be ``Cupid's
Love,'' in which Jennifer Love Hewitt plays a wedding planner who
falls for a client.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood is nothing if not efficient at marrying its most
lucrative genres. So there's already a slasher sequel with a bride
and high-school students: ``Bride of Chucky,'' Chucky being the
nasty little killer doll from ``Child's Play.'' In it, Chucky
befriends a bride doll named Tiffany, who goes on a murder spree in
her wedding gown, as they tag along with eloping high-school
students. This movie belongs in the Pandering Pantheon.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not going to end when all the heterosexuals are happily
married off.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many movies in development that cover gay
weddings,'' said Paul Rudnick, who wrote the screenplay for ``In
and Out,'' in which Joan Cusack's character is left at the altar
when Kevin Kline's character comes out. ``Lesbian weddings have the
potential for double the chiffon, and a drag wedding can
extrapolate into infinity,'' Rudnick said.
</P>
<P>
   It may be time to remake ``Seven Brides for Seven Brothers,''
while everyone's in the mood. Seven brides! Seven bridal dresses!
Forty-two bridesmaids! Think of the comedic possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Bride's magazine's February/March issue was some 1,160 pages and
weighed 4.4 pounds, which may have led to Vogue's doing its own
bridal issue in June. ``Certainly the fact we were in the Guinness
Book of World Records and there are so many people interested in
marketing to the bride and groom had an impact,'' said Millie
Martini-Bratten, the magazine's editor. ``We're seeing many more
advertisements with the icon of the bride and groom.'' That
includes television commercials for products not at the top of
anyone's bridal registry, like Pepsi, Tylenol, Met Life, Buick and
Dockers. The magazine's slogan after all is ``Where love meets
money.''
</P>
<P>
   In Style has an annual celebrity wedding issue in February, with
everything you ever wanted to know about events like the Kelsey
Grammer nuptials. ``The funny thing is, as cynical as a marketer
may be, I don't think there's any cynicism on the part of the
consumer,'' said Hal Rubenstein, the fashion editor of In Style.
``The consumer wants this desperately. You can tell it from the
letters; you can tell it from the reader response.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the celebrity weddings themselves have become powerful
marketing tools for the plethora of magazines that now cover the
lives of the stars. Barbra Streisand marries, and People magazine
sells more issues. And when cool young people like Uma Thurman and
Ethan Hawke wed, it changes the reputation of the event itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uma was eight months' pregnant when I did her dress,'' said
Vera Wang, the designer. ``You can't get much hipper than that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   She said that young celebrities, whom women throughout the
country copy, want traditional weddings. Like the ones in the
movies. ``I keep expecting the Hollywood weddings to be hipper,
modern and offbeat, and they end up with weddings that are the most
traditional,'' Ms. Wang said. ``I'm doing Posh Spice's wedding
dress, and that's pretty much the height of what's happening right
now among young people. When we came into weddings in the '80s,
weddings were happening, but when people around in the media
thought of weddings, they'd stick their finger down their throat.''
</P>
<P>
   The media, obviously, have gotten over that reflex.
</P>
<P>
   And that's good news for designers. The tradition of closing
each runway show with a wedding dress has been around for years,
but today's dresses have never been rivaled for their size. Yohji
Yamamoto's fall show had perhaps the largest ever; it practically
had to be turned on its side to fit through the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``The runway becomes more exaggerated, and that is the
entertainment value of it all,'' said Richard Martin, the curator
of the Costume Institute at the Metropolitan Museum of Art. ``If
you assume the wedding dress is the symbolic finale, it makes sense
that it's going to be more hyperbolic than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   It is one more sign of how utterly populist runway shows have
become, having to appeal, like movies and television shows, to the
widest audience possible. Maybe it's that today, the only way to
eke an emotion out of an overloaded audience _ whether sitting by a
runway, in front of a television set, in a movie theater or reading
a magazine _ is to throw a bride at it and hope for the best.
</P>
<P>
   Are we all really as simplistic as that? Actually, the better
question might be, ``Are we all as lazy as that?'' Not only are
writers clinging to the possibility of connubial bliss more
fervently than Mickey Rooney and Elizabeth Taylor put together, but
so are their audiences. Are we so lazy that someone must offer us
the quickest shortcut to emotion possible? After all, sending a
model down the runway in an exploded wedding dress, or marrying off
the star of a television show or movie, or putting a bride on a
magazine cover tells us a lot. It tells us about conventionality.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences might eventually get bridal overload. Or perhaps all
1,000 ways to marry that Marshall has found in researching his
documentary might get used up. Fortunately, blockbuster movies,
unlike designers, have other rituals and ceremonies to use, besides
weddings, to gain instant box-office success.
</P>
<P>
   Like funerals. P.J. Hogan, the director of ``Muriel's Wedding''
and ``My Best Friend's Wedding'' (hilarity ensues after a woman
flies in for her best friend's wedding), is moving on to funerals
in his next film, ``Unconditional Love'' (hilarity ensues when a
woman flies in for her idol's funeral).
</P>
<P>
   But how are fashion designers going to find a fresher way to
pander?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe designers can borrow some suggestions from television,
which is much more their medium today than mere fashion is anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Besides weddings, said David Kohan, an executive producer for
``Will and Grace,'' there are the standard heart-tugging plot
points like ``pregnancy, moving to a new place, starting over,
getting a new job, graduating, any big life change.''
</P>
<P>
   But models in caps and gowns probably won't have the same
effect. Too many of them drop out of school.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
