<HEADER>
A7717 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHARK-BIT-HNS &LR;      08-28 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARK-BIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN SURVIVES RARE BRUSH WITH SHARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY DELGADO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When razor-sharp teeth attached to a 2,000-pound
eating machine known as a great white shark rip through your skin,
it's a good idea to fight back. And, hopefully, you'll have a
friend handy to help.
</P>
<P>
   A San Rafael boy learned that lesson firsthand Wednesday
afternoon and is on the road to recovery after fighting off the
ocean's most fearsome predator in an encounter at Stinson Beach,
which is part of the Golden Gate National Recreation Area.
</P>
<P>
   A great white shark attacked Jonathan Kathrein, 16, while he was
awaiting a wave on his boogie board in shallow waters. It was the
first reported shark attack at the popular beach.
</P>
<P>
   Kathrein suffered several piercing wounds to his right thigh. A
foot-long gash stretches from just above his right knee to the
bottom of his buttocks.
</P>
<P>
   Kathrein, who spoke at John Muir Medical Center in Walnut Creek
Thursday, said the ordeal began with a little nudge from a curious
attacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been hit by jellyfish before, but I knew this was
different,'' he said. ``What hit me was fleshy and was hard like
cartilage. My first thought was that it was a shark.''
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 10 seconds later, the shark bit through his wet suit and
clamped down on his right leg, pulling him off his board and
underwater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would take my leg,'' he said. ``Then I thought it
would eat me. I was definitely scared, but I was not hysterical.''
</P>
<P>
   Instinct kicked in, and Kathrein shoved his hands into the
shark's gills until it let go. He then climbed onto his board and
screamed for help until a friend swimming nearby and a lifeguard
came to his rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Examination of Kathrein's wet suit confirmed a great white 6
feet to 8 feet long was the culprit, said Ed Ueber, sanctuary
manager for the Gulf of the Farallones National Marine Sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Following the attack, officials with the Golden Gate National
Recreation Area closed Stinson Beach for a week as a precaution.
Lifeguards conducted periodic patrols but did not see any sharks,
said spokeswoman Suzanne Summers. Although two beachgoers reported
possible shark sightings, lifeguards determined the dorsal fins
they saw most likely belonged to porpoises, Summers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that we monitor shark activity in the area for
everyone's safety,'' Summers said. ``People can still enjoy the
beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts who study great white sharks said they were not shocked
by the attack: Stinson Beach is bordered by two rocky areas popular
with seals and sea lions, among sharks' favorite food.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attack doesn't surprise me,'' said John McCosker, resident
shark expert with the California Academy of Sciences in Golden Gate
Park. ``What surprises me is that it hasn't happened sooner.
There's so many people in the water at Stinson Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are well over 100 great whites swimming in the waters
of Northern California during their high season of August through
November looking for food, raising the stakes for some unpleasant
encounters.
</P>
<P>
   Their territory is called the Red Triangle, stretching from
Bodega Bay to the Farallon Islands and down to Santa Cruz, one of
the most densely populated areas in the world for the great white
shark.
</P>
<P>
   Although great white attacks in Northern California seem few and
far between, they occur with some regularity compared to other
parts of the world. A good year for swimmers will see no attacks,
but there have been as many as three in one year and 79 along the
entire California coast since 1950.
</P>
<P>
   Because sharks are so hard to study, experts cannot explain why
the Red Triangle is such a populated territory, although the most
logical reason is the abundant food source, Ueber said.
</P>
<P>
   What's important to understand about shark attacks, experts say,
is that great whites do not care to make dinner out of human flesh.
The sharks, which can reach 20 feet to 30 feet long, typically feed
on blubber-rich seals and sea lions who populate the coastline and
the Farallones, a common breeding ground.
</P>
<P>
   When they do attack humans, they mistake them for a seal or sea
lion and rarely return to feed, even if the victim dies in the
water, Ueber said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the fattest of humans doesn't compare to a healthy
seal,'' Ueber said. ``We're talking 4 to 5 inches of blubber.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An attack from a great white is swift and painful and usually
occurs in water 20 to 30 feet deep. The shark will typically spot
its prey _ be it marine mammal or human _ floating at the surface
and shoot up toward it in a burst of speed, clamping enormous jaws
around the victim and biting down hard.
</P>
<P>
   Once the shark grabs a victim, it might pull the prey under
water for a few seconds and then let go to avoid the victim's
defense mechanisms. The shark usually hangs around until the victim
bleeds to death and then begins feeding on the carcass.
</P>
<P>
   ``They back off and wait for it to die because they don't want
to encounter this struggling animal,'' McCosker said. ``It's at
risk by trying to consume an angry sea lion.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, said Ueber, if the shark is uncertain of what the
prey is, it may nudge it first, as was reported in Wednesday's
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Sharks usually attack during the daylight because of better
visibility, experts believe, although there is not enough known
about a shark's nighttime patterns to be certain, McCosker said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
