<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; RUSSIAN UNCERTAINTY AND MARKET TURMOIL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans an extensive package of stories
relating to political and economic turmoil and Russia and its
impact around the world.
</P>
<P>
   These stories are being edited by The Times'  &UR; Foreign Desk &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-RDP (Moscow) _ Developments in Moscow, efforts to calm
the political and economic frenzy. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-YELTSIN (Moscow) _ Boris Yeltsin, in TV interview, says
he will not resign. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S. (Washington) _ The view of the Russian turmoil from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S.-SUMMIT (Washington) _ How next week's plans for a
Clinton-Yeltsin summit meeting are affected by the current
developments. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-GERMANY (Frankfurt) _ The effect of Russian crisis on the
coming German elections. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   NY-RUSSIANS (New York) _ The mood among Russian immigrants in
Brooklyn as their former homeland is engulfed by crisis. By Jim
Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   These will be edited by The Times'  &UR; Financial Desk &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks open higher, flatten out, then move
into negative territory. At 1:15 p.m., the industrial average was
off 52 points and the Nasdaq index was off 395 points. At midday,
the long bond was off 2/32 point, with the yield at 5.35 percent.
By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ One statistic stands out to explain the
importance of Japan, along with its misery: When trading ended
Friday in Tokyo, Japanese stocks this week alone had dropped in
value by $241 billion _ a sum that exceeds the size of the entire
Russian economy at present exchange rates. In other words, in one
glum week's work, Japan managed the financial equivalent of wiping
Russia off the world map. Japan is so monumental as to be central
to the health of the global economy, but for now it remains a mess,
albeit an impressively large one. A month after Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi took office, vowing ``to deal with each issue in a
dramatic, speedy way,'' Japan remains firmly in recession and
largely paralyzed politically and economically. By Nicholas D.
Kristof and Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-ECON (Hong Kong) _ Hong Kong's financial crisis is
gathering steam. The government on Friday went on the largest
buying spree yet in its two-week-old battle to hurt those betting
against stocks and the local currency. Still, the Hang Seng Index
fell 1.2 percent because the government stood virtually alone in
buying shares during the stock exchange's busiest day ever. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-FED (Jackson Hole, Wyo.) _ From the Fed's annual
conference, what the policy makers think. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-ECON (Mexico City) _ The problems are mounting in Latin
America, and the region's finance ministers will meet with the IMF
in Washington next week. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BANKAMERICA (Undated) _ BankAmerica says it has recorded
$220 million of trading losses this year, mostly in Russia. By
Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-SMALL-INVESTORS (New York) _ What the little investors
think of the markets. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-MARKETS (Rome) _ How European bourses fared. By John
Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   We will update this advisory as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
