<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARN-WALLSTREET-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOBS LOOK STEADY ON A LEANER WALL ST. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 30)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stockbrokers often complain that a customer never
remembers when their recommendations are proved right, but never
forgets when they're wrong.
</P>
<P>
   But if Wall Street, which makes a handsome living from its
ingrates, suffers these days from swooning prices, there is little
sign that this is putting many jobs at risk.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, brokerage houses expanded at breakneck speed as
the market and economy emerged from the doldrums, only to contract
after the 1987 crash. By contrast, the 1990s have been a time of
more sober hiring even as stock prices skyrocketed. ``In the past,
you've seen hiring booming and busting,'' said Bill Montgoris,
chief operating officer at Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. ``Now firms have
been much more cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   This suggests that even if the stock market plummets, job
casualties will remain few, mostly a result of mergers or confined
to niches like emerging markets, where disaster has already struck.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there would be a financial pinch _ probably more like a
squeeze _ for tens of thousands of people in the securities
business for whom annual bonuses have reached lavish proportions in
recent years and have driven average industry pay in New York last
year to $181,900, almost four times as much as the $48,800 earned
by the average city worker. (The securities business includes
investment banks as well as brokerage houses.)
</P>
<P>
   An analysis by the office of New York State Comptroller H. Carl
McCall concluded in August that in the event of a downturn,
``securities firms will likely reduce costs by lowering
compensation before resorting to layoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry's deliberate pace of hiring can be seen in the fact
that it wasn't until June that the New York City economy set a
record for the number of Wall Street jobs _ 164,300, according to
the Bureau of Labor Statistics. That eclipsed the 163,000 total in
1987, before the October crash. The reverberations of that crash
led to the loss of one in five securities firms and jobs by 1990,
said Jeffrey Schaefer, a consultant to the Securities Industry
Association, a trade group.
</P>
<P>
   But why has the latest bull market not led to even more hiring
on Wall Street? There is wide agreement on a main reason: Those who
run securities businesses today were chastened by 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not staffed as inappropriately as they were back
then,'' said Brian Sullivan, president of his own executive search
firm in New York that specializes in financial services. Moreover,
he observed, the economy is much stronger now and the industry's
``product line'' is broader and less reliant on junk bonds and
leveraged buyouts.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors that may lessen the industry's vulnerability to a
major market drop are vast improvements in technology and
efficiencies gleaned through mergers. An industry whose back
offices couldn't handle trading volume of 10 million shares a day
without expanded hours now breezes through 600 million shares a day
and more.
</P>
<P>
   After two companies combine, ``you can have two excellent people
but you only need one excellent person to do the job,'' said
Vincent Pica, a senior official at Prudential Securities. He said
Prudential had upgraded its staff by hiring people displaced by
mergers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, employment at member firms of the New York Stock Exchange
keeps climbing, by 3,384 in the first three months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're adding pretty much universally,'' said Sue Weiss,
employment vice president at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Co., which is based in
St. Louis and has 6,352 brokers in 615 offices. She said last week
that Edwards expected to add 450 to 550 employees this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more brokers, the more support they need,'' Ms. Weiss
said. The company has 228 more brokers than it did a year ago..
</P>
<P>
   Despite turmoil in many foreign currencies, officials say that
currency trading is one area in which job prospects are probably
fading. Mergers are one reason, but even more important is the
scheduled introduction in January of the euro, the European
currency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of firms have shut down their New York trading
operation'' to leave the field to better-equipped giants, Sullivan
said. ``There will be less business across the board _ you're
literally eliminating 11 currencies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
