A7751 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-401-COSTS-ART     08-28 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-401-COSTS-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUIDEBOOKS ON THE UNCERTAIN PATH TO A WELL-RUN 401(K) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Hawaii, Ariz., Mass., Calif., Md.)   (For release Sunday, Aug. 30)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the 200 workers at Hawaiian Host wanted a 401(k) plan, a
host of vendors eagerly offered their services. But Stacey
Nakasone, a human resources administrator at the Honolulu company,
which makes chocolate-covered macadamia nuts, said she was
overwhelmed trying to compare prices.
</P>
<P>
   Some vendors focused on their administrative costs while others
discussed investment fees; still others promoted special features
of their plans. ``We were taking a stab in the dark,'' Mrs.
Nakasone said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Public Service, the gas and electric utility in Phoenix,
faced a different problem. With 6,000 employees in two 401(k)
plans, it wanted to know if it was paying too much in trustee and
record-keeping fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most businesses really do not have a very good handle on the
costs of their 401(k) because they buy bundled services,'' said Jim
Margerum, a benefits department manager who was in charge of
examining the costs of the 401(k) plans for the utility, which buys
each service separately.
</P>
<P>
   Both administrators, though, were able to consult publications
that help employers analyze and compare costs of 401(k) plans.
</P>
<P>
   Using the ``(k)form Catalog'' from (k)la Publishing in San
Francisco, a committee of Hawaiian Host workers identified 79
potential vendors, then whittled the list to five. A final
selection is expected soon.
</P>
<P>
   Margerum turned to the ``401(k) Provider Directory Averages
Book,'' one of three such guides from HR Investment Consultants in
Baltimore. He found that Arizona Public's record-keeping and
trustee costs ``were very reasonable, very much in line'' with
those of companies of similar size.
</P>
<P>
   For benefits administrators across the country, the directories
offer help in reining in the costs of 401(k)'s. The Labor
Department has identified those costs as an important benefits
issue, and trade publications for benefits managers have written
about the employee lawsuits that companies may face if they do not
control 401(k) expenses.
</P>
<P>
   According to Stephen Butler, president of Pension Dynamics, a
401(k) consulting firm in Orinda, Calif., about a third of all
employers pay too much for their 401(k) plans and another third
waste money on features with little long-term value.
</P>
<P>
   Paying experts to invest the money, to prepare statements for
workers and to comply with government rules can easily cost $1 for
every $100 in the plan; some plans pay vendors more than twice that
amount. There are no hard standards, but the expense share tends to
shrink at bigger companies. The plan at Exxon, for example, costs
just 5 cents for each $100.
</P>
<P>
   Some benefits managers _ particularly at small- to medium-sized
companies just starting a 401(k) _ may have little experience with
such plans. The directories, by providing work sheets for
apples-to-apples comparisons of various expenses, help these
administrators shop for the best deals.
</P>
<P>
   A company with a long-established plan can use the directories,
too _ to help it switch to a less-expensive vendor. Perhaps a
company originally chose a vendor that charged low fees for
record-keeping and trustee services and little or no set-up fee;
the trade-off was that the vendor offered high-cost funds. The
company may decide that such a plan no longer meets its needs.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Schuster, benefits manager for Compuware Corp., a software
manufacturer in Farmington Hills, Mass., with 9,000 employees
worldwide, said that vendors frequently offer free administrative
services ``because for every dollar they make in administrative
fees, they make about $7 in investment fees.''
</P>
<P>
   A small company, of course, might find low start-up and
administrative costs very attractive. But a large company might not
mind a high start-up fee if the subsequent investment fees were
relatively low, giving workers more money when they retire.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, high costs can seriously erode the value of 401(k)
savings. For example, a worker who saves $2,000 annually for 30
years and earns 10 percent a year will have a nest egg of $345,437
before taxes at retirement. But if the fees charged to the plan
reduce the investment return by just one percentage point, to 9
percent, the worker will have just $286,246, or $59,000 less. If
the fees cut two percentage points off the return, the worker will
have just $237,895.
</P>
<P>
   Employers should check their 401(k) costs, said David Morse, a
compensation lawyer at Whitman Breed Abbott &AMP; Morgan in New York.
Companies that pay 401(k) fees out of the savings of workers, he
said, could ``be liable for breaching their fiduciary duty if they
choose vendors that charge excessive fees.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 1542EDT &QL; 
