<HEADER>
A7753 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTUND-401-SWITCH-ART     08-28 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTUND-401-SWITCH-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUFFLING THE RETIREMENT DECK IS EASIER, BUT FEW PLAY THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 30)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By MICKEY MEECE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the old days of 401(k) plans, if the stock market nose-dived
the way it did last week, participants who wanted to change their
allocations usually had to cool their heels for 30 or even 90 days.
Market timing was out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   These days, however, many 401(k) participants can shift assets
on the fly, moving money in or out of different categories of
stocks and bonds with a single phone call. And they can do so daily
if they want, with few restrictions and no penalties or fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier than ever for people to switch, and people have
more options available,'' said Tom Schlossberg, president and chief
executive of Diversified Investment Advisors in Purchase, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Some plans limit the number of times a participant can change
their asset allocations to four times a quarter, for example, or to
once a month. Some also restrict movement in and out of
fixed-income investments, to discourage participants from playing
interest rates, Schlossberg said. But these days the majority of
plans allow unlimited daily changes.
</P>
<P>
   When an investor moves ordinary assets around, capital gains on
sales are taxable right away. But gains in 401(k) plans are not
taxable until the assets are withdrawn, usually after retirement,
so there are significant tax advantages to using 401(k) assets to
satisfy any urge to time the market.
</P>
<P>
   While most 401(k) participants now have that opportunity, hardly
any are using it.
</P>
<P>
   Ned Burmeister, second vice president for pensions at Principal
Financial Group, a 401(k) administration company in Des Moines,
offered two possible reasons. Participants are either financially
savvy and know they are investing for the long haul, he said, or
they are paralyzed by inertia _ not knowing what to do, they do
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   During the market gyrations in July, Robert Rudell, president of
Scudder-Kemper Retirement Services in Boston, saw a slight uptick
in phone calls, but little shifting of money by its 350,000
participants. ``With so little activity in this current market
swing,'' Rudell said, it shows that ``we've done a pretty decent
job of education.''
</P>
<P>
   In its 401(k) index, which tracks the daily transfers of 1.4
million participants at large companies, Hewitt Associates, a
management consulting firm in Lincolnshire, Ill., has found that
fewer than 1 percent move money when the market goes haywire.
</P>
<P>
   For example, during the market crash of Oct. 27, 1997, the
Hewitt index showed four times its normal activity. But even so,
just under 1 percent of the participants made changes, transferring
two-tenths of 1 percent of their $62 billion in assets from stocks
to fixed-income investments.
</P>
<P>
   The same pattern has held true this year. On July 30, when the
Dow Jones industrial average and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index were both up over 1 percent, the index showed about twice the
average amount of switching activity _ mostly shifts from bonds to
stocks _ said Stacy Schaus, a Hewitt consultant. The next day, when
both stock indexes tumbled nearly 2 percent, the Hewitt index
showed that switching activity grew to three times the average as
participants moved from equities into fixed-income investments.
</P>
<P>
   The small minority who do such shifting might not be helping
themselves, Ms. Schaus said. Jumping to a different asset category
on the day of a plunge means that ``they're locking in a loss,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Most people do so thinking that they are timing the market, but
they often misunderstand a fundamental difference between changing
mutual fund allocations and buying or selling stocks directly.
</P>
<P>
   Karnig Durgarian, managing director and chief of Putnam
Investments' defined contribution business in Boston, observed that
in a typical plan, where the majority of assets are in mutual
funds, transactions do not take place until the end of the day. An
investor may call at 10 a.m. hoping to get out of a sliding market
early, but the assets must still ride out the day before being
transferred, he said. And if things look rosier the next morning, a
call at sunup to switch back before prices recover will also be
futile.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think you got back in early?'' he said. ``You didn't.''
Instead, the investor has absorbed all of the bad day's losses and
missed all of the good day's gains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 1542EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
