<HEADER>
A7757 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     08-28 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOONIES MAY BECOME 'BURBS ONE DAY ALL TOO SOON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOMEWHERE OUTSIDE OF BURLESON, Texas _ The hand-lettered sign
tacked to the utility pole was the first indication that city life
was far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of advertising help for an easy way to lose 10 pounds in
10 days, the note was letting the owner of a lost lamb know that
the little critter had been found and where to come get it.
</P>
<P>
   The official welcome took the form of a coyote serenade. With
the move into our new house, we traded the incessant yapping of a
neighbor's dachshund for the eerie predawn yips and howls from a
chorus of coyotes. We're much happier with the wild sounds,
although our cat's nocturnal strolls have been drastically
curtailed.
</P>
<P>
   The first time we heard high-pitched wails filling the air
before the sun tinged the sky pink came just hours after our
neighbor casually walked two wayward head of cattle across our
front yard.
</P>
<P>
   We definitely had left city life behind. The question now is:
For how long?
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I are part of that growing number of people
engaged in the process of reverse migration. Although we have not
yet forsaken urban jobs to live in the wilds of Montana, we tried
the next best thing by moving to a rural area beyond the busy
traffic loop that circles through Fort Worth and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   It's only a matter of time, however, before the city follows.
Urban exodus is happening all over the nation. Our specific journey
took us to the rural area south of Fort Worth, but counties to the
west of Cowtown are also experiencing explosive growth. According
to the North Central Texas Council of Governments, Johnson County
has experienced a population boom from 97,165 in 1990 to 112,800
this year. Building permits for single-family homes are up 30
percent in Parker, Johnson and Hood counties.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all the attributes that make rural living so
attractive _ no crowds, no traffic, no neighbor right over the back
fence _ wane as more and more people search for an escape from an
urban dwelling. The next thing you know, there will be zoning
restrictions, and permits needed to build a storage shed on your
own property, and emissions tests on automobiles, and a 10-minute
wait at the traffic light to get on the highway that leads to the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Rural life isn't for everyone. A move to the boonies comes with
compromises. Services that city folk take for granted _ rapid
response from public safety personnel, a hospital with a fully
equipped emergency room close by, municipal water and sewer lines _
aren't always available. You learn to live with septic systems and
volunteer fire departments and relying on the county sheriff _ and
yourself _ for crime protection.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, all members of the Labbe household are adjusting to
rural life. Our dog, a gentle giant of a German shepherd whose
previous brushes with wildlife were confined to chasing gray
squirrels up backyard trees, is mesmerized by the huge, lumbering
livestock that inhabit the acreage adjoining ours. Her first
glimpse of a cow stopped her dead in her tracks, as if she were
thinking, ``I've never seen squirrels this size before!''
</P>
<P>
   An instinct buried someplace deep within her shepherd soul
pushed her toward the bovine creatures quietly grazing across the
field, but she didn't appear sure of how to tap into what her
nature was telling her. A stamped hoof and a breathy snort from one
cow was enough to send the dog high-tailing it back to the safety
of the garage.
</P>
<P>
   It is so very quiet out here, in this place removed from the
white noise of highway traffic that was a constant backdrop to our
lives in the city. When a truck with an unmuffled engine does drive
by the house, it's such a jar to the senses that even the dog barks
_ the same dog that used to sleep through the next-door neighbor's
work on the noisy engine of his vintage Mustang.
</P>
<P>
   We know that more of you are coming, but it's OK with us if you
take your time.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Her e-mail address is
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com, and her phone number is (817)
390-7599. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
