<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7777 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-     08-28 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINCOLN-MERCURY ATTRACTING BOOMERS WITH UPSCALE SPORT-UTILITY
VEHICLES
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by CARS-GLANCE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, the luxury-car lines of Ford and General Motors have
struggled to draw well-heeled baby boomers into dealers' showrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Middle-age consumers have tended to associate Lincoln and
Cadillac products with their parents and have generally left those
cars to the older generation.
</P>
<P>
   But that's changing now. Lincoln-Mercury showrooms are busy
places, thanks to boomers' love affair with sport-utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury started bringing boomers into Lincoln-Mercury showrooms
with the Mountaineer, an upscale version of the best-selling Ford
Explorer sport-utility, a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But it is this week's test drive, the Lincoln Navigator, that
has dealerships really buzzing with boomers.
</P>
<P>
   The Navigator, like the Mountaineer, is an scale version of a
sport-utility being sold by the Ford division: the full-size Ford
Expedition.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced for the 1998 model year, the Navigator takes the
Expedition to a higher level with a revised exterior than includes
lots of chrome, an interior flush with leather and wood trim, and a
$40,000-plus price tag.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle, which is about 15 inches shorter than the
Texas-favorite Chevrolet/GMC Suburban, is priced way below three of
its intended competitors, the Toyota Land Cruiser and its clone,
the Lexus LX 470; and the Range Rover. Those vehicles start at
about $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Navigator also has a giant plus: Underneath, it's really a
Ford F-150 pickup, which is the nation's best-selling vehicle and
has a well-deserved reputation for toughness, reliability and
longevity.
</P>
<P>
   The downside, of course, is that being an F-150 underneath, the
Navigator is a truck, not a car. The ride, therefore, is not as
smooth as you would expect from a Town Car or Continental. It's not
bad, though, thanks in part to the standard load-leveling air
suspension. But if your bones are getting somewhat creaky, you
might want to go with a plush sedan.
</P>
<P>
   For me, a sport-utility is just fine, and the Navigator is one
of the best on the market. You could save $6,000-$12,000 by
choosing a less-cushy and less-well-equipped Expedition, of course,
but if you can afford the extra fare, the Navigator offers just
about everything you could want in a luxury SUV.
</P>
<P>
   It is powered by Ford's 230-horsepower, 5.4-liter V-8 engine,
connected to a smooth-shifting four-speed automatic transmission.
There is plenty of power to push this 5,000-pound vehicle. The
engine cranks out 325 foot-pounds of torque at 3,000 rpm, enough to
move the Navigator off the starting line with the rest of the SUV
pack.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if you are used to a similar V-8 engine powering a
sedan that is 1,500 pounds lighter, you might be a bit
disappointed. But those of you used to driving trucks and SUVs will
be pleased with the Navigator's power.
</P>
<P>
   Handling is what you'd expect from a large vehicle; it's not
real nimble, but it's not as clunky as a Suburban. And it will fit
in the standard garage and downtown parallel parking space, unlike
the Suburban. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The interior is plush, with leather, nice burled-walnut trim in
the dashboard and thick pile carpeting throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Standard seating includes bucket seats up front and in the
second row; a bench seat is in the third row, seating an additional
three people for a total of seven.
</P>
<P>
   Although our test vehicle came with the center-row bucket seats,
if I were ordering a Navigator I would choose the optional
three-passenger bench seat for the middle. It was awkward having
just four seats in the front part of the vehicle; a fifth person
going to lunch with me one day had to climb into the rear seat, not
an easy task for grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   With the third seat in place for passengers, there is not much
luggage space. That's where the Navigator comes up short compared
with the Suburban; that extra 15 inches in the Suburban is tacked
onto the cargo area. The Navigator's third seat can be folded down
easily to increase luggage space. Loading is easy; you can open the
whole tailgate by lifting it up, or open just the tailgate window
to sling grocery bags into the back.
</P>
<P>
   Navigator is available with two- or four-wheel drive. The
two-wheel-drive model carries a base price of $39,310 (plus $640
transportation). The four-wheel-drive version lists for $42,660.
</P>
<P>
   For my money, I would go with the four-wheel drive, even in
generally snowless Texas. Our test model was two-wheel drive, and I
found the tail-end slipping and sliding on wet pavement and losing
traction in turns. Those problems would be eliminated with the
four-wheel-drive system, which can be set to bring the front wheels
on line automatically when rear-wheel slippage is detected.
Besides, why buy half a truck when you can get a whole one for
$3,350 more?
</P>
<P>
   Although this really is an Expedition underneath, it looks like
a Lincoln, thanks to the chrome-edged, turbine-vane signature
grille.
</P>
<P>
   Safety equipment includes power four-wheel disc antilock brakes,
second-generation (depowered) driver and front-passenger air bags,
side-door protection beams, and rear-door child-safety locks.
</P>
<P>
   Automatic climate control is standard; our vehicle came with the
optional rear air-conditioning/heating unit ($705) to keep even the
rearmost passengers comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Navigator is a truck, sound-deadening materials
have made the interior nearly as quiet as that of a luxury sedan.
That makes it easy to carry on a conversation, or enjoy the nice
AM/FM/cassette stereo. A six-disc remote compact-disc changer is a
$595 option; the basic stereo can be upgraded to a 290-watt,
seven-speaker premium system for $355.
</P>
<P>
   Other standard features include cruise control, 16-inch aluminum
wheels, dual six-way power seats, digital clock, dual power
mirrors, fog lights, power door locks with remote control,
leather-wrapped tilt steering, power windows, rear privacy glass,
rear defroster, luggage rack and a trailer-towing package.
</P>
<P>
   Total price for our test vehicle was $40,800, including
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Maximum trailer weight is 8,000 pounds in the two-wheel-drive
model (with optional 3.73 rear-axle), and 7,700 pounds with the
four-wheel-drive version. The base two- wheel-drive can tow a
6,600-pound trailer.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings are 13 miles per gallon in the city and
17 mpg on the highway. The tank holds 30 gallons of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III writes on transportation issues for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. His mailing address is
Star-Telegram/Northeast, 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford,
Texas 76021; his E-mail address is chambers(at)star-telegram.com.
Fax: (817) 685-3883. Check out his Wheelin' new-car review column
weekly on the Internet at
ww.netarrant.net/today/news/opinions/necol.htm. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
