<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-WATCH-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNDS WATCH: FEELING THE PAIN OF CONCENTRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 30)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic on assets and total return for Yacktman is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don Yacktman has garnered quite a following over a three decade
career as a value investor. But loyalty, alas, can be fleeting.
Investors have abandoned his flagship Yacktman fund in droves as
returns have sputtered.
</P>
<P>
   Assets of the fund have shrunk 43 percent, to $616.4 million as
of Aug. 21 from $1.08 billion in December 1997. The fund returned
18.3 percent last year, well below the average 23.7 percent return
for mid-capitalization blend funds, which may hold a range of
different-sized companies and tend to invest with a combination of
growth and value styles. The underperformance continued this year:
Yacktman dropped 5.8 percent through Aug. 21 while its peers eked
out a gain of one-half percent, according to Morningstar Inc., the
Chicago financial publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Still, bailing out now is probably the wrong thing to do,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of concentrated funds is that they're volatile,''
said Amy Granzin, an equity analyst at Morningstar, referring to
the relatively small number of stocks _ 23 _ in the fund's
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Stolper, a financial consultant in San Diego, said
investors should take a longer-term outlook. ``Our view is that
he's been less than optimal over the last two years, but we measure
performance over 10 years. What happens in shorter periods is
almost random.''
</P>
<P>
   The poor performance stands in sharp contrast to Yacktman's
earlier record as manager of Selected American Shares, which he ran
from 1983 until 1992, when he left to start his own fund company.
During his tenure, Selected American, a large-cap value fund, had
an annualized return of 17.6 percent, exceeding the 14.1 percent of
its peers and the 16.7 percent of the Standard and Poor's 500-stock
index. In 1991, Yacktman was named Morningstar's manager of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   He earned those returns using a disciplined approach to
unearthing out-of-favor growth companies with high returns on
tangible assets, few fixed assets and a high turnover of products
and services. Most important for Yacktman is how a company uses its
cash, a key point of departure from many value investors. The best
use of cash, he says, is reinvesting in the business or making
acquisitions that fit well with existing operations. He prefers
management that buys back shares. Less favorable uses, he says, are
paying down debt or paying dividends.
</P>
<P>
   In managing his new fund, however, Yacktman felt free to abandon
the big-company tilt he used so successfully at Selected American.
Over the past two years, he has sold off many large-cap holdings,
notably drug stocks like Bristol-Myers Squibb, Pfizer and Merck,
which he thought had reached full valuation, and looked for
opportunities in smaller companies.
</P>
<P>
   But the shift took place during a period when the market favored
larger stocks and the fund has suffered accordingly. With currency
devaluations and other global problems, ``a lot of people threw
money at America as a safe haven, not as a value judgment but as a
market judgment,'' he said. ``What was already overvalued became
more overvalued.''
</P>
<P>
   One prominent laggard, however, has been one of his remaining
big stocks _ Philip Morris. It accounts for 15 percent of the fund,
but is down 3.3 percent this year through Aug. 21. ``Philip Morris
is doing well on an earnings and cash-flow basis,'' he said, adding
that if the company's Kraft Foods unit were valued on the same
basis as another company, Heinz, that alone would justify the share
price. ``So you get the cigarette business, which accounts for
two-thirds of the business, for free,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He plans no changes to his portfolio, which he characterizes as
defensive.
</P>
<P>
   Yacktman started the Yacktman Focused fund in April 1997, and
the $59 million fund, which holds 13 stocks of various market
capitalizations, has trounced its older sibling. It has returned
11.3 percent annually, on average, since inception and is off 0.29
percent this year through Aug. 21, according to Morningstar.
</P>
<P>
   Yacktman, while currently invested in both funds, plans to put
his future money into Focused. ``We believe in concentrating to get
better results,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
