<HEADER>
A7821 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-ISRAEL-Y2K-$AD     08-28 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-ISRAEL-Y2K-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING IN YEAR-2000 SOLUTIONS, INCUBATED IN ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 30)  
 (bl)  
 By JESSICA STEINBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV, Israel _ As with any issue in Israel, there are two
sides to the 488-day countdown to the new millennium. There is the
religious side, with several groups on global missions to guide
Jews toward celebrating the Sabbath when New Year's Eve falls on a
Friday night in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   And there is the business side, as several hundred software
engineers implement Israeli millennium-bug solutions worldwide,
making sure computers know to switch to 2000 instead of back to
1900. Known in industry shorthand as Y2K, the computer issue has
become a vital management concern for businesses and government
agencies around the world as they rush to convert computer systems
in time.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has been an incubator for several companies specializing
in diagnostic software and antivirus technology, thanks to a rich
lode of skilled workers, including Israeli military veterans who
honed their skills on classified army information systems and
Russian immigrants who flooded into the country in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the heart of the Israeli Y2K industry is a supply of
mainframe-trained programmers,'' said Jim Duggan, year-2000
research director at the Gartner Group, a market research company.
``I guess we have the former Soviet Union to thank for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the small Israeli technology companies that are
successfully selling year-2000 solutions are listed on Nasdaq. Two
of them, Crystal Systems Solutions and Forsoft Ltd., are part of
the Formula Systems high-technology holding group; a third, Sapiens
International, is independent.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal, founded in 1987, developed a general-purpose software
conversion tool called C-Mill and began marketing it in 1990,
initially without any reference to the millennium bug, said Ben
Levy, head of marketing at Crystal. But it soon proved especially
useful in rooting out and correcting certain software problems,
applying an automated find-and-fix process that allowed Crystal to
capitalize on the millennium-bug boom. A partnership with the
management consulting side of the accounting giant Ernst &AMP; Young
brought Crystal its first millennium-bug client in the United
States, Eastman Kodak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y2K is about looking for needles in the haystack, and C-Mill
is the magnet,'' Duggan said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tom Leib, a millennium-bug analyst at Ernst &AMP;
Young, which operates service centers for the problem in Chicago
and Costa Mesa, Calif., C-Mill effectively shifts a computer's
internal frame of reference by a certain number of years to
sidestep the millennium. When that change alone is insufficient,
C-Mill searches through computer programs for variables that appear
to be dates, indexing them and adding digits.
</P>
<P>
   C-Mill's success has come to dominate Crystal, which now depends
on year-2000 projects for 90 percent to 95 percent of its revenue,
much more than its Israeli counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Elan Zivotofsky, a high-technology analyst for Goldman, Sachs &AMP;
Co. in Jerusalem, estimates that Crystal, which had $10.8 million
in revenue in the second quarter of 1998, should remain strong for
the next 18 months because of peaking demand for year-2000
solutions. After Dec. 31, 1999, has come and gone, though, ``it's a
show-me story,'' Zivotofsky said.
</P>
<P>
   At Forsoft, Crystal's sibling, year 2000 projects accounted for
only a quarter of the company's 1997 revenue of $30 million, with
the millennium-bug work ``serving as a door opener'' for other
business, Zivotofsky said. Forsoft is a service company that uses
Crystal's C-Mill to help Israel's blue-chip companies and several
government departments manage year-2000 problems. Clients have
included Bank Leumi and the Israeli military. ``Forsoft is clearly
the leading Y2K service provider in Israel,'' Zivotofsky said. But
it does little work overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The year-2000 problem has spawned an immense but fragmented
industry throughout the industrialized world, in which small but
nimble companies can find profitable niches. The Gartner Group
estimates that $300 billion to $600 billion will be spent globally
on software-related year-2000 issues alone. (When hardware,
personnel, litigation and other aspects of the problem are added,
the global figure is expected to exceed $1 trillion.)
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the Federal Reserve puts projected
spending on software repair by businesses at $50 billion, with the
federal government expected to spend $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sapiens is banking on that government spending, especially by
the IRS, to fuel its sales of software development tools. The
company's products can translate mainframe programs written in the
assembler computer language, which are obsolete but still widely
used, into more modern languages, making year-2000 problems much
easier to identify and repair.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Belkin, an analyst at Hambrecht &AMP; Quist in San Francisco,
compares Sapiens' mapping technique to taking inventory,
classifying and counting pieces of code instead of boxes and parts.
``Sapiens has a hybrid mentality, which is probably why we like
it,'' Belkin said. ``It has a post-Y2K market, but the year 2000 is
also a great opportunity for Sapiens to get its foot in the
mainstream market door.''
</P>
<P>
   The company thinks the market for tools to fix year-2000
problems in mainframe software will be about $7.5 billion, and it
contributed 60 percent of Sapiens' revenue of $30 million for the
first half of 1998, said Ron Zuckerman, the company's president.
``We're practically the only ones out there with this knowledge,''
he said, ``so we've been able to establish a name for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Duggan of the Gartner Group estimates that Sapiens has about
half of the relatively narrow market for assembler conversions.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies using multiple computer systems have tackled the
more straightforward, high-volume year-2000 conversions first _
desktop computers and mini-computers _ and saved the thornier, more
painstaking mainframe work for last, Zuckerman said. Now, with time
growing short, they are starting to sweat, he said, and Sapiens
stands to reap long-term gains as they discover that his company
can help.
</P>
<P>
   Belkin of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist said corporate executives were only
now realizing that year-2000 conversions could not be done
overnight and were looking for outside vendors with proven track
records and turnaround times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
