A7826 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-MEDIA-TEX     08-28 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-MEDIA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA'S SNOOPING IN MAC'S LOCKER COULD BENEFIT ATHLETES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Go ahead and say it already. Somehow you just knew this glorious
Chase for Sixty-two was going to be tainted.
</P>
<P>
   And by who else but the media. There they go again, poking
around in Mark McGwire's locker, and before you know it, we've got
Steroid-gate.
</P>
<P>
   Big Mac pumped-up on something other than free weights? Please.
The guy hit 49 home runs in his rookie season. Back then, he was
just a skinny kid. It's not like this is Duane Kuiper chasing
Maris, right?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it's legal. Besides, it's OK by Major League Baseball.
If he wants to play fast-and-easy with that bad body of his, let
him. He's a big boy.
</P>
<P>
   If only he'd kept his stall free of everything other than Right
Guard, maybe the sports scandal of the summer would never have
happened.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe, some say, if only nosy reporters had kept the contents
of McGwire's locker to themselves. Then Big Red and Sammy Sosa
could duel in relative peace, if not obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists, naturally, would dispute such thinking. McGwire's
bottle of Androstenedione was in plain sight, they'd say, and
reporters are allowed in the locker room for the expressed purpose
of finding stories, after all. Further, they might add, anything
that could affect the performance of a man bidding to break one of
baseball's hallowed records is news. Big news.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like the media have gone off half-cocked in this case,
either. The stories I've read all mentioned that there is nothing
illegal about Andro and that it has the seal of tolerance of Major
League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   But hold on a minute. There may be something bigger about this
story, something more important than another oxygen-draining debate
over news coverage and press freedoms. Something that better
justifies the reporter's prying eye and its intrusion on one man's
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Call it greater awareness of a potential health risk, or call it
the better-safe-than-sorry theory.
</P>
<P>
   If that first ``Mac uses Andro'' story had never broken, there
probably would never have been the intense scrutiny that we have
witnessed this week of the use of sports supplements by athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Before Steroid-gate, even many major-league baseball players
didn't know what Andro is, or so they say. You can bet a lot of
high school and college athletes didn't know about it either.
Critics say writing about Andro now is going to cause a clamor for
these magic pills, for better or worse.
</P>
<P>
   In the short run, maybe it will. But it's also causing many
sports officials, administrators, coaches and athletes to
reconsider and study Andro and other performance-enhancers. That's
essential. A lot more knowledge is needed before they are approved,
recommended and ingested.
</P>
<P>
   Just consider what happened this past week.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball executives and the baseball player's union
asked doctors to gather more information about the effects of
muscle-builders including Andro. Baseball has allowed the use of
Andro, unlike the NFL, the NCAA and the International Olympic
Committee, but that could change.
</P>
<P>
   A pro tennis official said the men's tour had banned Andro and
cited the McGwire controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Boise State's athletic director said the school will re-examine
its practice of distributing the strength-building supplement,
creatine, free of charge to its athletes. The NCAA is deciding
whether to ban the substance.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Andro, creatine or any other muscle-building sports
supplement is harmful to a person's health is a matter of
uncertainty, even among doctors. New studies might provide enough
information, however, to either impose permanent bans or to give
some reasonable assurances of their safe usage.
</P>
<P>
   Would this sudden call for research into sports supplements have
happened _ this quickly _ if not for the McGwire incident?
</P>
<P>
   A Denver Post columnist this week had his baseball writer's
credentials revoked for the season after he was spotted examining a
bottle of Andro he had pulled from the locker of Colorado Rockies
star Dante Bichette. Clearly, the writer crossed the line and
invaded Bichette's privacy when he dug into his stall.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of McGwire, there was no such intrusion, even though
many of the initial stories focused too much on him and his use of
Andro and not enough on the larger issue of sports supplement
usage.
</P>
<P>
   More significant, the information obtained has shined a bright
light on what has been for too long a shadowy subject. Getting this
all out in the open now and dealing with the health risks of sports
supplements is the greater good. Not just for readers, but for
athletes, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
