<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-SCAM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDS ACTIVIST ADMITS MAILING BOGUS BILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A Sacramento AIDS activist said that it was he
who mailed 4,000 bogus letters billing Northern Californians for
$76 as an attention-getting device to persuade Gov. Pete Wilson to
declare a state of medical emergency because of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``The letter is intended to open up a public dialogue with those
who are behind the governor, who have a tremendous amount of
influence with him,'' Marc Keyser, who founded the AIDS Action
League in Sacramento in 1988, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, which directed recipients to mail their checks to a
Mill Valley address, listed phone numbers for Wells Fargo Bank and
a law firm as contacts. The phones of both the bank and the law
firm of Nielsen, Merksamer, Parinello, Mueller and Naylor have been
ringing off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my estimation, those are the people who are calling the
shots'' for the governor, Keyser said. ``It's often a waste of time
to call Governor Wilson because he doesn't respond, but opening up
a dialogue with Nielsen, Merksamer and Wells Fargo gives us a much
greater chance of getting them to influence the governor in a
positive way.''
</P>
<P>
   James Parinello, a partner at Nielsen, Merksamer, said Keyser's
admission was news to him, although he was aware of the existence
of the AIDS Action League.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some allusions to this, but there was never
anything that indicated bogus letters were going to be sent out,''
Parinello said.
</P>
<P>
   Had Keyser not identified himself as the sender of the bogus
letter _ both in a phone conversation and on the AIDS Action Web
site Thursday _ postal inspectors could have been stumped, because
the letters, mailed from Sacramento, were stamped, not metered. A
metered letter would have been easier to trace.
</P>
<P>
   Keyser, 56, who said he is the former owner-editor of the Battle
Mountain Bugle newspaper in Nevada, said: ``I want to personally
apologize to every one who received the letter for any
inconvenience it caused them ... But there is a larger issue
involved, and that's the issue of AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was unconcerned about possible criminal action
against him as a result of the letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This `bill' was addressed with an address such that I could
never receive any funds from this,'' he said. ``Absolutely in no
way could anyone say it's a (financial) fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   A Postal Service official said Keyser's actions did not appear
to be a violation of the federal mail fraud statute because it
wasn't done for self-wealth purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service announced Tuesday that it had stopped all
mail from reaching the Mill Valley address and that whoever wanted
to claim it would have to do so in person. No one has claimed it.
</P>
<P>
   Keyser, who said he is neither gay nor infected with the AIDS
virus, said his motivation in sending out the letter was to ``have
people pick up the phone to call and complain.''
</P>
<P>
   Were the state to declare the state of medical emergency for
AIDS that he seeks, Keyser said, ``it would be a major breakthrough
in getting things done. It would put the issue in the hands of the
state Department of Health Services, which could institute clean
needle exchanges and override local school boards on matters of
health education.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
