A7830 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-CLINTON-$ADV30-H     08-28 1488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CLINTON-$ADV30-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S TROUBLES CAST SHADOW ON GORE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Aug. 30) 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The vice president's limousine pulled out of Sea
Charm Lane and turned, appropriately, into the fog.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's political destiny is shrouded in a mist with the
potential to be as thick, chill and menacing as the damp veil that
rolled across San Francisco as he emerged from a posh fund-raising
reception last week.
</P>
<P>
   Like many vice presidents before him, Gore is at the mercy of
the incumbent as well as political and economic factors largely
outside his control. The vice president is virtually on auto-pilot,
and, contended a top Democratic strategist: ``He's not even flying
his own plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's chances of winning the White House in 2000, agree
analysts from across the political spectrum, is chiefly in the
hands of President Clinton, Attorney General Janet Reno, Special
Counsel Kenneth Starr and even Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's sex scandal just accentuates the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's own troubles mounted with Reno's decision
last week to launch another 90-day inquiry into whether a special
prosecutor should be appointed to delve into his role in 1996
Democratic campaign fund raising. Gore claims he did nothing
improper, but a new independent counsel would almost certainly mean
an investigation lasting well into the 2000 campaign cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Al, sorry,'' said Republican pollster Bill McInturff.
``You're not master of your own destiny. You are dependent on this
(Monica Lewinsky) story, the American economy. ... because you're
the third term for President Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Pick a cliche for the overarching effect of Clinton on Gore's
political future, they're all being used _ joined at the hip,
lashed to the mast, stuck to the tar baby.
</P>
<P>
   Robert D. Squier, Gore's top political adviser, understands the
argument but doesn't see it as a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me what you have here is a Clinton-Gore
administration that is so popular because of the programs they have
fought for and have delivered on,'' Squier said. ``This basically
is an administration that said here is what we want to do with the
American economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters voted them in to do. They did it. They voted them back
in to continue it ...'' Squier said. ``That's a platform on which
Gore builds whatever he wants to build.''
</P>
<P>
   But the vice president's strategy probably cannot be that simple
and direct, contended George C. Edwards III, director of Texas A&AMP;M
University's Center for Presidential Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an ideal world,'' Edwards said, ``Gore would have run on a
platform of `Let Us Continue' in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the approach taken by Vice President George Bush when
he ran in 1992 and succeeded Ronald Reagan after two White House
terms that were viewed positively by a majority of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's troubles ``make it more difficult to campaign like
that,'' Edwards said. ``Clinton is likely to be quiet ineffective
for the rest of his term, so `continue' what exactly?''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, as well as some Democrats, believe Gore and his
team may be putting too much faith in current polling that shows
Americans holding strongly favorable opinions of Clinton's job
performance while viewing the president personally with growing
distaste.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic campaign consultant Raymond Strother, who has
counseled Gore in the past, believes the vice president has ``his
own special set of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally a vice president about this time has to separate
himself in some way from his president _ even a little,'' Strother
said. The need for Gore to appear loyal to scandal-plagued Clinton
as well as defend himself in the new fund-raising inquiry
complicates the process.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M's Edwards said Gore ``has got to be a contortionist'' as he
prepares for the 2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to be loyal, but he's got to create an independent
identity, and that's going to be a difficult task,'' Edwards said.
``I don't know how he's going to pull it off because (Gore and
Clinton) have been so very close.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1992 campaign, Bush tried to finesse the issue, broadly
promising to continue Reagan's agenda but pledging a ``kinder,
gentler'' administration with ``a thousand points of light.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Very nuanced,'' Edwards recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Gore would be very wise to try to distance
himself too far'' from Clinton, said former Sen. Alan Cranston,
D-Calif. ``It's hard to be disloyal and make it sell.''
</P>
<P>
   As things stand now, Gore seems little interested in putting any
daylight between himself and the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me say that I am proud of the leadership that President
Bill Clinton has brought to the United States of America,'' Gore
told well-heeled donors in a Pacific Heights mansion.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Democratic strategist said such sentiments are expected
_ at least by the party faithful _ from a vice president and that
Gore can say little more until Clinton decides whether he is going
to offer a fuller public explanation of his sexual relationship
with the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards pointed out that Gore, despite Clinton's problems and
the new Reno inquiry, is not without formidable political
advantages, at least in terms of winning the Democratic nomination
in 2000. They include strong name recognition, a national political
organization and a tested, if now tainted, fund-raising ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so far ahead of everyone else that he'll wipe them up ...
unless something really startling come out of this investigation,''
Edwards said. But he also noted: ``There's nothing good about
having your hand in the air'' to be sworn in for testimony to a
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Strother is less sanguine about Gore's primary prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats are very unpredictable,'' Strother said. ``We almost
knocked off a vice president, Mondale, with Gary Hart in 1984.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mondale had been defeated, along with President Carter, in the
1980 election. Vice presidents are not famous for directly
succeeding to the presidency by election. Bush was the first to
make it since Martin Van Buren won in 1836.)
</P>
<P>
   Another Democratic strategist pointed out that Gore has ``a
history and a problem'' in Iowa, where he pulled out of the
Democratic caucus process and condemned the key early test in a
1988 try for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Were House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, who won the Iowa
Democratic presidential caucuses in 1988, to run in 2000 and
``puncture (Gore's) vice-presidential aura, there could be a
problem,'' the Democratic strategist said.
</P>
<P>
   Strother said Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., might be a serious threat
to Gore because of his ``renegade'' outsider reputation and
demonstrated flair for criticizing Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Gore's strong expressions of support for Clinton, it
seemed hardly an accident that the vice president was vacationing
in Hawaii on the night of Clinton's televised speech about his
personal transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he was sorry that Guam wasn't an American state and
he couldn't get farther away,'' McInturff said.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the Gore camp's belief that Clinton's sex scandal
does not directly damage the vice president, when Gore returned to
the mainland last week, his wife, Tipper, figured prominently in
his fund-raising stops and a town meeting on school violence.
</P>
<P>
   It was a clear reminder of what, by all accounts, is the Gores'
strong marriage and political partnership. As Tipper Gore entered
animatedly into the school violence discussion, Squier stood far to
the side, silently joining his thumb and forefinger to signal that
he thought her performance was A-OK.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewinsky case, a number of Democratic, Republican and
nonpartisan analysts agree, affects Gore only as it relates to
Clinton's overall standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people can compartmentalize their view about Clinton, they
can easily differentiate between Clinton and Gore,'' said A&AMP;M's
Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not connect to Al Gore, because it's not Al Gore's
behavior,'' said GOP pollster McInturff. ``There is no serious
conversation that Vice President Gore is anywhere near this story
or has conducted himself in a way that is close to this story.''
</P>
<P>
   McInturff, who has polled across the United States during the
last five presidential elections, said he is keeping his eye on
what some survey specialists believe is the most telling public
index, the question that asks prospective voters if they believe
the nation is on the right track or headed in the wrong direction.
</P>
<P>
   If the ``right track'' response remains strong, as it is today,
Gore has ``a very good shot at being the next president,''
McInturff said. If ``wrong track'' moves into the 60 or 70
percentage-point range, ``Gore is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
