<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7842 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LASER-TREATMENTS-$ADV     08-28 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LASER-TREATMENTS-$ADV30-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTY'S BOMB, BUT HOW SMART? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   (For release Sunday, Aug. 30)  
(lb) 
 By ELLEN TIEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Once employed only in futuristic weapons,
cardiovascular surgery, CD players and other high-tech gadgets, the
laser has become the beauty industry's favorite new power tool.
Lasers are showing up in salon ads and dermatologist brochures,
promising to zap away unwanted body hair, wrinkles and leg veins.
But laser technology is developing so rapidly that it's difficult
for consumers to discern what is safe and effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``A laser is something you use to deliver a certain amount of
energy in order to destroy a precise target,'' Dr. David Biro, a
dermatologist in Bay Ridge, Brooklyn, said. ``Like a smart bomb, it
selectively attacks a site without damaging any of the surrounding
tissue.''
</P>
<P>
   But the wrong machine in the wrong hands can cause burns, scar
dark skin or just annoy consumers, who pay for permanent removal of
hair only to see it grow back. Moreover, laser hair removal, tattoo
removal, facials and peels don't require a medical license; the
equipment can be deployed by anyone who has the $40,000 to $250,000
to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone can buy a machine,'' Dr. Debra Jaliman, a prominent New
York dermatologist, said. ``But only a physician knows your medical
history and can prescribe antibiotics, if necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   But even doctors are finding that as lasers have become more
available, cosmetic dermatology has become a technology-driven
field. The public, told in ads and beauty magazines about the
promise of laser procedures, demands them; doctors and others are
drawn to laser procedures because they are lucrative. (Patients pay
$1,000 to $3,000 for the removal of hair on the upper lip; such
elective procedures are not covered by most medical insurers.)
</P>
<P>
   One concern is that some doctors might recommend a particular
laser to their patients because they have a commercial relationship
with the laser manufacturer. Four of the six doctors interviewed
for this article said they had been offered equipment free or at a
substantial discount in exchange for doing demonstrations or
research with the lasers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a standard industry practice,'' said Gary Weinstein,
the chairman of Thermo Lase Corp., which makes lasers. The doctors
interviewed said they had turned down the offers of free equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Some laser manufacturers run their own aesthetic treatment
centers. The Candela Laser Center in Boston is owned by Candela
Corp., which makes a range of lasers; the Candela Laser Center
employs doctors in the spa to perform treatments from facials and
peels to hair removal.
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors are hiring publicity agents conversant in
``chromophores'' and other laser lingo to promote their laser
treatments. Dermatologists have devised stylish promotions for
various beauty packages.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Tina Alster, a renowned laser specialist at the Washington
Institute for Skin Care in Washington, offers ``Vanity Visits'' _
one-hour consultations at which she designs personalized skin-care
regimens for patients and determines which products and procedures
are best. (As a bonus, patients receive an autographed copy of a
book she co-wrote, ``The Essential Guide to Cosmetic Laser
Surgery'' (Alliance Publishing, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Steven Victor, an Upper East Side dermatologist, advertises
his laser peel as customized, so the energy level of the machine is
calibrated to the patient's unique nooks and crannies, but
theoretically all doctors should do this.
</P>
<P>
   And some dermatologists go even further, with brochures and
newsletters highlighting the latest, fastest, best laser
treatments. ``The hype and gimmickry are ridiculous,'' Ellen
Gendler, a Manhattan dermatologist, said. ``People are looking for
a quick fix, and these doctors are scrambling to give it to them.
Frankly, if I was forced to market myself that way, I'd rather quit
and go work in a shoe store.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With new laser machines coming out all the time, it can be
difficult for a consumer to sort out the facts. One of the newest
machines, the Coherent Lightsheer Diode Laser, is being promoted
for its ``cool-tip'' technology. The Lightsheer is used for hair
removal, and supposedly protects all skin tones from
laser-generated heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is the most elegant little machine,'' said Dr.
Jaliman, whose tony uptown practice has treated such celebrity
dermis as Tina Turner, Geena Davis and Winona Ryder. For hair
removal, ``it has the longest wavelength, the deepest penetration,
and once you've done it three times, you've hit all the
follicles.'' She continued: ``It's safe for use during pregnancy
and on children. Not that I would necessarily advocate hair removal
on children.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Lightsheer laser seems packed with promise, to date
there have been no clinical studies published on its efficiency or
safety. Yet news releases trumpet that it achieves ``permanent''
hair removal; on July 28, the Food and Drug Administration, which
approves the use of these devices, cleared the product for hair
reduction, not permanent hair removal.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jim Baral of the American Dermatology Center in New York
said the Lightsheer ``has great potential, and it seems to work
well,'' but he was waiting for clinical studies on large groups.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he prefers the Soft Light laser (manufactured by Thermo
Lase Corp.) for hair removal. He also uses it for facials and
peels. ``Soft Light has been used the longest, has an incredible
safety record and works on any skin type,'' he said. ``With
strictly cosmetic procedures, it seems wisest to err on the
conservative side.''
</P>
<P>
   Other doctors point out that clinical studies show that hair
grows back the fastest with the Soft Light _ that is, within three
to six months after removal.
</P>
<P>
   As for other types of procedures, it seems each doctor has a
favorite laser. For facials and peels, Victor prefers the Erbium
laser. It is ``the most selective and causes no heat damage,'' he
said. Biro says he prefers the Ultrapulse for skin resurfacing,
which he calls ``the gold standard in skin resurfacing.''
</P>
<P>
   Where then do truth and beauty meet? Dr. Melanie Grossman,
director of clinical and laser research studies for the Laser and
Skin Surgery Center of New York, says that in the laser race
there's no clear front-runner. Dr. Grossman co-developed the
long-pulsed ruby-tip laser for hair removal at Massachusetts
General Hospital in Boston; the ruby-tip laser is designed for dark
hair on light skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Choosing the right treatment ultimately depends on skin type,
hair color and the energy levels being produced,'' Dr. Grossman
said. She is currently conducting research on the newest generation
of lasers, the diodes like the Lightsheer.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Grossman and others agree that the most important thing for
a patient is to choose a doctor with care. As Biro put it, ``Would
you rather ride the newest, fanciest bus, or be with the most
trustworthy bus driver?''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as the beauty smart bombs continue to drop, the
waxers, electrologists and facialists across the country will
undoubtedly start to lose business. On the horizon: laser
manicures, pedicures, stretch-mark removal, cellulite reduction and
permanent hair eradication in a single session.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lasers are going to take over,'' Victor said. ``Once
technology advances further and the prices come down, there's no
contest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
