<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE DIANAPHILES TO THE HILLARY-PHOBES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Random comments on people in the news:
</P>
<P>
   PRINCESS DIANA: Still dead. Still in the news. It's only a
matter of time until we hear reports of a Diana sighting at
Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   Princess Diana, a k a the Queen of Hearts, was killed one year
ago Monday in a Paris car crash, touching off one of the most
bizarre bouts of media hysteria in the history of celebrity
worship. Just about every network and cable news programs seemed to
be broadcasting on The Diana Channel _ all Diana, all the time.
Anyone who had the audacity to suggest that the breathless news
coverage was overdone was rudely shouted down by the Dianaphiles.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a year later, we're being buried in enough tributes,
retrospectives and reflections on her death to keep a dozen Diana
Channels on the air.
</P>
<P>
   Even more amazing: French authorities are still investigating
that fatal car crash. Who do you suppose is heading up this inquiry
_ Inspector Clouseau?
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Just what we need _ another independent counsel, this
time to investigate the vice president's fund-raising phone calls
during the 1996 campaign. Didn't Attorney General Janet Reno look
into this once before, only to decide that no further investigation
was needed?
</P>
<P>
   Sure she did. Way last year. But now she's been confronted with
new evidence that didn't turn up in the original inquiry. Gore
faces a 90-day preliminary review that could turn into a
full-fledged investigation if the new evidence pans out.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense. If President Clinton should be impeached and
tossed out of office, we wouldn't want President Gore running
around the White House without an independent counsel nipping at
his heels, would we?
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton: The Hillary-haters keep insisting that
the first lady must have known all along that her husband cheated
on her with former White House intern Monica Lewinksy. All those
months that Hillary spent defending the First Philanderer, her
critics say, were obviously nothing but a con job by a woman who
will say or do anything to prop up her no-good mate because she's
more concerned about power and position than about marital
fidelity.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But when the first couple went off on vacation with their
daughter walking between them, they looked for all the world like a
pair of married folks who had just gone toe-to-toe over the brand
of marital malfeasance that turns a spouse into a wild-eyed
terrorist _ especially if the transgressor has been lying about his
transgression. Hillary can't be that good an actress.
</P>
<P>
   E.G. MARSHALL: As long as we're talking about acting, we might
as well talk about a man who did it as well as anybody and better
than most. E.G. Marshall wasn't exactly a household name, but he
spent plenty of time in America's households over the years as he
delivered some of the finest TV acting ever.
</P>
<P>
   He starred in one of the very first realistic legal dramas on
television, ``The Defenders,'' and also excelled in movies and
Broadway plays. When he died the other day at the age of 88 (or 84,
depending on the source), we lost a brilliant actor who brought
elegance and class to every performance.
</P>
<P>
   MARK MCGWIRE: There are still a fair number of classy actors
around, even in this era of overpaid, under-talented movie stars.
But a class act in professional sports is a rarity _ which makes
McGwire that much more of a national treasure. McGwire is chasing
major-league baseball's record for most home runs in a season and
thus has fallen prey to bottom-fishing media types who live for the
thrill of discrediting a hero.
</P>
<P>
   But even in the face of a phony scandal about his use of a
strength-building substance that is perfectly legal, McGwire has
remained gracious, polite and humble. This is a man who donates
significant amounts of time and money to charity _ most notably to
victims of child abuse _ and who prevailed on the St. Louis
Cardinals to let his son work as a batboy so that dad and kid could
spend as much time together as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not McGwire breaks the record, he's a Hall of Fame
athlete and a Hall of Fame human being.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
