<HEADLINE>
WILSON MAY TAP DEPARTING SENATOR FOR JUDGESHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY and RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Gov. Pete Wilson is considering a gift to
departing state Sen. Quentin Kopp of San Francisco _ a judgeship on
the Sonoma County Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   The position is tied up in politics in the final days of the
legislative session, which ends at midnight Monday. Wilson, a
Republican, has asked the Democratic-controlled Legislature to fund
40 new judgeships throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say Wilson is considering Kopp to fill a judicial
position mapped out for the Northern California county.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, however, are uncomfortable giving Wilson any new
appointments just months before he leaves office. Therefore, they
are demanding concessions in exchange, including a pay raise for
state employees.
</P>
<P>
   Kopp, an independent, would not confirm Thursday whether he had
been approached by the governor's office. However, he said, ``I
would not rule out a judicial appointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson spokesman Sean Walsh, said: ``Senator Kopp has a sharp
legal mind, is a person of great substance and depth and has the
character and acumen to make a wonderful judge. If indeed he does
have a desire to be a judge, we would be happy to take a close
look.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonoma County judge's seat would be for a six-year term. If
Kopp wanted to remain after that, he would have to go before
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Kopp, 70, must leave the Legislature this year because of term
limits.
</P>
<P>
   A conservative with populist appeal, Kopp has said that once he
leaves office, he intends to step up his law practice and continue
his weekly political commentary on a local television station. His
chief goal, he said, is to qualify a statewide initiative for a
quarter-cent sales tax to fund a high-speed rail line between San
Francisco and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   A Harvard Law School-educated lawyer who tries a couple of cases
a year, Kopp also has said he might go back into full-time law
practice with his son, Shepherd, an assistant public defender in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   He did not rule out the possibility of running for mayor in San
Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
