<SLUG> BC-LATIN-PRESIDENTS-$ADV30-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVERAL LATIN LEADERS LAUNCH CONSTITUTIONAL EFFORTS TO STAY IN
POWER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: This is sider with Panama-President) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ President Ernesto Perez Balladares isn't
the only Latin American leader who has been reluctant to clean out
his desk.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Menem of Argentina, Fernando Henrique Cardoso of Brazil
and Alberto Fujimori of Peru have all engineered constitutional
amendments allowing them to run for immediate re-election. Thanks
to political maneuvering last week, Fujimori, who won a second term
in 1995, might seek a third term in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Critics warn that Latin American governments lack credible
checks and balances and that several years in power can turn
democrats into autocrats. But others say that voters have simply
rewarded accomplished chief executives for good work.
</P>
<P>
   ``This trend is related to good management,'' said a South
American diplomat. ``Efficient governments have earned the right to
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   For much of this century, Latin America was ruled by brutal
dictators and corrupt civilian ``caudillos'' who stayed in power
through military backing or electoral shenanigans.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican Revolution was launched in 1910, in part, because
President Porfirio Diaz arranged to have himself elected six times
over 34 years. ``No re-election'' was one of the revolution's
rallying cries.
</P>
<P>
   Despite regular elections in Nicaragua, the Somoza clan clung to
power for 43 years. Anastasio Somoza Debayle, the last of the
family rulers, was finally ousted in 1979 by Sandinista guerrillas
_ who promptly set up their own authoritarian regime led by
brothers Humberto and Daniel Ortega.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some exceptions but, in general, re-election
is poison for democracy,'' said Bolivar Parientes, an opposition
Panamanian congressman.
</P>
<P>
   When dictators gave way to civilian leaders across much of the
region in the 1980s, most presidents were constitutionally required
to step down after one term.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Nicaraguans had become so wary of family dynasties that
they wouldn't even allow distant relatives of the president to seek
the office.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion has only recently begun to shift with the
emergence of a handful of dynamic civilian leaders who have led
their nations out of crises.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, Menem, Cardoso and Fujimori tamed hyperinflation,
stabilized the monetary system and brought galloping economic
growth to Argentina, Brazil and Peru. Fujimori dealt a crushing
blow to Peru's Sendero Luminoso rebel movement that had waged a
terrorist war against the state.
</P>
<P>
   All three leaders used their resulting political capital to push
through constitutional amendments allowing re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Warning that ``it's me or chaos,'' Menem went on to win a
landslide victory in 1995. Fujimori was returned to office with
more than three times the vote of his closest challenger. Cardoso,
who was first elected in 1994, is the front-runner going into
Brazil's first-round presidential vote in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you try to explain re-election in Argentina and Peru, you
have to take into account the extraordinary circumstances,'' said
Ricardo Arias Calderon, a former Panamanian vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Menem and Fujimori have demonstrated authoritarian
tendencies. Both maneuvered to extend their rule into the next
century.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori, in particular, has shown little patience for
democratic niceties. In 1992, he dealt with a corrupt legislature
and a growing rebel threat by dissolving Congress and declaring
one-man rule for eight months.
</P>
<P>
   Although Peru now has a semblance of constitutional rule, vast
powers remain in Fujimori's hands, and he seems reluctant to loosen
his grip. The courts are packed with the president's allies, and
the compliant Congress has approved laws with little debate.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Fujimori pushed through another constitutional
amendment that would allow him to seek a third consecutive
five-year term in 2000. Outraged opposition leaders called for a
citizen referendum on the issue, but the measure was blocked by the
pro-Fujimori Congress on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Menem considered further constitutional tinkering to pave the
way for a third term. But his popularity has fallen because of
rising unemployment. Last month, he announced that he would not run
in the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   Nations that don't allow re-election aren't necessarily more
democratic. Mexican presidents get just one six-year term. But
until very recently, Mexico was a virtual one-party state. The
Institutional Revolutionary Party has ruled the country since
1929. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; One diplomat pointed out that many Latin American nations
already have strong presidential systems. Rather than worrying
about the re-election of presidents, these countries should focus
on revamping their often corrupt and overworked legal systems and
strengthening their congresses.
</P>
<P>
   In Panama, for example, legislators lack staff and research
capabilities, making them dependent on the advice of the president
or their party's leaders. Lawmakers have little control over the
nation's budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good legal system would help tremendously. A real congress
would provide checks and balances,'' the diplomat said. ``But in
terms of improving things, re-election is not a priority.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
John Otis is a free-lance journalist who wrote this for the Houston
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
