<HEADER>
A7916 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VANITY-FASHION-$ADV30     08-28 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VANITY-FASHION-$ADV30-715(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE RIDDLE FITS ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala.)   (For release Sunday, Aug. 30)  
(lb) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let me begin by saying that I'm not a Lilly Pulitzer kind of
woman. But in July I found myself on Martha's Vineyard with an hour
on my hands, checked out the competition and thought, ``When in
Rome ....''
</P>
<P>
   I followed a group of women with sun-worn faces and plaid hair
bands into the closest boutique, and there I found it: a short,
flirty, flowered Lilly Pulitzer, printed with roses and frogs and
prancing children.
</P>
<P>
   The fit was miraculous, as if a team of steely-eyed couture
seamstresses had spent weeks plotting each angle and line and dip
of my body. I was ready to unburden myself of $130 when I stepped
out of the dress and saw the label. The magical phrase I read there
changed my life: size 6.
</P>
<P>
   I had unwittingly stumbled upon the holy grail of womanhood.
Sucking in my stomach, I decided to go for a size 4 plaid skirt.
The headband set listened as I struggled, wriggled and zipped. And
as a soft white light suffused the dressing room and the distant
strains of a divine choir (actually, it was Hanson) seemed to drift
past the swinging wicker doors, I took a long breath. Victory _
size 4 _ was mine.
</P>
<P>
   Women's apparel sizing is eternally mystifying. I am a
broad-shouldered athlete, close to 6 feet tall and weighing many,
many dozens of pounds. How I fit into a 6, the size of wraithlike
supermodels and desiccated society waifs who eat grapes for lunch,
or a positively puny size 4, is a riddle wrapped in an enigma
wrapped in, well, a size 4 wrap dress.
</P>
<P>
   And it's become a lightning-rod issue for American clothing
manufacturers. I described the incredible shrinking act to Dr.
Lenda Jo Anderson, a professor of consumer affairs at Auburn
University in Alabama, who at the behest of the Commerce Department
studies size in women's clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We define ourselves in our minds by size, and designers play
to that notion,'' she said in a demure Southern accent. ``It makes
us feel good to fit into a 6, but it also makes us feel good to be
able to say to our friends that we fit into a size 6. But it can be
ridiculous. I bought a pair of pants by Carlisle in a size 0 the
other day. Who wears a size 0?'' (Dr. Anderson said she usually
wears a 4 or a 6.)
</P>
<P>
   The American Apparel Manufacturers Association studies the
subject, but Carl Priestland, the association's chief economist,
says it's not a simple problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sizing has been an issue for years simply because there are so
many companies out there making garments,'' he said. ``There are 7
billion garments consumed in the United States each year that
require care labeling. So it's nice and pretty to say we want a
standard for each and every piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Priestland said that each year U.S. manufacturers make 200
million dresses, 375 million pairs of jeans, 2.4 billion knit
shirts and 45 million dozen pairs of women's panties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine?'' he said. ``Forty-five million dozen pairs
of women's panties?'' To be honest, I can't.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Anderson explained that American women's sizes originated in
the 1940s and '50s, when the Army, confronted with the enormous
task of outfitting tens of thousands of women for the first time,
tried to create a standard set of sizes. The chart that resulted,
outlining the 58 sizes for men and women was published by the
Bureau of Standards as Document 454.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Document 454 is not taped to the refrigerator of
today's designers. Since the '40s, sizes have been shifting as
crazily as the San Andreas fault.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department has founded the National Textile Center,
a consortium of colleges, to study the subject. The Air Force is
conducting a nationwide survey of American bodies to redefine the
standard body and size.
</P>
<P>
   And as more and more consumers buy clothing in the electronic
marketplace _ over the telephone or via the Internet _ Dr. Anderson
said, the problem becomes pronounced because consumers rely on
sizes, without actually trying on articles of clothing, to
determine what will fit them best. Companies like QVC report
returns of up to 50 percent on clothing because of poor fit, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from economic difficulties, there are psychological
ones. No woman who usually wears a 12 wants to go to her closet and
confront a row of stolid, round, pudgy black numbers that read 16
or 18 or 20.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Silence of the Lambs,'' the drag-queen killer always
chose young women who were size 14 _ and the only moviegoers who
remember that piece of trivia are women. And in certain female
quarters, the size of Monica Lewinsky's notorious off-the-rack
dress continues to inspire guessing games.
</P>
<P>
   I usually call myself a 10. But I've ordered shorts from J. Crew
that in a 10, without the tab pocket, are so loose I have to
duct-tape them to my body to keep them from falling off. Similar
shorts in the same size, with the tab pocket, are so tiny that I
have to grease myself like a watermelon on the Fourth of July in
order to slide them on.
</P>
<P>
   In noncatalog clothing, the discrepancies from designer to
designer are startling. Tahari makes a jacket that I _ a former
competitive swimmer with the shoulders of a Pittsburgh Steeler _
can wear only in a shrinky-dink 6. The skirt, on the other hand,
fits in an 8 (svelte), a 10 (poochy) or a 12 (nunlike).
</P>
<P>
   A benevolent aunt gave me a Mary McFadden couture dress in an 8,
and it is broad in the beam. Country Road makes wool pants that fit
beautifully in an 8, and viscose pants in the same cut that in a 10
fit like swaddling clothes.
</P>
<P>
   I wear a sample-size 8 in the famously revived Diane Von
Furstenburg wrap dress, and a 16 _ gasp! _ in a vintage dress from
the 1950s. (Sizes have shifted so much in the last four decades
that every woman loves to crow about how Marilyn Monroe wore a 14.
But that was back in the days when a 14 was really an 8, so button
your lip.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very upsetting,'' said one friend who tried on a
too-tight skirt in a size 14 at Agnes B. ``Even the salesclerk was
consoling me.''
</P>
<P>
   When men shop, they are not permitted to toy with their psyches
the way women do and to plot elaborate mazes of self-delusion.
Rather than playing a psychological shell game every time they go
to the Gap or Brooks Bros., they simply pick out the pants with a
36-inch waist and the shirt with the 16-inch neck. When they get
fat, they are faced with the cold, factual truth _ Got a 44-inch
waist, buddy? Well, you're fat! _ and simply scratch off the
numbers on the Levi's label.
</P>
<P>
   But every bubble has to burst. That same day on Martha's
Vineyard, a friend surprised me with a gift: a blue-and-white
polka-dot dress, a saucy Marilyn Monroe-esque number with a halter
top and a flared skirt, designed to play fast and loose with a
steam grate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't have your size,'' he said, as I twirled in front
of the mirror, wearing my new, snug dress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh? What size is this?'' I asked, slowing the gleeful twirling
to a more dignified rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a, um, a 12,'' he said, staring down at his
hands, clasped humbly in his lap.
</P>
<P>
   I stopped the cake-display twirl. The room was suddenly very
quiet. It was a big moment. He looked up, and his terror-filled
eyes said: Is she going to hit me now?
</P>
<P>
   ``But the lady in the store said the sizes ran really small,''
he said, painfully nonchalant. ``I mean really, really small.''
</P>
<P>
   Good answer, I thought, and then took a pair of manicure
scissors and snipped out the label.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
