<HEADER>
A7929 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV30-B     08-28 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV30-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT NOW, BILL NEEDS HILLARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 30, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the end of the summer, the end of the bull market, and the
end of the honeymoon between Bill Clinton and the female voters who
up till now had mostly given him the benefit of the doubt.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not the end of his presidency, it is not the end of
his influence, and it need not be the end of his domestic
tranquility _ if Hillary Rodham Clinton hangs in there with him.
</P>
<P>
   The First Lady is a big part of the collateral damage caused by
the Monica missile. That not-so-smart-bomb came right down the
chimney of the Oval Office and, ignited by lust, bravado,
concupiscence or the kind of frat-house stupidity that is never
absent from the political gene pool, jolted America's faith in its
leader's concept of honor. What would Jackie O counsel Hillary?
</P>
<P>
   Bill bears the scarlet letter on his furrowed brow. Shame is the
rawest of emotions. Not only has one done something wrong, stupid
and base; but one is caught out, so the guilt is apparent to all,
and the blushing shines not only outward but inward, where it
constricts the gullet, sours the stomach, loosens the entrails,
taints the outlook on life. One shudders at the psychic cost.
</P>
<P>
   The public reaction was generally friendly and forgiving in
Worcester Thursday, it appeared. Ted Kennedy gave seatmate John
Kerry a lesson in how to stand by a fellow in a jam. Editorial
thunder scolds the voters for not being less forgiving. Anyone with
a keyboard puts the presidential marriage on the couch and
pontificates shamelessly. Hillary is upbraided for holding hands
with You-know-who. Every move is meticulously analyzed. A hundred
cameras on Martha's Vineyard are cocked for the slightest wrinkle
of petulance or frost.
</P>
<P>
   It's a rotten way to live, while trying to repair a
relationship, to raise a teenager. Being First Family can stagger
marriages; we've seen plenty evidence of that. Buddy the dog is the
only living thing in the White House whose opinion of Bill has not
changed. I am one who hopes Hillary forgives Bill, again, and tries
to move on.
</P>
<P>
   Not the least of Brother Bill's penance is the grief his
randiness showered on wife and daughter. Everyone's scarred by
proximity to this shoddy charade. Though it is not the end of the
world, its impact on his wife and daughter has to bother the hell
out of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Think ill of him as you may, his record is clear: he has never
been much of a villain, except in the eyes of political enemies
he's crossed. He does not have a track record as viictive,
punitive, mean-spirited, greedy. His indifference to money is
almost laughable in this age of I'll-get-mine-while-I-can. He is a
man of tolerance, inclusion, open-handeed-ness and
open-heartedness. Too open, too willing to feel your pain (and
perhaps more) if you're young and female and play up to his
blandishments.
</P>
<P>
   He may eventually stumble back into the good graces of enough
voters to survive, though the nation's editorial pages wax wroth,
and his many enemies in the media devote millions of harsh words
each day to denounce his fall from grace. That's politics. And
Bill, if he's shown nothing else, has shown he can handle the
politics with the best of them.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary has saved his sorry butt before. She burst on our
consciousness the night of the Super Bowl in '92, sitting on the
Ritz sofa in Boston, staring into the 60 Minutes camera, denying
she was lip-synching Loretta Lynn's lyrics of ``Stand By Your
Man.'' That steely stare-down of the nation's curiosity about her
marriage saved Bill's bacon that night. Hillary could have croaked
him with one arched eyebrow, and chose not to.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton now admits having lied about not having an affair with
Gennifer Flowers. I didn't buy his denial then. You never know for
sure about these kinds of things. But after listening to Gennifer's
tape of Bill's phone calls, hearing Clinton repeat rubbish about
Mario Cuomo, it just sounded to me like Bill and Gennifer were
involved. Put that together with the other rumors, the innuendo,
the ``bimbo eruptions'' that rattled the campaign War Room, and it
was plain Bill had an eye for the ladies. If it was OK by Hillary,
it was OK by me.
</P>
<P>
   So all of his appointees, staff, and associates who now claim to
be betrayed are, in my view, incredibly naive. Where were you when
all those smoke signals were darkening the sky? I concluded early
on that Hillary and Bill had some sort of deal. I don't know the
details, and don't want to know. He was Lil' Abner on the political
make in Arkansas, she was the icily-ambitious Wellesley girl
plunked down in Dogpatch. Early on he showed signs of world-class
political talent. She made her bargain. Both of them wanted to
change the world, late-'60's style. Neither could do it without the
other.
</P>
<P>
   The late Jim McDougal's new book, ``Arkansas Mischief, The Birth
of a National Scandal,'' written by the Globe's Curtis Wilkie, is
the best explanation I've seen of the political culture Bill &AMP; Hill
grew up in. McDougal explains the $2,000 retainer his Madison bank
paid the Rose firm as a regularization _ okay, laundering _ of a
$2,000-a-month payoff that was being fed Clinton. McDougal, an
admitted perjurer, is dead, as are some other participants, so we
may never know for sure, but the tale fits the times.
</P>
<P>
   My impression, just off seven years of Clinton-watching, is that
Hillary was the one most eager to make money, in Whitewater, the
cattle futures, her law career. Why? Bill was a naif when it came
to money, a political wunderkind who was only making 30 grand a
year as a backcountry governor. When Chelsea was born, Hillary may
have wondered: who's going to pay for her to go to Wellseley, or
Stanford? Certainly not Bubba here. I'll have to do it, she
reasoned.
</P>
<P>
   So she thrashed around in the Whitewater underbrush, lost money
in the deal, got cross with McDougal, fought over the partnership,
and eventually got snared when a vengeful prosecutor, Kenneth
Starr, got hundreds of FBI agents and $45 million of tax money to
destroy her husband, and her. Like Inspector Javert of Les Miz, the
puritanical Starr pursued relentlessly. This right-wing Ahab
devoted four years to harpooning Bubba the White Whale.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget Starr piously doubting the Clintons' ``spousal
integrity'' early on. The public pillorying both Clintons endure
has to be weighed against everything they've done, for women,
blacks, the powerless. Hillary fell short on health care, alas. But
her fingerprints are all over those appointments naming women as
secretary of state, attorney general, Supreme Court justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every professional woman I know in Wasngton is furious at
him,'' said a female White House correspondent of the Monica
confession. His sin is incontestable. But all those women who got
big government jobs count for something, and that wouldn't have
happened without Hillary's decision, made years ago, to stand by
her man, the one with those soulful lyin' eyes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhana is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
