<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7933 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARN-SALARIES-ART-$AD     08-28 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARN-SALARIES-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAY IS RISING, THANKS TO SWEETENERS IN A TIGHT LABOR MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 30) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By SUSAN J. WELLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is no secret that employers have had to compete like never
before to hire and keep qualified workers in the 1990s. Now comes
research suggesting that pay increases could reach their highest
level in six years in 1999, fueled in large part by a rise in
bonuses, stock options and other variable forms of pay that are
being extended not just to senior executives but also to other
levels of the work force.
</P>
<P>
   Several private studies of employers' salary budget plans now
project combined merit, cost-of-living and incentive pay raises of
4 percent to 4.5 percent next year _ far more than double the
current annual inflation rate of 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next decade will really be the decade of the employee,''
said Wallace Nichols, executive director of the American
Compensation Association, a 23,000-member industry group in
Scottsdale, Ariz. ``Low inflation, low unemployment, continuing
scarcity of qualified workers and an increase in real wages are all
combining to put employees in the driver's seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, government data confirm that employers' costs to attract
and retain employees at all levels rose in the year ended June 30
at the greatest rate since 1993. The Employment Cost Index for all
civilian workers _ which measures changes in compensation costs,
including wages, salaries and employer costs for benefits _ rose
3.5 percent for the 12 months through June, according to the Bureau
of Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   In the private sector, the index data show that wages and
salaries rose 4 percent for the year ended in June, compared with a
gain of 3.3 percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of 1,069 employers this summer by Hewitt Associates, a
management consultant based in Lincolnshire, Ill., found that
salary increases for those workers who don't qualify for overtime
will average 4.2 percent next year, the highest projected increase
since 1993, when raises averaged 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Increases are expected to average 4.1 percent for salaried
workers who are eligible for overtime; 3.9 percent for nonunion
hourly employees, 3.2 percent for union workers and 4.4 percent for
executives, the Hewitt survey suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a survey by the compensation association found that
1999 salary budget increases at almost 3,000 U.S. and Canadian
companies will average 4.35 percent. Moreover, the association's
survey indicates that the gains are consistent from region to
region.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Hewitt survey, employers are feeling the most
pressure to increase pay for information technology, engineering,
finance, sales and marketing positions.
</P>
<P>
   Salaries may be rising slowly and steadily, but there has been
far more rapid change in how companies are shaping their
compensation policies. Performance-based, or ``variable pay,''
rewards like bonuses and stock options are a growing part of the
total pay packages being offered to employees.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-two percent of the employers surveyed by Hewitt reported
offering at least one variable-pay plan this year, up from 61
percent just two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The compensation association's survey found that the use of
stock is becoming prevalent in compensation plans. According to the
survey, conducted in June and July, 63 percent of companies offered
stock and stock-option plans to employees this year. And more
employees can expect offers of stock options next year, the
association said; nearly 55 percent of the companies reported that
they would extend stock options further down the organizational
ladder in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employees are getting heavily involved in all the variations
in pay, just like CEOs,'' Nichols said. ``It's no longer just a
package of perks for executives only.''
</P>
<P>
   John Boudreau, director of the Center for Advanced Human
Resource Studies at Cornell University, said the potential for
earnings windfalls tied to company performance was increasingly
driving today's work force and influencing the way companies
structured pay plans.
</P>
<P>
   Boudreau cited the ``dream factor'' _ the idea that a company
``may be the next Microsoft,'' turning its employees into instant
millionaires based on the swift growth in the value of their stock
options.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates an interesting contract between employer and
employee'' that goes directly to the goal of retaining workers, he
said. ``The company is saying, `Join us, take on some of the risk
and perhaps you'll make out great.'''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that is not a sure thing. Employers are able to share
success with employees in profitable years, but retain the
flexibility to withhold bonuses or other incentives if the company
performs poorly.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Boudreau questioned whether widespread use of
stock and bonuses would keep workers at a company in the long run.
Such variable-pay instruments ``work only if a company performs
well,'' he said. ``And if tomorrow everybody has them, will they
really be a competitive advantage or just a base benefit that
everyone gets?''
</P>
<P>
   A survey by Buck Consultants Inc., a human resources consulting
firm based in New York, found that 76 percent of 406 companies in
the Fortune 1000 use hiring bonuses to attract employees; 50
percent are using retention bonuses for their existing staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of hiring and retention bonuses is a major shift in
compensation policy,'' said Paul Gavejian, a Buck compensation
consultant. Three-fourths of the survey respondents are also using
perks like performance bonuses, group incentives and stock options.
</P>
<P>
   And more employers are moving in that direction. Thirty-five
percent of companies responding to the compensation association's
survey reported that they planned to change compensation methods to
place more emphasis on variable pay over merit pay. But 86 percent
of companies that already have variable plans reported that those
plans were in addition to, not instead of, merit raises.
</P>
<P>
   Economists have warned that pay raises could end the low
inflation that has been a crucial component of the nation's robust
economy. But so far, the researchers noted, that hasn't occurred.
In recent years, they said, companies have largely succeeded in
keeping compensation costs in check, partly because of the
productivity gains realized from these types of incentives. Greater
reliance by companies on one-time variable forms of compensation
has made fixed salary budgets more flexible, they argue, and thus
controllable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, we've seen a number of trends converge,'' said Ken
Abosch, a compensation consultant at Hewitt who oversaw its survey.
``And the combined impact has been positive for employee
paychecks.''
</P>
<P>
   Nichols of the compensation association added, ``Reliance on
variable-pay plans won't trigger inflation because they are based
on company performance and won't be paid out if results are poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What could affect inflationary pressures,'' he said, ``is the
continuing scarcity of labor and bidding up of costs to attract
qualified workers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 1708EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
