r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-RUSSIA-$ADV31     08-28 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-RUSSIA-$ADV31-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S SOME DEEPLY MEANINGFUL STUFF ON RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With visions of impeachment dancing in his head, Bill Clinton is
off for a summit in Moscow with the mercurial Boris Yeltsin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moscow, as you may recall, is in Russia, which is no longer in
the Soviet Union because the whole Soviet Union itself went
belly-up several years ago. It happened when ideas about democracy
and market economies and cable TV swept through eastern Europe,
revealing communism to be the nincompoop idea everyone with a lick
of sense had always said it was. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans have to force themselves to remember that the
Soviet Union has gone the way of the dodo bird, which some of you
smarty-pantses (a description that certainly does not fit Bill
Clinton) may know by its technical name, Raphus cucullatus. I
didn't know it by that name until I looked up whether dodo is one
word or hyphenated, which shows you the depths of research to which
I'll go on your behalf. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All of which tells me that some Americans may not fully grasp
the notion that Russia now is, once again, a country (sort of) all
its own and is no longer the Russian Soviet Federated Socialist
Republic, which was its ridiculous name until the Soviet Union
ceased to exist on Jan. 1, 1992. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (I don't know why, but for years now it has tickled me that my
father outlasted the Soviet Union by one day. He began his life
eight years to the day before the Bolshevik revolution succeeded in
1917, so he lived eight years and one day longer than the USSR _
and, I might be excused for saying, he did a lot more good for
humanity in his single life than the entire Soviet Union ever
did.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I am, it turns out, in a position now to enlighten you at least
a little bit about the struggling Russia that Bill Clinton is
visiting. One reason is that one of my sisters spent several weeks
there this summer cruising down rivers. And I have seen the
pictures she took. Seeing pictures is pretty much all it takes
nowadays to be thought of as an expert on something. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My sister's Russian pictures show a beautiful countryside full
of handsome old buildings and sad people. (A little like Arkansas
now.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps one reason for the sadness (in Russia, not Arkansas) is
the people realize that their country is about twice the size of
the United States but has hardly any suburban shopping malls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I have never been to Russia. But if, like my sister, I were to
spend several weeks floating down wide Russian rivers, I would take
every opportunity to yell from the deck something like this to
people on the banks: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``ATTENTION, you Russian people on the river banks who look so
sad: If you are sad because you wish you had some suburban shopping
malls, stop it. Cheer up. Malls are a bad idea. They chew up good
farmland and create hostile architecture and encourage wretchedly
excessive consumption of useless goods. Trust me. You're better off
nurturing your human-scale shopping districts in your towns and
villages, even if your ruble is now almost worthless.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, because I'd be yelling this, all the letters in all
these words would be capitalized. I chose not to do that here in
print because it's hard to read and off-putting and so forth and,
unless I miss my guess, you did not get this far to be off-put. You
got this far to see if you could learn something about Russia.
Well, it's not too late for that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's something you may not know about Russia: The 1997
population estimate was 147.3 million people. One of those Russians
is Boris Yeltsin. Yeltsin is like Mikhail Gorbachev was in 1990 in
that he already has accomplished all he can, yet he's (barely)
still in office. His predicament should give Yeltsin and Clinton
something in common to talk about. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
