<HEADER>
A7951 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-PLAYERS-0829-C     08-28 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PLAYERS-0829-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA'S KEY PLAYERS AS THE COUNTRY ENDURES CHAOS
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-CRISIS-0829.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Here are the leading figures in Russia's government,
parliament and business as the country struggles with the current
economic and political crisis:
</P>
<P>
   BORIS YELTSIN, 67, president
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``I'm not going to resign. I will work as I'm supposed to
for my constitutional term. In 2000 there will be an election for a
new president and I will not run.''
</P>
<P>
   Background: Russia's first democratically elected president was
a political maverick in the old Communist Party. Yeltsin helped
hasten the end of the Soviet Union in 1991 and promised Russia the
rewards of democracy and free markets. Seven years later, the dream
has soured with economic and political chaos and an ailing Yeltsin
viewed as unable to cope with the crisis. While denying he will
resign, Yeltsin has agreed to cede powers to his prime minister and
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   VIKTOR CHERNOMYRDIN, 60, acting prime minister
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``We must forget (political) ambitions, we must stabilize
the situation and ease tensions that have reached a critical
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Background: A Soviet-era bureaucrat, Chernomyrdin went on to
serve as Yeltsin's prime minister from December 1992 until March
this year, when he was fired for failing to fix the economy. Now
he's back and struggling to form a government and satisfy the
interests of the Communist opposition, Russia's powerful tycoons
and Western lenders urging Russia not to revive a Soviet-style
economy.
</P>
<P>
   GENNADY ZYUGANOV, 54, leader of the Communist Party
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``We will only support a policy and a leadership that
will clearly and straightforwardly reject the so-called market
reforms and agree to take a different course.''
</P>
<P>
   Background: Leader of the opposition in the Duma, parliament's
lower house, Zyuganov was dismissed as politically impotent after
Yeltsin defeated him in the 1996 presidential race. But Zyuganov's
clout has risen considerably in the past week as he seeks a role
for his party in setting policy and filling key jobs in the new
government. Polls show he is the leading candidate to replace
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   YEGOR STROYEV, 61, chairman of the Federation Council
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``We should hurry to create a new government. Lack of any
authority at all is worse than the worst possible regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Background: The lackluster head of Russia's upper house of
parliament, Stroyev largely has served as a go-between for the
Kremlin and the Communist-dominated Duma. Opposition parties have
promoted him as an alternative candidate for prime minister. A
Soviet-era economist, he represents the interests of Russia's
provinces, whose governors sit on the federation council.
</P>
<P>
   YURI LUZHKOV, 62 mayor of Moscow and business tycoon
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``If the Central Bank lacks either the money or the
desire to halt the crisis, the financial system will slowly crawl
towards destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Background: The powerful mayor of Moscow -- who like
Chernomyrdin has aspirations to become president -- demonstrated
his status by his attendance in a meeting Friday with Yeltsin,
Chernomyrdin and Stroyev on the fate of Russia. A nationalist who
enjoys strong popularity in Moscow, Luzhkov has distanced himself
from the Kremlin during the current crisis. He could exploit the
current chaos to his political advantage should Chernomyrdin fail
to reverse the economic declines.
</P>
<P>
   ALEXANDER LEBED, 48, governor of the Krasnoyarsk region and a
presidential aspirant.
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``Over the years, the population has grown poorer and
output has fallen, but the president and government told fairy
tales to Russians instead of taking the necessary steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Background: A tough-as-nails former army general with a popular
following in Russia (he finished third in the 1996 presidential
balloting), Lebed was courted by Chernomyrdin earlier this week in
what many analyst believed was an attempt to have him join the new
government. He likely wants to remain on the outside, though and,
like Luzhkov, attempt to exploit a failure of the new government in
time for the presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   BORIS BEREZOVSKY, 52, industrial and media baron; Yeltsin
advisor
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``I am a product of privatization.''
</P>
<P>
   Background: A multibillionaire who helped finance Yeltsin's 1996
campaign and went on to become a Kremlin insider, Berezovsky has
emerged as the power behind the throne. Berezovsky is the most
prominent of the wealthy Russians known as the oligarchs, who made
their money buying and selling the assets of the dissolved Soviet
Union. He and others reportedly engineered Chernomyrdin's return to
protect the status quo, fearing economic reform amid the crisis
could dismantle their empires.
</P>
<P>
   ANATOLY CHUBAIS, 43, fired as Yeltsin's chief economic reformer
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``Even given the present difficult financial situation,
there is no alternative to development of a market economy in
Russia or the country's integration into the world financial
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Background: Fired Friday as from his job as chief financial
liaison to the West, Chubais is an erudite reformer who since 1991
was the main architect of Russia's plan to privatize its Soviet-era
industries. He is the darling of Western economists, but is blamed
by many Russians for the country's economic misery and consistently
ranks as one of Russia's most unpopular figures. He continues as
head of Unified Energy Systems, the nation's electricity utility.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
