<HEADER>
A7966 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV30-     08-28 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRICKING PLANTS INTO BLOOMING EARLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 30)  
(lb) 
 By CASS PETERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In gardening as in life, timing is everything. The fall asters
are setting buds and the Joe-Pye weed is in full and glorious
bloom, so naturally I'm thinking about next spring's sweet williams
and cornflowers.
</P>
<P>
   Many of spring's brightest flowers are biennials, plants that
live for two years, producing only foliage the first year and
blossoms the second. If planted in the late summer or early autumn,
however, they can be tricked into thinking they have had a whole
year in the ground already. Sweet william, a sweetly scented
relative of pinks and carnations, will be blooming next May if I
plant it in September.
</P>
<P>
   Other spring bloomers, like cornflowers and larkspur, are
technically annuals, but they are so hardy that even well into
Canada they will survive the winter as small seedlings. If planted
in the fall, they will burst into growth early the next season and
easily produce twice as many flowers as they would if planted in
the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Fall planting is also a useful subterfuge for Canterbury bells,
biennial varieties of foxglove, and many perennials that can't
tolerate muggy summers. If they are planted in autumn, they get
nothing but the cool weather they prefer from the time they are
committed to the soil until the time they open their flowers in the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   English daisy, for example, is a perennial so sensitive to heat
that it will grow in my south-central Pennsylvania garden only as a
fall-planted biennial. Spring-planted English daisies melt out by
the end of July, never living long enough to bloom the following
year.
</P>
<P>
   I grow lupines, which are perennials, in the cutting garden as
biennials, planting in the fall for cutting the next spring. There
are clumps of lupines in the perennial garden, but I can't reliably
supply the cool summers and mild winters they prefer. I never know
for sure whether the summer's heat will have weakened the lupine
enough that it will die over winter. As a hedge against a
lupineless spring, I plant a few in the autumn.
</P>
<P>
   To make room for all these flowers, I am happy to rip out the
flowering annuals that have brightened the garden all summer but
now are looking a little scraggly. Out with the mildewed zinnias,
the spent sunflowers and the petunias that I'm tired of pinching.
To every plant its season, and the time of the ageratum has come
and gone.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet william (Dianthus barbatus) and Canterbury bells, a
biennial member of the bellflower family that produces spikes of
cup-shaped flowers in shades of pink, blue and white, are best
planted from seedlings, which should be started about six weeks
before your first frost date.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer the tall cutting-type sweet williams, but the dwarf Wee
Willie is a charming edging plant, perfect for interplanting with
flowering spring bulbs. Single-flowered Canterbury bells (Campanula
Medium) do best in my garden, but the double-flowered
cup-and-saucer types (C. Medium calycanthema) are so striking that
I always plant a few.
</P>
<P>
   I like to crowd the plants a bit, planting them about 6 inches
apart, to encourage long stems. Canterbury bells have fairly weak
stems, and jamming them together allows the plants to support each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Biennial foxgloves and most perennials should also be started
indoors and put out as small plants. If you're a little late
getting the plants started, you can overwinter the seedlings in a
cold frame and set them out early next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Larkspur, cornflower and a few fast-germinating perennials like
feverfew can be seeded directly into the ground. They really should
be planted in the fall _ even though the instructions on seed
packets generally say cornflower and larkspur should be planted in
the spring, as early as the soil can be worked.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that in most years the soil is too wet to be
spaded up early enough in the spring to give the flowers the head
start they need. Or the soil can be worked but the gardener doesn't
much feel like getting out there in the icy March wind to do it.
The result is that the seeds don't get planted until late April or
May, which is not nearly soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   Larkspur must be exposed to a period of cold weather, or it
won't bloom properly. Each year I plant a bed of larkspur in
September and a second one the following spring, as early as I
possibly can. Larkspur is one of my favorite flowers for drying,
and I can never get enough. Each year the fall-planted larkspur
grows to 4 feet and blooms magnificently, while the spring-planted
larkspur manages only a modest display of blossoms on 2-foot
stalks.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true of cornflower (Centaurea Cyanus), and its
cousin sweet sultan (C. moschata). Both will bloom if planted in
the spring, but the plants will be much shorter than they would be
had they spent the winter in the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Spring-planted cornflowers usually come into bloom just about
the time the weather is heating up, and their delicate flowers
wither quickly. A bed of them planted in the fall will bloom in
late spring, following the spring bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   Of course they will also finish blooming fairly early in the
season. No problem. They can be pulled out then and replaced with
fresh zinnias and perfect petunias. Timing is everything.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
