<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Aug. 29, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Storm Bonnie will sideswipe southeast New England early
Saturday, bringing gusty winds and fitful rains to parts of eastern
Massachusetts and Rhode Island. The system will then head toward
the Canadian Maritimes, allowing clouds to break and winds to ease
over southeast New England.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Danielle will continue to strengthen as it churns
west-northwest over the tropical Atlantic. Forecasting guidance
provided by computers suggests that Danielle will probably turn
northward and not threaten the Southeast seaboard, where
temperatures will climb into the middle and upper 90s under full
sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   A corridor of widely separated showers and thunderstorms will
develop from the northern and central Appalachians southwest across
the Tennessee and lower Mississippi Valleys to eastern Texas as a
trough of low pressure presses slowly east. Farther west, isolated
showers and thunderstorms will form over parts of Arizona in
response to moisture arriving from Mexico. Meanwhile, widely
separated showers and thunderstorms will develop in the very warm
and humid air mass covering Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Patchy fog and low clouds will caress the West Coast Saturday
morning before yielding to sunshine. Away from the coast, heat will
build across interior California and Oregon as a warm ridge of high
pressure holds steady several thousand feet above the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Variable clouds and breezy, cooler conditions will prevail over
the northern Great Lakes in the wake of a cool front pressing
southeast over the upper Middle West.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Discrepant Danielle
</P>
<P>
   The first reconnaissance from Hurricane Danielle on Thursday
puzzled weather specialists. A wind of 112 mph was measured at
about 10,000 feet, an altitude that is often used to gauge the
maximum speed near the surface. But the instrument package dropped
into the eye of the storm signaled back a central pressure of only
997 millibars, or 29.45 inches of mercury. Typically, such strong
winds at flight level would be associated with a pressure of 980
millibars. Apparently, due to a shifting wind below flight level,
the instruments dropped into the eye were carried outside the
center of the hurricane.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 1720EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
