<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSING-FASHION-$ADV30-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHIONABLY TRENDY, BUT EMPTY BY DESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 30)  
(lb) 
 By FRANK DeCARO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fur is not only back _ it's cool. So pronounces Vogue
in its big September issue.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine reports that hip-hop has gone glam as rappers trade
``baggy for Bulgari'' and opt for a look that's ``less ghetto, more
Gucci.'' The feature, called ``Rappers Deluxe,'' features Mary J.
Blige, Lil' Kim and Missy Elliott in three of the most happening
furs of the season. What would have been fashion suicide three
years ago is now fashion chic.
</P>
<P>
   It is quite a makeover _ lynx has never been more phat _ and one
that says a lot about where fashion is. As entertainment eclipses
the design world as the culture's most influential taste-maker,
glamour has become something you slap on like a fresh coat of
paint, and personal style something you change whenever the mood
strikes. Everyone's a chameleon. Take any girl, hire a stylist to
the stars, borrow some jewelry, and suddenly she's a Gabor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Renee Zellweger Goes for the Glamour,'' Vogue's cover
promises, as the homespun actress shows the world her Oscar. (It's
a de la Renta.) So what if you've never seen a Gretchen Moll movie?
She looks like a star on Vanity Fair, so she must be one.
</P>
<P>
   As a society, we've followed Madonna's advice of long ago _
``Strike a pose,'' she once commanded _ and embraced rampant
RuPaul-ism. We feel comfortable borrowing guises from other eras,
other classes and other cultures, without stopping to reflect on
their meaning. We've adopted a Village People approach to getting
dressed. One day you're an Alexander McQueen cowboy, the next
you're a John Galliano Indian.
</P>
<P>
   Playing dress-up is fun, of course. But when new fads are
embraced constantly, it means that the clothes don't have much to
say. An East Village girl in Sergio Valente jeans sports a bindi
jewel on her forehead. Does it mean she's found religion or that
she watches Gwen Stefani on MTV? Most likely, the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion trends no longer speak of one's personal style but of
one's media savvy.
</P>
<P>
   Piercings, tattoos, henna painting: It all seems calculated,
coming from without rather than within.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, Pat Boone tried to make a comeback as a
heavy-metal rocker, trading his white bucks, a genuine fashion
statement of a mainstream pop idol, for black leather. It wasn't
provocative _ it was preposterous. If Debbie Boone's father is
wearing leather, it has no potency.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, at any Tom of Finland party, hundreds of men will turn
out in leather gear: advertising art directors, fashion editors,
stylists and not a real biker in sight. On nights like the one last
June at the Tunnel, so many were strapped in leather that it seemed
as if every gay man in New York had a harness in the closet hanging
between his Armani and his Zegna. What was once an underground
fetish has become just another look.
</P>
<P>
   Real leather men are too shocking for most of us today, as real
punks were 20 years ago. If it's genuine, it is too intense.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In college, I had my first truly punk experience. At a Bad
Brains concert at Roseland, a friend and I stood at the front of
the stage waiting for the hard-core band to come on. As a pre-show
crush began to form around us, I naively said to my companion,
``Oh, I hope they're not going to slam dance.'' A 4-foot-tall girl
with safety pins through her ear, a razor blade around her neck and
incredibly bad teeth looked up at me and scathingly asked what we
thought they might do instead. I fled immediately.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago I had a punk experience, '90s style. On
the way to see ``The Avengers,'' I spotted three teen-agers who
looked like Sex Pistol wannabes in their Trash and Vaudeville drag
sitting on the curb on 19th Street, waiting for the theater to
start seating.
</P>
<P>
   The big one wore red tartan bondage pants, a leather jacket
covered in safety pins and a ripped T-shirt, his Mohawk gelled into
Statue of Liberty spikes. The other two were in thrift-store
tatters and Doc Martens, streaks of green Crazy Color dye in their
purposely damaged hair. They were just goofing around until a
pained cry pierced the night air. ``Ow! That actually hurt!'' the
nose-ringed one shrieked.
</P>
<P>
   Kid Vicious had accidentally poked him in the face with his
hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Affectation can be dangerous,'' the British style pundit
Quentin Crisp once observed. He was referring to Isadora Duncan's
penchant for scarves, but he could just as easily have been
cautioning these kids.
</P>
<P>
   There's a little bit of poseur in all of us, to be sure, whether
we're jet-set society women wearing Kabuki couture, working stiffs
dressed in Ralph Lauren's off-the-rack version of Old Money, geeks
in hula shirts and jams who do all their surfing on the Net or
suburban hip-hoppers in droopy pants hanging at the mall.
</P>
<P>
   But real style isn't just a borrowed fur or another look on
loan. Even Marilyn Manson knows that. The rocker recently
jettisoned his trademark Goth image for a new glam one. ``If you're
gonna pretend to be something,'' he told Rolling Stone, ``then you
have to at least live up to what it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
