<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8043 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRCON-STUDIES-NYT &LR;      08-28 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRCON-STUDIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDYING HOW THE DEFEAT OF HEAT CHANGED NEARLY EVERYTHING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Calif., Pa.)   (bl)  
 By JANNY SCOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raymond Arsenault stumbled into his scholarly sideline back in
1982 when he was invited to speak on a panel on climate and
history. ``Just tell them about air-conditioning,'' his wife, a
seventh-generation Floridian, suggested facetiously. And so began
Arsenault's great air-conditioning adventure.
</P>
<P>
   He turned his conference paper into an article, ``The End of the
Long Hot Summer: The Air-Conditioner and Southern Culture,'' which
was published in The Journal of Southern History, then syndicated,
then anthologized, then reprinted so often it has become the
journal's most requested article for the last 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm known jokingly among my friends as `the air-conditioner
man,''' said Arsenault, a professor of history at the University of
South Florida, who could be found recently discussing the cultural
history of air-conditioning on ABC's ``Nightline.'' ``I feel like a
typecast actor sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Air-conditioning, as it turns out, is a rich topic, something so
ubiquitous and so easily taken for granted that it seems to have
occurred to few scholars to examine its impact on everything from
industrialization, migration patterns and public health to
architecture, family life, the environment and attitudes toward
nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of my favorite subjects,'' said Richard Nathan, a
political economist and director of the Rockefeller Institute of
Government in Albany, N.Y. ``The civil rights revolution and
air-conditioning are the two biggest factors that have changed
demography and a lot of our politics in the last 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   From the installation of the world's first air-conditioning
system in a Brooklyn printing company in 1902, through its march
through industrial plants, then movie theaters, then government
buildings, hospitals, hotels and finally homes, air-conditioning
was catapulted in the public perception ``from luxury to amenity to
necessity,'' as Arsenault recently put it.
</P>
<P>
   The population of the South grew dramatically, as mortality
dropped and in-migration grew. Air-conditioning proved crucial to
the industrialization of the region. It improved productivity and
encouraged economic growth, Arsenault concluded. It encouraged
urbanization, in part by helping make skyscrapers and high-rise
apartments more feasible.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Arsenault wrote, it ``weakened the bond
between humanity and the natural environment'' and ``impinged upon
a rich tradition of vernacular architecture'' by making it possible
to build inexpensive tract homes after World War II without the
high ceilings, long breezeways, open porches, transoms and other
features that once kept people cool.
</P>
<P>
   For years Arsenault's 32-page article, replete with footnotes
citing such sources as Air-Conditioning, Heating and Refrigeration
News, has stood as the most comprehensive scholarly attempt to
explore the history of air-conditioning, the growth of the industry
and air-conditioning's impact on society and culture.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Gail Cooper, a historian of technology and an associate
professor at Lehigh University in Bethlehem, Pa., has published
``Air-Conditioning America: Engineers and the Controlled
Environment, 1900-1960'' (Johns Hopkins, 1998), a study focusing on
the engineering effort to create an ``indoor climate.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the National Building Museum in Washington, which
takes as its mission the celebration of American achievements in
``the built environment,'' intends to open next May what is being
billed as the first major exhibition to explore the transformative
power of air-conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cooper, 44, grew up with air-conditioning in California's
Central Valley and remembers crawling out of her crib and into the
hall to sleep on the floor under the air-conditioner. Now she lives
in an 1890s house in the historic district of Bethlehem, where her
summers are filled with ceiling fans, iced drinks and occasional
escape to the movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see it as a complex subject,'' Ms. Cooper said. ``I tried to
describe how users feel: sometimes they love it; sometimes they
don't.'' As for herself, she works in a windowless office. ``It's
the kind of room that is only possible with air-conditioning,'' she
said. ``I think a lot of people do miss windows.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 1746EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
