<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8045 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAZZ-SOCIOLOGY-NYT &LR;      08-28 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZ-SOCIOLOGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCIOLOGISTS WITH A GIG OFF THE BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PATRICIA COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It was past the 10:30 starting time, but no one
seemed to pay much mind. The piano and horn players stood by the
baby grand laughing with a small circle of friends while the
audience chatted and sipped drinks in the too small, too hot room.
</P>
<P>
   Not much different from any Saturday at almost any jazz club.
Except the hour was a.m., the beverage of choice was coffee, the
venue was a conference room at the American Sociological
Association's annual convention and the neighbors who would soon be
complaining about the noise were from a panel on ``The Self and
Identity'' next door.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Harper, a sociologist at Duquesne University organized
last Saturday's panel, the first ever on the sociology of jazz. His
idea was to offer a smorsgasbord of current sociological work in
this increasingly popular field.
</P>
<P>
   The first panelist, Paul Applerouth of New York University, took
a historical approach, looking at how early anxieties about jazz
reflected worries over changing morals and crumbling racial
boundaries. (In 1926, the Salvation Army of Cincinnati filed a
lawsuit to prevent the construction of a jazz theater next to a
shelter for girls, arguing that ``music emanating from the theater
would implant `jazz emotions' in babies born at the home.'')
</P>
<P>
   David Grazian, a sociologist at the University of Chicago, then
discussed what's known in the trade as ``commodification,'' how
many of the supposedly ``authentic'' countercultural jazz musicians
and clubs now in Chicago are actually calculated Disneyland
versions, modern minstrel shows, replete with menus of watermelon
and barbecue ribs, and souvenir counters.
</P>
<P>
   And Paul Lopes, a sociologist at Tufts University, reviewed
previous work, noting how the image of the jazz musician has
embraced both the drug-using deviant and the professional, cultured
elitist.
</P>
<P>
   While these three looked at the jazz from the outside, Robert
Faulkner, who teaches at the University of Massachusetts at
Amherst, tried to get inside the process of creating the music. The
soul-tingling solo may sound like a spontaneous, inspired artistic
creation, but in fact the music is built on a series of routine
steps and conventions. Faulkner was trying to break down that
process of creation, to ``unpack culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner, who wears his black hair slicked back and bears a
passing resemblance to Regis Philbin (a comparison that would
undoubtedly mortify him), turned to sociology after striking out as
a studio musician in Los Angeles. To demonstrate the art of
improvisation, he began with his own experience as a trumpet
player, learning the introduction to the Dixieland classic ``Tin
Roof Blues'' by what sociologists call ``appropriating cultural
recipes,'' and what everybody else knows as stealing.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying him on the piano was Howard (Count) Becker, one of
the pioneers of the sociology of jazz. Becker, who worked his way
through school playing piano on 63rd Street in Chicago, wrote a
classic book in which he used jazz to examine deviant behavior and
the love-hate relationship between the musicians and their
audience.
</P>
<P>
   With the Count at the baby grand and Faulkner on the cornet,
they started with the sinuous, rolling melody from Gershwin's
``Rhapsody in Blue,'' then picked up with a few bars from the
original introduction to ``Tin Roof Blues,'' before segueing into
an obscure R-and-B phrase and a classic Texas tenor lick.
</P>
<P>
   Jazz musicians, Faulkner explained, start with a common
vocabulary and grammar. This ``high scripting,'' as it's called, is
the conventional way of doing things, the standard set of tunes and
the way they're played. Think of the disaster film formula or even
the process of cooking a hamburger and fries at MacDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   High scripting requires enormous daily maintenance. As Donald L.
Maggin relates in his biography of Stan Getz, Getz pored over
Lester Young's solo rendition of John Green's 1930 classic ``Body
and Soul,'' listening to it hundreds of times. (Faulkner said he
had worked on the piece 15 minutes every day for the past 15
years.) Improvisational magic comes when the musician takes the
result of his solitary, tedious practicing and exports it back to
the stage in his or her own voice.
</P>
<P>
   You can hear the process, Faulkner says, by comparing the
different recording sessions leading to the final version of John
Coltrane's 1959 breakthrough album ``Giant Steps.'' ``As you
listen, you can hear Coltrane taking on and discarding different
ideas,'' Faulkner said. This move from high to low scripting is not
just confined to jazz, but can be found in painting, writing and
haute cuisine as well.
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner's sociological rendition of ``Body and Soul'' began
with exercise No. 141 from the horn player's bible, ``Clarke's
Technical Studies for Cornet,'' included a phrase from ``Star
Eyes,'' Janet Jackson's ``Where Are You Now,'' (which he was
introduced to by his 8-year-old daughter) and then a snatch from
``Alfie.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an improvisational in-joke. When Dexter Gordon recorded
``Body and Soul'' on his ``Manhattan Symphony'' album, he inverted
a series of notes from ``Alfie,'' which Sonny Rollins had recorded
for the 1966 movie.
</P>
<P>
   Round noon, Harper stepped in to cut off Faulkner, who was
running over his allotted time. He noted that as John Coltrane got
older, his solos were running longer and longer, 25, 30, 35
minutes. Troubled, Coltrane talked to Miles Davis about it. How do
I finish my solos, he asked. ``John,'' Davis replied, ``Put the
horn down.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Faulkner put the horn down, the standing-room-only
crowd was spilling out into the hallway of the Hilton hotel, and a
dollar had been stuffed in a glass atop the baby grand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 1747EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
