<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8046 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANAMA-PRESIDENT-$ADV     08-28 1406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-PRESIDENT-$ADV30-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANAMANIAN VOTERS TO DECIDE RE-ELECTION FATE OF PRESIDENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Aug. 30) 
(Eds.: Vote is Sunday) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ After being ruled by a tyrant nicknamed
``Pineapple Face'' and a jocular president known as ``Sweetbread,''
Panamanians have a dynamic chief executive whom everyone calls
``The Bull.''
</P>
<P>
   Under President Ernesto Perez Balladares, Panama's economy has
expanded, and poverty has fallen. Highways, hospitals and public
housing have gone up.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the president's bid to keep his job past September 1999 _
three months before the United States is to hand over the Panama
Canal _ is in jeopardy. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Panamanians vote Sunday on a constitutional amendment that, if
passed, will allow the president to run in May for a second
consecutive five-year term.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the outcome of the binding referendum is too close
to call. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Perez Balladares claims that Panama requires a steady hand as
U.S. troops leave the country and the nation prepares to assume
full control of the Panama Canal on Dec. 31, 1999. He says
continuity is needed, as Panama wrangles with Washington over a
proposed multilateral anti-drug center in the former canal zone
that would be staffed with about 2,000 U.S. troops. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Negotiations for the center have stalled, in part, due to
Panama's concerns that it could turn into a full-fledged military
base and be used as a staging ground for U.S. military activities
in the region. Under the 1977 Panama Canal treaties, all 10,000
U.S. troops who had been stationed at 10 bases here must leave by
the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the constitutional amendment say Panama needs
Perez Balladares in the presidential office during this period of
transition.
</P>
<P>
   But critics insist that the country's democracy is too fragile
to permit the president's immediate re-election. Under current
Panamanian law, an outgoing president cannot run again until 10
years after leaving office.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Perez Balladares an unscrupulous liar and a
dictator-in-waiting, opponents of the amendment point out that the
president indicated in a 1995 interview that he would not seek
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is very powerful. He is practically a king,''
said Ricardo Arias Calderon, a former vice president who is urging
Panamanians to vote ``no'' in the referendum. ``If he gets any more
power, the king may decide not to step down.''
</P>
<P>
   Such concerns spring partly from Perez Balladares' past. He
heads the Democratic Revolutionary Party, or PRD, which long served
as a rubber stamp for the whims of dictator Manuel Noriega. In
1989, invading U.S. troops arrested Noreiga on drug charges, ending
two decades of military rule. The former dictator, whom many call
``Pineapple Face'' because of his pock-marked skin, is serving a
40-year-sentence in a U.S. federal prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the point of view of democratic development, I don't
think it's a good thing to give someone 10 years in power after 21
years of dictatorship by the same group of people,'' said Raul
Leis, a political scientist at the Center for Panamanian Studies
and Social Action.
</P>
<P>
   In Panama, executive-branch powers already are vast. The
president controls the national budget and can manhandle the
legislature. He names supreme court justices, the attorney general,
the comptroller general and election tribunal members.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Leis said, Perez Balladares is perhaps the most
talented president in Central America. He is far more popular than
Guillermo Endara, his predecessor, who was known as ``Sweetbread``
due to his sunny disposition but was widely viewed as ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the last government had done half of what we've done, the
country would be much better off. But they didn't,'' said Housing
Minister Francisco Sanchez Cardenas, coordinator of the ``yes''
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Others say that fears of a civilian dictatorship are overblown.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential re-election ``doesn't raise any red flags,'' said
Peggy Scranton, a political scientist at the University of Arkansas
who has written a book on Panama. ``I think the country has had
plenty of time (to consolidate democracy). People have become
hypersensitive to the misuse of power.''
</P>
<P>
   Called ``The Bull'' for his ample girth and headstrong
personality, Perez Balladares was elected in 1994. He quickly
pushed through a series of free-market reforms that cut import
tariffs, revised the labor code, streamlined the government and
forced Panama to plug into the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   In a nationally televised address Thursday, Perez Balladares
argued that he needs more time to complete his reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are starting to see results,'' he said. ``What I'm
interested in is finishing my program of government ... to make
sure that the things we have done bare fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez Balladares said the fate of the proposed anti-drug center
is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if (an agreement) will be signed or not,'' he
said. ``If the conditions that Panama believes are necessary are
accepted by the United States and other countries, it will happen.
If not, it won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Panama suggested building the anti-drug center, because it has
been unable to attract substantial new development to the 335,000
acres of the former canal zone.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. military withdrawal from Panama is nearly complete.
Polls indicate, however, that most Panamanians support a continued
U.S. military presence here.
</P>
<P>
   Should Panama's 1.7 million eligible voters approve Sunday's
amendment, Leis said that Perez Balladares would almost surely win
the May presidential election. However, a ``no'' vote could kill
the anti-drug center negotiations and stall other major
initiatives, according to a Western diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would be a lame duck that has been explicitly rejected,''
the diplomat said of Perez Balladares. ``He will suffer a major
loss of political power.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid that scenario, the ``yes'' campaign has spent about $5
million, Leis said. It has saturated TV stations with propaganda,
staged free street festivals with salsa bands and hired James
Carville, a longtime strategist for U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Perez Balladares had expected an easy victory.
After all, Argentina, Brazil and Peru have all passed amendments to
allow consecutive presidential re-election.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than focusing on constitutional issues, the campaign
here has turned into a plebiscite on Perez Balladares.
</P>
<P>
   And he is gradually losing support.
</P>
<P>
   His economic reforms, which analysts say were unavoidable, have
angered industrialists, organized labor and the lower class. These
groups had expected protectionist policies and more social spending
from Perez Balladares, whose 1994 campaign slogan was ``power to
the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, they accuse the president of empowering bankers and
stockbrokers. Alfredo Oranges, a dissident PRD legislator, accused
Perez Balladares of ``hating the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is the lack of a compelling national theme to
rally Panamanians around the banner of presidential re-election.
</P>
<P>
   The three South American nations that have already changed their
constitutions to allow the practice did so to award presidents for
guiding them through periods of severe economic and political
upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   Panama suffered a traumatic U.S. invasion. But by the time Perez
Balladares was sworn in, the nation was back on its feet.
</P>
<P>
   Even the hand-over of the canal is considered a nearly done
deal. Most of the U.S. managers and laborers already have gone
home. Today, 93 percent of the 8,000 canal workers are Panamanian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a change of president in 1999 represents the
difference between chaos and order,'' said Fernando Manfredo, a
former administrator of the Panama Canal Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the ``no'' forces, made up of seven opposition parties,
could lose today if they fail to get out the vote. Divided and
disorganized, the parties signed a unification accord just last
week and failed to open a campaign office. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Back in 1994, similar divisions among these parties _ and their
failure to back a single candidate _ allowed Perez Balladares to
win the presidency with just 33 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
John Otis is a free-lance journalist who wrote this for the Houston
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
