<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
LOW-COST, COOL iMAC A HIT WITH FEW FLAWS 
 
(Eds.: Resending) 
 
By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's get two obvious things out of the way first.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Apple Computer's iMac is the coolest-looking computer
around. Apple has done a wonderful job of designing something
that's both very functional and aesthetically pleasing. It's also
given the company a great marketing opportunity, which has given
birth to a wonderful slogan: ``Sorry, no beige.''
</P>
<P>
   And no, the iMac does not have a floppy disk drive, and yes,
that's a big mistake. The floppy is not dead yet, and Apple's done
a disservice to buyers of the iMac by forcing them to spend extra
cash for an external, removable drive.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac is to Apple what the K-car was to Chrysler. It's the
product Apple is counting on to pull it permanently out of trouble.
It seems to be working _ iMacs are moving off the shelves at a
feverish pace. Apple's future hasn't looked this bright in years.
</P>
<P>
   It is also Apple's play for the low-cost, consumer market. At
$1,299, it's not as cheap as some Windows-based PCs, but it has the
benefit of being better designed and easier for novices to use.
</P>
<P>
   While Apple offers ``no beige'' for the iMac, it doesn't offer
any other colors, either. Its translucent, teal-and-white case is
all that's available. It looks nice in most decors, so long as the
carpet isn't fire-engine red and the walls aren't painted plum.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac is incredibly easy to set up, partly because the
monitor is built into the case. Plug the power cord (it's
translucent, too) in the back. Open a small door on the right side
to connect the keyboard, phone cord and any network cables if you
have them. Plug the mouse into a port on the side of the keyboard.
Push the power button on the keyboard, and that's it _ the iMac is
ready to rock.
</P>
<P>
   On initial power-up, the iMac walks you through a series of
set-up questions, determining if you are on a network and whether
you want to set up Internet access. While the Net access assistant
isn't quite as friendly as the Internet wizard found on Windows
95/98, it greatly simplifies this process for Macintosh owners.
</P>
<P>
   The operating system is basic Mac OS 8.1. Don't expect any
software surprises; what's new here is the hardware design. But the
Mac OS is better integrated with the Mac hardware than Windows is
with the Intel architecture _ you can't beat the Mac for
plug-and-play _ and the Mac's user interface is simpler. Given that
the market for this machine includes novices and home users, basic
may be better.
</P>
<P>
   With its 233-megahertz PowerPC G3 chip and 32 megabytes of
memory, it's a relatively fast computer, performing basic tasks,
such as launching programs and switching between them at speeds
comparable to Windows machines with similar specifications. If you
work with graphics-intensive programs, it will outrun most
Windows-based machines, but don't expect miracles for day-to-day
applications.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac uses two kinds of connections for hardware. There's a
built-in Ethernet port for connecting the system to a network, and
Universal Serial Bus, or USB, ports. There are no serial nor SCSI
ports, which means any devices you connect to this will have to use
USB connections, or go through an adapter. Because USB is
relatively new, there are not yet a lot of USB-based products,
though many are promised from manufacturers. Adapters are available
in the $50-$60 range.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac comes with a 56K modem _ I couldn't get it to do better
than 33.6, which apparently is a common complaint among many new
iMac owners _ and a 24-speed CD-ROM drive. Two small,
mediocre-sounding speakers are built into the front of the case.
The built-in, 15-inch monitor is an excellent display.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the iMac's floppy-free concept: it's definitely an
idea way ahead of its time. Apple argues the floppy is dead, and
raises this question: ``When was the last time you used your floppy
disk drive?'' They say that most software today comes on CD-ROM,
and that most data files are bigger than the floppy's 1.44-megabyte
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe hyper-geeks who are comfortable burning their own CD-ROM
disks think the floppy is dead, but most home users still rely on
the format. What about children working on Macs at school who want
to bring their efforts home on floppy disk?
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, there's no removable-disk standard that's
taken the floppy's place. Consumers can choose from a variety of
formats _ 100-megabyte Iomega Zip drives, LS120 SuperDrives,
Syquest's 1- and 1.5-gigabyte SparQ drives and Sony's upcoming
high-density floppies. The Zip drive has a bigger installed base,
but it's by no means a standard.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to buy an external drive, you'll have to pay about
$90 for a USB-based floppy, which is ridiculous for a consumer
machine. If you decide to move up to a larger format, such as the
LS120, you'll pay $120 and more.
</P>
<P>
   If its designers were going to insist on leaving out the floppy,
Apple should have made an external floppy an option in the $30
price range.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the lack of a floppy drive, my only serious complaint
about the iMac has to do with its mouse. The design is, frankly, an
abomination. The mouse is flat and round, like a pancake. It's
uncomfortable to use in a long computing session. And because it's
perfectly round, you've got no tactile sense of where the ``top''
of the mouse is pointing. After a while, I find that I've lost the
mouse's orientation and must adjust it. Fortunately, because it's a
USB-based mouse, it's easy to replace. Companies like Logitech that
make mice are going to make a killing.
</P>
<P>
   (At first, I thought this was just me, so I asked some of the
artists at work who are longtime Mac users to give it a try. They
hated it, too.)
</P>
<P>
   If you are the owner of an aging Mac at home, such as one of the
older Performa models, and you've been waiting for Apple to create
a compelling new consumer offering, you need wait no longer. The
iMac is a must for you.
</P>
<P>
   If you are one of the millions of people who have yet to take
part in the personal computer revolution and have not yet learned
how to use a computer, the iMac is an excellent choice.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a novice Windows user who hates hassling with the
quirks and shortcomings of that operating system _ and if you don't
have a large investment in applications software _ the iMac is
worth considering.
</P>
<P>
   While I'm a Windows kinda guy, it feels very good to be able to
once again recommend a Macintosh to certain readers. Thanks, Apple.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
