<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ One statistic stands out to explain the
importance of Japan, along with its misery: When trading ended
Friday in Tokyo, Japanese stocks this week alone had dropped in
value by $241 billion _ a sum that exceeds the size of the entire
Russian economy at present exchange rates. Japan is so monumental
as to be central to the health of the global economy, but for now
it remains a mess, albeit an impressively large one. A month after
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi took office, vowing ``to deal with each
issue in a dramatic, speedy way,'' Japan remains firmly in
recession and largely paralyzed politically and economically. By
Nicholas D. Kristof and Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
