<HEADLINE>
LINDSEY TESTIFIES TO GRAND JURY IN CLINTON INVESTIGATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Deputy White House Counsel Bruce Lindsey finally
testifed Friday before a federal grand jury, ending a hard-fought
battle to keep him from being questioned about President Clinton's
acknowledged relationship with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey testified for nearly four hours.
</P>
<P>
   As he left the federal court house, the president's closest
confidant declined to talk about his appearance or whether he
refused to answer some questions as he has done on three previous
occasions. Asked if he expects to be called back, Lindsey said, ``I
don't know. It's up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey, who had tried to claim lawyer-client privilege about
his conversations with the president, was forced to appear before
the grand jury after the Supreme Court denied a White House request
to block his testimony on grounds that it would violate the
president's right to confidential legal advice.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has yet to rule, however, on the larger White
House motion claiming attorney-client privilege concerning the
president's conversations with Lindsey. That ruling will not come
until after October, which may be after Starr wraps up his
investigation. The probe began with Clinton's Whitewater land deal
connections and is ending with an unprecedented examination of
whether the president lied about having a sexual relationship with
Lewinsky in the White House and tried to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey is considered a key witness in Starr's investigation.
But it is still unclear whether he has given Starr any information
that could be used to build a case of perjury or obstruction of
justice against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is reportedly interested in learning whether Lindsey was
involved in an alleged cover-up of the president's liaisons with
Lewinsky or tried to influence the testimony of other witnesses
before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Starr also is said to be interested in Lindsey's conversations
last year with Linda Tripp, whose secret and perhaps illegal tape
recordings of Lewinsky triggered the prosecutor's look into
Clinton's sex life. Lindsey apparently spoke to Tripp in an attempt
to learn more about allegations that the president made unwanted
advances on former White House volunteer Kathleen Willey in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   As Lindsey appeared before the grand jury, reports surfaced that
Lewinsky and Clinton secretary Betty Currie may have provided
different stories to Starr about how gifts the president gave to
the former intern were retrieved from her apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Currie, according to sources who spoke with The Associated
Press, testified that she picked up the gifts after being asked to
by Lewinsky. Her testimony is similar to what President Clinton has
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewinsky, the sources said, testified that Currie showed up
on her own and asked for the gifts to be returned to the president.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors working with Starr believe that the retrieval or
return of the gifts indicates that Clinton and Lewinsky may have
been trying to erase evidence of their relationship at a time when
the president was being sued by Paula Jones for sexual harassment.
Lewinsky was eventually questioned by Jones' attorneys and denied
having a sexual relationship with the president.
</P>
<P>
   In another development Friday, the Baltimore Sun reported that
Tripp, who is under investigation for illegal wiretapping in
Maryland because she taped conversations with Lewinsky, was told
when she bought her telephone taping equipment that it was illegal
to secretly record in the state.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Radio Shack store where she bought the
taping equipment issued a statement saying that it was the
company's policy to tell buyers that secretly taping phone
conversations would be a violation of Maryland law.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp, who sent her tapes of Lewinsky to Starr back in January,
has maintained that she was not aware that secretly recording over
the phone is illegal in Maryland. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
