<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-TRAVERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORMED QUEST FACES DISTANCE CHALLENGE AT TRAVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Shug McGaughey, who was born in
Lexington, Ky., site of the bluest of the bluegrass, is a
consummate horseman and has trained a long list of outstanding
horses, including seven Eclipse Award winners.
</P>
<P>
   McGaughey, 47, saddled his first winner at Rockingham Park in
1976 and has seen a lot over the years. Never, though, had he faced
as big a challenge as he did with Cornado's Quest, the reformed bad
boy, who won the $1 million Haskell at Monmouth Aug. 9 and is
listed at 8-5 to capture the 129th running of the $750,000 Travers
Stakes at Saratoga today.
</P>
<P>
   A son of Forty Niner who won both the Haskell and the Travers in
1988, Coronado's Quest won three straight stakes at Aqueduct last
fall to establish himself as a horse to watch for the Kentucky
Derby. When he arrived at Gulfstream Park for his winter campaign,
things were supposed to get better, but they got worse, much worse.
</P>
<P>
   Favored at 4-5 in the Hutcheson Stakes Jan. 31, Cornado's Quest
pulled a nutty in both the paddock and the post parade and finished
second. He wasn't any better before the Fountain of Youth Feb. 21,
acting up and finishing second at 7-5. The Florida Derby on March
14 was the final straw as he behaved badly again and faded to fifth
at 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   But this time McGaughey did something about it. He had known for
some time that Coronado's Quest was having minor breathing
problems, but after jockey Robbie Davis told him the horse had
``made a big noise'' in the Florida Derby, McGaughey had him
operated on to correct an entrapped epiglottis. Coronado's Quest
has not lost since, piling up four victories since April 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disappointed this winter in Florida,'' said
McGaughey. ``He just became completely unglued in the paddock
before the Hutcheson. We never got him back after that. I think
because of that one day, the whole winter was lost. As soon as we
got him out of Florida, he's not been beaten. He hasn't done
anything wrong since. He got through the Haskell in good shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there'll be a lot of people here for the Travers, but
there won't be 80,000 as there were for the Belmont (Coronado's
Quest won the Riva Ridge on the undercard). There were 40,000 at
the Haskell and he was fine. I go into every race hopefully
optimistic. I hope it's all behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming he behaves himself, the big question Coronado's Quest
must answer is whether he can handle the mile and one-quarter
Travers distance. His main opponent, the 7-5 favorite Victory
Gallop, long ago proved he could run a long way, finishing second
in the 10-furlong Kentucky Derby and the Preakness, at a mile and
three-16ths, and winning the 1 1/2-mile Belmont. Victory Gallop, a
son of noted closer Cryptoclearance, has a big heart, but he
doesn't have quick feet. Coronado's Quest, who has a sharp turn of
foot, got the jump in the Haskell and Victory Gallop couldn't catch
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the distance is going to be a problem for him,
though I might say something different after the race,'' McGaughey
continued. ``I'm not worried about a mile and one-quarter. He's the
kind of horse who will wait on his rider and I've always been told
that a horse who waits on his rider will run as far as he has to.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor to look at is that, while he has been training
very well here, Victory Gallop has never raced at The Spa, while
Coronado's Quest won two of three starts here as a 2-year-old,
losing only to eventual Horse of the Year Favorite Trick (who will
run in the 7-furlong King's Bishop on the Travers undercard) in the
Hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he likes this racetrack,''said McGaughey. ``He prefers
a bigger track (Saratoga is a 1 1/8-mile oval). He struggles to
change leads sometimes and I think he'll like the bigger turns
here.''
</P>
<P>
   McGaughey, who trained back-to-back Travers winners, Easy Goer
in 1989 and Rhythm in '90, schooled Coronado's Quest in the
Saratoga paddock Fridaythe last two days. Friday, Coronado's Quest
was well behaved, but on Thursday he created a bit of a stir with
some high-flying antics.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was certainly not the performance that we wanted, but it
was just feeling good kind of stuff,'' explained McGaughey. ``He
was bucking and kicking. It wasn't the stop and turn the other way
stuff he did in Florida. I think it's likely that the entrapped
epiglottis was the problem. He was not comfortable at Gulfstream.
We have used patience. My people have done a great job and they've
taken their time. We're just going to keep doing what we've been
doing since April.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, we're at Saratoga. We've seen upsets here
time and time again. Strange things happen. So, let's go over
there, run the race, and, hopefully, whoever is the best horse will
win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
