<SLUG> BC-NY-PORN-SHOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN GIULIANI'S CRACKDOWN ON PORN SHOPS, COURT RULING IS A SET BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A state judge dealt a blow Friday to New York City's
efforts to curtail the pornography industry, ruling that Show
World, a midtown Manhattan porn emporium, and two other adult video
stores can stay in business as long as no more than 40 percent of
their floor space and inventory are dedicated to adult
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by Judge Stephen Crane of state Supreme Court in
Manhattan breaks a long-running series of legal victories on the
issue for the Giuliani administration and suggests that the mayor
may achieve only a muted victory in his crackdown on sex shops. The
city said it would not appeal Crane's ruling, but it vowed to
continue trying to shut sex shops.
</P>
<P>
   While several strip clubs have already been shut down under the
new anti-pornography zoning law, Friday's court ruling indicates
that some adult video stores may be able to remain open by selling
non-adult merchandise in the front portion of their sales space and
reserving back rooms for adult entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to comply with the new zoning restrictions, the owners
of Show World, a 20-year-old, three-story business on Eighth Avenue
near Times Square, took advantage of vague language in the new law
that defined an adult establishment as a business that devotes a
``substantial portion'' of its stock or floor space to adult
entertainment. Citing the city Department of Building's
interpretation of ``substantial portion'' as more than 40 percent,
Show World and other video stores replaced more than 60 percent of
their ``triple X'' videos, ``peep-a-live'' booths and other sex
merchandise with luggage, cameras, NYPD T-shirts and classic films.
They then declared themselves ``non-adult'' businesses to the
court.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the city argued that the changes were a
``subterfuge'' by the stores to evade the new law, which bars adult
video stores and strip clubs from operating in residential areas or
within 500 feet of a school, house of worship or another sex shop.
</P>
<P>
   But in his opinion, Crane ruled that the changes implemented by
Show World, NRS Video and Les Hommes were substantial and make them
``non-adult businesses'' under the new law.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the victory by the sex shops, questions remain whether
sex shops that eliminate more than 60 percent of their lucrative
pornographic merchandise can remain economically viable,
particularly in high-rent parts of Manhattan such as Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Crane suggested in his ruling that the tactics used by the city
in enforcing the new law, tactics sex-shop owners have complained
are heavy handed, may have backfired.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
