<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO SPORT LIKE BASEBALL   AND ITS RECORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's late August 1998, and what kind of a sports world is it?
</P>
<P>
   It's one in which an individual obsession _ ours, not the
athletes' _ is the leading topic in sport. Totally secondary to the
issue of winning and losing baseball games is the matter of whether
or not Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa, or Ken Griffey hits another home
run and thus comes closer to catching the late Roger Maris. It is,
I suspect, much more of an American character trait to care about
personal records of any kind than it is elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   This interest speaks to the nature of the game, of course. It is
yet another example of how baseball will always dwarf our other
major team sports as a conversational topic. No other sport can be
so readily dissected into manageable conversational parts. Batting
is one fascinating topic. Pitching and defense have their own
endless areas of discussion. Each position _ the infield admittedly
more so than the outfield _ is specifically fascinating in a way
that, say, basketball or hockey positions can never be.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, we Americans love to quantify. The most. The biggest.
The longest. There is something within us that just loves lists and
rankings. The 100 greatest movies. The 100 greatest novels. The top
10 steakhouses. The top five sunsets.
</P>
<P>
   That's the subjective stuff. We get to that when we're through
with the clinically objective, and that's something sport provides.
We adore records. The team record, the arena record, the league
record, the all-time record, the record for holding the most
records (Wayne Gretzky, I suppose) ... we can't get enough of
records. And of all the American sports records, the one we
venerate the most is that for home runs in one season.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other achievements (scoring points in basketball comes to
mind), it is a pure, unarguable feat. Once a basketball player
reaches a certain talent level, he or she can score points if
enough shots are taken. But hitting a home run is an isolated act.
It is _ and this can never be emphasized enough _ not easy. It is
not a matter of sheer strength. It is not strictly a matter of
timing. It is not simply a matter of game intelligence. It is a
matter of all three.
</P>
<P>
   You know, everyone now routinely speaks of it being Maris's
record, which, of course, it is, but I believe the ultimate reason
it matters as much as it does is that in our collective
subconscious mind it still belongs to Babe Ruth and not the
taciturn Yankee of far more modest career accomplishment who
unaccountably exceeded his previous career best by 32 home runs to
break Babe's record back in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Hear me out. Please.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth remains the most outsized figure in the history of
baseball, if not in all of American sport. He was a pure fictional
character, a socially maladjusted, thumb-his-nose-at-society
roughneck from Baltimore who was on his way to a Hall of Fame
career as a lefthanded pitcher when Red Sox general manager Ed
Barrow converted him to a full-time outfielder in 1919 in the
belief that this man-child was too talented a hitter not to be in
the lineup every day. On a 1-to-10 scale of sports prescience, Mr.
Barrow's decision rates as somewhere between a 15 and a 16. It was
the single wisest American sports judgment of this century.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth popularized the home run. Indeed, he was the home run in
the eyes of the American sporting public. The fact remains that,
dead ball or no, if Ruth had been a full-time outfielder from the
beginning of his major league career late in 1914, he would have
had little trouble making up the 41-homer gap between his career
total of 714 and Hank Aaron's record total of 755. Hank has the
record in people's heads; the Babe has the record in their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, with Roger Maris and his 61. He did it. We all know
that. He did it with eight more games at his disposal, but he did
it in far tougher overall circumstances, in an era of
coast-to-coast travel and specialized relief pitching and sliders
and overall daily media attention that the Babe never had to
contend with. But the fact that it was Roger Maris, and not Mickey
Mantle, Willie Mays, or Hank Aaron, who did it always has been an
open sore in the American sports consciousness. He did it, yes. But
did he deserve to do it? In their hearts, millions of baseball
enthusiasts say no. That's just the way it is.
</P>
<P>
   The record resonates, I firmly believe, not because Maris holds
it but because Ruth, the very symbol of the home run itself, was
the man who first put the magic number of 60 on the board.
</P>
<P>
   That is why it is so easy to root for McGwire, as opposed to
either Sosa or Griffey. McGwire, so classically Brobdingnagian, is,
at the very least, the Jimmie Foxx, if not the Babe Ruth himself,
of our time. Of all the players who have come into the game in the
63 years since the Babe's retirement, McGwire is clearly the most
deserving heir to the swat throne. He looks the part, he acts the
part, and, with 50-plus home runs in three consecutive seasons
(something the Bambino himself never was able to do), he executes
the part.
</P>
<P>
   In a more orderly sports world, McGwire would be out there by
himself. But it's not fiction, is it? It's real life, and here is
Sammy Sosa, not high on anyone's list of Ruth/Maris pursuers prior
to this season, also ready to join the 60 Club. I don't sense that
people are as, you know, offended, by his presence as they were by
that of Maris. Perhaps it's because he brings such a refreshingly
cheerful Latino presence to the party.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey? He is always, always, always a threat. There is a 65
season lurking in his portfolio somewhere, and when it happens, he
will likewise be universally applauded.
</P>
<P>
   The home run record represents the convergence of a peculiarly
American obsession, record keeping, with that of a peculiarly
American myth, Babe Ruth. I read the other day where a leading
London sports bookie says he never even heard of Mark McGwire. Of
course. This is about nobody on earth but Us.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
