<SLUG> BC-MA-DRUG-BENEFITS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARSHBARGER SAYS HE'LL SUE TO PRESERVE DRUG BENEFITS FOR SENIORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Attorney General Scott Harshbarger is ready to sue to
preserve unlimited prescription drug benefits for Massachusetts
seniors, a position that could set state and federal authorities on
a collision course over the popular state law.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger's office Friday said he would fight to prevent
federal Medicare authorities from pre-empting the Massachusetts law
that forces insurers to offer the benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott Harshbarger is prepared to take the matter to court to
preserve the state's right to require this benefit for
Massachusetts seniors,'' said Barbara Anthony, chief of the
attorney general's public protection bureau. ``We will do
everything in our power to fight this. It is a very critical
benefit for seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities recently issued a letter suggesting that a
federal law passed under the 1997 Balanced Budget Act prevents
Massachusetts from requiring that Medicare health maintenance
organizations offer unlimited drug benefits. The federal
pre-emption would affect only Medicare HMOs, and would not apply to
Medex and other Medicare supplemental policies. Massachusetts is
the only state in the nation that requires unlimited precription
drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating a possible end to the state mandate, some HMOs have
submitted for federal approval plans with limited drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress and the Health Care Financing Administration (HCFA)
are granted the exclusive right to determine benefits,'' said
Nancy-Ann Min DeParle, administrator of HCFA, in a letter to
Harshbarger. ``Therefore, under the statute, states cannot specify
what must be included as a Federal Medicare benefit ....''
</P>
<P>
   The letter, though dated Aug. 22, was received by Harshbarger's
office Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Any litigation would be a long time in coming, however, because
the federal rule would not be final until the end of September at
the earliest. Meanwhile, HCFA is accepting public comment until
Sept. 24 on the federal rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not tomorrow, next week, or even a month from now,
because the comment period doesn't expire until Sept. 24,'' Anthony
said. ``There is always the possibility that federal
authorities &UR;  &LR; could change their minds and avert this collision
course.''
</P>
<P>
   Tufts Health Plan, Harvard Pilgrim Health Care, and Blue Cross
and Blue Shield of Massachusetts are among the plans that have said
they plan to introduce limited drug benefits. About 211,000 seniors
in the state belong to an HMO.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
