<SLUG> BC-MA-RAYTHEON-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON, ELECTRICIANS SEEK CONTRACT AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ With the expiration of the current contract set
for Saturday night, Raytheon Co. and its electrical union continued
talks Friday in an attempt to reach an agreement and ease tensions
among workers at the firm's manufacturing plants.
</P>
<P>
   Although they have not taken a strike authorization vote,
members of the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers
Local 1505 could do so following the expiration of their three-year
pact at 12:01 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are tired of concessions,'' said union steward Charles
D. Lake during a midafternoon break outside Raytheon's Waltham
plant Friday. ``Last year, they gave up a lot. Now, they want to
see what Raytheon has to offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon spokeswoman Toni Simonetti said both sides appear to be
making progress at the bargaining table. She declined, however, to
discuss details or sticking points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make progress everyday,'' Simonetti said.``I cannot
predict what will happen this weekend, but we are hopeful we will
reach an agreement and that the (union) membership will approve.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time,'' she added, ``we are prepared for any
outcome. We are prepared for a work stoppage in the event we do not
reach an agreement. There are three scenarios: We have a contract
everybody approves of; we extend negotiations and they work without
a contract, or they strike... We won't know which of those will
occur until Sunday morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Union officials did not return telephone calls Friday. However,
leaflets passed out to various members Friday noted that progress
had been made on job security, overtime, and training. The union,
which is seeking a wage hike and an end to the current two-tier
wage scale, said little progress had been made in that area.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2,000 members are expected to meet in Lowell at 8 a.m.
Sunday to discuss the status of talks and the provisions of a
company &UR;  &LR; contract proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions have risen among workers in recent months with the
announcements of layoffs at various Raytheon sites in
Massachusetts. In June, Raytheon confirmed the layoffs of 1,500
employees at its engineering and construction unit in Cambridge.
The unit, hard hit by reductions in defense industry contracts, saw
500 more layoffs than the company had proposed in January.
</P>
<P>
   Also this summer, news that 261 factory jobs would be cut due to
defense contract reductions sparked protests at Raytheon plants in
Andover, Waltham, and Quincy.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, union members said they had agreed to a wage freeze
and other concessions in the past so that Raytheon would stay in
Massachusetts and maintain jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon is one of the state's largest employers. It has
facilities in 10 communities with 15,400 employees in
Massachusetts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
