<HEADER>
A8138 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLOMBIA-HEROIN-HNS &LR;      08-28 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-HEROIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROP INITIATIVE A RARE VICTORY IN COLOMBIA'S WAR ON DRUGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Goes with Colombia-Heroin-U.S.) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITAYO, Colombia _ Pointing to the green patches of potatoes and
corn that surround this Paez Indian village, Jairo Soscue said the
landscape once reflected a different hue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was red with poppies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As a small cog in Colombia's booming heroin trade, hundreds of
Paez Indians in Pitayo until recently grew opium poppies and sold
their narcotic-laden gum to drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   But the crimson blossoms became a curse. Poppy farmers
squandered their earnings. Pitayo was plagued by shootings and
public drunkenness.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed tribal elders decided that the flowers had to go. They
persuaded growers to uproot their poppies and to plant traditional
crops.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 10 months later, the initiative appears to represent a rare
victory in Colombia's war on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The opium poppy was introduced to Colombia in the mid-1980s by
drug lords from Southeast Asia. Today, the country's heroin exports
are surging. According to the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration,
52 percent of the heroin seized in the United States in 1996 was
Colombian.
</P>
<P>
   The flowers spread to Pitayo through Paez Indians who worked as
migrant coffee pickers. Members of the now-defunct Medellin drug
cartel persuaded them to experiment with the new seeds back home in
the rugged Andes mountains, where the climate for growing opium
poppies is ideal.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the poppies seemed like a dream cash crop. Growers cut
small incisions in the flower pods and extracted milky-white opium
gum, which drug traffickers turned into heroin. From one acre of
flowers, farmers could earn up to $1,500 per harvest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Indians know a lot about agriculture, and this was very
easy to grow,'' said Soscue, who was elected governor of the Paez
last year. Drug merchants ``would pay in advance and say, `In four
or five months I'll be back for the entire crop.'''
</P>
<P>
   Yet new wealth led to new problems.
</P>
<P>
   Food had to be purchased at town markets, because farmers had
abandoned subsistence crops. Children quit school to work in the
fields. And with so many people focused on profits, the tradition
of communal work projects was lost.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of saving their money, many poppy growers splurged on
motorcycles, fancy clothes, pistols and cane alcohol. More than a
dozen Indians were killed in drug disputes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people began to drink and throw money around,'' said
Omaira Mostacilla, a town official in Pitayo. ``A lot of the women
complained, because they had to take care of five or six kids by
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People never learned how to manage their money,'' Soscue
added. ``They would go to the cantinas not for any old drink, but
for five-star brandy. That's when the big problems began, and
people began to kill each other.''
</P>
<P>
   That's also when members of the Paez tribal council began
looking for a way out. They found an answer in a nearby Guambia
Indian village. People there had voluntarily eradicated 1,250 acres
of poppies with the help of PLANTE, a government agency that
provides credits and technical support to farmers who abandon drug
crops.
</P>
<P>
   The Paez signed up for a similar project that included $285,000
in low-cost loans to help farmers plant soybeans, onions, corn and
potatoes and to set up small businesses. The credit was critical,
because few banks in Colombia lend to poor farmers.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, hundreds of machete-wielding Indians attacked their
poppies one morning last October. Within hours, they had cut down
the village's entire crop.
</P>
<P>
   A few disgruntled growers left Pitayo, and the tribal council
received threatening letters from heroin traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Though a few rows of red flowers have sprouted again, most
residents seem committed to the plan.
</P>
<P>
   The switch to legal crops ``can't just be an issue of money,
because drug money will always be greater,'' said Nelson Melo,
director of the regional PLANTE office. ``But if it's a
quality-of-life issue, drug money loses its significance.''
</P>
<P>
   Up until now, anti-drug efforts in the Colombian countryside
have focused almost entirely on forced eradication of opium poppies
and coca, the raw material for cocaine, by police crop-dusters
funded by the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   But Klaus Nyholm, who heads the United Nations' International
Drug Control Program in Colombia, insists that alternative crop
projects deserve more support. &UR;  &LR; ``It hasn't reached the size where
it really matters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's new president, Andres Pastrana, seems to agree. In
his Aug. 7 inauguration speech, he said the nation must build
roads, power plants and other infrastructure to help wean peasants
off drug crops. Even Washington is warming up to the idea.
</P>
<P>
   A senior State Department official said that massive aerial
spraying will continue but added that the Clinton administration
will consider supporting some of Pastrana's initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Nyholm said that alternative crop projects work especially well
in close-knit Indian villages, where tribal authorities are highly
respected.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, there is little sense of community among pioneer
farmers in the jungles of southern Colombia, where thousands of
acres of coca are grown and where many people live too far from
towns to sell legal crops.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Guambia and the Paez, who live just a few miles from
major cities, ``are still in the struggling phase,'' Nyholm said.
</P>
<P>
   Due to a bureaucratic snafu, just half of the PLANTE loan money
for Pitayo has arrived. While farmers make the transition to legal
crops, residents rely on U.N. food donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colombia is a country of good, healthy peasants, but they need
help`` said Melo, the PLANTE director. ``If there are alternatives,
I'm sure that they would accept them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we only offer them laws and prohibitions,'' he said, ``we
are not helping at all.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
John Otis is a free-lance journalist who wrote this for the Houston
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
