<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8155 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGO-ARMY-VOLUNTEERS     08-28 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-ARMY-VOLUNTEERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOINING CONGO'S ARMY WITH LITTLE PREPARATION BUT HIGH IDEALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo _ Damase Kava-Zumbu first heard about what his
nephew had done when he walked into his courtyard a couple of weeks
ago, a few days after rebels launched an attack against the
government here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonton's gone and volunteered,'' one of his children told him.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he sat down with his nephew. ``Are you aware of what
you've done?'' asked the uncle, a thoughtful, university-educated
agronomist. The nephew answered that he was eager to defend his
country against foreign invaders.
</P>
<P>
   The uncle asked nothing else, even though he knew the young man
would go to war with almost no training, in part because he agreed
with his simple reasoning, in part because he barely knew him. A
younger sister of Kava-Zumbu's had sent her son away from the
family's ancestral village to live with his uncle here in La Cite,
the sprawling collection of dilapidated neighborhoods south of
Kinshasa's business and diplomatic center.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his uncle's courtyard, leaning toward his
grandmother, who everyone knew spoiled him, the nephew, Tonton
Miaka, now waited for the government to hand him a uniform and an
AK-47.
</P>
<P>
   A quiet, impassive man of 24, Miaka let slip a faint smile only
when he recalled that since he had volunteered, the youths in the
neighborhood had begun saluting him and calling him Mokonzi,
``chief'' in the local dialect.
</P>
<P>
   Kinshasa is filled these days with young men who have
volunteered to join the army, compelled by vague notions of duty
and the unshakable belief that Congo has been attacked by the hated
Tutsi and their Rwandan backers. Each morning, except on Sundays,
they can be seen milling around La Cite's sports stadiums, waiting
to join the military or to begin their drills.
</P>
<P>
   The young men _ many are just teen-agers _ are the foot soldiers
in the Congolese government's notoriously unprofessional and
disorganized army. Many in the first wave of volunteers who left
for the rebel-held areas southwest of here were killed by mistake
two weeks ago when they ran into another group of government
soldiers from the south.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of the deaths reached Kinshasa and Miaka's training was
put on hold for more than a week. But he was called back to duty on
Saturday and on Monday, at 7 a.m., he resumed his training after
walking the two miles from his uncle's house to the nearest sports
center, the Stadium of Martyrs.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first group got killed, some volunteers changed
their minds and tried to discourage me,'' he said, leaning forward
in his chair, rubbing his leg with his hand. ``But I'm determined
to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonton Miaka has no military experience, having spent half his
life growing onions and cabbage back in the village. With few
prospects there, he came to Kinshasa and, with some seed money from
his grandmother, started a small business selling cigarettes at the
local market.
</P>
<P>
   The young man lived at his uncle's, in a squat house with
cinder-block walls and a thin tin roof. The family moved into the
house in 1948, said Kava-Zumbu, 55, in a neighborhood called
Ngiri-Ngiri that was one of the last areas built by the former
Belgian colonizers.
</P>
<P>
   The family's fortunes fell under the ruinous, 32-year
dictatorship of Mobutu Sese Seko. While Kava-Zumbu benefited from
what was once considered one of the best educational systems on the
continent, his nephew did not study beyond age 12. The uncle, who
worked as an agronomist for the government and spent 12 years in
the eastern Congo, also fell on hard times. His salary eroded under
soaring inflation and eventually, like many government workers, he
was not paid at all.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, the uncle _ along with his wife, their six children,
his mother and the nephew _ makes ends meet by renting rooms in the
house to two families, taking in a total of $70 a month. His
mother, an indomitable woman in her 80s who can be found sitting or
lying in the sand-swept courtyard all day, supplements the family
income by peeling sunflower seeds. She mashes the seeds into oil
and sells them at a stand in front of the house, or sometimes at
the local market.
</P>
<P>
   It was at that market, where Tonton Miaka was selling an average
of six packs of Ambassade cigarettes a day, that he first heard
that the army was taking volunteers. ``I wanted to go right away,''
he said, but he decided to wait until he told his grandmother that
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't be the first soldier in our family,'' his
grandmother, Veronique M'landu, recalled telling him, explaining
that five of her grandsons had now joined the army. ``Go defend the
country. Don't loot. Behave yourself like a man.''
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, wearing jeans and running shoes, he went to
the Stadium of Martyrs and enrolled. For the next 10 days, Miaka
and hundreds like him went through drills inside the stadium and
sang songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You Rwandans, God has not chosen you,'' Miaka said, recalling
a song. ``If you want dialogue, we'll have dialogue. If you want
war, we'll have war.''
</P>
<P>
   His uncle, who went to university instead of the army, shook his
head. ``He gave up everything,'' he said with a laugh. ``He shaved
his head, a la Kabila. He spent all the money he'd earned. He gave
some of it away and feasted on the rest of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But like many educated Congolese here, Kava-Zumbu has
complicated feelings about the war. He is weary of it. But he is
steadfastly behind efforts by President Laurent Kabila to push back
the rebels, who are led by ethnic Tutsi from eastern Congo and who
are widely supposed to have the backing of Rwanda and Uganda, two
countries that helped propel Kabila to power less than two years
ago but then grew disenchanted with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call Kabila a buffoon and say that he doesn't have the
profile of a president,'' the uncle said bitterly. ``This is a
sovereign country, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   The family is united behind the young man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud,'' the grandmother said. ``I'm not worried.''
</P>
<P>
   But each morning, after her grandson had left the house for the
Stadium of the Martyrs, Kava-Zumbu said, he noticed something
unusual. ``Every morning,'' he said, ``she cried.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
