<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8158 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLOMBIA-HEROIN-U.S.-     08-28 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-HEROIN-U.S.-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOMBIAN DRUG DEALERS TAKING CONTROL OF HEROIN TRADE IN U.S. 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ Thirty years ago, major heroin shipments
entered the United States through the infamous ``French
Connection,'' which funneled narcotics made from Turkish opium in
French laboratories to crime families in New York.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Colombia is the connection for many of the estimated
2 million heroin users in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In the past four years, Colombian drug dealers have moved from
being marginal players in the heroin trade to controlling an
estimated 52 percent of the U.S. market, according to Donnie
Marshall, acting deputy administrator of the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The Colombians' sales plan? Sell high-quality merchandise at low
prices.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s and 1980s, the average purity level of heroin sold
on U.S. streets ranged from 2 percent to 7 percent, experts say.
But much of the Colombian heroin is 80 percent to 99 percent pure,
and it can be smoked or snorted rather than injected. That
increases the drug's appeal to first-time and casual users, who
want to avoid dirty needles and the threat of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are pushing high-grade heroin onto the streets at
extremely low prices in a bid to wrest market share from Middle
Eastern and Mexican traffickers,'' Marshall said in testimony
before the House International Relations Committee on June 24.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Marshall said, Colombians routinely sell heroin for
$90,000 a kilogram, compared to $150,000 to $200,000 per kilogram
for lower-grade Southeast Asian heroin. Many Colombian traffickers
require wholesale customers to accept heroin along with cocaine as
a condition of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   The sophisticated Colombian cartels that once controlled the
cocaine trade sent planeloads of the drug north.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, independent heroin traffickers based in the
Colombian cities of Bogota and Medellin and in the country's
west-central coffee-growing region move a few kilograms at a time,
experts say. They export their heroin by using express-mail
packages, false-sided luggage and airline passengers, who ingest
heroin-filled balloons and condoms.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these ``swallowers'' are shuttled through Venezuela or
Central America to disguise their country of origin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heroin traffickers are very savvy and very flexible,''
Marshall told the House Committee. ``They adapt quickly, varying
their routes and methodology to limit the success of law
enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the drug reaches the United States, he said, Colombians
often enlist Dominican gangs, who also deal in cocaine, to make
connections with midlevel wholesalers and retailers.
</P>
<P>
   That reduces the risk for the Colombians, a key concern
following the dismantling of the Medellin and Cali cocaine cartels
in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 1846EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8161 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMELESS-VENUS-COX     08-28 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-VENUS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Once homeless, teen heads to college
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- With her white T-shirt and baggy jeans, Venus
Rodriguez looks the part of any 18-year-old Clark Atlanta
University freshman.
</P>
<P>
   But beneath the pleasant smile is a hardened woman-child who
refuses to mince words about her life in a homeless shelter or with
a drug-addicted mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the age of 15, I had been through things that 30-year-olds
couldn't dream of,'' Rodriguez said. ``I was homeless, went to 11
different schools, was in foster care. I want people to be inspired
by my story.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's story enters a new chapter today, when her freshman
classes begin at Clark Atlanta, where she plans to major in mass
communications.
</P>
<P>
   Almost by accident, Rodriguez has gone from a homeless teen who
watched her father beat her mother to a voice for the young and
homeless. She was appointed by San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown to
the city's Youth Commission and the San Francisco Homeless Board.
She worked at the YMCA as a coordinator for a mentorship program
and worked in the district attorney's office as an outreach worker
for teen girls.
</P>
<P>
   Major newspapers and national magazines have told her story and
in March 1999, PBS will air a documentary on her life. All of that
caught the attention of the United Negro College Fund, which
awarded her the full scholarship that she will use at Clark
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's story actually begins in New York, where her mother,
Katrina Powell, hooked up with a man with whom she would spend nine
years.
</P>
<P>
   But, Powell said, the man beat her throughout their
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of the constant beatings, Powell packed up her daughter
and moved to San Francisco in 1987. But after only two years, she
returned to her boyfriend. The beatings started again.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, who said she became addicted to crack in 1987, left for
California for good in December 1992. With no job or prospects, no
place to live, Powell and Rodriguez, 12, spent Christmas and the
next five months in a homeless shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez initially was numbed by the thought of moving into a
shelter. She talked to few children her age, instead spending time
with adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always ask me, `How was it there?' I dealt with it. I
love to read, and I used my survival skills. Living in a shelter is
a matter of survival. I had to do this. I had to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, while still in the shelter, Rodriguez was in a group of
kids that visited President Clinton at the White House. The
13-year-old asked the president what he was going to do to end
homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a very outspoken young person,'' Rodriguez said. ``When
there is an injustice, you should speak out about it. As soon as I
rose out of homelessness, I wanted to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sent her a personal letter thanking her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came back disillusioned, because I still came back to a
shelter,'' Rodriguez said. ``I was still homeless. I got
recognition; I got a letter from Clinton; but so what? I don't rely
on political promises. I have been let down too many times
already.''
</P>
<P>
   In April 1993, Powell and Rodriguez landed in a transitional
home for low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   One day in early June, Powell left the home _ and didn't come
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had $5, so I was fine,'' said Rodriguez, who would get up
every morning and go to middle school, where she had a 3.5 grade
point average. ``When people asked me where was my mother, I said
she went to the store; she'd be right back. I convinced myself that
she would be right back.''
</P>
<P>
   But surveillance cameras reported no signs of Powell coming or
going from the home.
</P>
<P>
   On the third day, June 3, Rodriguez was pulled out of school by
her principal, a police officer and a social worker, who took her
home to pack her belongings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started crying, because I didn't know what was going on,''
Rodriguez said. ``I thought they were just doing this to scare my
mom, and that I would be with her. I didn't know that they were
sending me to a foster home.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell arrived as Rodriguez was on her way to a foster home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so drug-addicted, I abandoned her,'' Powell said. ``I
remember she had been crying so much that her eyes were like two
puff balls, but she was so courageous. ... She was the adult, and I
was immature.''
</P>
<P>
   Going to a foster home was upsetting, Rodriguez said. ``In the
beginning it was hard. I cried a lot, and I was worried about my
mother.''
</P>
<P>
   While in foster care, Rodriguez met Naomi Gray through the
Sojourner Truth Foster Family Service Agency, a nonprofit
organization she helped establish. Gray got Powell into a drug
treatment center and paved the way for Rodriguez to attend the
prestigious and mostly white French-American International School
on scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the first time I met Venus, I was struck by her attitude
and the way she handled herself,'' said Gray, now the president of
the San Francisco-based urban institute for African-American
affairs. ``She talked about how much she liked school, and I
thought, `Here was a child that needed to be nurtured.' She was
very outgoing and very mature.'' By Aug. 19, 1993, Powell said she
was sober, and after three years in foster care, Rodriguez and her
mother moved into a two-bedroom apartment that Gray secured for
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foster care was a blessing in disguise,'' Powell said. ``Venus
being taken from me was reason to turn it around. Losing her was
the ultimate bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   As she prepared for her first college classes, first college
boyfriend and first visit to the college cafeteria, Rodriguez
harbors no bitterness for the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, I was thinking about survival. About today. I knew
everything would be all right, because things happen for a reason,
and I am stronger for it,'' she said, adding that she even called
her father, whom she hasn't seen since 1992. ``I just decided to
talk to him before leaving for college. But I'm on another level.
He is 40, but still very young.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said she and her mother haven't spent as much time
with each other this summer as they would have liked. She said the
trip to Atlanta has brought them closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad we still are friends, because she has never had a
fair break,'' Powell said. ``Without Venus, I couldn't have gotten
sober. ... Her strength and courage made me strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
