<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8169 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-CRISIS-COX     08-28 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CRISIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX-RUSSIA-CRISIS
 &HT;    Moving both the (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-PLAYERS.
 &HT;    YELTSIN VOWS TO STAY ON, WILL SHARE POWER, AS CRISIS DEEPENS
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A defiant President Boris Yeltsin vowed that Russia's
deepening economic crisis will not force him from office, even as
he warned that tougher times are ahead for the anxious nation.
</P>
<P>
   But underscoring Yeltsin's growing insignificance to the
critical events unfolding in Russia, the real action was taking
place in negotiations between acting Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin and the Communists as the Kremlin offered to share
certain powers with the opposition-led parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from days of seclusion and silence about his country's
plight, Yeltsin went on national television Friday night to douse
furious rumors that his resignation was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   `I want to say that I'm not going anywhere. I'm not going to
resign. I will work as I'm supposed to for my constitutional
term,'' he said in a taped interview on national television.
</P>
<P>
   `In 2000 there will be an election for a new president and I
will not run.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Chernomyrdin was haggling with the
Communist-controlled Duma.
</P>
<P>
   They compromised on an agreement to enact Soviet-style controls
on the economy in an effort to stem the financial meltdown caused
by mounting public debts, a shaky banking system and the plummeting
ruble.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin also was willing to make several major power-sharing
concessions, including proposed amendments to the 1993
constitution, which granted the president sweeping powers to rule
in most areas without the consent or advice of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The compromises included giving parliament more influence over
government policy. They were designed to ease the way for
Chernomyrdin's confirmation by the Duma, the lower house of
parliament, which has scheduled to open its debate on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov said talks were
stalled and the
</P>
<P>
   Kremlin offers were ``nothing more than an illusion.'' He
suggested that a vote on Chernomyrdin's confirmation may not take
place until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave the country without a government for another
week, prolonging the political uncertainty as Russia's financial
system continues to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts fear that a deadlock in negotiations will
only further weaken the ruble and increase the changes of social
unrest.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is scheduled to hold a summit with Yeltsin in
Moscow on Tuesday and Wednesday, a meeting arranged before Russia's
crisis erupted this month.
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing the new prominence of the Communists, the U.S.
ambassador to Russia, James Collins, met Friday with Zyuganov in
what may be a precursor to a meeting between the Communists and
Clinton when he visits Moscow next week.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Yeltsin's videotaped remarks were aired, his chief
legislative adviser confirmed that Yeltsin _ a domineering
president known as ``Czar Boris''
</P>
<P>
   with sweeping powers under the 1993 constitution _ has offered
to grant Chernomyrdin the authority to name his own government and
to give parliament greater role in government appointments.
</P>
<P>
   To the dismay of Western economists, Chernomyrdin and the
Communist Party
</P>
<P>
   leaders in the parliament also agreed to Soviet-style controls
on the economy, erasing elements of free-market capitalism
introduced after the Soviet Union collapsed seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In another symbolic concession to the Communists, Yeltsin on
Friday fired prominent market reformers Anatoly Chubais and Boris
Nemtsov _ the latter
</P>
<P>
   had already resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms being negotiated in an effort to ease the
financial crisis,
</P>
<P>
   the new government and parliament would implement price and
currency controls,
</P>
<P>
   nationalize some banks and companies and print more money
augment the nation's dwindling treasury.
</P>
<P>
   `The overriding goal is to stop the fall of the ruble, not to
allow the destruction of the economy and reduce the damage
sustained by every Russian,'' Chernomyrdin said.
</P>
<P>
   But repressive economic measures are likely to receive a cool
reception from
</P>
<P>
   the United States and other lenders.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said government controls on the economy and more rubles
in circulation
</P>
<P>
   may ease the current crisis for weeks or months, but risk
spawning massive
</P>
<P>
   inflation and social unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will see empty shops and, down the line, starvation,''
predicted Al Breach of the of the Russian-European Center for
Economic Policy. ``This country is not self-sufficient. There is a
complete breakdown of economic order. The infrastructure is
completely rotten and the whole place is living on debt. And now it
is going cold turkey. The long winter will be the real test here.''
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund is scheduled to deliver a $4.3
billion installment of a $22.6 billion bailout package agree to
last month, however the aid is tied to assurances by the previous
Russian government under Sergei Kiriyenko that it would pursue
economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   After months of mounting debt and falling financial markets,
Russia devalued the ruble on Aug. 17 and Yeltsin sacked the
Kiriyenko government on Sunday, replacing him with Chernomyrdin,
who had been fired in an earlier government overhaul in March.
</P>
<P>
   The turmoil sent the ruble into a free-fall this week,
plummeting as low as
</P>
<P>
   12.5 to the U.S. dollar from a previous rate of 6.2 to the
dollar two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Russians have mobbed banks seeking to withdrawal their savings
and headed to store to stock up on goods fearing shortages will
follow. Russia's largest jewelry distributor said sales increased
250 percent in the past two weeks as Russian sought to invest their
rubles in gold and silver before the ruble weakened further.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be naive to say that we'll take some steps and people
won't suffer,'' Yeltsin said in his televised remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``However as president, I must say that we'll take every measure
to ensure that people don't lose their savings. I cannot promise
that prices won't go up, but as president I am obligated to do
everything to keep it to a minimum,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 1858EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8170 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-PLAYERS-COX     08-28 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PLAYERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA'S KEY PLAYERS AS THE COUNTRY ENDURES CHAOS
 &HT;    Moving both the (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-CRISIS-0829.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Here are the leading figures in Russia's government,
parliament and business as the country struggles with the current
economic and political crisis:
</P>
<P>
   BORIS YELTSIN, 67, president
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``I'm not going to resign. I will work as I'm supposed to
for my constitutional term. In 2000 there will be an election for a
new president and I will not run.''
</P>
<P>
   Background: Russia's first democratically elected president was
a political maverick in the old Communist Party. Yeltsin helped
hasten the end of the Soviet Union in 1991 and promised Russia the
rewards of democracy and free markets. Seven years later, the dream
has soured with economic and political chaos and an ailing Yeltsin
viewed as unable to cope with the crisis. While denying he will
resign, Yeltsin has agreed to cede powers to his prime minister and
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   VIKTOR CHERNOMYRDIN, 60, acting prime minister
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``We must forget (political) ambitions, we must stabilize
the situation and ease tensions that have reached a critical
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Background: A Soviet-era bureaucrat, Chernomyrdin went on to
serve as Yeltsin's prime minister from December 1992 until March
this year, when he was fired for failing to fix the economy. Now
he's back and struggling to form a government and satisfy the
interests of the Communist opposition, Russia's powerful tycoons
and Western lenders urging Russia not to revive a Soviet-style
economy.
</P>
<P>
   GENNADY ZYUGANOV, 54, leader of the Communist Party
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``We will only support a policy and a leadership that
will clearly and straightforwardly reject the so-called market
reforms and agree to take a different course.''
</P>
<P>
   Background: Leader of the opposition in the Duma, parliament's
lower house, Zyuganov was dismissed as politically impotent after
Yeltsin defeated him in the 1996 presidential race. But Zyuganov's
clout has risen considerably in the past week as he seeks a role
for his party in setting policy and filling key jobs in the new
government. Polls show he is the leading candidate to replace
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   YEGOR STROYEV, 61, chairman of the Federation Council
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``We should hurry to create a new government. Lack of any
authority at all is worse than the worst possible regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Background: The lackluster head of Russia's upper house of
parliament, Stroyev largely has served as a go-between for the
Kremlin and the Communist-dominated Duma. Opposition parties have
promoted him as an alternative candidate for prime minister. A
Soviet-era economist, he represents the interests of Russia's
provinces, whose governors sit on the federation council.
</P>
<P>
   YURI LUZHKOV, 62 mayor of Moscow and business tycoon
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``If the Central Bank lacks either the money or the
desire to halt the crisis, the financial system will slowly crawl
towards destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Background: The powerful mayor of Moscow -- who like
Chernomyrdin has aspirations to become president -- demonstrated
his status by his attendance in a meeting Friday with Yeltsin,
Chernomyrdin and Stroyev on the fate of Russia. A nationalist who
enjoys strong popularity in Moscow, Luzhkov has distanced himself
from the Kremlin during the current crisis. He could exploit the
current chaos to his political advantage should Chernomyrdin fail
to reverse the economic declines.
</P>
<P>
   ALEXANDER LEBED, 48, governor of the Krasnoyarsk region and a
presidential aspirant.
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``Over the years, the population has grown poorer and
output has fallen, but the president and government told fairy
tales to Russians instead of taking the necessary steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Background: A tough-as-nails former army general with a popular
following in Russia (he finished third in the 1996 presidential
balloting), Lebed was courted by Chernomyrdin earlier this week in
what many analyst believed was an attempt to have him join the new
government. He likely wants to remain on the outside, though and,
like Luzhkov, attempt to exploit a failure of the new government in
time for the presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   BORIS BEREZOVSKY, 52, industrial and media baron; Yeltsin
advisor
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``I am a product of privatization.''
</P>
<P>
   Background: A multibillionaire who helped finance Yeltsin's 1996
campaign and went on to become a Kremlin insider, Berezovsky has
emerged as the power behind the throne. Berezovsky is the most
prominent of the wealthy Russians known as the oligarchs, who made
their money buying and selling the assets of the dissolved Soviet
Union. He and others reportedly engineered Chernomyrdin's return to
protect the status quo, fearing economic reform amid the crisis
could dismantle their empires.
</P>
<P>
   ANATOLY CHUBAIS, 43, fired as Yeltsin's chief economic reformer
</P>
<P>
   Quote: ``Even given the present difficult financial situation,
there is no alternative to development of a market economy in
Russia or the country's integration into the world financial
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Background: Fired Friday as from his job as chief financial
liaison to the West, Chubais is an erudite reformer who since 1991
was the main architect of Russia's plan to privatize its Soviet-era
industries. He is the darling of Western economists, but is blamed
by many Russians for the country's economic misery and consistently
ranks as one of Russia's most unpopular figures. He continues as
head of Unified Energy Systems, the nation's electricity utility.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
