<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8173 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-CRISIS-COX     08-28 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CRISIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX-RUSSIA-CRISIS
 &HT;    Moving both the (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-PLAYERS.
 &HT;    YELTSIN VOWS TO STAY ON, WILL SHARE POWER, AS CRISIS DEEPENS
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A defiant President Boris Yeltsin vowed that Russia's
deepening economic crisis will not force him from office, even as
he warned that tougher times are ahead for the anxious nation.
</P>
<P>
   But underscoring Yeltsin's growing insignificance to the
critical events unfolding in Russia, the real action was taking
place in negotiations between acting Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin and the Communists as the Kremlin offered to share
certain powers with the opposition-led parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from days of seclusion and silence about his country's
plight, Yeltsin went on national television Friday night to douse
furious rumors that his resignation was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   `I want to say that I'm not going anywhere. I'm not going to
resign. I will work as I'm supposed to for my constitutional
term,'' he said in a taped interview on national television.
</P>
<P>
   `In 2000 there will be an election for a new president and I
will not run.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Chernomyrdin was haggling with the
Communist-controlled Duma.
</P>
<P>
   They compromised on an agreement to enact Soviet-style controls
on the economy in an effort to stem the financial meltdown caused
by mounting public debts, a shaky banking system and the plummeting
ruble.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin also was willing to make several major power-sharing
concessions, including proposed amendments to the 1993
constitution, which granted the president sweeping powers to rule
in most areas without the consent or advice of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The compromises included giving parliament more influence over
government policy. They were designed to ease the way for
Chernomyrdin's confirmation by the Duma, the lower house of
parliament, which has scheduled to open its debate on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov said talks were
stalled and the
</P>
<P>
   Kremlin offers were ``nothing more than an illusion.'' He
suggested that a vote on Chernomyrdin's confirmation may not take
place until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave the country without a government for another
week, prolonging the political uncertainty as Russia's financial
system continues to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts fear that a deadlock in negotiations will
only further weaken the ruble and increase the changes of social
unrest.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is scheduled to hold a summit with Yeltsin in
Moscow on Tuesday and Wednesday, a meeting arranged before Russia's
crisis erupted this month.
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing the new prominence of the Communists, the U.S.
ambassador to Russia, James Collins, met Friday with Zyuganov in
what may be a precursor to a meeting between the Communists and
Clinton when he visits Moscow next week.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Yeltsin's videotaped remarks were aired, his chief
legislative adviser confirmed that Yeltsin _ a domineering
president known as ``Czar Boris''
</P>
<P>
   with sweeping powers under the 1993 constitution _ has offered
to grant Chernomyrdin the authority to name his own government and
to give parliament greater role in government appointments.
</P>
<P>
   To the dismay of Western economists, Chernomyrdin and the
Communist Party
</P>
<P>
   leaders in the parliament also agreed to Soviet-style controls
on the economy, erasing elements of free-market capitalism
introduced after the Soviet Union collapsed seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In another symbolic concession to the Communists, Yeltsin on
Friday fired prominent market reformers Anatoly Chubais and Boris
Nemtsov _ the latter
</P>
<P>
   had already resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms being negotiated in an effort to ease the
financial crisis,
</P>
<P>
   the new government and parliament would implement price and
currency controls,
</P>
<P>
   nationalize some banks and companies and print more money
augment the nation's dwindling treasury.
</P>
<P>
   `The overriding goal is to stop the fall of the ruble, not to
allow the destruction of the economy and reduce the damage
sustained by every Russian,'' Chernomyrdin said.
</P>
<P>
   But repressive economic measures are likely to receive a cool
reception from
</P>
<P>
   the United States and other lenders.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said government controls on the economy and more rubles
in circulation
</P>
<P>
   may ease the current crisis for weeks or months, but risk
spawning massive
</P>
<P>
   inflation and social unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will see empty shops and, down the line, starvation,''
predicted Al Breach of the of the Russian-European Center for
Economic Policy. ``This country is not self-sufficient. There is a
complete breakdown of economic order. The infrastructure is
completely rotten and the whole place is living on debt. And now it
is going cold turkey. The long winter will be the real test here.''
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund is scheduled to deliver a $4.3
billion installment of a $22.6 billion bailout package agree to
last month, however the aid is tied to assurances by the previous
Russian government under Sergei Kiriyenko that it would pursue
economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   After months of mounting debt and falling financial markets,
Russia devalued the ruble on Aug. 17 and Yeltsin sacked the
Kiriyenko government on Sunday, replacing him with Chernomyrdin,
who had been fired in an earlier government overhaul in March.
</P>
<P>
   The turmoil sent the ruble into a free-fall this week,
plummeting as low as
</P>
<P>
   12.5 to the U.S. dollar from a previous rate of 6.2 to the
dollar two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Russians have mobbed banks seeking to withdrawal their savings
and headed to store to stock up on goods fearing shortages will
follow. Russia's largest jewelry distributor said sales increased
250 percent in the past two weeks as Russian sought to invest their
rubles in gold and silver before the ruble weakened further.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be naive to say that we'll take some steps and people
won't suffer,'' Yeltsin said in his televised remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``However as president, I must say that we'll take every measure
to ensure that people don't lose their savings. I cannot promise
that prices won't go up, but as president I am obligated to do
everything to keep it to a minimum,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
