<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Saturday, Aug. 29, and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Tina May at (206) 448-8355.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-COMMUNISM-CZARS (Moscow) As some Russian leaders look
back to the Communist days in search of ways to pull the reeling
nation out of its tailspin, other Russians are looking back even
further _ to the days of the czars. While coping with its economic
and political crises, Russia also is enduring the latest of many
painful shakeups in place names, national symbols and recognized
heroes, part of the country's tradition of regularly reinventing
its past. Despite the country's poverty and financial turmoil, its
leaders continue to build grandiose monuments and reconstruct
symbols of days gone by, such as the Cathedral of Jesus Christ the
Savior, re-built at a cost of at least $300 million 60 years after
Soviet dictator Joseph Stalin had it blown up.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (story will move in the ``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON-BOEING (Undated) The Rev. Jesse Jackson says he'll meet
with Boeing's Phil Condit next week on race discrimination within
the aerospace giant. He says he's also thinking of setting up an
office here to monitor Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   By Bruce Ramsey. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-EXPLOSION (Undated) The head of the Boeing team
investigating the Delta III explosion holds media teleconference
this morning to talk about the accident for the first time, and to
lay out the scope of the investigation. Boeing delays the Sept. 1
launch of its Delta II.
</P>
