<HEADER>
A8179 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-SEMINOLES-QB-TEX     08-28 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEMINOLES-QB-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA STATE QB QUALIFIES AS OLD FOLKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By college football standards, Florida State quarterback Chris
Weinke qualifies as the sport's poster boy for the American
Association of Retired Persons.
</P>
<P>
   Make that ``former'' retired persons, in this case.
</P>
<P>
   Weinke, 26, spent seven seasons playing minor-league baseball in
the Toronto Blue Jays organization before deciding to take his
athletic career in another direction. That landed him at Florida
State, where a knee injury to projected starter Dan Kendra has
thrust Weinke into the starting lineup for Monday's matchup against
Texas A&AMP;M in the Kickoff Classic in East Rutherford, N.J. (7 p.m.,
WFAA/Channel 8).
</P>
<P>
   Weinke's last start at quarterback came nine years ago, when the
St. Paul, Minn., native led Cretin-Derham High School into the 1989
state playoffs. That same season, a rookie quarterback named Troy
Aikman made his debut with the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice to say, Florida State coach Bobby Bowden never expected
to hear from Weinke again after his prized signee informed him that
he would skip school and accept a $375,000 signing bonus from the
Blue Jays, who selected him in the second round of the 1990
major-league baseball draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had players in the same situation where I thought, `I'll
see this guy in a couple of years,' '' said Bowden, who vowed in
1990 to save a scholarship for Weinke if he ever changed his mind.
``But I thought Chris would make it. I never expected to have him
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinke decided to resurrect his football career in 1996 after
batting .186 in 51 games as a first baseman for the Blue Jays' AAA
affiliate in Syracuse, N.Y. Club officials wanted him to move to
catcher. Instead, Weinke moved to Tallahassee, Fla., and relishes
his chance to lead No. 2 Florida State against No. 14 Texas A&AMP;M in
the first national telecast of the college football season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't be happier with my decision. But it's hard to say
exactly what I'll be feeling on Monday night,'' said Weinke, a
sophomore who is older than 10 starting quarterbacks in the NFL.
``It'll be the first time I've started in nine years, so I know
I'll be excited ... and nervous. Anyone who says they're not
nervous in a game of this magnitude would be lying. I don't know
how I'll react.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither does Bowden, who watched Weinke (6-foot-5, 235 pounds)
complete seven of 13 passes for 82 yards in reserve duty last
season. Weinke ascended into the starter's role when Kendra
underwent reconstructive surgery after tearing the anterior
cruciate ligament in his right knee during the Seminoles' spring
game.
</P>
<P>
   During two-a-day practices, Bowden turned up the heat, freeing
first-team defenders to blitz at will in scrimmage situations.
Weinke withstood the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about him being under fire. He's been under
fire,'' Bowden said. ``He hasn't shown us anything where you'd
think he's not ready to play. I think he'll respond as good as you
could hope for a sophomore.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said his fondest wish is for Weinke to get ``a quick
taste of success'' against the Aggies to boost the confidence level
of a passer who has seen little game action since throwing for
3,956 yards and 24 touchdowns during 21 games as a high school
starter in 1988-89.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M coaches, who have little videotape of Weinke to study, are
unsure what to expect. On one hand, Weinke is untested at the
college level. He is coming off a long layoff from football and a
failed baseball career.
</P>
<P>
   But he is also mature, articulate and a millionaire, having
turned his signing bonus into a net worth in excess of $1 million
through investments over the past eight years. Because of his
maturity, Bowden said teammates have readily accepted Weinke as a
team leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put him under pressure, a 26-year-old man is going to
react differently than your normal 18- or 19-year-old
quarterback,'' A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum said. ``But he's still new.
And any time you're doing something for the first time, there's
some apprehension involved. I really have no idea what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Johnson, the Aggies' defensive line coach, predicted Weinke
would not play his best game of the season against A&AMP;M because it
would ``take a little while ... to get the speed of the game
back.'' Toward that end, A&AMP;M likely will throw lots of blitzes and
stunts at Weinke early in the game to gauge his preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   Bring it on, Weinke said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to limit the offense because I'm at
quarterback, by any means,'' Weinke said. ``Obviously, it's the
first game. And there's always a few surprises in the first game. I
just feel comfortable with what I've studied and what I'm doing. I
consider this an opportunity for me to shine and that's something
I've been waiting for a long time.''
CHART Older than pros
</P>
<P>
   Florida State quarterback Chris Weinke, a 26-year-old sophomore
who spent seven seasons playing minor-league baseball before
enrolling in college, is older than 10 projected NFL starting
quarterbacks. The list: Quarterback Team AGE Tony Banks Rams 25
Kerry Collins Panthers 25 Bobby Hoying Eagles 25 Rob Johnson Bills
25 Steve McNair Oilers 25 Jake Plummer Cardinals 25 Kordell Stewart
Steelers 25 Danny Kanell Giants 24 Ryan Leaf Chargers 22 Peyton
Manning Colts 22
</P>
</TEXT>
