<HEADLINE>
CORNHUSKERS GO WITH VIRTUAL ROOKIE AT QB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Inexperience at Nebraska typically involves an offensive lineman
who becomes a starter after three or four years of seasoning,
hundreds of practices and thousands of repetitions.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely do the Cornhuskers enter a season with a rookie at
quarterback, the hard drive of the team's option offense. But when
Nebraska begins defense of its co-national championship today
against Louisiana Tech, Bobby Newcombe will bring a sketchy resume
as he takes over as the team's quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I'm going to be a little nervous,'' said Newcombe, a
6-foot, 195-pound sophomore. ``As an offense, every first game is a
challenge. We're basically going to play this like it's a bowl
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The on-field focus will be on Newcombe. The sideline focus will
be on Frank Solich, who makes his head coaching debut. For the
first time in 25 seasons, someone other than Tom Osborne will be
the Huskers' coach.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska agreed to play in the Eddie Robinson Classic against
the Bulldogs (9-2 last season) because it wanted another game of
experience for its offense. Only three starters return from last
season's 13-0 team. The last time the Huskers were this green was
1996 and they lost their second game, at Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Newcombe was the No. 3 quarterback behind starter
Scott Frost and backup Frankie London. Nebraska coaches decided
Newcombe's abilities were wasting away as a spectator. After two
games, he was switched to wingback. He appeared in 12 games last
season, compiling 589 all-purpose yards.
</P>
<P>
   Newcombe, who completed his only pass attempt last season for a
15-yard gain, won the job in spring practice, beating out London,
who has been switched to wingback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an inexperienced quarterback, but he's a very mature
individual,'' Solich said. ``He has great athletic ability. He has
an excellent grasp of our offensive system. We think he can be
outstanding in our system. And he's done everything he can to
prepare himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Every day this summer, he stopped by the football office to
study film during breaks in his summer school classes. He's ahead
of schedule to obtain his degree in business management.
</P>
<P>
   Solich says that Newcombe is a threat every time he touches the
ball; considering the plan calls for him to take each snap, that
should make the Huskers offense dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   But Solich's hyperbole might be closer to the truth. In the Big
12 championship game against Texas A&AMP;M last December, Newcombe
caught a pass for 26 yards, gained 25 yards on a reverse and
returned a punt 40 yards. In Nebraska's spring game, he scored a
91-yard touchdown _ on the first play from scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Newcombe, was born in Sierra Leone, Africa, and grew up in
Albuquerque, N.M., from the fourth grade on. In high school, he won
five gold medals in track and was a star basketball performer. His
4.46 speed in the 40-yard dash makes him the fastest Husker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a much better thrower than people think he would be, but
we recruited him as a quarterback and he's a talented passer,''
Solich said. ``He's an excellent technician at running the option.
With his speed, he can turn any play into a big play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see him as a player able to handle the situation he's in. He
knows he needs to play well early.''
Nebraska at a glance 1997 record: 13-0, 8-0 in Big 12, won North
Division, Big 12 championship and co-national championship. Coach:
Frank Solich (first season). Stadium: Memorial (72,700). Returning
starters (offense): 3. Returning starters (defense): 7. All-star
candidates: K Kris Brown, DE Chad Kelsay, LB Jay Foreman. Key
newcomers: QB Bobby Newcombe, RT Jason Schwab, TB Correll
Buckhalter, TB Dan Alexander.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
