<SLUG> BC-OLY-HOTTER-'N-HELL-CYCLING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOTTER 'N HELL FILLS TILLS BETTER THAN COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STACY FEDUCIA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Cycling is better than football.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, someone had the guts to say it, and Midwestern State
University has the evidence to back it up.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the university recently completed a study on the
economic impact of having the Cowboys' training camp in Wichita
Falls, a city of about 100,000 in North Texas. Over the course of 4
1/2 weeks of football, fans contributed approximately $4.2 million
to the Wichita Falls economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotter 'N Hell Hundred, which rides today, will contribute
approximately $3.8 million to the local economy over the span of
``three days'', according to the Wichita Falls Convention and
Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Three days, $3.8 million. Four weeks, $4.2 million. Cycling
wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economic impact is a combination of retail sales _ staying in
hotels, going to restaurants, buying gasoline,'' explained George
Casper of the Convention and Visitors Bureau. ``When the Cowboys
were here, we had good occupancy and it was nice, but for this
race, every room is booked, all the restaurants are full. It's a
swarm of people.''
</P>
<P>
   The swarm commences with a mass start at 7:30 this morning on
Scott Street, with more than 8,600 expected to participate. The
United States Cycling Federation race begins at 7 a.m., with
nationally prominent teams such as defending champion Shaklee, EDS,
PowerBar and Mercury competing.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Hotter 'N Hell didn't quite live up to its name,
with overcast skies giving way to temperatures in the 80s and low
90s. Not so, this year, where temperatures in the mid-to-high 90s
are predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heat shouldn't slow the race down,'' said Bret Crosby of
the Wheels and Fitness in Motion/Cannondale team. ``It will take a
lot of riders out because of dehydration or cramping. In the past,
it's always been fast because it's flat.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also the largest sanctioned century ride and race in the
country _ which gives rise to the economic impact of the visitors
bureau _ and which is a draw for people from as many as 15 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people can participate in cycling rather than football,
which is a lot like voyeurism: You watch but you can't play,''
joked Jim Connally of Mid-Cities Wheelmen. ``All levels of people
can compete in this race.''
</P>
<P>
   And for all the unconvinced football fans _ the nonbelievers _
consider this: In cycling, there's no instant replay, no
commercials and no chance that they'll be riding with scissors.
Hotter 'N Hell Hundred What: Largest ride in the region with routes
of 10K, 25 miles, 50 miles, 100K or 100 miles.
</P>
<P>
   When: Today, 7:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Scott Street, adjacent to Multi-Purpose Events Center, in
Wichita Falls.
</P>
<P>
   Registration: Today, starting at 5:30 a.m. at Multi-Purpose
Events Center Cost is $25.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champions: Eric Wohlberg, Team Shaklee in men's stage
race; Jennifer Evans, EDS in women's stage race. Wohlberg won the
100-mile road race last year, while EDS Linda Kruse won the women's
62.5-mile road race. The stage race consists of last night's
criterium, today's road race and tomorrow's time trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
