<HEADLINE>
INSURORS AGREE TO CUT NONGROUP HEALTH INSURANCE PREMIUMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Some consumers buying their own health insurance will
face significantly lower premiums compared to last year's rates,
thanks to some concerted arm twisting by state authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Half-a-dozen insurance companies this month agreed to lower
their nongroup insurance premiums by as much as 50 percent after
they were approached by officials from the Division of Insurance
State Rating Bureau and the Massachusetts Attorney General's
office. The rates were released Friday by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen D'Amato, director of the rating bureau, said the state
wanted to make sure rates were more affordable. State law requires
carriers to sell health insurance to anyone wanting to buy it, but
companies can skirt the law by charging such high rates that no
consumer will buy their insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some carriers would have been priced (themselves) out of the
market had we not stepped in,'' D'Amato said.
</P>
<P>
   Tufts Health Plan, for example, lowered its premium 40 percent
for a 25-year-old single person living in Boston. United HealthCare
of New England Inc. cut its rate for the same person by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Tufts said the original, higher rates
represented the company's best estimate of what it would cost for
Tufts to break even on the plan. ``This product is definitely not
an income-generator for us,'' said Michelle Davis of Tufts. ``But
we do have a commitment to being in the market, so we're willing to
take that risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups were pleased with the results, but are still
worried that indemnity plans are unaffordable for many. ``We're
happy that the state has looked more carefully at the rates to make
sure that there is less disparity among the plans,'' said Rebecca
Derby of Health Care For All, a consumer group in Boston. ``We are
still concerned, however, with the high rates charged for indemnity
plans, especially in areas where less expensive HMOs are not as
available.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers wanting to buy their own health insurance can sign up
during open enrollment period, which begins Sept. 1 and ends Nov.
30. For consumers who already purchase nongroup insurance, carriers
are in the process of notifying their members of the new rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
