<SLUG> BC-MARKET-SELLOFF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW CLOSES DOWN ANOTHER 114 POINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average attempted to stage a comeback
from Thursday's 357-point decline, but instead fell more than 100
points Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a day notable for big swings in the index, and heavy trading
volume, the Dow Jones average of 30 blue-chip stocks closed at
8051.68, down 114.3 points, or 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The market's decline was led by the technology sector as
evidenced by the computer-dominated Nadsaq Composite Index, which
slumped 46.7 points, or 2.8 percent. Stocks such as Microsoft
Corp., which had withstood the market's slide better than most,
were hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
   But while a small decline Friday after Thursday's rout rattled
investors, it still did not shake their confidence in the US stock
market. Despite a market correction from its July highs, the Dow
Jones has gained 1.8 percent this year and the economy is still
growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we'd seen another down 300-point day today I'd probably be
heading for the hills,'' said Tim Ghriskey, senior portfolio
manager for Dreyfus Corp. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're in the middle of what I call the beginning
of a major bear market. I see this as a correction'' that may end
soon, Ghriskey.
</P>
<P>
   But world markets Friday were down in a continuation of their
reaction to the collapse of Russia's currency markets and banking
system. Japan's Nikkei was first to react to Thursday's turmoil.
The 225-stock Nikkei hit its lowest level since March 1986,
plunging by 3.46 percent to close at 13,915.63 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's retreat cut short a recovery on European markets in
midafternoon. The damage from the Dow was contained, however, and
European indexes saw continued but limited losses.
</P>
<P>
   Spain's IBEX index of 35 stocks, which has suffered from ties to
Latin America, fell another 2.3 percent. London's FT-SE 100-share
index finished with a loss of 2.2 percent. In Frankfurt, Germany's
DAX index fell by 1.7 percent, though officials said it might take
several hours to compute a final value after a hectic session. In
Paris, the CAC 40 index lost 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Global turmoil has forced a powerful lesson on investors who had
become bold in recent years about taking risks. ``There's been a
tendency (by investors) to focus on individual companies, on
Russia, on countries in Latin America,'' said Brian
Gendreau, &UR;  &LR; international economist for Salomon Smith Barney in New
York. ``But now it's pretty clear it's a global phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   The path of the Dow Jones index Friday was not straight down:
The index rose 78.53 points in early-morning trading and flirted
with 8,250 before tumbling to just above the benchmark 8,000 level
before noon _ the last time it crossed the 8,000 mark, on Feb. 2,
the market was on the way up.
</P>
<P>
   The afternoon brought a series of gains and losses that kept
market watchers close to their computer terminals.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow this week has lost a total of more than 600 points after
three straight days of losses, and the volatility is expected to
continue. Friday was the fourth busiest day ever on the New York
Stock Exchange; almost 840 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   A number of investment experts said that the US market's
correction may be nearing an end, though there are no guarantees
that it is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't a lot of silver linings,'' Scott Pape, a
portfolio manager for Loomis Sayles LP in Chicago, said Friday
after the market's close.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Microsoft lost 4 a share and closed at 105 1/4,
while Cisco Systems Inc., a maker of telecommunications equipment,
lost 4 1/2 and closed 94 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   William Landes, chief investment officer for Putnam Investments,
a $265 billion investment company in Boston, said there is still
much to be optimistic about over the long-term.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is fine. Profits are reasonable ... and interest
rates are down to 5.35 percent,'' Landes said. ``There's nothing
that would lead you to believe this is a bear market.''
</P>
<P>
   The US banking sector was slammed again Friday as concerns
mounted about Russia-related losses and business ties to Asia.
BankAmerica Corp. fell 4 1/4 to 69 1/2 after revealing that it lost
$220 million from trading this quarter, mostly in Russia.
BankBoston, which fell 3 to 36, said it lost $30 million on
trading, one third of it from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co., down 7 to 97 3/4, has lost a quarter of its
value since July 14.
</P>
<P>
   The bond market continued its rally as investors fled to
lower-risk markets. Yields on three-month Treasury bill yields fell
9 basis points to a 4.87 percent, the lowest since June 2, 1997.
The yield on 30-year Treasury bonds was little changed at 5.34
percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
