<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR PATRIOTS RUNNING GAME TO BREAK OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ If ever there was a time, a place, and an
opponent to instill a bit of confidence into the Patriots' running
game, Saturday night's final exhibition game against the
Philadelphia Eagles would be ideal.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots (2-2) have averaged 2.8 yards per carry against the
San Francisco 49ers, Minnesota Vikings, Dallas Cowboys, and
Washington Redskins, teams ranked second, 23rd, 24th, and 28th
against the rush last year in the NFL. The Eagles were 25th against
the run last season but in three exhibition games they have allowed
close to 150 yards on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   This week also marks the return of No. 1 pick Robert Edwards.
Edwards has gained 20 yards in six carries, all against the 49ers,
but has missed the last three games with a groin injury. He's
expected be used in relief of starter Sedrick Shaw. The Patriots
want Edwards to carry the ball at least a dozen times, but it might
be more if Edwards doesn't feel any pain from the groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is for one of the backs to break a long gainer, because
that's the only thing separating the Patriots from a decent running
attack. Derrick Cullors and Harold Shaw haven't posted a run of
longer than 16 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just a matter of time before it happens,'' said
Drew Bledsoe. ``t's a matter of one of the backs breaking one
tackle sometimes after they hit the hole. Sometimes it's a matter
of luck and our backs haven't had any so far.''
</P>
<P>
   The running game hasn't been that bleak. On third down and less
than three yards, which is the ``tough yardage'' category, the
Patriots have converted first downs on seven of their nine
attempts. They've also converted two out of three attempts on
fourth down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're making progress,'' said left guard Max Lane. ``I
know some people just look at the average, but we're getting the
tough yardage when we need to get it. If it's third and one, we're
getting the yard. If it's fourth and one, we're getting the yard. I
think that's really developing well. We do need to spring some long
ones, but I think that will come.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have had the toughest time running on first down,
averaging 2.7 yards per carry. They've been much better on second
down at 3.4 yards, and on third down, they've averaged 1.8 yards,
which is what brings down their overall average even though their
conversion rate is high.
</P>
<P>
   They've had 11 running plays which have netted negative yardage,
but one of them was an 8-yard loss by Troy Brown on a reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Sedrick Shaw leads the Patriots with 156 yards on 52 carries (a
3.0 average), while Harold Shaw has gained 131 yards on 51 carries
(2.6). The only back with an average above the desired 4.0 is
Derrick Cullors, who has 15 carries for 53 yards (4.1 yards).
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert needs to get the ball and run some,'' said coach Pete
Carroll. ``I'd like to keep him alive throughout a good portion of
the game and not overdo him too much at any one time. We want to
gauge that accordingly. I'd like to see him get the ball 10 times
or so and get a good dosage of our running plays and mix him into
the pass protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, considered a very smart player who picked up the
offense in no time during the mini-camps, fears only that his
conditioning might have lagged because of the weeks spent on the
bike.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do all the bike work you want, but it's different than
being out on the field and playing in a game. The speed is much,
much greater and the conditioning could be a factor if I'm running
a few plays at a time. I might have to come out for a breather or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   While Edwards certainly wants to be somewhat cautious for fear
of reinjuring himself and spending more time on the sidelines, he
also wants to make an impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I'd like to go out there and break a long run because it
seems that's what we're looking for right now,'' said Edwards. ``I
have to be smat about it. I can't risk getting hurt again and then
being out for a longer amount of time, but I want to contribute to
the team and help us win.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards's first training camp is certainly shaping up much like
Terry Glenn's two years ago, when the Patriots had trouble getting
Glenn on the field early. Glenn missed the first two games of the
'96 season as a result of a hamstring pull but came on like
gangbusters to catch 90 passes, setting a rookie record.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, who had never pulled a groin before, is being treated
cautiously by the trainign staff. But now Carroll and his staff
want to see more of what Edwards can do, though the consensus is
that Edwards could provide that breakaway threat that hasn't shown
up in the preseason thus far.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a huge game for Sedrick Shaw, who has gained some
tough yardage and has been able to get the ball into the end zone
inside the 5-yard line. With Edwards returning, the competition is
on again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played as hard as I could every time out there,'' said
Shaw. ``I'm trying to improve every time out in everything the
coaches want me to get better at. I really have no control over
what they're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Shaw has shown he hits the hole hard but not much beyond
that. His next step is to show a little more speed and burst once
he gets through the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Other points of interest in the exhibtion finale:
</P>
<P>
   _Bledsoe's goal is to hit the long ball to either Terry Glenn or
Shawn Jefferson. He's missed both wide open during the first four
games.
</P>
<P>
   _While most of the jobs are settled in Carroll and Bobby Grier's
mind, there's still some sorting out to do on the defensive line,
where Mike Jones, Leonta Rheams, Devin Wyman, and Brandon Mitchell
appear to be competing for two spots.
</P>
<P>
   _With Chris Slade sitting out another game, Vernon Crawford and
Bernard Russ will get a significant amount of playing time to sort
out their futures. Crawford has appeared to make it, but Russ may
be fighting for his roster spot.
</P>
<P>
   _The cornerback spot also needs sorting. Veteran Steve Israel is
reportedly running again and may be on his way to recovery from his
knee surgery in the off-season. Along with Tebucky Jones, the
Patriots also have Steve Lofton and Kato Serwanga, and they may be
fighting for one spot.
</P>
<P>
   _The Patriots like to hold onto their draft picks. Of the 19
they've taken the past two years, only Tony Gaiter has been cut
(twice). Gaiter was re-signed to the practice squad last year. They
have tough decisions to make not only on Rheams, a fourth-rounder,
but center Jason Andersen, a seventh-rounder from Brigham Young.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
