<HEADLINE>
STROBLE SWINGS TO EARLY SENIOR CLASSIC LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL HARBER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Mass. _ Bobby Stroble, the man of a thousand swings,
needed only 64 of them Friday to take the first-round lead of the
$1 million BankBoston Senior Classic at Nashawtuc CC.
</P>
<P>
   Stroble fashioned his 8-under-par total by hitting only 12
greens and escaping bogey six times.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Connor, one of only two men to play in both the golf and
tennis US Opens, is one stroke behind. George Archer is two behind
Stroble, while the gang of Joe Inman, Ed Dougherty, Gibby Gilbert,
Al Geiberger, Dale Douglass, and Walter Hall are at 5-under.
</P>
<P>
   Stroble, 55, says he isn't fazed by the money or the legends of
the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up hard in hard times, and nothing bothers me after
that,'' said Stroble, who honed his skills playing against the
likes of the legendary Teddy Rhodes on the United Golf Association,
a tour in which the money wagered between the golfers was usually
bigger than the tournament purse. ``You had to know what you were
doing on that tour,'' said Stroble. ``There were a lot of games
being played.''
</P>
<P>
   The UGA was the all-black tour that flourished when the PGA's
by-laws contained a Caucasians-only clause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I think there is prejudice today,'' said Strobel.
``Yeah, I think everybody is a little prejudiced but that's OK as
long as we give each other a little space.''
</P>
<P>
   Stroble has found success in Massachusetts. He shot a
final-round 65 to finish in the top five of this tournament two
years ago. As an itinerant pro preparing for the Senior Tour 10
years ago, he won the Boston Open at Franklin Park, fashioning a
course-record 64. And in the halcyon UGA days, he shot a
course-record 66 at Braintree Municipal some 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a whole bunch of course records,'' said Stroble, whose
proudest accomplishment is a 25 over nine holes in a UGA tournament
at Knoxville, Tenn. ``I don't think anybody will do that.''
</P>
<P>
   He had a round of 58 that day.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's 64 ties the course record first set by Bruce Crampton
in 1986 and tied by Dale Douglas (1988 and '89), Chi Chi Rodriguez
(1990 and '93), Kermit Zarley (1993), and Tommy Aaron (1995).
</P>
<P>
   Stroble hit only 11 fairways and 12 greens Friday and took just
22 putts. ``These are great greens,'' said Stroble. ``But they
seems a lot slower today that they were earlier in the week. But
that didn't matter. I made a ton of putts today.''
</P>
<P>
   Stroble went with a new, shorter putter this week but isn't sure
of its make.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. It's Rick Massengale's. Made by the English
guy,'' offered Stroble, who made four birdies on the front and four
more on the back nine. He started out by sinking a 5-footer on the
opening hole, then knocked in a 20-footer on No. 3. After dropping
a 6-footer on No. 6, he drilled a 12-footer on the seventh hole.
</P>
<P>
   On the back nine, Stroble tapped in a 3-footer on No. 11, canned
an 8-footer on No. 12 and a 10-footer on No. 14. The putt that put
him in sole possession of first place was a 25-footer on the
finishing hole.
</P>
<P>
   Connor, who along with Ellsworth Vines are the only men to
compete in the US Open in both tennis and golf, had a 31 on the
front nine on the way to his 65. Connor also is celebrating his
30th wedding anniversary this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   What did he get for his wife, who is home teaching third grade
in San Antonio, Texas? ``Nothing. When you make as much money as we
do, they go out and buy their own presents,'' said Connor, who has
won $320,653 in 25 events this year. He figures he needs to win
another $140,000 to finish in the top 31 and earn a berth in the
Tour Championship.
</P>
<P>
   George Archer is thinking more about retiring than winning
tournaments. Since having his hip replaced in 1996 _ his seventh
major surgery since turning professional _ the 59-year-old has been
in pain. However, he won the First of America Classic Aug. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fun for me to be out here by myself,'' said Archer.
``I've been giving a lot of thought to retirement. Then I won the
tournament at Grand Rapids. I think I'll play until June of next
year and then take July and August off and go fishing. I'll be 60
soon after that (Oct. 1, 1999), and then I might just play the
Super Seniors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
