<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHARACTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS SOURED ON CLINTON'S PERSONAL VIRTUES, POLLS SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has fallen into a character
chasm, the first modern president to be rated far higher by the
public for his performance in office than for personal virtues like
honesty and integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters are intrigued by surveys taken since the president's
confessions last week that he had an extramarital affair with
former White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky and misled the public.
They never have seen such a disparity in public attitudes between
presidential duty and character, they say, nor as dramatic a
reversal in how Americans typically view their presidents _ as weak
leaders but likable men.
</P>
<P>
   The polls also suggest the public may be much more unsettled
about Clinton and his capacity to lead than his soaring
job-approval rating indicates.
</P>
<P>
   With trust in the president at an all-time low, a report from
independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr that would focus on perjury or
expose the seamy details of a sexual relationship could anger
Americans and still turn them against the president, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see here is not so much about sex _ people say they
have had enough embarrassing and uncomfortable discussions about
that _ but a growing concern about whether the president was
truthful in his admissions and sincere in his apology,'' said John
Zogby, an independent pollster.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the president took a step in that direction, telling a
church audience on Martha's Vineyard that he was ``having to become
quite an expert at this business of asking for forgiveness, and it
gets a little easier the more you do it.'' In what appeared to be a
reference to Starr, Clinton said he realized he had to forgive
those who wronged him in order to be forgiven himself.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials have suggested that the president's high
job-performance rating _ between 60 and 70 percent in most recent
polls _ shows the public is unfazed by the Lewinsky scandal and
wants the president to get beyond the sordid story and back to the
nation's work.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby's most recent poll, taken for several New York newspapers
after Clinton's speech to the nation last week, put the president's
job-approval rating at 57 percent. That was slightly lower than the
62 percent reported in a USA Today/CNN poll conducted over the
weekend. Clinton's approval rating in the Washington Post/ABC News
poll late last week was 66 percent, as high as it has ever been.
</P>
<P>
   But the character questions told a different story. In the USA
Today poll, fewer than one-third of those surveyed said the words
``honest and trustworthy'' applied to Clinton. The results of the
Washington Post survey were worse for the president: Only 19
percent of respondents said he ``had personal, moral, and ethical
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans aren't ignoring the president's personal behavior, and
they are quite judgmental about it. According to a poll released
Thursday by the Pew Research Center for the People and the Press,
62 percent of those surveyed say they don't like Clinton
personally, 70 percent say his relationship with Lewinsky was
``very wrong,'' and the one word people volunteered most to
describe the president was ``liar.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Senator Nancy Kassebaum Baker, a Kansas Republican,
called on the Clinton this week to resign and questioned whether he
had the character to acknowledge he had acted irresponsibly and
``tarnished'' the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``For President Clinton, there is no sense of personal
responsibility for the action he's taken,'' Kassebaum Baker said on
Tuesday in an interview with the Wichita Eagle. ``That's why I'd
like him to stand up and say, `It does matter, it does count, I
recognize that, and I have let the public down.' But that doesn't
happen very much these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there isn't much public sentiment for the president's
resignation. In the Pew poll, 75 of respondents said Clinton should
stay in office. In the Zogby poll, 62.6 percent said the president
should consider resigning if he lied in his testimony to the Starr
grand jury on Aug. 17. The USA Today poll found 67 percent of the
public against impeaching the president over the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people's ability to separate Clinton, the man, from
Clinton, the chief executive, is very clear,'' said Andrew Kohut,
director of the Pew Research Center. ``They have a very poor
impression of him as a person, but they like his basic job of
running the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans generally give the president credit for a strong
economy and a successful foreign policy, and they want the country
to stay on course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The White House has clung to these job-performance ratings
like a life raft,'' said Alan Secrest, a pollster for Democratic
candidates. ``The mounting tension for Americans is whether they
want to view the president as an effective city councilman or
glorified ombudsman, or as a father figure in terms of imparting
morals and values.''
</P>
<P>
   For Democrat politicians, the most immediate concern is the
midterm congressional elections. There are growing fears that
Democrats disenchanted with Clinton won't turn out for party
candidates on Nov. 3, that the election agenda won't center on
Democratic issues such as health care and Social Security, and that
a ruckus over the Starr report in Washington could delay lawmakers
up for reelection from getting home to their districts.
</P>
<P>
   But the larger question is whether Clinton commands the respect,
has the time, or wields the moral authority to lead effectively.
House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt's criticism this week of the
president's conduct and credibility gave other Democrats the green
light to distance themselves from a vulnerable president.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Pew poll, 55 percent of the public believes the
scandal is interfering with the president's ability to govern, and
43 percent think Clinton does not command sufficient respect from
other leaders to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of Clinton's great weaknesses as a public official is that
he has always wanted to please people too much,'' said former
Senator Paul Simon, an Illinois Democrat who now directs the Public
Policy Center at Southern Illinois University. Simon predicted it
will be even harder for Clinton to pitch anything but ``political
softballs'' in the rest of his term. ``Character matters in
leadership. We are going to see a diminished presidency,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
