<P>
   DIANA-MEMORIAL _ PARIS _ Parisians and tourists have been
invited to join a candle-lit procession to the Pont de lAlma to
commemorate the first anniversary of the death of Diana, Princess
of Wales. A ceremony will be held at 12:26 a.m. (local time) today,
to mark the moment when Dianas limousine hit the 13th pillar of an
underpass on a right bank expressway. Her companion, Dodi Fayed,
and the driver, Henri Paul, also died. The ceremony is being
organized by a private association, Paris Odysee, after the royal
family informed the British embassy and Paris city council that
expressions of grief should be limited to personal reflection.
(Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move SPOT Monday, Aug. 31, in the (i) International
category.
</P>
<P>
   OPED-EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN-RETROSPECTIVE _ Cox senior writer Joe Murray has
traveled to Russia regularly since the beginning of the 1990s. He
made his seventh visit this year. ``Lucky seven,'' Murray writes.
``With any luck, I'm never coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Columns from his trip have been moving on the Cox wire; now, for
Cox papers only, a full-page layout is available utilizing those
columns, courtesy of The Lufkin Daily News and titled ``Russian
Retrospective.'' It focuses on the changes that have taken place in
Russian life with capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   It's available on the Cox server/International
folder/LDN-RUSSIAN RETROSPECTIVE. It would work well as a Sunday
Perspective/Insight page, especially given the current attention on
the Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
   The page will be followed soon by another focusing on Murray's
visit to the Baltics. For more information, please call Paul
Foutch, CoxNet news manager, at 404-526-5429.
</P>
<P>
   DIANA _ Monday is the first anniversary of Princess Diana's
birthday in eternity. That's a pious phrase long used by Christian
faithful to describe the day a saint died. For millions of her
fans, Diana, the rincess of Wales, remains a kind of secular
saint. She personifies, for them, all that is good and gracious in
a world of struggle and pain. To be sure, Diana struggled much,
knew great pain and was, in many ways, a good and gracious person.
But she is not likely to be a saint. The remarkable relationship
between the troubled princess and her adoring public is more
complicated. (Gushee, Palm Beach Post). 21.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GLENN _ John Glenn's historic return to space is now just two
months away but knowlegeable observers remain unimpressed with the
science of the flight, even as they pledge support for it on
thematic grounds. But that's what NASA had in mind anyway. NASA
Administrator Dan Goldin spoke frankly in an interview with us
earlier this summer about how he insisted the science be
legitimate, but how he never intended for it to be the sole
justification for Glenn's return to space. ``I wasn't asking the
National Institutes of Health to say, 'I want you to fly John
Glenn.' But I said, 'Given that John Glenn is flying I want you to
tell me that he's doing good science.''' (Montgomery, Dayton Daily
News).
</P>
<P>
   PROBATION _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A day in the life of a
probation officer in Palm Beach County, following him as he
monitors the whereabouts and conduct of 30 troubled people during
each work shift. We accompanied officers as they ``took down''
probation violaters. We detail the work load, the backgrounds of
the officers (most have master's degrees and have been a probation
officer for years) and the way the job has changed. (Moffett, Palm
Beach Post). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MACART _ Did you know Palm Beach County has a multiagency task
force that mobilizes everytime a child is reported missing to visit
the county's 400-plus pedophiles to make sure the child isn't with
one of them? We were the first county to create such a task force,
and ours has been used as a model for similar efforts around the
country. (Moffett, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   STORIES _ Rail of war stories from some of the county's
longest-standing probation officers. (Palm Beach Post). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
