<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL REPORT QUESTIONS CRANE'S MONOPOLY ON CURRENCY PAPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Crane &AMP; Co. of Dalton, Mass., the sole supplier of
US currency paper, should face competition that might lower the
government's cost of printing money, according to a report issued
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is unable to say whether it has obtained
a ``fair and reasonable price'' for its currency paper, said the
General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   While the GAO's conclusion has been long expected, Massachusetts
lawmakers said they had succeeded in ensuring that some of the
wording was watered down from a draft report circulated in July.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy, for example, had complained that the
draft report improperly suggested that subsidies be given to
Crane's competitors. That suggestion was deleted from the final
report.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a positive report for Crane, and a much fairer report
than the initial GAO report,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the report's main conclusion _ that Crane should face
competition _ remains the key recommendation. The GAO said the
Bureau of Engraving and Printing couldn't determine whether it had
paid fair prices for the paper supplied by Crane, which has been
the primary supplier of US currency paper since 1879,
</P>
<P>
   ``BEP sometimes accepted prices even though it was unable to
determine that they were fair and reasonable because it had no
other source for currency paper,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Lester Crane, the chairman of the Crane company, said it was
unfair for the GAO to leave any impression that the government had
wasted money in buying paper only from Crane. He said that his
company's cost efficiencies provide a fair price for the
government. Crane said it was unfair to describe his company as
having a monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Crane said that other companies have had the right to bid for
the four-year, $400 million contract. He said the report issued
Friday is moot because the government last January took bids from
several companies, including Crane, for the new contract. The
government is scheduled to announce the winning bidder _ or
bidders, if the contract is broken up _ sometime this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing wrong here that needs to be fixed,'' Crane
said. ``The solicitation process is open.''
</P>
<P>
   As many as 250 out of 1,350 employees at Crane are directly
involved in producing US currency paper. The company also
manufactures currency papers for other countries, including China,
and makes other paper products.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report was requested by Representative Jim Koble, an
Arizona Republican. Kolbe, whose district includes copper mines,
has sponsored legislation calling for the widespread production of
a dollar coin, which might include copper. If a silver dollar is
manufactured and becomes popular, that could pose another challenge
for Crane. About 45 percent of the currency paper produced by Crane
for the United States is for dollar bills.
</P>
<P>
   But Kolbe press secretary Ron Foreman said the congressman's
interest in Crane has nothing to do with the proposal for a dollar
coin.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a canard that Crane has been throwing around for some
time,'' Foreman said. ``The American taxpayer is paying too much
for the paper our money is printed on.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreman said that Kennedy and others in the Massachusetts
congressional delegation pressured the GAO to weaken the report,
which Foreman said might result in Crane's continued dominance. The
GAO report must be reviewed by Congress before the government
announces whether Crane will continue to have sole control of the
contract, Foreman said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Felix, a spokesman for the Bureau of Engraving and
Printing, said the government is ``happy with the relationsihp with
Crane &AMP; Co.'' The bureau ``has found that in most instances, the
price has been fair. In those instances we felt they weren't fair,
we went to an arbitrator. The arbitrator gave us some things and
gave Crane some things, as in most arbitrations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
