<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8212 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS &LR;      08-28 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOB-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTOR CHALLENGES MOBSTER'S CLIAM OF FBI PROTECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ If, as gangster/informant Stephen Flemmi claims, a
former FBI supervisor warned him and his fugitive criminal partner
James ``Whitey'' Bulger that they were about to be indicted, a
federal prosecutor asked Friday, why did Flemmi stick around?
</P>
<P>
   Grilling Flemmi on the witness stand, Assistant US Attorney Fred
M. Wyshak Jr. demanded to know why wasn't Flemmi on the lam now,
like Bulger, his longtime friend, who has eluded the law for more
than 3 1/2 years?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had mixed feelings about it,'' Flemmi testified, in his
seventh and final day on the witness stand in federal court. ``I
could have very well left.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyshak argued that the fact that he remained and was arrested at
gunpoint outside a downtown restaurant on the night of Jan. 5,
1995, casts doubt on one of Flemmi's claims: that former FBI
organized crime supervisor John M. Morris alerted Flemmi and Bulger
to the indictment a week before it was returned.Friday
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as he challenged Flemmi's claim that Morris had tipped
him off, Wyshak suggested that the sort of ``headstart'' that
Flemmi claims to have gotten from Morris was the sum total of the
deal he had cut with his bureau handlers _ not the blanket,
immunity-for-life for any crime short of murder, which Flemmi says
he has.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what Mr. Bulger got, a headstart?'' Wyshak asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what Mr. Bulger got was a telephone call telling him
the indictment was coming down, the same as I got,'' said Flemmi.
He said Bulger called him with the news after getting a call from
Morris, who he and Bulger had nicknamed ``Vino'' because of his
fondness for fine wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very brief conversation,'' Flemmi said of his phone
call from Bulger. ``He just told me that the indictments were
coming down. I said, `Goodbye and good luck.'''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators now know that Bulger and his longtime companion,
Teresa Stanley, were on vacation in San Francisco and New Orleans
in the weeks before his indictment.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last spring, Stanley told the Globe that she and
Bulger were driving home to Boston when they heard on the car radio
that Flemmi had been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Bulger seemed surprised by the news and stopped at a hotel
somewhere in Connecticut or western Massachusetts for the night,
according to Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Bulger dropped Stanley off at a Hingham
restaurant, where a relative retrieved her.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say Bulger then picked up Catherine Greig, a woman
he had secretly been having a relationship with for 20 years. Since
then, Bulger and Greig have been spotted in New York, Louisiana,
Mississippi, and Wyoming. Last year, the FBI announced a $250,000
reward for Bulger's capture and charged Greig with harboring a
fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   Wyshak suggested Friday that Flemmi knew independently that the
indictments were coming and squirreled money away in offshore
accounts. Flemmi refused to talk about that.
</P>
<P>
   Morris admitted in April that he took $7,000 from Bulger and
Flemmi and alerted Flemmi to a wiretap so he wouldn't be recorded.
But Morris denied alerting Bulger and Flemmi to the January 1995
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   At the time Flemmi says Bulger got the call from Morris, Morris
was working at the FBI's training academy in Quantico, Va., and had
been out of the bureau's Boston office for several years. He
retired in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Morris testified under a grant of immunity, which means that he
could only face criminal charges if it is shown that he lied during
his testimony in April.
</P>
<P>
   Morris also testified that he was the one who had confirmed
Bulger's status as an informant to the Globe in 1988, hoping that
the revelation would lead to the gangster's prosecution instead of
his protection.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi is trying to convince US District Judge Mark L. Wolf that
racketeering, extortion, and murder charges against him should be
dropped because he was promised immunity from prosecution in
exchange for information he gave the FBI on the Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly five months of testimony by defense witnesses, the
government is slated to begin its case next week when it calls the
first of 15 witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Flemmi said that he and Bulger held up their end of the
bargain but the FBI did not.
</P>
<P>
   La Cosa Nostra ``was taken down,'' Flemmi said. ``That was their
main concern. We fulfilled our bargain. ... We did a hell of a
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if informing on his criminal rivals _ including onetime
close friend and Mafia boss Francis P. Salemme _ had also made him
a wealthy man, Flemmi invoked his Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Besides the 1995 criminal charges he is contesting before
Wolf, Flemmi was charged in a separate indictment last year with
laundering criminal profits through the purchase of real estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We formed a partnership, the FBI and I. ... Yes, we did all
right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Shelley Murphy of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
