   These stories will move by  &UR; 8:30 p.m. Eastern time: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S. (Washington) _ Drawing a personal parallel to the
quality of friendship in difficult times, President Clinton said
Friday that he would go to Moscow on Monday as scheduled to meet
his struggling Russian counterpart, Boris N. Yeltsin. ``Anybody can
come see you when you're doing well,'' Clinton said, only hours
after a Yeltsin announced that he would not resign his office. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S.-SUMMIT (Washington) _ The scramble was on again at
the scramble-weary White House today. Three days before they are
scheduled to depart for a summit meeting in Moscow, senior
administration officials wondered whom they would wind up facing
across conference tables. By James Bennet.
</P>
