<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stock prices fell sharply for the second
straight day Friday, as continued fears about instability in Russia
and economic weakness closer to home led the stock market's to its
worst week in nine years. The Dow industrial average declined
114.31 points, or 1.4 percent, finishing the week at 8051.68, down
5.6 percent over the five-day period. The decline in the United
States continued a stream of losses in markets around the globe. By
Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   These stories will move by  &UR; 8 p.m. Eastern time: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ One statistic stands out to explain the
importance of Japan, along with its misery: When trading ended
Friday in Tokyo, Japanese stocks this week alone had dropped in
value by $241 billion _ a sum that exceeds the size of the entire
Russian economy at present exchange rates. In other words, in one
glum week's work, Japan managed the financial equivalent of wiping
Russia off the world map. Japan is so monumental as to be central
to the health of the global economy, but for now it remains a mess,
albeit an impressively large one. By Nicholas D. Kristof and Sheryl
WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   These stories will move by  &UR; 8:30 p.m. Eastern time: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-ECON (Hong Kong) _ Hong Kong's financial crisis is
gathering steam. The government on Friday went on the largest
buying spree yet in its two-week-old battle to hurt those betting
against stocks and the local currency. Still, the Hang Seng Index
fell 1.2 percent because the government stood virtually alone in
buying shares during the stock exchange's busiest day ever. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BANKAMERICA (Undated) _ The financial maelstrom ripping
through markets in Asia, Eastern Europe and Latin America added two
more banks to the growing casualty list of trading houses and
lenders swept into the storm's path. And while all eyes remain
focused on Russia's travails, it is now clearly apparent that
volatility in more economically significant countries like Brazil
and Argentina is eating into the profits of some financial concerns
doing business there. BankAmerica says it has recorded $220 million
of trading losses this year, mostly in Russia. By Timothy L.
O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
