<HEADER>
A8216 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALLMAN-GRAVE-COX     08-28 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLMAN-GRAVE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Allman fans trash grave site
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACON, Ga._ City workers Friday tore down and hauled away the
8-foot-tall, chain link-and-razor wire fence that the sister of
Allman Brothers Band member Berry Oakley erected around the graves
of her brother and band co-founder Duane Allman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in shock,'' said Candace Oakley. ``I'm having trouble even
thinking straight.''
</P>
<P>
   The graves are a magnet for fans of the band, and Oakley had the
fence put up about a month ago. Many fans were trashing the site,
she said, and three months ago someone tried to dig up the remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is paying your respects?'' Oakley asked. ``It's turned
into a freak show with a carnival atmosphere. I don't understand
why people leave (marijuana) roaches and liquor. Do they think
Duane and Berry get up at night and enjoy it?''
</P>
<P>
   But Rose Hill Cemetery belongs to the city, and Mayor Jim
Marshall said the fence had to go _ although he has found a donor
to replace it with something more aesthetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that you've got a bunch of nuts abusing the
public right of access by engaging in all kinds of immoral and
illegal behavior around these grave sites. It's entirely legitimate
for her to want to protect her brother's grave, but this is not the
way,'' Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people have visited the graves of Allman and Oakley
since they died in motorcycle accidents about a year apart in 1971
and 1972. The two are buried side-by-side near the Ocmulgee River
in the cemetery, which was designed in 1839.
</P>
<P>
   The band is performing next Tuesday, Wednesday, Friday, Saturday
and Sunday at the Fox Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley said she has photographs of beer cans, marijuana
cigarettes, lipstick kisses and people lounging on the graves.
People have chipped pieces of the marble stone and carved their
names and initials into it, Oakley said. She also said she has seen
people take nude photographs on the graves and has found condoms at
the site.
</P>
<P>
   The last straw, she said, came when ``someone tried to get into
the graves. They got down to the vault, and that stopped them.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Anthony, Macon's parks and recreation director, said,
``We are trying to work with her to get something more aesthetic
for a historic cemetery like this,'' he said. Other graves in Rose
Hill are fenced, he said, but with wrought iron, not chain link.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Marshall said, ``I have already found someone who will pay
for it. It's just a matter of working it out with the family.''
Marshall refused to identify the donor, but said he expected the
cost of a wrought iron fence with benches would run as high as
$25,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just can't be something that looks like Stalag 17,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley, however, was not mollified. ``I've been told a wrought
iron fence will just be stolen,'' she said. ``I guess the mayor is
going to make me dig a little deeper and put up a mausoleum.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
