<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-LMAY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: In praise of oft-overlooked houseplants
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   During his latest visit to keep the roaches on the run, the bug
man and I were chatting about chores. I mentioned my need to water
my plants, and he said, as he was leaving, ``It just rained.
Doesn't look like you need to do any watering today.''
</P>
<P>
   Houseplants, I said. They need watering, too. And attention. A
little respect wouldn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't enter the bug man's ken. And he's not alone. A lot
of gardeners give indoor gardening short shrift this time of year,
as the fall planting season beckons seductively. Fact is, though,
houseplants remained faithful during those hot summer months when
outdoor plants did everything they could to check out.
</P>
<P>
   On many days, when the misery index soared to a 9, heading
toward the maximum 10 (funny how some weather guessers love
flaming-hot temperatures just because the sun shines), houseplant
gardening was the only gardening I did.
</P>
<P>
   And now I anticipate a long, lush indoor season, focusing on it
in much the same way I look forward to spring in the outdoor
garden. It is in the cold days of winter that those oft-forgotten
indoor specimens will take center stage.
</P>
<P>
   On my plants' stage there will be a bit more room this fall and
winter, as I have moved a great many plants from Atlanta to the
cabin in McCaysville. Each specimen, then, will get better display
_ in both places. For example, the aralia in the Atlanta kitchen
looks a lot happier, now that it does not have to compete for
attention with the Boston fern and the maranta. Also, my Atlanta
home office feels a lot roomier, without the peace lily that has
moved to North Georgia, along with the ti plant, dumb cane, bamboo
and others.
</P>
<P>
   One huge space opened up with the jade plant's untimely death: a
gaping hole in the dining room decor. I did manage to save one jade
finger, which now grows in a much smaller pot than the one the sumo
jade occupied. If I can abstain from overwatering this little
survivor, it may one day turn into a nice living sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   The African violets have done as much as any plant to keep my
gardening muscles exercised, as most of the dozen or so always are
in bloom. I don't know how they keep performing so well with so
little rest, and I'm not going to try to figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   The lipstick plant got really busy this year, too, continually
producing burgundy-colored, trumpet-shaped blooms. Lovely.
</P>
<P>
   Ferns _ from the lacy asparagus in a bonsai tray to the zaftig
Boston hanging from the ceiling _ green up indoor spaces like
nothing else. And the rabbit's foot creeps and crawls, captivating
endlessly.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest-working vine in the house has to be pothos. Amazing
how little light this climber needs. Mine don't climb; they hang
from the tops of cabinets, painting the wood with touches of green
and white, getting trimmed from time to time when they start to
crawl along the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Crawling, hanging, standing, all my plants will share those
perfect days of autumn, when open windows admit breezes to delight
senses and ruffle leaves, reawakening both.
</P>
<P>
   On to winter, when indoor plants must endure conditions that
amount to a harsh flip side of their summer duty. In their time of
highest profile, they must survive dry heat _ just as they did dry
air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   That, along with playing second string to the outdoor garden,
shows again that it isn't easy being green.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: leemay(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
