<SLUG> BC-GARDENMUSUEM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Centuries-old gardening tools and rare plants from the 1700s
find a home in London church
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   London_It's a gardener's treasure chest _ a 17th-century
watering can, shovels more than 100 years old, an 1800s
wheelbarrow, even a Victorian cucumber straightener _ and the gems
aren't even outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   They're in church.
</P>
<P>
   Avid gardeners would agree a sanctuary's the perfect place to
pay homage to 300 years of tools that have made their lives easier.
</P>
<P>
   But because of its own legacy, the 17th-century church east of
London's Embankment is an even more appropriate home for the Museum
of Garden History _ the only one of its kind in the world. Its
churchyard contains the tomb of two famed plantsmen, a bit of
history that prompted Rosemary Nicholson and her late husband,
John, to establish their museum there.
</P>
<P>
   ``People thought we were absolutely mad,'' she says of the
struggle 20 years ago to convert the dilapidated church and
graveyard into a gallery and rare-plant repository. ``They would
ask, `Garden history? What's that? What do we need to know about
it?'''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently lots, as Americans' passion for gardening reaches
levels rivaling that of the British. ``Look at how many people are
doing it,'' says Nicholson, a redheaded senior with a persistent
grin. ``It's become such a pastime with everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the museum director can bask in the success of a program
run by a staff of six and manned by 50 volunteers. But the couple's
struggles to save St. Mary at Lambeth from a developer's wrecking
ball, revive the building from decay and secure funding for museum
operations remain vivid.
</P>
<P>
   The Nicholsons first visited the site 25 years ago to see the
tomb of the two John Tradescants, the 17th-century father-and-son
horticulturists who served as royal gardeners. The younger also
drew fame for the plants he introduced from Virginia, including
tulip trees, spiderwort and columbine.
</P>
<P>
   What the Nicholsons found was not pretty. Stained-glass windows
in the church, deconsecrated in 1972, were boarded up, and birds
flew in and out of a hole in the roof. The floor had fallen in, and
old car parts littered a weed-infested yard. ``At that point, we
didn't want to see the tomb,'' Nicholson says.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the visit came more disappointment: They learned of
plans to build a walk along the Thames for the queen's 1977 Silver
Jubilee, and St. Mary's stood in the way. ``It just seemed so
dreadful that it would be demolished,'' Nicholson says of the
historic site, where six archbishops of Canterbury and Capt. Bligh
of HMS Bounty fame are buried.
</P>
<P>
   The Nicholsons immediately launched efforts to save it. The
three hurdles were leasing the property, getting it listed with the
English Heritage (similar to the National Register of Historic
Places) and forming a trust.
</P>
<P>
   Some church officials objected to allowing a use for the
structure other than worship, while others simply couldn't
understand the interest. ``They said,' It's a heap on stone ready
to come down,' '' Nicholson recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Even many of England's pre-eminent horticulturists scoffed at
the idea of a garden museum.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, backed by art collectors, the Nicholsons began a fund
drive, and Prince Charles became a patron of the trust.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the real dirty work began. ``We'd come down on weekends
with rubber gloves and black plastic bags to collect the rubble,''
Nicholson says.
</P>
<P>
   In the churchyard, a new garden was designed to include rare
plants and shrubs, many of which the Tradescants had grown or
introduced to England and all of which were donated by nurseries.
</P>
<P>
   Since opening in 1983, the museum has acquired an additional
building for offering seminars, and the collection has grown so
large the museum is raising money to expand.
</P>
<P>
   The inventory runs the gamut, from shears, scythes and snippers
to baskets, bell jars and ``bird scarers'' (Victorian-style,
green-eyed cat's heads designed to protect plants). There's a
display of insecticide pouffes and sprayers, a group of early lawn
mowers and desks once owned by famed plantswoman Gertrude Jekyll.
</P>
<P>
   ``The variety of stuff here is absolutely amazing,'' says Martha
Jenkins, a green thumb visiting from Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   And the most unusual item?
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson says it's the ``vegetable lamb,'' the root of a
specimen fern thought in the 11th century to resemble a small lamb.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only four in the world,'' she says, adding with
pride, ``but ours is the best.''
</P>
<P>
   -- The Museum of Garden History is open Monday through Friday
from 10:30 a.m. to 4 p.m. and Sundays from 10:30 a.m. to 5 p.m.
Admission is free. Information: 011-44-171-401-8865c
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
