<SLUG> BC-HDEPOT-TOOLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot a small town's hero in deal with Emerson
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS, TENN. _ Home Depot is the toast of this tiny industrial
town midway between Nashville and Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 10,000 residents likely have never shopped in a Home
Depot (the nearest store is about 70 miles away), but the
Atlanta-based home improvement retailer has become an instant
hometown hero as a result of its new contract with Emerson Tool
Co., the manufacturer that for decades churned out Sears Roebuck &AMP;
Co.'s Craftsman power tools. When Sears ditched Emerson last year
and took its Craftsman power tool production offshore, it created
an immediate scare among the factory's 400 employees that the plant
would shut down after losing its top customer.
</P>
<P>
   But it turned into a golden opportunity for Emerson and Home
Depot. ''We've been looking for this product for 15 years, but we
couldn't find a manufacturer that could match the quality,'' said
Home Depot Chairman Bernard Marcus in an interview at the Emerson
factory. ''I've had conversations with (Emerson) for eight years to
get them to make these tools for us, but they couldn't because of
the loyalty to Sears. When they came to us last year and asked if
we still wanted them, there was a lot of hugging and kissing at
that meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a lot of fanfare at the Emerson plant on Friday, when
the companies celebrated the new partnership. Skydivers,
representatives from the Tennessee governor's office, a band and
Miss Tennessee joined about 600 Home Depot and Emerson employees to
welcome Marcus, who canceled his plans to visit the company's new
store in Santiago, Chile, that opened this week.
</P>
<P>
   Amid continual applause and Home Depot chants, plant manager
Bucky Purcell took a quick break from Marcus' plant tour to take it
all in. ''We've never had this much excitement here,'' Purcell
said. ''Arthur Martinez (Sears chairman and chief executive) never
came in.'' Marcus was careful to leave his mark at the
640,000-square-foot plant, autographing a giant orange Home Depot
logo emblazoned on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ''When it came time to look for another partner, Home Depot was
our first, second and third choice,'' said Dave Pringle, president
of Emerson Tool Co. The tool factory in Paris is one of 60
divisions of St. Louis-based Emerson Electric, founded in 1890 as a
manufacturer of electric motors and fans. Emerson, whose brands
include Louisville Ladder, Vermont American and Western Forge, had
revenue of $12.3 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   While Emerson is undoubtedly grateful for the new partnership,
Home Depot is also capitalizing on the opportunity in a big way.
For the first time, the company will now have its own brand of
high-quality, durable power tools, which it will position and price
midway between the do-it-yourself and professional markets. The
tools, which include table saws, sanders and other power products,
will be sold under Emerson's Ridgid logo, a 75-year-old brand name
widely known in the plumbing industry.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson developed a new product line of bench top and stationary
power tools, including table saws and an oscillating sander, for
the exclusive Home Depot partnership.
</P>
<P>
   The Sears contract officially ends Oct. 1. Emerson is busy
stocking a two-month supply of products for Home Depot, and the new
Ridgid line has already hit some stores, although it begins the
official rollout across the country next month. Home Depot has been
selling Ridgid wet/dry vacuums since May.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson is already working on more plans with Home Depot. ''Last
year we were in a phase of downsizing, but now we're in a growth
mode,'' said Charles Knight, chairman and chief executive of
Emerson Electric. ''We're already working on more products.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
