</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-LABYRINTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta churches are reviving the tradition of a medieval
labyrinth.
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_With the soft swish of sock feet on canvas, walkers step
methodically along a white path on a purple background at Holy
Trinity Episcopal Church in Decatur, Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   They are moving physically and spiritually through a labyrinth,
a carefully prescribed, centuries-old design being rediscovered
across the country as a tool of meditation and worship. Atlanta's
Episcopal Cathedral of St. Philip has a new canvas labyrinth and
Cedar Hill Enrichment Center in Forsyth County has held workshops
for people interested in learning about the ancient tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something we can't explain about the pattern of the
labyrinth that seems to help people very quickly to get into a
meditative state, to find their center very quickly,'' said the
Rev. Susan Latimer, assistant to the rector at St. Bartholomew's
Episcopal Church in the Toco Hill area of Atlanta. ``Many people
find somehow in their walk that they come out with a feeling of
God's love and care for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Holy Trinity labyrinth is modeled after one built into the
floor of the cathedral in Chartres, France, about the year 1200.
Its path twists and turns 34 times through 11 concentric circles to
a six-petaled rosette center. Walkers traditionally follow the path
into the center, stop to meditate, then follow the path back out.
</P>
<P>
   A labyrinth is not a maze, with false starts and dead ends.
Instead, it has one clear but winding path. Although the physical
path is narrow and serpentine, the spiritual journey of the
labyrinth is totally unscripted. All who step onto the pattern find
their own way.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the key is to be totally open,'' said Kit Kamper, 55, a
Holy Trinity member from Decatur and a regular labyrinth walker.
``It's not a matter of doing or solving or resolving for me. It's a
matter of being with God.''
</P>
<P>
   Kamper said she usually walks the labyrinth at night by
candlelight, but one early morning experience was especially
memorable. ``The sun was pouring in and there were these beams of
sunlight coming onto the labyrinth,'' she said. ``The morning was
cool but the sun was hot. I felt as if I were swimming underwater
and feeling the icy cold of the water, and then a warm pocket. That
experience was very exciting and very intimate.''
</P>
<P>
   Kamper, a software engineer, said she intentionally does not
analyze or interpret her feelings. ``That can be limiting,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dale Miller, 54, a United Methodist who recently walked the
Holy Trinity labyrinth for the first time, came with a list of
specific prayer subjects: her recently married son and his wife;
her younger son, who just finished graduate school; and a friend
whose sister has pancreatic cancer. She also brought gratitude for
her family, her kindergarten students and co-workers at DeKalb
County's Medlock Elementary School as the new year began.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me the act of walking is therapeutic if you're trying to
sort things out,'' she said. ``It was an opportunity when I could
focus on God, what I would hear from him and what I would like to
say to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The rapidly growing interest in the spiritual possibilities of
the labyrinth can be traced to the Rev. Lauren Artress, an
Episcopal priest and canon of Grace Cathedral in San Francisco.
During a retreat, she ``stumbled upon'' the tradition of the
labyrinth, little used for the past 350 years, and began to
research it.
</P>
<P>
   Artress learned that a form of the labyrinth has been used in
many religious traditions and cultures, including Native American
and Egyptian. Patterns have been seen on Cretan coins and Tibetan
sand paintings.
</P>
<P>
   During the Middle Ages, when political struggles made
pilgrimages to Jerusalem too dangerous and expensive for
Christians, the Roman Catholic Church established seven
``pilgrimage'' cathedrals, including the one in Chartres, where
people could use labyrinths to make symbolic journeys to the Holy
City.
</P>
<P>
   Artress visited Chartres, determined to walk the long-unused
labyrinth there. After moving 256 chairs to uncover the pattern,
she and some friends made their walk. ``I feel we had touched the
Holy Spirit,'' she wrote in the introduction to her book, ``Walking
a Sacred Path'' (Riverhead Books, 1995, $11).
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Artress supervised construction of a labyrinth for her
own parish, which has since added an outdoor version.
</P>
<P>
   Like many people from across the country, Latimer attended a
workshop at Grace. She left determined to bring the concept of the
labyrinth with her to Holy Trinity, where she then worked. Church
members donated the money for supplies, drew the pattern, painted
it and sewed it themselves. It was consecrated last September.
</P>
<P>
   Latimer would like to have an outdoor version in Atlanta,
perhaps at St. Bartholomew's.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Chartres pattern has strong ties to Christianity,
the Holy Trinity labyrinth draws people of many different religious
walks.
</P>
<P>
   Janice Goldstein, 75, of Dunwoody is a member of Temple
Emanu-El, a Reform Jewish congregation. She said she found peace in
the labyrinth, which she walked for the first time in June. ``I was
void of all tension and stress,'' she said. ``I found myself under
a spell of total relaxation.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Goldstein returned, bringing her friend Doree Kenler,
who is also Jewish, on an outing celebrating Kenler's 81st
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   For David Cates, 35, walking the labyrinth is a variation of the
walking meditation he learned as a Buddhist. Cates, a former
Southern Baptist, recently moved to Atlanta after 4 1/2 years in
Japan. He said he found in Buddhism a freedom for critical inquiry
and a strong sense of compassion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just wonderful,'' he said after finishing the Holy
Trinity walk with sister-in-law Judi Robinson, 43, of Norcross.
``It's very peaceful and centering. When I knew I was getting
toward the end, I wanted it to keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
