<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    B'nai B'rith collects furry friends for kids
 &HT;    By Derrick Henry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_Stuffed animals are cute and cuddly and have a way of
making children feel better.
</P>
<P>
   That's the belief of B'nai B'rith members who are collecting
hundreds of such dolls to give to children at hospitals in metro
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about bringing a smile to faces of kids who don't have a
lot of reason to smile,'' says Helaine Fruchtman, B'nai B'rith's
Southeast regional director.
</P>
<P>
   The collection program, B'nai B'rith Cares for Kids, begins
Tuesday. The drive will continue through September and will
culminate Oct. 4, when the stuffed animals will be given to
patients _ newborns to teens _ at Scottish Rite Children's Medical
Center, Egleston Children's Hospital and Hughes Spalding Children's
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to see the children's faces light up when we
present them with a cute teddy bear,'' says volunteer Jerry
Kravitz, regional chairman of the B'nai B'rith Center for Community
Action.
</P>
<P>
   Kravitz, 62, a resident of Roswell and a consultant for the
travel industry, has been volunteering with the Jewish service
organization for nearly 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   During September, Kravitz and others will be collecting new
stuffed animals from individuals, businesses and organizations.
Collection boxes will be placed in synagogues and businesses
throughout metro Atlanta. People can also donate money for the
cause _ a $10 contribution buys one bear; $18 will buy two.
</P>
<P>
   And volunteers are being sought to pick up and sort the bears in
late September and to deliver them to the children in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity for B'nai B'rith to give back not only
to the Jewish community, but the community at large, and in a way
that provides immediate impact both to the children and to the
volunteers,'' says Fruchtman.
</P>
<P>
   The local group's stuffed animal drive is the Southeastern pilot
for a campaign B'nai B'rith started in Houston in 1996. ``The kids
were thrilled and the hospital was delighted,'' says Thomas Wolff,
director of B'nai B'rith's Texarkoma (Texas, Arkansas, Oklahoma)
region.
</P>
<P>
   Since the program started, about 8,500 stuffed animals have been
donated to hospitals, shelters and schools.
</P>
<P>
   B'NAI B'RITH
</P>
<P>
   -- At a glance: Founded in New York in 1843 by 12 German-Jewish
immigrants, B'nai B'rith (``Children of the Covenant'') is the
oldest service organization started in the United States. It has
grown into what is claimed to be the world's largest service
organization, with 230,000 members in 57 countries on six
continents.
</P>
<P>
   -- Programs: Projects include funding emergency relief,
sponsoring affordable housing for senior citizens, espousing Jewish
causes and human rights, and youth programs.
</P>
<P>
   -- Further information: Call 770-992-0902, or check the
organization's Web site at: http://www.bnaibrith.org
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
