<P>
   HONGKONG-ECON (Hong Kong) _ In the climax of an unprecedented
two-week-long direct intervention in the stock market, Hong Kong's
government spent what traders estimated at $8 billion Friday in a
frenzied buying spree to prop up shares and foil speculators it
accuses of manipulating its market. On Thursday, an earlier round
of intervention had managed to push the Hong Kong stock market up
while every other market around the globe was down. Friday, for all
the money spent, the benchmark Hang Seng index still declined 93.23
points, or 1.2 percent, to 7,829.74. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The story is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-SMALL-INVESTORS (New York) _ The only way Dunstan Connell
could have been more emphatic would have been if he had borrowed
Alfred E. Neuman's shibboleth from Mad magazine: What, me worry?
``This?'' Connell, a clerk for Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. who works at
the New York Stock Exchange, said as the Dow Jones industrial
average was seesawing Friday between a gain and a loss. ``It's not
a big deal.'' By James Barron and David Barboza.
</P>
