<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8226 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-NEBRASKA-HNS &LR;      08-28 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NEBRASKA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
By TERRY BLOUNT 
Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
LINCOLN, Neb. _ Frank Solich admits he will be happy to get this
day behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Solich has been asked a thousand times what it feels like to
replace a legend, and he hopes those questions will end, or at
least taper off, once the Nebraska Cornhuskers get a game under
their belts without Tom Osborne's stoic presence on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The Cornhuskers, ranked fourth in the nation in preseason polls,
play Louisiana Tech today in the Eddie Robinson Classic. It will be
Solich's debut as a head coach and the first time in 25 years
Osborne will not call the shots in front of a sea of red at
Memorial Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get this game going will be a blessing for everybody,''
said Solich, who was an assistant under Osborne for 19 years. ``We
think we have a quality team, and we know we are going up against a
quality opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Tech might not be close to the level of a team that
was a co-national champion last season, but the Bulldogs were 9-2
and return one of the best quarterbacks in the nation. Tom Rattay,
a 6-1, 200-pound junior, passed for a school-record 3,881 yards and
34 touchdowns last season.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers seem more impressive when you realize Terry
Bradshaw is the player Rattay passed in the Louisiana Tech record
book.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great deal of respect for Louisiana Tech,'' said
Nebraska quarterback Bobby Newcombe. ``We're going to play this
game like it was our last instead of our first. We have to win the
first one and go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Solich, Newcombe is the player most of the 73,000
people at the game are coming to see. The talented sophomore will
make his first start as the signal-caller for Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby certainly is fast,'' said Nebraska linebacker Jay
Foreman. ``There are times when you think you have him, then he has
that little bit of extra speed, a burst that leaves you behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Newcombe, who played receiver and returned punts as a freshman,
said he knows how Solich feels because both will be the center of
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, coach Solich and I will be nervous, but we both have a
lot of confidence,'' Newcombe said. ``We're comfortable with the
expectations. It's just one of those things that comes with playing
football at Nebraska.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing quarterback at Nebraska automatically invites scrutiny.
Last season, quarterback Scott Frost criticized the fans for
questioning his ability. Newcombe has not taken a snap in a game at
the position, but he has been compared to former Nebraska
All-America quarterback Tommie Frazier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommie told me there would be a lot of pressure but that I
would do fine,'' Newcombe said. ``He told me to relax and go with
the flow. I know I'm prepared for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Solich, 54, believes he has prepared himself for all the
comparisons to Osborne that will come over the course of this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to keep doing a lot of the things that made this
program successful,'' Solich said. ``I don't believe my style is
much different than Tom's. I will try to do a lot of the things he
did, because he did things the right way. I have no designs for
placing my own stamp on the program. That will take care of itself
if we keep the team at a high level.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Cornhuskers enter today's game with some question marks,
especially on the offensive line. Only Josh Heskew returns as a
starter up front.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska also will have to play the first two or three games
without tailback DeAngelo Evans, the man designated to replace
Ahman Green. Evans had arthroscopic knee surgery this week to
repair a torn cartilage.
</P>
<P>
   But a new coach, an injured running back and a lot of new faces
on the offensive line probably won't keep the Cornhuskers from
rolling to another home victory. Nebraska hasn't lost in Lincoln
since 1991, a span of 42 games.
</P>
<P>
   The 'Huskers also haven't lost a season opener since 1985. Those
milestones, along with taking over for a man who won three national
championships in his last four seasons, doesn't make things easier
for Solich.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there's going to be pressure on coach Solich,'' said
Nebraska fullback Joel Makovicka. ``But we can take the pressure
away by playing well. The approach is the same under coach Solich.
He has us working for perfection, and I think people around here
respond to that. They did under coach Osborne, and they will under
coach Solich.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, Solich isn't an outsider. He became a part of the
Nebraska family when he played fullback for the Cornhuskers 35
years ago under Bob Devaney _ the legendary coach Osborne replaced.
So Solich knows taking over for a legend can be a successful
endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to follow Tom,'' Solich said. ``There are a lot
of people around the country who will look at this program and feel
it will keep rolling along. But that only will happen if we recruit
well, prepare well and keep a great staff. We have worked very
hard, and now it's time to show what we can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
