u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPACE-STATION-HNS &LR;      08-28 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-STATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN ECONOMIC WOES POSE NEW THREAT TO SPACE STATION, U.S.
LAWMAKER WARNS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Russia's latest economic upheaval poses a new threat
to the U.S.-led international space station, the chairman of NASA's
House oversight committee warned Friday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., head of the House Science
Committee, issued the warning as he completed a closed-door meeting
with NASA's top station program managers at the Johnson Space
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The more than five-year effort to assemble the laboratory in
Earth orbit is scheduled to begin in late November, a year behind
schedule due primarily to Russia's failure to adequately fund its
crucial contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Sensenbrenner blamed the Clinton administration for the prospect
of further postponements, claiming policy-makers have turned a deaf
ear to warnings from Congress as well as NASA and its independent
consultants that Russia is not up to the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``Statements of confidence in Russian performance on the station
in the near term contradict all the current economic and political
indicators in Russia,'' said Sensenbrenner, a reference to White
House assurances made as recently as Aug. 5.
</P>
<P>
   A staunch supporter of the station, the Wisconsin lawmaker has
nonetheless challenged the wisdom of the administration's 1993
invitation for the Russians to join the project. By late 1995, it
was clear the Russians could not or would not meet key development
milestones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The White House, very honestly, has been in denial since
then,'' Sensenbrenner said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmaker suggested that support within Congress for the
space station would remain strong even if Russia dropped out of the
project and U.S. costs escalated.
</P>
<P>
   ``You simply cannot build the space station that taxpayers
expect around the Russians if the Russians are not going to meet
their obligations,`` said Sensenbrenner. ``The odds are good that
Congress would be willing to view past failures as water under the
bridge.``
</P>
<P>
   Russia's contributions to the project include a habitable
42,000-pound component called the service module, Soyuz capsules to
transport crews to the station and serve as lifeboats, and dozens
of unmanned Progress capsule launches with the fuel that will be
needed to keep the station flying at a safe altitude.
</P>
<P>
   The assembly is scheduled to begin with the Nov. 20 launching of
the U.S.-financed, Russian-crafted control module. It is to be
followed in early December by a structural passageway that will
link future U.S. and Russian segments.
</P>
<P>
   The crucial Russian service module is set for an April 1999
launching. Without it, the first crew of astronauts and cosmonauts
cannot take up residence as planned next July.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's lack of funding for the module produced the earlier
postponements and forced the United States to initiate the
development of a replacement module that can perform the propulsion
duties of the service module, but not its life support function.
</P>
<P>
   Though the service module is nearly built, the installation of
final components and launch preparations have again fallen behind
schedule. Russian funding for station work has reached only $20
million so far this year, less than 10 percent of the requirement,
and one of NASA's consultants has suggested it may be necessary for
the United States to pay Russian contractors directly to complete
the task.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Russian engineers are scheduled to meet in late
September in Moscow to formally appraise the readiness of the
service module and make other schedule assessments. NASA is also
concerned that Russia is not acquiring the components that will be
needed for the Progress supply ships that will be needed once
construction gets under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we have to continually watch,'' James
Hartsfield, a NASA station program spokesman, said Friday. ``We
haven't had anything of concern to the point that we want to
reschedule launches.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
