<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8228 &Cx1f; tth-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-COMMUNISM-CZAR     08-28 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-COMMUNISM-CZARS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH RUSSIA IN TURMOIL, SOME FEEL NOSTALGIA FOR CZARIST DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As some Russian leaders are looking back to the
Communist days in search of ways to pull the reeling nation out of
its tailspin, other Russians are looking back even further _ to the
days of the czars.
</P>
<P>
   While coping with its economic and political crises, Russia also
is enduring the latest of many painful shake-ups in place names,
national symbols and recognized heroes, part of the country's
tradition of regularly reinventing its past.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the country's poverty and financial turmoil, its leaders
continue to build grandiose monuments and reconstruct symbols of
days gone by, such as the Cathedral of Jesus Christ the Savior,
rebuilt at a cost of at least $300 million 60 years after Soviet
dictator Joseph Stalin had it blown up.
</P>
<P>
   It is unsettling to some younger Russians. ``Why do we do this
when we cannot feed our old people?'' asked Misha, a government
employee who asked that his full name not be used.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of rebuilding a huge cathedral, a ``small monument''
should have been erected at the site of Stalin's vandalism, said
Nina Novikova, 23, a recent university graduate. ``It would have
served the same purpose,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Symbols of the past are all most Russians have to celebrate. Its
recent leaders are vastly unpopular. Mikhail Gorbachev is blamed
for the disintegration of the Soviet Union. Boris Yeltsin is seen
as ineffectual, enjoying the good life while the vast majority of
his countrymen have seen their standard of living go through the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, in recent times, it has been out with the new and
in with the old symbols of the Orthodox church and pre-1917,
czarist Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Names of Bolshevik heroes have been stripped from the country's
cities. Leningrad has reverted to St. Petersburg, the name given by
its czar founder, Peter the Great.
</P>
<P>
   In its third nomenclature this century, the name Tsarskoe Selo
(the ``Tsar's Village'') has been reattached to the town near St.
Petersburg where Catherine the Great built her summer palace. The
Soviets had first renamed it Detsoe Selo (``Children's Village'')
and later changed the name to Pushkin on the 100th anniversary of
the poet's birth.
</P>
<P>
   While busts of Lenin are still so ubiquitous that the Soviet
Union's founder is informally known as the pigeon's friend, other
Bolsheviks have been treated roughly in death.
</P>
<P>
   Statues of such Soviet heroes as Feliks Dzerzhinsky and Mikhail
Kalinin have been torn down and dragged to the New Tratyakov
Gallery in Moscow. The founder of the Soviet secret police, and the
puppet yes-man president under Stalin, can be found scattered in
the grass in what has been titled the Garden of Sculpture of the
Epoch of Totalitarianism.
</P>
<P>
   The ups and down of Marshal Georgi Zhukov, in death as well as
life, are instructive.
</P>
<P>
   Zhukov was a hero of World War II, which Russians call the Great
Patriotic War. He directed the defense of Leningrad and Moscow, and
drove German forces all the way back to Berlin. It was Zhukov's
soldiers who planted a Soviet flag atop the Reichstag on May 1,
1945, a day after Adolf Hitler committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Army marshal was so popular, however, that a year later
the jealous Stalin had him exiled to an obscure command in Odessa
by the Black Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Zhukov returned to the Kremlin after the dictator's death. In
1957, as Soviet defense minister, he used military planes to fly
central committee members to Moscow _ and help Nikita Khrushchev
turn back a challenge from Stalin's henchmen. Less than a year
later, however, Khrushchev fired him.
</P>
<P>
   Zhukov disappeared from war histories during his times of exile,
and died in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1990s, however, he has made a posthumus comeback. It
turns out that Zhukov is one Soviet-era figure who can safely be
celebrated in post-Communist Russia. He was a genuine national
hero, with the courage to bluntly speak his mind to Stalin. He also
was known to keep a religious icon in his home.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a statue of Zhukov has been erected just outside Red
Square.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest and gaudiest example of Russia's changing
symbolism is the Cathedral of Jesus Christ the Savior, built in the
1800s to give thanks to God for Russia's victory over Napoleon.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Christmas and Easter as many as 15,000 people squeezed
inside the cathedral _ all carrying beeswax candles _ and soloists
from the Bolshoi Theatre would sing the holiday chants and hymns,''
author David Remnick wrote in ``Resurrection: The Struggle for a
New Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Stalin had other ideas. After the cathedral was reduced to
rubble in 1931 _ it took 18 months to cart the debris away _ he
aimed to built a Palace of Soviets higher than the Empire State
Building. It was to be topped by a statue of Lenin that would dwarf
the Statue of Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   The dictator was thwarted when dozens of natural springs were
discovered on the site. Soviet rulers eventually gave up on their
palace. Instead, Khrushchev ordered the erection of what he called
``the biggest swimming pool in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, however, Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov decided the
cathedral would be rebuilt. Luzhkov presided over privatizing
property in Moscow, which gave opportunities to make great fortunes
to well-connected businessmen. In turn, Luzhkov could call on the
city's new oligarchs to help put up money for the church.
</P>
<P>
   The cathedral has arisen, a gleaming competitor for attention
with the nearby Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   Other Luzhkov projects have included a refurbished Bolshoi
Theatre, a restored Resurrection Gate at the entrance to Red
Square, an underground shopping mall and an enormous hilltop war
memorial complex complete with museum and Orthodox Church.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Alexander Tkachenko, an Orthodox priest in St.
Petersburg, was asked why such former Communist Party apparatchiks
as Yeltsin, Luzhkov and St. Petersburg governor Vladimir Yakovlev
have latched onto religious symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   He replied that such symbolism is essential in holding together
a fractious, fractured country _ whether the leaders are believers
or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeltsin is a Russian man, of course,'' said Tkachenko. ``He is
a politician. He understands that only the church can preserve
Russia from civil war. Only the church has kept alive cultural
traditions. Only the church prevents moral destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   While Russia builds symbols, its people must still eat. Beggars
have flocked to the square outside the Cathedral of Jesus Christ
the Savior. Outside Luzhkov's projects on the edge of Red Square,
elderly women trudge with heavy sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Well-dressed Russians summoned the old ladies by whispering,
``Babushka! Babushka!'', the term of endearment that roughly means
grandmother. The women would furtively look around for police.
Reaching into the sacks, they produced bottles of beer and canned
gin drinks at a fraction of the price charged at nearby bars.
</P>
<P>
   By such means do people survive amidst the renewed glories of
the ``new Russia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
