<HEADER>
A8229 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-600&AMP;AD     08-28 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN, ON TV, APPEARS TO BE IN POOR HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ If putting President Boris Yeltsin on the
government-owned television network Friday night in a staged
interview was supposed to restore public faith in his ability to
govern, it was not much of a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked like Chernenko,'' said Leonid Radzikhovsky, a
political commentator for the newspaper Sevodnya, referring to the
Soviet leader best known for shuffling through his last months in
office, supported at the elbow by attentive aides.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, Yeltsin's face looked puffy, his gestures were
uncoordinated and his words, which came slowly and with labored
pauses, were a wooden echo of the kind of language he would have
used 15 years ago, as a Communist first secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assignments have now been given to the Central Bank, the
government,'' he said. ``Everything is spelled out in detail, what
should be done, how, in what direction, everything.'' He sat across
the table from his interviewer, Nikolai Zvanidze, and referred at
one point, oddly, to his Cabinet members as ``cadres.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We must strictly comply with what is written there,'' Yeltsin
intoned.
</P>
<P>
   What detailed instructions? About those the president said
nothing, just as his prime minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin, has yet
to explain the decisions he said he had made on Thursday to start
bringing the country out of its spiraling crisis.
</P>
<P>
   So the Russian public, or the small portion that tuned in to a
government-run channel after the 8 p.m. news, remained in the dark
Friday night, just it has have been all week.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for some Russians, seeing the president was enough to
reassure them that the political situation has not changed utterly,
at least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be frank, he looks really bad. He has such bags under his
eyes,'' said Tatyana Levitskaya, 53, a gynecologist. ``But
everybody felt better after watching him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Levitskaya admits that she alone among her family and
friends does not criticize the president. But she said they shared
her relief Friday night. ``We need stability. He is our
stability,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Like other savvy Russians, she saw his meeting Friday with
political leaders including Mayor Yuri Luzhkov of Moscow, as a sign
that the president was regrouping his political forces to do battle
with an emboldened Communist opposition. ``Yeltsin is saying,
`Don't play around, boys _ I am still here,''' said Mrs.
Levitskaya.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin emphatically rebutted rumors that he will resign before
the end of his term in 2000, while the more pertinent question
about his willingness to cede some of his constitutional authority
didn't come up.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the same man who two weeks ago said that he would
not allow the ruble to be devalued and that he would stand by his
young embattled prime minister, Sergei Kiriyenko. With the ruble
now down by almost 100 percent, and Kiriyenko looking for a new
job, few Russians at this point are ready to take Yeltsin's word at
face value about anything, including resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors that he will step down soon after his new prime minister
and political heir, Chernomyrdin, is confirmed by the parliament
next week, continue apace, breaking down into elaborate and
conflicting scenarios about how the succession will take place.
</P>
<P>
   Another, complementary rumor holds that Yeltsin suffered a
stroke in recent weeks. If true, this is unlikely to be confirmed
as long as he is in office. But whatever the official health
bulletins may say, the president did not look well Friday night,
certainly not as well as most 67-year-olds who have just returned
to work after a five-week vacation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Russians have gotten used to their president's enfeebled state,
and they cringe when he is shown on television pounding his fists
or breaking into what Radzikhovsky described as ``that silly
smile.'' He is reportedly deaf in one ear, but that doesn't explain
his inability at times to grasp the questions put to him during his
rare encounters with the press.
</P>
<P>
   His reputation for gaffes and misstatements is such that when
Pavel Voshchanov, his former press secretary, watched him on
television Friday night, he thought it wasn't as bad as it might
have been. ``He didn't say anything strange or wild, on the one
hand,'' said Voshchanov. ``On the other hand, his condition is not
good. And there is nobody left around him who knows how to put him
in shape.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been other times when Yeltsin has been sick or
absent, or both. And each time he has been able to bounce back
sufficiently to take command and swing events his way. Although
Yeltsin watchers say that he hasn't worked more than a few hours a
day for much of this year, he made a good show last April, rallying
support for Kiriyenko's confirmation and lending his weight to the
government's appeals for international monetary relief.
</P>
<P>
   But this time may be different. By ruling himself out of the
running in the next presidential elections, Yeltsin on Friday night
officially became a lame duck _ not a comfortable position for any
Russian leader, even one in the best of health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
