<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-CAPE-RABIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPE COD SAID RABIES FREE AFTER 5-YEAR WILDLIFE PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOURNE, Mass. _ Five years after the state began dropping
vaccine-laced raccoon bait from the sky by helicopter, officials
Friday declared the Cape and Islands free of the dangerous disease.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the pilot program, which has been expanded to
include other towns in southeastern Massachusetts, comes at a time
when rabies is making a rebound in the Bay State. Raccoon-strain
rabies, by far the most common in the state, entered Massachusetts
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, more than 2,500 animals have tested positive for
rabies in areas throughout the state _ except for the area in the
pilot program. Rabies in humans is fatal unless treated quickly
with injections. House pets, mostly dogs and cats, are the usual
bridge between rabies-infected wild animals and humans.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alison Robbins, a Tufts veterinarian who helps direct the
pilot program, said Massachusetts has the oldest and most
successful rabies eradication program in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we continue to expand the rabies-free zone in our state, we
are proactively sharing our knowledge and experience with our
colleagues in at least seven other states, Canada, France, Belgium,
and other nations,'' Robbins said.
</P>
<P>
   In the pilot program, oral vaccines placed inside baits made
with fishmeal are scatterred on the ground for raccoons to find.
</P>
<P>
   ``The oral vaccine program has exceeded all our expectations,''
said Dr. Alfred DeMaria, director of the bureau of communicable
disease control for the state Department of Public Health, which
runs the program, along with Tufts University's School of
Veterinary Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public health benefits to people living or spending time
on Cape Cod are unquestionable,'' DeMaria said in a Bourne news
conference Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The program has been expanded beyond Cape Cod to include
Plymouth and Wareham and about half of Carver. As more funds become
available, officials plan to continue expanding the vaccination
program north and west.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot program costs about $100,000 per year, but could save
public health money in the long run, DeMaria said. In 1995, he
said, the state spent between $4 million and $5 million to treat
people exposed to rabies. Each series of human vaccinations costs
about $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an ideal world, we'd like to get the other New England
states involved, so we could start working in concentric circles
and eventually have all of New England covered,'' said Dr. Steven
Powell, director of the division of laboratories at Tufts
Veterinary School and a principal investigator for the pilot
program. ``But that all is dependent on the funding situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Public health officials say there is a greater sense of urgency
to find ways to combat rabies, because the disease is making a
strong comeback in Massachusetts. In 1995, at the height of the
previous epidemic, about 2,700 people in the state were vaccinated
for exposure to rabies. Deaths are rare; nationwide, one or two
persons die each year from rabies, on average.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1996 and 1997, the number of new cases of animal rabies
in Massachusetts more than doubled, from 115 to 282. The evidence
this year shows a continued increase. July and August are peak
months for new cases, state health officials say.
</P>
<P>
   In the pilot program, the vaccine-containing bait is distributed
in the fall and spring over about 170 square miles on the mainland
side of the Cape Cod Canal. State Police provide helicopters for
spreading the pellets over half the zone, especially in sparsely
developed areas, while in the rest of the zone the bait is strewn
by hand along roadsides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
