<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8234 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STORMS-COX     08-28 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bowing out with a flourish, Bonnie flogs Virginia coast
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIRGINIA BEACH, VA. _ John Fuller could talk only as long as his
cigarette lasted Friday afternoon, then it was back to work. The
chief engineer at the Holiday Inn on Atlantic Avenue, Fuller had to
deal with a torn roof and sea-soaked rooms, thanks to a
surprisingly powerful visit from Hurricane Bonnie, the storm that
just wouldn't quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't see anything. It was just sheets of rain between
the buildings,'' Fuller said, describing Thursday's late night
re-emergence by Bonnie.
</P>
<P>
   The storm had been downgraded to a tropical storm after smacking
North Carolina's Outer Banks earlier Thursday but, refusing
demotion, bashed the Hampton Roads area with an unexpected punch
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Gusts in Virginia from Bonnie hit 80-90 mph. The name on the
marquee of the The Oceanfront Inn was reduced to ``nt Inn.'' A
jagged shard of plastic and a gaping hole were all that was left of
the part of the sign that displayed ``The Oceanfro.''
</P>
<P>
   Winds late Thursday pushed a tidal surge over the beach
boardwalk in places flooding some hotel rooms and lobbies. Bits of
sand, seaweed and gravel were strewn along Atlantic Avenue,
adjacent to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   The wind also snapped mooring lines holding two ships to piers
in Norfolk. One ship broke free, but tugs were able to secure both
ships back in their berths
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to North Carolinians, who evacuated coastal areas
Tuesday and said Bonnie was more bluster than bite, residents of
southeastern Virginia felt lulled into security.
</P>
<P>
   ``People let their guard down,'' said contractor Chuck Arthur,
supervising a 65-ton crane used to lift pavers up to the Holiday
Inn's damaged rubber roof. ``I believe everybody was surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   But not disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Her Sony Handycam rolling, Maria Boyd captured every moment of
Friday's aftermath: gray overcast, thundering surf, damaged
buildings, 30-mph winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was up all night. I love this weather,'' said Boyd. Standing
on the boardwalk Thursday night ``was like being in a tornado,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd's mother-in-law is named Bonnie, whom she compared to the
storm: ``You never know what she's going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie also surprised some inland residents of eastern North
Carolina, who waited and waited before finally getting walloped
late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wondered, Where is it?'' said Will Starman, a boat salesman
from Camden, N.C., in the northeastern corner of the state. ``There
was absolutely nothing happening. And then all of a sudden, it hit.
And when it did, the rain fell in two or three different
directions. It was weird.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Starman couldn't take his normal work route to the
Edenton Marina on the Albemarle Sound because water blocked a
causeway in Elizabeth City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were of the opinion that it was going to hit us dead on _
and then it stalled,'' Starman said.
</P>
<P>
   Tree branches and leaves on U.S. 17 from North Carolina into
Virginia increased in frequency to the north. In Chesapeake, Va.,
police directed traffic on highways where electrical outages killed
traffic lights.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia Beach visitors center operated Friday in the dark
without power. The only clue that it was open was a box of maps
that held the glass doors ajar. Attendant Reggie Stevenson said the
handful of tourists who came in were curious. ``People are
interested to see what Bonnie has done,'' he said. ``They do
understand the circumstances, that there's going to be some
limitations.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourists made the best of it. When power went out at the
oceanfront Holiday Inn at 7 p.m. Thursday, guests gathered in the
lobby where a generator kept lights aglow.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were in good spirits,'' said Fuller, the hotel engineer.
``They had a hurricane party, drinking beer and wine.''
</P>
<P>
   By 2 p.m. Friday, the overcast cleared, the winds slacked off
and a hot sun beat down on the beach. There are more than 140
hotels on the beach with 11,000 rooms, and even though evacuations
were only voluntary, the storm threat reduced reservations by at
least 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the first places to get power back was the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the city's money here,'' said Fuller, motioning his
cigarette toward the hubbub of hotels and restaurants on Atlantic
Avenue. ``They watch out for the oceanfront.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
