<SLUG> BC-MARKET-SAFETY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS SEEK SAFE HAVEN IN MARKET SCARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The phone on investment adviser Susan Kaplan's desk has been
ringing off the hook amid this week's scary plunge in stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   But Kaplan's clients aren't directing her to unload their shares
while they're still worth something. Instead, they're forking over
more money, telling her to buy, buy, buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been an avalanche of people with new money who want to
invest in stocks they couldn't afford before,'' said Kaplan,
president of Kaplan Financial Services in Wellesley, Mass.
``They're saying, `I want to buy Microsoft, or I want to buy Intel,
so put the money in my account and when you think things have
settled down, buy it for me.'''
</P>
<P>
   This week's stock market drop, while admittedly nerve-wracking,
is actually a great buying opportunity, even for the most skittish
of investors, say financial planners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of it this way: stocks are on sale now,'' said Roy
Komack, president of Komack Management Services Inc. of Natick.
</P>
<P>
   But such advice only works if you've got extra cash lying
around. If you don't, financial planners say there are still things
you can do to minimize your losses in today's volatile market
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you need cash soon _ say, for a downpayment on a house in
the next year or two _ the best advice is to sit tight, planners
agree. Playing the stock market is a long-term investment strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing people can do, when things get scary enough
and the markets have been down for a while, is to sell and put
their money in the bank,'' Komack said.
</P>
<P>
   That's because often the stock market rebounds as quickly as it
tanked.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to get out too late, but much worse, they tend to
get back in too late, too,'' agreed Kaplan.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason to stay in the stock market, some advisers say,
is that most of the logical investment alternatives _ bonds or
money market accounts _ aren't as attractive as they were during
previous stock market downturns because interest rates have
remained relatively low.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to escape the market, will you logically put
your money into something that's not going to grow more than 5 1/2
percent?'' said Robert Siefert, a principal at Back Bay Financial
Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But that decision depends on whether you believe interest rates
will fall further. That's because bond prices are tied to
interest-rate fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a stock, which represents ownership in a company, a bond
is an IOU _ a promise from a government or corporation to repay
money borrowed from the investor at a particular interest rate over
a specified period of time.
</P>
<P>
   If, sometime down the road, a bond is paying more interest than
generally available elsewhere, investors will be willing to pay
more to own it. But if the bond is paying less than prevailing
interest rates, investors will typically put their money elsewhere,
and the price of the bond sinks.
</P>
<P>
   Pran Tiku, president of Peak Financial Management in Wellesley,
is among those who think interest rates will fall soon. So he's
recommending that investors who are nervous about staying in the
stock market buy bonds instead, particularly three- to five-year US
Treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very bullish on bonds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If you do decide to ride out the stock market, Siefert suggests
you use the downturn as an opportunity rebalance your portfolio of
stocks and mutual funds in accordance with your original investment
goals.
</P>
<P>
   That's fairly straight-forward advice for people who own
retirement accounts, because there aren't any tax implications. Now
is the time, for instance, Siefert said, to load up on stocks in
categories that have been hard-hit by the recent volatility, such
as small US companies and those in emerging foreign markets, which
he believes are still valid investments.
</P>
<P>
   It's a little trickier, Siefert said, for investors who own
taxable portfolios. But investors would be wise to sell those
stocks or mutual funds that are now worth less than when they
bought them, so they can lock in a tax loss on the investment for
the year. But instead of parking the proceeds of the sale in a bank
until the market recovers, they should plow the money back into a
comparable small company fund that's bargain-priced, Siefert said.
</P>
<P>
   With this strategy, investors can take advantage of a tax
benefit, without losing the opportunity to ride the stock market
back up.
</P>
<P>
   People who rely on cash distributions from their investments for
living expenses should also think twice about selling shares to
replenish the cash balances in their portfolios, Siefert warned.
That's because they would be selling into a depressed market and
wouldn't get the same return they might otherwise get if they
waited for the market to rebound.
</P>
<P>
   The only good reason for getting out of the stock market now,
said Kaplan, is if your financial goals have changed.
</P>
<P>
   If you've decided to retire early, for instance, you'll need a
steady stream of income now, so the stock market is not a good
place to have your money, she said. Likewise, if your son-in-law
loses his job and you want to help support your daughter's family,
you also have a greater need for income.
</P>
<P>
   But fear of what the market is going to do next week shouldn't
alter the behavior of long-term investors, Kaplan and other
financial advisers agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Said Tiku, ``If you pick good stocks and hang onto them, there's
a very good opportunity for you to do well in the next three to
five years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
