<SLUG> BC-MARKET-SMALL-INVESTORS-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL INVESTORS STAY THE COURSE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mo., N.J., N.Y.)  (jw) 
 BY JAMES BARRON AND DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only way Dunstan Connell could have been more emphatic would
have been if he had borrowed Alfred E. Neuman's shibboleth from Mad
magazine: ``What, me worry?''
</P>
<P>
   ``This?'' Connell, a clerk for Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. who works at
the New York Stock Exchange, said as the Dow Jones industrial
average was seesawing Friday between a gain and a loss. ``It's not
a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   He enumerated the milestones of his 15-year career. ``I was down
here for the crash,'' he said, as everyone on Wall Street refers to
Oct. 19, 1987, when the Dow plunged 508 points, or 22 percent. ``I
was down here last year,'' when the Dow fell 554.26 points, or 7.2
percent, on Oct. 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been through this before,'' he said. ``Even Thursday
wasn't that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   From the fashion industry's workrooms on Seventh Avenue to the
exercise bicycles in private midtown clubs to the carpeted waiting
rooms in storefront brokerage offices, New Yorkers watched as the
markets dipped and climbed and dipped again Friday. By the time the
Dow finally settled at 8051.68 _ down 114.31 points, or 1.4 percent
_ most still seemed unworried by Wall Street's sudden turn toward
bear market territory.
</P>
<P>
   Like millions of other American investors who have ridden the
stock market like a roller-coaster the last few years, investors
and stock market employees interviewed during the day acknowledged
some queasiness about where the market was headed _ if not now,
then next week. But no one seemed to be using the p-word.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see anybody panicking,'' said Dean Rasi, a clerk at
the New York Stock Exchange. ``Some brokers are having a hard time.
I hear them talking. You can hear guys go, `This is killing me,
this is killing me,' trying to rush their orders.''
</P>
<P>
   Other stock exchange workers reported hearing an unaccustomed
edginess in brokers' voices, an unfamiliar uncertainty. But many
small investors still sounded confident. Some said they had shifted
their money into cash or money market funds, but most said they
were not selling out. Not yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've inherited a lot of my stocks, and if you inherit blue
chips, you hang onto them,'' Anne Murphy, a costume designer, said,
smiling brightly in Bryant Park in New York City. ``I figure it's
all going to balance out. We went up so much last year, so if it
went back to where it was a year ago that wouldn't be so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Banks, an engineer in St. Louis who specializes in
high-definition television sets, was even more upbeat. Despite the
economic meltdown in Russia and the tremors in Asia, he said the
stock market was still a healthy outpost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not all that concerned,'' he said Friday afternoon, when
the Dow was down about 61 points. ``Right now, our economy is
strong. The rest of the world looks to us, so you have to be
careful of knee-jerk reactions.''
</P>
<P>
   Staying the course has been a motto for many small investors
throughout the long bull market of the 1990s, which many Wall
Street analysts date to October 1990. It was the small investors
who ``bought the dips.'' They went bargain-hunting. They ignored
all the noise about Asia and currency collapses. After all, last
October's 13.2 percent drop in the Dow, the worst in the 1990s, was
followed by a 30 percent rally.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Soriano of Trenton, N.J., who gave up managing health
clubs to manage his portfolio from home, was convinced that pattern
was still intact. ``It can only go up,'' he said. ``It will go
down, but in the long term it's always gone up.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But on Friday he was selling. ``I'm in front of my computer
right now, trying to get out of stuff,'' he said. ``I'm ready to
jump off the Empire State Building, but they don't do that
anymore,'' he added with a chuckle. ``My net worth is down 50
percent in the last few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Soriano said he was ``not trading money I need.'' He also said
he had started to put aside cash as a cushion if prices tumble more
than they already have.
</P>
<P>
   Like Soriano, millions of other investors are more attuned than
ever to the stock market's every gyration. Labor officials talk
about how even union halls have big-screen television sets tuned to
CNBC and how the buzz in the room stops as the closing bell nears.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps nothing has brought the market closer to small
investors than the Internet. Omar Wasow, who monitors online chat
rooms for MSNBC, said the chatter remained almost universally
optimistic about the market's long-term prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really astonished, given the leading, critical questions
I asked, that people were not concerned,'' Wasow said. ``One person
I talked to said you've got to be in it for the long term, and that
sort of echoed the general consensus.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those in one Internet chat room Wasow plugged into was
someone identified as Crabtown, who said that baby boomers could
sustain the stock market through 2005, when boomers begin to retire
and cash in their holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Crabtown, with the characteristic bravado of the '90s investor,
predicted that the Dow would hit 15,000 before then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
