<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8246 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV     08-28 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET WATCH: LOOKING FOR THE BANKS' RUSSIAN WRECKAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Losses, losses, who's got the losses?
</P>
<P>
   That is the parlor game for investors and traders as they try to
plumb the damage sustained by American financial institutions from
the mess in Russia. That nation's devaluation and de facto default
on its debt Tuesday roiled markets worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   While a few domestic banks came clean late last week about their
Russian exposure _ Republic New York with a $110 million loss,
BankAmerica with $220 million and BankBoston with $10 million _ the
silence from many other financial institutions is deafening.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean that it's safe to go back into the water and
scoop up some of battered financial services stocks? No way.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with the increasingly complex financial transactions
that have become routine at banks around the world today is that
when disaster strikes, it takes an inordinate amount of time to
track down whether the institution on the other side of the trade
is still standing, let alone solvent. If history is any guide,
complete information about these transactions may not trickle out
for months.
</P>
<P>
   This is not what investors have come to expect in a wired world.
But it happened with the losses taken by banks in Asia following
the devaluation of the Thai baht in July 1997 and is likely to
happen again after the Russia disaster. ``The disclosures started
coming in Southeast Asia in third-quarter earnings reports and
fourth-quarter regulatory filings,'' said Paul Spraos, publisher of
Swaps Monitor, a derivatives industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Among the stickiest parts of this mess are billions of dollars
in foreign currency transactions entered into by Western banks and
hedge funds with Russian banks. As these hedge funds bought
ruble-denominated Russian bonds, they needed to offset their risk
that the ruble might fall. So when they bought their bonds, they
sold contracts covering an equivalent amount of rubles and maturing
when their bonds did. That way they bore no currency risk while
awaiting return of their principal. Or so they thought.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 17, the Russian Central Bank announced a 90-day
moratorium on all payments due from Russian banks; included were an
estimated $50 billion owed on foreign currency contracts, called
forwards. Many of the Russian banks on the other side of the
currency trades are not expected to reopen after the freeze.
</P>
<P>
   Combine this with the radical restructuring of Russian debt, in
which investors are getting roughly 10 cents on the dollar for
their holdings, and the losses begin to pile up. Hedge funds, which
borrowed money to buy debt, were the biggest losers.
</P>
<P>
   Don't cry for these guys. They are hardened speculators known
for big gambles.
</P>
<P>
   What is amazing is that banks, which should know how to conduct
due diligence on institutions they do business with, were willing
to enter into contracts with dubious Russian banks. Many are not
much more than piggy banks for the Russian organizations they are a
part of. National Reserve Bank, for instance, is linked with
Gazprom, the big natural-gas producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard investors were trying to hedge with Russian
banks, I thought they were off their rockers,'' said David Riley, a
director at Fitch IBCA, a credit-rating agency in London. ``The
first-tier banks are dreadful and the second tier, awful.'' When
this is over, he predicted, ``a forward with a Russian bank won't
be worth the paper it's printed on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0315 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8247 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-WEEK-ART-$ADV30-N     08-28 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-WEEK-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK IN BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 30)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUSSIA: The Ruble Takes a Beating
</P>
<P>
   With Russia's economy shaken after the government suspended debt
payments, and President Boris Yeltsin under pressure to cede some
of his powers, investors were quick to sell Russian shares and try
to exchange rubles for stronger currencies. As a result, the
central bank suspended foreign-exchange trading Thursday. A
security officer posted a notice at an exchange office in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS: A Global Unraveling
</P>
<P>
   Stock market investors around the world rushed to sell,
frightened by economic problems in Russia and Asia. Thursday, the
worst trading day of the year, the Dow Jones industrial average
fell 4.19 percent, or 357.36 points, to close at 8,165.99, some
12.5 percent below its July 17 high of 9,337.97. Investors are well
into what Wall Street calls a correction. And a bear market _
defined as a price decline of 15 to 20 percent _ appeared to be at
hand. The Dow ended the week at 8,01.68, down 481.97 points, and
the Nasdaq composite fell 157.93 points, to 1,639.68. The rate on
the 30-year Treasury bond fell to 5.34 percent, the lowest
long-term yield in three decades.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT: Was Intel Bullied?
</P>
<P>
   In its continuing antitrust investigation of Microsoft, the
government is looking into whether the company used its market
muscle to force Intel, its only real peer, to shelve new-technology
efforts that conflicted with Microsoft's ambitions. Federal and
state investigators were said to have taken depositions from key
Intel employees, including chairman Andrew Grove, left. Microsoft
contends that the investigators are trying to portray routine
business meetings as attempts to forge an anti-competitive
conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRAFT: Clipping Boeing's Wings
</P>
<P>
   British Airways, long loyal to Boeing, ordered as many as 188
short-haul, single-aisle jets worth $8.5 billion from Boeing's
rival, Airbus Industrie, the European aircraft consortium. The
order is expected to assure 38,000 British jobs at factories of
Rolls-Royce PLC, the jet engine maker, and British Aerospace, one
of the four partners in the Airbus group. British Airways, Europe's
largest carrier, also announced that it would buy 16 new Boeing
777-200 jets, with an option for 16 more, for a total of $4.8
billion, but said that it was canceling previous orders for 5 of 15
larger and more expensive Boeing 747-400s, as well as options on 7
others.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN, SACHS: A Money Machine
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., officially registering to end its
partnership and go public in November, confirmed what Wall Street
had long known: It is obsessively secretive and phenomenally
profitable. In a filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, the firm disclosed that earnings had grown at a 15
percent compound annual growth rate over 15 years, to $3 billion in
1997. It also reported a pretax return on partners' capital that
exceeded 60 percent in its best years. But the firm was vague on
what it intended to do with the capital it raises _ it is earmarked
for ``general corporate purposes'' _ and left many blanks in its
prospectus, presumably to be filled in at the last possible moment
in October.
</P>
<P>
   OIL: Betting on a Comeback
</P>
<P>
   Venturing into a field littered with failure, Hicks, Muse, Tate
&AMP; Furst, the leveraged-buyout firm in Dallas, agreed to pay $250
million for a 62 percent stake in Coho Energy, an oil exploration
and production company. The deal, while modest, signals a bet that
the long-suffering oil industry is ready for a comeback. Another
indication came at the latest federal auction of offshore oil
leases in the western Gulf of Mexico. The average high bid, $1.37
million, was sharply higher than the $766,417 average of a year
earlier. A rig for Shell Oil is towed into place in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   DEALS: A New King of Radio
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Media said it planned to buy Capstar Broadcasting for
$2.3 billion in stock and to assume nearly $1.8 billion in debt,
surpassing CBS as the nation's largest chain of radio stations.
CBS, seeking to bolster its sagging stock price, said it planned to
spin off up to 20 percent of its radio and outdoor advertising
businesses in an initial public offering. . . . Marsh &AMP; McLennan
agreed to buy the Sedgwick Group of London, the largest independent
insurance broker in Europe, for $2.05 billion in cash. . . . Adobe
Systems rejected an unsolicited offer from Quark Inc.
</P>
<P>
   THE ECONOMY: Persistent Strength
</P>
<P>
   Despite a strike against General Motors and a slowing of exports
to Asia, the economy grew at a faster-than-expected annual rate of
1.6 percent in the second quarter, the Commerce Department
reported. That was still well below the 5.5 percent growth rate of
the first quarter. . . . Orders for durable goods unexpectedly rose
a healthy 2.4 percent in July, the department said. . . . Consumer
confidence slipped in August, the Conference Board reported, to an
index reading of 133.1, down from 137.2 in July. The 30-year peak
was 138.2, reached in June.
</P>
<P>
   LAYOFFS: More Pink Slips
</P>
<P>
   For workers at several companies, however, the economy does not
look so healthy. Northrop Grumman said it planned to reduce its
work force by 8,000 people, or 15 percent, by the end of 2000 to
remain an independent and competitive aerospace company. . . .
Harnischfeger Industries, reporting a wider-than-expected quarterly
loss, said it would eliminate about 3,100 jobs, or 20 percent of
its workers, because of a glut of paper and weakening demand. . . .
Applied Materials, citing a downturn in the global semiconductor
industry, said it would cut 2,000 jobs, or 15 percent of its work
force, mostly in Santa Clara, Calif., and Austin, Texas, and would
shave executive salaries by 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   PARTING SHOTS: An Outspoken Director
</P>
<P>
   Breaking the customary code of silence, Agnes Varis, above, quit
the board of Copley Pharmaceutical Inc., accusing Hoechst AG, the
German conglomerate that bought a majority stake in Copley in 1992,
of mismanaging the company, whose stock has been battered. ``They
look for directors that are `parsley on the fish,' '' Ms. Varis
said, describing the trivial role that, she contended, Hoechst's
executives expected outside directors to play. She added that she
would not abandon Copley, but would ``join the ranks of other
concerned shareholders'' in trying to restore value.
</P>
<P>
   ORANGE COUNTY: Merrill to Pay $2 Million
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. agreed to settle SEC charges that it failed
to disclose to buyers of the Orange County, Calif., bonds that it
was underwriting important information it had about the country's
precarious finances. The $2 million settlement stemmed from one of
a long-running series of legal actions that arose from the firm's
dual role as underwriter and investment adviser to the county. . .
. A federal judge ordered Trans Union Corp., one of the nation's
largest credit bureaus, to stop selling detailed credit information
about consumers to advertisers and marketers without the subjects'
consent. The company said it would appeal. . . . Merck and its
Merck-Medco Managed Care unit agreed with the FTC to bar Medco from
discriminating against drugs made by Merck's competitors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
