<HEADLINE>
NEW TOOL TO HELP WOMEN IN 40S WEIGH MAMMOGRAM RISK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women in their 40s confused by the bitter and complex debate
over the value of routine mammograms for their age group were given
a new tool Friday to calculate their personal cancer risk and guide
them toward a decision.
</P>
<P>
   The tool is a formula for determining whether a 40-something
woman has a high enough risk of breast cancer to justify undergoing
the screening X-rays yearly in an effort to detect tumors early.
</P>
<P>
   In general, women in their 40s have a very low risk of breast
cancer _ though the risk grows steeply over the course of that
decade.
</P>
<P>
   The new method, devised by National Cancer Institute scientists,
is the first to provide women in this age group and their doctors
with a relatively simple scheme for sorting through the welter of
confusing factors that weigh for or against routine mammography.
</P>
<P>
   Although many women and their doctors currently try to think
through these factors on their own, the new tool should help
clarify the decision ``for the large proportion of women who either
underestimate or overestimate their risk,'' said an NCI statement.
</P>
<P>
   Several major health organizations and agencies now favor
routine breast X-rays for women aged 40-49, and many women feel
strongly they want the screening. But some groups continue to argue
the small number of cancers detected early doesn't justify the
costs and the frequent ``false-positive'' results leading to
unnecessary further exams, surgical biopsies, anxiety and cost.
</P>
<P>
   The process designed by Dr. Mitchell Gail and Barbara Rimer of
the NCI is aimed at singling out those women in their 40s who,
because of their medical history and other risk factors, have at
least as much chance of developing breast cancer as a woman in her
50s with no other risk factors. By age 50, there's no dispute that
all women are at high enough risk to warrant annual mammograms.
</P>
<P>
   In a paper published in the current issue of the Journal of
Clinical Oncology, the authors say that following their scheme
would lead to an estimated 10 percent of white women age 40
undergoing yearly screening. The proportion would rise to 95
percent at age 49. For black women, it would be 16 percent at age
40 and 95 percent at age 49.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't disagree with general recommendations that screening
is beneficial for women in their 40s,'' said Gail, an NCI
biostatistician, in a telephone interview. ``But I think this may
be helpful in allowing women to put their own risks into
perspective and relate them to those of women for whom there's no
doubt'' that routine mammography pays off, by catching breast
cancers at an early, treatable stage.
</P>
<P>
   The NCI and the American Cancer Society have endorsed yearly
screening for women in their 40s. However, a panel sponsored by the
National Institutes of health concluded in 1997 that the data from
a number of studies ``did not warrant a single recommendation for
all women in their 40s.'' Nor has the US Preventive Services Task
Force, a panel reporting to the Department of Health and Human
Services, recommended routine mammograms at that age.
</P>
<P>
   A physician at Harvard Vanguard Medical Associates who is not in
favor of mammograms for all women in their 40s hailed the
development of the risk-assessment method.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any method that helps clarify clinical risk to patients will
help patients make better decisions for themselves,'' said Dr. Mary
Burton, an internist at the group's Copley Center. She said Harvard
Vanguard recommends a mammogram every two years for women in their
40s.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Eric Winer, director of the breast oncology center at
Dana-Farber Cancer Institute in Boston, called the paper ``very
interesting'' and helpful because it highlights the fact that ``all
40-to-49-year-old women are not alike'' in their cancer risk.
</P>
<P>
   But Winer questioned whether the method would become widely
used. For one thing, he said, ``there's still an incredible amount
of emotion involved in this issue'' that could sway many women,
regardless of the outcome of a more-rationally based method for
decision making.
</P>
<P>
   The paper offers two versions of the method. One, the
``exact-age procedure,'' relies on a table giving a risk value for
each year of age between 40 and 50. The other ``grouped-age
procedure'' provides one flow chart for women 40-44 and a second
for women 45-49.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, a woman first checks a table of ``strong'' risk
factors, any one of which should prompt regular screening. The six
risk factors are: previous breast cancer; having a breast cancer
gene such as BRCA1 or BRCA2; a mother, sister or daughter with
breast cancer history; atypical hyperplasia (abnormal cells) found
in a previous biopsy; 75 percent or more dense breast tissue on a
mammogram if the woman is 45-49 years; two or more breast biopsies
in the past, even if no cancer was found.
</P>
<P>
   If she has none of these risk factors, the woman turns to a
table of weaker one _ her age when she began menstruating, the
number of previous biopsies (zero or one), and her age when first
gave birth, if she has children. The values from this table,
combined with her age, yield the woman's risk of developing breast
cancer in the next year relative to the risk of a 50-year-old woman
with no risk factors.
</P>
<P>
   Gail acknowledged that some women are willing to accept a lot of
inconvenience, anxiety and needless followup procedures for even a
small chance of catching a tumor early. ``A lot depends on the
particular values and mindset of the woman, and ths (the formula)
is just one part of the individual's decision,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
