<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-MARKETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER DAY OF UNCERTAINTY FOR EUROPEAN MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MARKET, JAPAN-ECON, HONGKONG-ECON) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The economic uncertainty in Russia and its reverberations
in emerging markets around the globe continued to rattle European
stock markets Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The only gains in Europe appeared to come from traders vacating
short positions for the weekend. In shorting a stock, traders
borrow shares from a broker for a fee and sell them. They hope to
replace the shares by buying them at a lower price and pocketing
the difference as profit.
</P>
<P>
   Indexes in the region fell about 2 percent after rallying from
sharp drops of up to 5 percent earlier in the day. The London Stock
Exchange, Europe's largest, led the downward slide, plummeting 2.2
percent to a seven-month low, while Frankfurt closed down 1.7
percent after suffering losses of up to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fledgling stock markets in Eastern Europe were also swept by a
wave of selling as the uncertainty in Russia cast a shadow over the
prospects of businesses in Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic
that continue to trade with Russia; food-processing and
pharmaceutical companies were particularly hard hit. The Prague
exchange lost ground, and stock indexes in Warsaw and Budapest fell
to their lowest level since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In Spain, the plummet in share prices showed the effects of
collapsing stock prices in Latin America, where Spanish banks and
corporations have invested heavily in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The Madrid exchange closed down 2.3 percent, pushing Spanish
share prices to a weekly decline of almost 20 percent as investors
fled companies that they feared were particularly exposed in Latin
America, including banks like Banco Santander and Banco Bilbao
Vizcaya, but also the telecommunications giant Telefonica.
</P>
<P>
   Aysha Zaman, European equity strategist at BT Alex. Brown in
London, said the main forces behind the European selloff were
inflated share prices, which in late July were averaging about 22
times earnings, and unrealistic expectations for growth, given the
uncertainties of the Asian and Russian crises.
</P>
<P>
   The deepening crisis in Russia is accelerating the tailspin.
</P>
<P>
   While the first phase of Europe's adjustment in early August hit
banks and corporations exposed to Asia, like Paribas and Societe
Generale of France, the financial turmoil in Russia is determining
which shares are being hurt now. In Germany, the big losers have
been Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank and automakers like
Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss banks with Russian exposure, like Credit Suisse, have also
suffered, but so has UBS, despite its limited exposure in Eastern
Europe; UBS became Europe's largest bank last year after the merger
of Union Bank of Switzerland and Swiss Bank Corp. By contrast,
German chemical companies like Bayer AG and Henkel, which had steep
drops in their share prices earlier in the week, benefited from a
wave of buying Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of lowered growth expectations were felt in Britain,
where a recent surge in the value of the pound added to concerns
about the outlook for export-oriented companies, like GKN PLC, the
maker of helicopters and auto parts; the shares of GKN plummeted
more than 6 percent Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts said that as long as hedge funds and other money
managers who have big losses in places like Russia continued
selling to raise cash, a general liquidity tightness would cause
European exchanges to slide even further.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zaman said the current selloff might be stopped, or at least
slowed, if major central banks like the U.S. Federal Reserve or the
Bundesbank took steps to increase market liquidity. Even that,
however, would have only a temporary staying effect, she said, at
least until it becomes clear what long-range effects for European
economies the crises in Russia and East Asia will bring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very bearish,'' she said. ``We expect the adjustment
will go further.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
