<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ASIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETS IN ASIA TUMBLE TO LOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Panic over Wall Street's slump and nosediving
economies worldwide reverberated through Asia Friday, dragging
already depressed markets to historic lows and fueling fears of a
feedback effect on exchanges from New York to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the decline was the world's second largest economy, as
Japan's Nikkei index plunged to a 12-year low. Shares in Malaysia
and Singapore hit 10-year lows, while the Philippine stock market
closed at a 6 1/2-year bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Fending off a decline here, the Hong Kong government intervened
massively in the local market Friday, spending several billion
dollars to prop up blue-chip stocks and punish speculators who had
bet share prices would fall.
</P>
<P>
   The drastic intervention in a famously free market capped two
weeks of flurried stock buying by the government, bringing to a
crescendo a debate over whether supporting shares is beneficial or
foolhardy. Analysts Friday said the government cannot afford to
prop up the market much longer, and predicted a crashing correction
in the week or month ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to its woes, Hong Kong officially entered recession
Friday, joining other once-invincible powerhouses like Japan and
South Korea. The gross domestic product shrank for the second
consecutive quarter, this time by 5 percent _ a far cry from 5.3
percent growth last year. Economists Friday predicted Hong Kong
would not recover until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   With every major Asian market down, it was a grim day across the
region that dominated global economic growth for the last decade _
and which now is fueling market corrections worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   But it is perhaps more in Hong Kong than anywhere else in Asia
that market watchers are tensely awaiting next week's trading. The
coming days will test whether the government can prop up the market
and the Hong Kong dollar, one of the only Asian currencies that has
retained its value in the last year. If the Hong Kong dollar
devalues, it would destroy both wealth and confidence here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hong Kong has had a crash, but it's nothing like it will be if
the Hong Kong dollar or the renminbi (the Chinese currency) go. I
think we'd see worldwide panic on the back of that,'' said Edmund
Bradley, global research director at Credit Lyonnais Securities
Asia. ``The first week of September is going to be a nasty one for
global markets.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Hong Kong government stops intervening in the market,
some analysts say the index could easily lose 1,000 points in a
day, or one-eighth of its value. But if the government continues to
buy blue-chips, it could spend down its reserves too low to defend
its currency against speculative attacks _ the recipe that brought
down Thailand and Indonesia last year. Either way, the government
may have boxed itself and its beleagued economy into a corner.
</P>
<P>
   The implications for Asia and beyond are enormous. The
government intervention has angered many who credited this place as
the freest market in the world, and could scare off foreign
institutional investors. It has also prompted long-term individual
buyers to sell off shares and exit the market, a trend that could
delay recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The government buying spree _ estimated by brokers to have cost
between $6.5 billion and $15 billion in taxpayer money so far _ set
a record trading volume Friday of $10.19 billion _ almost twice the
previous record set a year ago. Friday was a key day, because
August futures contracts expired.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind the intervention has been to chase out
speculators _investors who bet against the market _ thereby
lowering interest rates and boosting the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the intervention would be considered manipulation
elsewhere. Defenders counter that short-selling tactics employed by
fund managers here are illegal in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Financial Secretary Donald Tsang said Friday the government is
considering measures to ``tighten up discipline in the areas of
short-selling and stock borrowing,'' fueling concerns that market
controls might be imposed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, government officials are describing the intervention
that began Aug. 14 and reached a fever pitch Friday as ``a war''
and ``armageddon'' against speculators. But most analysts predict
the scheme will backfire.
</P>
<P>
   The government's ``goal has not been achieved in the least.
Everyone has been leaving the market except for speculators,'' said
Mac Overton, fund manager for MBf Unit Trust Management in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
   A number of countries, including the United Kingdom, Thailand,
Indonesia, Malaysia and Japan, have tried to intervene in their
markets and have failed, he said. A better use of public reserves
would have been to buy mortgages from banks, making them healthier
and better able to loan money.
</P>
<P>
   There are others who are more sympathetic to the government's
position, saying it needed to do something to prevent a collapse of
the market. The Hang Seng index had dropped nearly 60 percent in
the last year, and government buying raised the index 20 percent in
the last two weeks, saving some major companies from
balance-of-payment crises that would imperil banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``People make the mistake of thinking that a free market is the
same as a fair market,'' said Richard Verin, head of equity trading
in Asia for Credit Suisse First Boston. He said big overseas hedge
funds had taken advantage of the Hong Kong market, attacking the
currency and driving up interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   But the risk, he said, is that huge speculators may be too big
an opponent even for the government.
</P>
<P>
   Even many outspoken defenders of the government's intervention
two weeks ago had changed their tune by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't approve of it anymore ... not of the amount of money
they have spent,'' said Jim Mellon, managing director of Regent
Pacific Group, a Hong Kong-based emerging markets fund manager.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong has $97 billion in reserves _ the second-highest in
the world after China's _ but $50 billion of that is set aside to
cover the basic money supply, since the currency is pegged to the
US dollar. Ten billion dollars will be needed to cover this year's
budget deficit, plus another $10 billion for next year's deficit,
Mellon says. He estimates the government had spent at least $6.5
billion by the end of trading Friday, leaving just $23.5 billion of
usable reserves _ a dangerously low figure. (The government has
refused to reveal how much it has spent in the market).
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he predicts, Hong Kong will lose _ not the
speculators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hedge funds are like cockroaches,'' he said. ``You can drown
them, you can crush them, you can stamp them out. But they always
come back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
