<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZENGA SHOWS HIS COACHING SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY, Mass. _ Roles were defined during Walter Zenga's
first practice as coach of the Revolution Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a player with a lot of experience who has a good feeling
with the other players,'' Zenga said. ``As for being a true coach _
he is a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   And Zenga pointed to Sid Mazzola, the former Revolution scout
who is Zenga's assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Zenga is interim head coach of the Revolution. He
took charge at the start the workout at Babson College, postponing
an autograph-signing session with about a dozen youngsters by
saying, ``It is best if the coach is at the practice.''
</P>
<P>
   During the two-hour practice, Zenga held a plastic water bottle
and gave suggestions, especially to the defense. He stopped the
action, showed players how to mark on set pieces, to advance in
unison after a clearance _ just like a real coach.
</P>
<P>
   But Zenga, who retired in December after a 20-year career as a
goalkeeper, barely disguised his intention to return to a playing
role. He wore a Revolution uniform, took part in some drills,
exercised during breaks, joined the others in post-practice corner
kicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of coach will I be?'' Zenga said. ``I play to win,
and the only way to win is to score goals. Or, at least, score one
more goal than the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Zenga will concentrate on defense first. The Revolution
have the worst goals-against record, and the worst record, in the
MLS as they chase tomorrow's opponent, the Miami Fusion, for the
final playoff berth in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, Zenga played for conservative, defensive specialists
such as Giovanni Trapattoni at Inter and Azeglio Vicini with the
national team. Those teams expected to play several games in
succession without surrendering a goal, and seldom gave up more
than two goals in a game. That was a different era, though, and
even Trapattoni is attempting to be progressive at Fiorentina this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have played for great coaches, Trapattoni, Vicini, but every
coach has something to teach,'' Zenga said. ``We want to put a
balanced team on the field. We will trust the players and we will
put the players in the positions they belong. It's not like, I
arrive and everything changes. We have one chance for the playoffs,
and that is to win in Miami. I asked them to believe in that and to
think positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga was unfamiliar with the Fusion, an expansion team which
has rallied recently since Brazilian Ivo Wortmann replaced Cacho
Cordoba as coach. Nor had he settled on a formation for the
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzola, though, has been plotting the Revolution's strategy
since Thomas Rongen resigned as coach Monday, two days after the
Revolution lost, 5-1, to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a last-place team,'' Mazzola said. ``We can beat
Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazzola is used to building teams with limited resources and is
familiar with the local talent since he has coached the
Massachusetts representative in national amateur tournaments. When
Mazzola owned the Boston Bolts from 1988-90, he not only financed
the team but also selected the players and coached them. He had a
31-29 record and guided the Bolts to the American Professional
Soccer League playoffs in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want more variety in players, some with strong technical
qualities, some with speed, some with strength,'' Mazzola said. ``A
team must be built up the middle, with a central defender,
midfielder, and a striker who can play with his back to goal and
hold up the ball for play to develop.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazzola led the team during Wednesday's scrimmage against the
Rhode Island Stingrays, a 1-1 tie.
</P>
<P>
   The players responded with enthusiasm to the new coaching staff
_ even Ian Feuer, whose starting goalkeeping position could be
threatened if Zenga becomes player-coach next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, it couldn't be better for me to have one of the
best goalkeepers in the world as coach,'' Feuer said. ``You can
only learn from that. He's a nice guy with a good sense of humor.
He's had some great coaches and he's learned from them. Ever since
I was a young kid he's been a hero of mine, and I'm not saying that
because he's the coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the prospect of losing his position to the coach
next year, Feuer said: ``I'll battle him for it. I'm not here to be
a reserve keeper. But he's the coach and you have to respect
whatever decision he makes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we have to concentrate now on Sunday. Everyone is
upbeat about it. No disrespect to Thomas, but everyone wants to
work hard to get ready. I know (Zenga) wants to work on getting the
defense tighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwin Gorter will remain at sweeper, next to Brian Dunseth.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Zenga) has traveled the world, he knows soccer,'' Gorter
said. ``He said he is not a magician, he can only give more
stimulus to us. But he ... doesn't have the key to solve all our
problems in one day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
