<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8262 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-725&AMP;ADD-N     08-28 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-U.S.-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON STRESSES IMPORTANCE OF SUMMIT WITH RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Ind.)  (lb) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Speaker of the House Newt Gingrich said Friday that
President Clinton's plans to visit Moscow next week to meet the
beleaguered President Boris Yeltsin were ``imprudent'' and should
be canceled.
</P>
<P>
   While some prominent legislators from both parties urged Clinton
to proceed with the summit meeting, Gingrich added his own
influential voice to those who have criticized the meeting, which
comes in the midst of economic and political upheaval in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are two weak presidents trying to prop each other up,''
Gingrich said in a telephone interview Friday. ``Who knows what
kind of promises they'll make to each other, what they'll agree to?
I think it's very imprudent for him to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton was undeterred, speaking at Martha's Vineyard,
Mass., about the importance of friendship in difficult times, and
vowing to press ahead with the meeting and with an effort to aid
Russia if the new government there did ``the disciplined, hard
things they have to do to reform their country.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending his trip, Clinton said, ``Anybody can come see you
when you're doing well.'' Clinton spoke shortly after Soviet
television broadcast an interview in which a puffy Yeltsin
announced that he would not resign his office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton received support for the summit from Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y., who said that the Indian-Pakistani nuclear
confrontation in South Asia was reason enough for Clinton to go to
Moscow. The Russians could help with the Indians, he said, ``and
we've not had that conversation with the Russians.'' A
collaboration to make South Asia stable ``would cost a lot of money
but it's worth the world,'' Moynihan said. ``That alone would be a
good morning's discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., also said Clinton was right to go.
``To cancel now would be a further blow to what little credibility
Yeltsin has remaining,'' he said. ``The president should obviously
tell Yeltsin to get a grip on his country and recognize that we
can't pour good money after bad without evidence of reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., said that Clinton should stress the
U.S. desire for a prosperous Russia, fully integrated in the world.
``There is a sour mood about Russian in Congress today, principally
because of their missile and nuclear help to Iran,'' Hamilton said.
``We have to engage Russia and build bridges when possible, but
also draw red lines about acceptable behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   In a theme echoed Friday by his national security adviser, Sandy
Berger, Clinton said that the United States had to stand with the
Russian people in their time of difficulty and be willing to help
if the Russians themselves made the hard sacrifices required to get
their house in order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the key political and economic choices are up to the
Russian people themselves,'' Berger said, ``we need to engage
actively, even _ or especially _ in a time of crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton would urge Russians to hold fast ``to the basic
objectives of democracy and economic reform in the face of new
challenges,'' Berger said. ``The Russian people should know that,
particularly in times of difficulty, the United States and the West
will not turn away from cooperation. As they do the things
necessary to restore stability and progress, we are prepared to
support them.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's officials, struggling themselves to prepare for a
summit meeting in a land undergoing a political and economic
earthquake, had encouraging news Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian acting prime minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin, told
Clinton administration officials privately that he had made no deal
with the Russian parliament that would undermine the general course
of economic reform, senior U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Although members of Chernomyrdin's own party were saying
``worrisome things'' about a more Soviet-style state control over
parts of the economy, one U.S. official said, Chernomyrdin ``tells
us he hasn't struck any deal on the policy stuff.'' At least he had
not done so yet, the official acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke after a half-hour conference call among Clinton, Deputy
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, who is in Moscow, and Deputy
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers. Talbott emphasized that
Yeltsin would not resign, that Russian officials of all stripes
wanted Yeltsin to attend the summit, and that the streets were
calm.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``They're not sacking kiosks to get crackers,'' the official
said. ``It's not like Clinton's walking into a maelstrom.''
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin has been negotiating with Russian parliamentary
leaders, including the Communist Party, on a broad economic and
political strategy for recovery. Chernomyrdin, who controls
parliament's second-largest faction, needs wider support to be
confirmed as prime minister, in a vote expected on Monday, as
Clinton leaves Washington for Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   But Chernomyrdin also needs parliament to pass legislation to
reform Russia's tax and pension systems, at least if Moscow expects
the next $4.3 billion of aid from the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Senior officials said they remained deeply concerned that the
Communists would strike a high price, and that Chernomyrdin might
have to give some ground to the call for stricter state controls on
the economy and for more rubles to be printed in order to reflate
industry and pay workers, driving up inflation and further
undermining the value of the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chernomyrdin can go pretty far toward the Communists,'' said
another senior official dealing with Russia. ``We understand that
he needs to stabilize the situation in terms of public reaction. He
needs a coalition. That's the concern: He needs their support and
they'll make him pay for it. But he's a lot smarter than they
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the official said, Washington had no real options.
``We're prepared to be generous in our interpretation of what
Chernomyrdin can put together. But frankly, we don't have any
choice. We don't have any alternatives, nor is anybody asking us
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger conceded that Yeltsin's firing on Friday of reformers
Anatoly Chubais and Boris Nemtsov was ``not encouraging,'' but he
continued to emphasize that the policies of any new government
mattered more than its personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Berger and other officials continued to press their theme of
fundamental Russian responsibility for the country's troubles and
for their solutions. But Summers also emphasized that the IMF would
be prepared to be flexible, depending on the pace of reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has to be put in the context of Russian economic policy,
which is what we're waiting to see,'' Summers said. ``And at this
point, we don't have a Russian economic team; we don't have a
Russian economic plan.''
</P>
<P>
   And Berger said that important foreign-policy and security
issues could still be discussed in Moscow, including nuclear
stockpiles, the protection of fissile material, and Russia's
policies toward Iraq, Iran and Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
