<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-U.S.-SUSPECTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPLAINT AGAINST BOMB SUSPECT SHEDS NEW LIGHT ON BIN LADEN GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government's case against Osama bin
Laden, the wealthy Islamic militant suspected of directing the
bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, emerged in
sharper detail Friday as federal agents brought a second suspect to
New York to face charges in the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The federal charges against the suspect, Mohammed Saddiq Odeh,
were contained in a complaint unsealed Friday in federal court. The
complaint provided a sketch of the global reach and sophisticated
operations of bin Laden's group, Al Qaeda, whose chief objective,
the complaint said, was the killing of Americans, including
civilians, anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   According to the complaint, Odeh played a role in terrorist
actions in Kenya and other countries including Somalia, where he
trained Islamic fighters against United Nations forces, which
included 1,800 U.S. servicemen. He worked in an independent unit
that he said was managed by senior commanders and concealed its
activities through legitimate businesses like a fishing company set
up in Mombassa by Odeh using Al Qaeda money.
</P>
<P>
   The focus on Odeh's relationship to bin Laden's group suggested
that prosecutors hope to persuade the two men in custody in New
York to provide more detailed information about the activities of
bin Laden, who Odeh referred to in his interviews with agents as
the ``emir'' or prince of the terrorist organization.
</P>
<P>
   More detailed information could help prosecutors expand their
charges against bin Laden, who has already been indicted for
terrorist acts committed before the Aug. 7 bombings in Africa and
has emerged as the principal architect and financier of the embassy
attacks. Friday's complaint offered a tentative road map to what
some of those charges might include.
</P>
<P>
   Odeh told federal agents, the complaint said, that he accepted
responsibility for the bombing. But he denied a direct role in the
attack, saying he left Nairobi on Aug. 6, one day before the blast.
Nevertheless, he acknowledged meeting with bin Laden confederates
at a Nairobi hotel and visited the U.S. Embassy grounds three days
before the explosion, which killed 258 people and wounded thousands
of others.
</P>
<P>
   Odeh's lawyer, Jack Sachs, said his client acknowledged
membership in bin Laden's group, but denied knowing that members in
Kenya were planning to bomb the embassy. ``He has stated to being a
member of the organization but he has not admitted to taking part
in any acts,'' Sachs said. ``He didn't confess to doing it. There
was no confession.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Odeh appeared briefly at a hearing in federal court in
Manhattan before U.S. Magistrate Sharon Grubin who ordered him held
in jail pending another hearing Sept. 28.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Odeh were identical to those brought against
another member of bin Laden's organization, Mohamed Rashed Daoud
al-'Owhali, who was brought to New York from Kenya on Thursday
after agents accused him of riding in the bomb-laden truck and
throwing a dummy grenade at an embassy security guard seconds
before the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Odeh was charged with conspiracy to commit murder, use of a
weapon of mass destruction and 12 counts of murder, one count for
each of the Americans killed in the Nairobi bombing. If found
guilty of the charges he could face a maximum sentence of life in
prison or death. Odeh was ordered held in jail pending another
hearing in the case, which is scheduled for Sept. 28, when another
hearing is planned for al-'Owhali.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, Sachs said that Odeh was 33 years old and
apparently of Jordanian descent, although he was carrying a Yemeni
passport when he was initially detained in Karachi, Pakistan, on a
flight from Kenya. Sachs said that Odeh has a wife and small child
who are living in Amman, Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer said that the government's account of Odeh's
relationship with bin Laden contained some mistakes that he would
not discuss. But Sachs confirmed that Odeh knows bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows him and that's his leader,'' Sachs said, adding that
Odeh did not agree with bin Laden's encouragement of violent acts
against civilians. ``It was not his mission in life to injure
unarmed civilians,'' the lawyer said. ``He said that it was against
his religion to kill unarmed civilians.''
</P>
<P>
   Odeh who authorities have suspected of helping to build the bomb
_ although he has denied it _ studied engineering in the
Philippines. The lawyer made no reference to the government's
reports of Odeh's fishing business while living in Kenya, but said
Odeh made and sold furniture.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint Friday against Odeh provided the first official
indication that investigators had connected bin Laden's group to
events like the attacks on U.S. soldiers in Somalia. Odeh told
investigators that in 1993 he helped train Islamic fighters who
opposed the U.N. forces in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-month peacekeeping mission to Somalia ended in 1995, but
it was a 1993 battle in which 18 Army Rangers were killed in the
streets of Mogadishu that had a searing effect on U.S. military
thinking. Government officials have said the battle resulted in a
cautious narrowing of the military's role in aid missions to
countries like Rwanda and Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's complaint hinted that bin Laden might have had a hand
in attacks on Americans in Saudi Arabia, saying that Odeh said that
``hypothetically'' he would consider a bombing of Americans in
Saudi Arabia, where there have been two attacks in recent years.
The first, in November 1995 at a U.S.-run military training center
in Riyadh, killed seven people, including five Americans. The
second, in June 1996 at an apartment complex in Dhahran, killed 19
U.S. airmen. Both cases remains unsolved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
