<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8273 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLION-COX     08-28 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    African-Americans to stage youth rallies
 &HT;    By S.A. Reid
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- First there was the historic 1995 Million Man March
in the nation's capital, then two years later the Million Woman
March in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Now young African-Americans are preparing to stage their own
mass gatherings Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Convened by separate networks of young activists, the Million
Youth Movement in Atlanta and Million Youth March in New York are
organized, like their predecessors, around similar themes: black
empowerment and nation building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people have to be an integral part,'' said Ati
Cushmeer-Muhammad, coordinator of the Atlanta event. ``Their voices
must be heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of these grass-roots events is intended to be more than a
feel-good gathering. Participants see them as serious efforts to
help solve problems that ail African-American youth.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for both gatherings grew out of the Million Man March,
but ideological differences prevented them from coming together
into a single event.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point we're not against each other, just working on
two different pieces,'' said Olimatta Taal, Southern region
co-chair of the New York march.
</P>
<P>
   African-American youth aren't monolithic and need a choice,
organizers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any event that will energize and mobilize young blacks in
America is good,'' said Byron Amos, Southern region co-chair of the
New York event.
</P>
<P>
   Planners for the black nationalist-tinged event, scheduled for
Thursday through Saturday in Harlem, will use the occasion to call
for reparations, self-determination, an end to gang violence,
creation of youth security groups and a re-dedication to nation
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Million Man March was good, the Million Woman March was
good,'' Taal said. ``But to me, the agendas weren't strong enough
for the issues we face.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the statistics are daunting for African-American youths:
Every three hours, a young adult is murdered; every day a child and
four young adults die from AIDS; every eight minutes, a youth is
arrested for a violent crime; and every 45 seconds of a school day,
a child drops out, according to statistics gathered by the Black
Community Crusade for Children, a Washington-based advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Organizing for both events has been under way for months. And
though each has attracted its own set of high-profile supporters,
neither has yet to match the groundswell of interest of the Million
Man March.
</P>
<P>
   The New York event is being convened by the controversial
Minister Khallid Abdul Muhammad, a former high-ranking Nation of
Islam official accused of anti-Semitism. Organizers, whose
anticipated crowd estimates range from 150,000 to 3 million,
earlier this week won a court battle to force New York City
officials to approve their parade permit.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta planners, however, say they have had none of those
problems and on Friday secured their special-event permit from the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers hope their event, which begins Sept. 4 with a town
hall meeting at the Shrine of the Black Madonna in West End, will
lead to the development of a 10-year action plan and annual
summits. They, too, call for reparations and self-determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the legacy we want to leave behind,'' said
Cushmeer-Muhammad. ``We're asking young people to help be an
integral part of improving the lives of other young people.''
</P>
<P>
   Activities will focus on spiritual, social, political,
educational and economic issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not Freaknik, Part 2,'' said Cushmeer-Muhammad.
``We're looking at a God-centered movement, planned activities and
young people coming with chaperones. We're not looking at a party
atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta organizers expect thousands to participate, including
NAACP President Kweisi Mfume.
</P>
<P>
   Their effort could get a boost from the Rainbow/PUSH Coalition,
which plans to do a mass mailing by Monday urging Georgia youth to
attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a positive thing they are trying to do,'' said Joe
Beasley, the organization's Southern regional director. ``Of
course, many of us had hoped for one march instead of two.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the official travel agency for the Atlanta event, the
Virginia Beach, Va.-based American Way, has received very few
calls, according to agent Ana Moreno.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate sponsorships have not materialized. Donations and
in-kind services totaling roughly $40,000 fall short of the event's
$55,000 estimated cost.
</P>
<P>
   Budget constraints have made it necessary to confine activities
to smaller venues, such as the Shrine.
</P>
<P>
   City officials have worked closely with Atlanta organizers,
whose long list of endorsees includes council members C.T. Martin
and Mable Thomas, as well as a coalition of civil rights advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've seen the Million Man March and the Million Woman
March,'' said Thomas, a supporter of both events. ``It didn't
surprise me that young people want to be in a leadership position
to say they are the next leaders of the new millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Julian Bond, the NAACP's board chairman, has given his support,
as have the National Council of Negro Women, the Rev. Jesse
Jackson, Georgia Association of Black Elected Officials, Nation of
Islam leader Minister Louis Farrakhan, Black Law Students
Association and the Atlanta-based rap group Goodie Mob.
</P>
<P>
   Bond, however, has expressed concern about the simultaneous
scheduling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's problematic because it appears to be headed toward a test
of wills. Who will draw the biggest crowd?'' the civil rights
stalwart told the Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel. ``It may not reflect
who is really reaching the young people, but we will all be looking
if 10,000 show up at one march and one million show up at the
other.''
</P>
<P>
   But Beasley warned against playing the numbers game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you have young people coming together around issues,
it's positive, however many are there,'' he said. ``We're declaring
it a success already.''
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 4:
</P>
<P>
   Town Hall Meeting, 8 p.m. to 10 p.m., Shrine of the Black
Madonna, 946 Ralph David Abernathy Jr. Blvd. S.W. Topic: ``Youth,
Privatization and Criminal Justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 5:
</P>
<P>
   Workshop/forum for ages 13-24, 9 a.m. to 7 p.m., Wheeler Hall,
Morehouse College, 830 Westview Drive.
</P>
<P>
   Film Festival, 10 a.m. to 3 p.m., Auburn Avenue Research Library
auditorium,101 Auburn Ave.
</P>
<P>
   Hip hop/poetry party, open mic, 8 p.m. to midnight, Shrine, 946
Ralph David Abernathy Blvd. S.W. $5.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 6:
</P>
<P>
   Interfaith Service, 11 a.m., Shrine.
</P>
<P>
   Gospel Jam '98 and presentation of Youth Achievers USA awards, 5
p.m., Big Bethel AME, 220 Auburn Ave. N.E.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Sept. 7:
</P>
<P>
   Mass rally, 10 a.m. to 3:30 p.m., Auburn Avenue. Program
features entertainer Melba Moore, rap group Goodie Mob and speaker
Jean Ayinde-Baptiste.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call 404-658-1313 or visit the Web site at
www.millionyouthmovement .org
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   The round-trip cost is $60 per person. Buses will depart at 6
p.m. Sept. 4 from the Afrocentric Cultural Center, 19 Ashby St.
N.W. and return Sept. 6. For more information, call 770-281-7260 or
visit the Web site at www.millionyouthmarch.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
