<SLUG> BC-RANDSTAD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Randstad buys staffing unit of rival in $850 million deal
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Randstad Holdings NV, the Dutch parent of
Atlanta-based Randstad Staffing Services, has acquired the
commercial staffing arm of rival AccuStaff Inc. in an $850 million
cash deal.
</P>
<P>
   Once a regional bit player, the Atlanta company now vaults into
the top 10 in the $54 billion U.S. temporary staffing industry,
surpassing its Atlanta competitor, Norrell Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Strategix Solutions, one of the largest deals
in the industry, also puts Randstad Staffing on par with giants
Manpower and Kelly Services in the United States. Its parent,
Randstad Holdings NV, already is the world's sixth-largest staffing
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Randstad Staffing will now have 440 offices in 36 states and
$1.4 billion in revenue. Together, Randstad Staffing and Strategix
have about 65,000 people working nationwide on an average day.
Randstad Staffing's 600-employee complex at Windy Hill Road and
I-75 will be the headquarters for the newly combined companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will put Randstad (Holdings) in a race with Manpower and
Adecco for global leadership,'' said Peter Yessne, editor of
Staffing Industry Report in Los Altos, Calif. ``Manpower and Adecco
had head starts because they were in many European countries.
Randstad was perhaps at the next level ... but it had a small U.S.
presence. So it's a big jump for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal began unfolding in June when officials at Randstad
Holdings approached Accustaff after learning of its intention to
sell Strategix.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been our long-term goal to establish a solid market share
nationally and this of course is a fairly sizable step in
accomplishing that,'' Randstad Staffing President Erik Vonk said.
``The companies are complementary to each other. There's hardly any
overlap.'' Vonk, also a member of the holding company's executive
board, said he does not expect any layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement also meant good news for AccuStaff. Shares of
the Jacksonville-based company rose 31 percent Friday on news of
the acquisition, which ended plans to take Strategix public. The
stock closed Friday at $17, up $1. AccuStaff will now focus on its
information technology consulting and professional services
business.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson-Humphrey analyst Mark Allen said the deal is a ``good
move'' for Randstad and Accustaff. It lets Accustaff focus on its
primary business and ``Randstad has a vehicle to move into the
higher end skills sets,'' which yield higher profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
