<SLUG> BC-KOLBE-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 OPTIONS FOR CLINTON: RESIGNATION OR IMPEACHMENT  
 (EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOLBE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - ``This has gone on too long...and hurt too many
innocent people.'' &QL; 
_Bill Clinton, Aug. 17 &QL; 
 &QL; 
In what may have been the least satisfactory presidential crisis
speech in television history, the president did make one assertion
on which nearly all his countrymen, amazingly, might agree. This
truly has gone on too long.
</P>
<P>
   People may differ, however, over just what ``this'' is.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made it clear what he meant. He said it during a
diatribe blaming independent counsel Ken Starr for his woes, as if
the evil prosecutor had somehow thrust Monica Lewinski into an
unsuspecting president's arms. He wants Starr's investigation to
shut down (begin ital) ``now,'' (end ital) and Americans to forget
everything.
</P>
<P>
   His constituents, however, might be excused if they have a
different take on his remark. For many of them, it's the saga of
lies, denials, debauchery, delays, and lawyerly half-truths that
must end.
</P>
<P>
   But must it? And if so, how?
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, declares CNN's Bill Press, is ``totally
absurd...It's about sex.'' And as such, Clinton adds, ``it's
nobody's business but ours.'' Feminist Wendy Kaminer wonders: ``Why
should we hold the president to standards of moral behavior that
few of us meet consistently?''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, as we're often reminded, the economy's in great shape
(although the cheerleaders may want to reconsider after last week).
So why sweat sex?
</P>
<P>
   The president's defenders want us to think of adultery like
jaywalking, risky at times but mostly harmless. But it isn't. It's
``a betrayal of a very high order,'' as virtue maven Bill Bennett
has written and any victimized spouse can attest, shattering
``fragile...social networks,'' causing ``acute emotional damage,''
and in a public arena, extinguishing any claim to moral authority.
``Leaders who flout moral codes weaken them.''
</P>
<P>
   In any event, this wasn't ``just about sex.'' This was Bill
Clinton's defining crisis, like Kennedy's missile crisis or Bush's
Gulf war. It was about saving his presidency. And he lied.
</P>
<P>
   When the president accosted a 21-year-old intern (and kept doing
so for 18 months) in his office while at work, wagged his finger
and lied to us about it, enlisted aides to spread the deceit,
launched a smear campaign against his own government's lawyers and
forced them to spend months and millions of our dollars searching
for answers he already had, he made it (begin ital) our (end ital)
business.
</P>
<P>
   Against that history, Americans not only have a right, but a
(begin ital) civic duty, (end ital) to be offended. To do less, to
accept his reckless behavior as a political norm, is an affront to
public order.
</P>
<P>
   Every time he snips a ribbon, or awards a medal, or makes a
speech, or trades toasts with another crippled foreign leader (as
he is scheduled to do this week) without paying a price for
offenses that would get him fired at almost any company or
government agency in America, is a rebuke to the structure of
values which has always made the United States a beacon of freedom
and goodness in a treacherous, immoral world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that...we still live well,'' wrote John Updike,
``cannot ease the pain of feeling that we no longer live nobly.''
Six out of seven Americans, says pollster Daniel Yankelovich, fear
``something is fundamentally wrong with America's social
condition.''
</P>
<P>
   If he really cares about his agenda, which is now dead in the
water, and the country he claims to work for tirelessly, which is
flailing aimlessly amid a growing global economic and political
crisis, Clinton would resign honorably.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that we all assume he won't speaks volumes about
the degree of self-absorption we see in him.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are properly wary of this political death penalty, but
in their wariness they assume that it is reserved only for extreme
violations of the law. Not so. ``High crimes and misdemeanors''
dates from the 14th Century, and applies only to offenses meriting
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Such offenses, wrote Hamilton in the ``Federalist Papers,''
``may with peculiar propriety be denominated as political, as they
relate chiefly to injuries done immediately to the society
itself.'' The impeachment power is for ``keeping (officers)
virtuous whilst they continue to hold their public trust,'' said
Madison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impeachment is the first step in a remedial process,''
reported the House Judiciary Committee in 1974. One of its staffers
was named Hillary Rodham.
</P>
<P>
   She should know, in more ways than one, that this has ``gone on
too long.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
John Kolbe can be reached jkolbedit(at)aol.com on the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
