A8279 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-REEVES-COL-TEX     08-28 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-REEVES-COL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEASE DON'T PASS AROUND HOMER RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is with deep despair and sincere apologies that I come to you
today. I looked in the mirror yesterday morning and there, staring
back at me, was an old fuddy-duddy.
</P>
<P>
   It was a shocking discovery, but there's no getting around it.
The evidence was unmistakable. There the fuddy-duddy stood,
gray-haired, narrow-minded and with a queasy stomach at the idea
that baseball's most hallowed record is about to fall.
</P>
<P>
   That's at the crux of it, you see.
</P>
<P>
   I've decided I don't want to see Roger Maris' home-run record
broken.
</P>
<P>
   I thought I could handle it. Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa are
both nice guys. Either one would be a fine representative. That's
what I've been telling myself for weeks now.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not working any more, and I can no longer pretend that
I don't care.
</P>
<P>
   I care too much.
</P>
<P>
   This, you must understand, is baseball's most hallowed record.
It has already been broken once in my lifetime. That'll do just
fine, thank you very much.
</P>
<P>
   I know, you're caught up in the chase. I understand. It's
exciting. It's something to talk about. And if you weren't around
to watch it happen in 1961, then it's your chance to be in on a
piece of history.
</P>
<P>
   All that's well and good.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, I have this bad feeling that we may be in on
history every year from now till the cows come home.
</P>
<P>
   I fear that what was once a sacred record, held for 34 years by
``The Babe'' and for 37 years now by Maris, is about to be passed
around like a quart of Schlitz at a frat party, like a wrinkled
copy of Playboy in a baseball clubhouse, like a platter of fried
chicken at a church potluck supper.
</P>
<P>
   What if it's Big Mac this year and every French fry in the bag
next year? Or what if it's Big Mac and So-So this year and some
shortstop the next?
</P>
<P>
   Is that really what you want?
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem. There's something wrong here, and we've
gotten so caught up in whether it's going to be McGwire, or Sosa,
or a dozen other guys just like 'em that we can't see it.
</P>
<P>
   If it is just McGwire and he is going to hold the record for the
next 30 years, that would be fine. Bring him on and we'll sing his
praises and explore the wonders of ``andro'' together.
</P>
<P>
   But if it's McGwire leading the cast of Saving Private Ryan in
an annual assault on the beaches of baseball's record book, can we
call timeout and rethink our position?
</P>
<P>
   Are we the unwitting victims of a baseball ``conspiracy,''
devised to rejuvenate the game and provoke August and September
sellouts in normally semiconscious communities like Pittsburgh,
Milwaukee and Miami?
</P>
<P>
   That's a possibility that noted Fort Worth baseball historian
Larry Swindell has considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a clear pattern that you can find,'' contends
Swindell, who believes that baseball has often responded to crises
with a juiced and livelier baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that somebody who is very significant to major-league
baseball is whoever is responsible for ordering the baseballs,''
Swindell says. ``We don't know who that is _ maybe a clerk in the
commissioner's office _ but we do know that the balls change from
season to season.''
</P>
<P>
   Do you realize that when Ruth hit his 60 home runs in 1927, the
only other player in the American League to hit more than 20 that
year was Lou Gehrig, who had 47?
</P>
<P>
   ``That magnifies Ruth's accomplishment even more,'' Swindell
says. ``He revolutionized the game.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, when Maris and Mickey Mantle waged their two-man chase
of Ruth's record in September, 40 major-leaguers hit 20 or more
homers, a dozen passed the 30 mark and eight had 40 or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the press that the home run got last year, I
predicted that the ball would be at least as juiced this year, if
not more so,'' Swindell says. ``It's not just McGwire and Sosa.
There are a number of others at 40 who will be pushing toward 50
and there will be another big group at 30 or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty home runs used to be the mark of a slugger. Now it's
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Example: Will Clark hit his 20th for the Rangers yesterday, the
first time he's reached that mark since 1991 in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's another reason why I think it's a combination of the
ball and the bat,'' Swindell says. ``Have you ever seen a season
where there were so many pitchers hit by balls? Never. There must
have been five instances this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball is being hit harder than it's ever been hit before.''
</P>
<P>
   Harder and more often, for a variety of reasons, from expansion,
to year-round conditioning, to the technology of vitamins and
creatine shakes.
</P>
<P>
   Call me an old fuddy-duddy, but I shudder at the thought of the
most honored record in baseball history being passed around like a
bottle of Thunderbird at a hobos' convention.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Reeves is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
