</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON WINS POLE POSITION AT NHIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ No longer employed by Hendrick Motorsports, Ricky
Craven may have been conspicuously absent Friday at New Hampshire
International Speedway, but he was not forgotten by former teammate
Jeff Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Winner of eight races and seven pole positions this season,
Gordon, the two-time and defending NASCAR Winston Cup champion,
added yet another bauble to his overflowing treasure chest by
winning his eighth pole of the season for Sunday's Farm Aid on
Country Music Television 300 at New Hampshire International
Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Craven returned from a three-month layoff in July to win the
pole for the Jiffy Lube 300 at NHIS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess since my old buddy Ricky Craven wasn't here to qualify
today, he decided to let me have a pole this weekend,'' said
Gordon, who battled slippery track conditions at the one-mile oval
to win his first pole at NHIS by turning a fast lap of 129.033
miles per hour in his No. 24 Dupont Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``We
were a little worried going out early (in the qualifying order),
but luckily we weren't in the Top 10. We were 15th and that
certainly helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got a really good lap and tried to be a little
conservative going into (Turn) 1,'' he added. ``I've overdrove
going into 1 several times and ended up 21st, and further back than
that before. And so, I got into 1 and the car felt good and really
carried a lot of speed the rest of the way around the track. As
long as you stayed in the groove today, which wasn't easy to do,
you could get a pretty good lap and really get some grip.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, track officials had each turn treated with
seven 45-gallon drums of ``asphalt reconditioner,'' a mix of liquid
asphalt and sand, in an attempt to expand the racing groove around
the track.
</P>
<P>
   However, several drivers experienced trouble getting their
groove back after sliding off it and hitting the wall. Dale
Earnhardt; Jeff Burton, a two-time winner at NHIS; Sterling Marlin,
and Ernie Irvan all made wall contact during Friday morning's
practice session. Earnhardt, who was 18th fastest (127.002 m.p.h.);
Irvan, who was 19th fastest (126.918), and Burton, who barely made
the first-round cut at 25th fastest (126.677), were forced to
qualify in backup cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's already becoming one of my best friends right now,''
Earnhardt said of his backup. ``Coming off the truck with about 45
minutes worth of practice and being able to qualify in the Top 25,
I feel good about the car. I think I could have done a little more
with it, but after wrecking I was a little careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte took a stab at the pole but qualified second
fastest (128.398) in his No. 18 Interstate Batteries Pontiac. Ken
Schrader, who set a track record (129.423) by winning the pole for
last year's Jiffy Lube 300, was third fastest (128.212) while Kenny
Wallace (128.182) and Mark Martin (128.079) rounded out the top
five qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were one of the fastest cars here in practice the earlier
(July) race last year. We went out to qualify and all but lost it
going into Turn 1,'' said Gordon, who will take a 67-point lead
over Martin in the Winston Cup standings into Sunday's race. ``I
just tried to carry too much speed into Turn 1 and I tried to drive
it like I was in practice. I think, just learning from Ricky
Craven, and talking to him about running around here, and from that
experience of practically losing control going into 1 (helped).''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he missed Craven, who was replaced by Wally Dallenbach
after he resigned from the No. 50 Budweiser Chevrolet, Gordon said,
``There's nobody that wanted things to work out more for Ricky than
me _ other than maybe himself. I was one of the key people who
influenced Hendrick into hiring him. I think Ricky's a great race
car driver and I hope he gets some good opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a chemistry thing,'' he added. ``The guy's on the
Bud team have struggled and it was hard for them to get people to
stay together, and I hate that it didn't work out for Ricky or for
Hendrick.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ted Christopher of Plainville, Conn., won the pole for
Saturday's CMT Twin 100s Busch North Series race with a lap of
123.446 m.p.h. ``We won this race last year,'' said Christopher,
``so hopefully I'm going to win it again.'' ... Driving with a
broken left thumb, Mike Ewanitsko, of North Babylon, N.Y., won his
fourth pole position of the 1998 Featherlite Modified Series with a
fast lap of 129.366.
</P>
</TEXT>
