<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG'S MARKET MEDDLING DRAWS MIXED REVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)  (jw) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Amid the battering of stock markets around the world
this week, Hong Kong has seemed strangely stable _ an oasis of calm
in a storm. But appearances are deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   In a climax to an unprecedented two-week-long direct
intervention in the stock market, Hong Kong's government spent at
least $8 billion Friday on a frenzied buying spree to prop up
shares and foil speculators it accuses of manipulating its market.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, an earlier round of intervention had managed to
push the Hong Kong stock market up while every other market around
the globe was down. Friday, for all the money spent, the benchmark
Hang Seng index still declined 93.23 points, or 1.2 percent, to
7,829.74.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong has always been unusual in Asia, practically a lone
outpost of free markets in a region of state-managed capitalism.
The government, while committed to a fixed exchange rate with the
U.S. dollar and even prepared to try to support the property market
the way South Africa's DeBeers regulates the price of diamonds,
historically has gone to great lengths to avoid all trade
restrictions and keep hands off its financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   So, in a city where tracking the Hang Seng is a favorite parlor
game, Friday's wild ride _ by far the market's biggest trading
volume ever _ left people slack-jawed. At moments during the
morning trading session, the Hong Kong Stock Exchange seemed less a
market than a giant clearance sale, with the government buying
everything in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did this at a time when there is gloom around the
world,'' said Glenn Lesko, the director of regional sales and
trading at ABN Amro Securities in Hong Kong. ``I think they ran
into far more sellers than they expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials, however, claimed victory. They said the
intervention had stabilized the Hang Seng, even as markets across
Asia, Europe and the United States were plummeting because of fears
about the financial turmoil in Russia and other emerging markets.
That stymied traders who had taken short positions on shares and
futures contracts on the bet that the Hong Kong market would
tumble.
</P>
<P>
   For Hong Kong, Friday's action was the boldest step yet in a
costly effort to erect a wall between this former British colony
and the financial typhoon raging around it. Although Hong Kong has
already been whipsawed by the Asian crisis, the territory's leaders
are determined not to be sucked into an even more calamitous vortex
of currency attacks followed by a stock market collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong Monetary Authority has spent at least $12 billion
since it began buying shares and futures contracts on Aug. 14.
Nonetheless, Donald Tsang, Hong Kong's financial secretary, said
the government was ready to continue intervening. Hong Kong has
already spent more than 10 percent of its $100 billion in foreign
reserves on the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Tung Chee-hwa, the chief executive of Hong Kong, held open the
possibility that China might support Hong Kong's campaign, with its
$140 billion worth of reserves. ``The central government has said
many, many times openly that they are very willing to support us if
there is a need to do so,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's tough stance came in the wake of more bad economic
news. The government released data confirming that Hong Kong had
slipped into a recession in the second quarter, as the economy
contracted 5 percent. It also projected that the economy would
shrink 4 percent in 1998 _ the first full year of contraction since
Hong Kong began keeping records in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the government's intervention that had analysts
rattled. Several said the stock market would plummet as soon as the
government stopped supporting it. And some argued that Hong Kong
was squandering both its reserves and its reputation as the freest
financial market in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the short run, if you pour billions of dollars into stocks,
you can pump up the market,'' said Steve Hanke, a professor of
applied economics at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore. ``But
in the long run, this is doomed to fail because it convinces
speculators that Hong Kong can't take the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, no less prominent a currency trader than George Soros
seems to view Hong Kong's intervention as a quixotic effort.
Stanley Druckenmiller, the manager of Soros' Quantum Fund, said in
an interview on Thursday with CNBC: ``No matter what they do in
their market, when they wake up on Monday morning, they're still
going to be in a depression.''
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong may not stop at simple intervention. Tsang announced
that the government was considering measures to curb ``manipulative
practices.'' These could include restrictions on the short-selling
of stocks and increased disclosure requirements in the trading of
index futures.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong would not be the first Asian market to restrict
certain kinds of trading. Japan, Korea and Malaysia all do it, just
as they intervene in their markets. But Hong Kong has long prided
itself as the New York of Asia _ a market where Wall Street
openness meets Chinese entrepreneurialism.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, some analysts believe the government has been
forced to act by Hong Kong's most prominent entrepreneurs _ the
property tycoons _ who have seen their share holdings decline in
value by 50 percent since last year. Two months ago, the government
announced it would suspend sales of land, in an effort to halt the
downward spiral of property prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony is that the government is taking the people's money
and using it to bail out the property developers,'' said Marc
Faber, an investment adviser and managing director of his own
brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   Tsang dismissed the suggestion that the government was putting
Hong Kong's reserves at risk. He noted that the Hang Seng index has
risen 1,200 points since the intervention began, which means that
the government owns more in shares than it did in cash before it
began buying.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the government's buying spree has put it in the
uncharacteristic _ and potentially awkward _ position of being a
major shareholder in many blue-chip Hong Kong companies. The
government now even owns a stake in HSBC Holdings, the parent
company of the Hongkong and Shanghai Bank. Traders said that one of
HSBC's brokerage subsidiaries was buying shares on behalf of the
government, raising questions about a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Tsang said he was not concerned about owning large stakes in
Hong Kong companies or about the potential negative effect of
dumping those positions on the open market once the intervention
was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am quite happy to hold on to them for quite a while,'' Tsang
said. ``These are the assets of the Hong Kong people.''
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's battle with the currency traders has mutated from a
guerrilla skirmish into a full-scale war of attrition. Several
traders said the government had recruited an unidentified expert to
help it plot moves to thwart even the shrewdest of hedge funds.
Beyond buying blue-chip shares like HSBC and Hong Kong Telecom, the
government has taken a complex set of long and short positions on
August and September index futures contracts. The goal has been to
put the traders who hold the contracts into a bind: They can either
sell their August contracts at a loss, or roll them over into
September at a discount.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the mechanics of the market, Hong Kong's intervention has
rekindled a debate about how much governments can and should
intervene to protect themselves from the vagaries of the global
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Chan, a prominent Hong Kong property developer, said the
government had an obligation to protect its citizens from a wave of
speculation that was threatening to swamp the stock market and the
local economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The total annual output of Hong Kong is dwarfed by the daily
capital flow of the markets,'' Chan said. ``At will, the market can
destroy an economy overnight. Is Hong Kong being destroyed? No. But
is it suffering hugely? You bet.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong's case, however, the debate is complicated by the
fact that it has set itself up as a mecca for global capital. Last
year, the Hang Seng index rocketed to 16,000 points as foreign
investors poured money into shares of ``red chips'' _ Chinese
companies with publicly listed Hong Kong subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong dollar is another example of the territory's
supposed openness to the global economy. The currency is pegged to
the U.S. dollar at a fixed rate. The price for preserving that link
at a time when most Asian countries devalued their currencies has
been a spike in interest rates, which drove down property prices
and the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Until this summer, Hong Kong had seemed ready to absorb those
blows. But then in June, the government announced it would stop
selling land. And two weeks ago, it waded into the stock market.
After Friday's session, some market experts began talking about the
``nationalization'' of Hong Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
