<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON REMARKS CENTER ON FORGIVENESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAK BLUFFS, Mass. _ Embraced by his most ardent supporters, an
emotional President Clinton said Friday that he had been wrestling
with the process of forgiveness _ both as a seeker of forgiveness
from his family and the nation, and as one who forgives his
enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so it is important that we are able to forgive those we
believe have wronged us, even as we ask for forgiveness from people
we have wronged,''the president said in apparent references first
to Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel who has been delving into
the Clintons' lives, and then to his wife and the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The anger, the resentment, the bitterness, the desire for
recrimination against people you believe have wronged you _ they
harden the heart and deaden the spirit and lead to self-inflicted
wounds,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks came almost two weeks after he spoke in a televised
address to the country about his relationship with former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky. In the days that followed the brief
address, Clinton was widely criticized as less contrite than he
should have been and too eager to cast blame for his predicament on
Starr. Since then, aides have hinted he might make a more
conciliatory statement.
</P>
<P>
   If Friday's words did not constitute the outright apology that
some critics have been demanding, they reflected a man who is still
navigating his way through the self-imposed crisis that has tested
his marriage and threatened his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was speaking to 400 people who had come to a simple
wood-shingled chapel here to commemorate the 35th anniversary of
the historic civil-rights march on Washington.
</P>
<P>
   His aides, who have said Clinton would refer publicly to his
personal situation in his own time and way, said they had no idea
he would offer up this fillip on forgiveness Friday, and they
refused to interpret it. But they said that Friday morning he
rejected a speech written by his staff, turning over the very paper
the prepared speech was written on and scribbling his own thoughts
in long hand.
</P>
<P>
   He continued to revise his remarks in his car on the way to the
chapel Friday afternoon and jotted even more as he sat on stage,
where he was bathed in an emotional outpouring of support from
black leaders, who have been his most reliable supporters. The most
recent New York Times/CBS News Poll, conducted Aug. 19 and 20,
showed that 94 percent of blacks approve of the job he is doing,
compared with 60 percent of whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been with you from the beginning,'' declared Rep. John
Lewis, D-Ga., who played a central role in the civil-rights
movement. ``And I will stand with you now till the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Ogletree Jr., a professor at Harvard Law School, said to
the president: ``All these times, it was very easy for us to be
with you because you were with us. And now in difficult times, I
want you to know that the people here understand and feel your
pain, believe in redemption and are here because of you and are
here with you through thick and through thin.''
</P>
<P>
   Ogletree represented Anita Hill, the former University of
Oklahoma law professor who once accused Supreme Court nominee
Clarence Thomas of sexual harassment. Ms. Hill also attended the
ceremony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
