u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-GINGRICH-340&AMP;ADD     08-28 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-GINGRICH-340&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GINGRICH QUESTIONS CLINTON'S POLICY ON IRAQI ARMS INSPECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Speaker Newt Gingrich said Friday that the
resignation of a senior American weapons inspector in Iraq raised
``disturbing questions'' about President Clinton's policy and
suggested that Clinton had misled Congress about his commitment to
uncovering the extent of Saddam Hussein's nuclear, chemical and
biological weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter he sent to Clinton on Thursday, Gingrich expressed
his ``deepest concern'' about charges by the inspector, William
Ritter, who resigned Wednesday in part to protest administration
policy and U.N. Security Council inaction on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said Ritter's charges suggested that ``your
administration at every turn has undercut and hindered the ability
of the inspection team to do its job.''
</P>
<P>
   If true, Gingrich said, the allegations suggest that ``your
administration's tough rhetoric on Iraq has been a deception
masking a real policy of weakness and concession.''
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, Gingrich noted that Clinton had six months ago
``justifiably'' threatened military action against Saddam if he did
not give U.N. inspectors unfettered access to purported weapons
sites. He complained that Iraq's Aug. 3 refusal to do so had not
prompted the tough action promised, but only a ``weak response,''
specifically, letting ``the U.N. decide.'' The United Nations,
unfortunately, he added, had decided ``not to take firm action.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Gingrich wrote, the ``U.S. appears ready to give up
on inspections and to be satisfied with the maintenance of an
increasingly porous and ineffective sanctions regime.'' This, in
turn, raised a number of ``very disturbing questions,'' he added,
among them ``Has your administration misled Congress and the
American people on our actual policy towards Iraq?''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Alaska, where Gingrich is fishing,
he said he was particularly troubled by Clinton's inaction and
Ritter's charges because they are ``virtually the opposite of what
he and his people have been telling us for months.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The contradiction between Clinton's tough rhetoric and his
apparent inaction, Gingrich said, suggest ``a level of
disinformation that would be startling.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said he was particularly troubled by assertions that
the United States is unwilling to challenge Iraqi defiance, because
``I know that the president is very concerned about the spread of
weapons of mass destruction,'' and with Iraq's role in such
proliferation. ``We've spent a lot of time talking about this.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gingrich did not say where, when, or how often Clinton and
he had discussed these issues, a spokesman for the speaker's office
said that Gingrich and Clinton had regular telephone conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said that within the last two months, Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright had given Congress information that turned
out not to be true. When challenged about what appeared to be the
misinformation, he said, senior administration officials told
Gingrich that Albright ``had not been briefed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to ask, `what is going on here'?'' he said.
``Have the people at State been running their own independent
policy of appeasement?''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich would not disclose what Albright had discussed with him
and other senior members of Congress, except to say that it
involved very sensitive information.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary's office did not return calls for comment, but
Gingrich called back Friday evening to say that Albright had
tracked him down to assure him that the administration was not
softening its stance on Iraq and that there was no rift in policy
toward Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich added that ``We've still got to explore this. The issue
will not go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich asked Clinton to assure him that the administration
would not allow Iraq to defy inspectors and return to developing a
significant arsenal of biological, chemical and nuclear weapons.
Backing down from the confrontation with Iraq, he added, would
``destroy our credibility in the international community and have
devastating consequences,'' he wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
