<HEADLINE>
JACKSON TO MEET WITH CONDIT TO DISCUSS RACE RELATIONS AT BOEING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY and CONSTANCE SOMMER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boeing Chairman Phil Condit will meet with the Rev. Jesse
Jackson in Seattle next Friday to discuss race relations at Boeing,
a company spokesman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement to meet comes one month after the
affirmative-action advocate sent a letter to Condit asking for an
end to racial discrimination at Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has taken a hand in other discrimination cases,
including a case at Texaco that involved a tape of a company
officer talking about ``black jelly beans.'' In 1996, Texaco
settled that case for $115 million in cash payments to
African-American employees and ex-employes, $26 million in raises
over five years and $35 million in sensitivity and diversity
training.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's focus is now Boeing. In his letter, he expressed
concern about accusations of racial bias and retaliation detailed
in several employee lawsuits, including a federal class action
filed in Seattle earlier this year, a separate group case filed in
King County Superior Court, and a 1997 federal case filed by a
manager in Boeing's Security Investigations Department. The latter
case, brought by Jesse Jones, is scheduled to go to trial Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Condit responded to Jackson's letter in early August, saying he
would like to get together and suggesting they attempt to set up a
time, said Boeing spokesman Larry McCracken. But the two men did
not agree on a time until Jackson took his case public Friday,
complaining that Boeing had failed to come up with a date.
</P>
<P>
   Condit called Jackson that same day, McCracken said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a conversation about 10 minutes long,'' he said.
``(Condit) took the initiative of calling because he wanted to
assure (Jackson) that there was no misunderstanding and that they
are interested in the same goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he would be in the Seattle area next Friday, and
Condit agreed to clear his afternoon schedule, McCracken said. The
details of when and where the meeting will take place and who will
attend are still being worked out. Jackson has also asked to tour a
Boeing facility, McCracken said.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Jackson asked Condit for data on Boeing's hiring
and promotion practices. McCracken said he did not know if Boeing
could provide it. But he said the company welcomes Jackson's
requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to the same things _ equality of opportunity
and fair treatment of all Boeing employees,'' he said. ``We agree
inclusion leads to growth and where there is growth, everybody
wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing may not be perfect, but neither is it complacent, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are making every effort,'' he said. ``As a company ... we
probably have a lot of the same problems society has.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
