<SLUG> BC-STORMSIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All rain makes for dull vacation
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, N.C. _ At the halfway point of a two-week vacation
with his wife and two sons, accountant Geoff Meyers has entertained
his family the past three days by looking at areas flooded by
Hurricane Bonnie and watching the rain fall outside their hotel
window.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly the fishing trip or long bike rides they had
planned for the Outer Banks. Meyers was among thousands of tourists
evacuated from coastal North Carolina in advance of Bonnie on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With blue sky emerging around them Friday for the first time
since Tuesday, Meyers hoped to get back to the fishing village of
Avon, N.C., in the middle of Outer Banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as they open the highway, we're gone,'' said Meyers of
Gardiner, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of N.C. 12 on the Outer Banks were closed until Friday,
when residents began streaming back onto the barrier islands.
Between Rodanthe and Frisco on the Outer Banks, soundside flooding
began as ocean overwash subsided. Most of N.C. 12 south of Oregon
inlet was reported under 10 to 12 inches of water early Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Closed highways make for boring vacations. Entertainment for
10-year-old Devin and 4-year-old Trevor was limited. Nintendo games
held their attention for only so long before they were practically
bouncing off the walls at the Comfort Inn.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to do here,'' Meyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Meyers stowed his fishing tackle in a luggage shell on top of
his Ford Aerostar and made sure the fiberglass carrier was strapped
down each night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had it all unpacked Saturday, and we spent (Tuesday)
packing it back up,'' said Meyers, an accountant who had a deep-sea
fishing trip postponed by Bonnie.
</P>
<P>
   Devin was disappointed the fishing trip was postponed while the
family waited out the storm. ``He was a little nervous, but he's
also a little excited because of the hurricane,'' Meyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Meyers' father, 74-year-old Howard Meyers, stayed behind and
successfully rode out the storm. ``He just battened everything
down. He's been through them,'' Meyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
