<HEADER>
A8294 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLIND27-COX     08-28 1921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLIND27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Life without eyes
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Her water broke on the evening before, and Lori and
Brad Hardy waited through the night as gradually the contractions
became more frequent, more intense. It would be a boy _ they knew
that much. On the ultrasound examination, the doctor had spotted
the boy parts and told them it was all but certain. Both were
happy. Just so he was healthy.
</P>
<P>
   By 8 the morning of Sept. 7, 1995, her hard labor was under way.
It lasted for 2 1/2 hours, and at 10:19 Lori Hardy, 22, gave birth
to their first child, David Tyler Hardy. They would call him by his
middle name.
</P>
<P>
   A mother's reward for her labor is usually to hold her newborn
to her breast, but it is not always immediate. In Lori Hardy's
case, the nurses were having a hard time getting the infant's
eyelids open, and when nothing seemed to work, Tyler was taken off
to be examined by a specialist.
</P>
<P>
   But the waiting and expectation and morning sickness were over.
He had entered the world, 6 pounds, 13 ounces, and was breathing on
his own.
</P>
<P>
   It was another two hours before a doctor returned to Lori
Hardy's hospital room and told her, ``As for eyes, he doesn't have
any.''
</P>
<P>
   She lay there, in the company of her family and her husband's
family, all of them gathered in Birmingham for the birth, and a
doctor was telling her that the child she carried for nine months
had been born without eyes.
</P>
<P>
   And then the doctor said, ``Now, we're going to do some tests to
make sure nothing else is wrong.'' When a child is born without
eyes, he explained, there often are other problems as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad, who's always been the emotional one, just broke down
crying,'' Lori Hardy says. ``He had to leave the room.''
</P>
<P>
   His weren't the only tears. But Brad Hardy, 25, put his aside
and told the unbelieving, grief-stricken family that it wasn't a
time to dwell on misfortune. Their son needed their strength and
support, he said, and he and his wife were going to provide him a
life as close to normal as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Learning by touch
</P>
<P>
   The building at 763 Peachtree St. has a storefront appearance.
Inside, the paint on the wall tells you things operate on a small
budget. From his second floor office at the Center for the Visually
Impaired, Scott McCall administers programs that last year served
1,460 clients. Some were a few days old, others were aged. Many hav
</P>
<P>
   e limited vision, others have severely impaired vision, still
others have no vision at all _ what one instructor calls ``lights
out.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall is among the latter, an Americus native, 50 years old,
married to a sighted woman. He earned a bachelor's degree in
psychology from Mercer University and a master's degree in
rehabilitative counseling from the University of Georgia. At his
desk, he works on a Braille laptop computer, which he says is
subject to crashing like any other. He lives a life almost like any
other _ not in every single respect but in the essential ones of
knowing he can learn, make a living, participate in his community.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think about the things you did today,'' he says, ``from
the time the alarm went off and you looked at the clock to see if
maybe you could sleep another 10 minutes, from going to the closet
to see what tie you were going to wear with this or that shirt,
from shaving and showering to fixing breakfast and going to the
MARTA _ all those are things that most people take for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   They are things the blind, and many with visual impairment, do
at an obvious disadvantage _ but must learn to do nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus here,'' McCall says, ``is to provide them with the
skills to achieve two things _ independence and dignity.
Independence comes from acquiring the skills to travel, to read, to
cook and maintain a home, to use a computer, to do most of the
things other people do. Dignity comes from the kind of attitudes
people develop toward their blindness or visual impairment.''
</P>
<P>
   The center _ a not-for-profit corporation that receives both
private and public funds _ is almost 50 miles from the Hardys' home
in Canton, and Lori and Tyler make the drive once a week. ``I know
he wouldn't be where he is today if it weren't for that place,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   In classes that last most of the morning, Tyler Hardy joins five
children who have varying degrees of visual impairment. He is the
only one completely without vision. With his classmates, he learns
to find his way around a room, to identify objects by their shape
and feel and to manipulate what he cannot see. Children who are
blind see with fingers that fly over surfaces, the tactile sense
transmitting information to the brain.
</P>
<P>
   And they must learn things the rest of us might assume children
do naturally. ``Children with visual impairment have to be taught
how to play,'' says Anne McComiskey, director of the center's
program for babies, toddlers and young children. ``It's not
something they just do on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Her words stop you short. The spontaneity of child's play
wouldn't seem like something that could be carved into step-by-step
lessons, but then you realize your own unthinking assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety percent of early development is vision-related,''
McComiskey says. ``Children learn to play by watching others
play.'' They imitate, improvise, invent.
</P>
<P>
   But children who are blind or whose vision is seriously impaired
do what McComiskey calls ``stilling.'' When sighted infants, for
example, are on the floor and a sibling runs by, they'll turn their
head to follow what they saw. It registers in their mind. Ideas are
formed. With everything it sees, the infant's relationship to his
surroundings and to others becomes clear.
</P>
<P>
   A blind child, when a sibling runs by, doesn't turn its head to
follow what it's heard. It is alert, head tensed, but still.
``Nothing is being strengthened,'' McComiskey says.
</P>
<P>
   And so, in class at the Center for the Visually Impaired, Joyce
Burnett, Kathy Chappell and other instructors teach them first what
blocks are and then how blocks can be played with. They teach them
to form circles, each holding the hand of another. They teach them
to stand in single file, and they teach them to sing in harmony.
</P>
<P>
   But the main thing they teach them is how to learn by touch. The
shape and feel of something are part of knowing what it is. They
also learn to know where they are and where they are going. Using
walkers, students negotiate a path from one side of the room to
another.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying assumption is ``doing things differently,'' not
physical handicap. ``Our philosophy is that blindness is a pain in
the butt, not a life-stopping crisis,'' McComiskey says. There's
even a small computer in the room, and that, too, is part of their
preschool play. By learning to recognize the clicks and sounds,
they come to know that computers are part of the world in which
they will be living.
</P>
<P>
   Parents set goals high
</P>
<P>
   Scott McCall had nothing like the Center for the Visually
Impaired to attend when he was stricken with optic glaucoma at 6
months and lost his sight. But he had his parents. He calls them
his heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectations they set for me were no different from those
they set for my brothers and sisters,'' he says. ``They taught me
that blindness was something that required me to do things
differently, but didn't define my character.''
</P>
<P>
   And neither did it prevent him from understanding the world
around him. One day, when McCall was about 8, his father took him
to a baseball field. They started at home plate. Reach down and
feel it, Bill McCall told the boy, and he did. From home plate they
walked the 90 feet to first base. The boy crouched and felt the
square bag, something like a pillow but coarse to the touch. And
then, making a right angle turn, 90 feet more. This was second
base. Another turn, another 90 feet. Third base. Back to home
plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember it like it was yesterday,'' McCall says. ``To see
it, I had to get down and feel it. And my father said, `Now, over
there is where foul balls go and over here is where fair balls
go.'''
</P>
<P>
   Today, he watches Braves games on TV with his wife, with friends
``or just by myself'' and goes to an occasional game at Turner
Field. ``If we're watching a game on TV and Skip Caray says there's
a hard grounder to short, I know what's going on.'' The game is
being played in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't like to think he's an exception to anyone's rule.
``As a society,'' he says, ``we haven't had the same expectations
of the blind. That leads to the blind not expecting much of
themselves. So, that's why I say our goal at the center is twofold
_ independence and dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   `A special little boy'
</P>
<P>
   The Hardys might not have found the center if not for Lori's
sister, Leeann Harrington. After Tyler's birth, Harrington set
about researching services for the blind. When she learned about
the Center for the Visually Impaired, the Hardys moved from
Birmingham back to Georgia, where most of their family were living.
Brad was able to transfer from a Home Depot store in Birmingham to
one in Woodstock.
</P>
<P>
   In Birmingham, a doctor had told the Hardys nothing much could
be done for Tyler in his first three years. Until then, take him
home and enjoy him, Lori Hardy remembers being told. To the
contrary, much needed to be done if Tyler were to live a productive
life one day. The painful part was surgery to enable doctors to fit
prosthetic eyes into his sockets. As he grew older, the bones in
his skull grew, and he needed repeated surgery. Over a 30-month
period he underwent 17 operations, and soon the electronic beeps
and the lifting feel of an elevator in a medical building became
signals that he was in for more pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd take him to the doctor's and as soon as we'd get on the
elevator, he'd start to cry,'' Lori Hardy says.
</P>
<P>
   His younger sister Tatum, born 15 months later, learned early on
that her brother is blind and accepts it as part of who he is.
``She'd see him come home from the hospital and his eyes would be
red and swollen'' Lori Hardy says. ``She asked me why, and I told
her. She just picked it up.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks shy of his third birthday, Tyler weighs 29
pounds and stands a few inches more than 3 feet. At home he often
talks of Miss Kathy _ Kathy Chappell, his orientation teacher, at
the center. By the time he's 6, he will be enrolled in a public
school, like other 6-year-olds. ``The thing we don't want is for
him to be treated differently just because he's blind,'' says Brad
Hardy.
</P>
<P>
   The additional tests that the doctor in Birmingham performed
turned up nothing abnormal. Tyler was born with what doctors call a
genetic mistake, a one-in-a-million chance.
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't denied life, and Brad and Lori Hardy, like all
parents, are intent that he make the most of it.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler himself has reached the age that he realizes it will be a
life lived differently. One morning this summer Lori Hardy was
swinging him in the hammock and Tyler, ``out of nowhere, said,
`Mommy, I can't see.'''
</P>
<P>
   He had never said it before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It caught me off-guard,'' his mother says. ``He had this sad,
pitiful voice. Later that night, I cried. But I just said to him,
`It's OK, it's OK. You're a special little boy and you can do a lot
of other things.' And he will.''
</P>
<P>
   She went back to swinging her son under the blue summer sky.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
