<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8295 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-FED-545&AMP;ADD-NY     08-28 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-FED-545&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED'S FOCUS SAID TO BE SHIFTING ON INTEREST RATES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wyo., Kan., Mo.)  (lb) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON HOLE, Wyo. _ The latest round of global financial
turmoil is forcing the Federal Reserve Board to shift its sights
from guarding against inflation through higher interest rates to
the possibility that it might have to reduce rates to head off an
economic downturn, central bank officials and economists said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Although it has left rates unchanged for nearly a year and a
half, the Fed has consistently seen inflation, stemming from strong
growth and low unemployment, as a greater threat than recession at
home or a financial meltdown around the world.
</P>
<P>
   But the stock market's slide and the continued deterioration of
most developing economies _ both of which accelerated this week
amid Russia's crisis _ mean that the Fed will almost certainly not
raise rates anytime soon and may seriously debate cutting rates in
coming months, officials and economists said.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, made no
substantive statements about the markets or monetary policy during
a presentation he made here Friday on income inequality. But Fed
officials, as well as economists who held informal discussions with
them here during a symposium sponsored by the Federal Reserve Bank
of Kansas City, said events of the last several weeks will
inevitably reshape the debate within the Fed's policy-making
committee.
</P>
<P>
   One indication of the change in thinking came from William
Poole, the president of the Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis, who
earlier this year was pushing for a rate increase. At the beginning
of July, Poole dropped his call for a rate increase, and he told
reporters here Friday that the best option for the Fed now is to
wait and see how much the domestic economy is hurt by what is
happening in the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given what's been going on in the markets, there is more
reason than before to wait and see how things play out,'' Poole
told the Reuters news service.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said, though, that any backing away from raising
rates would still leave the Fed a long way from cutting them.
``Clearly the events of the past few days make easing by the end of
the year a possibility, though I wouldn't put it higher than 50
percent,'' said David Hale, chief economist at Scudder Kemper
Investments.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Blinder, a former Fed vice chairman, said the fallout from
the situation in Russia ``can only push the spectrum of the debate
in the dovish direction,'' but he said the most likely course was
that the Fed would hold rates steady unless Wall Street was plunged
into a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as its policy-making meeting on July 1, most Fed
officials ``felt that the risks continued to point on balance
toward rising inflation,'' according to minutes of the meeting
released last week. At that meeting, the Fed voted to keep a formal
policy tilt toward raising rates. Minutes of the Fed's most recent
meeting, on Aug. 18, will be released after the next Fed meeting,
on Sept. 29.
</P>
<P>
   But with economic and financial conditions worsening, some Fed
officials suggested that their assessments of the outlook were
changing. The selloff in the stock market, they said, could be
expected to help rein in demand as consumers grew less confident
about their finances, slowing the economy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Financial-market weakness will only underscore expectations of
weakened growth and reassure policy-makers of the remoteness of
inflation as a risk,'' said John Lipsky, chief economist at Chase
Manhattan Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the market reaction to Russia's woes has effectively
brought about a severe tightening of credit conditions for nearly
all developing nations, as investors are demanding sharply higher
premiums over safe investments like U.S. Treasury bonds before they
put their money just about anywhere outside the United States and
Western Europe. Many investors suffered heavy losses in Russia and
are wary of taking another hit.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of credit and investment capital, as well as the
continued turmoil in the markets, could bring a further slowdown to
regions like South America and put further pressure on important
economies like that of Hong Kong, where officials are battling to
stem a sharp slide in the stock market and pressures for a
devaluation of the currency.
</P>
<P>
   The implications for the United States of mounting problems in
other countries, even apart from the effect the turmoil is having
on the financial markets, could be considerable. Mexico and South
America together, for example, account for nearly 20 percent of
U.S. trade, and a downturn there could have a pronounced impact on
U.S. jobs and corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   But Fed officials said they were by no means convinced that the
economy would stall or even slow to a noninflationary pace.
Although growth slowed to 1.6 percent in the second quarter after
surging to a 5.4 percent annual rate in the first quarter, one Fed
official noted that the average for the first half, at 3.4 percent,
was still quite strong.
</P>
<P>
   With unemployment remaining extremely low, there are also
tentative signs that wage increases are beginning to bite into
corporate profits, putting pressure on companies to raise prices
and set off an inflationary spiral.
</P>
<P>
   There was widespread agreement among the experts here that one
thing monetary policy in the United States could not do was help
Russia in any meaningful way. The loss of confidence in Russia
among international investors is so profound that it will take
wholesale changes in the country's political and economic climate
to woo them back, in this view.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Corrigan, a managing director of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.,
said Russia's best course would be to make up for its mistake in
unilaterally limiting its debt repayments and try to negotiate an
agreement with its creditors as a first step toward restoring
stability and credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia, and Russia alone, must take the first steps to get
this process back on track,'' Corrigan said.
</P>
<P>
   But other economists said a rate cut could help economies like
Hong Kong's, where the currency is tied directly to the value of
the dollar and would therefore benefit from any reduction in dollar
interest rates, and those in South America, which need robust
demand from the United States to avert deep downturns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
