<SLUG> BC-INVEST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investors waiting out stock woes
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Hank Thomas has scaled the stock market's peaks and
fallen in its valleys before, so this week's turmoil hasn't shaken
the Stone Mountain investor's confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still ahead of where we were one year ago,'' said
Thomas, who owns several metro McDonald's franchises. ``I still
think we'll end up with a double-digit increase by the end of the
year.'' Despite the turmoil on Wall Street, which extended its
losses Friday, many investors appear ready to ride out the storm.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average lost an additional 114 points
Friday and is now 1,268 points, or 13.8 percent, below the July 17
record of 9,337.97. Stocks also were down around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Trading volume Friday was lower than it was the day before, when
more than 2 billion shares exchanged hands, only the second time in
U.S. market history.
</P>
<P>
   Investors continue to fear the vulnerability of corporate
profits to currency devaluations and economic problems in Asia,
Russia and emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   Added Lovette Lindon, an operations manager at Evercare who says
she has $6,000 invested in the stock market: ``I take my lead from
the big players. If they start worrying about their big
investments, then I will worry about my small one.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
