u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-RUSSIANS-450&AMP;ADD-N     08-28 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RUSSIANS-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMONG RUSSIAN-AMERICANS: CONCERN MIXED WITH RESIGNATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She only arrived in Brighton Beach, Brooklyn, from
Moscow two weeks ago, but Natalia Kuznetsova has followed the
crisis at home by telephoning friends. She knows that the banks are
closed, that the stores are closed, that the ruble is practically
worthless. Her friends tell her they pass the days drinking vodka.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Ms. Kuznetsova in one breath compares daily life in
Russia to a war, in the next breath she smiles and shrugs at the
financial and political upheaval in Moscow that has rippled across
the world. She said she hoped to stay in the United States for a
year or longer, but the thought of returning home did not bother
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the same situation five years ago, 10 years ago,'' said
Ms. Kuznetsova, 26, who spoke with the resignation of someone
considerably older. ``It's a normal situation in our country.''
</P>
<P>
   In Brighton Beach, the neighborhood that for two decades has
absorbed layer upon layer of emigrants from the old Soviet Union,
the news from Russia was greeted with alarm, but also with apathy.
For every person who rushed to wire money to relatives in Russia,
others claimed they couldn't care less about life there. People who
still own property there, or conduct business, stayed in close
contact with friends, monitoring the latest changes. And still
others considered the crisis about as realistic as the televised
Russian soap operas playing at some of the stores on Brighton Beach
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great play by the government to get money from the
international financial system and to steal their money,'' scoffed
Gennady Grigorovich, a Ukrainian immigrant who has lived in
Brooklyn for 20 years and the owner of the Cafi Paris restaurant on
Coney Island Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   A few people at Cafi Volna on the Brighton Beach boardwalk
watched Boris Yeltsin announce Friday on Russian television that he
would remain as president until 2000. Not long after the speech,
the channel was quickly changed to the Weather Channel to follow a
more immediate problem, the path of Tropical Storm Bonnie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to stay?'' asked Sopha Liebanov, manager of
Feminik, a women's clothing store a few blocks away on Brighton
Beach Avenue. ``I don't think so. It doesn't matter if it's Yeltsin
or Chernomyrdin. They stole all the money and put it in their
pockets. The people don't work, and everything is closed. They
expect credits from America.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Liebanov blamed those in Brighton Beach who shrugged off the
crisis, saying that many immigrants have lived in Brooklyn for so
long that they have forgotten the hardship of their old lives.
``The people don't understand,'' she said. ``They think, `It's so
far, so who cares?'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Boris Talis, executive director of Brighton Beach District
Management Association, a coalition of local businesses, said
several Russians visiting the United States on business have rushed
back in the last two days as the fiscal crisis has deepened. As for
Brighton Beach merchants, Talis said the crisis has had ``no
effect, only morally. This is a sad story. Nobody knows what can
happen in the next three or four days.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexy Dementyev, a clerk at United Air and Parcel Service on
Coney Island Avenue, said that on Thursday customers wired a total
of about $10,000 to relatives in Russia and other former Soviet
states, a significant increase. But he also said that the money may
not be bringing much help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Western Union in some cities are paying in rubles,'' Dementyev
said. ``That's not very convenient because the exchange rate is not
too positive. Nevertheless, people are sending.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Irena Chikantseva and her husband, Andrey
Ahramov, came to Brighton Beach from Moscow and opened a gift
store. They still own a four-bedroom apartment in downtown Moscow,
but they said they can no longer find anyone able to pay the $2,000
monthly rent. Besides the financial crisis, the couple say that
rising crime has kept the apartment empty; the last tenant moved
out because the building had no doorman. Now, the couple regularly
call friends and family in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chikantseva's sister in Moscow, whose son is approaching
draft age, worries that the instability could lead to another war
like those in Chechnya and Afghanistan. Ahramov's mother lives in
Moscow, surviving on a pension, but he said she was not alarmed,
perhaps because crisis is nothing new to the older generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can fix the situation,'' Ahramov lamented.
</P>
<P>
   At a barber shop, a Russian barber waved off questions,
unimpressed with the latest crisis at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's life,'' he said. ``People suffer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
