<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8300 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-FUND-325&AMP;ADD-N     08-28 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-FUND-325&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF CHIEF BACKS RUSSIAN PREMIER ON AUSTERITY PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ International Monetary Fund managing director
Michel Camdessus threw his support Friday behind what he described
as the attempts of Russia's new acting prime minister, Viktor
Chernomyrdin, to resurrect an austerity plan for Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He accepts the challenge,'' Camdessus said, in his first
public comment after a hastily arranged meeting with Chernomyrdin
in the Ukraine on Wednesday night. ``Mr. Chernomyrdin has told me
that he recognizes the validity'' of the IMF program for restoring
the Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
   Camdessus and his chief deputy, Stanley Fischer, also suggested,
at a news conference at IMF headquarters in Washington, that if the
Russia fails to embrace the fund's approach, then it would be
fruitless for the IMF for the major industrial nations to lend more
money to Russia to support its currency and economy.
</P>
<P>
   When the ruble began to slide in value earlier this month, ``we
had to decide how much further to go, once it was clear'' that
foreign lenders would no longer roll over short-term loans to
Russia, Fischer said. ``The IMF and its major shareholder decided
that it would take more resources than were available.'' The IMF's
major shareholder is the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Camdessus' remarks seemed clearly aimed at giving Chernomyrdin
public backing in his attempts to convince a racalcitrant
Parliament to reject ``populist'' inflationary policies in favor of
the the conditions the IMF has attached to a recent loan agreement.
The IMF is pushing Russia to move to a balanced budget, restrain
borrowing, and much improve its tax collections.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Boris Yeltsin agreed to these terms in last
month and had received, in return, $4.8 billion in loans from the
IMF to support the ruble. Another $4.3 billion loan was promised
for late September, and this will be forthcoming, Camdessus said
Friday, but only if the Russia shows progress toward meeting the
IMF's conditions for the credits.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The loans are part of an agreement last month between Russia,
the IMF and other international lenders to provide more than $17
billion in additional loans over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin ``indicated that he understood the severity,'' of
the financial crisis in his country, Camdessus said, ``and that the
Russian government was prepared to take the needed action in close
consultation with the political parties and Parliament.''
</P>
<P>
   A political uproar over the IMF's terms played a role in
Yeltsin's decision to sack his reformist prime minister, Sergei
Kiriyenko, last Sunday, and reappoint the more centrist
Chernomyrdin, who was the previous prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Camdessus and Fischer said they were operating in concert with
the seven largest industrial nations that are the IMF's major
contributors. Fischer had been quoted in German and British
newspapers in recent days as having criticized these nations for
failing to provide additional money to bail out Russia as several
of them had for Mexico in 1994, particularly the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, Fischer indicated that he had been misquoted. He
said, ``there was no disagreement between the fund managers and the
G-7''_ the United States and the six other largest industrial
nations _ ``that the resources needed were more than were available
to deal with the problem.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a separate effort to reassure the financial markets, this
time about Latin America, Camdessus announced that the IMF had
invited the finance ministers and central bank chiefs of the
Western Hemisphere nations _ the United States and Canada included
_ to a meeting in Washington late next week. The meeting, the first
of its kind, would attempt to organize ``regional surveillance,''
in which the various nations help each other maintain
market-friendly economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that the IMF's available money, depleted by the
Asian and Russian crises, is unusually low, Camdessus insisted that
the IMF will not cut back its assistance programs. His remark
seemed aimed at getting the IMF's various member countries to come
through with an $85 billion infusion, including $18 billion from
the United States, an amount that the Clinton administration
favors, but many in Congress oppose.
</P>
<P>
   ``If at some point we run out of resources,'' Camdessus said,
``the international community will have to face its
responsibilities and decide whether countries that are helping
themselves should be abandoned by the international community.''
</P>
<P>
   The IMF now has in the bank only about $13 billion not already
committed to lending programs or to other IMF commitments, fund
officials say. That is one of the lowest levels in the IMF's
history. The $13 billion does not include about $10 billion that
the IMF has already earmarked for Russia but has not yet actually
disbursed.
</P>
<P>
   The $4.3 billion loan scheduled for late September would come
out of this $10 billion. That would leave $5.7 billion for future
lending. Since 1992, after Russia had emerged from the former
Soviet Union, it has received a total of $21 billion in IMF loans
and has made repayments on time, according to fund officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
