<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-BROKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECURITIES FIRMS' OWN STOCK PRICES ARE HURTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While banks worldwide have seen values tumble because
of the Russian flu, Wall Street's brokerage firms and investment
banks are suffering from their own version of a severe head cold.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Merrill Lynch and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter are well
off peak prices, trading Friday for about one-third less than they
were in July, when they hit yearly highs. Lehman Brothers Holdings
Inc., which closed at $45.6875 Friday, is fast approaching its
52-week low. Even Travelers Group, the diversified financial
services company that owns the investment bank Salomon Smith
Barney, is off 34 percent since it announced its merger with
Citicorp in April.
</P>
<P>
   Although the weakness in bank stocks is mainly being chalked up
to concerns about loans and investments in Russia and Asia,
brokerage firms are troubled by even more mundane concerns at home:
fear that equity underwriting and trading in fixed-income products
will not be as lucrative this year. Volatile prices and declining
liquidity in corporate and high-yield bonds in recent weeks are
making it harder for brokerage firms to turn a profit in those
products.
</P>
<P>
   And August 1998 has turned out to be one of the worst months in
years in terms of the demand for initial public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, analysts have revised earnings estimates on
brokerage stocks to reflect a growing pessimism regarding Wall
Street's profitability. Friday, for instance, Guy Moszkowski, a
Salomon Smith Barney brokerage analyst, lowered his third-quarter
estimate for Merrill Lynch to $1.05 a share from $1.29, citing
possible weaknesses in its fixed-income trading and equity
underwriting businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Two days earlier, Merrill Lynch lowered its estimates for Lehman
Brothers' 1998 fiscal year earnings to $6.10 a share from $6.35 as
a result of the firm's international market exposure and its
dependence on revenue from fixed-income products.
</P>
<P>
   And the week before, Goldman, Sachs removed Credit Suisse from
its ``recommended for purchase'' list, fearing the company's
exposure to Russian markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is trashing these companies because of uncertainty
about the earnings stream in the next six to eight quarters,'' said
Dean Eberling, a brokerage industry analyst at Putnam, Lovell, de
Guardiola &AMP; Thornton. ``The risk around earnings is as high today
as it was in 1994.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the dimmest spots for brokerage firms is the lucrative
initial-offering market, which has been almost comatose this month.
In August, 19 companies valued at $1.3 billion have gone public,
according to Securities Data Co. That is the lowest number since
January of 1995. Compare that with August 1997, when 49 companies
valued at $2.9 billion went public. While August is typically a
slow month for new issues, analysts fear the volatile markets could
cool any interest in new issues this fall. ``The market has been
severely hampered by the uncertainty in all markets,'' said
Securities Data analyst Richard Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, it is questionable whether Goldman, Sachs _ which
filed a preliminary prospectus last week for its own much-watched
initial public offering _ will be able to command the lofty
premiums partners hoped to get when they voted to go public in
June. That is even more true now, people in the industry say,
because Goldman relies on its trading operations and
initial-offering underwriting for revenue.
</P>
<P>
   While there is nothing to suggest that Goldman will pull the
offering, a discounted price could give some partners reason to
pause.
</P>
<P>
   The one bright spot for all brokerage firms and investment banks
in the third quarter, surprisingly, should be mergers and
acquisitions. It is unlikely that business will halt completely
even in a tumultuous market, and the string of deals closing this
quarter will provide firms with a stream of revenue that should
offset shortfalls in other businesses, Moszkowski said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, low prices could spur some companies to act. ``For
strategic buyers it depends on whether their stock price has
declined,'' he said. If not, but the target has suffered a decline,
``it could be more tempting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
