<SLUG> BC-HOT-ITEMS-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT ITEMS: HAIR SHADES; BOOSTER SHOTS; ARCHITECTURAL PHILOSOPHY;
SHRINKING THIGHS; DRESSING UP THE ROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 30)  
(Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fashion emergency: ``When you're at your desk and
want to wear your glasses on your head, you don't want them to keep
falling in your face, sliding down your nose,'' said Frederic
Fekkai, the entrepreneurial hairdresser. ``It's annoying _ not to
mention unflattering.'' His remedy is a line of women's sunglasses
designed to be worn atop the head.
</P>
<P>
   With specially curved arms and extra-flexible hinges described
as ergonomic temple tips, the shades, created by Fekkai with the
eyewear designer Alain Mikli, can double as hair bands, without the
usual trouble of stretching or damaging the frame or giving the
wearer an unfashionable headache.
</P>
<P>
   They come in colors designed to enhance all hues of hair: green
tortoise for light chestnut or dark red hair, apricot for
strawberry blondes or brunettes, blue for ash blondes. The glasses,
which are $135 to $165 at Fekkai's salon, Saks Fifth Avenue and
Neiman Marcus, have 100 percent ultraviolet-protective lenses to
protect the eyes from the sun _ though not necessarily from hair
gel.
</P>
<P>
   _ ELLEN TIEN
</P>
<P>
   Booster Shots
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the culture of now, no one has time to wait for
vitamin capsules to break down and start working. So tiny vials of
liquid herbal and vitamin supplements are popping up around town,
being consumed by health-minded people looking for a quick jolt.
Made by Nature's Solutions, the vials _ bright orange beakers sold
in six-packs at health-food stores _ are advertised to provide
quicker absorption into the bloodstream and higher potency in
smaller doses. Plus they're cute.
</P>
<P>
   But can they actually provide instant results? ``Liquid vitamins
and herbals enter your system faster, but they still require time
to be absorbed from the stomach,'' said Gayle Reichler, a
nutritionist and the founder of Active Wellness Inc. ``So any
immediate effects you feel are probably a case of mind over
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   That's good enough for Gabrielle Sherb, 25, a Manhattan retail
consultant and marathon runner who downs Nature's Solutions'
Ginseng and Royal Jelly cocktail as if it were espresso. ``I wake
up, drink a shot and start my day,'' she said. ``And in 20 minutes
I feel a difference. It's like, wow, I really do have more
energy.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ELLEN TIEN
</P>
<P>
   Architectural Philosophy
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alberta Ferretti is a designer known for her subtly
layered look: tulle over cotton, a sliver of hand-beaded gauze
peeking out from beneath the hem of a wool dress. So when Ms.
Ferretti, who is based in Milan, Italy, asked the Manhattan
architect David Ling to design her first store in New York,
Philosophy di Alberta Ferretti, which opens in SoHo on Tuesday, he
came up with the architectural equivalent of her clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The pristinely white 1,000-square-foot shop is a light-filled
study of layers, from the sheer cotton scrim that veils the
staircase to the running water glimpsed beneath a translucent glass
floor. ``The wood is analogous to the wools and cashmere, the glass
to the transparent fabric, the mirror to the crystal beading,'' Ms.
Ferretti said.
</P>
<P>
   All the philosophy behind the design may not be instantly
apparent to the clothes horses visiting the store, at 452 West
Broadway, near Prince Street. But if they miss at first the
hand-waxed finish on the walls or the hand-rubbed patina on the
furniture, that's OK with Ling. ``Unlike the typical SoHo loft,
which is seen and understood at one glance,'' he said, ``I want
people to peer around corners and unpeel the layers.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ELAINE LOUIE
</P>
<P>
   Shrink Your Thighs
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jungian analysis interprets the psyche through
archetypes. Now it's being applied to treat body types. Dr. DeAnsin
Parker, a psychotherapist and the founder of the Goodson Parker
Wellness Center, a gym and health club at 30 East 76th St. visited
by celebrities like Elle Macpherson, Kyra Sedgwick and Yasmeen
Ghauri, is taking the craze for mind-and-body merging a step
further than power yoga.
</P>
<P>
   Using Myers-Briggs test questions (``Are you usually a good
mixer or quiet and reserved?''), Dr. Parker offers hourlong
sessions, for $200, to classify clients into one of four
personality types _ and matches them to a workout that she says is
``spiritually appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   For an introverted-integrated personality type, who likes to
function on multiple levels, she suggests sports with complex
circular movements, like golf. For a concrete personality type, who
needs to see results and statistics, a treadmill is what the doctor
orders.
</P>
<P>
   But some Jungian experts believe it takes more than an hour to
classify a personality type. ``Jung wouldn't like it,'' said Paul
Wink, a psychology professor at Wellesley College. ``He was always
skeptical of Americans' need for a quick fix.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressing Up the Robe
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Grooming to look good apparently isn't enough. These
days, New Yorkers need to look good while they groom, and they are
making fashion statements even while wrapped in frumpy protective
robes in salons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got women wearing their own Hermes belts outside the
robe, sticking in shoulder pads, flashing peekaboo lingerie,'' said
Steven Berg, a stylist at John Barrett Salon in Bergdorf Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   At Kim Lepine on Madison Avenue, brooches on robes are a must.
``Robes can be pretty uninspiring,'' Ms. Lepine, the owner, said.
``Dressing them up makes you feel better.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg offers pointers: Avoid jeans, because they create a lumpish
effect. Pull the belt straight and flat for a neater finish. And
men, for heaven's sake, keep your pants on. ``A lot of guys think
they're at the doctor and take everything off,'' he said. ``A short
robe, hairy legs and dark socks is not a good look.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ELLEN TIEN
</P>
</TEXT>
