<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8310 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIANAWHY?-AZR &LR;      08-28 1597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIANA HAD `IT`: THE MYSTERIOUS POWER TO ENCHANT 
</HEADLINE>
 WHY?-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KYLE LAWSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - It is the fate of princesses and commoners to die.
Most pass without fanfare, but for a few the trumpets sound. What
is there about a Diana, a James Dean, a John F. Kennedy or a
Rudolph Valentino that engages the imagination and hearts of
millions?
</P>
<P>
   The vast outpouring of grief and affection that accompanied the
Princess of Wales to her grave caught many by surprise. They asked,
and still ask, ``Why did she touch so many?''
</P>
<P>
   They could do worse than turn to Elinor Glyn for the answer.
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the Jazz Age, a Hollywood fan magazine asked
the English novelist to define celebrity appeal. Glyn, notorious
for her florid prose and her penchant for receiving callers in the
nude, summed it up in one word.
</P>
<P>
   ``It.''
</P>
<P>
   `` `It' is that quality possessed by some which draws all others
with its magnetic force,'' she wrote. ``With `It' you can draw all
men, if you are a woman, and all women, if you are a man. `It' can
be a quality of the mind, as well as a physical attraction.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Madame Glyn, as she insisted on being called, gave examples.
Clara Bow had ``It.'' So did Greta Garbo and Rudolph Valentino.
Charles Lindbergh and Albert Einstein were loaded with the
commodity. Even Calvin Coolidge was no stranger to the phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe she was wrong about Coolidge, but even so, Glyn was on
to something.
</P>
<P>
   Every so often the human gene pool tosses up an individual with
the power to enchant the rest of the species. Is it black magic or
sexual chemistry? Manipulation or circumstance? Thousands of words
have been written on the subject but none explain it any more
clearly than Madame Glyn's single syllable.
</P>
<P>
   A few have that indefinable something. The rest of us don't.
</P>
<P>
   Diana, in whatever manifestation she chose to parade herself _
Sloan Street Ranger, Princess of Wales, devoted mother, adulterous
wife or tireless worker for good causes _ was simply the latest in
a long line of those possessed of ``It.'' What sets her apart is
the textbook illustration she provides on how an individual can
sidestep the normal banality of life and pass into the iconography
and, ultimately, the mythology of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Like her predecessors in that regard, Diana didn't ask for
``It;'' she was born with charisma and an instinct for manipulating
her environment. Like most of those who receive such gifts, she was
fated to live on a grand scale, with her Feragamo pumps mired in
the clay even as her tiara pierced the clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Sanctity and soap opera are a vulgar mix but it is the life's
blood of this chosen few.
</P>
<P>
   It is the vanity of our age to believe that media celebrities
are a contemporary invention. The chain of succession probably
stretches back to a cave somewhere in Africa's Rift Valley, when an
apelike individual found himself (or perhaps herself) lifted above
the shoulders of the hairy throng.
</P>
<P>
   The invention of the printing press and the media circus it
ultimately unleashed didn't increase the ranks of those with
``It,'' it simply stratosphered their publicity. Circulars and
broadsheets, then newspapers and tabloids spread the word, joined
in the 20th century by movies, TV and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to this adulation and exposure, the ``Its'' have defined
the planet's dreams even as they aroused its fantasies, shocked it
with their behavior and titillated it with their all-too-human
failings.
</P>
<P>
   The power can be insidious as well as inspirational. There is a
dark side to the force, as George Lucas warned in his ``Star Wars''
trilogy, the best-ever evocation of celebrity (every character in
the trio of films has ``It''). Genghis Khan possessed the quality,
so did Hitler, Idi Amin and Pol Pot. One of the hallmarks of the
breed is the ability to ensnare hearts and minds, whether for good
or evil.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the ``It'' qualities, charisma is the hardest to pin
down, yet the most necessary to the holder's appeal. What is it
about some people that asks _ no, demands _ that we look at them?
Spread out a dozen photographs of crowds containing Diana in their
midst and the eye almost immediately goes to her.
</P>
<P>
   It's not really about looks. No one can call Humphrey Bogart
cute or Bette Davis classically beautiful. Helen's face may have
launched a naval armada, but Cleopatra was by all accounts a rather
dumpy woman. Napoleon, whose reputation as a stud owed nothing to
invention, didn't let being short and a bit bow-legged slow him
down.
</P>
<P>
   What made Diana seem beautiful to us? Dollmakers are learning
how difficult it is to capture her appearance. Few of the replicas
look like the princess; in frustration, the designers concentrate
on the gowns. That inner glow, that intensity of spirit, is not
susceptible to molds of porcelain or vinyl.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage of hindsight is that we can see that it was always
there, even in Diana's first public engagements. Behind the
gawkiness and inexperience lurks the glint of humor, the suggestion
of genuine humanity and depth. Like John Wayne, who showed up in
his first movie, ``The Big Trail,'' with the legend largely intact,
only younger and better looking, Diana made her entrance with her
flags in place, needing only time and maturity to unfurl them and
set them flying.
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone truly possessed of ``It,'' Diana could touch those
around her in subtle but powerful ways. Recently, ``TV Guide''
published a picture of the princess walking with Sir Richard
Attenborough. As always, the eye focuses on her, but her attention
is squarely on Sir Richard. Intensely, physically so. Something
passes from nerve end to nerve end in these instances, the feeling
that in spite of their fame and beauty, these people really care
about us. (begin ital)``We'' (end ital) are important to them _ and
therefore of consequence, regardless of how lowly our status is in
comparison to theirs.
</P>
<P>
   It can't be denied that part of the appeal is sexual. There is a
physical chemistry involved, one that isn't reproducible in the
laboratory but is no less real for all that. People with ``It''
have something extra, and a good chunk of it is carnal. Marilyn
Monroe's impact was hormonal, as was the young Marlon Brando's. In
Napoleon's day, women swooned over his painted portrait, even as
they did a hundred years later over the filmed image of Valentino.
</P>
<P>
   One suspects that a portion of the sympathy poured out on Diana
was a subconscious response to the dichotomy of a vibrant,
life-affirming woman paired up with a stick like Charles. It was
hard enough to picture them having a decent conversation, much less
in bed.
</P>
<P>
   One would like to take the high-minded approach and ignore the
more human failings of Diana and the other ``Its,'' but it is their
behavior as much as anything that elevates them into the realm of
legend. Arthur may have created the Round Table, but it is his
wife's adultery that is the stuff of Broadway musicals. Helen was a
married woman. So, for that matter, was Cleopatra _ to her brother.
And when it comes to sex, the less said about Grover Cleveland and
JFK the better, while even today's tabloids might shy at printing
the details of Clara Bow's affair with Gary Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feet of clay'' is more than a cliche. It is virtually a
requirement for iconhood. The average person leads a mundane
existence; a little soap opera is to be relished, and the juicier
the details, the tastier the feast.
</P>
<P>
   If not soap opera, then tragedy. The kidnapping and death of
Lindbergh's baby has as much to do with his legend as his solo
flight across the Atlantic. The wealthy passengers on the
``Titanic'' are as real to the modern world as they were to the
public of 1912.
</P>
<P>
   And, always, a touch of mystery plays well. Was it Princess
Grace or her daughter at the wheel? Did Marilyn commit suicide or
was she murdered?
</P>
<P>
   Of the world's billions, few are paged for their 15 minutes of
fame, and fewer still emerge as genuine celebrities. Of that
number, only a handful are raised by virtue of personal charisma or
fate to the level of icon and myth.
</P>
<P>
   It can be argued that we worship these people for the wrong
reasons, and, mostly, we do. But every now and then we get it
right. From the ranks of these emotional flytraps, we settle on a
few that, in spite of their shortcomings, aspire to and achieve, as
much as is ever humanly possible, something worthy of our
admiration.
</P>
<P>
   Being what we are, we won't forget Diana's bulimia, her
relationships with the royals or her manipulation of public
opinion. But what will kindle our imagination and hope, and the
imagination and hope of future generations, is that she genuinely
tried to make the world she inherited a better place. Even as JFK
tried, and Joan of Arc and Mother Teresa and Gandhi and all the
rest tried.
</P>
<P>
   Her achievements cannot be equated with theirs, but there is no
result without intent. It was Diana's gift of charisma and fateful
life that made her first a celebrity, then an icon for an age. But
it was her heart, which she wore on her sleeve and shared with all,
that may, in years to come, transform her into an enduring myth.
</P>
<P>
   What is mythology's role if not to instruct the race to a nobler
end? And what is Diana's legacy if not the determination that no
matter what the gods send, one must endure and soldier on?
</P>
<P>
   Love her, despise her or simply remain indifferent: She had what
it takes. She had ``It.''
</P>
<P>
   And ``It'' will not be denied. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
