<SLUG> BC-MRV-SHARES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRV SHARES DROP SHARPLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shares in telecommunications equipment maker MRV
Communications lost more than half their value Friday, a day after
the company said it will experience lower-than-expected
third-quarter sales.
</P>
<P>
   Like thousands of publicly traded firms, MRV saw its share price
dip in Thursday's big market sell-off, losing $2.50, or 14.8
percent of its value. But while other companies were breathing
easier Friday, MRV shares were melting down.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 10 minutes of trading the issue dropped 42.6
percent, going from $14 3/8 a share to $8 1/4. By the end of the
day, the share price had lost $7 9/16, or 52.6 percent of its
value. More than 11.5 million shares in the company traded hands,
roughly 22 times its three-month average daily volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not exactly what I expected,'' said MRV President and
Chief Executive Officer Noam Lotan, who said he spent nearly all of
Friday speaking with investors, reassuring them about the company's
fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts, too, were caught off guard by the plunge. ``It seems a
bit excessive unless there's another story we don't know about,''
said Craig Bernstein at First Montauk Securities. ``Just yesterday
it looked like $14 or $15 would be the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, Lotan said weak sales of the company's existing
networking products, particularly in Europe, will mean
third-quarter revenues 10 to 15 percent below the $65.7 million
generated in the second quarter. Also, delays in the introduction
of next-generation products meant to launch this quarter will pinch
earnings. The products are now slated to arrive in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding its sales woes, MRV's gross margins will shrink,
Lotan said, as costs for research, development and general expenses
will rise 8 percent to 10 percent above the $17.4 million reported
in the second quarter. Lotan said that would hurt earnings, but
would not speculate by how much. Before Thursday's announcement,
MRV was expected to earn 31 to 32 cents a share by analysts
surveyed by IBES International Inc. and First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lotan said, the company will not lose money and should
experience a 30 percent or more increase in third-quarter sales,
year-to-year. Last year the company had earnings of $5.92 million,
or 23 cents a share, on sales of $42 million. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
