u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGO-REBELLION-NYT &LR;      08-28 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-REBELLION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT SAID TO GAIN UPPER HAND IN CONGO'S CAPITAL
</HEADLINE>
  (See related CONGO-ARMY-VOLUNTEERS)  
(jw) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo _ Two days after heavy shelling and gunfire
erupted on the capital's fringes, government forces continued to
assert control over the area Friday, and fighting with rebels was
confined to a few pockets.
</P>
<P>
   On city streets that had been deserted in the last two days,
life was closer to normal, and residents could be seen selling
goods and traveling around despite numerous security checkpoints.
Government soldiers moved around in trucks, flashing victory signs,
chanting songs and firing automatic weapons into the air.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials warned that it was too early to claim final
victory in Kinshasa. But it appeared that the threat of a rebel
takeover of Kinshasa _ which had seemed all but inevitable before
Angola and Zimbabwe began supplying arms and men to President
Laurent Kabila _ is now greatly diminished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if the rebels really intended it,'' said a Western
diplomat here, ``they would have come in a big way last night or
the night before. All of this now seems to have been a half-hearted
attempt by the rebels to stir the pot to see what would happen, and
the government is getting the situation under control.''
</P>
<P>
   The government continued to prevent foreign journalists from
reporting freely in the city. But on a trip to the airport,
organized by the government, the effects of the war were visible.
Thousands of residents, who were fleeing outlying areas where the
fighting had been concentrated, could be seen marching toward the
city's center in single file, many pushing handcarts and carrying
other belongings.
</P>
<P>
   A great number of people could also be seen leaving a
residential neighborhood near a forest where rebels were supposed
to be hiding. Government soldiers said they were preparing to bomb
the forest.
</P>
<P>
   City residents coming to downtown hotels also reported seeing
more instances of public killings that began on Thursday. Bodies of
suspected rebels could be seen throughout the city, some hanging
from trees, they said. One taxi driver said he saw soldiers push
four men into a river near a sports stadium and shoot them before a
cheering crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels, who are led by ethnic Tutsi in eastern Congo and are
believed to be backed by Rwanda and Uganda, still control key
cities in eastern Congo. But they have been weakened in the area
southwest of Kinshasa because of the support the government has
received from Angola and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   The government and its allies say they are expected to
eventually eliminate the rebel presence in the southwest, and
Western diplomats here agree that is likely. Rebels still control
critical points, however, including a giant hydroelectric dam that
supplies electricity to the Kinshasa region.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials took reporters to Kinshasa's main airport,
near where the most intense fighting had taken place on Wednesday.
No gunfire was heard in the area.
</P>
<P>
   In the airport's VIP lounge, furnished with plush beige sofas
and glass coffee tables, government officials showed reporters nine
young men, whom they said had been taken prisoner in battles
southwest of Kinshasa. Six of the men identified themselves as
Rwandan, and spoke the languages of Rwanda. The others said they
were Congolese.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kagame sends children to die here, and here is the evidence,''
said Mawapanga Mwana Nanga, the Congo's minister of agriculture,
referring to Paul Kagame, the Rwandan vice president and defense
minister.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda have denied supporting the rebellion against
Kabila, although most Western officials believe that they have.
Both countries played key roles in choosing Kabila to lead a
successful rebellion less than two years ago against Mobutu Sese
Seko, the country's dictator for 32 years.
</P>
<P>
   But relations between Kabila and his Rwandan sponsors soured
after he distanced himself from them. Kabila's close ties with the
Rwandans and the ethnic Tutsi had made him unpopular among the
Congolese.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
