<TEXT>
<P>
   The following Arizona Republic story has been added for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, Aug. 30. If you
have any questions, please contact the Republic News Desk at (602)
271-8108.
</P>
<P>
   DIANA-WHY (Undated) - It is the fate of princesses and commoners
to die. Most pass without fanfare, but for a few the trumpets
sound. What is there about a Diana, a James Dean, a John F. Kennedy
or a Rudolph Valentino that engages the imagination and hearts of
millions?Why did she touch so many? We could do worse than turn to
Elinor Glyn for the answer. At the height of the Jazz Age, a
Hollywood fan magazine asked the English novelist to define
celebrity appeal. Glyn, notorious for her florid prose and her
penchant for receiving callers in the nude, summed it up in one
word.
</P>
<P>
   ``It.'' By KYLE LAWSON. Story moved in the ``A`` category.
EMBARGOED FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 30. &QL; 
 &QL;
