<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8319 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATTACK-U.S.-ODEH-NYT &LR;      08-28 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTACK-U.S.-ODEH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELATIVES CALL EMBASSY BOMB SUSPECT STRICT BUT KIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also ATTACK-U.S., ATTACK-U.S.-SUSPECTS) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY JR.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOMBASA, Kenya _ Salim Nassor Salim still remembers the day he
stopped talking to his brother-in-law, Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, the
man charged Friday with taking part in the bombing of the American
Embassy in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   About a year and a half ago, Salim said, he was driving a car
with Odeh in the back seat in the coastal town of Malindi. A
smoker, Salim had lit a cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   Without a word, Odeh, a conservative Muslim who objected to
smoking on religious grounds, reached forward and ripped the
cigarette from his brother-in-law's lips, scratching them badly and
drawing blood. He then threw it out the window with silent
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not something to be done by someone with a good
mind,'' Salim said.
</P>
<P>
   While relatives said they had no clue that Odeh might have been
living a secret life as a terrorist, the incident may have been a
rare glimpse into his inner fury.
</P>
<P>
   Odeh has admitted to federal agents that he is part of a
dedicated and well-trained terrorist organization, based in
Afghanistan but operating worldwide, according to the indictment
against him.
</P>
<P>
   But for the last four years he managed to persuade his wife's
relatives in Kenya that he was a simple fisherman and carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   His relatives said that while he was man with strict religious
values, they nonetheless considered him kind and humble, as well as
a good husband. ``He didn't tell us about it if he was working for
any international societies,'' Salim said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his stay in Kenya, Odeh's outward face was that of an
entrepreneur, struggling to make enough money with fishing and
carpentry to provide for his young wife, Nassim Nassor Salim, and
their infant son, Yasser.
</P>
<P>
   Until his relatives heard that he had been arrested in Pakistan
on Aug. 7 _ the same day twin car bombs exploded in Kenya and
Tanzania, killing more than 260 people _ none had gleaned any
reason to suspect differently. He had not even told his wife he was
leaving the country.
</P>
<P>
   He never spoke to his wife's family about his past, his
relatives said. He arrived in Mombasa in mid-August 1994, bearing a
Jordanian passport and saying he was a student. The passport said
he had been born in Saoudia, in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   By October 1994, he had married Ms. Salim, a bright young woman
from Malindi who had gone to the best Koranic school in Nairobi. It
was a match arranged by mutual friends.
</P>
<P>
   Odeh practiced a strict form of Islam, his acquaintances said.
He objected strenuously to the family photographs on the walls, to
people smoking, to a woman showing her hair or ankles in public.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the rest of her family, Ms. Salim had also adopted
conservative ideas about religion while she was going to school at
Madras, a well-known Islamic college in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after their marriage, Odeh bought a fiberglass boat from
Somalia with a powerful motor, his relatives said. He started a
fishing business and took an apartment in Kisauni, a slum outside
the ancient and bedraggled port of Mombasa, where Islamic and
African people of other religions have existed side by side for
centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick Moturi, a real estate agent who rented him the house,
said Odeh had told him he was a fisherman who had dropped out of
engineering college after two years. ``I didn't see anything wrong
with him,'' Moturi said. ``To me he seemed like a good guy. Gentle.
Humble.''
</P>
<P>
   For three years, his family said, Odeh plied the fisherman's
trade. But he traveled frequently into Somali waters and brought
fish not only to busy ports like Malindi and Mombasa, but also to
less traveled ones known for smuggling, like Kiunga, Lamu, Ngomeni
and Kilifi. Sometimes he would be gone for a week at a time, his
relatives said.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, in 1996 he obtained a Kenyan birth certificate, and
then, in November of that year, an official Kenyan identity card,
which listed his hometown as Malindi and his date of birth as 1975,
according to copies of the documents seen by The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   He applied for a Kenyan passport in 1998 with these phony
documents. It remains unclear whether the Kenyan authorities issued
him one.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Odeh abruptly abandoned fishing, maintaining
life in Mombasa was too expensive, his family members said. In
January, he moved to his mother-in-law's simple house in the remote
northeastern village of Witu. He started a carpentry workshop,
producing ornately carved furniture, his relatives said.
</P>
<P>
   They said he frequently quarreled with them about religious
doctrine, especially prohibitions against tobacco and laws
governing relations with women. He read the Koran incessantly, and
was fond of quoting from it when he scolded people for their lax
adherence to Muslim laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good man,'' said a younger brother-in-law, Ali Nassor
Salim. ``He used to be a very religious person and always likes to
give you advice about religion.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, at the family home in the Kisauni section of
Mombasa, his wife declined a request for an interview. Other family
members said Ms. Salim was convinced that her husband was innocent,
but she said she knew nothing more about the case than what she had
read in the newspapers. ``I am fine,'' she said, looking exhausted
and distraught. ``I can say nothing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
