<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-605&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: R.I.)  
 WHEN THE BISHOP FINDS HERSELF IN NEED OF PRAYER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earlier this month, when nearly 800 Anglican bishops from around
the world gathered at the Lambeth Conference, their once-a-decade
meeting in Canterbury, England, one of the more public faces seemed
to belong to one of the newer prelates, Bishop Geralyn Wolf, head
of the Episcopal Church's Diocese of Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Wolf, one of only 11 women among the bishops at the
conference, was also one of a handful of prelates featured in a
film produced for the meeting by Trinity Television, of Trinity
Church in New York, that was shown in the conference's Bible study
sessions. In her segment, she spoke about the fear and grace she
encountered during a serious illness two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As many people in her diocese probably remember, breast cancer
was diagnosed in Bishop Wolf in June 1996, four months after she
had become the first woman to be an Episcopal bishop in Rhode
Island (and the second ever to head a diocese in the
2.4-million-member church).
</P>
<P>
   She did not wait long to inform the 100-plus priests in the
diocese about her condition. Two days later, by coincidence, the
U.S. Postal Service issued a stamp calling attention to breast
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The Providence Journal-Bulletin noted the conjunction of the two
events, Bishop Wolf recalled in a recent interview. Through news
coverage, she found herself a public figure who not only was
experiencing suffering but also was expected to interpret it from a
religious standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided it was really important to speak the truth on
this,'' Bishop Wolf said, ``and to take something that was hidden
and allow it to be revealed to a wider public. I also thought it
was a good opportunity to combine the realities of my own faith and
what I was going through.''
</P>
<P>
   Articles in The Journal-Bulletin chronicled her radical and
reconstructive surgery, followed by chemotherapy and recuperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back on it,'' she said, ``I wanted to show perhaps a
different face to Christianity, one that was more realistic, that
could speak to the experiences people have and not be afraid of
those experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Bishop Wolf said she thought it was not unusual
for people experiencing tragedy or suffering to feel as if they
were not dealing well enough with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel as though there's a certain way to do it,'' she
said. ``I was trying to say that the only way I know is with a lot
of heartache and tears and doubts and anxieties, in the midst of
seeking God's presence. I didn't want to pretend that my
relationship with God relieved me of the very real experience of
heartache that I had.''
</P>
<P>
   During that time, Bishop Wolf said, she was sometimes frustrated
by well-meaning people who flatly assured her that she would
recover, because they were praying for her. She said she had felt
more comfortable with those who could be quietly supportive of her
``in the midst of my not knowing'' where the illness would lead.
</P>
<P>
   This, she said, came close to her idea of a healing ministry,
one that ``honored'' the experience of suffering and left open the
possibility that it might hold some meaning for the person
undergoing it.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Wolf said she drew a distinction between such a person
and the sort who seems to enjoy suffering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm talking about suffering that leads to life and that holds
within it hope,'' she said. ``That's different from those who want
to stay where they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, she said, she believes that the capacity to suffer can work
as ``an extraordinary gift'' to human beings, ``because it speaks
so much to our ability to feel deeply about life's experiences and
other people.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Her own experience may have sharpened her response to a moment
at the Lambeth Conference: Having attended a presentation about
African food shortages and violence that had left many children
malnourished and dying, she said aloud that she felt too
overwhelmed to speak. An African archbishop responded that no one
should be able to speak in the presence of such horror.
</P>
<P>
   Two years have passed since her surgery, and Bishop Wolf, who is
51, said that she had finally regained her strength after
chemotherapy and that her health was good.
</P>
<P>
   Women who know of her experience still stop her in the
supermarket in Providence to share their own stories. She listens,
she said, and tries to encourage them to seek support and guidance.
Once a week, she feels the need to go shopping in Boston, where she
will not be recognized.
</P>
<P>
   After she appeared in the film at the Lambeth Conference, Bishop
Wolf said she got a call from a priest who had been found to have
breast cancer and felt guilty that she could no longer meet her
parishioners' needs. That reaction, Bishop Wolf said, is not
uncommon in people with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   And it led her to offer another thought: ``People want so much
for the leader to be happy that it's hard to see the leader as
continually vulnerable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
