<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSLIMS-JIHAD-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN A JIHAD FLOUTS THE RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Osama bin Laden, the renegade Saudi financier linked to the
recent bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, has
justified his call to kill Americans by citing Muslim holy law.
``Allah ordered us in this religion to purify Muslim land of all
nonbelievers,'' he said in an interview with ABC in May.
</P>
<P>
   Libya, Iraq and militant Islamic groups have also applauded the
bombings. Meanwhile, leaders in the Arab-American community and
Islamic specialists have argued that such terrorists have distorted
Islam's traditional teachings. And in a speech last week, President
Clinton made a point of drawing a distinction between Muslim
extremists and traditional Muslims _ the ``hundreds of millions of
good, peace-loving people all around the world,'' as he described
them _ who condemn the killing of noncombatants in terrorist
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But just what does Muslim holy law say about these kinds of
terrorist attacks?
</P>
<P>
   Islamic holy law, or sharia, is based on the Koran and the
precepts and practices of the Muslim prophet Mohammed and his
seventh-century companions.
</P>
<P>
   Islam, of course, is open to many interpretations. But several
Islamic scholars who live in the West say that bin Laden has
justified his jihad, or holy war, against the United States by a
highly unorthodox, though increasingly common interpretation of
Islamic law and political tradition. Following in the tradition of
other 20th-century radicals, like Sayyid Qutb, the Egyptian
militant theorist executed in 1966, bin Laden argues that a war
against the United States is obligatory because of U.S.``crimes''
against Islam.
</P>
<P>
   These are often listed as America's presence on sacred Saudi
Arabian soil, support for rulers throughout the Middle East whom
the radicals say are ``un-Islamic'' and corrupt, Washington's
``blind support'' for what is characterized as Israel's ``theft''
of Muslim land and persecution of Palestinians, and supposed U.S.
indifference to the suffering of Bosnian Muslims. During his May
interview, bin Laden made a point of saying, ``After World War II,
the Americans became more aggressive and oppressive, especially in
the Muslim world,'' adding, ``We do not differentiate between those
dressed in military uniforms and civilians; they are all targets in
this fatwa.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Islamic scholars, however, argue that the holy war bin
Laden has declared violates not only the elaborate regulations of
Islamic law as traditionally accepted, but also Arab tribal custom.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Awn, professor of religion and Middle Eastern studies at
Columbia University, said that according to classical Islamic law,
a jihad must be fought for the ultimate good of the Muslim faith.
``It cannot be used simply for economic or political gain,'' Awn
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to mainstream Muslim jurists and scholars, there are
four kinds of legitimate warfare in Islam, including wars against
infidels and apostates, which are both jihads; all must be declared
and conducted by the Muslim ruler of a state, or failing that,
Islamic wise men. Bin Laden, of course, is not a leader of a state.
Nor is he a qadi, a judge, or a mufti, a Muslim legal scholar, Awn
added, and thus, is unqualified to issue what his supporters call
fatwas, his religious rulings or opinions justifying the
anti-American campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Quadir Amiryar, a political scientist at George Washington
University, agrees with Awn and notes that many of those who issue
fatwas don't follow the detailed procedures that Islamic law
requires.
</P>
<P>
   He also argues that spreading Islam ``by the sword'' is
traditionally considered a last resort. While it might have been
justified during the invasion of Afghanistan, he said, ``that
justification evaporated with the departure of the Soviet Union.''
True, many Muslim clerics in the Middle East and elsewhere have
interpreted Muslim law to justify terrorism, but Amiryar argues
that those calls for jihad often stem from frustration with their
own leadership: ``They are using these Islamic concepts in other
contexts which were originally not intended.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his 1996 book on jihad, Rudolph Peters, a Dutch scholar,
argues that while the umma, or Muslim community, has a duty to
``expand the territory of the state,'' the doctrine of jihad
forbids, among other things, the killing of noncombatants like
children, women and elderly people.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, it would appear that even if Islamic law were stretched to
consider women and children at the U.S. embassies combatants, the
hundreds of Africans, many of whom are Muslims, who were killed
near those embassies could not be considered combatants.
</P>
<P>
   Muslim law also provides that ambassadors and their missions be
respected as long as they do not engage in espionage. (That's why
the Islamic government in Tehran insisted on characterizing the
U.S. embassy where hostages were seized in the 1970s as ``a nest of
spies'').
</P>
<P>
   Peters says a ``war against unbelievers may not be mounted
without summoning them to Islam or submission before an attack.''
In other words, people should be given a chance to embrace Islam as
their faith before they are killed.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden's defense of and reported ties to Egyptian and
Palestinian suicide attacks on Israeli and U.S. targets are also
questionable under traditional Islamic precepts, scholars say.
Islamic holy law forbids suicide. According to the traditions of
the Prophet Mohammed, which believers claim are divinely inspired,
the punishment is eternal repetition of the act by which a person
dies. So if a man hangs himself, he'll spend an eternity choking.
</P>
<P>
   But as Awn points out, Islam endorses martyrdom _ fighting, and
if necessary, dying for one's faith. And one Muslim's suicide might
be another's martyrdom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
