<HEADLINE>
EXPLODED DELTA ROCKET'S GUIDANCE SYSTEM FAILED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A guidance system failure caused Boeing's new Delta III rocket
to veer out of control and break apart about a minute into its
inaugural flight from Cape Canaveral Wednesday night, the leader of
the accident investigation team said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rocket motors on the Delta III were trying so hard to steer the
wavering vehicle during its final seconds of flight that they
literally ran out of hydraulic fluid. The rocket then pitched over
more than 30 degrees and was ripped apart by aerodynamic forces and
its self-destruct system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a car. When you don't have power steering you're in
trouble,'' said Clarence Quan, a Boeing engineer who is heading up
the investigation. He and others on the team spoke to reporters
Friday during a news teleconference at Cape Canaveral.
</P>
<P>
   Quan said engineers believe they will be able to fix the
guidance system problem _ once they understand it _ and launch the
next Delta III by February, which would mean only a four-month
delay in the program.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has delayed Tuesday's launch of a Delta II rocket that
will carry 5 communication satellites for Motorola's Iridium
project.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the guidance systems on the two rockets are not the
same, engineers want a few more days to study the data from the
Delta III accident before going ahead with the Delta II launch from
Vandenberg Air Force Base in California.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's news conference was remarkable for its openness,
veteran aerospace journalists said. Usually, investigations into
the cause of rocket explosions are shrouded in secrecy, especially
when the booster or payload is military.
</P>
<P>
   But the Delta III program is entirely commercial, and that is
why Boeing decided to make the accident investigation as public as
possible. Delta III is the first large booster ever developed
through the private sector without government help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to have an open investigation,'' Quan said. ``We
want to keep our customers informed ... and the public.''
</P>
<P>
   During the news conference, investigators also disclosed that a
large piece of burning rocket debris that witnesses along the coast
off Cape Canaveral saw hit the ocean and explode into an eerie,
orange mushroom cloud was actually the Galaxy X communications
satellite that was being carried into orbit for PanAmSat Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Because the piece was so large, there had been speculation the
rocket's destruct system did not work properly. In event a rocket
goes out of control, the destruct system is supposed to blow it up
into tiny pieces.
</P>
<P>
   But the satellite was blown out and away from the Delta III when
it exploded, said Roger DeVivo, a chief flight analyst with the Air
Force's range safety office.
</P>
<P>
   When the 4-ton, $200 million satellite hit the ocean about 15
miles offshore, it still had most of its internal fuel needed to
maneuver the satellite in orbit. That fuel resulted in a blast
equivalent to 532 pounds of TNT, DeVivo said. That is enough to
cause a mushroom-like cloud, he said.
</P>
<P>
   All the rocket pieces fell where they were supposed to, in an
area of the Atlantic that had been cleared of all boats before
launch.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear from the news conference that investigators have
collected a lot of data about what happened to the Delta III.
</P>
<P>
   The flight went as expected for the first 55 seconds, Quan said.
Then the Delta III began to oscillate. Over the next few seconds,
the rocket's main engine and three thrust-vectoring solid rocket
motors strapped to the side tried to regain control, but
overcompensated for unknown reasons. The three solid rocket motors
made so many corrections they used up all their hydraulic fluid and
the main engine alone was not enough to steer the rocket.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 seconds into the flight, the rocket pitched over and
broke up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what happened,'' said Rich Murphy, Boeing's launch
site director. ``Now we've got to find out why it happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
