<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-465&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO ACCOUNTS OF GIFT RETRIEVAL VARY, LAWYERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Monica Lewinsky and Betty Currie, President
Clinton's personal secretary, have offered a grand jury different
versions of one element in the investigation of obstruction of
justice by Clinton, lawyers familiar with their accounts said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The contrasting accounts concern who told Mrs. Currie to show up
at Ms. Lewinsky's apartment last winter to retrieve gifts that
Clinton had given Ms. Lewinsky, the lawyers said. Mrs. Currie
testified that Ms. Lewinsky, a former White House intern, had
telephoned her and told her to come by and get the gifts; Ms.
Lewinsky testified that Mrs. Currie had simply shown up, presumably
having been told to do so by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel, is
investigating whether the president sought to obstruct justice by
trying to conceal the gifts, including some T-shirts, a hat pin, a
brooch and souvenirs from New York and Martha's Vineyard, Mass.,
from lawyers for Paula Jones, a former Arkansas clerical employee
who had sued Clinton for sexual misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   As part of their unsuccessful effort to demonstrate that Clinton
and Ms. Lewinsky had had an intimate relationship, Mrs. Jones'
lawyers had asked Ms. Lewinsky to turn over any gifts she had
received from the president. The Jones lawyers wanted to
demonstrate a pattern of sexual misbehavior by him with
subordinates.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's advisers hope that the testimony of Mrs. Currie, who
has been cast before the public as an honorable witness, would tend
to support an interpretation that Ms. Lewinsky orchestrated the
transfer of gifts herself without the president's involvement and
that thus he did not obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
   But the conflicts in testimony between Ms. Lewinsky and Mrs.
Currie may ultimately be less important than the conflict in
testimony between Ms. Lewinsky and the president himself.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton testified before the grand jury nearly two weeks ago
that he had told Ms. Lewinsky she had no choice but to comply with
the subpoena from the Jones lawyers to turn over the gifts, lawyers
familiar with his testimony said. Ms. Lewinsky has testified that
Clinton counseled her that she would not have to turn over the
gifts if they were no longer in her possession, other lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   As Starr's investigation moves toward its conclusion, Bruce
Lindsey, one of Clinton's closest and longest-serving advisers,
testified again before the grand jury Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The White House had tried to block the testimony of Lindsey, the
deputy White House counsel, on grounds that it would violate the
president's right to confidential legal advice. The Supreme Court
agreed to hear the matter after it reconvenes in October but
refused to order Starr to wait until then before hearing from
Lindsey.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a related inquiry, Linda Tripp, the former colleague of Ms.
Lewinsky who recorded their conversations about a presidential
affair, was told when she bought the tape recorder that it was
illegal to secretly record telephone conversations in Maryland, The
Baltimore Sun reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun said that a clerk at the Radio Shack store where Mrs.
Tripp had bought the recorder had testified before the Maryland
grand jury that is investigating Mrs. Tripp for possible
wiretapping violations. The clerk, Antoine Burrell, 21, told The
Sun, ``I know she was told.'' He did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp was an important figure in starting the investigation
of whether Clinton had a sexual liaison with Ms. Lewinsky and then
tried to cover it up. She took hours of recorded conversations with
Ms. Lewinsky to Starr, who quickly sought authority to expand his
investigation of the failed Whitewater land deal.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun reported that the policy of the Radio Shack store was to
inform all customers about the Maryland law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 2129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
