u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-28 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
REAL kids have Christmas morning. Grown-up kids have college
football Saturdays, those wonderful afternoons when we fire up the
grills, wear the colors and mock our rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Is there anything more wholesome and fun than sharing a stadium
with 80,000 normally rational people, screaming passionately,
trying to will a 19-year-old from Cuero to score one for the alumni
or, better yet, the entire state? It is our favorite time of year,
and beginning today, 'tis the season. Christmas every Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, we even find a few gifts in the morning paper on
these days, like Colorado State getting 4{ points at Michigan State
today. It might not be a lock, but CSU is one of my dark-horse
favorites to go a long way in 1998. Take the Rams and laugh _ ho,
ho, ho _ all the way to the winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads to why we are here today. It is not just to give you
today's news today but to offer a glimpse at the months ahead. May
we offer a Top 15 list of tomorrow's college football news today:
</P>
<P>
   1) Johnny Superflash, a middle linebacker for the 10-and-under
Pee-Wee Mites of Houston, will give an oral commitment to the
University of Texas in December as Mack Brown wraps up a strong 8-3
season and continues to wow the state's masses with sweeping early
recruiting efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Superflash, 4-11 and 92 pounds, runs the 40 in 6.6 seconds, and
his mother reports he has the vertical leaping ability to jump and
touch the top of every doorway in the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``This takes a lot of pressure off me,'' Superflash will say.
``Now, I'll be able to focus on my fifth-grade schoolwork. Hook
'em.''
</P>
<P>
   2) In the wake of news that Texas A&AMP;M scientists are working on
ways to clone a dog, only Reveille will show up at Monday's
critical Florida State game with a more nervous look on his face
than the Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   3) Ohio State Heisman Trophy candidate Andy Katzenmoyer will
pass the three summer courses he needs to stay eligible _ music,
golf and AIDS awareness.
</P>
<P>
   The final exams will range from having to name three of the
Spice Girls to an oral exam in which Katzenmoyer is asked if he is
aware of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he'll answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Correct,'' the professor will respond. ``Now, beat Michigan!''
</P>
<P>
   4) Ohio State indeed will win the national championship, beating
Florida in the title game, thanks to Katzenmoyer's stupendous play.
Baby Spice dots the ``I'' at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   5) Texas star Ricky Williams will win the Heisman Trophy. But
Syracuse quarterback Donovan McNabb _ not UCLA's Cade McNown _ will
be the one making the race interesting.
</P>
<P>
   6) Alabama will win a couple of Southeastern Conference games.
This will be big news. Someone will notice the Big East Conference.
This also will be big news. Prairie View A&AMP;M will break its losing
streak. Huge news.
</P>
<P>
   7) Florida-Florida State will be the best game of the year. This
will not be big news.
</P>
<P>
   8) Someone finally will figure out the BCS _ Bowl Championship
Series, not Bryan/College Station _ three days after the game
actually is played.
</P>
<P>
   9) Notre Dame fans will file a suit against Bob Davie based on
age discrimination, the gripe being that this Irish team is again
too young.
</P>
<P>
   10) The Western Athletic Conference will splinter again, this
time forming three conferences _ those schools that want to break
away, those that don't and those that feel strongly both ways. This
new third league will be named the Clinton Republicans. Granted, it
won't be a big league.
</P>
<P>
   11) The Big Ten will make its best run yet at supplanting the
SEC as the top conference in the country. Still, the SEC will be
more fun. I'll take a Saturday afternoon at Death Valley, The
Swamp, Neyland Stadium and the like over anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   12) The Big 12 will not make a run at being the best league in
the nation, although Kansas State (North Division champs) and Texas
A&AMP;M (South) will do their share.
</P>
<P>
   13) The surprise powers this year will be Colorado State,
Arizona State and Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   14) The surprise flops will be Tennessee and UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   15) The local elevens will play better than you might expect,
the Houston Cougars winning six games, the Rice Owls eight.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a fun season. Like Christmas morning every Saturday
afternoon, as always.
</P>
</TEXT>
