<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FORGIVENESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TELLS CROWD: `LOVE THY NEIGHBOR' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ President Clinton offered his tacit
forgiveness to independent counsel Kenneth Starr Friday while
continuing to seek forgiveness of his own, in a sharp reversal of
tone that has veered from defiant to contrite over the past two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to some of the nation's most prominent civil rights
activists, Clinton quoted the Bible, spoke in a soft voice, and
ultimately told the hushed crowd: ``Love thy neighbor as thyself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All of you know, I'm having to become quite an expert in this
business of asking for forgiveness,'' Clinton said to applause and
laughter. ``It gets a little easier the more you do it. And if you
have a family, an administration, a Congress and a whole country to
ask you, you're going to get a lot of practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have to tell you that in these last days, it has come to
me, again, something I first learned as president, but it wasn't
burned in my bones, and that is that in order to get it, you have
to be willing to give it,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The speech was given at a ceremony to honor Democratic
Representative John Lewis of Georgia, and to commemorate the 35th
anniversary of the March on Washington in 1963, when Dr. Martin
Luther King Jr. made his ``I Have a Dream'' speech. Lewis, who
recently published a book chronicling the movement, is the only
major speaker from the march still living.
</P>
<P>
   ``The anger, the resentment, the bitterness, the desire for
recrimination against people you believe have wronged you, they
harden the heart and deaden the spirit and lead to self-inflicted
wounds,'' said Clinton. ``And so it is important that we are able
to forgive those we believe have wronged us, even as we ask for
forgiveness from people we have wronged.''
</P>
<P>
   The words as well as the tone contrasted with Clinton's Aug. 17
speech from the White House Map Room, where he admitted his affair
with former White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky and struck back
at the independent counsel for the personal nature of the probe.
Friday, Clinton seemed to regret some of those words, indicating
that they hurt his own cause to be forgiven and move beyond the
Lewinsky probe.
</P>
<P>
   The conciliatory tone seemed to surprise some of Clinton's
senior advisers, who said they had not been told by the president
of his plans to use the speech to set a new course in his response
to Starr. The speech, while markedly more conciliatory, still fell
short of an explicit apology.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton's closest confidant, White House deputy counsel Bruce
Lindsey, appeared before the Starr grand jury in Washington Friday,
Clinton awoke late in the morning, somewhere between 10:30 a.m. to
11 a.m., and began writing the notes for his speech by hand on two
sheets of paper, aides said. He continued to work on his outline
notes until about a half hour before he left for his midafternoon
speech. The gathering was held at the Union Chapel, a 129-year-old
nondenominational chapel that serves as a religious and cultural
center in Oak Bluffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any idea he was going to say those remarks and
neither did anyone else on the staff,'' said Doug Sosnik, a White
House counselor and Clinton's most senior aide accompanying him on
the Martha's Vineyard vacation. ``That's the way he felt when he
wrote it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said deputy White House press secretary Barry Toiv: ``He got up
today and decided that's what he wanted to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's speech followed nearly two weeks of wrangling among
senior staff aides, Democratic lawmakers and political strategists,
most of whom agree that the president badly bungled his earlier
speech by striking back at Starr and failing to offer the public
apology for his affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In that speech, Clinton said of the Starr investigation, ``This
has gone on too long, cost too much and hurt too many innocent
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oak Bluffs speech also follows an unusual conversation in
the presidential limousine in Worcester on Thursday afternoon, when
Clinton spoke with Senator John Kerry and Representative Jim
McGovern, Democrat of Worcester, and rued the four-minute speech
earlier in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``He expressed to me personally great awareness of the hole he
has dug and the need for him to build trust,'' Kerry said of the
limousine ride to the Worcester airport. ``He expressed it in very
personal terms, within his own family, with his countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He expressed an awareness that it was probably a mistake to
come right out of the grand jury and go into a speech when he was
probably angry and edgy after a fairly exhaustive and tiring day,''
Kerry said. ``To try to talk to the nation as tired as he was
didn't allow him to put his best foot forward.''
</P>
<P>
   During that ride, as residents lined the sun-streaked streets
waving and holding signs, Kerry and McGovern both urged Clinton to
in some way present his case to voters in a more conciliatory way.
The three concluded that another speech would probably not be
politically wise, but that Clinton could address the issue within a
separate speech or respond to a question from a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He clearly understands and recognizes that it is an ongoing
process, and I know he is prepared to make clear to people the
degree to which he understands that he bears responsibility in
creating the problem,'' said Kerry.
</P>
<P>
   Said McGovern: ``He seemed very remorseful, very regretful over
what has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, in Worcester, Kerry seemed to take pains to
distance himself from Clinton, refusing to follow other members of
the Massachusetts congressional delegation in offering even a
carefully worded endorsement of Clinton or airing the hope that the
nation would soon move on. Friday, in a telephone interview, he
sounded more supportive, though still cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel personally supportive of the struggle he is going
through,'' Kerry said. ``I hope he can work through it. The country
would be better off. We need to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``I don't think anyone can make any judgments.
There's a report that's going to be made and we don't know what's
in it. We'll have to exercise our responsibility. But that doesn't
mean on a personal level we shouldn't be supportive of the
president and his family.
</P>
<P>
   In his 24-minute speech Friday, Clinton's references to his own
situation took up only a few moments. In some respects, Clinton
drew a parallel between his own personal and political difficulties
and the civil rights movement of the 1960s. Both, he said, involved
forgiveness and redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the towering chapel, filled with some 400 people, Clinton
appeared moved by Lewis and others, even wiping at his eyes as the
program concluded. At one point, he laughed uproariously at a Lewis
anecdote, tossing his head back and burying his reddened face in
his hands.
</P>
<P>
   The support for Clinton seemed widespread, even before the
president spoke. Charles Ogletree, a Harvard University Law School
professor and the moderator of the program, offered his unbridled
backing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the president has a lot of fair-weather friends,'' said
Ogletree, from the pulpit. ``This is not a fair weather crowd. In
difficult times, I want you to know that people here understand and
feel your pain. We believe in redemption and are with you through
thick and through thin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
