<HEADER>
A8338 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOTHER-SFCHRON &LR;      08-28 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTHER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Mother Jones magazine's liberals at odds   By Carol Emert  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
The 1960s and the 1990s have collided at Mother Jones, and the
liberal magazine lost its longtime editor as a result.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeffrey Klein, a MoJo co-founder who has been the magazine's
editor and president for six years, tendered his resignation last
week, citing pressure from some board members to toe a conventional
left-wing line.
</P>
<P>
   Klein's departure, which becomes effective when his contract
expires next year, comes just as MoJo is preparing a high-stakes
marketing effort aimed at expanding its readership. The magazine
ran a $300,000 deficit last year and is attempting to boost its
subscriber base by more than 100,000 readers.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints by board members, which have grown more heated in
the last year, culminated in recent threats to withhold marketing
money for the launch of a redesigned magazine, the first issue of
which hit newsstands this week.
</P>
<P>
   Rob McKay, chairman of the board of the Foundation for National
Progress, which oversees MoJo, says he would never have allowed the
funding to be cut off. But Klein resigned a few days after the
threat was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was part of my mandate to take the magazine to a
place where it could be a useful journalistic force in the next
century,'' said Klein in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some extent that means accepting places where (the left
has) been successful and rejecting places where you've been a
failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionalists on the MoJo board have questioned a number of
Klein's decisions, including last fall's publication of an article
that raised questions about affirmative action, a historic liberal
cause.
</P>
<P>
   The same people oppose a move by Klein to explore broad social
issues, such as Americans' interest in spirituality, rather than
adhering strictly to MoJo's historic bread and butter:
investigations of commercial polluters, backroom dealmakers and
other corporate and political ne'er-do-wells.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the opposition was led by Adam Hochschild, who
co-founded MoJo with Klein and several other journalists in 1976,
according to board members and other MoJo insiders. In the late
'70s, Klein and Hochschild worked together as the top two editors
at the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Hochschild, a well-known Bay Area author and intellectual,
declined comment on the board debate, saying it should ``stay
within the family.'' However, he said, ``I really admire Jeffrey's
work at its best and I think he's made a strong and lasting
contribution to the magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   The rift at San Francisco's MoJo, a liberal standard-bearer
since its founding, reflects strains within the left in general.
From Washington, D.C., to Berkeley, liberals are divided over
whether to adhere to 1960s-rooted values or to rethink approaches
toward achieving the goals of feminism, affirmative action and
other causes.
</P>
<P>
   Resolving the debate is critical for Mother Jones and the left
more broadly as they attempt to woo today's young adults, a group
that has little identification with 1960s radicalism and exhibits a
strong distaste for dogma.
</P>
<P>
   MoJo is largely counting on people ages 18 to 34 to boost its
circulation from the current 140,000 to about 250,000 in the next
three to four years. Circulation peaked at above 200,000 in the
early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, 18- to 34-year-olds comprise only about 15 percent of
subscribers; the average age is 49.
</P>
<P>
   Greater circulation is also key to another MoJo goal: to become
less dependent on contributions to fund its $4.5 million annual
budget. Fund raising accounts for about one-third of the revenues
in the budget, subscriptions for half and advertising for 17
percent.
</P>
<P>
   A larger subscriber base would make the magazine more attractive
to mainstream advertisers, such as Apple Computer and General
Motors' Saturn division, which are ``attempting to differentiate
themselves with the unique identity of their brands,'' said MoJo
Publisher Jay Harris. Today, most ads in MoJo are for
``alternative'' products such as folk music CDs and herbal dietary
supplements.
</P>
<P>
   While the magazine's editorial direction is now uncertain, the
redesign and a simultaneous marketing effort were undertaken
specifically with young adults in mind.
</P>
<P>
   The issue's current cover story on Rupert Murdoch, for example,
spoofs Murdoch's sometimes-sensationalistic media empire, News
Corp. The profile, which accuses Murdoch of using journalism to
promote his business agenda, is printed on a tabloid-esque pullout
section that features the blaring headline ``World domination plot
exposed! Now, the inside scoop on Rupe!''
</P>
<P>
   Today's young adults ``realize that you're not likely to
overturn (institutions) with the French Revolution, so you deal
with it with satire and irony,'' said Klein, who believes the
current issue of MoJo is the best he's ever published.
</P>
<P>
   The renovated MoJo also includes a new column on marketing, an
area of particular interest to young adults. Its design is bolder
and more colorful. And it will focus less on Baby Boomer icons,
such as author Margaret Atwood, and more on people relevant to
youth such as radio talk show host Ira Glass.
</P>
<P>
   To jump start interest in the magazine, MoJo plans to spend
about $100,000 for outdoor ads this fall that will appear in major
metropolitan areas and college towns such as Ann Arbor, Mich. MoJo
editors will also lead political discussions at college campuses
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, today's young adults represent a natural following
for Mother Jones because many of them share a distrust of
institutions, both political and commercial, and concerns about the
environment that mesh well with the magazine's core readership.
</P>
<P>
   But Mother Jones will have to maintain Klein's tack if it is to
attract younger readers, said Viswah Marwah, a San Francisco
marketing consultant who assisted in MoJo's redesign.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's circulation has grown by 30,000 since 1992, when
Klein became editor, and Marwah believes that with the new
marketing campaign and redesign, it can reach its ambitious
readership goal.
</P>
<P>
   But ``if you know what the article is going to say before you
read it, then you don't need to read it,'' said Marwah, founder of
the consulting firm Tattoo. ``Where Jeffrey is taking it now, when
he does a story that attacks the bastions of even the left, I think
that is surprising and not predictable.''
</P>
<P>
   McKay said the majority of board members support Klein's
direction and want it to continue under the next editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The magazine will be broader than maybe some members of the
board have traditionally been comfortable with,'' said McKay.
``This brand, if you will, was built in another era, but the reason
I'm involved with the magazine is to try and make it relevant to
the next generation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
