<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-BLAKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS STALLED BETWEEN BLAKE, KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Training camp starts in two weeks, and not only have the Kings
not signed Norris Trophy-winning defenseman Rob Blake, they appear
to remain millions of dollars apart following an all-day meeting
Thursday between General Manager Dave Taylor and agent Ron Salcer.
</P>
<P>
   Blake, 28, was honored in the past year as the top defenseman in
the NHL and at the Olympic Games in Nagano, Japan. But to this
point, the Kings have declined to tender an offer to Blake that
would make him hockey's highest-paid defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, Blake -- who earned $3.15 million last year -- has
rejected a $5-million-a-year offer that would have matched the
salary of St. Louis' Al MacInnis, the current money leader among
defensemen.
</P>
<P>
   According to Salcer, his client deserves to be not just the
highest-paid at his position but among the highest-paid in his
sport. Detroit's Sergei Fedorov has the highest salary for 1998-99,
$14 million. The Mighty Ducks' Paul Kariya and Eric Lindros of
Philadelphia will earn $8.5 million each.
</P>
<P>
   Salcer did not cite Fedorov as an example of the amount of money
Blake is seeking. But he did use Toronto center Mats Sundin, who
will make $6.35 million this year, as an example.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rob was a first-team All-Star,'' Salcer said. ``Only six
players made first-team All-Star. Look at a player like Mats
Sundin. He was voted eighth at his position for centers in the NHL.
Rob was the No. 1 defenseman. We think Rob's value to the Kings is
at least as great as any player to his team.''
</P>
<P>
   Salcer and Taylor both said they remain hopeful of reaching an
agreement in time for the start of camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be optimal,'' Taylor said. ``I think it's
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor also still has to sign enforcer Matt Johnson (another
Salcer client), goalie Jamie Storr, defenseman Aki Berg and winger
Steve McKenna. Reserve defenseman Jaroslav Modry agreed to terms
this week on a contract, terms of which have not been disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Salcer said a sizable portion of Thursday's meeting with Taylor
was spent negotiating a new deal - with little progress -- for the
6-foot-5, 230-pound Johnson, 22, who earned $400,000 last season.
The parties may meet again next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not many out there like Matt Johnson,'' Salcer said.
``He's truly a feared player. When people come to L.A. and see the
lineup card, they don't like seeing Matt Johnson's name on the
lineup card. He makes a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
