<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Brave Little S.F. Web Startup, Xoom, Floats $46 Million IPO   By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Braving the tempest in the stock market, a San Francisco Web
startup called Xoom floated a $46 million initial public offering
yesterday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``That takes balls,'' whistled Charles Kaplan, president of
Equity Analytics, an IPO-tracking firm on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   His assessment pretty much describes Xoom's entire 368-page
offering. Founded just two years ago, Xoom has created an online
community of about 3 million people by offering them free personal
Web pages, e-mail and other services.
</P>
<P>
   And although the company hasn't made a profit yet, its
prospectus calls Xoom ``the second-fastest-growing site on the
Web'' and professes that all this growth must surely yield
money-making opportunities through e-commerce and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   In the best of times, such a ``concept'' IPO _ that is, a
company with a good idea but no profits _ would be a risky
proposition.
</P>
<P>
   By going public in this gale-force market, Xoom hopes to signal
Wall Street that its concept is strong enough to brave the storm,
Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, you only see the strongest offerings come out in a
down market,'' he said. ``The weak ones just don't get done.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Taulli, an analyst with IPO Monitor in Southern California,
said Xoom probably drew inspiration from the success of GeoCities,
a similar Web community that raised $80 million in an IPO earlier
this month _ on the same day the Dow dipped 112 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``For an IPO, the most important thing is to be in the buzz, and
the latest buzzword in Internet IPOs is `community,' '' Taulli
said.
</P>
<P>
   Xoom has experienced hands at the tiller. Chairman Chris Kitze
and chief executive Laurent Massa are tech veterans who know how to
make partnerships, raise cash and hire talent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Xoom is in a quiet period, so the executives can't talk. We
can only guess that Kitze and Massa are betting Wall Street will
calm down in the 90 days or so it will take them to court
institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   But can I float another speculative outcome?
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Lycos, the evil search engine of the East, has
acquired two Web community sites. If the good search engines of the
West have developed community envy, they may well have dickered
with Xoom about acquiring it. Floating an IPO doesn't preclude such
deal. It merely puts a public deadline on any negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But shame on me for speculating. The fact is, Kitze has started
and sold three companies in his career. All were private affairs.
So he's no stranger to such sellouts.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether, this time, he'll go all the way to
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Busy signal? &LR;  High-tech execs are fuming that Vice President
Al Gore has refused to take their calls _ much less their side _ on
the volatile issue of raising the quota of foreign professionals
who can work in the United States under H-1B visas.
</P>
<P>
   With pro-industry legislation stalled in Congress by a White
House veto threat, Bay Area execs have tried to get their buddy,
Al, to get his boss, Bill, to lighten up. But when a
Hewlett-Packard exec phoned Gore's office recently, trying to
arrange for HP Chairman Lew Platt to chat with the Veep, the HP
exec was told to call the White House comment line instead.
</P>
<P>
   That's the same number you or I _ or an unemployed, over-40
programmer _ would call to blow off steam. But then none of us have
paid to attend all those Clinton-Gore fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Gore won't escape if the tech lobby doesn't get its
way. ``If this bill fails I don't think he can be inculpable _ if
that's a word,'' one source said of Gore.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; In joke: &LR;  San Francisco artist Kathryn Siegler has taken a
humorous stab at the venture capital subculture in a cartoon strip
called the VC  &LR; (www.thevc.com). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Siegler, who designs children's books for a living, created the
strip with her husband, Robert von Goeben. He reads business plans
and doles out money for Red Leaf Venture Management in Saratoga.
The couple moved here two years ago, trading L.A.'s music scene for
the Silicon Valley VC beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I found funny was the language,'' Siegler
said. ``They bastardize these words and then use them in normal
conversation, like, `I can't fit you in today, I don't have the
bandwidth.'''
</P>
<P>
   After showing cartoons with themes like that to VC friends, the
couple convinced Upside Magazine to run the strip. Now they're
working on a humorous book on the same vulture _ I mean venture _
capital world.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I don't see such a book on America's coffee tables.
But maybe I lack the vision to see the business model. A publisher
could do a limited run for $999. Target Silicon Valley
millionaires, exclusively. There must be a gazillion of 'em
already.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail at abate(at
sign)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
