<SLUG> BC-SPAM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Assembly OKs Bill to Ban `Spamming'   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Adding legislative oomph to a growing anti-spam movement
nationwide, the state Assembly Thursday night overwhelmingly passed
a bill that would outlaw unsolicited commercial e-mail.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Legislation to Can Spam'' would make it illegal to send
e-mail from forged domain names and would allow Internet service
providers with e-mail equipment in California to sue junk mailers
for up to $25,000 a day in damages.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which lawmakers sent to Governor Pete Wilson
yesterday, could become law next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bill sends a clear message to spammers: If you use the
systems of state ISPs to send pornographic material and
get-rich-quick schemes, you will pay a price,'' said Assemblyman
Gary Miller, R-City of Industry (Los Angeles County), who authored
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial e-mailers often ``forge'' their return addresses _
making it appear as if the message came from AOL or another popular
online service _ to trick consumers into opening their mail and to
avoid being traced. Many of these messages hawk sex sites, pyramid
schemes and miracle drugs.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 10 billion pieces of spam a year are clogging
Internet pathways and individuals' e-mail accounts, according to
industry observers.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer outrage has prompted a pair of high-profile
congressional bills designed to can spam and tag-team efforts by
Internet heavyweights to eradicate the problem.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, only two other states _ Washington and Nevada _ have
laws outlawing spam.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is by far the best spamming legislation in existence,''
said Justin Newton, San Francisco public policy director for the
200-member ISP/Consortium, which represents a dozen California
ISPs. ``It gives ISPs a stronger legal leg to stand on, and it
doesn't require consumers to get involved.''
</P>
<P>
   While the pending law would enable scores of California ISPs,
such as EarthLink Network, Netcom and Pacific Bell Internet
Services, to put a lid on spam, it is unclear if AOL _ the nation's
largest online service and one of the biggest in California _ would
be covered.
</P>
<P>
   Although AOL operates modem banks in California, its e-mail
server facilities are based in Vienna, Va. The Dulles, Va., company
has aggressively sued spammers to keep them off its service. As
much as one-third of AOL's 30 million messages a day are spam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not we're protected, this is another important step
in curtailing spam,'' said AOL General Counsel George Vradenburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a start, but we need a national law to put an end to this
nuisance,'' Miller added.
</P>
<P>
   The Netizens Protection Act, sponsored by Representative
Christopher Smith, R-N.J., and now pending, would amend the
Telephone Consumer Protection Act of 1991, which bans unsolicited
junk faxes, to also regulate junk e-mail. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In May, the Senate unanimously passed a provision of the
Consumer Antislamming Act, co-sponsored by Senator Robert
Torricelli, D-N.J., that would fine junk e-mailers up to $15,000 if
they mask their identities with forged addresses. The overall bill
prohibits the unauthorized switching of telephone service providers
for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a coalition of Internet giants, led by AOL and
AT&AMP;T, in July submitted a report to the Federal Trade Commission
urging a major crackdown on spam. The Ad-Hoc Working Group on
Unsolicited Commercial Email is proposing that federal and state
regulators be given the authority to prosecute spammers who
disguise e-mail addresses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
