<SLUG> BC-BOFA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 BofA Takes $220 Million Hit in Crisis   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Stock market investors are not the only ones rattled by the
financial fallout from Russia. Bank of America announced yesterday
that it will write off $220 million in the current quarter,
primarily the result of trading losses in Russia.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The charge, which reduces the bank's securities and foreign
currency trading profits so far this year by 41 percent, is the
largest hit taken by a U.S. bank in the crisis to date.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Republic New York Corp. said it would write off
$110 million for losses on Russian government bonds, wiping out its
earnings for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   BofA said its write-off reduces its exposure in Russia from $412
million at the end of June to approximately $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers appear large, but the San Francisco bank generated
more than $1.7 billion in profits in the first half of the year and
only a tiny fraction of its $166 billion in loans were to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, investors did not take the news kindly. BofA's
stock skidded $4.18 to $69.56 yesterday after dropping $3.88 on
Thursday. The two-day slide of more than 10 percent was in line
with declines at other big banks, caused in part by their Russian
exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors are concerned about political uncertainty and the
impact Russia's problems could have on an already fragile world
economy. After all, U.S. trade with Russia barely shows up on the
financial radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. banks have lent $315.1 billion to foreign borrowers,
according to Federal Reserve Bank figures at the end of March. But
only $5.1 billion has gone to Russia. By contrast, U.S. banks have
lent $23 billion to Japanese borrowers and $6.5 billion to entities
in the Cayman Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts applauded BofA's action. ``A number of money center
banks have exposure in Russia and now BofA has put Russia behind
it,'' said Van Kasper analyst Jeff Runnfeldt. ``The bank
essentially reduced its ruble-denominated debts to about 10 cents
on the dollar and is left with primarily secured short-term
loans.''
</P>
<P>
   BofA was not alone in owning up to recent losses in Russia.
BankBoston Corp. said it lost $30 million in trading so far this
quarter, including $10 million in Russia-related loans.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan said that losses from foreign exchange and
securities trading in Russia has reduced its trading revenue this
quarter, but it did not disclose the amount. The New York bank also
said that its total exposure in Russia is now about $160 million _
only about half as much as recent analyst estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Citicorp had $420 million in Russian exposure at the end of
June, but the bank has no plans to announce possible losses,
according to Bloomberg News. Billionaire George Soros' investment
funds have lost about $2 billion in Russian investments, one of his
fund managers told CNBC television yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign financial companies are also feeling Russian pain.
Germany's Deutsche Bank has close to $750 million of uninsured
credit risk to the Russian government and is raising its provision
for losses by an unspecified amount.
</P>
<P>
   Losses in the past two months, mainly from Russia, cut Credit
Suisse profits by $254 million, or about a third. And UBS, another
Swiss banking giant, said it lost $120 million in trading Russian
securities this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 2137EDT &QL; 
