<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROSJEAN MAKES IT HOT FOR BJORKMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Who's feeding the cats and dogs back home?
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Larry Richard, far from the yips and meows of his
hospitalized patients, says they're covered, don't worry about it.
``I've taken my first weekday off in 25 years,'' he said Friday,
``because I've always wanted to see professional tennis players in
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard, a veterinarian from Andover, picked a good day to make
his spectating debut, and the best seat in the house at Longwood
Cricket Club to survey the MFS Pro Championships. Maybe Row Z,
Section 10 at the pinnacle of the south stand is the best seat
anywhere tennis is played, even though it's only general admission.
</P>
<P>
   Although the sun poked relentlessly from an azure ceiling while
a 20-year-old French outsider named Sebastien Grosjean burned
prime-rib seed Jonas Bjorkman to a 7-6 (9-7), 6-1 crisp. The Row Z
Zealots lazed happily behind a baseline and against the backrest
fence. The elderly oak of 80 feet that reaches out over the
grandstand is their shepherd, providing shade, and always
attracting natural AC: A leaf-riffling breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Lying directly below, the court is a rectangular jade overlooked
by the neighboring arboreal ramparts of Dunster and Middlesex
Roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so restful to sit here, in this bower, witnesses to
fierce battles down there,'' says Bunny Mahler from Needham. She
has sought out these sweet seats for more than 50 years, but
sheepishly confesses recently taking up golf to complement her
tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not old enough for that game, Bunny,'' says her friend,
Hyacinthe McKenna, from Dunstable.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly this perch beats anything at the forthcoming US Open.
Some might find Carlo aesthetically superior, where the handsomely
landscaped courts hang from the Maritime Alps and extend over the
Mediterranea.
</P>
<P>
   Wimbledon's Royal Box has its adherents. Diana was there often.
</P>
<P>
   Queen Elizabeth, who hates tennis, perfected a technique of
sleeping behind dark glasses while seated regally upright. But you
generally have to pass a blood test (watered-down blue) to get in
or know somebody who has.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about Bretton Woods up in New Hampshire, the Mt.
Washington Hotel, where the Volvo began in '73?'' asks Joe Valof.
His wife, Anita, nods and they stand up to display weathered
cushions bearing that bygone tournament's logo. The Valofs, veteran
tennis hunker-downers from Natick, have learned that a cushion is a
comforting accessory for those braving Longwood planking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember,'' he says, ``how you sat on a hillside beside the
court, with mountains in the background?''
</P>
<P>
   Very, very pleasantly bucolic _ but, alas, perished. Killed by
an inability to generate enough revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to the Volvo a long time,'' says Anita. ``So far back
we can remember when Andre Agassi had hair. Lots of it. And he wore
blue jean shorts.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard, the tennis-playing veterinarian who knows about
dogs, is disappointed by Bjorkman's collapse, but doesn't call the
Swede a mutt or even a sick puppy. He sympathizes. ``Seems to be
having confidence problems after his terrific '97,'' is the
diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Ilene, in a nifty floral straw hat, and 11-year-old
daughter, Jodi, also play and were pulling for Bjorkman. But son
Corey, who is a restless 9, prefers soccer and looks like he might
climb down the oak tree to get outta here. Of course Corey approves
of the winner, Grosjean, when his mother tells him the name means
big jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Coomas of Dracut approves of the two guys appearing next,
reigning champ, 21-year-old Sjeng Schalken and Paul Haarhuis. Dutch
masters, she calls them. Haarhuis, 32, had said at lunch: ``We've
come to Longwood to play for the championship of the Netherlands.
How about that? Sjeng and I grew up 20 miles and 10 years apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday their tiny country wasn't big enough for both of them as
long-toothed Haarhuis revived to reach the semis, 0-6, 6-4, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   That may have inspired the Machiavellian master of spinning
surprises, lefty Gianluca Pozzi, the tour's Methuselah at 33.
Torturing Michael Chang with his sinister strokes for nearly two
hours, the Italian (No. 62) couldn't quite make it, 6-4, 2-6, 6-1,
so it wasn't totally Fickle Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Longwood wasn't big enough for its ambitions when the club moved
from the Back Bay to Chestnut Hill in 1922. Glancing over to the
right at club members playing their own games on the mini-mesa, the
terrace courts beside the stadium, Bunny Mahler wonders if a story
she heard some time ago is true.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that the terrace plot, coveted by Longwood to build
more courts and the stadium, was owned by Mrs. Saltonstall, mother
of renowned US senator, Leverett Saltonstall. She grazed a cow
there, and said she'd be willing to sell the property only when the
cow died. Soon it did.
</P>
<P>
   Was that cow poisoned by an overeager club member? In Section 10
none of the Row Z Zealots seemed to care about a suspicious bovine
death so long ago. They're just glad the stadium did rise here, so
that one day they could climb to their airy row with a view.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 2138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
