<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8348 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-MFSPRO-BOS &LR;      08-28 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-MFSPRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROSJEAN MARCHES OVER BJORKMAN TO FACE CHANG IN SEMI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Qualifier Sebastien Grosjean was feeling no
pressure Friday when he took on No. 1 seed Jonas Bjorkman Friday in
the MFS Pro Championships. After all, who'd expect the 96th-ranked
player to beat No. 12?
</P>
<P>
   Grosjean's laid-back approach worked wonders as he downed
Bjorkman, 7-6 (9-7), 6-1, to make the semifinals and a match
Saturday night against fourth-seeded Michael Chang.
</P>
<P>
   It might have been Grosjean's best outing since he defeated
11th-seeded Felix Mantilla in the first round of Wimbledon before
he eventually lost in three sets to Pete Sampras in the round of
16.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play a guy who's better than you, you always play
better,'' said Grosjean. ``I woke up this morning and said that I
could win. There's no pressure. I have nothing to lose. You play
without pressure. I played a good match. I passed him. That's my
game, to stay in the back and pass.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the case for a long time,'' said Bjorkman. ``I play
good for one or two matches, if I'm playing on a pretty good level,
but not good enough to win matches. That's a problem I've been
having. I can't maintain the tennis I've been playing for the first
two matches I had here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bjorkman simply has to fight for everything he gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't have the length on the shots,'' he said. ``I
wasn't really aggressive on the balls. He's a quick guy and I've
played a lot of guys who are really fast and quick, but I've still
been able to put away the volleys and I just couldn't do that
during this match. I didn't play at my best level, and when you
don't do that everyone can play tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have enough power in my volley. I wasn't aggressive
on it. I gave him a second chance on winning points.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first set, Grosjean had two mini-breaks and then held to
go up, 4-0. That's when Bjorkman started a comeback. Grosjean had
three set points, but he couldn't put them away. Two were on
Bjorkman's serve and one became a Bjorkman ace, followed by a
backhand winner as he approached the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was putting the pressure on me. He made two errors on easy
volleys, one on set point when he missed a point on a backhand,''
said the 20-year-old Grosjean, who was the world's No. 1 junior in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   On his fourth set point, Grosjean finally captured it when
Bjorkman banged a backhand volley into the net.
</P>
<P>
   In the second set, there were exchange of breaks in the first
two games. But Grosjean kept going, taking Bjorkman's serve in the
third and fifth games. Bjorkman was not thrilled with his service
game, especially on the first offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't do too much, he's hitting the ball back,'' Bjorkman
said. ``If you can overpower him, you will do it. He will not win
the match. I lost the match more than he won it. I neither made the
winner or I made the mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   In another afternoon match, Paul Haarhuis defeated practice
partner Sjeng Schalken, the tourney's defending champ, 0-6, 6-4,
6-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started out very sluggish and he didn't make any mistakes
and I didn't have any rhythm,'' Haarhuis said. ``My feet were very
tired from last night when I finished at 12:30 (in the morning) and
I didn't get to bed before 2:30, 3. Then it became a close match,
the way I thought it would be from the start. And in the third set
I felt I was the better player.''
</P>
<P>
   Chang defeated Gianluca Pozzi, 6-4, 2-6, 6-1. At 33, Pozzi is
the oldest player on tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my fair share of trouble with him,'' Chang said. ``He
was playing some good tennis. He played consistent, not making very
many errors. For me in the third set, I tried to step it up and I
kept my errors down and I got the brace that I needed that set. In
the second set, I was impatient and I made some errors. Gozzi plays
with a lot of touch, a lot of feel, a lot of placement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
