<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNING BLACK VOTES IN A SENATE RACE  
 CLINTON SPOKE HERE (BUT NO NEED TO BRAG)  
 GOP CAN'T BANK ON HAWAIIAN WOES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Hawaii, Mo., N.C.)  (js) 
 By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Missouri, as in most other states, Democrats depend on solid
support from labor and blacks to give them a winning edge in
elections. In the case of Attorney General Jay Nixon, the
Democratic nominee in this fall's U.S. Senate contest, he has
labor's backing but has been struggling to win over black voters.
</P>
<P>
   Now that struggle may be paying off in this race that is being
watched more closely than most for clues about which party will
control the Senate next time around and by what margin. Nixon is
beginning to gather some black support and may be regaining some of
the impressive momentum he enjoyed when he first challenged the
Republican incumbent, Sen. Christopher Bond.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 10 days, several top black leaders in the state
have begun speaking up for the attorney general, breaking with
other black leaders, including many top officers of the NAACP, who
refuse to forgive Nixon for once calling for an end to
court-ordered school desegregation. That break came after Nixon
said he had made a ``mistake'' by not communicating more closely
with Missouri blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's new-found supporters include Freedom Inc., one of the
most influential black political organizations in Kansas City's
large black population, as well as two leading members of the large
black population of St. Louis, former Mayor Freeman Bosley Jr. and
the Rev. B.T. Rice, president of the St. Louis Clergy Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing that Freedom Inc. had decided to back Nixon, the
group's president, state Rep. Mary Groves Bland, said that a
comparison of Nixon's and Bond's records favored Nixon, whatever
his shortcomings on civil rights matters. Admonishing blacks who
have threatened to vote for Bond or stay home, including some NAACP
members, Ms. Bland said, ``You can be mad, take your marbles and go
home, or you can look at what will help our community.''
</P>
<P>
   Political pros rated Bond, a conservative, as ``vulnerable''
going into the race with Nixon, in good part because he only
narrowly won his two previous Senate contests. But Bond still holds
a fairly comfortable lead over Nixon, a moderate Democrat, in the
few polls taken thus far, and some political experts have begun to
say that he may well go on to a fairly comfortable victory in the
fall if the attorney general is unable to build on his recent
success in gaining black support.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to head off any more gains, Bond has begun spending long
hours working black precincts, political turf often bypassed by
Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Spoke Here (But No Need to Brag)
</P>
<P>
   In the action-speaks-louder-than-words approach to politics ...
</P>
<P>
   The morning after President Clinton made his Monica Lewinsky
speech, there was in the North Carolina General Assembly in
Raleigh, as everywhere, then and since, talk, talk, talk about what
it all means and what to do.
</P>
<P>
   A House member in a cluster of Republicans working over the
issue recalled a less portentous and lurid moment just 18 months
earlier when the president visited Raleigh and made a speech to the
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Another member recalled that after that speech, unbeknown to
most legislators, a small plaque commemorating the address had been
screwed to the House lectern that Clinton had used.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go take it off!'' one Republican partisan cried out.
</P>
<P>
   Better to hold a vote on whether to take if off, a more politic
member of the almost evenly divided House suggested.
</P>
<P>
   It was all just talk. Nothing came of it.
</P>
<P>
   Not right then.
</P>
<P>
   But later, when no one was looking, the plaque disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   How? Who?
</P>
<P>
   The House clerk put out word that all it would take to expose
the perp was a quick study of the videotape in the security cameras
that keep watch on the House chamber.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Cherie Berry, a Republican from Newton, in the
western part of North Carolina, came clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I marched right in there and unscrewed that puppy,'' she
confessed to The Charlotte Observer on Wednesday. ``You don't have
to be a dentist to remove the plaque. With all that's gone on, I'd
rather have a plaque that says Billy Graham prayed here rather than
Bill Clinton spoke here.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaque is back.
</P>
<P>
   GOP Can't Bank On Hawaiian Woes
</P>
<P>
   Hawaii's 1st Congressional District, which encompasses Honolulu,
is normally solidly Democratic, as is just about all of Hawaii. But
Honolulu and the rest of Hawaii are suffering because of the
faltering Asian economy, unlike most of the rest of the country,
and as a result Democratic candidates all over the state are in
political trouble, particularly the 1st District's congressman,
Neil Abercrombie.
</P>
<P>
   National Republican leaders have put the 1st District near the
top of their target list. They have promised to throw in money and
manpower and whatever else it takes to steal away a Democratic seat
and strengthen the party's hold on the House.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday Republican hopes for ousting Abercrombie
suffered a setback. State Rep. Quentin Kawananakoa, who was
expected to win the party's Sept. 19 primary, abruptly withdrew
from the contest, explaining that he was suffering from
hypertension, severe headaches and heart palpitations after an
earlier bout with strep throat and pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am unable to lead the winning campaign we all wanted,'' said
Kawananakoa, who is the Republican leader in the Hawaii House and
descends from the islands' royalty.
</P>
<P>
   His withdrawal left the other primary contender, state Rep. Gene
Ward, to carry the fight.
</P>
<P>
   In most recent polls, Ward did not run as strongly as
Kawananakoa in theoretical pairings with Abercrombie. For that
matter, in one of the latest surveys, Abercrombie showed surprising
strength against both men, beating Kawananakoa by 10 percentage
points and Ward by more than 20.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
