<HEADER>
A8350 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LEWIS-COX     08-28 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEWIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rueful Clinton admits he's `expert' in seeking forgiveness
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARTHA'S VINEYARD _ President Clinton acknowledged Friday that
he has become an ``expert in asking for forgiveness,'' and he
seemed to be heeding the advice of his host, Georgia Democrat Rep.
John Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who appeared with Clinton at a Martha's Vineyard church
to mark the 35th anniversary of the historic March on Washington,
said in an interview that he recently told Clinton ``not to hide''
from the Monica Lewinsky scandal, but to keep faith in the public's
ability to forgive.
</P>
<P>
   And while Clinton stopped short of offering an apology for his
admittedly inappropriate relationship with the former White House
intern, he said of asking for forgiveness, ``It gets a little
easier the more you do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you have a family, an administration, a Congress and a
whole country to ask you, you're going to get a lot of practice.''
</P>
<P>
   And without naming independent counsel Ken Starr, whom Clinton
criticized in his short speech about the Lewinsky matter 11 days
ago, Clinton said in order to get forgiveness, ``you have to be
willing to give it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to tell you that in these last days, it has come home
to me, again, something I first learned as President, but it wasn't
burned in my bones, and that is that in order to get it, you have
to be willing to give it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cited South African President Nelson Mandela as one
example, commenting on how the leader of the anti-apartheid
movement did not hate the people who held him captive for nearly
three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela, Clinton said, told him that at one time he did hate his
government captors, for they had beaten him, separated him from his
family and kept him from watching his children grow up. But,
Mandela told him that he had come to terms with his enemies. ``They
could take everything away from me _ everything _ but my mind and
my heart,'' Clinton quoted Mandela as saying. ``Now, those things I
would have to give away. And I simply decided I would not give them
away.''
</P>
<P>
   And if a person does not learn how to forgive in the same way
that Mandela did?
</P>
<P>
   ``The anger, the resentment, the bitterness, the desire for
recrimination against people you believe have wronged you, they
harden the heart and deaden the spirit and lead to self-inflicted
wounds,'' Clinton said. ``And so it is important that we are able
to forgive those we believe have wronged us, even as we ask for
forgiveness from people we have wronged. And I heard that first _
first _ in the civil rights movement: ``Love thy neighbor as
thyself.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in attendance saw the speech as an apology for the Lewinsky
affair. ``I think he is apologizing to the whole country,'' said
Flo Haynes of Michigan. ``But I don't think he has anything to
apologize for.''
</P>
<P>
   But Arline Tannenhaus does think the president has something to
apologize for. She is angry that she had to explain to her daughter
the details of the president's affair with Lewinsky. However,
Clinton's remarks at Union Chapel appeared to have won her over.
``I just don't look for the president to be my moral compass,'' she
said. ``I was angry with him, but now I forgive him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who has been unwavering in his support of Clinton, said
before the speech that it is time for Congress to focus its
attention on the nation's agenda, not on the private life of the
president. ``I think we should just cool it and talk about the
issues,'' said Lewis. ``We are all in this thing together. We need
him, he needs us.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the president in a recent telephone conversation,
Lewis said that he repeated his mother's saying that ``we all make
mistakes and should be prepared to forgive.''
</P>
<P>
   And in what may have been a metaphorical reference to the
political storm he is now weathering, Clinton quoted from a passage
in Lewis' recent book, ``Walking With the Wind.'' In that passage,
Lewis recounts how he and his cousins attempted to prevent a storm
from sweeping away his aunt's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so it went, back and forth, fifteen children walking with
the wind, holding that trembling house down with the weight of our
small bodies. It seemed that way in the 1960s, at the height of the
civil rights movement, when America itself felt as if it might
burst at the seams _ so much tension, so many storms.''
</P>
<P>
   Pausing, a somber Clinton looked at the audience and continued,
``But the people of conscience never left the house. They never ran
away. They stayed, they came together, and they did the best they
could, clasping hands and moving toward the corner of the house
that was the weakest.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
