<HEADLINE>
OXFORD PROJECTS $300 MILLION LOSS FOR YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Oxford Health Plans, the troubled managed-care
company whose stock has plunged more than 90 percent since last
summer, estimated future losses and took questions at its annual
shareholders meeting Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford's new chief executive, Norman Payson, outlined a
turnaround strategy before a packed room of shareholders, many of
whom said they had lost thousands of dollars on their investments.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford expects losses, before interest, taxes, depreciation and
amortization, of roughly $300 million this year. While it expects
to break even on a cash-flow basis in 1999, Oxford is likely to
report a slight earnings loss. Its goal is an operating profit
margin of 4 percent to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Payson emphasized that Oxford, whose popularity depends on
providing affordable health care plans that allow consumers to
choose their doctors, is committed to the plans and to its method
of paying doctors for their services. It will raise premiums and
cut some fees.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders questioned Oxford's malfunctioning computer system,
which Oxford said would be fixed, not replaced. Marvin Rich, the
company's new chief administrative officer, stressed that Oxford's
problems resulted not from its computers but from a flawed strategy
of charging too little for its plans.
</P>
<P>
   Much rancor was aimed at Oxford's former chairman, Stephen
Wiggins, who was awarded a $9 million severance package. While that
package is under review by New York state regulators, several
shareholders expressed anger at the terms. Wiggins, who remains on
the board, did not attend the meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
