<SLUG> BC-SPEND-AUTO-STATES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 STATES EXPERIMENT WITH AUTO CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Pa., Ky.)   (For release Sunday, Aug. 30)  
 (Sidebar with SPEND-AUTO-INSURE)  
 (bl)  
 By PETER PASSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   While federal auto choice legislation remains a long shot this
year, three states have adopted insurance systems that already give
drivers some discretion to limit their right to sue for pain and
suffering in exchange for lower premiums.
</P>
<P>
   None offer decisive evidence of how a full-blown auto choice
system would play out nationally, but each offers at least modest
insights.
</P>
<P>
   KENTUCKY _ The first state with ``choice'' _ its changes more
than a decade old _ hardly offers one. Those who choose to limit
their right to sue for intangible losses like pain and suffering _
the vast majority of drivers _ do not have to impose much
discipline on themselves. Lawsuits are permitted as long as the
injured party has medical bills of $1,000 _ a low hurdle, indeed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Joint Economic Committee of Congress estimates that a switch
to a system that bars virtually all claims for pain and suffering
would reduce annual liability insurance costs in Kentucky by an
average of $134, or 38 percent. But with premiums already below the
national average, rates are not a significant political issue in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA _ This state's system looks a lot more like the
federal choice plan. Drivers who choose limited coverage must vault
a significant threshold _ having incurred ``serious injury'' _ to
be able to sue for pain and suffering. But full tort coverage
remains the default option; to get the limited coverage, drivers
must request it from their insurers.
</P>
<P>
   At present, the majority of drivers have full coverage, though
David Snyder of the American Insurance Association said that
insurers who make the effort find they can sell the limited
coverage to about half of their customers. Those who accept limited
coverage receive a 20 percent discount on liability insurance.
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY _ As in Pennsylvania, drivers can choose limited or
full tort coverage. But the default option for those not specifying
a preference is the limited coverage. Roughly 85 percent of drivers
end up with limited coverage; to sue for pain and suffering, they
must meet a threshold that is somewhat weaker than Pennsylvania's.
Still, according to Snyder, drivers opting for the limited coverage
in New Jersey's competitive insurance market save 50 percent off
the price of unrestricted liability coverage.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey currently mandates a hefty $250,000 minimum of
no-fault personal injury protection. But under pressure from voters
to reduce insurance premiums, which remain among the highest in the
nation, the state will allow drivers to cut that coverage to just
$15,000 beginning next year. That should lure some uninsured
drivers back into getting required insurance, but the move could
undermine the thrust of the choice system: $15,000 is grossly
insufficient to compensate for many injuries, so it is likely that
more people will go to court to try to make good their medical
costs and lost income.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 2142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0385 </DOCNO>
