<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8353 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-MERIDIAN-ART-     08-28 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-MERIDIAN-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERIDIAN VALUE: WITHOUT A SPLASH, A TINY FUND STAYS AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 30)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   While many mutual funds spend a lot of their shareholders' money
on splashy magazine ads and TV commercials, Meridian Value budgets
zero for marketing to investors. ``Our philosophy is to focus on
investment performance with the idea that good performance will
attract assets to the fund,'' said Kevin O'Boyle, the fund's lead
manager.
</P>
<P>
   As a marketing strategy, that clearly hasn't worked. Meridian
Value, started in 1994, holds a puny $12 million. Throw in the
value of stock grants, and that's what some of O'Boyle's peers take
home in a year.
</P>
<P>
   But the focus on performance has worked quite well for
investors. The fund has returned an average of 20.4 percent
annually for the three years ended Thursday, compared with just
10.7 percent for its peers in the small-capitalization value
category, according to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial
publisher. This year, Meridian Value managed a 2 percent return
through Thursday, while its peers lost 13.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While Morningstar classifies him as a value manager, O'Boyle has
built his track record at the fund by identifying what he calls
``busted growth stocks,'' shares of fast-growing companies that
stumble. He became lead manager in June 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a company with a strong balance sheet and a history of
generating strong returns from capital fails to meet its earnings
estimates for a year, the stock prices tend to decline
dramatically,'' he said. ``We find this happens even if the
company's three- to five-year business outlook remains strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Meridian Value can invest in companies of any size but tends to
favor smaller ones; the median market capitalization of the
companies in the portfolio is $400 million. O'Boyle aims to spread
the fund's assets evenly among about 40 stocks _ he currently has
38.
</P>
<P>
   He will consider any company in any industry except
biotechnology. ``Those companies generally have no profit history
and often no revenues,'' he said. ``So we have a hard time valuing
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, he looks for companies with rock-solid balance sheets
and for industries with strong growth prospects. The fund has more
than 14 percent of its assets in retail stocks and hefty amounts in
consumer products, telecommunications, health services and
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a busted growth stock is one thing, but before he buys,
O'Boyle also identifies a catalyst that will let the company
increase its earnings by more than 15 percent a year over the next
two years.
</P>
<P>
   One catalyst might be a shift in one or more industry trends.
For example, the fund owns shares of Tyson Foods and Sanderson
Farms, two poultry processors. This industry suffered from excess
capacity for years, O'Boyle said; shares of Tyson lagged behind the
market from 1993 through 1997, while those of Sanderson fell from
$19.25 in early 1997 to less than $12 in the fall of that year. But
starting last year, consolidation reduced industry capacity,
pushing up retail prices; meanwhile, the producers' feed prices
declined.
</P>
<P>
   He began buying both stocks last May, Tyson at $20 a share and
Sanderson for between $12 and $13. O'Boyle expects Tyson to earn
$1.25 in its 1999 fiscal year; the stock now sells for $17.625,
just over 14 times those projected earnings. Sanderson, at $12.25,
sells for under 14 times his 1998 fiscal-year earnings estimate of
90 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   A switch to a more effective business strategy can be a
catalyst, too, especially when new competition has beaten down a
company's stock. O'Boyle cited Discount Auto Parts, a
do-it-yourself car parts retailer in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   The company implemented a ``store clustering'' strategy, putting
many stores close together to fend off competitors like Auto Zone
and Pep Boys. The strategy reduced sales at individual stores and
cut earnings growth for the company in 1996 and 1997, but sales
started picking up earlier this year. The company is also starting
a commercial parts delivery service.
</P>
<P>
   O'Boyle expects Discount Auto to earn $1.90 a share in fiscal
year 1999; At $21.50, it trades for just 11 times those projected
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Another example is Shoe Carnival, a 100-outlet discount retailer
that does business in the Midwest and parts of the South. It more
than doubled the number of its stores in 1993 and 1994, but had
problems: it sold too many low-margin private-label shoes and
struggled with a bloated inventory.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-1996, the company had eliminated its excess inventory by
cutting prices and used the resulting cash to pay down debt. The
stock traded at $5, just above tangible book value.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Boyle began buying shares only after Shoe Carnival rolled
out a strategy in the second half of 1996 to sell quality-brand
shoes at a discount. Sales in the company's established stores
began rising shortly thereafter, and O'Boyle held on, recently
adding to his holdings at $11 a share. The stock now trades at
$9.25. He expects the company, which trades at just over 11 times
this year's earnings, to earn 75 cents a share in 1998 and 90 cents
a share in 1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'Boyle keeps in shape by swimming two miles a day, four days a
week after work. ``Swimming gives me time to think and relieves the
stress from work,'' he said. He swims competitively with the
masters' team at the University of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   His proclivity for staying active shows itself on the business
side of his life as well. His fund's turnover rate is 144 percent,
versus an industry average of about 90 percent. He is quick to dump
companies that do not improve their operating results, or whose
stock price outstrips their business prospects.
</P>
<P>
   O'Boyle aims to stay fully invested, but right now, cash makes
up a steep 17 percent of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been having trouble finding companies with prospect of
improved operating results because the Asian situation has slowed
economic growth and the strong U.S. dollar has slowed export
growth,'' he said. ``The economy has been strong in the U.S. for so
long that few companies fall into our category of having operating
problems for one year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 2143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
