<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8354 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-THEATER-2TA     08-28 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-THEATER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO GATHER EVERYONE IN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SARAH BOXER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It sits in plush seats or on hard benches. It watches.
It claps. Sometimes it stands up and asks for more. Then it goes
home. Critics have spilled a lot of ink writing about actors,
playwrights, even directors. But what about the audience? Where has
it been and where is it going?
</P>
<P>
   Aristotle described the theater as an ``essentially religious
ritual,'' said Robert Brustein, the artistic director of the
American Repertory Theater. Euripides, Sophocles and Aeschylus
approached the Greek myths in a variety of ways, he said, ``and the
audience had the role of communicants.'' The right balance of
terror and pity would bring a collective catharsis, and they would
return home feeling cleansed.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the Greeks' theatrical sense, the playwright Arthur
Miller said: ``They used masks and music and scary stuff. There was
screaming and hollering and sometimes a guy sticking his eyes out
and bleeding on the stage.'' And that wasn't all. ``Those plays
were resoundingly popular works,'' Miller added. ``They were not
for a clique of theatergoers.'' A single play could move a city.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's quite a far cry from where we are now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Something momentous has happened to the audience. To illustrate
the change, Brustein recalled a scene in Virginia Woolf's novel
``Between the Acts'' in which some actors perform a pageant of
English history. The actors representing the 18th and 19th
centuries wear period costumes. But those representing the 20th
century simply hold up mirrors. As the audience looks at itself,
horrified, a record accompanying the performance gets stuck on
these words: ``Now we are dispersed. Now we are dispersed.''
</P>
<P>
   So the question becomes: how can such a diverse, dispersed
audience be moved? The various attempted answers form a brief
history of political theater.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, ``The Theater of Revolt'' (Ivan Dee, 1991),
Brustein described how the theater of communion represented by
Sophocles, Shakespeare and Racine was torn apart by the ``theater
of the great insurgent modern dramatists'': Ibsen, Strindberg,
Chekhov, Shaw, Brecht, Pirandello, O'Neill, Artaud and Genet.
Rather than allowing the audience to sit complacently, the modern
actors and playwrights incited the audience to change.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it appears, a new kind of theater has arrived that's
neither affirmative nor polemical, but instead seeks to bring
together the voices of society into a grand civic dialogue. This is
the kind of theater practiced by Anna Deavere Smith, who is best
known for her two one-woman shows based on street interviews,
``Fires in the Mirror: Crown Heights, Brooklyn and Other
Identities'' and ``Twilight: Los Angeles, 1992.'' Ms. Smith is now
the artistic director of the new Institute for Arts and Civic
Dialogue at Harvard University, sponsored by the W.E.B. Du Bois
Institute and the American Repertory Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to bring disparate worlds together, not so that
we can all get along, but so we can see out of the `me' into `us,'
'' Ms. Smith said. And once again, the role of the audience is
changing. It is being assembled not to be affirmed or incited, but
simply to be represented.
</P>
<P>
   The evolution of the audience has come slowly. In Shakespeare's
time, Miller said, ``the play became a commodity,'' consumed by the
audience. And it remained that way through the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences, witness to secular plays and sentimental comedies,
would weep a little and then go home happy. Basically, Brustein
said, those plays were confirmations of the audiences' values.
</P>
<P>
   The momentous change in theater came in the mid-19th century,
when Henrik Ibsen started writing plays that challenged the middle
class. Today, Brustein said, Ibsen's ``Doll's House'' might look
mild, but back then it was called a ``loathsome sore unbandaged.''
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of the modern theater of revolt presented
something of a paradox. ``Every modern play has tried to break down
the barrier between actors and audiences,'' to remove the fourth
wall so that audiences cannot rest secure in their voyeurism,
Brustein said. And what better way to do that than make them
uncomfortable? All the important modern dramatists saw no point in
putting on plays that did not challenge, alienate or push away
their audiences. But they knew they needed their audiences to
survive. They faced the classic problem of the avant-garde: How do
you offend people and keep them coming? And when they keep coming,
how do you keep offending them?
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's plays were offensive in length. They went on and on, with
prefaces, afterwords and postscripts. In its uncut version, ``Man
and Superman'' takes five hours to perform and that doesn't even
include the book-length afterword, with maxims for revolutionaries.
</P>
<P>
   Brecht had utter contempt for what he called ``culinary
theater,'' easily digested stuff. ``I aim for an extremely
classical, cold, highly intellectual style of performance,'' he
once said. ``I'm not writing for the scum who want to have the
cockles of their hearts warmed.''
</P>
<P>
   For Artaud, alienation was not enough. He introduced the world
to ``the theater of cruelty.'' As he put it: ``We are not free. And
the sky can still fall on our heads. And the theater has been
created to teach us that.'' He recommended that the spectator
accept the disorder and anarchy of life, that he use the theater as
``an outlet for repressions'' so he would not be violent or cruel
in real life.
</P>
<P>
   The followers of Shaw, Brecht and Artaud have gone in a hundred
different directions. One of the longest living descendants is the
Living Theater, the pacifist, anarchist theater group begun by
Judith Malina and Julian Beck 50 years ago. Following Brecht's
trail and adding some of Artaud's anarchic touches, the Living
Theater practiced ``total theater,'' Ms. Malina said. The actors
played themselves and the audience became part of the performance.
Everyone was ``forced to make choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Total theater reached a fever pitch in 1968 with a play called
``Paradise Now.'' During the performance, the actors ran naked into
the streets demanding ``paradise now.'' They were arrested for
indecent exposure and during one performance at the Brooklyn
Academy of Music Ms. Malina was raped onstage by someone in the
audience. ``If we're going to be brave,'' she said, ``we're going
to be misunderstood.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The Living Theater still performs ``Not in My Name'' in the
middle of Times Square whenever someone on death row is executed.
The actors celebrate the life of the victim at the hour of his
death, then go out to spectators, touch them, stare them in the eye
and say: ``I will swear to you that I will never kill you. Can you
promise me the same?''
</P>
<P>
   There have been many other instances of theater performances
that assault or embrace the audience. But these days, Brustein
said, most of the public is revolted by the merging of audience and
actors. The director Kenneth Tynan, Brustein recalled, said that
every time some actor came into the audience he felt like lighting
a match and burning his feet.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that means political theater is at an end depends on how
you define it. Athol Fugard, the South African playwright, says he
believes that every great playwright is political, from O'Neill to
Beckett. He adds, however, that there are only a few who still
practice what he calls ``resistance theater,'' plays intended to
bring down a system of government, like apartheid, by imparting
courage to the resisters and educating everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is resistance theater in America,'' he
said. Why? ``With resistance theater it's one voice, a voice of
denial saying, `No!' '' Resistance theater, Fugard said, is only
possible when there is something great to resist. By that
definition, there isn't even resistance theater in South Africa
anymore. ``Going back to my own country,'' he said, ``there's still
a long way to go before we become the democracy we want to be, but
the work we've got to do is not in opposition to it, but affirming
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, every society needs a constant critique of itself. And
that is what many playwrights do. Fugard singled out Tony Kushner's
play ``Angels in America'' as ``incredibly powerful,'' but not
revolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics worry that critical theater has become fragmented
into so many splinter groups that each one is simply preaching to
the converted, offering each congregation its own catechism. Black
playwrights write for black audiences, gay playwrights for gay
audiences. Indeed, there are even troupes that adapt their plays to
fit the towns they are playing in, turning, say, ``Tartuffe'' into
something Texans can relate to.
</P>
<P>
   Brustein suggests there is too much emphasis on identity
politics in theater: ``A woman comes up to me and says, `I'm black,
lesbian and a poet. Who is speaking for me?' To her I say: `I'm
old, white and Jewish. And if I want someone to speak for me I look
in the mirror.' We are living in a time of such cultural narcissism
that we think we can only attend to something that is speaking to
our own concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith offers an evenhanded solution. Her idea is not to
focus on one voice but to represent them all. ``There is way too
much of the individual voice in theater,'' she said. ``The
limitation of most actors' training is that it is all about `me.'
'' With the Institute for Arts and Civic Dialogue, she said, ``We
are hoping to learn about the artist's relation to society. And we
are trying to transform the audience into a community. The question
is whether we as citizens can become an interesting collective
force.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, she has put a lot of work into creating what she
calls a ``core audience'' for the institute's performances. This is
a group of 150 people of all different races and backgrounds who
show up for every show and become an extension of the cast. But she
is under no illusion that it is easy for a vast and varied crowd to
become unified.
</P>
<P>
   One theme of ``House Arrest,'' Ms. Smith's play about the U.S.
presidency, based on 4,000 hours of taped interviews with everyone
from prisoners to press secretaries to President Clinton himself,
is that, as she put it: ``We are living in a fractured community.
We are without a patriarchal guide and we're mad about it, mad
about not having a voice of authority.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, though, she doesn't seem to think there is any
other choice. After all, we aren't communicants and we aren't
revolutionaries. ``We're not in any shape to be a harmonious
thing,'' she said. We're just the audience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
