<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-TEACHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TESTING WORTH, AND PATIENCE, OF TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Austrian men and women who arrived in New York
City this week to teach public school math and science might have
to pool their salaries and share housing if they expect to be able
to afford an apartment. They could also turn to veterans of the
system to guide them in their search for a place to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't ask Gregory Muriel, even if his house might soon be
available for new tenants. Muriel has been a public school teacher
for 15 years but has repeatedly failed the state's licensing test.
He has been allowed to continue teaching as a full-time substitute
teacher, but with a $12,000 salary cut, to $28,000. Now he faces
foreclosure on his New Jersey house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in the process of filing for bankruptcy because of bills
that have yet to be paid,'' he said. ``It's humiliating. You try to
keep your integrity, but you see teachers throughout the city with
less experience than you getting paid more than you.''
</P>
<P>
   Muriel is part of a class-action lawsuit filed in 1996 by black
and Hispanic teachers who have been allowed to stay in classrooms
for years as substitute teachers even though they have not passed
their licensing exams. Some of them have lost tenure, seniority
rights and medical benefits while working the same hours at the
same jobs as licensed teachers; others have left the profession.
</P>
<P>
   The federal lawsuit contends that the general-knowledge parts of
the National Teacher Examination and its successor, the Liberal
Arts and Sciences Test, are culturally biased and have resulted in
higher failure rates for them than for white teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than look at how well they fill in the dots, they say,
why not look at how well they fill their roles as teachers? Their
experience with children from diverse backgrounds, poor families or
rough neighborhoods, they insist, should count.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they're hiring teachers from Austria with no real
classroom experience,'' said Victor Acevedo, who has been a teacher
for 18 years but has yet to pass his licensing exam. ``We had
teachers from Spain who they brought here years ago. They spoke
Spanish, and they failed. What makes them think that teachers from
Austria would do any better?''
</P>
<P>
   Citing pending litigation, officials of the New York City Board
of Education and the state Education Department offered limited
comment on the class-action suit, which they have moved to dismiss.
A spokesman for the Education Department also said the test had
been extensively evaluated for any possible bias.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. LaRock, a spokesman for the Board of Education, said the
test was a valid requirement for teacher certification. ``Teachers
have five years to meet that requirement,'' he added. ``We think
that's a fair time frame in which to get their requirements
completed.''
</P>
<P>
   The teachers contend that the part of the test that has
repeatedly tripped them up sometimes seems little more than a
combination of factoids and trick questions. And while they don't
dismiss subject areas like literature and science, they say their
teaching duties prevent them from keeping on top of the test's
subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're good areas, but they're not my specialty,'' said
Acevedo, who is a bilingual social studies teacher at Seward Park
High School on the Lower East Side. ``The last time I took science
was in 1970. When you're in a classroom teaching in New York City,
it's not easy. You have a full range of responsibilities in the
classroom. All my time is spent on my lesson plan and classroom
management.''
</P>
<P>
   But coming during a week when the city's business leaders issued
a scathing report on the lack of skills among high school
graduates, those comments may prove unconvincing. Leaders of the
teachers union said they wanted to assist those teachers who have
yet to pass the test, but they did not accept the contention that
the current test is biased.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hard call here,'' said Randi Weingarten, president of
the United Federation of Teachers. ``In a period of time when we
are demanding higher standards of our students and want to attract
the best and brightest, we have to make sure we are consistent and
demand high standards from teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet teachers like Carolyn Lee ask why, if they are not
qualified, they continue to receive satisfactory reviews from their
bosses. Ms. Lee, a special-education teacher in the Bronx, has just
learned that she will be put on daily substitute-teacher status.
That means no guaranteed hours or benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel betrayed,'' she said. ``And I'm being thrown out the
door for the simple reason I didn't bubble in the right answers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
