<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8361 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-RIGHTS-1STLD-     08-28 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RIGHTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SURPRISE SPEECH, CLINTON SEEKS TO FORGIVE AND BE FORGIVEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for additions; second half is new; some refinements in top
half)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAK BLUFFS, Mass. _ Embraced by his most ardent supporters, an
emotional President Clinton said Friday that he had been wrestling
with the process of forgiveness _ both as a seeker of it from his
family and the nation, and as one who forgives his enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so it is important that we are able to forgive those we
believe have wronged us, even as we ask for forgiveness from people
we have wronged,'' the president said, apparently in references
first to Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel, who has
been delving into the Clintons' lives, and then to his wife and the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The anger, the resentment, the bitterness, the desire for
recrimination against people you believe have wronged you _ they
harden the heart and deaden the spirit and lead to self-inflicted
wounds,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president's aides declined to interpret the remarks, which
came almost two weeks after Clinton spoke in a televised address
about his relationship with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky. In the days that followed the brief address, Clinton was
widely criticized as less contrite than he should have been and too
eager to cast blame for his predicament on Starr. Since then, aides
have hinted he might make a more conciliatory statement.
</P>
<P>
   If Friday's words did not constitute the outright apology that
some critics have been demanding, they reflected a man who was
still navigating his way through the self-imposed crisis that has
tested his marriage and threatened his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was speaking to 400 people who had come to a simple
wood-shingled chapel here on Martha's Vineyard to commemorate the
35th anniversary of the historic civil rights march on Washington.
</P>
<P>
   His aides, who have said Clinton would refer publicly to his
personal situation in his own time and way, said they had no idea
he would offer these thoughts on forgiveness Friday. They said that
Friday morning he had rejected a speech written by his staff,
turning over the paper the prepared speech was written on and
scribbling his own thoughts in longhand.
</P>
<P>
   He continued to revise his remarks in his car on the way to the
chapel this afternoon and jotted even more as he sat on stage,
where he was bathed in support from black leaders, who have been
his most reliable constituents. The most recent New York Times/CBS
News Poll, conducted on Aug. 19 and 20, found that 94 percent of
blacks approved of the job he was doing, compared with 60 percent
of whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been with you from the beginning,'' declared Rep. John
Lewis, D-Ga., who played a central role in the civil rights
movement. ``And I will stand with you now till the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Ogletree Jr., a professor at Harvard Law School, said to
the president, ``All these times it was very easy for us to be with
you because you were with us, and now in difficult times, I want
you to know that the people here understand and feel your pain,
believe in redemption and are here because of you and are here with
you through thick and through thin.''
</P>
<P>
   Ogletree represented Anita Hill in 1991 when she accused Supreme
Court nominee Clarence Thomas of sexual harassment. Ms. Hill also
attended the ceremony.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The support came as some Democrats in Congress have been
expressing reservations about the president and publicly distancing
themselves from him, indicating an erosion in confidence among
those who may be asked to judge whether Clinton should be
impeached.
</P>
<P>
   His aides had agreed that he needed to offer the public
something beyond his admission on Aug. 17 that he had had improper
relations with Ms. Lewinsky, a speech that critics said expressed
too much anger at Starr and not enough contrition. There was no
indication from the White House as to whether Clinton thought
Friday's remarks would be enough to quell his critics, but the
president indicated he was in the midst of a process.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of you know,'' he said, ``I'm having to become quite an
expert in this business of asking for forgiveness. It gets a little
easier the more you do it.'' He said that seeking forgiveness from
his family, his administration, the Congress and the whole country
would give him ``a lot of practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he seemed to be taking the extraordinary step of
expressing magnanimity toward Starr, there was a residue of
defiance toward the prosecutor, whom he has made no secret of
loathing.
</P>
<P>
   It came in a reference to Nelson Mandela, the South African
leader who had been jailed for 27 years and still forgave his
oppressors. Clinton said that Mandela had told him his secret _
that he realized his enemies could strip him of everything but ``my
mind and my heart,'' a possible clue to how Clinton might handle a
public bow to Starr without giving in to him.
</P>
<P>
   Those inside the steamy one-room chapel here immediately
embraced Clinton. Ogletree cited black support for Clinton based on
favorable policies, including his appointment of minorities to his
Cabinet and judgeships, his ``historic'' visit to Africa and his
initiative on race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to the wall with this president,'' said Henry
Louis Gates, the Harvard professor and writer and one of many
prominent blacks who vacation here. The Oak Bluffs section of
Martha's Vineyard, where the Clintons are vacationing for two
weeks, has served as a refuge for blacks since former slaves from
Virginia and servants of white Bostonians settled here more 200
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great deal of voyeurism going on in the media and in
society about his personal life,'' Gates said. ``People are acting
like they want the man to bleed in public, and I think he's bled
enough.'' He called Clinton's speech ``a subtle, very sophisticated
thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis suggested it may have been too subtle. ``You had to read
between the lines,'' he said, but added that in talking about
Mandella, ``I think he was talking about himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hill, who has become synonymous with the issue of sexual
harassment, said: ``We do believe in forgiveness and we believe in
redemption. But I would love to see the president come out and do
something really positive for women. I think that's how we're going
to be able to get beyond this. This was a beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Gill, 40, a lawyer from Greenburg, N.Y., who has a summer
home here, said of the president: ``He has not fully dealt with
that issue and has a way to go, but I think he very much wants
forgiveness. He really needs to dig down in his heart, acknowledge
what he has done, acknowledge he has hurt some people, and then to
move on. His apology will be apparent by his actions, not
necessarily by a public statement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
