<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-ORIENT-EXPRESS-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN ORIENT EXPRESS: LUXURIOUS (BUT EXPENSIVE) RAIL
RELAXATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 30)  
 (duplication warning: also sent with `t' code)  
 (bl)  
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Orient Express luxury train, operating for less
than a year, already has its legends: the 94-year-old traveler who
has ridden it three times, the train buff who traveled across
Canada just so he could ride on an obscure 250-mile piece of track,
and the man who searches out the most expensive vacations possible.
</P>
<P>
   He probably felt right at home. An eight-night trek across
Canada or the United States in the Presidential Suite, which
includes a private shower, costs $7,890 a person, double occupancy.
Even the smallest compartments go for $4,990 on those runs.
</P>
<P>
   Operated by Oregon Rail Corp., the Express is the only fully
private passenger train running on the main rail lines in the
United States, said Henry Hillman Jr., the company's president and
owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider it a cruise train, where you can live on board and
you don't have to unpack,'' he said. ``It's intimate, and it's an
opportunity to experience travel on a smaller space.''
</P>
<P>
   The train carries 15 cars built 40 to 50 years ago: seven
sleeping carriages, two dining cars, two club cars, two crew cars,
an observation car and a laundry. The cars were reconstructed,
their mechanical systems upgraded and their interiors refurbished
for about $1 million each.
</P>
<P>
   It's a graceful operation, paneled in Honduran mahogany. The
club cars feature painted ceilings and murals, plush carpeting and
faux marble walls, and the dining cars have inlaid portraits of
birds.
</P>
<P>
   Other elegant touches abound. A bottle of Mumm champagne chills
in each Presidential Suite and Godiva chocolates wait on pillows at
night. Rubrum lilies and long-stemmed red roses adorn the public
cars.
</P>
<P>
   In the dining car, the menu borrows from an earlier era of rail
travel, with dishes like venison chasseur from the Canadian Pacific
Railway and crab cakes with spicy citrus sauce a la B &AMP; O Lines.
</P>
<P>
   And the tours take travelers through some of the continent's
finest scenery, from the Canadian Rockies to the Deep South.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a deluxe train for North America came from Swiss
investors more than a decade ago. They bought vintage rail cars
from museums, private collections and Amtrak and had them
refurbished, starting operations in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   That train, called the American European Express, stuck to a
Chicago-to-New York-to-Washington route as an alternative for
business travelers. But low ridership and an accident with a dump
truck caused the company to shut down soon after, Hillman said. For
four years, the train was used only for charter trips.
</P>
<P>
   The line came under its current ownership just last fall, when
Hillman said he and other ``venture capitalists willing to take a
flier on a new idea'' bought the train and its operations.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon Rail pays Amtrak and other rail lines for use of the
track, and contracts for the use of Amtrak and Canadian Northern
locomotives. The company aims to attract the richest 10 percent of
travelers _ people who might take cruises and who relish a relaxed
pace.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing of the train has also branched out to corporate
events, like a media tour for Subaru's introduction of its 1999
sport utility sedans. Other trip sponsors have been nonprofit
groups like the Smithsonian Institution and the National Trust for
Historic Preservation.
</P>
<P>
   The train travels from March through October, rotating among
eight scenic and historical tours around the continent, including a
``Jazz and Blues Express'' from Chicago to New Orleans, an
``American Heritage'' run from Montreal to Washington, a ``Rockies
and Yellowstone'' tour from Portland, Ore., and another national
parks trip, from Denver to Santa Fe, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Nine routes are scheduled next year, and one more will be added
in 2000: a fall foliage tour of Vermont, New Hampshire and upstate
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Because of start-up and capital costs, the company is running at
a loss, but Hillman said he was confident that the train would
eventually be able to turn a profit, even at prices teetering
toward $1,000 a night. Indeed, he is assembling a second train of
vintage cars to run the routes.
</P>
<P>
   More than 5 million people in North America travel on cruise
ships each year, and 497,000 ride Amtrak's route down the Pacific
coast from Seattle to Los Angeles. So, company officials said, it
should not be too difficult to find 3,500 people to fill the
train's 35 trips next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Express carries up to 104 passengers, and, depending on the
route, has been running from 75 percent to 100 percent of capacity,
Hillman said. Several trips on the West Coast are already nearly
filled through 1999, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As passengers boarded earlier this month for the train's ``Great
Trans-Canada Rail Journey'' _ about 2,100 miles from Vancouver
through the Canadian Rockies to Montreal _ the crew stood at
attention in blue capes and white gloves. Each day, they provided a
meticulous itinerary, allowing passengers to pick out mountains,
ghost towns and waterfalls by watching for the numbered mile
markers along the track.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers could get out at some stops and explore the towns and
scenery. In Jasper, Alberta, for example, travelers could tour the
Athabasca Glacier off the Columbia Icefield.
</P>
<P>
   To break even, company officials said, most trips need to run at
about 75 percent of capacity but this particular run carried only
54 travelers. They ranged from mother-daughter pairs who had read
about the Express in Victoria magazine or seen it on a PBS program
called ``The Rockies by Rail,'' to corporate lawyers relaxing after
deals done, to couples celebrating anniversaries or birthdays.
</P>
<P>
   There were also train enthusiasts, known in the world of rolling
stock as ``foamers'' _ as in foaming at the mouth. These people
recognize locomotives by number and make comments like: ``So he
says you're an investor in his chooch.''
</P>
<P>
   One passenger, Frank Fairbanks of Pittsburgh, said he ranked
second among collectors of North American route miles _ at close to
250,000, not counting repeat trips. He once worked for American
Locomotive, an engine manufacturer, for a few years and loves
finding sections of track that he hasn't ridden before. On this
run, that meant 250 miles between Thunder Bay and Longlac,
Ontario. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another traveler, John Harmon of Lawrenceville, N.J., used to
take his wife, Elaine, on Friday-night dates to the Bethlehem, Pa.,
train station to watch the trains hook up. He worked for the New
York Central Railroad for five years as a computer programmer, and
has traveled from Berlin to Vladivostok behind a steam engine and
enjoyed ostrich for dinner on Rovos Rail, a luxury train that
operates in southern Africa. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back at home, Harmon called the Canadian trek ``a truly
first-class, luxurious train-travel experience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The food was outstanding,'' he said. ``I thought there were
very few things they could do to improve on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Company officials say train buffs do not make up a high
percentage of passengers. But Hillman thinks everyone is a train
buff at heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask anybody if they like trains and train travel, and they all
love it,'' he said. ``But if you ask them when was the last time
they've done it, they don't recall at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
