<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEV-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENEGADE CHALLENGER IN NEVADA GOP RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BRETT PULLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The bodyguard who sits at the entrance of the
campaign headquarters of the gubernatorial candidate Aaron Russo
has few if any words for visitors who walk in. He just sits there,
way too big for his chair, incessantly spitting tobacco in a
Styrofoam cup. But his menacing presence befits the renegade
campaign of Russo, a rich Hollywood producer who swaggered into
town just two years ago and has become an intimidating and
unsettling force leading to next week's primary election.
</P>
<P>
   Although the polls show Russo trailing in his bid to win the
Republican nomination to succeed Gov. Bob Miller, his presence in
the race has turned what was expected to be a cakewalk for the
party's favorite into a competitive, and colorful, contest. The
Republican Party's favored candidate is Kenny Guinn, a 62-year-old
retired businessman and educator who for more than two years has
been considered the likely choice to succeed Miller, a Democrat who
is prohibited by state law from running for a third term.
</P>
<P>
   Although Guinn has the backing of the moneyed and muscular
casino industry, a funny thing happened on the way to his
coronation. Russo, 55, who has never sought public office and has
not voted since Ronald Reagan was in the White House, decided to
spend some of the millions he earned producing motion picture hits
like ``The Rose'' and ``Trading Places'' in an effort to upset
Guinn. And, surprising many here, Russo has managed to attract a
following among disaffected and anti-establishment voters.
</P>
<P>
   As a current favorite of the state's talk radio listeners, Russo
has insisted that Nevadans are paying too much in taxes, while the
casino industry _which for 18 years has paid 6 1/4 percent of its
gross revenue _ is paying too little.
</P>
<P>
   ``They own the state,'' Russo said of the gambling businesses,
which have contributed one-third of the $3.9 million that Guinn's
campaign has raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Casinos contribute to all the politicians,'' he added in an
interview. ``So government does whatever the casino industry
wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Built like a meatloaf _ round and fleshy _ with a bone-crushing
handshake, Russo, at 5 p.m. on a recent 100-plus-degree day, talked
about his campaign as he quickly devoured a chocolate-covered
doughnut topped with candy sprinkles.
</P>
<P>
   He has refused to accept contributions from casino interests,
and in fact a $1,000 check from the Atlantic City casino owner
Donald Trump sat uncashed on top of his desk. He said he had no
plans to cash it.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign has raised only $30,000, but Russo has spent nearly
$1 million of his own money in an effort to match Guinn's hefty
spending on advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight months ago, the prediction of most people was that Guinn
would just walk into the governor's mansion,'' said Michael Bowers,
who teaches political science at the University of Nevada at Las
Vegas. ``I don't think anyone expected Russo to do as well as he
has done.''
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by 41 percentage points in a poll conducted in June by
The Las Vegas Review-Journal, Russo closed to within 7 points in
another of the newspaper's polls conducted earlier this month.
Friday, however, the latest Review-Journal poll results show that
recent negative advertising by the Guinn campaign might be paying
off, as 51 percent of those surveyed said they would vote for Guinn
on Tuesday, compared with 33 percent for Russo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that seven months of pounding on Kenny by
Aaron Russo has probably cut a little bit,'' conceded Michael
Getto, Guinn's press secretary. But the latest poll results, he
said, are ``more in line'' with what Guinn's own internal polls
have indicated.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected face-off between the Republican candidates has
also bolstered the chances for the leading Democratic contender,
Mayor Jan Jones of Las Vegas. Ms. Jones, 49, who entered the race a
few months after a diagnosis of breast cancer, has a comfortable
lead over her rivals.
</P>
<P>
   With the two leading Republican candidates attacking each other
in television advertisements, Ms. Jones has been able to stay on
the high road, running more positive advertisements. The television
commercial that has perhaps best defined the race and also helped
Guinn regain a comfortable lead in the polls is one that shows
footage from a 1994 video pilot that Russo filmed called ``Aaron
Russo's Mad as Hell.''
</P>
<P>
   In the video, the future candidate for governor, sporting long
hair and a dangling earring, unleashes a vitriolic attack on
government.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisement has ``been pretty effective,'' Getto said.
``It's overturned the rock a little bit to show what he's really
all about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
