<SLUG> BC-NY-PORN-SHOP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN GIULIANI'S CRACKDOWN ON PORN SHOPS, COURT RULING IS A SET BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for comments from representatives for the porn shops and the
mayor's office.)  (js) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A state judge dealt a blow Friday to New York City's
efforts to curtail the pornography industry, ruling that Show
World, a midtown Manhattan porn emporium, and two other adult video
stores can stay in business as long as no more than 40 percent of
their floor space and inventory are dedicated to adult
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by Judge Stephen Crane of state Supreme Court in
Manhattan breaks a long-running series of legal victories on the
issue for the Giuliani administration and suggests that the mayor
may achieve only a muted victory in his crackdown on sex shops. The
city said it would not appeal Crane's ruling, but it vowed to
continue trying to shut sex shops.
</P>
<P>
   While several strip clubs have already been shut down under the
new anti-pornography zoning law, Friday's court ruling indicates
that some adult video stores may be able to remain open by selling
non-adult merchandise in the front portion of their sales space and
reserving back rooms for adult entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to comply with the new zoning restrictions, the owners
of Show World, a 20-year-old, three-story business took advantage
of vague language in the new law that defined an adult
establishment as a business that devotes a ``substantial portion''
of its stock or floor space to adult entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the Department of Building's interpretation of
``substantial portion'' as more than 40 percent, Show World and
other video stores replaced more than 60 percent of their ``triple
X'' videos, ``peep-a-live'' booths and other sex merchandise with
luggage, cameras, NYPD T-shirts and classic films. They then
declared themselves ``non-adult'' businesses to the court.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the city argued that the changes were a
``subterfuge'' by the stores to evade the new law, which bars adult
video stores and strip clubs from operating in residential areas or
within 500 feet of a school, house of worship or another sex shop.
</P>
<P>
   But in his opinion, Crane ruled that the changes implemented by
Show World, NRS Video and Les Hommes were substantial and make them
``non-adult businesses'' under the new law.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear whether sex shops that eliminate more than 60
percent of their lucrative pornographic merchandise can remain
economically viable, particularly in high-rent parts of Manhattan
such as Times Square.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Herald Price Fahringer, the lawyer representing 107 of the 144
sex shops affected by the law, said Friday that he believed that
the profit margins of the video stores might shrink if they
eliminated most of their sex-related inventory, but predicted that
many would remain in business.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Wexler, Show World's controller, said Friday that the
business had been forced to end all strip shows and lay off 20
people, including the dancers, since changing its inventory. But he
said the store was still making a profit and would definitely
survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not operating in the red, but our bottom line has
definitely been hurt,'' he said. ``We're confident we'll be able to
keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Fishner, the mayor's criminal justice coordinator, said
the ruling would not affect the city's enforcement of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``To date, 13 illegal establishments are closed due to court
orders and more than 20 others have voluntarily closed their
doors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Crane's decision applies to Friday's case only, and it does not
present a legal impediment to future enforcement of the zoning law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
