<SLUG> BC-BEEF-GLUT-$ADV30-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERSUPPLY DEVASTATING BEEF PRICES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Aug. 30) 
 
By NELSON ANTOSH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Dave Scott sums up in one word how his investment in
the cattle feeding business is performing _ ``horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   The experienced Texas cattleman describes the current state of
the business as a money loser for himself and others who fatten
cattle.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of growing steers and heifers to slaughter weight has
exceeded the selling price for at least a year, he says. Each
situation is a little different, but he estimates the break-even at
65 or 66 cents per pound.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison the average price paid for fattened steers in the
Texas Panhandle, the heart of the nation's beef production, dropped
to 57 cents per pound this week, the lowest since early May 1996.
</P>
<P>
   This translates into losses ranging anywhere from $15 to $200
per animal sold, depending upon such things as how much was paid
for the calf when it was bought from the rancher.
</P>
<P>
   The cause for the lower prices is an oversupply of beef, itself
brought about, in part, by the drought, a reduction in beef
exports, and competition from pork and poultry.
</P>
<P>
   The cumulative losses over such a long period of time may be
unprecedented and are eating into the beef industry's equity, say
some industry observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty serious, there will be farmers and ranchers in
foreclosure over this,'' said Guy Walker, manager of Dawn Cattle
Feeders, near the Panhandle town of Dawn. ``It's been 25 years
since we saw losses of this magnitude. This is one of the worst
market disasters since the 1970s.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the situation in 1974 when President Nixon
froze the price of beef and the futures price for live animals fell
the limit for seven days in a row, said Lindsay Davis, president of
Alamo Commodities in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The feedlots didn't go out of business, said Davis, but a lot of
people stopped investing in feeding and never returned.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are seeing some lower prices in the meat counters but
not as low as some of the feeders would expect.
</P>
<P>
   The National Cattlemen's Beef Association in Englewood, Colo.,
quotes government figures that the retail price for all beef,
including choice, select and ungraded cuts, was $2.54 per pound
during the first six months of this year, down from $2.71 per pound
five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And the average price for choice cuts is the lowest since 1989,
the organization said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been some ``hot'' specials on beef througout the
summer and they will get even better for the Labor Day weekend,
said Gary Huddleston, spokesman for the Houston-area Kroger stores.
Prices will be lower than a year ago, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   But feedlot operators like Walker and Jay Davis, general manager
of the Graham Land &AMP; Cattle Co. in Gonzales, Texas, don't think the
wholesale prices are really that low. ``Here we are giving cattle
away,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Packer buyers have been holding back because large supplies in
the feedlots work to their advantage, Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Packers have found that the best way to defend their margins
is to not run wide open,'' he said. ``It's been very effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Packer giant IBP responds that all of its beef plants are
currently running 40 hours a week or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could increase production further;, however, we would have
no place to go with the additional product,'' the Dakota City,
Neb., company said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   The driving force behind current prices is oversupply, said IBP
spokesman Gary Mickelson. An estimated 16.7 billion more pounds of
beef, pork and poultry will be produced this year than in 1990, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Poultry production alone will be up by about 10 billion pounds,
followed by pork at 3.5 billion and beef at 3.2 billion pounds.
</P>
<P>
   There are several other reasons that prices for live steers and
heifers are depressed.
</P>
<P>
   Exports are down because the economic problems in beef-buying
countries in Asia reduced demand. Shipments to South Korea dropped
55 percent during the first five months, said Chuck Lambert, chief
economist for the beef association.
</P>
<P>
   The drought pushed thousands of calves off pastures into
feedlots in Texas _ the No. 1 beef-producing state.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a huge oversupply of pork, which competes with
beef in the meat case. The pig raisers are in much the same
situation as ranchers, mired in a meat glut.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's feedlots, with Texas far in the lead, are crowded
with grain-munching steers and heifers. Compared with a year
earlier, Texas added 14 percent as of Aug. 1 while Kansas and
Nebraska, the other two big feeding states, decreased slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are there more animals in the pens, but they are also
heavier. The wheat pastures of winter and spring provided excellent
grazing, meaning that calves went into the feedlots at heavier
weights.
</P>
<P>
   And in a mass example of wishful thinking, many cattle owners
have been holding off selling in hopes that the market will turn
upward.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the number being slaughtered is off slightly but the
tonnage of meat produced is up. Cattle are being slaughtered at
record weights of more than 1,200 pounds each.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few extra pounds per animal adds greatly to the tonnage
in a country that slaughters from 33 million to 36 million head per
year, according to Lambert of te National Cattlemen's Beef
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Too many owners were sitting on their hands two weeks ago when
93,498 cattle were sent to slaughter, said Burt Rutherford,
spokesman for the Texas Cattle Feeders Association in Amarillo.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, even though the price was 2 cents a pound lower, a
relatively high 123,500 cattle went to the packing house. ``There
was no choice, they had to sell,'' he said. In the meantime the
animals gained about 25 pounds each.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to resist the temptation to hold on for one more week
in hopes that prices will improve, said Rutherford.
</P>
<P>
   ``They lose so much they don't want to sell, it's a
hope-and-pray kind of deal, '' said Walker whose custom feedlot in
the Panhandle feeds animals on a fee basis.
</P>
<P>
   But Scott isn't holding on for better prices. He sells when the
feedlot operator says the animals are ready. ``They're like
watermelons, when they're ripe you better pick them,'' said Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Scott's cattle are located in feedlot pens at opposite ends of
the state, in the King Ranch feedlot at Kingsville and in Cattle
Town at Hereford, in the Panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   He softened the blow of falling prices with some fortunate
hedges, locking in a price by selling ahead. But probably less than
half the cattle in feedlots are hedged. A number are owned by the
yards themselves, ``who are losing a ton of money,'' said Scott.
</P>
<P>
   The drought takes much of the blame for so many cattle in
feedlots in Texas. Calves were pushed off pastures when the supply
of grass ran out.
</P>
<P>
   The number of new animals coming into the feedlot during May and
June skyrocketed, said Gray, in Gonzales. They came from east of
Austin, the Tyler, Nacogdoches and the Sulphur Springs areas, in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't have had half that many if it hadn't been so
dry,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of big grain crops in the Midwest is another reason
so many people are willing to continue feeding cattle. Holding on
for a week or two is less painful, and if feed goes down enough
they may be able to break even at some point in the future even at
58 or 59 cents.
</P>
<P>
   There is an old saying in the industry, said Lindsay, ``cheap
feed, cheap cattle.'' Cheaper feed also results in more pork and
more poultry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
