<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8369 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TRIP-$ADV30-C     08-28 1542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TRIP-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AS CLINTON HEADS FOR RUSSIA IN CRISIS, FOCUS OF AGENDA REMAINS
UNCLEAR
 &HT;    With TRIP-BOX-$ADV30.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Aug. 30 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Early Friday, with the staggering Russian economy
careening through another catastrophic day and embattled President
Boris Yeltsin emerging from three tense days of public silence to
vigorously denounce rumors of his imminent resignation, National
Security Advisor Samuel R. ``Sandy'' Berger placed an urgent call
to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking over a secure line from Martha's Vineyard, Mass., where
he's been struggling against long odds to have a vacation truncated
by scandal, airstrikes and global economic pains, Clinton wanted to
know one thing: should he scrap this week's summit in Moscow?
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely not, Berger counseled.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Berger insisted, Russia's economic and political turmoil
made it all the more imperative that Clinton be fully engaged, and
be seen by the Russian people to be fully engaged, in a crisis that
threatens to turn back the clock on a decade of hard-fought reform
in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one is nostalgic for the Cold War,'' Berger told reporters
later. ''And no one wants a weak Russia beset by crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, diminished by scandal at home and convinced that pouring
new aid into Russia's failing economy has become a losing game,
Clinton leaves Monday for Moscow on a mission of commiseration with
the addled Russian leader.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is to spend Tuesday meeting with Yeltsin, speaking to
students and parents about the next generation of Russians and
attending a state dinner with the Russian leader. On Wednesday,
Clinton is scheduled to confer with a wide range of national and
regional figures, including communists and nationalists, as well as
reformists. He later in the week travels to Northern Ireland and
the Republic of Ireland, where a fragile, U.S.-brokered peace
process is struggling to gain traction.
</P>
<P>
   Where most state visits tend to be tightly choreographed down to
the slightest presidential utterance and move, Clinton's trip to
Moscow is a loosely scripted work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely there will be a Russian government in place when
Clinton arrives, after all, and even Yeltsin's position is
precarious.
</P>
<P>
   Surmised Russia analyst Thomas Remington of Atlanta's Emory
University: ''Clinton's going to have to improvise.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be a kind way of putting it.
</P>
<P>
   With polls showing that four Americans in 10 believe Clinton's
months of deception over his affair with Monica Lewinsky has left
his credibility too threadbare for effective leadership, and
Yeltsin's support fast dwindling to something like family members,
some analysts have already dismissed this week's summit as little
more than a desperate voyage of the politically doomed.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have, to different degrees, two discredited leaders who
are, in some ways, using each other to no concrete end -- except
maybe for their own ratings and popularity,'' said economist
Matthew Sherwood, a Russia expert with PlanEcon Inc., a Washington
consulting firm that specializes in the former Soviet states. ''For
Clinton, I think he's trying to look statesmanlike, and, for the
Russians, I think they want to make it look like it's business as
usual.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Yeltsin sacked his entire cabinet, claiming that
youthful Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko had failed to lead the
country toward a market-based economy capable of contending in the
global marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Such political chaos broke the back of the Russian currency,
already lumbering from the sagging price of oil, the country's
chief generator of dollars. In less than two weeks, the ruble has
lost nearly half of its value against the dollar, despite heavy
intervention by Russia's central bank and last month's pledge by
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to provide $22.6 billion to
help prop up the battered currency.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers stampeded banks in hopes of pulling out rubles and
converting them to dollars while the Russian coin was still worth
converting.
</P>
<P>
   The government said it would not be able to repay its
dollar-denominated debt, and banks, threatened with collapse,
suspended some operations. This fueled further panic in a country
already reeling from nearly a decade of dislocation and diminished
output spreading from the loss of empire and the pain that has come
from shedding decades of communist controls in favor of the risks
and rewards of the free market.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, for the third day in a row, Russia's central bank shut
down trading rather than risk a ruble free-fall, as Yeltsin's pick
to head a new cabinet, former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin,
met with opposition lawmakers to discuss new economic measures that
harken back to the communist era. He's got good reason to deal: the
Russian Duma, dominated by opposition groups ranging from
communists to nationalists, is scheduled to debate Chernomyrdin's
nomination on Monday. Weeks of discord are expected to presage his
confirmation, unless political fighting stalemates the process
completely.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials were quick to say they had no confirmation
that Moscow was considering a return to a centrally planned
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Even rumors, though, that Yeltsin was considering price
controls, massive ruble printing, artificially freezing the ruble's
value and perhaps even nationalizing industries only recently
turned private, were enough to elicit dark warnings from Deputy
Treasury Secretary Larry Summers, the administration's global
economic constable with jurisdiction over emerging markets gone
awry.
</P>
<P>
   ''A move back towards central planning based on price controls
and administrative allocation of goods,'' Summers cautioned,
''would be a serious policy error and very unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Summers and Berger, who briefed reporters at the White House on
Friday, are part of the delegation accompanying Clinton to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   They leave Monday for a summit that was scheduled in June, amid
hopes of resolving issues such as the future of the Serbian
province of Kosovo, where Serb troops last week added to weeks of
anti-Albanian bloodshed by murdering three aid workers ferrying
humanitarian supplies for an agency founded by the late Mother
Theresa.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, though, the White House was in emergency mode,
worried about the continued viability of Yeltsin and the economy of
a country that less than a decade ago formed the core of a global
superpower that challenged the United States in virtually every
corner of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, White House officials voiced confidence in Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said he had ''absolutely no reason to believe that he's
not in firm control of the military and other elements of the
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, however, officials are weighing a three-tiered
hierarchy of concern.
</P>
<P>
   Of greatest worry is the risk of a breakdown of law and order in
the world's second-largest nuclear power. Russia still controls
thousands of nuclear warheads and a vast arsenal measured in tons
of nuclear weapons material.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts need look no further back than last spring's
economically-triggered riots that paralyzed Indonesia and brought
the government of aging autocrat President Suharto to his knees for
an unsavory glimpse at what a descent into chaos might look like in
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ''People see turmoil in a country that has a lot of nukes,''
said Sherwood.
</P>
<P>
   Even absent a turn toward anarchy -- which isn't expected yet
can't be ruled out -- Russia's woes have compounded long-festering
U.S. fears that terrorists, organized crime rings, or some unholy
alliance of both, might get their hands on a Russian nuclear weapon
and use it, or threaten to, in the ultimate security nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   The second order of threat U.S. policymakers fear is the
overthrow of the Russian government, and its fledgling system of
democracy, by leaders who use the current political and economic
troubles to justify usurpation of power.
</P>
<P>
   ''The threat is that the army would combine with conservative
leaders and take power,'' said Remington, professor of political
science at Emory. ''We could get a suspension of the
constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Failing such extremes, Russia could, finally, retreat from the
political and economic reforms it has struggled to embrace in the
six and a half years since the collapse of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   That would represent a dramatic, and potentially dangerous,
setback of the twin pillars of U.S. policy in the post Cold War
world: the promotion of democratic governments and free-market
economies.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Berger sounded like a man already haunted by the
question: Who lost Russia?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have supported policies that we thought made sense,''
Berger said. ``President Yeltsin, after all, is the elected
president of Russia, twice elected by the people of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a democracy, they get to make the decisions about the
directions that they take. But I don't think by any stretch of the
imagination one can argue that the current financial situation in
Russia is a result of U.S. actions.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
