<SLUG> BC-GLF-USAMATEUR29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spaniard ousts Kuchar
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. _ It's a scene that promises to be replayed
dozens of times over the next two decades or so.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, 18-year-old Spaniard Sergio Garcia on Friday ended Matt
Kuchar's dream of retaining his U.S. Amateur Championship, winning
2 and 1 their brilliant display of shotmaking at storied Oak Hill
Country Club, but it's only the beginning. When they both
eventually turn pro _ Garcia's gone after the '99 Masters _ there
are sure to be Ryder Cup matches played throughout the world to
regularly showcase their talents and similarly stir their thousands
of fans.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Friday's match, with 4,500 fans following in the fairway,
close enough to touch the tension, might always serve as the
reference point. It became match play at his finest, loaded with
great shots and sprinkled with some grand gamesmanship. Though
officially the featured match of the U.S. Amateur quarterfinals, it
never felt like anything other than a Sunday final. In the end,
Garcia, the British Amateur champion, put away the Georgia Tech
junior with a 8-foot birdie at the 16th hole to go 1-up _ prompting
a low, triple-pump of his right fist _ then clinched with a
two-putt par at the 17th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran into El Nino, I guess,'' Kuchar said, referring to
Garcia's nickname, which means ``the Boy'' in Spanish. ``It was
just a heck of a match. From the first hole to the 17th hole, it
was great shot after great shot. I'll probably watch it over and
over again just to see good golf. Hopefully, we can relive this at
a Ryder Cup. That would be exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably one of my best matches I've ever played,''
said the 5-foot-10, 150-pound Garcia, whose aggressive recovery
abilities have painted him as another Seve Ballesteros, ``and I
played with a great opponent, a great guy. I think we are very good
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia moves on to face Tom McKnight, a 43-year-old petroleum
distributor from Galax, Va., in a 9 a.m. semifinal match today,
trying to become the first player to win the British Amateur and
the U.S. Amateur in the same year since American Bob Dickson in
1967. Kuchar returns to relative college normalcy after a whirlwind
year that began with his out-of-nowhere Amateur win last year at
Cog Hill and continued through to magical performances in the
Masters and U.S. Open. His next tournament with any potential
national focus will be an appearance in the PGA Tour Buick
Challenge at Callaway Gardens Oct. 1-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very glad I came back,'' Kuchar said. ``I'm glad I decided
to stay an amateur even though I lost in the quarterfinals. ...
It's been a wild ride. I kind of enjoy the limelight, but every
once in a while it's nice to kick back and get away and be Matt
Kuchar, be a kid who's unknown and just walk around campus. Right
now I'm ready to go chill out for a while, be myself and go back to
school.''
</P>
<P>
   For Georgia Tech, the day became, in coach Bruce Heppler's
words, ``Black Friday.'' While in the back of his mind pondering an
all-Tech final of Kuchar vs. Bryce Molder, Heppler got a double
whammy. Molder lost 5 and 4 to long-hitting Hank Kuehne, 22, a
recovering alcoholic for the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   Searching for solace in the absence of a championship chance,
Molder decided, ``It's probably good I'm not going to have to go
through a lot of what Matt went through this year. I'm probably
going to play in at least three more of these.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
