</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BUCKSHOT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jones carries `reckless' reputation
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ A reputation is a fragile thing. It can carry you
to the heights or leave you dangling somewhere in between.
</P>
<P>
   Buckshot Jones knows that well.
</P>
<P>
   His infamous feud with driver Randy Lajoie, which began in 1996,
has calmed. But those incidents _ the two ran into each other often
during Busch races _ has other drivers worried about Jones'
``reckless'' driving and Jones is on the defensive about every
collision.
</P>
<P>
   The low was last week at Bristol during a Busch race. Elton
Sawyer and Robert Pressley accused Jones of ``stupid driving,'' and
radio commentators blistered him for instigating a wreck on a
restart with 11 laps remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The accident began with the field racing out of turn four and
onto the front stretch. Jones was on the low side, a lap down, when
the race leaders began passing. Pressley, who was leading the race,
was in the high groove. Jones and Pressley collided, and the
ensuing melee damaged the cars of Ricky Craven, Ken Schrader, Tim
Fedewa, Mike McLaughlin, Sawyer, Tony Stewart and Kevin Grubb.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Pressley was looking at a 19th-place finish
instead of a victory, and Jones was standing his ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't cause that wreck,'' he said during an interview with
television commentators. ``I kept my line on the bottom of the
track. Pressley came down on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Replays backed that contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shocked me, what they said on radio and TV,'' Jones, who
finished eighth, said this week. ``Somebody pointed the finger at
me. I know I've got a reputation as being out of control at times,
and sometimes I push too hard. But I stayed on the bottom of the
track this time. I did not go up and hit him.''
</P>
<P>
   Television commentators Benny Parsons and Buddy Baker, who were
critical during the telecast, agreed. But they also said Jones
needs experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buckshot has a lot of ability, but like everyone he has a lot
to learn,'' said Parsons, the 1973 Winston Cup champion. ``At
Bristol, he didn't do anything wrong, but he put himself in
position to be hit. He shouldn't have been where he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker, winner of 19 Winston Cup races, believes Jones' run-in
with Lajoie built a reckless reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The booing he received last week at Bristol shouldn't have
happened,'' Baker said. ``If those people, and I don't mean just at
Bristol, would take time to look at the replays, they would see
things differently. He's talented and will never have to worry
about backing once he comes to Winston Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsons believes Jones can be a better Winston Cup driver than
he has been on the Busch circuit. He showed it at Dover in May,
finishing eighth in the Circuit City car.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if he's one of the best Busch guys, he should be like
(Jeff) Gordon, above the fray, rather than part of it,'' Parsons
said. ``He needs to sit down and examine who he is. All the money
in the world won't bring him success. Look at (team owner) Gary
Bechtel. He has all the money in the world and can't win out here.
Bottom line? He has no future out here if he keeps wrecking.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
