<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-IRL-QUALIFYING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Boat hits 223, takes the pole for the Classic
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Billy Boat might have been one of the few surprised
Friday when he blazed around Atlanta Motor Speedway at 224.145 and
captured the pole for Saturday night's Atlanta Classic 500.
</P>
<P>
   Boat and owner A.J. Foyt were concerned that the green No. 111
Conseco/A.J. Foyt Dallara/Aurora/Goodyear couldn't get around the
track five times because of electrical problems.
</P>
<P>
   Boat was one of six drivers who went 223 mph or faster in
qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   His Foyt teammate, Kenny Brack, looking for his third
consecutive win _ which would be the first in IRL history _ ran his
Foyt Power Racing team car 223.117 mph to qualify for sixth
position. Brack is No. 2 in points.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Ward was second at 223.973 and IRL points leader Scott
Sharp third at 223.837.
</P>
<P>
   The big surprise of the day was the dismal 213.543 _ unexplained
_ by 1997 IRL champion Tony Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   No one in the pits or stands _ some 18,000 _ would have bet that
Stewart would qualify 25th in a 28-car field.
</P>
<P>
   Boat drives the green car, supposedly an unlucky color in
racing, but Stewart has had buzzard luck the past couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He was the IRL points leader and dropped to third after losing
15 points as part of a penalty to Team Menard for altering the
wings to lessen downforce and get more speed (he exceeded 228 mph
in July tests at AMS).
</P>
<P>
   Then, he was involved in the 22-car Busch-race pileup at
Bristol.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's starting at the bottom of the heap today, trying to
catch a driver who still walks with a cane.
</P>
<P>
   Before the season began, Stewart announced he was switching to
NASCAR because there were no more challenges in the IRL. Today,
he'll have 24 challenges to take the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee a lot of people are going to see that (No. 1)
Menard going through the pack,'' said Boat.
</P>
<P>
   As for Boat's mild surprise about being on the pole: ``We never
got consistent charging,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So, as has been the case since his June crash in New Hampshire,
Boat did it the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that might help Stewart is the possiblity of help in
the draft. Boat said the draft will be a ``huge'' factor at
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than any other track,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said fans might see as many as five or six cars running
together.
</P>
<P>
   And at speeds never before seen on a Southern raceway.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
