<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slick surface has drivers sliding into wall
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Under most circumstances, Winston Cup practice is
as exciting as watching street cars run on the interstate.
</P>
<P>
   But there was nothing ordinary about Friday's 90-minute session
at New Hampshire International Speedway. A recently applied asphalt
conditioner became as treacherous as an ice skating rink.
</P>
<P>
   Five cars slid into the wall, four of them damaged serious
enough to cause teams to go to backup cars for qualifying. The cars
were: Jeff Burton's Ford, Dale Earnhardt's Monte Carlo, Ron
Fellows' Monte Carlo, Ernie Irvan's Pontiac, Ward Burton's Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Marlin spun his Monte Carlo but missed the wall. Dale
Jarrett spun, hurting the engine and forcing his crew to change
engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't miss the groove, I didn't miss it at all,'' said Jeff
Burton. ``For whatever reason, there was oil on the track.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlin and Earnhardt wrecked in almost the same place, but
Earnhardt hit a little harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just going to be a survival Sunday,'' Marlin said. ``You
can't race hard because you're going to wreck. If they don't fix
it, they'll wreck 20 cars on restarts. I don't know how they'll fix
it. I guess if you got some dynamite you could fix it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sealer is on it. I guess the more laps run, the more
they'll burn off the sealer and maybe they'll get down to some
decent asphalt. They've either got to concrete it or find out the
mix they've got at some other tracks and put it on this track and
bank it so we can race.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: Gordon's crew chief Ray Evernham put aside his tools
Friday after Winston Cup qualifying to take a few laps in a Busch
North car prior to its qualifying.... The field of current Busch
Grand National drivers moving to Winston Cup in 1998 include
Buckshot Jones and Elton Sawyer. Sawyer likely will team up with
the Wood Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
