<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-POLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gordon has time for CMT pole win
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Timing is everything in Winston Cup qualifying,
and Jeff Gordon timed things just right Friday, winning his first
pole at New Hampshire International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon drew the 15th qualifying slot for Sunday's Country Music
Television 300 and made the most of it with a speed of 129.033 mph.
That was safely ahead of those who tiptoed around the 1.05-mile
oval, still slick from an asphalt reconditioner applied earlier in
the day.
</P>
<P>
   ''We needed a little momentum coming out of that fifth place
finish at Bristol,'' Gordon said of his start last week. ''I'm
feeling a little bit better than I was last week when I was under
the weather. We were right there in the top 10 and top five in
practice all day, and it was a great run for us. I feel a little
sorry for those who went out first. It was a tough track for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   So tough, in fact, that three of the first four couldn't hold it
off the wall, with Dan Pardus, Ricky Rudd and Wally Dallenbach
taking the hardest hits. They qualified 46th, 34th and 37th
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   From there it was mostly clear sailing, with few exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was just a big disadvantage if you went out first or got an
early draw,'' Rudd said. ''I don't know what it is about New
Hampshire, but for some reason the guys that go later can be as
much as a second faster.''
</P>
<P>
   The luck of the draw kicked in with Mark Martin, the 11th car
out, giving confidence to those followed. For instance, Bobby
Labonte went out 40th and qualified second; Ken Schrader was 35th
to go and was third fastest; Kenny Wallace was last, but starts
fourth Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our goal was to make the top 10,'' Martin said. ''This was a
real poor situation with the draw. This track bleeds some kind of
grease whenever you don't run on it, and an early draw really hurts
you. You feel for those who went out early.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those facing second round qualifying today are Johnny
Benson, 39th, Rich Bickle (40th), Dave Marcis (41st), Buckshot
Jones (43rd), Michael Waltrip (44th) and Ron Fellows (45th).
Darrell Waltrip is 42nd, but has a past champion's provisional to
fall back on.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a backup car these guys have used at tracks like
Martinsville,'' said Fellows, who wrecked the same car twice during
practice. ''We've got some work to do. I guess the backup car club
has grown a lot today, and it looks like we're in good company.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
