<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON: ONE MUST FORGIVE TO BE FORGIVEN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAK BLUFFS, Mass. _ In a sweltering church echoing with kind
words toward him, a clearly moved President Clinton sought a
measure of atonement Friday as he said one must forgive in order to
seek forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, stopping short of an apology for the Monica Lewinsky
scandal, made his first remarks on the topic since a defiant
address to the nation Aug. 17, the day before coming here to
Martha's Vineyard for vacation.
</P>
<P>
   His remarks, handwritten on the back of the original draft
written by aides, caught even his staff by surprise. White House
aides for nearly two weeks have pondered a way to help Clinton save
his presidency since he conceded an ``improper relationship'' with
the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday afternoon, the president stood on familiar territory,
in a pulpit at Union Chapel here, where 300 people gathered to
commemorate the 35th anniversary of the March on Washington and
Martin Luther King's ``I have a dream'' speech. The president spoke
about the lessons he learned from the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of you know, I'm having to become quite an expert in this
business of asking for forgiveness,'' he said as the racially
diverse audience repeatedly applauded him. ``It gets a little
easier the more you do it. And if you have a family, an
administration, a Congress and a whole country to ask you, you're
going to get a lot of practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have to tell you that in these last days, it has come
home to me again, something I first learned as president, but it
wasn't burned in my bones, and that is that in order to get it, you
have to be willing to give it,'' he said as the crowd again
applauded.
</P>
<P>
   ``And all of us _ the anger, the resentment, the bitterness, the
desire for recrimination against people you believe have wronged
you, they harden the heart and deaden the spirit and lead to
self-inflicted wounds. And so it is important that we are able to
forgive those we believe have wronged us, even as we ask for
forgiveness from people we have wronged,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks perhaps were aimed at independent counsel
Kenneth Starr, whose four-year investigation into the president
turned in January to allegations of an affair with the former White
House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The president, who addressed the nation after testifying before
Starr's grand jury, acknowledged deceiving the nation and his wife
about Lewinsky for seven months, but he then attacked Starr and
called for the matter to be left alone.
</P>
<P>
   The speech angered Republicans and upset Democrats who had hoped
for the president to apologize and appear contrite. Calls for
Clinton to resign have increased even as opinion polls indicate the
public wants him to stay in office.
</P>
<P>
   But still there was no apology, and aides refused to provide any
interpretation of the president's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Sosnik, a presidential adviser traveling with the
president, said Clinton personally wrote his speech and did not
tell aides its contents. ``That's the way he felt when he wrote
it,'' Sosnik said.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Toiv, the White House spokesman, said, ``I don't think
we're going to be in the interpretation business. The words speak
for themselves. He got up today and decide that's want he wanted to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Since admitting he deceived his wife and Americans about an
affair with Lewinsky, the president has secluded himself in a
waterfront estate near here with first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
and daughter Chelsea. But his vacation from Washington, both
personal and political, comes to a close on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   What exactly happened in that house for nearly two weeks isn't
known, but White House spokesmen repeatedly said the family was
working on ``healing'' the breach in the family caused by Clinton's
affair. There has been no golf, Clinton's usual form of relaxation.
And, his break was interrupted by his order for military strikes
against terrorist bases last week.
</P>
<P>
   Temporarily, the president can take some refuge in an
international crisis as he leaves Monday for Russia, Ireland and
Northern Ireland before returning on Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But the president will return to Washington to face an uncertain
political future and no clear strategy other than trying to change
the focus.
</P>
<P>
   The president did fly to nearby Worcester on Thursday where he
was greeted by large and enthusiastic crowds as he spoke about
school violence. And, the event at Union Chapel originally was
intended to underscore Clinton's policies.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton enters the unknown as both the White House and
Congress await Starr's report into the relationship with Lewinsky
and the possible abuse of power in covering up the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton's advisers seem divided on what the
president's next steps should be in dealing with American public
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sense I have is that public opinion isn't settled and they
don't know quite how to reinforce it and he's going to give a
speech to put a policy face back on the administration,'' said
Bruce Buchanan, a presidential expert at the University of Texas at
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the question of what next seems very much up in the
air,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One Democratic congressional aide speculated that Clinton's
fellow Democrats will take a ``wait and see'' attitude until
Starr's report arrives at the House of Representatives. Until then,
few are willing to offer any defense of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in Union Chapel, the defense was long and loud and
clearly moved Clinton, who mouthed the words ``thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the president has a lot of fair-weather friends,'' said
Charles Ogletree Jr., a Harvard University law professor who hosted
the celebration at Union Chapel. ``This is not a fair-weather
crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
