<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8387 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPEND-AUTO-INSURE-ART     08-28 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-AUTO-INSURE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CALL FOR `AUTO CHOICE' AND LOWER PREMIUMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (also see sidebar, SPEND-AUTO-STATES)  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 30) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
By PETER PASSELL  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spending more for auto insurance than on car payments? You're
not alone.
</P>
<P>
   Although heightened competition, a fraud crackdown and
double-digit returns on insurance companies' investment portfolios
have kept premiums in check for the last few years, the high cost
of auto insurance remains a hot political issue in traffic-choked
states from New Jersey to California.
</P>
<P>
   And an unusual coalition of would-be reformers, urban
officeholders and partisan Republicans is trying to channel that
simmering discontent into the most far-reaching changes in auto
coverage in a quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   The advocates' motto is ``auto choice,'' which stands for a set
of legal changes based on the idea of cutting premiums by limiting
the right to sue for damages. Republican congressional leaders,
eager to seize an issue that touches a populist chord, have vowed
to bring to the floor in both houses before the November elections
a bill that would require states to adopt the auto-choice approach.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of such legislation _ bitterly opposed by trial lawyers
and some consumer groups _ would seem unlikely this fall. But
hardly anything about the plan, which supporters say would save
drivers some $40 billion annually, is following the conventional
script.
</P>
<P>
   For example, insurance companies are divided on auto choice,
even though they might be expected to stand behind any proposal
that clipped the wings of their nemesis, the trial bar. Support for
the plan, meanwhile, has come from such disparate political players
as the conservative U.S. Chamber of Commerce and the pragmatic
mayor of Denver, Wellington Webb.
</P>
<P>
   The roots of auto choice are found in the wreckage of the last
great push for change in auto insurance: the no-fault movement of
the early 1970s. In jurisdictions that adopted no-fault coverage _
13 states, including New York, New Jersey and Connecticut, plus
Puerto Rico _ an accident victim's own insurance company pays
claims against medical bills and lost wages (called economic
losses) up to the policy limits. That contrasts with the ``pure
tort'' arrangement in most other states, in which the injured must
collect from those they say were at fault _ typically, the other
driver's insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   When states first adopted no-fault plans, it was widely assumed
that lawsuits would become rare and that the chunk of insurance
premium dollars swallowed by litigation costs would shrink to
almost nothing. In fact, legislation in almost every no-fault state
left wide loopholes that permitted lawsuits for a range of
non-economic losses.
</P>
<P>
   State no-fault laws routinely make exceptions for deliberately
caused injuries, injuries caused by drunken drivers and injuries
resulting in death. Many states also permit suits for ``loss of
bodily function,'' ``serious disfigurement'' or ``temporary
disability'' _ all examples of injuries serious enough to meet a
legal standard, the so-called verbal threshold for litigation.
Still others set a dollar threshold; when injuries result in
medical bills exceeding some minimum, claims can be brought for
pain and suffering.
</P>
<P>
   These dollar thresholds have had a particularly perverse effect,
according to Michael Horowitz, a senior fellow at the Hudson
Institute, a conservative research group in Washington, who
champions auto choice: They encourage the injured to spend extra on
physicians and chiropractors to meet the legal minimums _ or even
to enlist them in fraud. ``It's become a rule of thumb that
insurers settle claims for three times the medical costs,''
Horowitz said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Worse, perhaps, the tort system rarely compensates those who
most deserve to be compensated. In a 1991 study of thousands of
accidents in pure tort states, the Rand Institute for Civil Justice
estimated that injury victims with economic losses exceeding
$100,000 received just 9 cents on the dollar in compensation, on
average.
</P>
<P>
   And across the spectrum of tort and no-fault states, a
remarkable amount of money is spent just to keep the wheels of
justice in motion. According to a study this year by the Joint
Economic Committee of Congress, attorney fees absorbed 28 percent
of every premium dollar paid for bodily injury coverage in 1996.
Fraudulent claims chewed up an additional 13 percent. And agents'
commissions and other overhead expenses devoured 25 percent. That
left just 34 percent of premiums for compensating accident victims.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, no-fault seems to work best in minimizing lawsuits in
states that set the toughest thresholds for determining whether an
accident victim can go to court _ a requirement, for example, that
an accident result in ``permanent injury or disability.''
</P>
<P>
   But even in Michigan, widely regarded as the toughest no-fault
state, coverage for bodily injuries remains relatively expensive,
because the state mandates that every policy provide unlimited
coverage of economic losses.
</P>
<P>
   Auto choice aims to accomplish the initial goal of no-fault _
lower premiums and fewer lawsuits _ by putting a price on the right
to sue.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers choosing the basic coverage would receive virtually
bulletproof no-fault: They would be permitted to sue for pain and
suffering only when contending that the injury was intentional or
that the other driver was drunk. (They could also sue in the
relatively uncommon circumstance in which tangible economic losses
exceeded their ``personal injury protection'' coverage.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, drivers who wanted the option to sue for pain
and suffering could retain it _ but would pay an additional
premium.
</P>
<P>
   The price difference would be substantial. According to Stephen
Carroll and Allan Abrahamse, researchers at Rand, the cost of
providing bodily injury insurance would be 45 percent less, on
average, for drivers who opted for basic coverage. And since
personal injury protection represents a bit more than half the cost
of auto insurance, the cost of a basic policy under the choice
system would fall a bit less than 25 percent _ an average of $184
for each car each year, by the Rand calculations.
</P>
<P>
   But there would be new complications. When a driver with full
tort coverage was injured by another with a full tort plan, they
would be free, of course, to duke it out in court. And when two
drivers with basic coverage were in an accident, there presumably
would be no suit. But when a driver with tort coverage was hit by a
driver with basic coverage, the injured party would have to sue his
own insurance company for pain and suffering. That situation _
which could occur often _ ``is terribly complicated,'' said Bob
Pike, general counsel for Allstate, one of the nation's biggest
auto insurers, which opposes auto choice.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey O'Connell, a law professor at the University of Virginia
and a proponent of auto choice, says the interaction between tort
and basic drivers had a Rube Goldberg feel to it. But, he noted,
``it's no worse than the problem with uninsured-motorist coverage,
where injured parties must collect from their own insurance
company.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Criticism of auto choice comes in many stripes. Some is
financially motivated, at least in part. In a membership
recruitment letter last year, the Association of Trial Lawyers of
America called auto choice ``an assault on our livelihood.''
</P>
<P>
   Other opposition comes from consumer groups that view any limit
on the right to sue as a dangerous constraint on the little guy.
Without much thought, the vast majority of drivers would give up
their rights in return for premium savings, said Joan Claybrook,
president of Public Citizen, the consumer advocacy group founded by
Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, she argued, ``drivers who cause grievous harm ought to
pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Many insurance executives see the whole notion of federal
intervention as the camel's nose under the tent. ``How we
compensate injury victims should be addressed at the state level,''
said Pike of Allstate.
</P>
<P>
   George Priest, a law professor at Yale University, generally
sympathizes with initiatives to minimize the cost of settling legal
disputes. But he wonders about the justice of auto choice. No-fault
plans socialize the cost of accidents, he said, and barriers to
suits for pain and suffering reduce the chance of collecting from
wrongdoers. Put those together, and auto choice reduces the odds
that dangerous drivers will be forced off the road by higher
premiums. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of auto choice have an answer to each of the
objections. To begin with, the state's rights issue is a red
herring, argued O'Connell of the University of Virginia. Under the
measure pending in Congress, state legislatures would have the
discretion to reject auto choice, while state regulators would have
the authority to block its implementation if insurers could not
guarantee minimum levels of savings for insured drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the states' broad discretion to reject or modify auto
choice _ included in the bill in order to attract conservatives'
votes _ worries some advocates, who remember the process that
peppered no-fault insurance with the loopholes that largely
nullified its impact.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters also scoff at the idea that auto choice would give a
free ride to dangerous drivers. While any no-fault system reduces
deterrence of bad driving, Horowitz argued that the impact would be
very modest. ``Insurers would still have plenty of reason to charge
higher rates to bad drivers,'' he said, because they are more
likely to injure themselves. Besides, he added, drivers who cause
injuries could still be sued for economic losses that exceeded the
injured person's own coverage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However consumers come down on these issues, the potential
savings in premiums will win them over, proponents of auto choice
say.
</P>
<P>
   They figure that those 25 percent savings in premiums for basic
coverage would prove attractive across the board. And the potential
savings for two influential groups are even more striking.
</P>
<P>
   Premiums for commercial vehicles would fall by about 28 percent,
according to the Joint Economic Committee. Corporations, which now
face a disproportionate share of suits for pain and suffering,
would enjoy bigger-than-average savings as the number of suits
declined; injuries to their own drivers, moreover, are already
covered by workmen's compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real simple,'' said Larry Kraus, a spokesman for the
Chamber of Commerce. ``Our three million members would save $8
billion annually.''
</P>
<P>
   City dwellers are also in a position to reap exceptional savings
from restrictions on suits, because urban accident victims are
exceptionally litigious. In Washington, D.C., for instance, auto
accident rates fell 22 percent between 1985 and 1995, but the
number of lawsuits over auto accidents rose 137 percent, according
to the Joint Economic Committee. In 1994, the committee found,
people involved in auto accidents in Los Angeles were 2.2 times as
likely to claim they were injured as people in the rest of the
state. In Philadelphia, the multiple was 3.5; in New York City,
2.7; in Newark, 2.4. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By no coincidence, a 1991 survey by Robert Klein, then the
director of research for the National Association of Insurance
Commissioners, showed that the average liability premium was 32
percent higher for drivers in large cities than in other parts of
the same states. Hence the support for the overhaul proposals from
some big-city politicians. ``I favor auto choice for one reason,''
said Webb, the Denver mayor. ``My constituents would be a lot
better off.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The numbers help explain the eclectic band of supporters drawn
to auto choice. In the Senate, they include Mitch McConnell, R-Ky.,
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., and Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn.
Other supporters are Rep. James Moran of Virginia, a centrist
suburban Democrat; Republican Governors Christie Whitman of New
Jersey and John Engler of Michigan; Mayor Rudolph Guiliani of New
York City, and past presidential candidates like Michael Dukakis
and Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   To deepen this coalition, Republican congressional leaders say
they intend to cast their insurance proposals in populist terms,
just in time for the November election. ``Auto choice is for the
moms and dads who sit at the kitchen table every month with the
family checkbook trying to balance the family needs with the family
budget,'' said House Majority Leader Dick Armey.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the biggest auto insurers, USAA and State Farm, support
auto choice, on the grounds that it would cut the portion of
premium dollars burned up by fraud and litigation. But other major
insurance companies are either opposed or are watching from the
sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Trial lawyers are investing heavily in the defeat of auto
choice. ``We're focusing like a laser beam on this issue,'' said
Richard Hailey, the past president of the trial lawyers
association.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes for passage rest on a combination of pressure from the
Congressional leadership to keep Republicans in line and
small-business support drummed up by the Chamber of Commerce. But
swing votes will have to come from Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   And legislators might very well feel pressure from their
constituents on the topic. While auto insurance is not on voters'
minds in much of middle America, it is a volatile issue in densely
populated parts of the East and West Coasts. High premiums almost
toppled Whitman last year, when her Democratic opponent, Jim
McGreevey, made the cost of auto insurance a centerpiece of his
campaign. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Will Washington politicians remember this episode? That depends
on how much consumers care about the issue. ``Auto choice would
give city residents a much needed break on insurance,'' said Moran
of Virginia. ``The big question is whether they'll get the message
and explain their feelings to Congress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
