<SLUG> BC-SLAVES-DATABASE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD TO OFFER COMPUTERIZED RECORD OF SLAVE TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After four years of research, Harvard University is prepared to
release the most comprehensive computerized record of the
Trans-Atlantic slave trade, allowing teachers, scholars, and
ordinary Americans unprecedented information on 27,233 slave trips
to the New World, or 70 percent of all voyages.
</P>
<P>
   The database, published this fall on a $195 CD-ROM, will
challenge popular perceptions about the inaccessibility of
information on slave roots. It will make known more information
about slave migration prior to 1820 than the European migrant flow
during that same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is that slaves were commodities, owned by somebody,
and the records are therefore better than for most Europeans that
came over during the earlier period,'' said David Eltis, a fellow
at Harvard University's W.E B. Du Bois Institute of Afro-American
Research.
</P>
<P>
   The database, which tracks more than 300 years of slave trading
from 1527 to 1866, doesn't provide names of slaves. But it does
contain the names of ship captains, vessels, ship owners, mortality
rates of the slaves, their ages and genders, as well as indicators
of slave rebellions, said Frank Smith, a history editor at
Cambridge Univerity Press, publisher of the CD-ROM.
</P>
<P>
   The names of the enslaved ``were never part of any records of
the past,'' said Smith. ``If you were captured they didn't care
about the names of the slaves; it's the brutal truth.''
</P>
<P>
   But seeking genealogical information, for example, can
determine, with the click of a mouse, where in Africa each voyage
originated and its specific destinations in the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   This alone, said Stephen Behrendt a Havard fellow who worked
with Eltis on the project, could change the way people view the
continent of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Africa has just as many differences as Europe, so you want
people to start looking at who the various people are that live in
Africa ... like someone from Gambia and Senegal,'' Behrendt said.
</P>
<P>
   The project gathered information about slave ship voyages from
archives all over the world and knitted it all together. So, now,
for the first time, large amounts of information are placed in one
spot, allowing historians to study patterns that may show how
Africa, or at least the African slave trade, has influenced the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The database, Eltis said, provides evidence of some provocative
trends. For instance, data suggest that slave traders went out of
their way to capture Africans known for their rice cultivation,
eventually bringing that skill to America.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, route patterns show that Europeans
avoided certain African coastal areas known for rebellious tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Eltis, a history professor at Queens College in Canada in
addition to his Harvard appointment, said he hopes the data will
help scholars better understand how African skills and traditions
took root in the New World.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to think that certain institutions came from Europe _
like the political and judicial systems _ but what this dataset
does is allow people interested in Afro-America culture to see the
influences of the African culture,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The CD-ROM will be unveiled before more than 400 international
historians, scholars, and journalists at a conference called
``Trans-Atlantic Slaving and the African Diaspora: Using the W.E.B.
Du Bois Dataset of Slaving Voyages,'' from September 11-13 at the
College of William and Mary in Williamsburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Historians believe 11 million people were taken from Africa as
slaves to the Americas, Caribbean islands, and Europe _ with up to
600,000 of them shipped to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the data in this project was compiled over the past four
years by Eltis and Behrendt, assisted by two other researchers,
David Richardson and Herbert Klein, who are not associated with
Harvard. But the gathering of information about slave ship voyages
began about 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The effort began when computers became widely available, and
scholars around the world could input archival information on the
slave trade, said Behrendt.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1980s, 11,000 individual voyages were included in
databases. Behrendt and Eltis, who met while working independently
on projects that focused on the British slave trade, compiled
information on an additional 16,000 voyages. They finished
compiling information at Harvard last year and began preparing it
for publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a starting point, not a finishing point,'' said Eltis.
`` There is a lot of information out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
