<HEADLINE>
SEARCH IN NEW JERSEY FOR MISSING WIDOW ENDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.J., N.Y., Utah)  (js) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The police searched an overgrown field on the outskirts of
Jersey City, N.J., for a second day Friday, but abandoned the
effort late in the day after failing to find Irene Silverman, the
82-year-old New York City widow who vanished eight weeks ago and is
believed to have been killed in a swindlers' scheme to get her town
house and fortune.
</P>
<P>
   The search, prompted by information from a Florida man who had
worked for the mother and son who are the prime suspects in the
disappearance, was another setback in a two-month investigation
that began with intriguing circumstantial and documentary clues but
has produced no forensic evidence and only fruitless searches for a
body.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Mode, a spokeswoman for the New York City Police
Department said Friday that the search had ended. ``It concluded at
5:10 p.m. with no plans to return tomorrow, having turned up
nothing of note,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For 10 hours on Thursday and more than eight hours Friday, a
score of police officers using lawn mowers, machetes and shovels
whacked through weeds and dense foliage on a tract larger than a
football field, just north of St. Peter's Cemetery and west of
Highway 1-9, where the western fringe of Jersey City gives way to
the tall grass and scrub of the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   It was a plausible site to search for a body: an isolated field
distant from any homes or commercial areas.
</P>
<P>
   The search was undertaken on information provided by Jose
Antonio Alvarez, 24, of Belle Glade, Fla., who was employed as a
handyman last spring by Sante Kimes, 63, and her son, Kenneth Kimes
Jr., 23, the suspects in the disappearance of Mrs. Silverman, who
was last seen on July 5 at her home in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez accompanied the Kimeses to New York in June, but
returned to Florida before Mrs. Silverman vanished and is not a
suspect, the police said. The police said he told investigators
that Kenneth Kimes, in a drive past the Jersey City field last
June, had remarked that it would be a good place to get rid of
something.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of the widow's disappearance, the Kimeses, who had
rented a room in her mansion, were arrested in Manhattan on an
unrelated Utah warrant on a bad-check charge. The police said the
two were holding a deed transferring Mrs. Silverman's town house to
them for $390,000, a tenth of its value, and had a passport and
financial papers belonging to Mrs. Silverman.
</P>
<P>
   But later searches in the metropolitan area have failed to find
a body. While the Kimeses have not been charged in her
disappearance, investigators say they believe the widow was killed
in a plot for her mansion and money.
</P>
<P>
   The mother and son are being held in New York on the Utah
warrant and on a New York indictment charging them with credit-card
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The Kimeses' lawyers have repeatedly denied the allegations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
