<SLUG> BC-NORTHWEST-PILOTS-TRAVEL-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR TRAVELERS TAKE STRIKE POSSIBILITY IN STRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.D., Minn., Tenn., Pa.)  (lb) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many passengers of Northwest Airlines were worried and confused
Friday ahead of the midnight strike deadline set by the airline's
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest had canceled 170 of its 1,700 flights Friday, and some
passengers were forced to seek other flights. Still, travelers
reacted stoically to the problems they might face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between Hurricane Bonnie and the threat of a Northwest strike,
I figure I'm playing double jeopardy,'' said Tammy Wangler of
Fargo, N.D., who was waiting at Hector International Airport in
Fargo for Northwest Flight 1074 to Raleigh, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Wangler, 32, refused to worry about how she would get
home from her vacation in 10 days. ``Maybe the last couple days of
the trip I'll worry about getting back,'' she said. ``But until
then, I'm just going to let go and have fun. I figure if I can get
back to Minneapolis, I can make it back to Fargo somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wangler had better not depend on booking a flight with
United Express, the commuter airline that provides the only
scheduled air service to Fargo other than that provided by
Northwest. ``The earliest guaranteed seat isn't until September
9,'' said Steve Dahl, the United Express customer service manager
in Fargo.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest is also the biggest carrier serving North Dakota
airports in Bismarck, Minot and Grand Forks.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Dobberstein, director of the Municipal Airport Authority
in Fargo, has advised travelers to use such options as Greyhound
and Amtrak.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest said it would cancel an additional 230 flights
Saturday, even if a strike was averted.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers at several airports seemed to be taking the
disruption, and the strike threat, in stride.
</P>
<P>
   Tricia Walker, 23, an accountant from Minneapolis who planned to
visit friends in Kent, Conn., for the weekend, had been booked on
Northwest's 7 p.m. nonstop flight Friday to Hartford, Conn. But an
airline representative told her to be on the 5 p.m. flight, which,
after a layover in Detroit, was scheduled to arrive in Hartford 30
minutes later than her original flight.
</P>
<P>
   Although her return flight is uncertain, Ms. Walker said, ``I'm
crossing my fingers that I can get back on another carrier.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Harris Layne of New York also did not appear unduly
concerned. Waiting at La Guardia Airport to fly to Minneapolis for
a wedding this weekend, Ms. Layne recalled having been stranded in
Iceland for three days several years ago. ``But this is America,''
she said. ``We'll find our way back.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Forbes, her traveling companion, was equally unconcerned,
noting that Minneapolis had lots of hotels and ``I've got a credit
card.''
</P>
<P>
   At Northwest's terminal at La Guardia on Friday, passengers were
treated to free muffins, coffee, tea and other refreshments. But
Northwest had few passengers Friday morning or on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very slow last night,'' said Maureen Carlin, a
Northwest customer-service agent. ``We were talking to each other
all night long.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Memphis, Tenn., Eleanor and William Allen of Sharon Hill,
Pa., were awaiting a flight to San Antonio for a Veterans of
Foreign Wars convention. Fifteen minutes after their 6 a.m. flight
took off from Philadelphia on Friday, the plane had to return for
repairs. They arrived in Memphis at 10 a.m., missed their flight to
San Antonio and had to wait for the last flight of the day, at 2
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope we don't have to go halfway around the world to
get back home,'' Mrs. Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   That Philadelphia-to-Memphis flight carried 11 adults and
children who were going to a beach house near Fort Walton Beach,
Fla. Because they missed their morning connection, Kathy Sheedy, a
lawyer from Red Bank, N.J., negotiated with Northwest to give them
vouchers to store their bags at a local hotel and take cabs to
Graceland, Elvis Presley's home in Memphis, before boarding a
connecting flight to Fort Walton Beach on Friday afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
