<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
45% IN POLL SEE LESSENING OF CLINTON'S POWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Almost half of Massachusetts voters surveyed believe
that President Clinton's ability to perform the duties of his
office has been diminished, according to a new Boston Globe-WBZ
poll.
</P>
<P>
   Of 800 likely voters polled this week by KRC Communications, 45
percent said they thought Clinton's ability to do his job has been
impaired by his relationship with former intern Monica Lewinsky, by
his lying about their relationship, and by allegations that he may
have encouraged her to commit perjury and obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton vacations with his family on Martha's Vineyard, he
and his aides have been busily trying to shore up Democratic
support among political leaders and the citizenry to prevent a
groundswell of calls for either impeachment or resignation. Clinton
aides say he will need all the help he can get as Congress prepares
to receive independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report on the
Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   While half the voters polled think Clnton's job performance has
been hurt, 43 percent said they believed Clinton will be unaffected
by the scandal and 5 percent said his job performance will be
enhanced.
</P>
<P>
   More women than men say Clinton's ability to serve in office has
been diminished. Forty-eight percent of female voters in the survey
and 42 percent of male voters said they view Clinton's situation as
damaging to his work.
</P>
<P>
   Like those in the rest of the country, Massachusetts voters
believe Clinton has been lying, but would prefer that the matter be
put to rest, with the president continuing to serve out his term.
Traditionally, Massachusetts has been a bastion of Clinton
admirers, and Clinton's favorability rating has always been
significantly higher here than in the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Massachusetts likes Clinton and thinks it's an issue
that should go away, Massachusetts doesn't believe him,'' said
pollster Gerry Chervinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Only 30 percent of those polled believe that Clinton's
relationship with Lewinsky is worthy of national attention, while
65 percent say it is not. Democratic voters say it is not worthy of
national attention by 81 percent, while 57 percent of Independent
voters and 45 percent of Republican voters say the issue should not
be the subject of national attention.
</P>
<P>
   Voters are far more upset, however, when asked what they think
about Clinton misleading the American people about Lewinsky. Of
everyone polled, 37 percent said it is very serious, and 39 percent
said it is somewhat serious. Twenty-two percent said it is not
serious.
</P>
<P>
   When voters were told that Clinton has denied urging Lewinsky to
lie under oath about their relationship, 50 percent of those polled
said they do not believe him. Only 27 percent said they believed
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that showing, 63 percent say he should not resign and
should not face impeachment. Twenty-two percent said Clinton should
resign or face impeachment, and 11 percent said they needed more
information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
