<SLUG> BC-GLF-WORLD-SERIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNHAPPY BIRTHDAY TO YOU: JANZEN IS DISQUALIFIED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (jw) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AKRON, Ohio _ An eventful day at the World Series of Golf
featured both controversy and competition.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy involved Lee Janzen, who was disqualified this
morning for signing an incorrect score card. The competition
involved Tiger Woods, David Duval and Craig Parry, who ended Friday
locked in a three-way tie for first place at five under par,
setting the stage for an interesting weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen, who turned 34 Friday, will remember this birthday for
the wrong reasons. After he arrived at Firestone Country Club, he
was summoned into a meeting with tournament officials, who informed
him of their decision to disqualify him. Tipped off by a telephone
call from a television viewer, tournament officials reviewed a
videotape of Janzen's first-round putt on the 17th hole. It was a
putt that stopped tantalizingly close to the cup, with part of the
ball hanging over the lip of the hole. After at least 20 seconds,
the ball finally dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen signed for a 3, but, according to the U.S. Golf
Association rules, Janzen should have signed for a 4. Rule 16-2
states that when the ball overhangs the hole, and the player is
allowed time to reach the hole without reasonable delay, then the
player is given an additional 10 seconds to determine if the ball
is at rest. After 10 seconds, the ball is deemed to be at rest, and
even if it eventually falls into the hole, the player is assessed a
penalty stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen did not intentionally violate the rule, and both he and
his Thursday playing partner, Vijay Singh, felt that Janzen was
within the 10-second limit. But that didn't matter. Janzen was out
of the tournament. And understandably, the two-time U.S. Open
champion was upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no intention of breaking any rule,'' Janzen said before
leaving. ``Strange things happen on the course, and this was one of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was strange. After Janzen stroked the fateful putt,
he walked to the hole, then past it, then stared at it, wondering
why the ball wouldn't drop. Singh walked over to take a peak as
well. Finally, after at least 20 seconds, the ball dropped. Janzen
laughed, and the gallery cheered.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen said he was afraid to tap in the putt, because players
are not permitted to strike a moving ball under Rule 19. However,
when the ball is hanging over the lip of the hole, Rule 16-2
supersedes Rule 19. If Janzen had tapped in the putt while it was
moving, he would not have been disqualified, as long as he signed
for a 4 instead of a 3.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more well-known incidents of fans' calling in with a
rule violation and a player's being penalized came in 1987 at the
Andy Williams Open in San Diego. Craig Stadler, who was among the
third-round leaders, needed to kneel down under a tree branch to
execute a fairway shot. He used a towel to shield his pants from
wet grass.
</P>
<P>
   Television viewers flooded tournament officials with phone calls
when they saw tape of Stadler's antics before that Sunday's final
round. He had broken Rule 13-3, which prohibits ``building a
stance.'' Stadler, like Janzen, was subsequently disqualified
because he failed to assess the proper penalty when signing his
score card.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen, who was 43rd out of 44 golfers after Thursday's first
round here, will still be paid last-place money ($18,475), though
that sum will not count on the official money list.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the first time that Rule 16-2 had been mentioned in
a prominent tournament. At the 1985 U.S. Open, Denis Watson
assessed himself a one-stroke penalty for waiting too long for a
putt to fall. Watson finished in a three-way tie for second, one
shot behind Andy North.
</P>
<P>
   So this World Series of Golf continued without Janzen, and the
weekend has compelling potential. Shooting a 66 on Friday, Duval
soared from a tie for ninth place into a tie for first place with
Woods and Parry, both of whom shot 68 Friday.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
