</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox gives Klesko shot against lefty starter
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Bobby Cox gave Ryan Klesko a rare start against a
left-hander Friday night and it had nothing to do with his 1-for-4
history against St. Louis' Kent Mercker either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never even looked,'' Cox said. ``I just want to get him some
at-bats. He's trying some different things and he needs to get in
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Klesko needs something. The club's leading home run hitter the
past two seasons, Klesko has fallen to sixth this year with 16, a
disturbing pattern for a power hitter who has seen his homer
production drop from 30 to 24 the previous two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   While keeping his average near .280 the last eight weeks, he has
not hit a homer since Aug. 5 and has hit just three in the second
half. He is on pace to drive in 72 runs, which would also be a
three-year low.
</P>
<P>
   ``The year ain't over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his trouble stems from his June 29 appendectomy, which
disrupted his most productive month of the season (.382 with five
homers and 16 RBIs in 21 June starts). But his bat has slipped so
far down and back in his stance that he is having trouble handling
inside fastballs, which had been his staple.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gone through about three or four stances,'' said hitting
coach Clarence Jones. ``He's got to find one he's comfortable with.
He's got to get that relaxed feeling again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is disturbing,'' said Cox, ``because he is a power hitter.
Sixteen is not a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also disturbing because Klesko is in the first season of a
four-year $20.5-million contract, reflective of the Braves'
confidence that he could provide a left-handed anchor in the middle
of the order into the next century. At present, he is fifth on the
club in RBI (60).
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two weeks, I've had like six starts (actually 10)
because there's been a barrage of left-handers,'' Klesko said.
``I'm trying to find my swing from where it was before my surgery.
I've been back and forth (between swings) the whole time. I'm not
dissatisfied. I'm not hitting .220. I'm hitting .280. It's just my
power numbers are down.''
</P>
<P>
   History lesson
</P>
<P>
   When Andruw Jones reaches 25 homers _ he opened play Friday with
23 _ the Braves will have four players with 25 or more for the
first time in Atlanta history. The last Braves club with four
25-homer seasons played in Milwaukee in 1965, with Hank Aaron (32),
Eddie Mathews (32), Mack Jones (31) and Joe Torre (27).
</P>
<P>
   Day in court
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have been notified Andres Galarraga's appeal for his
three-game suspension will be heard next Tuesday, when National
League president Len Coleman will be in Atlanta. If his appeal is
denied, Galarraga should expect to start serving the suspension
immediately, meaning he would sit out the last two games of the
Houston series at Turner Field and a Friday game in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Dispatch from Richmond
</P>
<P>
   Four years after the Braves took him in the fourth round of the
1994 draft, Wes Helms drew his first breath in the major leagues
Friday, celebrating the occasion by slamming a batting practice
homer off the glassed-in restaurant in the second deck above left
field of Busch Stadium. After bombing out in Class AAA Richmond
last year, Helms was leading the team with 75 RBI Thursday when the
club called him up, thinking Chipper Jones has sustained a rib cage
injury. Cox asked Helms Friday if he could play the outfield (he
did in high school but was drafted as a shortstop), which may be
the foreshadowing of Helms' eventual fate in the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
