<HEADLINE>
ANGELS SHOW WHY THEY'RE IN PENNANT RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It may have been forgotten, but there is a pennant
contender in town this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim Angels, currently in first place in the AL West,
just came off a five-game series in which they beat the mighty New
York Yankees three times. They added to their success by beating
the Red Sox, 7-3, in the opener of a three-game series Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   But they have plenty to come on road trip; after their
three-game set against the Red Sox, they'll meet another likely
playoff team, the Cleveland Indians. No one has to tell the Angels
that if they don't make a good showing on this trip, they might
drop out of first. And that's something they don't want to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got our work cut out for us,'' said Angels general
manager Bill Bavasi. ``But it sure beats the alternative. I'd
rather be nine games up on the spot I want than where we are. The
Sox are probably trying to get ready for postseason. We're just
trying to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Where the Angels wanted to be was on Easy Street, not fighting
for their postseason lives. Anaheim has five games left with the
Texas, Rangers, their closest pursuer, inclduing three at home. Its
final four games are at Oakland, the divisional cellardweller. But
as far as the Angels are concerned, the race is in high gear right
now.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim won the season series over the Yankees, while leading
the Red Sox by a game with two to play. Texas can tell you how
tough the road can be. On their last swing of New York, Boston, and
Cleveland earlier this month, they were under .500 and saw a 1
1/2-game lead change to a 2 1/2-game deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why getting out of this road trip with our head above
water is important,'' said Angels manager Terry Collins. ``We got
off to a great start in New York. But we've got a tough weekend
ahead and we've got to go to Cleveland next. If we get out of this
month with our lineup intact and a healthy Jack McDowell and Ken
Hill, we should be OK. Then it should really be a good last
month.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels finished six games behind Seattle in last season's AL
West race and after several off-season moves started the year as
the co-favorite. The club had a new chemistry, with veterans Cecil
Fielder, Randy Velarde, and Dave Hollins expected to fit into the
middle of a talented young nucleus that included players like Tim
Salmon, Gary DiSarcina, Jim Edmonds, Garrett Anderson, Todd Greene,
and Darin Erstad. As late as May 22, the Angels were as many as six
games out.
</P>
<P>
   How they jump-started the effort this still puzzles some
observers. McDowell and Hill were lost for legnthy periods due to
injuries. So were Erstad, Salmon, Velarde, Allen Watson, Hollins,
Mike James, and Charlie O'Brien. But the Angels are tough and show
up to play every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The five games in New York,'' said hitting instructor Rod
Carew, ``were five of the most grueling games they've gone through
this year. They didn't quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins won't let them quit. He has re-tooled his lineup with
his style of players. It worked. On Aug. 5, just after the club had
failed to pull the trigger on a deal before the Aug. 1 deadline,
the Angels stunned the West Coast by designating the powerful
Fielder for assignment. He had started the year in the middle of
the Angels lineup. He left as a guy in the middle of all that was
wrong. Collins told his troops to return to the style of play
they'd used in his first season as manager in 1997, one that had
worked for him in Houston. So far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cecil is the greatest guy in the world,'' said Collins. ``But
we had to change the way we were playing. We weren't hitting home
runs. We weren't driving in runs. We had to do something to create
a different way to go about the game. What had made us good last
year was that we ran the bases great. We moved runners and got
runs. We've added more speed to the lineup and now try to create
more energy on the club. We're going to get better at it. If we can
take this guys and play a certain way, we can say that have a real
good club.''
</P>
<P>
   With McDowell and Hill rejoining the rotation, the Angels may
finally move away from the dark cloud that has hovered over the
club since the trading deadline. There was major criticism when the
Angels stood pat and didn't pull off a deal for a No. 1 starter.
People thought Disney, if no one else, would demand a deal be made.
Baseball minds prevailed. Bavasi still feels the club made the
right decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We refused to make a deal to just make a deal,'' said Bavasi.
``I It doesn't haunt us. We've played pretty hard without making
one. I feel bad we couldn't find good deals to make. But I don't
feel bad that we didnt make bad deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is anything that is disturbing, it's that a lot of
made by people saying, `How are you doing it? How are they staying
in contention with so many injuries and no trade?' Well, that's not
giving these guys enough credit. They're good players who play the
game the way it should be played ... hard every night. Can they do
it the next 29-30 days? We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do people want most in a trade?,'' he asked. ``Either
pitching or young players in return. We wanted to find a pitcher.
What did they want back? Young, talented guys. Well, ours are in
the big leagues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
