<SLUG> BC-TEN-FOREST-HILLS-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNIS THROWBACK IN FOREST HILLS IS IN JEOPARDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By VIVIAN S. TOY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The view at dusk from the Tudor clubhouse terrace at
the West Side Tennis Club in Forest Hills, Queens, is as
magnificent as it ever was.
</P>
<P>
   In the foreground, neatly trimmed grass tennis courts stand
shoulder to shoulder, while red and green clay courts flow to the
right and left. And the stadium _ where thousands of fans cheered
as the likes of Billie Jean King and Arthur Ashe made tennis
history _ rises elegantly toward the sky.
</P>
<P>
   But beneath the towering arches of the 14,000-seat arena, years
of disuse have taken their toll. Porcelain water fountains are
chipped and dry. Cracks in the concrete have been patched and
repatched. Telephone booths stand empty without phones.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since 1978, when the U.S. Open abandoned Forest Hills to
move to a bigger and plusher home two miles away, in Flushing
Meadows, the fate of the stadium has been an open question. But
now, as the tennis world prepares for the start of this year's Open
on Monday, club officials are considering tearing down the
nostalgia-laden stadium, sparking a contentious fight within the
club between those wanting to defend its heritage and others who
worry about the finances of an aging country club with a shrinking
membership.
</P>
<P>
   The club has already received six proposals for different types
of housing complexes and will accept bids until the end of
September. But the sale and later demolition of the stadium, whose
courts club members still sometimes play on and which is also
occasionally used for concerts, is by no means a foregone
conclusion. Two-thirds of the club's 400 voting members must
approve such a monumental change, and the outcome of a vote is
still as unpredictable as John McEnroe's temper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stadium is a landmark and I'd hate to see it go,'' said
James Frangos, a former president of the club. ``It would be like
selling your grandmother's heirlooms, and it's something you do
only as an absolute last resort.'' So far, no vote has been
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   William Maloney, the current president, said that while many
members feel the stadium is an important monument to the past,
others feel that it is outdated and part of a bygone era. In the
end, he said, the decision would be ``a function of fiscal analysis
and cost-benefits for the club.''
</P>
<P>
   Change of any kind comes slowly at a place like the 106-year-old
West Side Tennis Club, which has its origins on the Upper West Side
of Manhattan but moved to Queens in 1913. For example, the club
next year will finally get a swimming pool, but it took club
members 20 years to thoroughly thrash out the issue and approve the
construction.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the club's older members remember when the U.S. Open was
played on grass at Forest Hills. The halls of the clubhouse are
lined with photographs of American tennis stars going back to Bill
Tilden and Helen Wills. Silver trophies from tournaments of yore
decorate the lounge.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more than 100 years of history here,'' said Howard
Gordon, a member of the board of governors. ``Some of it good, some
of it not,'' he added, alluding to the club's restrictive policies
in the past that prevented blacks and Jews from becoming members.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last two decades, the voting membership has declined
to just under 400 from about 750. (A nonvoting population of
members who do not play tennis but use the clubhouse for its
restaurant and bridge tournaments has held steady at about 300.)
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For years, club officials have been grappling with how to
attract new members to a club that charges an initiation fee of
about $3,000 and annual dues of about $5,000 for a family and
$2,400 for an individual.
</P>
<P>
   They said they hoped that the new pool would broaden the appeal.
``Times have changed,'' Gordon said. ``You have to give the young
people something besides just tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the question of the stadium, which sustained
itself through the 1980s with the Tournament of Champions _ an
event that attracted big-name players like McEnroe, Ivan Lendl and
Andre Agassi. But after that tournament folded in 1990, the club
has been unable to attract another tournament to replace it.
</P>
<P>
   The club has also tried to restore the luster of the stadium as
an outdoor concert site. The Beatles and the Rolling Stones played
Forest Hills in the 1960s. But just as tennis outgrew Forest Hills,
so apparently did rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   There have been only about half a dozen concerts in the last
decade. Two concerts this summer included a popular Japanese rock
band called the Alfee and a Caribbean festival of reggae and
calypso.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stadium helped put Forest Hills on the map,'' said Linda
Hoffman, a member of the corporation's board. ``So we would feel
sad to see it torn down, but if it's necessary for the club to
remain in existence then it has to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Many professional tennis players remember Forest Hills fondly.
</P>
<P>
   While less charitable in her descriptions of the stadium in an
autobiography 25 years ago, Billie Jean King, who won four U.S.
Open titles at Forest Hills, said this week that she would never
forget the view from the terrace of the clubhouse, which looks out
on the open side of the horseshoe-shaped stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sitting there and watching the sun go down behind the stadium
_ you'll never see another sight like that in tennis,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Smith, who won the U.S. Open in 1971, said he went back to
watch a tennis match there about 10 years ago and was saddened to
see how much the place had deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look back, it's hard to imagine that it worked at
all, he said, ``because it was so small and there was no parking
for fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I always tell people that I can say I won Forest Hills,
and now when you say you won Flushing, it just doesn't have the
same ring.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
