<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 8/28/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) LAS VEGAS -- Aug. 28, 1998 -- SKINHEADS-2, 8-28 -- Lin
Newborn, 24, who was found dead on the Fourth of July, along with
friend Daniel Shersty, 20, on the outskirts of town. Newborn and
Shersty, both anti-racist skinheads, are believed to have been
killed by racist neo-Nazi skinheads. The killings have shed light
on divisions among the skinheads, a vaguely defined subculture
whose definition is the subject of fierce debate. (Andrew
Itkoff/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LAS VEGAS -- Aug. 28, 1998 -- SKINHEADS-1, 8-28 --
Walter Shersty and wife Sharon, in a Las Vegas hospital with a
photo of his son, Daniel, 20, who was found slain on the Fourth of
July. Shersty and a friend, Lin Newborn, 24, both skinheads who
shared a passionate hatred of racism, were found dead on the
outskirts of town. Police, family and friends of the young men,
suspect that they were killed by racist neo-Nazi skinheads. (Andrew
Itkoff/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. -- Aug. 28, 1998 -- BBO-LITTLE-LEAGUE,
8-28 -- Eric Campesi and teammates of Toms River East, watching
players from Kashima, Japan, warming up on Friday. Coming off the
high of Thursday night's exhilarating 5-2 victory over Greenville,
N.C., to win the United States Little League championship, the
players from Toms River, N.J., now dream of winning the Little
League World Series on Saturday. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) LAS VEGAS -- Aug. 28, 1998 -- NEV-POLITICS, 8-28 -- Aaron
Russo, a rich Hollywood producer who is seeking the Republican
nomination for governor of Nevada, at his campaign office. Russo
who swaggered into Las Vegas just two years ago, has become an
intimidating and unsettling force leading to next week's primary
election. (John Gurzinski/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Aug. 28, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 30 --
ABOUT-CARS-GALANT-2, 8-28 -- The standard leather interior of the
Galant GTZ, a new, sporty version of the redesigned midsize sedan,
has a V6 engine, a performance-tuned suspension, a rear spoiler,
white-faced gauges. At $24,770, it is the most expensive car in the
line. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Aug. 28, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 30 --
ABOUT-CARS-GALANT-1, 8-28 -- The Galant GTZ, a new, sporty version
of the redesigned midsize sedan, has a V6 engine, a
performance-tuned suspension, a rear spoiler, white-faced gauges
and a standard leather interior. At $24,770, it is the most
expensive car in the line. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MILAN, Italy -- Aug. 28, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 30
-- WEDDINGS-2, 8-28 -- A Yohji Yamamoto wedding design, closing his
show for fall 1998. The dress was so large it practically had to be
turned on its side to fit through the door. The tradition of
closing each runway show with a wedding dress has been around for
years, but today's dresses have never been rivaled for their size.
(Corina Lecca/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MILAN, Italy -- Aug. 28, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 30
--WEDDINGS-1, 8-28 -- The only couture dress a woman may ever own.
The bride as seen by Dior. One sign of how utterly populist runway
shows have become, having to appeal, like movies and television
shows, to the widest audience possible. Maybe it's that today, the
only way to eke an emotion out of an overloaded audience, is to
throw a bride at it and hope for the best. (Dan Lecca/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) SAN FRANCISCO -- Aug. 28, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 30
-- MUTFUND-MERIDIAN, 8-28 -- Kevin O'Boyle, who has led Meridian
Value to strong returns by finding what he calls ``busted growth
stocks,'' shares of fast-growing companies that stumble. ``When a
company with a strong balance sheet and a history of generating
strong returns from capital fails to meet its earnings estimates
for a year, the stock prices tend to decline dramatically,'' says
O'Boyle. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Aug. 28, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 30 --
EARN-WALLSTREET, 8-28 -- Bill Montgoris, chief operating officer at
Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co., says that the 1990s have been a time of more
sober hiring even as stock prices skyrocketed. ``In the past,
you've seen hiring booming and busting,'' says Bill Montgoris.
``Now firms have been much more cautious.'' (James Estrin/ New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Aug. 28, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 30 --
INVEST-AIRLINES, 8-28 -- Kevin Murphy, an analyst at Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter, expects airline industry earnings to be up 20 percent
in the third quarter. ``There were fears that the weak
second-quarter gross domestic product number would lead to a real
slowdown in the second half,'' says Murphy. But we are looking for
the economy to snap back to more than 3 percent real growth in the
last two quarters. (Nancy Siesel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
