A8409 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      08-28 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUSSIAN INSTABILITY SENDS STOCK PRICES EVEN LOWER
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices fell sharply for the second straight day as
continued fears about instability in Russia and economic weakness
closer to home led the stock market to its worst week in nine
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average declined 114.31 points, or 1.4
percent, finishing the week at 8,051.68, down 5.6 percent over the
five days. Not since October 1989, when the Dow fell 7.8 percent,
has the bellwether market gauge fallen so far in the span of a
week.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices ended slightly higher, extending a rally
sustained by investors fleeing turmoil on world markets.
</P>
<P>
   The recent turmoil has weakened several Latin American
currencies and drastically reduced the wealth of many Latin
companies, raising prospects that governments in the region may be
forced to take sterner measures to contain the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   European stock markets were led down by the London Stock
Exchange, which fell 2.2 percent. Frankfurt closed down 1.7
percent, and stock markets in Eastern Europe were also swept by a
wave of selling.
</P>
<P>
   NO ECONOMIC HELP FROM JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   Japanese stocks dropped in value by $241 billion this week, a
sum that was the financial equivalent of erasing Russia from the
world map for a year. Japan is central to the health of the global
economy, but it remains firmly in recession and largely paralyzed
politically and economically.
</P>
<P>
   BROKERAGE FIRMS FEEL PINCH AT HOME
</P>
<P>
   While banks have seen values tumble because of international
worries, Wall Street's brokerage firms and investment banks are
troubled by more mundane concerns at home: fear that equity
underwriting and trading in fixed-income products will not be as
lucrative this year.
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMY CONTRACTS IN PHILIPPINES
</P>
<P>
   The Philippines, becoming the latest Asian country to report an
economic contraction, said its gross domestic product declined in
the second quarter at an annual rate of 1.2 percent, worse than
economists' forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   PASSENGERS BRACE FOR AIRLINE STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   There were no signs of panic at Northwest Airlines terminals or
ticket counters as the United States' fourth-biggest carrier and
its pilots union met well into the night to avert a strike. But
confusion and concern were evident among many passengers.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER SPENDING FELL IN JULY
</P>
<P>
   Consumer spending dropped in July for the first time in more
than two years as the strikes at General Motors took a toll on auto
sales. Analysts said falling stock prices could cause spending to
weaken further in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   OXFORD HEALTH CHIEF OUTLINES PLAN
</P>
<P>
   At the annual meeting of Oxford Health Plans, whose stock has
plunged more than 90 percent since last summer, the chief executive
outlined a turnaround strategy and fielded questions from a packed
room of shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   DEAL FOR FRENCH SUPERMARKET CHAIN
</P>
<P>
   Carrefour, France's biggest retailer, said it had agreed to buy
Comptoirs Modernes, a supermarket chain, in a cash-and-stock deal
worth up to $2.38 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
