u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SYNAGOGUE-FIRE-280     08-28 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SYNAGOGUE-FIRE-280&AMP;-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCIDENTAL FIRE HEAVILY SCARS LANDMARK SYNAGOGUE IN NYC 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Central Synagogue on Manhattan's East Side, a
126-year-old twin-towered architectural treasure of Moorish
inspiration that is a national and city landmark and the oldest
temple in New York state in continuous use by one Jewish
congregation, was heavily damaged Friday in a roaring five-alarm
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently sparked by a workman's blowtorch during renovations,
orange-red flames and dense gray-black smoke shot through the roof
of the sandstone and limestone Reform synagogue at 652 Lexington
Ave., on the southwest corner of 55th Street, as the evening rush
hour got under way shortly after 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   No one was killed or seriously injured in the fire, which raged
out of control for three hours and sent heavy smoke billowing over
the city.
</P>
<P>
   As commuters and congregants watched grimly, many of them
sobbing, and firefighters shot streams of water from the streets,
from tower ladders and even from terraces on adjacent buildings,
the flames attacked the synagogue's roof, breaking through at
several points and eventually destroying almost the entire roof.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, falling flames and cascading torrents of water
heavily damaged the synagogue's magnificent interior, with its
stenciled and handpainted walls of rich blues, earthy reds, ochres
and gold in dazzling geometric designs, with its muted stained
glass windows and ebonized woodwork.
</P>
<P>
   As twilight slowly painted the sky with streaks of darkness and
the last flaming embers and smoke drifted up, more than 250
firefighters who had used 45 trucks finally brought the fire under
control just before 8 p.m., and a congregation that had existed for
more than a century and a half faced a harsh reality.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While the damage was great, officials said the synagogue's
collection of Judaica, its archives dating to the 1870s, many of
its early architectural drawings and many of its sacred Torah
scrolls were out of harm's way, having been removed in recent
months in preparation for a renovation project.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the remaining Torah scrolls were taken from the ark
and saved, officials said, and the renovation project, which
included interior and roof work and the installation of new
air-conditioners, had closed the synagogue for the summer, with
services moved to a temple community house across 55th Street, so
that no one but workmen were inside when the fire broke out.
</P>
<P>
   But to many congregants, the fire was nonetheless devastating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am heartbroken,'' Sara Gorfinkle, a member of the
congregation for 10 years, said as she looked up solemnly at
billowing smoke and leaping flames. ``I heard about the fire on the
radio and I had to come down and see it. This is terrible. This is
breaking my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Peter Rubenstein, the Central Synagogue's senior rabbi,
said: ``This is a national and city landmark and more than that it
is the soul of the congregation. Fortunately, the Torah scrolls had
been taken out of the building.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, ``Already our Christian neighbors and friends have
offered the use of their facilities for the High Holy Days,'' which
begin in mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation has 1,400 members, he said, but as many as
5,000 attend High Holy Day services, the most sacred of the year
for Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who went to the scene, said there
appeared to be nothing suspicious about the fire, which was
apparently started by a workman using a propane torch to perform
some soldering on the roof. ``The fire marshal is pretty confident
that this fire looks like an accident,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   First Deputy Fire Commissioner William Feehan said workmen were
soldering copper flashing around air ducts on a flat portion of the
roof near the front when some saw smoke. They stopped soldering, he
said, pulled up the flashing and tried to put out what appeared to
be a small fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought they had extinguished the fire, but the fire was
under the roof boards,'' Feehan said. He said the flames soon
spread under the roof and were far advanced by the time the first
firefighters arrived at 5:13 p.m., six minutes after the alarm was
turned in.
</P>
<P>
   The synagogue struck by the flames Friday dates from 1872.
Designed by the Prussian-born Jewish architect Henry Fernbach _ one
of the first Jewish architects in America _ it is regarded as a
masterpiece of the Moorish Revival style.
</P>
<P>
   Its brooding facade of sandstone with limestone features banded
arches, and twin, 122-foot minaret towers capped by bronze onion
domes, the whole structure modeled after the Dohany Street
synagogue in Budapest, but reflecting the style of the Moors in
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   It has a rich history. The synagogue was commissioned by a
congregation of Jews from Bohemia, called Ahawath Chesed, that was
founded on Ludlow Street on the Lower East Side in 1846, when the
Jewish population of the city was only 12,000 out of 500,000
residents. By 1872, when the synagogue was built, the city's
population had grown to 900,000, with 120,000 Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation merged in 1898 with the members of Shaar
Hasomayim and took its current name in 1920. The city's Landmarks
Preservation Commission designated the synagogue a landmark in
1966, and it was named a National Historic Landmark in 1975, the
only synagogue in the state to have such status.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
