<HEADER>
A8416 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYC-LEMOND-COX     08-28 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-LEMOND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lemond: Drug scandal is best thing to happen to cycling
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- America's most famous cyclist hopes something good
will come out of the drug scandal that engulfed this year's Tour de
France, a race he won three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best thing that's happened in cycling,'' said Greg
LeMond, now driving on the Forumla Ford 2000 circuit and competing
tonight at Atlanta Motor Speedway. ``The worst would be for drugs
to stay on the back side and nobody doing anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's Tour de France, a three-week bike race held every
July, was marked by controversy. The world's top-ranked team was
kicked out for suspected drug use, and another six squads quit.
Police are still investigating.
</P>
<P>
   LeMond, who retired in 1994 after winning the Tour in 1986, 1989
and 1990, said he always has detested drug use.
</P>
<P>
   ``I raced a clean career,'' he said. ``I made it very clear. I
was fortunate to be on certain teams that wouldn't tolerate it.''
</P>
<P>
   LeMond even left one squad when his contract expired, he said,
because one of its riders was caught using drugs and the team
directors did not do anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   But LeMond said that in a sport in which athletes often pedal
eight hours a day for weeks at a time, some competitors look for
any advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so physically demanding that even a slight edge can make
a difference,'' he said. ``I don't believe any rider wants to take
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's a huge temptation to maintain equality.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though cycling has been under suspicion since 1967, when a
British rider died of amphetamine use during the Tour de France,
drug use picked up eight or nine years ago, LeMond said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is drug use limited to cycling. Running and swimming, along
with professional sports such as football, have been tainted by
scandal. In recent weeks, three 1996 Olympians _ a swimmer, a
weightlifter and a sprinter _ have been accused of possible doping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything you take, there's a side effect,'' said LeMond, who
was forced to retire because of a rare genetic muscle disease. ``I
wanted to get done with cycling with my health.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ironic thing is I ended up finishing unhealthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 2227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8417 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-PILOT-NYT &LR;      08-28 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-PILOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEADY GRAF EARNS RIGHT TO MEET NOVOTNA FOR TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ Steffi Graf continued her comeback in
dramatic fashion Friday night, recovering from a 5-0 deficit in the
second-set tie breaker to beat top-seeded Lindsay Davenport, 6-3,
7-6 (8-6), and advance to the final of the Pilot Pen International
tennis championships.
</P>
<P>
   By winning seven of the last eight points in the tie breaker,
after having squandered a 5-2 lead in the second set, the
29-year-old Graf earned the right to meet Jana Novotna, the
reigning Wimbledon champion who is seeded No. 2 here, on Saturday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   After losing five consecutive games, during which she failed to
capitalize on a match point on her serve in the 10th game, Graf
seemed destined to lose the set when a rejuvenated Davenport won
the first five points of the tie breaker.
</P>
<P>
   But Graf, playing in only her ninth tournament of the year after
a long recovery following knee surgery, overcame a set point by
Davenport at 6-5 and eventually closed out the match with a service
winner.
</P>
<P>
   That Davenport _ who had won 15 matches and 3 tournaments in a
row _ managed to stay as close as she did was somewhat remarkable,
because Graf broke her big service the first five times in the
match and seven of her first eight service games.
</P>
<P>
   But then the 6-foot-2-inch Davenport, moving much better since
losing 30 pounds over the last three years, also managed to break
Graf's vaunted serve in the fourth, eighth and 10th games of the
second set.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was Graf's forehand and steadier backhand _ and,
it seemed, her championship mettle _ that made the difference
against Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport won this tournament last year, when it was the U.S.
Hardcourts Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got a little tight in he second set but then she started
playing great in the tie breaker,'' said Davenport, who was treated
for a sore right wrist several times during the match before a
crowd of about 6,000 at the Connecticut Tennis Center. ``She's
obviously a great champion.''
</P>
<P>
   For Graf, it marked the first time that she has made it to a
final this year.
</P>
<P>
   Three times she had reached a semifinal, but in two of those
instances she had been beaten by Davenport, who had defeated her
three times in their last four meetings.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday night, she was facing a Graf who is approaching the
form that has won 21 Grand Slam titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was definitely not happy that I let it slip away from me in
he second set,'' said Graf, who had entered this tournament late as
a wild card after having won 14 of 21 matches this year. ``I just
got nervous and tight and didn't go for my shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to relax and it didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   For future tournament play, Graf said, her shaky experience in
the second set _ which required her to raise the level of her play
under pressure _ should prove beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will definitely give me the confidence that I really need
to start next week,'' she said, alluding to the U.S. Open, which
she has won five times.
</P>
<P>
   In Novotna, Graf will be meeting a longtime rival. Graf has won
26 of 30 meetings against Novotna.
</P>
<P>
   Novotna, also 29, gained Saturday's final with a 6-4, 6-4
victory over unseeded Julie Halard-Decugis of France in Friday
night's opening match.
</P>
<P>
   Novotna had won 19 straight matches since the French Open until
she was beaten by Arantxa Sanchez Vicario in the semifinals of last
week's du Maurier Open in Montreal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
