<HEADLINE>
IT'S TOMISUE'S DELIGHT'S TURN TO LEAD FILLIES AT SARATOGA
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ It was supposed to be a replay of their
classic battle four weeks ago, but Saratoga's capricious fates
forced a surprise ending Friday: Aldiza and Escena, two of the
finest fillies in the country, fell out of the money while
Tomisue's Delight was flying through the homestretch and winning
the $400,000 Personal Ensign Handicap by two lengths.
</P>
<P>
   The same three fillies raced in the Go For Wand Handicap at
Saratoga on Aug. 2, and finished in this order: Aldiza by a nose
over Escena, who had three lengths on Tomisue's Delight. But when
they ran an eighth of a mile farther Friday, it was Tomisue's
Delight first, Escena sixth and Aldiza eighth and last.
</P>
<P>
   The two losing fillies came with all kinds of pedigrees and
connections, but no excuses.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Mott, the trainer of the favorite Escena, owned by Allen
Paulson with Jerry Bailey riding, said flatly: ``There was no
excuse for her. She just came up empty.'' Bailey, after leading for
one mile to the head of the stretch, said: ``All I can say is, it
wasn't her best race. She ran hard and had everything her own way.
She just didn't have the kick when the others came to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Shug McGaughey, the trainer of Aldiza, owned by Helen Alexander
of King Ranch Farm and her mother, Helen Groves, was even more
terse. He was the trainer of Personal Ensign, who retired with a
13-for-13 record and who gave her name to the race, formerly known
as the John A. Morris Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing to say about the race,'' McGaughey said with an
air of finality. And his jockey, Mike Smith said: ``The filly just
couldn't get her air today. After four and a half furlongs, I could
really hear her gasping for air.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheerier comments came from the winner's camp. Neil Howard, who
trains Tomisue's Delight for Stephen Hilbert, noted that his filly
had won her sixth race in 17 starts and had run in the money 14
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's put up a lot of seconds and thirds in graded company,''
Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   Tomisue's Delight ran the mile and one-quarter in 2:04, paid
$10.40 for a $2 bet to win and earned $240,000 and possibly a shot
at the Breeders' Cup Distaff in November. The long shot Tuzia
finished second by a neck over One Rich Lady.
</P>
<P>
   While all this was going on with the fillies, the colts were
either jogging, galloping or resting for their $750,000 Travers
Stakes on Saturday, with Coronado's Quest and Victory Gallop the
chief candidates to gain some yardage on the injured Real Quiet for
the 3-year-old championship.
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop, the slight favorite at 7-5 and the only veteran
of the Triple Crown races in the field of eight, galloped over the
main track this morning with his ``rabbit'' stablemate, Sheila's
Flag. But Elliott Walden, who trains both, was still somewhat
tight-lipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to talk to anyone yesterday,'' he said on
Friday, ``because I wanted it to be a surprise that I entered
Sheila's Flag.''
</P>
<P>
   McGaughey, the trainer of Coronado's Quest, the second choice at
8-5 and the winner of four in a row, reported that his star had
galloped a mile and a half, and said on Friday, ``He'll just gallop
about a mile tomorrow morning, and we'll be set.''
</P>
<P>
   FINISH LINES:
</P>
<P>
   You do not often see the Horse of the Year running on the under
card, but Favorite Trick will skip the Travers distance of a mile
and a quarter Saturday and aim instead for seven-eighths of a mile
in the King's Bishop Stakes. He has won 11 of his 13 starts with a
third- and an eighth-place finish. The field of eight colts
includes Limit Out, who has won four of his six starts for Allen
Jerkens.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
