<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 TENNIS COLUMN: FOR GIBSON, HER LEGACY TO TENNIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early Friday morning, three New Jersey mayors stood shoulder to
shoulder in East Orange City Hall. One by one they invoked the
image of Althea Gibson, the first African-American to win a major
tennis title. In 1957 and '58, Gibson was the dominant player in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   The mayors initially gathered to support the establishment of
the Althea Gibson Foundation by friends, and to promote a gala that
will be held in New York on Sunday to raise money for the
foundation. After short presentations, the politicians recalled the
powerful impact Gibson had on their lives in 1957 when she won her
first Wimbledon title.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Robert Bowser of East Orange recalled how news of Gibson's
victory at Wimbledon was met with shouts and cheers from neighbors
listening on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone went out and bought a racket,'' he said. ``Tennis
seemed to be another way out.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Sarah Bost of the Township of Irvington said that when she
was growing up, there were few black female role models. The idea
of Gibson winning something so distant and elitist as a Wimbledon
title opened new vistas of possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Mims Hacket, the mayor of Orange Township, recalled being a
junior high school student in Birmingham, Ala. Rosa Parks' refusal
to give up her seat and move to the back of the bus in 1955
triggered the Montgomery bus boycotts. Gibson's victory seemed part
of the burgeoning civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson burst through one of the most enduring pillars of
segregation in the United States. But tennis has proved to be more
resistant to marches and protest than have lunch counters and
public accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   The status of race and racism in tennis is raised every year
around this time, when the U.S. Open is played in New York City.
This year, William Washington, an African-American whose son,
MaliVai, is a professional player, has threatened to lead pickets
and demonstrations to call attention to the lack of a black
presence within the U.S. Tennis Association.
</P>
<P>
   But the cry for more black faces must become a bit more precise.
When Gibson played, the grip of segregation was so suffocating that
the call for a mere increase in numbers playing the game seemed
appropriate. In 1998 the question Washington must answer is: Would
you rather have a black face or a strong African-American presence?
The two no longer go hand in hand, if they ever did.
</P>
<P>
   The USTA argues that it has increased the number of
African-American employees. Who are the employees? And how hard is
the USTA pushing, fighting to find more Althea Gibsons by scouring
the Harlems of the world?
</P>
<P>
   In any event, tennis is what it is: snooty. Snooty at a level
that often goes beyond race.
</P>
<P>
   The sport clings to its country-club roots even as it craves
something new.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis is eager, anxious _ indeed desperate _ for something new,
something colorful. The sport is crazy for Venus Williams to do
well.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson wanted to play tennis. She never wanted to be a race
warrior, but she was forced by time and circumstance to play take
on that bitter role. She suffered deep scars that apparently have
never healed.
</P>
<P>
   There will never be another Althea Gibson, She lived an eclectic
life, not drenched in the traditional country-club path to tennis.
She played paddle ball on the street and was street-wise at an
early age. Her father taught her to box, and she was kicking
behinds _ boys' and girls' _ at an early age. Racism made her
tougher, focused, but it also cut her deeply.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson was the pride and joy of black and white Americans. She
was an inspiration to women, and a quintessential American story of
perseverance as significant in some ways as Jackie Robinson's. She
was the first black woman to break through in an elitist sport.
</P>
<P>
   From a sharecropping family in Alabama to Harlem's 143rd Street.
Receiving the Wimbledon trophy from the queen of England, dancing
with the duke, singing at the Wimbledon Ball and receiving the U.S.
Championship trophy from Vice President Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Today her ailment is not cancer as has been reported, but a
terminal case of life: She suffers from depression and has decided
not to take drugs to help her deal with it. Her husband died in
1995. Close friends have passed on, too, and the world she knew is
rapidly disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   This foundation, designed to pluck more Althea Gibsons from
inner cities, will be her legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Picketing the master's mansion is fine, but at some point a
desirable option would seem to be building a mansion of your own.
It never hurts to go back to fundamentals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
