<SLUG> BC-NY-HURRICANE-SHORE-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG ISLAND SUFFERED NO MAJOR DAMAGE FROM HURRICANE BONNIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HICKSVILLE, N.Y. _ The tail end of Hurricane Bonnie sideswiped
Long Island Friday as the storm slowly headed eastward over the
Atlantic Ocean, spinning off some heavy rain and gusts of wind but
causing no major damage.
</P>
<P>
   Beaches, which had already suffered a loss of sand during the
more than a dozen storms that lashed the region so far this year,
easily absorbed the remnants of Bonnie, which grazed the New Jersey
and New York coastlines and whose eye came no closer than 200 miles
south of Montauk Point at the eastern tip of Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the North Shore of Long Island remained sunny throughout
the day, as high tides along the South Shore caused some minor
flooding in low-lying waterfront areas normally inundated by high
tides.
</P>
<P>
   State transportation officials said they were keeping a close
watch on two small bridges at the southern end of the Wantagh
Parkway near Jones Beach. One of the bridges, which crosses Goose
Creek, is 68 years old, and engineers expressed concern that the
overnight high tides and wind-driven waves might undermine its
age-weakened supports.
</P>
<P>
   A second nearby bridge across Sloop Channel was closed earlier
this year because of tidal damage to its supports and was replaced
with a temporary bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're keeping both under a 24-hour watch,'' said Craig
Siracusa, the regional manager of the Transportation Department.
</P>
<P>
   Jones Beach, Robert Moses State Park and Hither Hills State Park
were all closed to swimmers because of 8-foot waves and strong
undercurrents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still are not allowing people in the water,'' said George
Gorman, a spokesman for the state Parks Department. ``We don't want
people being swept into the ocean.'' He said that erosion at the
state beaches had been minimal, then added: ``But we're not going
to breathe a sigh of relief until the storm leaves.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Richard Schaffer, supervisor of the town of Babylon, said that
some of the beaches on Fire Island appeared to be taking a bigger
hit than elsewhere, especially in the area of Gilgo and Tobay
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 11 or 12 northeasters that blew in here this year took a
sizable chunk,'' Schaffer said. ``We've lost about a million cubic
yards of sand at Gilgo, leaving us only about 25 feet of beach
between the actual shoreline and Ocean Parkway.'' The parkway
bisects that narrow 15-mile-long barrier island.
</P>
<P>
   The passing storm was the first major test for the Long Island
Power Authority as well as for Marketspan, which has signed a
long-term contract to maintain the power authority's electric
system throughout Long Island and parts of Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Burt Cunningham, a spokesman for the power authority, said
shortly before 6 p.m. Friday that the latest weather advisory it
had received from the National Weather Service was ``good news.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Trackers say the storm has taken a turn more toward the
east,'' Cunningham said, ``and the latest indications are it will
pass 200 miles south of Montauk overnight, so it looks as though
the storm is not going to have much of an impact on us. So far,
we've suffered no damage.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that earlier Friday the Weather Service had predicted
that the center of the storm might pass about 100 miles south of
Montauk Point about 2 a.m. Saturday. He said the utility had gone
to a condition red, or its highest emergency alert, two days ago in
preparation for the hurricane. ``It's been a good exercise for all
of us,'' he said, ``well beyond the experience of a drill.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey was spared the brunt of the storm. Although there was
heavy surf along the Atlantic, there was no tidal flooding, and the
Weather Service canceled its tropical storm warning at 5:15 p.m.
Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
