<SLUG> BC-NJ-FAKED-DROWNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY MAN SURRENDERS TO POLICE AFTER FAKING DROWNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ A young man accused of faking his drowning on
Monday at Point Pleasant Beach surrendered to the Bergen County
sheriff's office Friday afternoon along with his fiancee, who had
spent six hours feigning distress after reporting that he had been
swept into the Atlantic, the sheriff's office said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the suspect, Antonio Mandarino Jr., 23, and
his fiancee, Kimberly Kuda, 21, who live together in Oakland, N.J.,
had seen the churning surf caused by Hurricane Bonnie as an
opportunity for him to avoid prosecution on a number of criminal
charges he faced in Bergen County. Ms. Kuda, appearing breathless
and distraught, flagged down an officer about 7:30 p.m. Monday,
prompting a frantic search.
</P>
<P>
   Before he disappeared, Mandarino had been scheduled to appear in
Bergen County Superior Court in Hackensack on Sept. 15 on a charge
of eluding the police. He also faced charges of writing bad checks
in several northern New Jersey towns and charges of aggravated
assault in Leonia.
</P>
<P>
   Now he faces even more charges. After his arrest, detectives
found heroin in the couple's motel room; both have been charged
with drug possession. In addition, the authorities in Ocean County
have charged the couple with conspiracy and making a false public
alarm.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing Friday in Bergen County Superior Court, Judge
William Meehan revoked Mandarino's bail in the earlier cases and
ordered him held at the Bergen County Jail in Hackensack. Ms. Kuda
is scheduled to be arraigned on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
