<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0443 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8431 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-RDP-2NDLD-WRIT     08-28 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-RDP-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE RUMORS, DEFIANT YELTSIN SAYS HE WILL NOT RESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert 2 new grafs after 4th graf; also inserts a graf
about IMF Director Camdessus toward end )   (See related: RUSSIA-YELTSIN, RUSSIA-U.S., RUSSIA-U.S.-SUMMIT)  
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Boris Yeltsin, reclaiming a bit of his old defiant
nature, insisted on national television Friday night that he would
serve out his term as Russia's president and that, for him,
resignation was impossible.
</P>
<P>
   But rumors and reality alike suggested Friday that his
presidency, if it does last, is rushing toward figurehead status.
</P>
<P>
   In excerpts from a videotaped interview, Yeltsin cast himself as
once again in command of his nation's increasingly desperate
financial situation. He said new instructions given to the Central
Bank and the government ``spelled out in detail what should be
done'' and would be strictly obeyed. And he took pains to portray
the country's new prime minister, Victor Chernomyrdin, as a
subordinate and not a pretender to his throne.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been given as much power as he is entitled to as a
prime minister in any developed country,'' Yeltsin said. ``This was
given to back up strategic tasks. So, consult the president. All
the rest _ you have a free hand. Take decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday Chernomyrdin gave no indication of his plans for
ending the economic crisis. After returning from a quickly arranged
meeting with the International Monetary Fund earlier this week,
Chernomyrdin had signaled on Thursday that he had a program that he
might soon announce.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Friday belonged mostly to the president, who besides
appearing on television also reportedly agreed to give up some
important presidential authority.
</P>
<P>
   But even before he spoke _ slowly, with stilted speech and
almost painful pauses _ his envoy to the powerful Communist bloc in
Russia's lower house of Parliament, the Duma, said Yeltsin had
already agreed to cede key portions of the almost-dictatorial
powers of the Russian presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The president's representative to the Duma, Alexander Kotenkov,
and the Communist Duma speaker, Gennady Seleznyov, said in a news
conference that they had reached broad agreement on a new economic
policy and on changes to the 1993 constitution that is the
foundation of presidential power.
</P>
<P>
   Kotenkov said Yeltsin has agreed to allow the prime minister _
that is, Chernomyrdin _ to name Cabinet ministers and to give the
parliament the right to reject those appointments. Yeltsin also
agreed that Chernomyrdin's government should be given a year's
grace period in which it would be spared political attack by the
president or the Duma, Kotenkov said.
</P>
<P>
   Either concession would mark a general loosening of the reins
that Yeltsin has held in his seven years in power. Any serious
alliance with the Communists, who want to re-nationalize industry,
increase social spending and re-establish control of the economy,
should be anathema to western governments and investors who had
begun to build a market economy here.
</P>
<P>
   None of that is to say that Yeltsin or future presidents would
not remain powerful. The president would, among many other things,
choose the prime minister, set economic and defense policy and
remain the nation's representative to the world.
</P>
<P>
   But a consensus has emerged _ true or not _ that Yeltsin is no
longer in control of his fate, or that of his nation. And there
seems to be growing agreement, even among the country's squabbling
political barons, that Chernomyrdin is just about all that stands
between Mother Russia and the abyss.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin effectively said Friday night that that is baloney. ``It
is impossible to remove me, especially considering my character,''
he said in the interview. ``I will not go anywhere. I will not
resign. I will work as long as the constitution allows. Elections
for a new Parliament will be held in the year 2000, but I will not
take part in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding his denial, speculation continues to mushroom
that Yeltsin is seriously ill and soon will resign _ perhaps next
week, if the Duma confirms Chernomyrdin as prime minister _ and
that his maneuverings on television are aimed mostly at persuading
the Duma to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't believe his words,'' Leonid Radzikhovsky, political
columnist for the Moscow daily Segodnya, said in an interview after
Friday night's speech. ``More precisely, I think Yeltsin in his
character wants to hang on until the last second, but he's already
not together. And to take the place of Yeltsin, you need
Chernomyrdin.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's wan countenance and his wooden mannerisms do
little to discourage such speculation. Nor do real-life political
events.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, in a meeting with Yeltsin, two of Chernomyrdin's leading
rivals in the next presidential election _ Moscow's mayor, Yuri
Luzhkov, and Yegor Stroyev, the chairman of the upper house of
Parliament _ endorsed Chernomyrdin's accession to power. So did
Alexander Lebed, the charismatic army general who now is governor
in Russia's Siberian region and Luzhkov's principal opponent in the
early handicapping of the next presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Such unity is unheard of among Russian presidential political
rivals. But one western investor, who refused to be identified,
surmised Friday night that they decided that they and the nation
had little choice. ``Read the history of the Weimar republic,'' he
said. ``I think they should be scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Russia will again endure the sort of hyperinflation that
rent post-World War I Germany is pure speculation, but signs of
economic turmoil are everywhere. Russian stocks sank another 10 per
cent and more, but on such low volume that the decline was almost
meaningless. By one estimate, the value of all corporate stocks on
the Russian stock market has now dropped almost sevenfold this
year, to a paltry $15.9 billion _ roughly that of Caterpillar
Corp., the Peoria, Ill., bulldozer maker.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Michel Camdessus, managing director of the
International Monetary Fund, reiterated at a news conference that
Russia's new government must stick to the austerity plan that was
part of last month's agreement for additional loans. After meeting
with Chernomyrdin in Ukraine this week, Camdessus said Friday that
he supported the acting prime minister's efforts, and that he
believed Chernomyrdin understood ``the validity'' of the fund's
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The ruble briefly traded on electronic markets Friday at a rate
of almost 13 to the dollar _ more than double two weeks ago _ and
in the few street shops that sold dollars, the rate was even
higher. Lines, albeit orderly ones, queued outside many Moscow
banks Friday, and some stores reported panic buying by consumers
who anticipated _ accurately _ that prices were about to skyrocket.
</P>
<P>
   Some Russian stores shut altogether, unable to figure out what
their goods were worth when the ruble's value was proving almost
impossible to accurately measure. Other companies in Moscow
abandoned ruble pricing altogether to value their goods in an
unnamed currency whose value could be measured against the American
dollar. Charles Blitzer, a former World Bank official who now
assesses emerging markets in London for Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette, said the crucial job of the new Russian government is to
stop the ruble's free-fall.
</P>
<P>
   ''Given their financial position, that's going to mean cutting
demand for dollars, either for luxury goods or with stronger
measures to force repatriation of export earnings,'' he said.
``That's an absolute must in stopping the panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Blitzer said the government cannot dawdle if it is to save
itself, and the nation, from fiscal chaos and the prospect of
shortages and social unrest. ''We're in a situation where, really,
a month is a long time,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
