<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY SCHOOLS TENTATIVELY AGREE TO LET POLICE HELP RUN
SECURITY
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After years of fighting between the Board of
Education and City Hall, schools Chancellor Rudy Crew has
tentatively agreed to give the New York City Police Department
significant control over security at the city's public schools,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would include turning over the recruitment, screening
and training of school security officers to the Police Department,
according to school and City Hall officials. But it would not
involve assigning regular police officers to any more than the 130
schools they already help patrol at the invitation of principals,
school officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Crew had agreed on a
memorandum of understanding. Some details must still be worked out,
and the final plan requires the approval of the Board of Education,
which appeared divided on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Colleen Roche, a spokeswoman for the mayor, said Friday that
Giuliani's and Crew's staffs were continuing to negotiate but hoped
to have a plan for the next board meeting, Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we are close to an agreement that would improve the
safety of students and staff,'' Crew said through his spokeswoman,
Chiara Coletti. He declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   The 3,200 officers of the board's Division of School Safety, who
patrol the more than 1,000 public schools armed only with handcuffs
and the aura of authority, would become employees of the Police
Department but not sworn law enforcement officers, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, first reported Thursday in Newsday, all but abolishes
the Division of School Safety, which has patrolled the schools
since 1969, when 200 guards went on duty. A high-ranking school
administration official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
said the board would effectively retain the Police Department to
run the division, which has a $110 million budget.
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor would set up an oversight committee of board
officials, police personnel and community members to settle
disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The draft memorandum of understanding came about after arduous
negotiations. Giuliani, who has never shied away from criticizing
the division insisted that the police play a greater role in school
security.
</P>
<P>
   Crew sought to maintain schools' academic atmosphere without the
concern that police officers might cause to students. Under the
agreement he would retain ultimate say over where the officers are
deployed and how many are assigned to schools. In gray areas, such
as whether students' horseplay has crossed over into assault, the
final decision over arrests would lie with principals.
</P>
<P>
   The Division of School Safety has been the subject of no fewer
than seven investigations since 1971 by the board, city and outside
auditors, all of which found lapses in training, recruitment and
discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, there have been several incidents in which
safety officers have been arrested on charges of sexually
assaulting students or possessing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   A high-ranking school administration official said there were no
plans to dismiss any of the current safety officers, and it was
uncertain what, if any, retraining they might undergo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
