A8534 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-USOPEN-TICKETS-NY     08-28 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-TICKETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE EXAMINING HANDLING OF U.S. OPEN TICKETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The state attorney general's office is investigating
allegations that employees in the box office for the U.S. Open
tennis tournament illegally diverted prime seats to scalpers who in
turn resold the tickets at vastly inflated prices, officials said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   An undercover agent recently paid $1,700 for a ticket to a
women's semifinal match that had a face value of $80, said David
Corvette, a spokesman for Attorney General Dennis Vacco. The
two-week tournament begins on Monday in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   New York state law bars the resale of tickets to entertainment
and sports events for more than $5 above face value, or 10 percent
more than face value, whichever is greater, plus tax. The
allegations about the box office employees were made by people with
knowledge about the tournament's operations, Corvette said.
</P>
<P>
   Tournament officials acknowledged Friday that ticket scalping is
a widespread problem for the U.S. Open and for most other popular
sports events. But they said they doubted that people working in
the box office of the National Tennis Center in Flushing
Meadows-Corona Park, where the tournament is held, were to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that we don't have anyone dishonest in the box
office,'' said Jay Snyder, the tournament's director.
</P>
<P>
   David Meehan, the director of operations for the tennis center,
said the scalped tickets probably originated with longtime
boxholders, who pay as much as $26,000 for 150 tickets and may be
tempted to resell some of them to defray their costs. ``We think
the real root of the problem are the people who have subscribed for
many years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Corvette said the investigators suspect that box office
employees accepted bribes in exchange for the tickets because the
seats were always in the best locations. ``In a lot of cases, the
seats that these brokers are selling are the seats that were
withheld from sale to the public,'' he said. Most theaters and
sports arenas reserve a block of seats, known as house seats, for
dignitaries and friends and associates of the people involved in
the event.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan, however, said that only two box office employees have
access to house seats, which can be sold only to people who are
exchanging other tickets that they have previously bought.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation of the U.S. Open is part of a wider
examination of ticket scalping in the entertainment and sports
industry that Vacco, a Republican who is seeking re-election this
year, is conducting.
</P>
<P>
   The tennis tournament became a focus of concern because of a
case involving a Manhattan couple who were convicted on Aug. 13 of
selling thousands of tickets for concerts and sports events at
inflated prices. During an August 1996 raid at the home of the
couple, Gerard Nahay and his wife, Janet Rosenblatt, agents seized
more than 1,000 tickets to the Open and hundreds of tickets to
Mets, Yankees and Jets games.
</P>
<P>
   Nahay and Ms. Rosenblatt, co-owners of Tickets on Request, 424
W. 33rd St., were convicted of 19 counts of ticket scalping and tax
evasion. They are scheduled to be sentenced in state Supreme Court
in Manhattan on Sept. 23 and face a maximum of four years in
prison. The company's telephone number is no longer listed, and it
could not be determined whether it remains in business.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the tennis center was fined $40,000 for failing to
comply with a rarely enforced 1965 law that requires ticket sellers
to register with the state. Under the law, the state has to be
notified when a ticket seller changes jobs, Corvette said.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket sellers who accept illegal payment from brokers _ known
as ``ice'' _ are subject to suspension or cancellation of the
registration.
</P>
<P>
   Corvette said he did not know how many ticket sellers at the
tennis center might have engaged in illegal business dealings with
scalpers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-28-98 2309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980828.0449 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-28 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
