<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More victims likely as Del Rio clears debris
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The death toll from flooding in Del Rio is
almost certain to rise as workers search through mud and debris
left by the worst storm in the Southwest Texas border town since
1954, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Some victims might never be found.
</P>
<P>
   Seven fatalities have been confirmed. Authorities have not been
able to account for 187 other people. The vast majority are thought
to be alive, but nine of them are known to have been in Del Rio
when torrential rains fell Sunday night and Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself an optimist,'' said Sparky Dean, a spokesman
for the Texas Department of Public Safety. ``But I just can't
believe, with the severity of this, that we would only have seven
fatalities.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean said he spoke with one elderly man whose wife was ripped
from his grasp when floodwaters spawned by Tropical Storm Charley
swept through their house. ``He could hear her hollering as she was
washed downstream,'' Dean said. ``His wife is one of the nine
confirmed missing.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of unaccounted-for people has fluctuated widely. That
is because names are added to the list as calls are received from
relatives inquiring about Del Rio residents. Ninety-seven other
people previously listed as unaccounted for have been found, Dean
said.
</P>
<P>
   Public and private organizations were stepping up relief efforts
Friday in Del Rio, a town of 34,000 people on the Rio Grande. Heavy
equipment was brought in to dredge San Felipe Creek, along which
most of the damage occurred. The Salvation Army arranged to assist
flood survivors not only in Del Rio but across the river in the
Mexican community of Ciudad Acun(tilde)a.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Land Commissioner Garry Mauro, responding to a request
from local officials, sent a mobile communications unit to Del Rio
to help work crews and law officers. The unit, normally used at oil
spills, has computer, telephone and radio capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Emergency Management Agency was preparing to acquire
mobile homes and other temporary housing. A total of 1,562 homes
and businesses were damaged in Del Rio, according to the Department
of Public Safety. That includes 625 that were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Housing ``is going to be the major issue'' along the Rio Grande,
said FEMA Director James Lee Witt. The agency's director of human
services, Laurence W. Zensinger, was scheduled to arrive in Del Rio
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funds will start to flow over the weekend,'' Zensinger said.
</P>
<P>
   That would be none too soon for Gemma Garza. She and her family
spent the day carting belongings out of her parents' damaged house.
Her own home just down the block was also damaged. Neither she nor
her parents have insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a brand-new bedroom set,'' Garza said, pointing to a
smashed dresser on the curb. ``I hadn't even made the first
payment.''
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Dan Morales warned that he would use the
deceptive-trade law to prosecute price-gougers, dishonest
remodelers and anyone else who attempts to take advantage of flood
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Relief seemed to be arriving more slowly in Rio Bravo, a poor
community south of Laredo. Rio Bravo's mayor issued an open letter
seeking assistance for about two dozen families left homeless after
floodwaters invaded their modest mobile homes and wood-frame
houses. The flood wave on the Rio Grande was working its way
downstream from Laredo to Falcon Reservoir. Falcon had risen 6.7
feet by Friday and was expected to rise an additional 5.3 feet by
Monday. Amistad Reservoir, upstream from Del Rio, has risen 14 feet
from flooding in the Devils and Pecos rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Falcon and Amistad are expected to reach 29 percent of their
combined capacity, far below what is needed to break a five-year
drought in the Lower Rio Grande Valley, said Ken Rakestraw, chief
of water accounting for the International Boundary and Water
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The flooding in Del Rio was the worst since June 28, 1954, said
Daryl Williams, a forecaster with the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the seven fatalities in Del Rio, five people were swept
away by floodwaters in Ciudad Acun(tilde)a, and four people died
when their pickup was swept down a stream in Real County on Sunday.
One man died Sunday of a heart attack during an evacuation from
rising waters at Garner State Park in Uvalde County.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
