<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BEAT SEATTLE, 10-3, FOR 3RD STRAIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees drifted off their 120-victory course this
week after their rudder _ the starting pitching _ took on some
dents and three different relief pitchers blew save opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday night, the Yankees got a strong outing from Orlando
Hernandez, the first from a starter in a week, as they overwhelmed
the Seattle Mariners, 10-3, before 47,785 fans at Yankee Stadium.
The Yankees, having won three straight games and on pace to win
118, seemed to have navigated their way through the season's first
squall.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are three victories from reaching 100, a milestone
the 1906 Chicago Cubs and the 1954 Cleveland Indians reached on
Sept. 9, the earliest in the 20th century, according to the Elias
Sports Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Since David Wells shut out Texas last Friday, the Yankee machine
had endured a few glitches: David Cone had struggled through two
outings, the Rangers had pummeled Hernandez, Andy Pettitte had
fallen apart in the seventh inning against Anaheim, and Hideki
Irabu had disintegrated after five innings. Ryan Bradley, a rookie,
had to start Wednesday after Ramiro Mendoza underwent a minor bit
of surgery. The starters were faltering and the bullpen was spent
and reeling.
</P>
<P>
   But as he has several times this season, Hernandez
re-established equilibrium, allowing just three hits and two runs
over seven innings, striking out eight and walking two Friday
night. He lacked control in the first inning of his last start,
against the Rangers, but against the Mariners, his control was
superb.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coaches generally will be pleased if their students can
throw first-pitch strikes to two-thirds of opposing hitters;
Hernandez threw first-pitch strikes to the first eight Seattle
batters Friday night, and 11 of the first 12.
</P>
<P>
   By getting ahead in the count, of course, Hernandez then forced
the Mariners to swing defensively at his sidearm slider and
curveball and assorted variety of off-speed stuff. He struck out
Alex Rodriguez, Ken Griffey Jr. and David Segui in the first
inning, and got Segui again in the third. After Rodriguez swung
through a fastball to strike out in the fifth, he turned and
slammed his bat against the plate, in utter disgust.
</P>
<P>
   Run support was not a concern for Hernandez, who improved his
record to 9-4.
</P>
<P>
   Over five games in four days this week, the Anaheim Angels
demonstrated they have the hubris to challenge the Yankees in the
postseason, and there's nothing the Yankees can do to change that
between now and when the leaves turn.
</P>
<P>
   What the Yankees can accomplish in the last 30 days of the
regular season is address their own weaknesses (right-handed middle
relief, first and foremost), surpass records and re-establish their
dominance over the rest of the American League. They took long
strides to those ends Friday night, beating on Seattle as Evander
Holyfield might a sparring partner.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Spoljaric, the Mariners' starting pitcher, could have used
some protective gear, as hard as he was hit. Chuck Knoblauch drove
Spoljaric's second pitch into the right field corner for the first
of his four hits, then scampered around first base and challenged
the arm of Raul Ibanez, sliding safely into second with a double.
</P>
<P>
   After Tim Raines walked and Bernie Williams singled through the
middle, Chili Davis crushed a double between the right and center
fielders and just like that, the Yankees led 3-0 and everything
seemed back to 1998 standards.
</P>
<P>
   But there was more: Jorge Posada pulled a double down the third
base line and into the left field corner, Davis scoring. If there
was any apprehension or worry remaining from the Anaheim series, it
was gone, like a migraine headache. The crowd jeered Stan Williams,
the Seattle pitching coach, as he went to and from the mound, in a
mission to calm Spoljaric.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Curtis walked, and Segui, the first baseman, and John
Marzano, the catcher, visited Spoljaric. Luis Sojo pulled a ground
single through the left side, scoring Posada, and Alex Rodriguez,
the shortstop, and Marzano talked to Spoljaric, who was quickly
running out of counseling options.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee rally finally ended on Spoljaric's 43rd pitch of the
inning, after five hits, seven baserunners and five runs. The
Mariners might have Rodriguez and Griffey, but the Yankees were
giving them the same treatment extended to the Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees added two runs in the third inning, when Scott
Brosius blasted a two-run homer into the third deck above left
field, and three more runs in the fourth inning, Raines slapping a
two-run single. In all, Spoljaric (4-3) was charged with nine runs,
and when he was removed, some Yankee fans behind the Seattle dugout
stood and cheered and thanked him in their own special way for
helping to restore order in the Yankees' special world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
