<HEADLINE>
E-MAIL HOAX TOUTS DISNEY TRIP  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KATHLEEN INGLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The e-mail message seems too Goofy to be true: Get a free trip
to the Magic Kingdom just by clicking a button.
</P>
<P>
   Computer users across the nation are receiving that enticing
promise, supposedly a reward for helping the Walt Disney Co. check
out a new computer program.
</P>
<P>
   The catch? The offer is as phony as the ears on a Mousketeer's
hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fraud,'' said Disney spokesman Ken Green, sounding a bit
Grumpy about the whole affair.
</P>
<P>
   And it's the latest in a series of e-mail hoaxes that are
spreading like wildfire, thanks to the ease of electronic mail. The
technological tall tales range from fake warnings about
non-existent viruses to bogus appeals to protect public radio.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney hoax popped up this month. The e-mail, supposedly
from Walt Disney Jr., explains that the company is working with
computer giant Microsoft and needs help testing an e-mail tracing
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forward this to everyone you know,'' the message instructs,
``and if it reaches 13,000 people, 1,300 of the people on the list
will receive $5,000, and the rest will receive a free trip for two
to Disney World.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire offer is no more real than Mickey Mouse, and even the
author is make-believe. Walt Disney never had a son, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   But computer users, from business owners to Ph.D.s, want to
believe, and they're forwarding the e-mail by the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   Their forwarding messages give a hint: ``Can't hurt to do it,
anyway.'' ```Who knows? Stranger things have happened.'' ``Why
not?''
</P>
<P>
   As Adam Sohn, spokesman for Microsoft, observes, ``There's no
consequence for sending it along. Some send it tongue in cheek,
some because they believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just by their volume, however, these e-mails aren't as harmless
as they seem, according to the U.S. Department of Energy's Web site
that monitors hoaxes and chain letters.
</P>
<P>
   If each one of the recipients sends the message to just 10 other
people, the ninth round of messages will add up to 1 billion. That
could interfere with legitimate e-mails, plus there's the time lost
to reading and deleting such chain letters.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney message is a new twist on an e-mail hoax that started
last year. The earlier version, purportedly from Microsoft Chairman
Bill Gates, offered $1,000 for forwarding messages to help in an
e-mail tracking project.
</P>
<P>
   But the payoff isn't even technologically possible, Sohn said,
because there's no way to track all the various e-mail providers to
find out where messages were forwarded.
</P>
<P>
   It's also virtually impossible to figure out where a hoax
started. The only way to track down the culprit is through a copy
of the original e-mail, which gets lost in the blizzard of
forwarding.
</P>
<P>
   Sohn has three theories for what motivates people to launch
hoaxes:
</P>
<P>
   Collecting e-mail addresses for future junk mailings, although
this is possible only if a return message is requested.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to clog up the system in general or for some target
company, such as Microsoft. This is rarely a problem, because most
e-mail servers have such large capacities.
</P>
<P>
   Getting some personal, if anonymous, glory if the hoax is
publicized.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet offers an incredible amount of freedom &UR; to search
out information and find people with similar interests and
products,'' he said. ``It's unfortunate that some folks have chosen
to abuse that freedom, but in some respects you have to take the
good with the bad.''
</P>
<P>
   His advice on dealing with hoaxes: Hit the delete button. &QL; 
 &UR; Kathleen Ingley can be reached at 444-8171 or at
kathleen.ingley &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
