<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE SIDE, TESSMER HAS IMPRESSIVE DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jay Tessmer tried throwing a baseball overhand, but
it felt weird, like slipping your left foot into a right shoe, or
like a left-handed person brushing his teeth with his right hand.
He decided to throw the way he felt most comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   And though Tessmer's sidearm delivery produces fastballs with
velocity comparable with other pitchers' changeups, he made it to
the big leagues because of his unusual motion.
</P>
<P>
   In his major-league debut Thursday night, Tessmer, 26,
contributed a perfect inning of relief _ two strikeouts and an easy
flyout _ and collected his first victory when the Yankees scored in
the bottom of the 11th inning to beat Anaheim, 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   For a pitching staff in need of stabilization, Tessmer's outing
came at the right time. ``He used one baseball for three outs,''
said Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager. ``That's impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Yankees attempt to sort out their right-handed relief
problems before the start of the American League playoffs on Sept.
29, Tessmer will be among those thrown against the proverbial wall;
if he gets outs, he will stick. If he does not, he will join the
growing number of Yankee relievers who have tried and failed to
hold a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, if you keep putting up the numbers, you're
going to be given the opportunity,'' said Brian Cashman, the
Yankees' general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Tessmer has survived and thrived under those conditions in his
career, after being drafted in the 19th round in 1995, out of the
University of Miami. Like knuckleballers, soft-throwing sidearmers
are looked upon as if their pitches are freakish, and teams are
rarely patient with them.
</P>
<P>
   Tessmer's sinking fastball reaches a maximum speed of 85 miles
an hour _ pedestrian, by Kerry Wood standards _ and, in fact,
Tessmer would rather throw it 80 to 82 mph, he said, because it
tends to sink more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The harder I throw,'' Tessmer said, ``the more the ball tends
to flatten out.''
</P>
<P>
   Tessmer also throws a changeup, along with a curveball that
breaks inside on left-handed hitters. But it is the movement of his
pitches and his ability to change speeds and throw all of his
pitches for strikes that pushed him through the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Tessmer had 55 saves in his first two seasons, but in 1997, he
accumulated a 5.31 earned run average for Class AA Norwich. During
the off season, Tessmer watched videotape of Dan Quisenberry,
perhaps the most memorable sidearmer in recent history, with the
Yankees pitching instructor Billy Connors, and between them they
tried to figure out a way to get more movement on Tessmer's
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Tessmer made a slight adjustment, opening his delivery more
quickly and allowing his right arm to drag more. He enjoyed an
exceptional minor league season. In Class AA and AAA, his ERA was
0.93 in 57 appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the Angels on Thursday, he struck out Phil Nevin and
Darrin Erstad. His fastball darted down and away from the
left-handed hitting Erstad, and afterward he got the game ball, as
well as the ball Bernie Williams drove for the game-winning,
two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing hitters, especially left-handed batters, sometimes
feast on sidearmers, but Torre will continue to use Tessmer, until
he does something to fall out of favor, the same parameters in
which Todd Erdos, Joe Borowski, Mike Buddie and Ryan Bradley have
worked under this year.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry said of Tessmer, ``He could turn out to be an
important guy for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees remain hopeful that Jeff Nelson will recover from
back trouble and reclaim his role as the right-handed setup man.
Nelson and Darren Holmes both threw in Tampa, Fla., Friday, and if
all goes well, they will pitch in a minor league rehabilitation
game Monday and then again two days later, before being activated
by the Yankees. Nelson had already reached that point before in his
rehabilitation, before his back trouble flared.
</P>
<P>
   Prospect's Parents Killed
</P>
<P>
   The parents of the top Yankees prospect Jackson Melian were
killed in a car accident on Interstate 77 early Friday morning,
shortly after watching their son play in a game for Class AA
Greensboro (N.C). Vicente and Jasmine Melian were driving from
Columbia, S.C., where Greensboro played, to Hickory, N.C., ahead of
the team bus.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Yankees' game against Seattle at Yankee Stadium
Friday night, a moment of silence was observed for the outfielder's
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees General Manager Brian Cashman said, ``We'll give him the
support and the prayers he needs.''
</P>
<P>
   According to John Frey, general manager for the Greensboro team,
Melian learned of his parents' deaths when the team bus came upon
the accident. Melian is in Charlotte, N.C., away from the team and
tending to his family, Frey said. Melian's older brother survived
the accident, Frey said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Melian, who was born in Venezuela, signed with the
Yankees at age 16 for $1.6 million in 1996, the most money, at that
time, for a teen-age prospect from outside the United States.
Vicente Melian had an affinity for the Yankees, naming his son
after the Hall of Fame slugger Reggie Jackson.
</P>
</TEXT>
