<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ATP-DRUG-BAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATP CLARIFIES POSITION ON ANDROSTENEDIONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMACK, N.Y. _ The men's tennis tour clarified its stand on the
testosterone-producing substance androstenedione Friday, saying
that it had been previously banned by the ATP and that players are
not being given a grace period to test positive for it.
</P>
<P>
   A story in Friday's New York Times quoted Bill Norris, a medical
trainer for the ATP, as saying that the men's tour had decided on
Wednesday to ban use of the substance and that there would be a
grace period for testing. Norris said that David Cooper, the tour's
executive vice president in charge of rules and regulations, was
involved in the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The ATP said, however, that androstenedione, an over-the-counter
supplement now in the spotlight because of its use by the St. Louis
Cardinal slugger Mark McGwire, was already on the banned list,
although not by name. Dr. Brian Hainline, the chief medical officer
at the U.S. Open and an advisory board member for the sport's
anti-drug program, said androstenedione fell under the ATP's ban on
``related substances,'' which includes any drug that theoretically
raises testosterone levels.
</P>
<P>
   Graeme Agars, a spokesman for the ATP, said that at a regularly
scheduled meeting of the tour's players on Monday, the first day of
the Open, it was quite likely androstenedione would be discussed.
Agars said the ATP accepted responsibility for the initial
misstatement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
