<SLUG> BC-NJ-MOLEST-TAPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAPE OF PHONE TALK ERASED IN MOLESTATION CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ One of several tapes of telephone conversations
from a sting operation against a man accused of molesting a
15-year-old Jackson Township boy was accidentally erased by a
technician who was trying to make copies, the Monmouth County
prosecutor said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The slip-up has taken on greater significance largely because
the teen-ager, Samuel Manzie, angrily stopped cooperating in the
sting and was charged less than a week later with the rape and
strangulation murder of Edward Werner, 11, who was selling candy
door-to-door for a school fund-raiser. The Sept. 27, 1997, slaying
sparked parents' deepest fears and led to an effort in the
Legislature to ban such school fund-raising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, John Kaye, said that the lost tape was the last
of three that his office's investigators had made of a series of
telephone conversations between Samuel Manzie and Stephen Simmons
in September 1997. Simmons, 44, a convicted pedophile from
Holbrook, N.Y., has been charged with luring Samuel, then 14, into
four sexual encounters, including at least one in Monmouth County,
in late 1996 after the two met in an online chat room.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons, his lawyer and others involved in the case have known
about the loss of the tape since January, according to Kaye. He
said that its loss, while unfortunate, had not seriously hurt the
prosecution's case against Simmons. For one thing, he noted, in
November a grand jury found sufficient evidence to indict Simmons
based on information in the other two tapes and in the written
recollections of investigators as to what was on the third tape.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons, in a letter sent to The Asbury Park Press earlier this
week, questioned whether the erasure was an accident. The paper
published an article about the letter and the prosecutor's response
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons' lawyer, Howard Golden, said that the prosecutor's
account of the entire taping episode was ``ambiguous.'' He said he
had been unsuccessful in getting clarification from the
prosecutor's office about what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``My client believes that the tape would have been helpful to
his defense, and he disagrees very strongly with police accounts of
what it contained,'' Golden said. ``I can't say that there are
actual denials of the charges in the indictment, but there is a
question of the validity of any case against Simmons because
evidence was destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons is being held in the Monmouth County Jail in Freehold
and Kaye said that his trial would not take place until the murder
case against Samuel in adjacent Ocean County was concluded. Samuel
is charged with trying to sodomize and then strangling Edward, the
sixth-grader who rang his doorbell to sell candy for his school.
Samuel, according to police, hid the body in a suitcase in his
house before dumping it in nearby woods.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel had agreed to help investigators build a criminal case
against the man who had enticed him into a sexual affair. But on
Sept. 22, after nearly a month of cooperation, he rebelled against
the investigation, tipped off Simmons and smashed the recording
device. Over the next few days, his parents unsuccessfully tried to
have him committed for long-term psychiatric care.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye said that the Sept. 22 conversation was the one
inadvertently erased. The erasure apparently happened shortly after
the conversation was recorded. A technician using the office's new
high-speed dubbing machine, which can make three copies at once,
placed the master tape in one of the copy slots by mistake and a
blank tape in the slot where the master should have been, Kaye
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we made three recordings,'' Kaye said, ``and the first
contained the evidence crucial to the case and the second was a
tape of our attempt to have Sam lure him to New Jersey so we could
arrest him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We explained what happened to the tape to the grand jury and
provided them with copies of the recollections and the notes of the
officers who were there.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the things about the account of the accident that were
ambiguous, Golden said, was Kaye's assertion that three separate
conversations were taped. Golden said records from the pretrial
discovery phase indicated that only two conversations were
originally taped. He said that Simmons' handwritten, nine-page
letter about the erasures sent to The Asbury Park Press had brought
out more information than he had been able to get from the
prosecutors.
</P>
</TEXT>
